<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS' ANGER HITS MARTINEZ WRONG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ There are some smart men who coach and play for the
Cleveland Indians. I am sure of that. What I'm not sure of is this:
Why did those intelligent people appear to be so ignorant and
thickheaded Sunday at Jacobs Field?
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the Indians' explanation for being angry with
Pedro Martinez, I was embarrassed for all of them. And after
realizing that their logic is not in the minority in the major
leagues, I was embarrassed for all of baseball. The cliche is that
the shrinking strike zone is one of the problems in the game.
That's not true. A major issue is the shrinking mental zone by some
of the players.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Indians and Red Sox cleared their benches twice
during the finale of a spectacular three-game series. The Sox
avoided a sweep with a 2-1 win, and Martinez extended his scoreless
streak against the Indians to 20 innings. But what really upset
catcher Einar Diaz and the rest of his Cleveland teammates was the
behavior of Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't like the way Martinez ``almost'' hit Diaz in the
head in the seventh inning. They didn't like the way Martinez
stared at Diaz in the same inning after striking him out with an
inside fastball. They didn't like it when, during the first bench
clearing, Martinez sat in the dugout. He was eventually invited to
come outside by Scott Kamieniecki and he obliged. He was
accompanied by hitting coach Jim Rice, a man who probably could
transform the 6-foot, 200-pound Kamieniecki into the size of a
wallet in 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As you can imagine, there was a lot of yelling and
finger-pointing from the Indians. They talked and talked, even
though they should have sat down and kept quiet. They also should
have reviewed a copy of the Essential Pedro Profile, a piece of
literature that every team should have on its bookshelf.
Apparently, the Indians don't have a copy. Let's give them some
help:
</P>
<P>
   Martinez loses all humility when he is on the mound. He'll stare
at you when he strikes you out. He'll plunk you when you play games
with him in the batter's box. He is territorial. Inside of the
plate? His. Close calls? Should be his. Sunday he cursed plate
umpire Tim Tschida _ he later apologized _ when he didn't get the
calls he wanted. Or, from his Mound View, the calls he deserved. He
is Pedro Martinez, you are not, and you had better get used to it.
He is bright and thoughtful away from the diamond, but he ain't
trying to be a humanitarian when you are 60 feet 6 inches away.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians still don't understand this. They don't have to like
it, but they should at least understand it. They don't.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Omar Vizquel said it was ``horse (expletive)'' that
Martinez threw at Diaz. Vizquel reasoned that Martinez was trying
to big-time the second-year catcher because he was upset by the two
doubles Diaz hit. I was waiting for him to get to the point, the
point that would make me gasp, but it never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't like the way he stared at Einar after striking him
out,'' second baseman Robbie Alomar said. ``That was disrespectful.
We have always shown the Red Sox respect, so we didn't think that
was right.''
</P>
<P>
   I was tempted to cut out the lights in the Cleveland clubhouse
and show a movie featuring Bob Gibson and Sandy Koufax. Too many
players in baseball don't comprehend the art of intimidation. They
also don't grasp the psychology of claiming the inside of the
plate, a nebulous area that truly doesn't belong to anyone _ sort
of like the armrest between you and your neighbor on an airplane _
but is often claimed by pitchers. There was a time when brushbacks
and near misses did not inspire complaining and a charge to the
mound. But the truth is that some of today's players, with all
their elbow pads and sense of offensive entitlement, have lost
historical perspective and gone soft.
</P>
<P>
   And some pitchers have lost their minds. Kamieniecki, who made
the Big Ten's all-academic team at Michigan, proved that Sunday. He
said Martinez ``hid'' behind Rice. Is this guy serious? Rice
protecting Martinez doesn't illustrate the pitcher's cowardice; it
proves the coach's intelligence. Why would the Sox allow Martinez
to fight and risk an injury that would end his season? Teams in the
NHL have perfected this logic, by bringing in bodyguards on ice to
protect high-scoring forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only guy talking trash out there was Kamieniecki,''
Martinez said. ``He told me to come out, I came out, and he didn't
do anything.'' Later, Martinez said, ``I don't think Kamieniecki
will be one of the guys that will intimidate me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland silliness affected the Sox in the eighth inning.
In an obvious retaliation for Martinez's near miss, Charles Nagy
hit Jose Offerman in the ribs. Offerman, who is hitting .175,
should have blown a kiss to Nagy and thanked the pitcher for
putting him in a rare place _ on base. Instead, he made a move for
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the eighth, when Martinez hit Alomar in the
thigh and was ejected, the reasoning ability of the 42,065 fans was
altered as well. A chant of ``Pedro Sucks'' began. Martinez should
be proud of this because he now joins the gallery of legendary
athletes (Michael Jordan, John Elway) who have seared themselves
into the memories of northeastern Ohioans.
</P>
<P>
   If Diaz had been hit in the head, this would be a different
story. I don't think anyone can defend throwing at someone and
hitting him in the head. But Diaz was not hit, and didn't come as
close to being hit as he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone throws a 96-mile-per-hour pitch close to you, I'll
bet you'll be a little mad,'' Sox reliever Derek Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is right. A pitch under your chin will anger you, although
several players in baseball history have been angered and not
attempted to pick a fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
