<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ EJECTED BUT BEATS CLEVELAND AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ To an outsider _ or someone in a Cleveland Indians
uniform _ it might have seemed rash, foolhardy, shortsighted, or
just plain dumb when Pedro Martinez hit Robbie Alomar with the
first pitch of the eighth inning Sunday afternoon, even though
Martinez knew he would be ejected from a game the Sox had to win to
avert a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the Sox clubhouse, where Sunday's 2-1 win over the
Indians was almost secondary to the issues raised by Martinez's
obvious act of retaliation for Indians pitcher Charles Nagy hitting
Jose Offerman in the hip with his first pitch of the top of the
inning, they spoke with one voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a closeness,'' said Mike Stanley, whose seventh-inning
home run ultimately proved the difference in the weekend's third
one-run game between these foes, allowing the Sox to survive Richie
Sexson's home run in the ninth off Derek Lowe. ``We do so much
together. It is like a family, we spend so much stinking time
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You live and die for one another. And if we have to fight for
one another, we fight for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no punches thrown by either side, though benches
emptied twice, the first time after Offerman took a couple of steps
toward Nagy, and again when Martinez struck Alomar in the backside
with a fastball. Given the record penalties handed down in the
aftermath of last weekend's brawl between the White Sox and Tigers,
which led to the suspensions of 16 managers, coaches, and players
for a total of 82 games, further hostilities surely would have
invited some unscheduled vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any fighting,'' said manager Jimy Williams, who
also was automatically ejected by plate umpire Tim Tschida because
both sides had been warned after Offerman was plunked that any
further incidents would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether those decisions that came down before crossed
anybody's mind at the time, I don't know,'' Williams said, ``but
there wasn't any fighting. I don't know what will happen, being
that there weren't any fights. Nobody got hurt. A couple of players
got hit in the leg. That's pitching aggressively inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagy hit Offerman an inning after Martinez threw a 1-and-1,
noggin-level fastball that spun Indians catcher Einar Diaz to the
ground. Diaz had doubled in each of his previous two at-bats
against Martinez, the first a three-hopper into the hole that
bounced off Nomar Garciaparra's glove and went into short left
field, the second a line drive to the base of the wall in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared the pants off him,'' Sox catcher Jason Varitek said.
``He thought it came really close to hitting him in the head. It
was close, but it didn't hit him. For everybody's sake, you never
want to see anyone get hit in the head. But (the Indians) felt it
was too close.''
</P>
<P>
   After the dustoff, Martinez struck out Diaz, then stared at him
as he walked away from the plate, prompting Diaz to bark back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was staring at me after he struck me out,'' Diaz said. ``I
said, `What are you looking at? You already got what you wanted.'
That pitch was pretty close to my face. I don't think that's
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox pitcher, who escaped a no-out, second-and-third jam in
the third, struck out 10 in all, and has pitched 20 straight
scoreless innings against the Tribe, including the playoffs, was
unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not allowed to pitch inside?'' he said. ``I pitched plenty
of good games against Cleveland and I never had an incident like
this happen. I don't know why they would get upset for just one
pitch, going up and in on somebody, especially when the guy goes
diving into the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Indians, Martinez was the agent provocateur of all that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he was throwing at Einar,'' said Indians shortstop
Omar Vizquel, who was hitless in four at-bats against Martinez,
striking out in the third with runners on second and third, after
which Troy O'Leary made a terrific running catch on Alomar after
turning the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cheap shot and stupid thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Given what passes for baseball protocol in the last 20 years, it
was hardly surprising that Nagy greeted Offerman the way he did.
But Offerman, when asked if he expected to be hit, said, ``Not
really.'' And he rejected any suggestion that he charged the mound,
though he took a couple of steps in that direction until being
wrapped up by Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to charge the mound,'' he said, ``I wouldn't
have taken that long.''
</P>
<P>
   The dugouts and bullpens emptied, but the only potential
flare-up came when Indians reliever Scott Kamieniecki pointed in
the Sox dugout, where Martinez was still sitting. That provoked the
ire of Sox first baseman Brian Daubach, still sore at Kamieniecki
for throwing behind O'Leary on the last weekend of the season in
Baltimore, a game in which Kamieniecki was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get Pedro's attention,'' Kamieniecki said. ``I
was wondering why there were only 49 of us out there. We had a
25-to-24 advantage. I didn't want to get the wrong impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez finally ambled out of the dugout, but when he did, the
imposing figure of coach Jim Rice was beside him.
</P>
<P>
   What was said to Martinez on the bench after that, Williams
wasn't saying. ``What I said or didn't say stays in the clubhouse,
it stays within the team,'' Williams said. But it was pretty clear
he had no problem with what Martinez did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take care of our own the best we can,'' he said.
``That's all I can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   He clasped his fingers together. ``This,'' he said, ``is so
important. That's a team. That's what's important. It's a marathon.
That doesn't mean we're a great team, but we're going to try. And
as long as we try, that's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he did what had to be done when he hit Alomar.
``Baseball has been like that forever,'' he said. ``We play as a
team, fight as a team, go down as a team, win as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie said he didn't expect me to hit him. But you go home,
he'll understand that he was the last person I wanted to hit,
because I have so much respect for him. But it's part of the game.
I have a job to do. I hope he understands.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe stranded two Indians in the eighth when he struck out Jim
Thome looking and Travis Fryman grounded to third. Sexson led off
the ninth by golfing a low pitch into the seats, ending the
Indians' 0-for-32 streak against Lowe. Pinch hitter Mark Whiten
then drew a walk and wound up on third when Garciaparra threw
wildly trying to double him off after catching Vizquel's liner.
But, with the crowd of 42,065 in a frenzy, Alomar tapped to
Garciaparra to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something you expect out of these teams,'' said
Stanley, who also homered Saturday. ``Both teams have a legitimate
chance coming out of spring training every year to be in the
playoffs. These teams know they may have to play each other in
October. I have a great deal of respect for all of their players.
This is growing into a pretty intense rivalry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
