<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKYDERBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY DERBY AN AMERICAN SPECTACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words from Kentucky brought forth an instant image. The
favorite for the Kentucky Derby was standing on his hind legs at 6
a.m. last Thursday, straight up, for so long that his rider was
tossed and the horse eventually fell over on his hindquarters.
</P>
<P>
   This is the noble pose for a horse.
</P>
<P>
   It is the ultimate bucking bronco, the image of the huge white
bronco statue at Mile High Stadium in Denver, posing in the noblest
stance of all.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, bucking broncos don't win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   So the madness and mayhem and merriment of the Kentucky Derby
begins with Fusaichi Pegasus, who cost $4 million as a yearling,
cast in the unhappy role as favorite, and a strong favorite at that
(9-5 or so). Derby denizens realize that no favorite has won the
race in 21 20 years, since Spectacular Bid in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The Derby can be appreciated on so many levels. It is one of
America's four true athletic spectacles, along with the World
Series, Super Bowl, and Indianapolis 500, uniquely American. But
the Derby, unlike the other events, attracts all levels of society,
from the ragamuffins to the rich, from Midwestern college students
to celebrities (real and self-anointed). The 130,000 or so fans in
Churchill Downs on Derby Day reflect all of America.
</P>
<P>
   When the horses, perhaps as many as 20, step onto the track
Saturday afternoon, a college band will strike up ``My Old Kentucky
Home'' and no other sports event in America has such a moving
entrance hymn. Eyes get misty.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is reminiscent of what racetracks used to be like. It
is spectacular. For one day a year _ the only day _ the Kentucky
Derby vaults horse racing from its narrow circle into the wide
circus that is American sports in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Across America, the Kentucky Derby has a visceral attraction for
millions. Close to $100 million will be wagered legally on the
Derby and millions more illegally. And, for millions of fans, it is
as much a point of pride as it is winning money to be able to
select the winner of the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to last Thursday morning and Fusaichi
Pegasus posing as the noble steed. Some trainers claim Fusaichi
Pegasus is a basket case but his trainer, Neil Drysdale, insists he
is merely a playful teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who consider picking a Derby winner an intellectual
challenge must first come to a fundamental decision. If the Derby
favorite acts up at dawn before a few hundred people, how will he
act on a Saturday afternoon before 130,000 fans?
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems obvious, but Fusaichi Pegasus's antics will be
chronicled and analyzed all week.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Haskin, who compiles a daily Derby Report on the Internet,
made a keen observation: Fusaichi Pegasus went vertical and goofy
after spotting an ambulance. He also went goofy after winning the
Wood Memorial two weeks ago at Aqueduct after spotting an ambulance
on the track.
</P>
<P>
   There was another telling moment after Fusaichi Pegasus's recent
antics, as the horse was returning to his barn. While Fusaichi
Pegasus passed the stall of The Deputy, who may well be the second
choice in the Derby, trainer Jenine Sahadi was unwrapping a mint to
give to her horse. Fusaichi Pegasus heard the pleasant noise,
stopped in his tracks, and headed over to Sahadi. Sahadi offered
the mint to her rival but Drysdale declined, saying his horse eats
only healthy foods like carrots.
</P>
<P>
   The point, said Haskin, is that Fusaichi Pegasus is extremely
sensitive to sights and sounds. Ordinarily, this would be a
blessing, but what will the Derby's festivities _ a clash of
mesmerizing sights and sounds _ do to a 3-year-old colt?
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi, of course, will be a fascinating story all week. She
once worked in the publicity office at Hollywood Park but took out
a trainer's license and won a Breeders' Cup Sprint race in 1996
with Lit de Justice. Wisecracking trainer Bob Baffert said Sahadi's
success with The Deputy might be due to her husband, also a
trainer. Sahadi took umbrage and stomped out of a press conference.
So horse racing, which is usually behind the times, has a furor
over a successful woman clashing with The Old Ways.
</P>
<P>
   And fans will be fascinated by this Kentucky Derby for another
reason: bloodlines. Specifically, certain horses have bloodlines
that don't allow them to do what other horses can do. Many believe,
after years of study, that pedigree allows horses to run a certain
distance and no farther.
</P>
<P>
   Which, once again, brings us back to Fusaichi Pegasus, the
favorite. Fusaichi Pegasus was sired by Mr. Prospector, America's
top sire of the last quarter-century. Many students of heredity
believe that Mr. Prospector sires sons and daughters who are
brilliant sprinters and great milers but can't go farther than 1
1/8 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby, alas, is run at 1 1/4 miles. When a horse
``tires in the stretch,'' it often is because of heredity as much
as not being ready.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the men and women who spend millions to find a horse
good enough to run in the Derby _ and win it _ will be there.
Others have money to burn and merely love the thrill and celebrity;
others have made a science of breeding. A few, such as Sheik
Mohammed al-Maktoum of the United Arab Emirates, do both.
</P>
<P>
   And the piece de resistance is that the Derby will be run in
Kentucky, the one state where the horse is king.
</P>
<P>
   Anything seems to go with racing in Kentucky, and sinister
rumors persist of the fates that have befallen favorites. Jimmy
Croll, for instance, insisted for years that someone got to his
Holy Bull, who ran the poorest race of his life in the Derby,
finishing 12th in 1994. And the late Sonny Hine hired a private
security force to guard Skip Away, who finished 12th in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At so many levels, the Kentucky Derby is a uniquely fascinating
event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0029EDT &QL; 
