<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-PIPPIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPIG BEGINS HER COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEDHAM, Mass. _ Clenching her fists and glancing heavenward, a
radiant Uta Pippig crossed the finish line of Sunday's James Joyce
Ramble 10K in 34 minutes 33 seconds. Barely allowed to catch her
breath, the beaming three-time winner and darling of the Boston
Marathon was besieged by TV reporters, autograph seekers, and
requests to pose for a photo with every runner who ever owned an
Instamatic.
</P>
<P>
   Not the usual reaction to finishing a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 34-year-old Pippig and the thousands of fans who
lined the 6.2-mile course, the only place that mattered Sunday was
the place they held in each other's hearts, as Pippig chose Dedham
for her long-awaited comeback. A two-year ban on competition
imposed by the German Athletic Federation after testing positive
for performance-enhancing drugs expired April 23, and for Pippig _
who has vehemently denied taking illegal drugs _ it was natural to
make her return in front of a loving Boston-area crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on Cloud 9,'' said Pippig after the race. ``I am so happy
to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, she said, no disappointment in not winning. Suspended
in October 1998 after a test taken the previous April 23 came up
positive, Pippig hadn't competed since the Falmouth Road Race in
August of that year and, lacking race sharpness, was aiming to
finish in 34:30 regardless of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the whole way good,'' she said. ``I didn't push to the
limit. I wanted to enjoy every moment of this race.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the competition was fierce, with a lineup that
could put the popular 17-year-old Ramble, which features costumed
readers of Joyce along the route, on the map as an elite event.
Pippig's time would have been good enough to win here the past two
years, but Sunday Kenyans Teresa Wanjiku and Pauline Konga raced
shoulder-to-shoulder for more than 4 miles before Konga pulled
ahead to win in 33:10, trouncing the course record of 33:37 set in
1987 by Lorraine Moller, an Olympic bronze medalist in the marathon
from New Zealand. For her victory, Konga, 1996 Olympic silver
medalist at 5,000 meters, earned a $1,000 record bonus on top of
the $3,000 first prize. Wanjiku's 33:28 also broke the previous
record.
</P>
<P>
   The men's winner was 40-year-old Simon Karori, also of Kenya, in
30:22.
</P>
<P>
   The day, however, belonged to Pippig. ``This is fun!'' she
shouted midway through the race, laughing as a reporter pulled up
in a motorcycle sidecar, waving at every ``Go Uta!'' sign, greeting
friends waiting in Dedham Square, and smiling every step of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling together with the runners, being with the crowd, it
was so cool,'' she said. ``I love it here.'' Blowing kisses from
the awards platform, she thanked the record field of 2,892 entrants
for their support and the crowd thanked her back.
</P>
<P>
   Pippig plans a few more low-key races around Longmont, Colo.,
where she and her coach/companion, Dieter Hogen, have lived for the
past eight years, before gearing up for a still-unspecified fall
marathon. If all goes well, she could be back in Boston next April
to try for her fourth win.
</P>
<P>
   But she won't be at the Sydney Olympics. Having renounced any
connection to the German federation to protest what she considers
unfair treatment during the drug investigation, Pippig will have to
wait until she gets US citizenship before trying to make her third
Olympic team in 2004, when she will be 38. In 1992, she was seventh
at 10,000 meters, and in 1996, she led the marathon for about 10
miles before dropping out with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful even Sydney could have surpassed the emotions of
Sunday. After hours of dancing eyes and delighted laughter, Pippig
abruptly burst into tears, shaking with relief and joy.
</P>
<P>
   The sobs stopped as suddenly as they had begun. ``I shouldn't
cry,'' she whispered, banishing the last tear. ``I wasn't sure if I
could still do it. Sometimes you wonder. But I can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she smiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
