<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-LEWIS-GRANT-BOS &LR;      05-01 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS STRIKES BLOW FOR HIS DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't pretty to watch, but then few assaults are.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly six minutes Saturday night, heavyweight champion
Lennox Lewis bludgeoned overmatched Michael Grant. Nearly every
time Lewis slammed rights into Grant's face, the challenger fell to
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And Grant kept getting up.
</P>
<P>
   At least he did until a final right uppercut came whistling into
the middle of his face late in the second round and dropped him for
the third time. After lying on the floor for several seconds, Grant
struggled to his feet but couldn't beat the count of referee Arthur
Mercante Jr., who waved the heavyweight title challenge to a close
at 2:53 of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mercante could have done that any time after midway
through the first, which was the first time a Lewis uppercut sent
Grant to the floor. Although Grant got up at eight, he was never
the same after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me with an equilibrium shot,'' Grant (31-1) said.
``That pretty much affected me for the rest of the knockdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had promised to attack Lewis from the outset, few
expected the untested 28-year-old challenger to follow through.
That he appeared nervous and unfocused all week furthered those
doubts, but when the opening bell sounded, Grant attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' Lewis (36-1-1) said. ``I didn't think he
was that aggressive, but he did come and throw some punches. Most
of the time I could see it when he was winding up. I just held my
position so I could get a good shot. I said if he came out
aggressive it would be over early. His style was perfect for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it was, because Grant was imperfect in every way.
Although mistakenly considered the world's top heavyweight
contender, the fact is there was little on Grant's resume to back
that contention. World Boxing Association No. 1 contender John Ruiz
has been criticized because Lewis's refusal to fight him before
Grant cost the champion the WBA belt, but there is no more on
Grant's resume than is on Ruiz's.
</P>
<P>
   The point is not that Ruiz necessarily has fought the toughest
men in the division but that Grant had not either.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters seldom are thrown in with the best competition in the
hopes they will learn from the experience today. They are carefully
cultivated to get to the point Grant did Saturday &UR;  &LR; night _ a $4
million payday to take a shot with Lewis. That Grant was
ill-prepared for such a moment was beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed a lot of heart to keep getting up,'' Lewis said.
``Especially after the third knockdown. I was surprised his corner
sent him back out.''
</P>
<P>
   That third knockdown was actually the second because there was a
standing 8-count in the first. But when Lewis unloaded four
streaming right hands and a left late in that round, Grant
collapsed to the floor a second time with only seconds left before
the bell.
</P>
<P>
   Grant struggled up with two seconds remaining, but the better
man was Lewis. While he looked amateurish at times, he still
destroyed his challenger in fewer than six minutes, so what point
is there to debate between them?
</P>
<P>
   What was obvious was that Lewis never will look like a classic
puncher. His are not crisply thrown shots. They are blows with a
tire iron, punches that do not knock someone down because of their
snap and precision but because they land with the force of a
wrecking ball.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing artistic about that, but the building falls
soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I hit him he went down, so I just kept hitting
him,'' Lewis said. ``I didn't know how hurt he was but I realized
he wouldn't be able to take too many of those punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant learned that quickly, just as he learned his plan of
attacking Lewis wildly was a fool's approach because it allowed the
more experienced 34-year-old champion to lure him in and then knock
him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charging him was stupidity on my part,'' Grant said. ``I was
just too anxious. I didn't execute the things I needed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous. I was prepared but I took the wrong
mentality into it. I leaned on a selfish issue. I should have used
my speed instead of taking it like a grudge match from the
(opening) door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is very smart. He put his hands down and showed me
openings and I tried to knock his head off. He knew I'd open myself
up and he took a half step back and did what was necessary to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis did that for himself and for boxing. If there was one
thing the sport desperately needed Saturday night it was a clear
and devastating winner. If there was one thing Lewis needed to
erase his image as the Hamlet of boxing it was a clear and
devastating win.
</P>
<P>
   Both the sport and its champion got what they needed at Madison
Square Garden. What Grant got was what a lot of people get on
Eighth Avenue and 33d late at night: He got mugged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
