<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING BACK ON BELICHICK'S FIRST MINICAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Odds and ends from Patriots minicamp:
</P>
<P>
   --Coach Bill Belichick and his staff weren't real impressed with
the conditioning of his 36 rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a bit was asked of them, but I told them as a group I
didn't think they were in real good condition,'' he said. ``I don't
think they're ready to play football the way it needs to be played
at this time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our veterans are ahead because they've been working
hard in March and April. What happens to rookie players right
through March when teams are working them out . . . I think a lot
of these guys haven't done a whole lot since then. We all know how
quickly conditioning can leave us. They've seen in these last three
practices they have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   --The Patriots' signing of 26 rookie free agents was the most of
any team in the NFL. Buffalo came close with 23. The reason? This
is Belichick's modus operandi. He's had success bringing along free
agents in the past, particularly offensive linemen such as Orlando
Brown in his Cleveland days.
</P>
<P>
   --The rookies were oriented on how to be a pro football player
for the New England Patriots at one of their evening sessions.
Belichick covered things such as eating habits, living in the
Boston area, security issues, living on their own, time management,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick didn't say he would ban certain nightspots where
players have run into difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things we talk to them about, maybe not so much the
specific places, but we emphasize they're on their own, it's a
different situation than college. Now they have some money and that
brings different opportunities and temptations. We can't baby-sit
them 24 hours a day, but we can provide them with information so
their careers won't get derailed,'' said Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said other than the football, the biggest difference
between college and the professional level is time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more time and more money. How they deal with those
factors is hard to predict,'' Belichick said. ``You think you know
what a guy might be like with more time and more money, but
sometimes you're surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   --J.R Redmond's father, Joseph, speaking on his son's
versatility, said, ``His best position is defense. He should have
played defense (safety or corner) at Arizona State, but the coach
wanted him to be a running back.'' Redmond fractured his right
pinkie during Sunday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   --Belichick on discipline: ``I don't think discipline is short
hair. What it really means is being able to perform under pressure.
In the fourth quarter when the game is on the line, not to jump
offside. If we call for a no-huddle field goal team, that 11 guys
run out there, line up before the gun goes off, and kick the field
goal. Everybody on the team, the coaches, and the staff have to
operate as a unit. You can't segment those situations; you have to
be able to react to them in a disciplined fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   --Clubhouse manager Don Brocher understands class and dignity.
On a team that will have more than 90 players on its roster, he
didn't give out Nos. 87 (Ben Coates) and 78 (Bruce Armstrong).
</P>
<P>
   --Seventh-round pick Patrick Pass, a running back out of
Georgia, insists playing four years in the Florida Marlins system
didn't hurt his football progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say it set me back at all,'' said Pass. ``It
was a great experience for me. If I had to do it all over again,
I'd make the same decision. Right now, I'm going to concentrate on
football.'' But Pass seemed to leave the door open to a return with
the Marlins as an outfield prospect if things didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest thing for Pass is to stay healthy. A few nagging
injuries limited his playing time at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   --The Patriots are still considering a number of veteran free
agents, including wide receiver Leslie Shepherd, linebacker Chad
Cascadden, center Steve Everitt, and defensive linemen Nolan
Harrison, Ferric Collons, Anthony Pleasant, and Mike Frederick.
They'll also scan the June 1 cuts. They must also make some tough
decisions on cuts soon. As they sign their draft picks they'll have
to begin cutting players. Those in jeopardy: fullback Tony Carter,
free safety Chris Carter, safety Larry Whigham, receiver Vincent
Brisby, and perhaps one of the higher-priced offensive linemen _
Todd Rucci and Max Lane. Both players have workout bonuses of more
than $200,000 payable if they complete their program by early June.
</P>
<P>
   --The player showing the most burst, speed, and hustle:
fifth-round pick Melvin Harris, a defensive back from Virginia.
Harris was very impressive on his kick return drills, even more so
than Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   --The most interesting hairdo: Maugaula Tuitele, a linebacker
from Colorado State, who sported a ponytail. And Gil Santos, radio
voice of the Patriots, already was practicing pronunciation of
Tuitele's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
