<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAVIJO PERTURBED BY REFEREES' NONCALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Fernando Clavijo retained his composure a
day after the great non-call that likely cost the Revolution a
chance to defeat Miami Saturday night. Actually, Clavijo displayed
an admirable balance between anger and tranquility after the game,
which concluded in a 1-1 tie after referee Noel Kenny failed to
detect the yank-down of the Revolution's Johnny Torres.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo declined to discuss the play publicly Sunday but said he
will take legal action if Major League Soccer imposes a fine on him
for his postgame protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incredible that we have had two obvious penalties not
called in the last three games at home,'' Clavijo said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the 13,172 in attendance seemed to have seen the
Fusion's Francis Okaroh pull Torres from behind as the striker
closed in on the goal in the 100th minute of a chaotic, physical
match.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, Okaroh received the benefit of the doubt from Kenny
and linesman Roger Itaya for his guile and reputation. Kenny said
he could not see the play and Itaya simply said he viewed two
players running side by side. But the non-call, combined with an
unwarranted earlier caution of the Revolution's William Sunsing,
sent a message that will do little to promote the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, defenders were rewarded instead of punished for
fouls. And offensive play either was viewed skeptically or
downright discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Torres clearly had beaten Okaroh in a race for the ball and was
accelerating for the goal. Torres went to the ground as he was
about to unleash a shot, and the officials must have believed he
tripped himself, a highly unlikely occurrence for a young, highly
motivated athlete who was about to complete a glorious play. If,
however, the officials suspected Torres of diving, they should have
cautioned him.
</P>
<P>
   Sunsing was cautioned in the 98th minute after he had succeeded
in one of his many fakes to evade a defender, and went to the
ground near the Miami penalty area. Sunsing was cautioned,
apparently for embellishing the foul, though the official
scoresheet listed the reason as ``dangerous play.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sunsing was grabbed and tripped by a defender who had
no intention of playing the ball. Sunsing's sways and dribbles
sometimes cause him to be in a vulnerable position, in which even
slight contact can throw him off balance. But that is just the part
of the game MLS referees seem unable to comprehend. So, one of the
league's bright young talents was penalized simply because a
referee failed to understand not only what Sunsing was doing, but
what the crowd seemed to be enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   This game was an example of the MLS shooting itself in the foot
with an ill-advised mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   A chance was squandered for a dramatic conclusion, just what the
league had hoped for by canning the postmatch shootout and
installing 10 minutes of golden-goal overtime. Certainly, Torres's
move would have become a theme for the week and a rallying point
for the Revolution, or for the Fusion if goalkeeper Jeff Cassar
would have stopped the penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brian Dunseth and Rusty Pierce are expected to return to
practice Wednesday, according to Clavijo. Dunseth suffered a
concussion and Pierce had a concussion and a 10-stitch cut in his
forehead after they collided in the 84th minute. The Revolution
played the overtime period with 10 players after having reached the
limit of three substitutes . . . Striker Eduardo Hurtado's
suspension by the MLS has been lifted and he will join the
Revolution for practice Monday. ``I don't anticipate any problems
with Eduardo,'' Clavijo said. ``My conversation with him was good.
Now he has to show the team he wants to come back. It's crucial
because we need everybody physically and mentally ready to go. We
are a team of professional players, not a children's playground
team. He is a member of the team and we all have to accept each
other. But we can talk all day, but everyone has to go out and show
what they can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
