<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CROPDUSTING (Rioblanco de Sotara, Colombia) _ Over a
two-week period, a fleet of crop-dusting counternarcotics planes
taking part in a U.S.-sponsored program to eradicate heroin poppy
cultivation have returned here repeatedly. Time and time again,
residents charge, the planes also sprayed buildings and fields that
were not supposed to be targets, damaging residents' health and
crops. (Exclusive.) By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT23,24) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TRIAL (Shiraz, Iran) _ Thirteen members of Iran's dwindling
Jewish minority are to begin trial on Monday, accused of spying for
Israel, in a case that has been caught up in the swirl of Iran's
internal political battles and could undo the country's tentative
overtures to the West. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-ANNIVERSARY (Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam) _ Around the
city, quite a few people had ``forgotten'' to display the red
Vietnamese flag with its gold star, as their local party watchdogs
had ordered. But this is not to say that there was not a mood of
real pride and patriotism Sunday in a nation that has shrugged off
centuries of foreign domination and is determined now to carve its
own path into the future. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-STRATEGY (Undated) _ Proposed U.S. plans to change a
keystone arms control agreement have revived some of the more
important, if arcane, debates over nuclear strategy that not long
ago seemed consigned to the dustbin of the Cold War. By William J.
Broad.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-EMBARGO (United Nations) _ The first American member of
Congress to go to Iraq to assess the impact of economic sanctions
on the population has concluded that while some of the suffering he
saw was ``heartbreaking,'' he could not support lifting the embargo
imposed by the United Nations after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-LAND (Kagoshi, Kenya) _ As in Zimbabwe, Kenya has a
problem with land distribution and with the many angry people who
do not have any. As in Zimbabwe, there is no question that British
colonialists set the stage for a serious land crisis in Kenya. But
37 years after independence, the source of the problem is not so
clear. There are still white farmers, but most have sold out or
gone into business with Africans. Many of their partners have ties
to President Daniel arap Moi. And Moi himself is one of the
nation's largest landowners. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-PUBS (Manchester, England) _ Since World War I, when it
restricted pub hours to prevent munitions workers from getting
drunk and using poor judgment on the assembly line, Parliament has
kept tight control of its citizens' drinking. The regulations are
complicated, but the best known and most reviled is the law that
requires the country's 60,000 pubs to close at 11 p.m. six days a
week, and at 10:30 on Sunday. Now, more than 80 years later, it
looks as if change is at hand. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REDESIGNING-NATURE (Undated) _ The pastoral landscape of
Canada's Prince Edward Island seems an unlikely place to encounter
one of the most decidedly modern creatures on earth. Yet it is in
the tanks at Aqua Bounty Farms that hundreds of truly novel fish
swim: schools of genetically engineered salmon that await approval
for sale in the United States. A special report. By Carol Kaesuk
Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CAB-SCENE (New York) _ After five years driving a livery cab
on weekend nights through some of the toughest neighborhoods of
Upper Manhattan and the Bronx, Angel Miranda, 34, has a particular
way of doing things, for his sanity and survival. He won't pick up
anyone wearing a ski cap _ a potential robber's mask _ or anyone
with what he calls a ``thuggish'' style of dress. By Sarah Kershaw.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KAISER-LABOR (Undated) _ The 18-month struggle between Kaiser
Aluminum and the United Steelworkers of America, one of the
biggest, longest and fiercest labor disputes in years, is coming to
a head. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SOCSEC (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush plans to push
soon for a fundamental overhaul of Social Security, reopening an
issue that could be among the most combustible and bitterly debated
of the presidential campaign. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-STRATEGY (Boston) _ As shown in his foreign policy speech
Sunday, Vice President Al Gore is turning the same weapon against
Gov. George W. Bush that Vice President George Bush used so
effectively against Gov. Michael Dukakis in an earlier presidential
campaign. He is painting his opponent as inexperienced to the point
of danger. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RIGHTS-COMMISSIONER-PROFILE _ Profile of the head of the U.S.
Civil Rights Commission. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ People of the Seattle region are
not too concerned about the possible breakup of Microsoft. Local
economists say they know of no projects that have been scuttled
because of concern about the company, although one man decided not
to buy a house because he couldn't bare to part with his Microsoft
shares now that the stock price has fallen by about 45 percent. But
this is Bill Gates they're talking about; people say innovation and
creativity will continue in one form or another in the Puget Sound
region. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-THIRDPARTY (San Francisco) _ Third-party software
developers, the programmers whose products are written for use with
Microsoft's Windows operating system, are one of the groups that
the government's proposed antitrust remedies are meant to help. But
what do they really think of the proposal to break up Microsoft? By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As stock analysts pored over
Friday's filings in the Justice Department's proposal to split
Microsoft in two, some marveled as much about what was missing as
what was included. In particular, bankers and analysts who have
read an affidavit prepared by the firm of the respected investment
banker Robert F. Greenhill, which defended the feasibility of such
a task, said the affidavit falls short of justifying why a breakup
would be good for Microsoft shareholders. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-MAG-MEDIA (Undated) _ In the magazine industry, it is an
article of faith that George magazine won't be able to survive the
death of JFK Jr. Frank Lalli, the new editor, is trying to prove
everyone wrong. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISING-MERGERS (Undated) _ A look at some acquisition
developments in the world of advertising. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   MICHAELJORDAN-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column:
Marketing the new Imax film, ``Michael Jordan to the Max.'' By
David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: Here's an
old wrinkle for the new economy. As more and more electronic
marketplaces crowd onto the internet, selling goods and services
has seemed to be turning into a youngster's game, a forum in which
tech-savvy entrepreneurial types in their 20s are running the show.
But when it comes to dealing with the would-be clients, the b-to-b
dot.coms are looking over steel mills, auto parts companies, indeed
all of the basic industries. They're looking for people who can
talk the talk of the customer base, and persuade their generational
counterparts to switch their transactions from handshakes to
mouseclicks. By Claudia Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: Since the
stocks of e-tailers have fallen from favor on Wall Street, the
companies have had to think about marketing budgets that actually
serve the purpose of attracting customers, not investors. So portal
deals have been the second line item on the budget, after
television ads, to come under the microscope of e-tailing
executives who are no longer willing to pay hundreds of dollars to
acquire each customer. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-TV-MEDIA (Frankfurt) _ A prominent television news
anchor is suspended from ZDF, one of the German national networks,
because of evidence he had been working with a PR agency on the
side. The PR agency sent him a fax that alluded to great things he
had done for them and suggested a number of story possibilities he
should pursue. The anchor, Alexander Niemetz, has denied any
wrongdoing, but the real point is that German journalists often
make money on the side through advertising and promotional work. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC-MEDIA (Undated) _ Folo on Friday's federal court
ruling against MP3.com, an apparent victory for the recorded music
industry in its effort to guard copyrights in the era of digital
distribution. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-RADIO-MEDIA (Undated) _ ClickRadio Inc., an upstart
Internet radio service, plans to announce a licensing agreement
soon with the record company BMG Entertainment that grants it the
rights to BMG's entire catalog of artists. The deal, closely
following a similar pact ClickRadio announced last month with
Universal Music Group, is part of an industry effort to let
listeners create customize music channels for the Internet. By
Laurie J. Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   BERKSHIRE-HATHAWAY (Omaha) _ They were shaken by a big downturn
over the last year, but shareholders of Berkshire Hathaway came to
the company's annual meeting here this weekend as reverential as
ever toward their chairman, Warren Buffett. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SUFFIXES (Washington) _ Armed with a formal but vague
go-ahead from one of its advisory panels, the Internet's
international oversight body has begun writing a plan for new
suffixes that would be added to ones like .com, .net and .org used
in addresses on the global network. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   EXCITE-HOME (Undated) _ Excite(at)Home plans to announce a
version of the Excite portal for mobile applications. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   KPN-TELEFONICA (Undated) _ Talks are heating up between the
mobile phone units of the Netherlands' KPN and Spain's Telefonica.
A deal could presage a bid for Orange, Britain's third largest
mobile telephone company. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TATE-MUSEUM (London) _ Britain's huge new Tate Modern
prepares for its opening. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   CRAZY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``Crazy'' by Benjamin Leibert.
</P>
<P>
   VANYA-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews ``Uncle
Vanya'' by the Roundabout Theater Company at the Brooks Atkinson
Theater.
</P>
