<HEADLINE>
SHARKS AWAIT FRIENDLY TANK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Sharks have a library of feel-good films to choose
from on their flight back to San Jose:
</P>
<P>
   Sharks vs. Stars, Game 3, 1998
</P>
<P>
   Sharks vs. Avalanche, Game 3, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Sharks vs. Blues, Game 3, 2000
</P>
<P>
   They hope to add:
</P>
<P>
   Stars vs. Oilers, Game 3, 2000
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks own an impressive and resilient record in Game 3s
over the past three seasons. They trailed the Stars 2-0 in 1998,
went home and tied the series. A year later, down 2-0 to the
Colorado Avalanche, the Sharks returned home and tied the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 3 is pivotal for us,'' center Mike Ricci said. ``We've
got to come out with our best game. I believe in our team, and I
believe our team is going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the Sharks tormented the St. Louis Blues with
home wins in Games 3 and 4 to fuel their first-round upset. They're
2-1 at home in the playoffs this season but have been outscored
9-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're going in the Shark Tank, and the fans are a big part
of things,'' said Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor, with a 5-2 Game 3
loss in Edmonton still fresh in his mind. ``We have to go out there
and take the life out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharks coach Darryl Sutter applauded the way his Sharks rallied
last night in a 1-0 loss full of missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter was so confident that the Sharks will bite back inside
the noisy San Jose Arena, he said farewell to Reunion Arena with
these parting words: ``See ya in Game 5.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks have reason to be optimistic. Although they became
only the fourth team in 31 years to start a playoff series by being
shut out in consecutive games, they finally put pressure on Stars
goalie Ed Belfour and kept the score within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about the effort, but not about the result,''
center Vincent Damphousse said. ``Both sides, it was a very, very
tight game, and that's the way we have to play to beat them. I
think we showed tonight we can beat them. Tonight we played a
stronger game and played the way we beat St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin of victory was a Mike Modano rebound shot off a Brett
Hull slap shot that bolted off Sharks goalie Steve Shields' pad,
and a bevy of Sharks chances gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks managed 19 shots, but missed the net 20 times, 31
times in the two games. Ricci misfired on a two-on-one early in the
first period. Marco Sturm couldn't poke in a puck that hit off
Sydor and dropped in front of Belfour at the left goal post. Jeff
Friesen and Patrick Marleau couldn't handle cross-slot passes on
odd-man rushes in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks went 0-for-5 on the power play _ 0-for-11 in two
games _ including one in the final minute of play. With Shields on
the bench, the Sharks attacked with a two-man advantage. Belfour
stoned slap shots from Gary Suter and Friesen, a poke check by
Ricci and finally a rifle from the point from Brad Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave ourselves a chance to win,'' Friesen said. ``We have
to go home and get the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   They have plenty of footage to flame Game 3 emotions.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
