<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MODANO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS USUAL, MODANO SPRINGS INTO THE SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mike Modano knows how to play the part of star better
than anyone on the Stars. Despite goalie Ed Belfour's third playoff
shutout this season, and the Stars' special teams, which killed the
final minute when the San Jose Sharks had a two-man advantage,
without Modano, the Stars might still be playing Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Modano scored the only goal in the Stars' 1-0 victory against
the Sharks last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played great tonight,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher
said. ``I think he was one of the few players besides Eddie who
really looked good. He was flying out there, and he's been flying.
A player of his caliber, when he's skating like that, it's tough to
get a hold of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks have yet to tame the Stars' center. Modano has four
goals in the playoffs, including two against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   He got the game-winner out of the way early last night.
</P>
<P>
   A Brenden Morrow pass to Brett Hull set up a breakaway for Hull.
Sharks goalie Steve Shields deflected Hull's shot wide to Modano at
the top of the left circle. Modano sent the puck between two
defenders and underneath the diving Shields at 7:26 of the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came out pretty high, but it was right on my stick,''
Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano has become a broken record. It was his 36th career
playoff goal, breaking the franchise record he had shared with
Steve Payne since Friday night. In the first-round series against
the Edmonton Oilers, he had become the Stars' all-time postseason
scoring leader when he recorded his 84th point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just seem to accumulate,'' Modano said. ``Good things
happen when your team is consistent and in the playoffs this
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano is accumulating frequent-flyer points at a
businessman-like pace. He now has scored a point in six consecutive
games, which matches a personal best he set during last season's
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our line is getting four or five good opportunities a game,''
Modano said. ``As long as those keep happening, we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, who was first on the Stars in points (81), goals (38),
assists (43) and game-winning goals (8) during the regular season,
is feeling good. That has the Sharks down in the dumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs felt real good, just skating and feeling like I have
some jump,'' Modano said. ``When I'm feeling that way, good things
seem to happen. The puck seems to follow me around, and it seems
like I'm in good position all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Modano who has the Stars in position for a Stanley Cup
repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous player. There's no doubt about that,'' Stars
forward Blake Sloan said. ``He pretty much does everything that's
asked for in any hockey player. He plays defensive-style hockey. He
plays offensive-style hockey. He plays with tenacity in the
corners, and he's got tremendous speed, too, which makes him that
much more difficult to stop. That's not to mention that he can
shoot the puck as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the whole package. Sometimes I find myself just
watching him. He puts you in awe.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
