A1913 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     05-01 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK IN A HUFF OVER STARS' POOR EFFORT UP FRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Only the Reunion Arena scoreboard correctly identified
last night's Game 2 winner. Certainly the mood of the opposing
coaches provided zero clues.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Sutter was relaxed, smiling and cracking a few
one-liners. If his San Jose Sharks ever score a goal in this
series, a gleeful Sutter might add a song-and-dance routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you in Game 5,'' he added when departing the media-room
podium. Sutter's grin was one of those ``hey-I'm-serious'' kind of
things.
</P>
<P>
   For a total contrast, Ken Hitchcock's red face obviously matched
the color scheme of his posterior-area. Usually a media-room
orator, Hitch was in a huff. His comments were short, not so sweet,
and his mood was basically summed up by this dart aimed in the
direction of the Stars' locker room:
</P>
<P>
   ``They had more players play well than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a quick walk toward the coaching quarters at Reunion,
it was mentioned to Hitchcock how he seemed sour. What's this? Not
even a 1-0 victory, back-to-back shutouts, a 2-0 series lead, and a
tense final 60 seconds when The Eagle of old _ meaning the playoffs
a year ago _ suddenly saved the evening, could cheer up Hitch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' he replied. ``Not enough players were on board. To
beat this team, more players than tonight will have to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant tomorrow night in San Jose. But before then, it would
be best to do some re-evaluation about the direction of this
series. And try to figure out why the expected nasty stuff was
suddenly replaced last night by a style of hockey that might as
well have been Sweden vs. Norway in some European Cup sectional
qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks were humiliated in the opener and took the blows
instead of delivering them, a distant contrast from what served
them so well in the upset of St. Louis in the first round.
Forty-eight hours later, San Jose showed up without top scoring
threat Owen Nolan, which also removed a physical presence. He was a
scratch due to injuries that were a carryover from the Blues
series, but the Stars added to his pain in the opener when Nolan
was a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter threw a curve ball by also scratching a bruiser like
Ronnie Stern, then going with a speed lineup. No way San Jose wins
this series, or even a game in this series, by trying that finesse
stuff on the Stars _ right, right, right? Where's the usual bite,
Darryl? Bryan Marchment is just not cut out for the Ice Capades.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Sharks didn't win with this style, but as Hitch's
demeanor showed, they did everything they needed to do to steal a
critical game. Except actually steal it.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, without your best player in uniform, then try to
hang around, keep it a 1-goal affair, hope for the break that gets
you to overtime, and then, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose game plan reached a point of perfection when Derian
Hatcher was whistled down for cross-checking with exactly 60
seconds remaining, gifting the goalie-less Sharks with a 6-on-4
advantage. Then they won the initial faceoff in the Stars' zone,
another huge plus.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, who had faced minimal pressure most of the evening, was
on the spot. Eddie, however, answered like this was 1999 all over
again. Three quality chances by the Sharks resulted in nothing
except thunderous cheers for Belfour from a Reunion sellout that
like the goalie, had to quickly come to life after 59 minutes of
rather mundane hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask much more from our team than they did
tonight,'' said Sutter, who explained the final minute this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three good chances. You approach that situation hoping
to get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three other teams in NHL history have opened a playoff
series with back-to-back shutouts, and for what's it worth, two of
them (the Devils and Rangers in the '90s), went on to win the
Stanley Cup. In his overall displeasure, Hitchcock did toss
compliments the way of his defensemen (all six of them, and
particularly Dave Manson), and, of course, Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we had people up front tonight who didn't play well at
all. That will have to be addressed,'' Hitchcock added.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement with the coach is not unusual around here, but
publicly, at least, there was no rebuttal to Hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we did get kind of lucky tonight,'' defenseman Darryl
Sydor said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Hatcher: ``Our effort really wasn't what we wanted it to
be. But we did what we had to do to win the game, thanks to Eddie.
When you don't play well, and you still win, that can be a good
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock didn't see it that way, and will spend the next 48
hours stressing just that.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
