r s BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX     05-01 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Even with the Sharks having a six-on-four in the final
minute of the game, Jamie Langenbrunner, for one, felt good about
the Stars' chances of winning faceoffs in their own zone.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Guy Carbonneau _ an 18-year veteran and one of the
league's best at winning faceoffs _ took two key defensive draws in
that minute to help seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of guys on the ice then who have played in a lot
of games like that,'' Langenbrunner said. ``Seeing a veteran guy
like him taking those key faceoffs, you can't ask for much more.''
\Nsubheds:Getting even better The Stars were impressive enough on
the penalty kill in the regularson, setting an NHL record by
killing off 89.3 percent of opponents' power plays.
</P>
<P>
   They've been even better in the postseason, especially in two
games against the Sharks. After going 0-for-5 with a man advantage
last night, San Jose is now 0-for-11 in the series with a man
advantage. And, during one second-period power play last night, the
Sharks allowed the Stars to spend 40 seconds in the Sharks' zone,
getting off two shots during that sequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you shut a team out two games in a row you're doing
something right defensively,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
\Nsubheds:Very careful The Sharks might have been concerned about
the loss of Owen Nolan in Game 2, but no doubt it weighed on the
Stars' minds as well.
</P>
<P>
   Stars captain Derian Hatcher said the loss of an opponent's best
player can sometimes force a team to make the fatal mistake of
relaxing _ something the Stars didn't do last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the board and see their best player's not
playing, sometimes you tend to let down,'' Hatcher said. ``We
talked about trying not to let down. It's just like if they saw
\RMike\S Modano wasn't playing, they might let down. You can fall
into that trap easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan isn't expected to be on the ice tomorrow night in San Jose
and might not return this series. \Nsubheds:Grateful for trade Had
Stars center Scott Thornton remained with the Montreal Canadiens,
he would be doing ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what,'' he said. ``Whatever I would have been
doing it wouldn't have been as fun what I am doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who was acquired from the Canadiens on Jan. 22 in
exchange for Juha Lind, is playing in the fourth playoffs in his
10-year NHL career. By this time most springs, Thornton wasn't
playing, or watching, much hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would turn it on periodically,'' Thornton said. ``It's a
sore spot when you're not playing. It's not a lot of fun. It feels
like your season is really incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, the most playoff games Thornton played in
any one season was 1998 with Montreal, where he played in nine
games; the Canadiens failed to reach the playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things I've seen it happen to other guys _
guys who get traded and they end up going far in the playoffs,''
Thornton said. ``It's something that I always hoped would happen to
me. It's been a good move for me to play with a team with this much
talent after 10 years of struggling.'' \Nsubheds:Lehtinen progress
Stars winger Jere Lehtinen practiced at yesterday's morning skate
but was again a scratch for the game. He will, however, travel to
San Jose, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best it's felt since I played against Phoenix,'' said
Lehtinen, whose last game was against the Coyotes on the last day
of the regular season. ``It was better today; I skated harder. I
have to see how it feels tonight and tomorrow morning. We haven't
had a set back so that's the main thing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Lehtinen and Hitchcock said that Lehtinen's right ankle has
not suffered any increased swelling and there has been no major
regression. Hitchcock has said that when Lehtinen returns to
practice, that would mean he was a few days away from playing. Does
that mean that his return is imminent?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can play this game, but it's tough to say,'' said
Lehtinen, who missed 65 games this season due to the injury. ``I
don't want to put a timetable because I don't really know; it's
been so long. It's better to go day-to-day basically and see how it
feels better.'' \Nsubheds:Feeling good Despite being down two games
to none, at least one person in the Sharks' organization doesn't
expect to see his team get swept at home.
</P>
<P>
   It's San Jose coach Darryl Sutter, who told reporters when
leaving the interview room, ``We'll see you at Game 5.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
