<HEADER>
A1915 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX     05-01 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND SHUTOUT PUTS STARS GOALIE IN ELITE COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS_ Three times in the past 30 years has an NHL team started
a series with consecutive shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Must be goalies like Patrick Roy, Curtis Joseph or Dominik
Hasek, right? They wish.
</P>
<P>
   With his third shutout in the 2000 playoffs, Stars goaltender Ed
Belfour became the fourth goalie to join that elite company by
shutting out the San Jose Sharks, 1-0, for the second consecutive
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher said, ``the biggest
reason we won was Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Shielded by a defense that continues to be stronger than
two-month-old milk, Belfour maintained his domination of the Sharks
by posting the first back-to-back playoff shutouts of his career.
</P>
<P>
   This comes amid remarks from some hockey analysts, who said
Belfour isn't in his 1999 Stanley Cup-winning form. They're right.
</P>
<P>
   He's in 2000 Stanley Cup shape ... which could be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure there are a lot more critics out there right now
trying not to give him the benefit of the doubt, but he's been real
solid,'' Stars center Mike Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   How solid?
</P>
<P>
   Last night he stopped 19 shots, including three in the final,
frantic minute with the Sharks on the power play and goalie Steve
Shields on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has allowed 11 goals in the playoffs, five in the Stars'
one loss and a total of six in their six victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he wasn't satisifed by his play in the first round,''
Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``But we still got through it
and he got another chance to be big and that's exactly what he
was.''
</P>
<P>
   How big?
</P>
<P>
   He has allowed three goals in five home playoff games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   He has stopped 37 shots in the series and hasn't allowed a goal
since Edmonton's Jim Dowd scored at the 1:07 mark of the third
period in Game 5 of Round 1, pushing Belfour's personal
record-streak of scoreless minutes to 138:53 and counting.
</P>
<P>
   He is 7-0 in the past seven home playoff games, with four
shutouts running his career total to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three seasons, he leads all NHL goalies in playoff
victories (32) and shutouts (7).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strong and focused,'' Belfour said. ``That's key for me
is when I am feeling that way. I am seeing the puck real well.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Sharks see it, that's part of the problem. With the
Stars' defense limiting the number of opportunities on even
strength or the power play, Belfour has been perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him and when's he is in that zone, there is not much
for rebounds,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said. ``You have to get
something he doesn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour is seeing everything. The problem is for a goalie such
as Belfour who has said he would rather see more shots to stay in
rhythm, he isn't seeing much.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing just 18 shots in Game 1, he saw 19 last night,
including just one in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he doesn't see a shot for 10 or 12 minutes and he
still comes up with the big save,'' Stars winger Jamie
Langenbrunner said.
</P>
<P>
   He almost always does. He has the Cup to prove it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
