<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     05-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAN'T CLOSE IT OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - All the right pieces were tucked in all the right
places, tightly, neatly and in orderly fashion, as the Lakers
pushed the Sacramento Kings across the floor and to the edge of
playoff elimination Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant was soaring high enough, often enough to rack up
frequent-flier miles. The Lakers had most of the rebounds. Most of
the loose balls. Plenty of defense. All the momentum. And a
10-point lead midway through the third quarter. ...
</P>
<P>
   Everything they needed, packed in a cardboard box and ready to
be mothballed, along with the Kings, for a nice, hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Arco Arena rafters started to shake, the Kings started
to rumble, the decibel meter red-zoned, and it all came crashing
down, like fine china on the San Andreas fault.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, extended stay in the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   With a late collapse and a 99-91 loss, the Lakers gave the Kings
their first sign of hope as they extended this best-of-five series
to Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ticked off, very ticked off,'' Bryant said. ``I thought we
had the game in our hands and let it slip away real fast. We wanted
to close this thing out.''
</P>
<P>
   They failed, despite 35 points from Bryant, who recorded a
career playoff high for the second straight game. They failed,
despite denying Sacramento the lead until early in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then it all unraveled in a blur of missed Shaquille O'Neal free
throws, offensive rebounds from tiny Tony Delk and a flurry of
baskets by Peja Stojakovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought energy from the crowd kept the (Kings) playing,''
Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``A few things went wrong for us,
and the game got out of hand real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   When it all ended, the Kings had strung together a 21-4 run that
turned a Laker lead into a 94-82 deficit with 2:32 left to play.
Down on the scoreboard and then just down, period, after failing to
complete the sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to be down,'' Jackson said. ``They should be
embarrassed by the way they played today. This is not a good
performance from our team. We have to come back and play better. So
we should lick our wounds tonight, come back (today) and be ready
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   A case of overconfidence?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that way at all,'' Glen Rice said. ``We realized
what we had to do coming in here we tried to take the life out of
them, and it just didn't happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they controlled the game for most of three quarters, this
never looked like a vintage Lakers performance. O'Neal struggled
from the field (8 for 22) and from the line (5 for 14), settling
for 21 points and 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Lakers went 16 for 32 from the line - ``That's the
ballgame right there,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, Bryant's theatrics and team defense balanced O'Neal's
low production. Not this time. Rice scored just 13 points on
5-of-13 shooting, and the defense disappeared as the Kings scored
33 points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored 16 points in the final frame, but O'Neal went 1
for 4 and no one else made a dent. Stojakovic, a non-factor until
Sunday, scored all 19 of his points in the second half. Delk got
nine points in the fourth, but it was his four offensive rebounds
that hurt most.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber did the rest, with 29 points, 14 rebounds and eight
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their interior defense stiffened, and we weren't able to make
the adjustments necessary at that time in the game,'' Jackson said.
``They were denying Shaq access to the lane, and they did a good
job powering against him. And our adjustments weren't good. ... Our
defense came undone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an unfamiliar sight, the NBA's most dominant team this
season frittering away a late lead in a big game. To find the
Lakers' last meaningful loss, you have to trace through the
schedule to perhaps a mid-March defeat at Washington that snapped
the 19-game winning streak. Or maybe back to early February, when
they were routed at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   So where did that air of invincibility go?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we still have that air,'' veteran Ron Harper said. ``I
don't think I'm going to allow us to be down as a basketball team.
The guys know what kind of attitude that I have. The one thing I
told the guys is we let this slip through our hands, it's our
fault. We can't blame it on one guy, we've got to blame it on what
we did. We missed foul shots and did things that we just don't
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing they don't do: close out a series well. The Lakers
of Kobe and Shaq have never had a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically wanted a sweep because I've never done it before.
Something new,'' Bryant said, then let a hint of swagger slip out:
``But there's always next series.''
</P>
<P>
   And amid the anger and frustration, Harper offered this don't-
worry-be-happy final thought: ``Put it this way. The sun will shine
tomorrow, right?'' he said. ``So we should be OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1922 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN     05-01 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ ISN'T WHOLE FOR A HALF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - These things don't happen. For all of Shaquille
O'Neal's amazing ability, not even he can make 7-foot-1 and 330
pounds of center fade into the background.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a single half.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by his standards - and we're talking otherworldy here -
O'Neal was just another player in the second half of the Lakers'
99-91 Game 3 playoff loss to the Kings on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At the break, he was again the indomitable force the Lakers have
grown to expect and the Kings to dread.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidently, the Lakers led by five.
</P>
<P>
   But this was less a tale of two cities than two halves.
</P>
<P>
   And in the second half, O'Neal scored just six points. His game
seemed to fade the longer it went.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, he was just 1 for 4 from the field, with
no rebounds and no assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was, if he didn't have that pop in his
shot or else a lot of body on him, and he just couldn't get off the
floor with a body on him,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``But
he had a real struggle in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal blamed no one, nor handed out any particular credit. The
Kings sent a second defender, usually a guard, each time he caught
the ball, but coming at him aggressively is hardly some new
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I just missed some chippies that I usually don't miss,''
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was hounded by ex-Laker Vlade Divac and designated
hack-a-Shaq defender Scot Pollard (total fouls: 11). Then some
little guard would come darting in each time he took a pass down
low.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought in the second half we did a better job of when he
shot the ball, not allowing him to get it back,'' said Kings coach
Rick Adelman. ``That's what we talked to Vlade about, when he
shoots it, you just keep guarding him. Don't try and find the ball.
That's really important, because he is so quick to the ball that
you just have to give his guy help.''
</P>
<P>
   Some had another theory on why O'Neal's production faded in the
second half. Somebody else's was taking off?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe (Bryant) really took a lot of shots, and that came out of
him,'' Kings guard Tony Delk said. ``It's better for us. We can
give Kobe his points, we can't let Shaq get 30-to-40.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with 21 points on 8-of-22 shooting, 17 rebounds,
three assists and a blocked shots. All very good numbers, of
course, just not the kind O'Neal is used to posting.
</P>
<P>
   This is the guy who scored 46 in the Lakers' Game 1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, when O'Neal was taking only four shots,
Bryantwas taking 10 and making half of them. He finished with 35
points.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even by the time Bryant started firing aggressively in the
fourth quarter, the Kings had built a 12-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to be just a little more hungry on Tuesday,''
O'Neal said. ``We're kind of upset. We'll look at film (today) and
see how poorly we played. We just have to pick it back up.''
</P>
<P>
   For all those ready to unfurl a championship banner at Staples,
and for any Lakers who might have gotten a little carried away by
their recent success, O'Neal figured a lesson might have been
learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was,'' he said. ``We didn't play well at all, all
day. Even though they played the best ball they can play, we still
had a couple opportunities to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just gave it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for O'Neal's atypical performance in the second half, Divac
went for the simple explanation:
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he missed a lot of shots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-HOUSTONOPEN-HNS &LR;      05-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOUSTONOPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE WOODLANDS _ If this keeps up, they can change the Shell
Houston Open trophy to a Foster's can topped with a kangaroo
throwing a boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   Either that or it can be a statue of a burly, goateed guy
missing a putt.
</P>
<P>
   Both would be appropriate after Australian Robert Allenby
survived in a sudden-death playoff only because Craig Stadler
bricked three putts inside 10 feet, then stuck a 10-footer of his
own on the fourth extra hole for the victory at the Tournament
Players Course.
</P>
<P>
   The SHO. It's Australian for golf. There's no other way to
explain how two fast friends from Melbourne can take back-to-back
victories at the Tournament Players Course. Last year, it was
Stuart Appleby. This time, his closest buddy did a great Crocodile
Dundee imitation, except that it was a Walrus he was wrestling with
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On a blustery day that kept scores higher than they had been all
week, Allenby fired a 72 _ the highest final-round score by a
Houston winner in 23 years. He then put a ball in the water on the
first playoff hole and still found a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Appleby, who had missed the cut Friday in his
title defense, was watching his mate come up big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was pretty emotional, watching Stuey win,'' Allenby
said. ``And for him to come out and be here, we got a bit
teary-eyed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Appleby won the '99 SHO, it was his first victory since his
wife, Renay, died in a traffic accident. In the scoring tent after
the tournament, Allenby's wife, Sandy, was the first person to give
Appleby a victory hug.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's finish made it two years in a row that she has been the
first to give the victor a squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to have my first U.S. tour win,'' said Allenby,
who matched Stadler's 13-under 275 total, a stroke better than
Loren Roberts and Joel Edwards. ``It's also nice to have Stuart
Appleby's name right above mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby seemed almost as stoked for his friend as he was for his
own victory a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely pumped for Robert,'' Appleby said. ``I'm so
happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama was thick throughout most of Sunday. Allenby and
Stadler were playing together, and while they each had problems
during the course of their rounds, they never were far from the
lead. Allenby overcame a water ball and double bogey at the third
hole, and Stadler dodged the trouble of bogeys at the ninth and
10th holes.
</P>
<P>
   Allenby had a one-shot lead through 16 holes and had some
company along the way. When he got to the 17th fairway, Appleby was
walking in the gallery to the right of the 17th green. Little did
Appleby know that Allenby would practically doink him in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Allenby's shot was about 10 yards to the right of the green and
chipped 12 feet by the pin. His par try slid by the high side,
dropping him into a tie with Stadler, who narrowly missed a 35-foot
birdie try.
</P>
<P>
   So to the 18th they went, tied at 13 under par.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes earlier, Brad Fabel had lost his chance with a
double bogey on the 17th when his drive went into the jungle right
of the fairway. Edwards missed his chance at a spot in the playoff
when his tee shot found the left trees on No. 18 and he had to
punch out, making a bogey to drop to 12-under.
</P>
<P>
   When Allenby and Stadler had to make testy par putts to force
the playoff, it looked like the extra holes would be a showcase for
sharp putting.
</P>
<P>
   When Allenby put a 6-iron into the water just a few feet from
the bulkhead at the 18th, he gave Stadler a seemingly simple chance
at victory. He was 35 feet left of the hole and needed only two
putts for victory. But the first one stopped five feet short and
the second one buzzed the right lip. Allenby sank an eight-footer
to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Both players made routine pars on the 10th and 18th holes, which
they alternated on in the playoff. But Stadler missed a six-footer
at the 10th and an eight-footer at the 18th, either of which could
have won the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a bit of intrigue on the 76th hole, the matter
was settled. Allenby bombed a 140-yard wedge out of the left
fairway bunker over the green and into the bleachers. His nearest
point of relief was to the left of a television tower left of the
green. He chipped 10 feet past the hole, then stroked the putt into
the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler had powered his approach over the pin and about three
inches into the rough behind the green. His flop shot stopped 12
feet short, and his putt to extend the tournament died off to the
right.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler was trying to win for the first time since 1996. He had
quite the home-course advantage as fans roared approval at his good
play, while Allenby's support was more polite than partisan.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was Allenby, who also had a four-year drought
between wins, who came through. His last one came in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   After the win, Australians were calling in from all over.
Houstonian Steve Elkington, who was born and raised Down Under,
called Allenby on the green via a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt they'll be checking in from the Outback, too.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
