<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     05-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ Momentum might as well be the equivalent of eternal
life on Earth, as unattainable as it appears to be for the Astros
so far this season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foiled once again in their attempt to string together more than
two consecutive victories, the Astros on Sunday suffered a tough
4-3 loss to the Milwaukee Brewers at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This game was one the Astros never should have let escape their
grasp. In command for most of the afternoon, they lost a three-run
lead in the sixth inning and eventually lost the game on Jeromy
Burnitz's two-out RBI double off Doug Henry in the bottom of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating that we haven't been able to put more
wins together,'' Astros third baseman Ken Caminiti said. ``But it's
not like we're not trying. We're definitely capable of playing
better than we're playing. We're just not clicking right now; we're
not meshing. But we just have to keep pushing and try not to get
too frustrated. I still believe we're going to show more
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros closed out April with a 9-14 record, their most
losses in the opening month of the season since they were 11-14 in
1989. Their .391 winning percentage is their worst in April since
they opened the 1984 season with an 8-14 record (.364).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough year so far,'' said Astros starting pitcher
Shane Reynolds. ``We've just started out bad. We're trying to put a
winning streak together, and we still have a chance to win this
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds had won his previous three starts before taking a
no-decision in Sunday's game. He held the Brewers to three runs
(two earned) in 6 innings before the bullpen took over.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthanded reliever Yorkis Perez retired the only batter he
faced, and Henry (0-1) retired five of seven before his encounter
with Burnitz, who was hitless in his previous eight at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to stay away (with the pitch), and I got a little
more of the plate than I wanted to,'' said Henry, who has allowed
nine runs in his 11 appearances. ``It just gets frustrating. I'm
trying to turn this around, and it's not working. But I ain't
quitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a different set of circumstances, Astros center fielder
Roger Cedeno probably would have caught Burnitz's game-winning hit,
which sailed over his head and bounced over the fence, allowing
Marquis Grissom to score the decisive run. Because Grissom was at
second base, Cedeno was playing shallow with hopes of being able to
throw Grissom out at the plate on a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit that ball pretty good,'' Cedeno said. ``With the
winning run on second base, I had to play kind of in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Burnitz's double, the extent of the scoring was a pair
of three-run homers _ Richard Hidalgo's in the second and Geoff
Jenkins' in the sixth, the latter serving as the precursor to a
near brawl. After Jenkins' massive blast, which he admired from the
batter's box before circling the bases, Reynolds came in high and
tight with an 0-2 pitch on the next hitter, Charlie Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers starter Jason Bere already had hit Hidalgo in the plate
appearance following his home run. Reynolds insisted he wasn't
throwing at Hayes, but both benches and bullpens emptied before
order was restored. Home-plate umpire Dan Morrison issued warnings
to both managers, and the game was completed without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure any of it was intentional,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the Astros scored in just one inning and produced only
seven hits was disturbing, especially considering they're hitting
just .217 through the first three games of the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``As explosive as our offense is, we should be scoring a lot
more runs,'' said Caminiti, who was 1-for-2 with three walks.
</P>
<P>
   The first of Caminiti's three walks gave the Astros their first
baserunner of the game, and left fielder Matt Mieske followed with
an infield single, setting the table for Hidalgo's sixth homer,
which ranks second on the team behind Jeff Bagwell's eight. The
Brewers tied the game in the sixth on Jenkins' towering shot to
right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly feel like I only threw one bad pitch the whole
game, and that's the one that tied it up,'' Reynolds said. ``This
might have been the best I've felt all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers' winning rally started with one out in the ninth.
Henry walked Grissom, who was pinch-hitting for relief pitcher
David Weathers. After James Mouton flied out to right field, Mark
Loretta singled to right, setting the stage for Burnitz's heroics,
which dropped the Astros to 0-4 in one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
