<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-01 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
THE WOODLANDS _ This is not to disparage anything about Robert
Allenby's performance under stressful and pressure-packed
circumstances.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the picture that followed his wonderful and gutsy Shell
Houston Open playoff win Sunday is, to say the least, more common
on the PGA Tour than 32-inch waists.
</P>
<P>
   There's the young, handsome champion, shaking his fist into the
air after sinking his nerve-racking 12-foot putt on the fourth
playoff hole and watching his opponent barely miss. There's the
tall, slim, fair-haired champion with the prim-and-proper accent,
rushing to the ropes to hug his blond wife and beautiful baby.
There's the trophy presentation. There's the obligatory kiss
planted on the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Craig Stadler.
</P>
<P>
   He's lost 50 pounds and still buys pants that he has to hitch up
after every shot. He stands there, all disheveled, his hair a mess,
sweat dampening his shirt and his emotions on his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   He plays the game the way we all would, if we had his talent.
Mis-hit a shot? Throw the club. Hit an iron into the rough? Slam
the club into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Mis-hit a five-foot putt for the money? Let out a choice
four-letter word. Blow another putt, then another, then another?
Call yourself stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have at it,'' Stadler told reporters, after running his hand
through his mussy hair in complete frustration. ``Take your best
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to second place at the
SHO, which Stadler so eloquently described in everyday terms:
``Second place isn't worth a compared to first.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadler only endeared himself more to the people who crammed
themselves around the TPC hoping to see him win a tournament that
should've, would've and could've been his. The Walrus wallowed and
wavered and came down with the yips at money time, just like we all
would have.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody seemed to care. Why not? He was one of us, someone
with whom the hackers can relate, while Allenby was one of the
countless PGA pretty boys, with so much talent it almost makes us
sick.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, the best golfer on this day ultimately won and
deserved the $504,000 check and all the pride and prestige that
goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Allenby stayed focused and determined throughout the tournament,
but especially on the gut-wrenching final day of the SHO, which
never ceases to amaze with its great finishes. Allenby made big
shot after big shot even when the odds of his winning seemed
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Allenby deserved was to hear cheers when his
approach on the first playoff hole landed in the water, while
Stadler was safely on the green in two.
</P>
<P>
   But the rude cheers indeed happened, because much of the crowd
grasped the obvious. Stadler is Everyman if Everyman had a game.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly a classy show put on by the fans, but, hey,
how many times does a former Masters champion, a terrific golfer
with 12 PGA Tour wins to his credit, look and sound like one of the
fellas in our regular Sunday morning 50-cents-a-skin foursome?
</P>
<P>
   ``The playoff pretty much stunk,'' Stadler said. ``I hit a lot
of good shots and a lot of really bad putts.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. On the first playoff hole, the title should have been
Stadler's, but he pushed a five-footer right. Groan. We've been
there.
</P>
<P>
   On the second playoff hole, it should have been Stadler's title
again after a terrific iron to six feet, but he yanked the putt too
much. We've been there.
</P>
<P>
   On the third playoff hole, Stadler had a straight eight-footer
for the win. He pushed it again _ ``Cold-cocked it,'' he said.
We've been there.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after Allenby received a favorable drop after hitting
his approach under the bleachers on No. 10, Allenby chipped to 12
feet and made the putt. Stadler got a good read from Allenby's putt
but missed his 12-footer by an inch.
</P>
<P>
   We've been there _ disappointed and disheartened.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, someone asked Stadler what he'll take from the bad
playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of Bud Lights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. All those fans who cheered wildly for Stadler and groaned
with his every miss as if it was them flubbing the putts probably
did the same. In fact, some obviously got a head start on Stadler
drowning his sorrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose that many opportunities,'' Stadler said, ``it
certainly doesn't leave a good taste in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Bud Light. We've been there.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
