<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     05-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IN the sixth inning, after Milwaukee's Geoff Jenkins had unloaded a
game-tying three-run homer off Shane Reynolds, the Houston pitcher
brushed back Charlie Hayes with an inside fastball, and Hayes took
a few ominous steps toward the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon you heard Bill Brown, calling the game on TV, utter
the most ominous phrase in baseball: ``Both benches have emptied.''
They came from the dugouts, and they came from the bullpens. But
only words were exchanged, and after a warning to both teams from
the men in blue, the game continued.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was splendid. Only a few days earlier, a brawl
between the Tigers and White Sox had resulted in the suspension of
16, including both managers. A total of 25 players and coaches were
hit with fines.
</P>
<P>
   And in a casual moment Sunday, before tempers flared, Jim
Deshaies had mentioned there was talk of the pitchers forming their
own union. Brown jokingly asked the former Astros pitcher, now his
partner in the booth, if he would seek the job of running the
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will support their agenda any way I can,'' he said. ``The
problem is, you want the really top pitchers to be out front. But
the good ones win no matter what; they could be pitching from
second base.''
</P>
<P>
   You reflect that the pitchers are rebelling because of a trend
that can no longer be ignored. Virtually every recent change made
by the game's interior decorators has favored the hitter. The mound
is lower, the strike zone smaller, and in most of the new parks _
Enron Field somehow comes to mind _ the fences are closer.
</P>
<P>
   Today pitchers are scolded for not throwing inside and driving
back the hitters, whose tender sensibilities are offended if they
can't crowd the plate. Yet the umpires rarely call the inside
strike, adding to the frustration of the men on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   The tension builds. Pitchers feel more and more under siege,
pressured to take back with force the inside corner. Some hitters
now wear pads on their arms and legs and don't mind taking one for
the team _ as long as the location is fairly benign. Any pitch high
and tight is regarded as a barbaric practice, roughly in the class
of clubbing baby seals.
</P>
<P>
   In another era, it was the general custom for a batter who felt
abused to meet the pitcher under the stands after the game. The
next advance in retaliation turned out to be the bunt along the
first-base line. This offered two exciting options: If the pitcher
fielded the bunt, the batter could level him going down the line.
And if the first baseman came after the ball, forcing the pitcher
to cover the bag, the runner could nail him with his spikes. Spikes
were metal in those days, and players wore them very sharp. They
cut each other like fighting roosters.
</P>
<P>
   Always popular, of course, was the ``purpose pitch,'' a term
created by the late Branch Rickey, a pious man who did not attend
games on Sunday. The pitcher avenged a fallen teammate by drilling
someone on the opposing side. The goal was to punish, not to maim.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, a batter would demonstrate his displeasure by
throwing his bat at the mound. But you seldom see this today
because it was hard to be accurate from a distance of 60 feet, six
inches.
</P>
<P>
   What batters are partial to now is charging the mound and trying
the case with knuckles. Of course, it makes no sense at all. The
pitcher has to throw inside for tactical reasons, as well as to
show his teammates he doesn't lack innards. Of more importance, no
owner wants to see his high-priced talent injured in a scrap or a
pileup.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the benches clear, valuable merchandise is in
jeopardy. So plainly the remedy of going to the mound has failed,
and baseball now must look for alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manager must control his players,'' said Detroit skipper
Phil Garner. Of course, Phil said this prior to getting slapped
with an eight-day suspension, along with Chicago counterpart Jerry
Manuel. It is hard to see how the managers can exercise control
from their vantage point in the commode.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Tigers and White Sox penalized and the total
number of games to be missed, 82, represent the harshest group
punishment on record. In an interesting footnote, the judge in this
case was Frank Robinson, baseball's director of operations. In his
own playing days, Frank had his share of fights.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers have the worst record in baseball, meaning it isn't
hard to imagine their frame of mind. The Chicago fireworks started
when Dean Palmer, the Detroit third baseman, rushed the mound after
being hit by Jim Parque. The Tigers may have found an outlet for
their stress, but their play hasn't improved.
</P>
<P>
   As home runs pile up, and pitchers walk the park, one forecast
seems safe. This is going to be a long, hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
