<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-NAPA500-LADN     05-01 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NAPA500-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CONTROVERSY, MAYFIELD WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. - Jeremy Mayfield, under a cloud of suspicion by
NASCAR, overcame a day of adversity and anxiety to win the NAPA
California 500 on a brilliant Sunday afternoon. Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   More than four hours after taking the checkered flag at the NAPA
California 500, the sanctioning body announced his Ford Taurus
failed to meet the requirement for minimum roof height during a
routine post-race inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like Mayfield's dance on the No. 12 of his Mobil
1-sponsored car, might have caved in the roof. According to NASCAR
spokesman Danielle Humphrey, the required height of 51 inches was
not met at a post-race inspection, although she did not have the
amount of infraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The win will not be affected,'' said Humphrey. ``The car will
be confiscated by NASCAR so it can be looked at further.''
</P>
<P>
   With his performance, Mayfield became the 10th different winner
of a Winston Cup Series race this year in 10 starts. His journey
before an estimated sellout crowd of 110,000 at California Speedway
took him from a lap down and in last place to a 0.300-second margin
of victory over Bobby Labonte and a winner's check of $125,925.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, we had a great car,'' said Mayfield, who went 62 races
before scoring his second Cup victory. ``We had a problem in the
oil lines. The gauge was pegged at 340 degrees, but it hung in
there. That won the race right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was burning up in my car and everything else. It really
shows how tough this team is.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 22 lead changes among 15 drivers in the 250-lap event
that took 3 hours, 20 minutes and 50 seconds to complete. Darrell
Waltrip, retiring from racing after a 29-year career at the end of
the season, gave his fans one last chance to applaud as he led lap
156 before fading to the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd and Jeff Burton completed the top five, followed by
Ward Burton, pole-sitter Mike Skinner, Rusty Wallace, Dale Jarrett
and Tony Stewart. Defending champion Jeff Gordon, who was never a
factor throughout the day,finished 11th. He was one of 20 cars in
the field of 43 that finished in the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Mayfield, the Owensboro, Ky., resident who
finished second at this race in 1998 to Mark Martin, went through
an eventful weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NASCAR vice president and chief operating officer
Mike Helton acknowledged there was ``an issue with the No. 12
car.'' There had been reports that Mayfield's fuel did not meet a
post-race inspection in the last Cup race at Talladega, Ala., two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Talk in the garage area has focused on possible suspensions,
loss of points and fines, although Helton said it would be early
this week before a decision is rendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' Mayfield said about the off-track
distractions. ``I don't know what to say because nothing has come
out yet ... but these two weeks have been pretty weird for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But no tougher than Mayfield's day at the track. The Mobil 1
Ford Taurus driver overcame:
</P>
<P>
   -- The oil problem which plagued him all day and was never
fixed. Mayfield spent the entire day with his back against the
32-gallon oil container.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rookie Matt Kenseth, who probably would have won had there
not been two yellow flags in the last 30 laps. Kenseth, who led
four times for 119 laps, rallied to finish third after falling as
far back as seventh when he pitted on lap 220.
</P>
<P>
   -- A failed ignition box on the final restart of the race on lap
246.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into turn one I had a good start and all of a sudden it
quit running,'' said Mayfield, ``Your natural instinct is you start
hitting switches somewhere and I knew where the ignition box was
and I slapped it real quick. Bobby was under me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Man, we're done here,' but I guess he got loose
or whatever and our car recovered. I just had my hand up trying to
motion him off because that could have been a big wreck if I would
have switched boxes and it wasn't that
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who assumed the Winston Cup points lead by 20 points
over Martin, wanted to pass Mayfield on the outside, but checked up
when he saw Mayfield slow and lost momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kinda scared me a little bit because I thought I was going
to run into him,'' said Labonte. ``It was one of those deals where
I kind of had the pass but wasn't sure I was clear.''
</P>
<P>
   What was clear to Labonte was that without the yellow flags,
Kenseth would have won his first Cup race in his 15th start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Matt would have won and I might have finished
second,'' said Labonte. Kenseth, who won Saturday's Busch Grand
National Series Auto Club 300 for the second straight year, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were two cautions at the end and we didn't (win),''
said the rookie points leader. ``I mean, a 4 1/2 - or five-second
lead - plus we were running a tenth faster than Bobby was with 30
laps to go - unless I did something incredibly stupid or something
broke on the car, we were probably gonna win the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not the way it turned out. It's great to run third,
but it's not my goal to finish third.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth lost the lead when Jimmy Spencer, who sat on the outside
pole, became the third of four drivers to hit the wall in turn
four. He came in for four tires, as did Labonte, but Mayfield opted
for two tires and two bags of ice. ``One time I was like, `I'm not
going to make it.' '' said Mayfield, whose worst finish at the
Fontana track is 12th in the 1997 inaugural event. ``I've never
gotten out of a car but I was burned up and I didn't think I was
going to make it until the end, but they filled me up with ice and
I took off from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield led just 26 laps, at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is made of strong people that have been through a
lot and never gave up all day long,'' said Mayfield. ``No matter
how far you're down, just keep digging and keep working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
