r a BC-WATER-REUSE-2Takes-LA     05-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-REUSE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS REUSED WATER SAFE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &HT;    By HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chemical and biological contaminants in wastewater
to be recycled for drinking under Los Angeles' ``toilet-to-tap''
program pose a threat to human health because of the difficulty of
detection and filtration, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in the water reuse field said there is no way to know
for sure whether treated wastewater is really free from every
possible chemical and biological contaminant, and testing for such
matter is often unreliable or outright flawed.
</P>
<P>
   City and state officials insist the project to recycle
wastewater for household use -- labeled by critics as a
``toilet-to-tap'' program -- will produce safe, clean, drinkable
water for residents of the San Fernando Valley and other parts of
Los Angeles. The project, now on hold, could start producing
recycled water for use in about five years.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say there are too many variables, and using filtered
wastewater for human consumption should only be considered ``a
solution of last resort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always inventing new chemicals for all kinds of
purposes, and they end up in the wastewater,'' said water reuse
consultant Daniel Okun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to measure them because they don't tell us
what's there -- they're trade secrets. There are thousands and
thousands of these chemicals in the water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Okun is a retired University of North Carolina environmental
engineering professor who has served as a consultant on reuse
projects throughout California since the 1970s. He opposes reuse
for human consumption, calling it ``a risk I believe is
unnecessary,'' but says more needs to be done in the area of
agricultural reuse and water conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Local and state water officials dispute Okun's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water is safe,'' said S. David Freeman, general manager of
the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very stringent water-quality standards. This is not
the DWP saying the water is safe, this is the (state) department of
health, which throws you in jail if you're violating the health
standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said treated water coming from the Donald C. Tillman
water reclamation plant -- which will be spread into the ground,
where it percolates some 500 feet into the groundwater supply -- is
much cleaner than the water that, for example runs through people's
lawns, picking up fertilizer and pesticides, before it reaches that
same groundwater supply.
</P>
<P>
   He and other officials also noted that the water Los Angeles
imports from other regions -- specifically from the Colorado River
and the San Francisco Bay Area -- is already made up partly of
treated wastewater. Upstream communities treat their sewage and
then dump the water into the rivers feeding the Bay Area, before
that water is pumped to Southern California and disinfected, they
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The East Valley Water Reclamation Project was supposed to start
pumping water in April but is on hold while the DWP board and the
City Council review it.
</P>
<P>
   The DWP board is expected to discuss it Tuesday, while the City
Council's Environmental Quality and Waste Management Committee is
expected to schedule a hearing sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   It will at first treat 10,000 acre-feet of water a year, but
could be expanded up to 35,000 acre-feet -- enough to supply about
70,000 families for a year. The water will spread underground for
about five years before it is drawn up through wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people should be anxious or worried,'' said
David Spath, chief of drinking water and environmental management
for the state Department of Health Services. ``I think there are
enough safeguards in place to reduce the risk to a level that is
very, very low.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most well-known health studies in Southern
California are based on one of the nation's oldest water reuse
projects, the Montebello Forebay project near the Whittier Narrows
Dam, run by the Water Replenishment District of Southern California
and the Los Angeles County Sanitation District since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies of the health of people drinking water from that
project have turned up rates of cancer and diseases that are no
different from the rates found in similar populations drinking
water from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would expect, if there was an adverse effect from drinking
reclaimed water, the more you drank the worse people's health would
be. It didn't work out that way,'' said Earle Hartling, water
recycling coordinator for the Sanitation District. ``It was
statistically scattered, just like you would find anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Ongerth, a former chief of the state Bureau of
Sanitary Engineering and a co-author of the state's regulations on
water reuse, said the study was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Ongerth, who agrees with Okun in opposing the use of recycled
wastewater for human consumption, said it is extremely difficult to
measure the health of a large population over a long period of
time, especially one as mobile as Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1941 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WATER-REUSE-2nd-Take-     05-01 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-REUSE-2nd-Take-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: Southern California 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Also, it is difficult to know exactly what quantity of
reclaimed water people in the study have ingested. And sometimes
health effects such as cancer take a much longer time to manifest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't prove anything,'' Ongerth said. ``It's almost
impossible to prove either way, safe or unsafe. It's a matter of
degree and a great deal of subjective opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   A study of water reuse done by the National Research Council in
1998, considered one of the most comprehensive looks at the issue,
said the results of the Montebello study ``do not necessarily prove
the safety of reclaimed water for human consumption.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it calls for more sophisticated tests at a national
level to evaluate health risks associated with using reclaimed
water.
</P>
<P>
   Hartling acknowledged there are many unknown substances present
in untreated water but said ``every single time this new pollutant
du jour comes up ... health department officials set standards for
them, and the treatment process
</P>
<P>
   we operate has been found to remove them to down below the
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRC study, titled ``Issues in Potable Reuse,'' said that
while reusing wastewater for human consumption appears to be safe,
it should be considered ``a solution of last resort.''
</P>
<P>
   The report added that it should ``be adopted only when all other
alternatives for nonpotable reuse, conservation and demand
management have been evaluated and rejected as technically or
economically infeasible.''
</P>
<P>
   So what are the alternatives?
</P>
<P>
   There are always other options, of course, but experts note that
some of them are significantly more expensive, involve political
obstacles and environmental consequences, or are unreliable during
a drought.
</P>
<P>
   Importing more water, for example, is not likely because
Southern California is being forced to live within its current
amounts due to environmental concerns, as well as competition with
other states that use the same water sources, said Metropolitan
Water District spokesman Adan Ortega.
</P>
<P>
   Other options include encouraging more conservation measures,
either by farmers who use large quantities of water or by suburban
households that consume the majority of their water in keeping
their lawns green.
</P>
<P>
   But both of those involve asking for voluntary measures from
other people and are therefore not considered reliable. In
addition, both groups already have taken conservation steps.
Farmers have improved their irrigation techniques, while households
reduced their water usage by installing low-flush toilets and more
efficient shower heads during the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The point, Freeman said, is to plan ahead for the future and
become more self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we absolutely need this last drop of water today?'' Freeman
said. ``Of course not. We don't need any last drop of water today.
Anybody can be successful in water supply in years of plenty. It's
our job to be sure there's enough water here when we have a
drought.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman added: ``My daddy was an umbrella salesman, and he said
any fool can buy an umbrella on a rainy day. It takes a wise one to
buy when the sun is shining.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
