<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1942 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN     05-01 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELK PUTS A CHARGE INTO KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - This was a little hard to see coming, no short
jokes intended.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll have to forgive the Lakers if they were not expecting
Tony Delk to come off the bench in the fourth quarter Sunday and
make like Teddy Roosevelt leading the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Delk is a 6-2 backup, journeyman point guard. Plays behind Mr.
Flash himself, Kings star Jason Williams. Delk spent most of the
season's first half never getting off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there he was in the fourth quarter, acting like Magic
Johnson in miniature.
</P>
<P>
   Delk had four offensive rebounds and nine points in the decisive
quarter. The smallest guy on the floor, and he was pounding the
boards. He and Predrag Stojakovic, another forgotten bench player
in this series, were the sparks that led the Kings to an 18-2 run
the lethargic Lakers could never overcome.
</P>
<P>
   And Delk pulled it off while giving the Kings something Williams
often struggles to provide - control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes as a team, I think you have to slow the ball down,''
Delk said. ``Sometimes we rush our offense. We've done that a lot
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The playoffs are really important, you can't just run down the
court and take the first shot available. You can't do that. Teams
are too good.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day, Delk had 11 points and five rebounds - all on the
offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever had a game like that,'' he said.
``I've had a lot of rebounds, but never all offensive. This is
something new for me. I took a page out of Ron Harper's book.''
</P>
<P>
   And Delk did his damage in the fourth quarter while being
guarded by Kobe Bryant, who has at least five inches on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Delk played tremendously,'' Kings forward Chris Webber
said. ``His patience, his dribbling, hitting the 15-footer. We
could really see it during the game. He was ready and pumped up to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   A guy who sat on the bench in 21 of the Kings' first 55 games
was coming up big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Delk was just terrific,'' Kings coach Rick Adleman said.
``What can you say? He defended, he got those offensive boards. He
had a pretty tough assignment in Kobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's been playing so well for us. He's the one guy in all
three games who played pretty darned good.''
</P>
<P>
   Stojakovic had been the Kings' second-leading scorer against the
Lakers in the regular season, averaging 20.3 points in the four
games.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the first two games of their playoff series, he was 2
for 12. Sunday, he had 19 points and four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a different player on his home court,'' Bryant said.
``His confidence level is higher at home. We could have chased him
a little bit better and done a better job of guarding him.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the Sacramento bench was coming through.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat the Lakers, we have to have those two guys click, and
they did tonight,'' Kings center Vlade Divac said. ``Tony just put
on a show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
