r s BC-CAR-NAPA-SIDE-LADN     05-01 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NAPA-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENSETH'S LUCK TAKES A TURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA - Is it better to be lucky than good?
</P>
<P>
   Ask Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Winston Cup rookie knows the answer after finishing
third in Sunday's NAPA Auto Parts 500 before more then 100,000 at
California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``To finish third was great,'' said Kenseth, who finished .87
seconds behind winner Jeremy Mayfield. ``But it's not my goal to
run third. I want to win races. If we would have run third or
fourth all day and finished third, I could take that. But when you
lead almost the entire race and dominate the last half and have it
wrapped up and lose it at the end like that, it's a tough one to
swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you consider how strong Kenseth was Sunday. He
led 119 of the 250 laps, including 78 of the final 163, and was a
comfortable 4.92 seconds ahead of second-place Bobby Labonte with
just 30 circuits remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a four-and-half, or five-second lead and were running a
(tenth-of-a-second) quicker than (Bobby Labonte),'' Kenseth said.
``So unless I did something incredibly stupid or something broke in
the car, we were going to win the race. But that's not the way it
turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jimmy Spencer changed that when he hit the outside wall
in turn four, bringing out the fourth of five cautions and wiping
out Kenseth's margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I planned on losing all day,'' Kenseth joked. ``I knew
something was gonna happen, and the minute I start thinking to
myself, `Boy, we are in pretty good shape,' sure enough, something
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   That caution brought the field to pit lane on lap 220. Kenseth
and Labonte each took four tires. Martin and Mayfield each took
two, putting them up front. Kenseth and Labonte dropped to seventh
and ninth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just made more sense to get four tires than two,'' Kenseth
said. ``As soon as the caution came out, I told (crew chief Robbie
Reiser), `give me four tires.' In hindsight, maybe I could have
just got two and would have been able to hold (the field) off,
maybe not. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did everything in my power, and my team did everything in
their power to win the race. We just came up a little bit short.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for lack of trying.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth fought his way through the field and was running fourth
when the caution was shown for the final time with seven laps
remaining after Dick Trickle scraped the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be tough to come back (from seventh),''
Kenseth said. ``We were too loose with new tires the entire day. I
knew we had our work cut out for us. I'm actually pretty happy to
come back and finish third, considering we came out in the pits in
(seventh) place and bunched together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like our chances were a little better (when the track
went green with four laps left). That (caution) helped. There just
wasn't enough laps.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth slipped by Jeff Burton on the restart and zoomed to
within two-car lengths of Mayfield and Labonte but could get no
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both better on short runs,'' Kenseth said. ``We saw
it all day. I would get new tires with air pressure down, and my
car would just be extremely loose. I just couldn't stand on the gas
like I needed to be able to catch those guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0136EDT &QL; 
