<HEADLINE>
NOT EVERYTHING RUNS IN CYCLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About that promotion running each day on the
Dodgers' radio broadcast - $1 mil and a new home from an Internet
company for the fan who picks which player will hit for the cycle
in that game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most baseball fans with a clue know this particular
freakish feat is even more rare than a no-hitter. It just doesn't
get quite the same attention.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Did ya know the White Sox's Jose Valentin did it
last week? And he got the single, double, triple and home run in
order.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Dodgers, a cycle brings even more psychotic odds.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years have elapsed since Wes Parker did it in May 1970 a
10-inning game, by the way. That's the longest cycle drought of any
current big-league team.
</P>
<P>
   And Parker is the only L.A. Dodger to (begin ital)ever(end ital)
do it.
</P>
<P>
   By our calculations, that makes the chances of it happening ...
about as good as a Dodgers catcher throwing out a runner this
season.
</P>
<P>
   They're 0 for 20 in that department so far, in case you were
wunderin'...
</P>
<P>
   - Gabe ``The Babe'' Kapler, the pride of Taft High, is also
referred to as ``The Texas Ranger with Big Guns'' in the June issue
of Muscle &AMP; Fitness magazine, which tabs him as one of baseball's
all-star bodies for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``Rising Star With Abs and Ability'' is Montclair Prep's
Brad Fullmer of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's worst physique? Boston Red Sox reliever Rod Beck, of
course, the man with a lot of guts outta Grant High. ...
</P>
<P>
   -A capper on Kapler:
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers run a radio spot with a husband at a game noticing
his wife checking out Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   Husband: ``He put up pretty good numbers last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wife:: ``6-2, 208 pounds, 34-inch biceps ... I'll say those are
good numbers.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   -If the Clippers wanted Charles Barkley as a player-coach for
next season, they wouldn't have to twist his ego too much. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Maybe you knew, but we didn't figure it out until the other day
that the alternate rock group ``Lucious Jackson'' got its name from
the Philadelphia 76ers forward of the '60s, (best known as Luke
Jackson), one of Wilt Chamberlain's teammates on the '68 NBA title
team. ...
</P>
<P>
   -When more than one person comes out to contest the authenticity
of the basketball sold at auction for more than $550,000 and
purported to be the one Wilt used to score 100 in a game in '62,
you gotta think something's up.
</P>
<P>
   In the same auction, Beverly Hills author and songwriter Seth
Swirky shelled out more than $60,000 for the ball that supposedly
rolled through Bill Buckner's legs in the '86 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   That ball was part of the collection of actor Charlie Sheen, who
paid about $100,000 for it in the mid-'90s. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Orlando Brown, the Cleveland offensive lineman accidentally hit
in the eye by an official's flag last December, has reportedly
retained attorney Johnnie Cochran to represent him in a suit
against the league he plans to file.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie C will likely use the ``eye for an eye don't lie''
defense. ...
</P>
<P>
   -``Love And Basketball'' should do more for USC's men's and
women's basketball than anything else this recruiting season. ...
</P>
<P>
   -IOC head spaz Juan Antonio Samaranch told the folks organizing
the 2004 Games in Athens that prehistoric conditions won't be
tolerated. He specifically said the city has to improve its plan
for accommodations, traffic, security, communications, venues and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   So much for giving the Greeks time to start their own
toilet-to-tap water project. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
