<HEADER>
A1982 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     05-01 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW CHALLENGERS LEFT FOR LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The mismatch between Lennox Lewis and Michael
Grant was good for Lewis, bad for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the undisputed champion in the eyes of everyone who is
objective, did what he wanted to do: He destroyed a reputedly good
opponent to bolster his image as the world's dominant heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it with Tyson-like finality: the equivalent of four
knockdowns in less than two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's no Mike Tyson, and he never will be. The Briton is
a very good boxer with considerable power but neither the savage
warrior nor the sublime boxer who can carry the heavyweight
division - and boxing, to a good extent - on his massive shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   After this fight, we're left with a good, but uninspiring
heavyweight champ, and no one who can give him much of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sad, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Grant, only a 2-1 underdog, was supposed to have been a
legitimate test. He was young, athletic, hungry and Lewis' size,
even a bit bigger. Some experts actually picked him to win.
</P>
<P>
   However, he was an embarrassment come fight time. If he's
learned anything in his career, he forgot it Saturday. He fought
like a big, strong amateur who had no business in the ring with a
fighter of Lewis' skills.
</P>
<P>
   And, again, he was deemed Lewis' best possible opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Who else is out there?
</P>
<P>
   -Evander Holyfield. The 37-year-old former champ, who faces John
Ruiz next month for the vacant WBA title stripped from Lewis, might
be the best equipped to compete with Lewis, but we saw what
happened in two forgettable bouts between the two.
</P>
<P>
   -David Tua. Some believe the big-punching Samoan could test
Lewis. He's short (about 5-10) but wide (about 225 in shape) and
has a tremendous punch.
</P>
<P>
   However, many wonder whether he's simply too small for the 6-5,
250-pound Lewis, who probably would be able to keep Tua at a
distance (as he did Holyfield) with a stiff jab and his own big
right. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Tyson. See above. Too small (begin ital)and(end ital) too far
over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   This fight (begin ital)does(end ital) have the most intrigue
because of Tyson's notoriety and is the fight Lewis wants because
of the buzz it would cause and the money he'd make, not necessarily
in that order.
</P>
<P>
   However, we wonder how serious Tyson is about fighting at all.
After two postponements, he's scheduled to face Lou Savarase on
June 24 in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there's an opportunity out there for me and him,''
Lewis said. ``I'm the man at the top, and he knows where to find
me.''
</P>
<P>
   After those three? No one.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Steward, Lewis' trainer, said openly he believes there
are no promising heavyweights and that his fighter could reign for
three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four boring years.
</P>
<P>
   More Lewis: Promoter Panos Eliades said immediately after the
fight that Lewis would face Francios Botha on July 15 in London.
</P>
<P>
   Botha doesn't have the speed or athleticism of Grant but is a
solid boxer and has experience in big fights. He won't win, but he
probably won't go out with the whimper Grant did. ...
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who received a reported $10 million for Saturday's fight,
earned $28,328 per second - about the same as the average
wage-earner makes in a (begin ital)year.(end ital) ...
</P>
<P>
   New rankings: The publisher of a boxing Web site has established
rankings similar to the Associated Press college football poll, in
which selected writers vote.
</P>
<P>
   So far, roughly 25 major boxing writers have agreed to take part
in the monthly poll orchestrated by Howard Sirota of
boxingranks.com.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to have more than 100 writers worldwide participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a new ranking system that will completely replace
the corrupt and self-serving rankings jerry-rigged by the sectarian
sanctioning bodies,'' a group of five prominent writers said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope the writers don't become corrupt and that
they're able to put in the considerable time necessary to rank 10
figh in each of 17 divisions - 170 fighters.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big job.
</P>
<P>
   The first poll has been posted on the Web site. ...
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: IBF junior middleweight champion Fernando Vargas
is negotiating to fight No. 1 contender Ross Thompson on July 29
and could fight Felix Trinidad in December.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' trial on assault charges has been pushed back to late
July. He and four others have pleaded not guilty to charges they
beat up a man last year in a home outside Santa Barbara. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's official, or as official as any fight involving Julio Cesar
Chavez: Kostya Tszyu will defend his WBC junior welterweight belt
against Chavez on July 15 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Many fear for the 37-year-old former champion's safety.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is 103-4-2, with 86 KOs. He could stop fighting now and
call it a decent career. ...
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 seats - $300 to $900 - remain for the Oscar De La
Hoya-Shane Mosley fight June 17 at Staples Center. ...
</P>
<P>
   The junior middleweight division is becoming more interesting by
the minute.
</P>
<P>
   First, middleweight Bernard Hopkins said he'd like to move down
to claim some of the fame and fortune at 154 pounds. Now, Antwun
said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Echols, a friend of Michael Nunn's from Davenport, Iowa, would
like to avenge a loss to Hopkins first.
</P>
<P>
   After that - or if that fight doesn't happen - he'd like to meet
Vargas. He said he walks around about 165 and would have no problem
making 154.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said. ``I'd have no problem making
weight. I think Vargas would be a good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Echols faces Lionel Ortiz in a middleweight bout Friday in North
Carolina on ESPN2. ...
</P>
<P>
   Paul Spadafora defends his IBF lightweight title Saturday
against Mike Griffith in Pittsburgh on HBO. ...
</P>
<P>
   The latest daughters to become boxers are J'Marie Moore (Archie
Moore) and Irichell Duran (Roberto Duran). Let's see, that brings
the total to five. The daughters of Muhammad Ali, Joe Frazier and
George Foreman already are pro fighters.
</P>
<P>
   They all have sons. Don't boys fight anymore? Well, Marvis
Frazier was a pro boxer - sort of. ...
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Duran, well aware of the rigors of the sport, said he'll
never forgive his daughter for her decision to become a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   So what does he do? Signs for another fight at 48. He'll face
Pat Lawlor - who once beat Duran - on June 3 in his native Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Duran, who began his career in 1967, will have fought in five
decades. He should have quit two decades ago. ...
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Martinez of Fontana, the fighter who made the U.S.
Olympic team only to quit ``for financial reasons,'' has turned
pro.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Cameron Dunkin, said it's likely Martinez will fight
on the ABC show in L.A. the afternoon of the De La Hoya-Mosley
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Dunkin also advises junior lightweight champ Diego Corrales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid (Martinez) can already hang with Corrales. It won't
be long before you hear a lot about him,'' Dunkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunkin also has signed Larry Mosley, Shane's cousin. ...
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Tapia is scheduled to defend the marginal WBO
bantamweight title Saturday against Javier Torrez in Las Cruces,
N.M., on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the promotion, Tapia is trading two $25 tickets to
the fight and $50 (donated by HUD) for guns.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, 387 guns were turned in. ...
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Briggs' shocking decision loss to unknown Sedreck Fields
last week was a big blow to his career. ...
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Williams, the heavyweight from Long Beach, has become an
``opponent.'' He was stopped by Denmark's Brian Nielsen in the
fourth round last week in Copenhagen. ...
</P>
<P>
   Israel Vasquez faces Angel Chacon in a 12-round junior
featherweight bout Saturday at Fantasy Springs Casino in Indio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
