<HEADLINE>
IT'S OLD HAT TO THESE BALL CATCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Richard Villalobos of West Hills saw last week's
review of the ``Game Hat,'' a patented ballcap made by a fellow
near San Diego that helps baseball spectators shag foul balls
without the use of a glove.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't agree more about our lack of enthusiasm about
wearing it as fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's probably because he, along with Richard Brown of
Pasadena and Bill Hunt of Macon, Ga., have for the last dozen years
have their own patented ball-grabbing device disguised as a hat.
Which not only looks more snazzy, but, with a little more
dexterity, cou efficient for souvenir collectors.
</P>
<P>
   While the ``Game Hat'' might be more adept at snaring line
drives because it's easy to flip off, the trick to the ``Catch-It
Cap'' (patent numbers 4,628,543 and 4,768,232) is getting the hat
off your head and then your left hand into the slot on the left
side in time. A mitt-like padded glove concealed inside does the
catching.
</P>
<P>
   (The newer version soon to be out will take the back inside
panel of the cap and make it easier to get your hand in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really made to catch line drives that well,'' said
Brown, who, in the early days of production, hand-sewed the mitts
into the caps himself. ``This is more for high fly balls - like
home runs. And you really need two hands to make the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Catch-It Cap,'' now manufactured and marketed through
athletic apparel company Fila, is available for $24.95 by phone at
888-92CATCH or for $19.95 on the Internet at Web site
www.catchitcap.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
