r s BC-GEN-BOOKS-LADN     05-01 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT UP HOLLYWOOD'S FAIRWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Book: ``The Greatest Player Who Never Lived,'' by J. Michael
Veron.
</P>
<P>
   Vital stats: Sleeping Bear Press, $22.95, 286 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The story: A piece of fiction? That's what it says. But the more
you get wrapped up in this fact-finding mission of law firm intern
Charley Hunter, the more the Grisham-like history-mystery seems
plausible. Hunter is asked to catalog old files that once belonged
to Bobby Jones - the legendary amateur golfer and a former partner
at the firm. What Hunter discovers piece by piece is the existence
of another golf legend, Beau Steadman. Who? That's the point.
</P>
<P>
   The potential movie: Since the book's release several months ago
it has sold out of the publisher's first two printings reps from
Creative Artists Agency and Artists Management Group in Hollywood
are among a half-dozen groups who've asked about buying the movie
rights. Also asking is Jack Nicklaus Productions, headed by former
ABC Sports executive Terry Jastrow (who's married to actress Anne
Archer).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dumbfounded me, all the attention it's received lately,''
said Veron, a trial lawyer in Lake Charles, La., of his first
novel.
</P>
<P>
   The best gauge for a movie future will be how another golf
flick, ``The Legend of Bagger Vance,'' does this summer. That
movie, directed by Robert Redford and starring Matt Damon, Will
Smith and Charlize Theron, is also based on a book written in the
similar vein of Veron's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they have a herd instinct (to making movies
today),'' Veron said. ``If someone makes one about a blue shirt and
it goes well, everyone starts making one about a blue shirt. I
guess if (`Bagger Vance') does well, it gives us a better chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But until then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a huge case that goes to trial May 15 that's really
taking all my time right now,'' Veron said. ``Maybe that helps, so
that I don't get too distracted by all this talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up: Veron is working on a second novel entitled ``The
Greatest Course That Never Was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
