<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OJAI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES FLOW AT OJAI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE JARES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. - Tradition at the Ojai Valley Tennis Tournament is
almost palpable, like the heat of the sunshine in Libbey Park,
where the main matches are played, or like the tang of the freshly
squeezed orange juice served free each morning.
</P>
<P>
   Probably never has the tradition hung thicker than in the last
four days, when the event celebrated its 100th anniversary and
introduced a Wall of Fame, honoring the 80 people who have
participated in ``The Ojai'' and later won at least one Grand Slam
title. (The list includes Bill Tilden, Billie Jean King, Pancho
Gonzalez, Stan Smith, Pete Sampras and Lindsay Davenport.)
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of those champions, and many other alumni, came back
for the festivities, sharing their memories under the eucalyptus
trees at Libbey and at a banquet Saturday night at the Ojai Valley
Inn.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the ambidextrous Beverly Baker Fleitz, who came out
of Santa Monica in the 1950s with a left-handed forehand and a
right-handed forehand. No need for a backhand. She served
right-handed until she hurt her arm; then she served lefty.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled winning the Ojai mixed doubles in 1956 with
soon-to-be husband John. That trip she stayed with an Ojai family
who made sure to have cold milk and cookies at her bedside each
night.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, her hosts gave her permission to go out on a date
with John. They returned and were enjoying a goodnight kiss at the
door when John's car, the brake improperly set or not set at all,
rolled backward into the hosts' swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that I still got my cold milk and cookies,''
said Beverly Fleitz, ``but John was not invited back.''
</P>
<P>
   And how's this for Ojai tradition:
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Beverly Fleitz presented the trophy to the winning
CIF boys' doubles team from Peninsula High, one of whom is her
grandson, Jeff Kazarian.
</P>
<P>
   Family is important here. Pat Henry Yeomans pointed out that her
mother, Corinne Henry, won mixed doubles in 1926, Yeomans herself
won the mixed in 1939 (with Gene Mako of Glendale, now 84 and also
here for the celebration), and Yeomans' son, John, won the men's
open singles in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kramer, who some consider the greatest player of all time,
was on hand, remembering that, as a rising star from Montebello
High, he won the interscholastic singles at Ojai in 1937 and 1939.
He would have won in 1938, too, he said, but he stayed up late the
night before the final, losing at poker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kramer lost all our money betting three kings against three
aces,'' said Ted Schroeder, another of the returning champs. ``We
had to live off orange juice and cookies from the hospitality
tent.''
</P>
<P>
   (Oh, the boy Kramer lost to in '38? Arthur Marx, son of
Groucho.)
</P>
<P>
   Patty Fendick, women's intercollegiate singles champ at Ojai in
1986 (for Stanford), is now the women's coach at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fondest memory is probably the picture board,'' she said.
``We used to laugh at all the old pictures. Now my players come and
laugh at the old pictures of me the bad haircuts and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospitality of the Ojai citizenry was praised time and
again, and much was made of the orange juice provided each morning,
and the tea provided each afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   George Toley, 84, who coached the USC men to 10 NCAA titles
before retiring, recalled a hotly contested morning doubles match
between his Trojans and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Lesch of the Bruins became unhappy with the decisions and
left the court to go to tournament headquarters to see if he could
get a change in officials,'' said Toley. ``Well, the orange juice
tent was right next to the court, so Pancho Contreras of USC went
in, got a pitcher of orange juice and some paper cups and delivered
juice to each of the linesmen and the umpire while we waited for
Lesch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was roaring with laughter, and even the UCLA side
was laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Noted tennis coach and psychologist Vic Braden was master of
ceremonies at the Saturday-night banquet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people who lost in the first round remember this as one
of their favorite tournaments,'' he said. ``I'm still looking for
someone who had a lousy time here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is heaven,'' said ex-Wimbledon champ and U.S. Davis Cup
hero Alex Olmedo, who won seven Ojai titles. ``I have great
memories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
