<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-CAMPAIGN-1std-writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR RACE AT GRASS ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Inserting dropped word in first graf) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The race for Los Angeles mayor will be fought in
the trenches of neighborhood politics next year, with the
candidates attempting to do what none has dared in this city for
more than 40 years -- a grass-roots campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was the city where the modern political campaigns of
slick mailings and television commercials developed. But with the
burgeoning demands of neighborhoods wanting recognition and power,
all major candidates say their chances of success lie in the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the essence of my campaign,'' said Councilman Joel
Wachs, who is using his Studio City base of homeowner activists to
reach across the city. ``I am out every night in different parts of
the city talking about neighborhoods and community involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wachs said it is that preliminary work he has done in
the campaign that has put him in a virtual dead heat as
front-runner in independent polls with City Attorney James Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is part and parcel of my candidacy, and I think the others
are recognizing that it works and they're trying to emulate me,''
Wachs said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic political consultant Joe Cerrell said the campaigns
at this early stage remind him of the 1950s, when the California
Democratic Clubs and organized labor had active groups where people
walked precincts to get votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, this is a nonpartisan race, but you have that sense
they're trying to rebuild that,'' Cerrell said. ``The only real
organized group in the city now is labor, but I have a sense that
people are tired of all-mail-and-television campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cerrell pointed to the national campaign of Vice President
Al Gore, who has been campaigning in small towns and community
groups, and the U.S. Senate campaign in New York of first lady
Hillary Clinton, who has concentrated on small towns.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hahn announced plans to develop a group of committees
around the city to build grass-roots support. His first will be in
South Central Los Angeles, where he has a base of support inherited
from his father, former county Supervisor Kenneth Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grass-roots support will be the key to winning the election,''
Hahn said. ``We will have committees throughout the city from the
Valley to the Westside and the Eastside.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, who follows his
term as speaker with a run for mayor, has been working for months
throughout the city to build support, a campaign adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio comes out of the neighborhood and he knows what it
takes to build consensus,'' said Steve Gray-Barkan. ``He has done
that his entire life.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, as he did while speaker, he will continue to reach out to
different communities, like labor, education and the Valley. He was
the one who made sure the Valley would get the money to pay for the
secession study.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray-Barkan said he believes the emphasis on community
campaigning is a reflection of the number of candidates in a race
more than a year away with no clear favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see a lot more neighborhood and community organizing
this time around because of the lessons that have been learned,''
Gray-Barkan said. ``Look at labor and neighborhood associations.
They have been very effective at expressing their concerns at the
city level and getting things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Soboroff, the businessman-adviser to Mayor Richard
Riordan, has been campaigning throughout the city, mostly at small
groups, campaign consultant Ace Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Soboroff was one of the first to announce a grass-roots campaign
and used the San Fernando Valley -- which accounted for more than
50 percent of the vote in the last mayoral election -- as his
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to have 1,000 volunteers on board by the end of
the year,'' Smith said. ``(Soboroff) already has started doing
precinct walks and coffees all over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is it is not enough to run the traditional
advertising campaign. All that stuff doesn't turn real unless the
candidate spends time talking to real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Los Angeles, said the effort is essential
for any candidate who wants to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many credible candidates you need to get people out to
vote,'' Becerra said. ``You're looking at needing 25 (percent) to
30 percent to get in a runoff, and that means it is essential to
identify your supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer in grass roots. It's what got me elected in the
first place. I wasn't supposed to win my Assembly seat in 1990 but
did it through meeting with people.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
