<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 06:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2007 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      05-01 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    WEB&AMP;MAGS (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in the ``E'' and ``L''categories ) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS.
</P>
<P>
   .Here are Bill Muller's capsule reviews of a website and some
current magazines:
</P>
<P>
   The Nine Planets
</P>
<P>
   seds.lpl.arizona.edu/billa/tnp/nineplanets.html
</P>
<P>
   Outer space is cool again. On the heels of box office hits such
as (beginitalic)Armageddon(enditalic), Hollywood is churning out
space adventure films, such as (beginitalic)Mission to
Mars(enditalic) and (beginitalic)Battlefield Earth(enditalic) and
(beginitalic)Red Planet(enditalic), another Mars movie coming out
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better time to bone up on the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ``The Nine Planets,'' a Web site dedicated to everything
that orbits the Sun, from Earth to the rings of Saturn and beyond.
Although great for those last-minute science papers, the site is
also just plain interesting.
</P>
<P>
   It has extensive information on the planets and their moons,
from mythology to hard science. For example, the site notes that
Mercury was probably named for the messenger of the gods because it
moves quickly across the sky. Also, its eccentric orbit helped
prove Einstein's theory of relativity.
</P>
<P>
   It also notes that Neptune, the eighth planet from the sun, was
discovered after astronomers noticed a peculiarity in the orbit of
Uranus, the seventh planet. Pluto was discovered by accident, for
much the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of good photos, such as a full color shot of
Io, one of the moons of Jupiter, which has active volcanoes on its
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Bored with all the book learning? You can also vote for your
favorite planet. In an amazing turn of events, Earth seems to be
winning. What a bunch of homers. Mars rules!
</P>
<P>
   George
</P>
<P>
   This magazine just can't win for losing. Much of this month's
issue is devoted to John McCain, whose presidential campaign flamed
about the same time they were dropping this collection of
irrelevancy in the mail. There is an essay by the White Tornado
himself, repeating much of what we heard in stump speeches all
winter. There is also a feature on Cindy McCain, who,
(beginitalic)George (enditalic)has learned, loves her children. In
all fairness, there also are pieces on the wives of George W. Bush,
Al Gore and Bill Bradley, whose campaign fell apart about the same
time as McCain's. Beyond that, there's not much to keep the covers
apart, though the Vietnam retrospective by Pulitzer Prize winner
David Halberstam is worth a look. The main feature is on stars who
give extensively to charity, and it leads with U2's Bono, who has
become involved in Third World debt relief. That, and finding that
elusive word that rhymes with Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   Reason
</P>
<P>
   The lead piece happily notes that the world hasn't come to an
end, as gloomily predicted by experts during the first Earth Day
back in 1970. There hasn't been a global famine, city dwellers
aren't wearing gas masks, and we haven't run out of oil. While the
statistics seem to bear this out, the piece is written in an
off-putting we-told-you-so style that makes it read like an
eighth-grade social studies book. In another piece, a dad defends
the ribald animated TV show (beginitalic)South Park(enditalic),
which has sent the Religious Right into a tizzy with its profane
dialogue and adult themes. Writer Barry S. Fagin taped and
previewed the show and then let his kids watch a few episodes. He
emerged believing that (beginitalic)South Park (enditalic)can
actually teach his kids something, mainly that it's fun to ridicule
celebrities, hypocrites and ``people who believe stupid things.''
Also, cartoons are not real. We had an inkling. That Yosemite Sam
just never seems to run out of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Utne reader
</P>
<P>
   The main package deals with dwindling privacy in an increasingly
computerized world. The most interesting piece involves a man who
walks 120 miles from his tiny Quaker community in southeastern Ohio
to the state capital, Columbus, to return his driver's license in
an act of defiance. We later learn that he and his wife have no
marriage certificate (no government interference, thank you),
refused immunization for their first child and never filed birth
certificates for the rest. Great idea, except he can't take them as
