<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 06:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2008 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PERILS-AZR &LR;      05-01 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERILS-AZR </SLUG>
  
In the Heart of the Sea
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Philbrick
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 20, 1821, the Nantucket whaling ship Essex sank after it
was rammed by a huge sperm whale, the first ever known to
deliberately attack a ship. The incident, which a member of the
crew called an act of ``fury and vengeance,'' was as famous then as
the fate of the Titanic would become in the 20th century (it
inspired Herman Melville's climactic scene in his 1851 novel,
(beginitalic)Moby-Dick(enditalic)). Philbrick recreates the months
at sea with the hard-working men of the Essex, and the chilling
attack and its aftermath, when 20 men in three small boats tried to
save themselves. Only eight survived the following months, which
Philbrick calls ``a kind of terrible laboratory experiment devised
to see just how far the human animal could go in its battle against
the savage sea.'' This is a terrific addition to the list of recent
books about danger and adventure on the high seas.
</P>
<P>
   Home and Away
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Simon
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   National Public Radio's Simon has written a memoir that is a
thinly-veiled excuse to talk about sports. No, we are too kind.
It's not veiled at all. It's a fan's memoir. If you enjoy the
author as host of NPR's (beginitalic)Weekend
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Edition(enditalic), you will enjoy him here
- he is witty, easy company. It helps, of course, if you have your
own feelings about sports, especially sports from Chicago. Simon
has an undying allegiance to that city, forged by incidents such as
when he was in kindergarten and his family moved to San Francisco,
where some evil second-graders tied him to a tree with a jump rope
after he ridiculed them for not knowing White Sox pitcher Billy
Pierce. In addition to Chicago and its athletes, Simon covers his
family traumas - his father's alcoholism, the divorce of his
parents, whom he calls ``the funniest man and the most beautiful
woman in Chicago'' - and his career as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Ravelstein
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saul Bellow
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravelstein, with his bald powerful head, was at ease with
large statements, big issues, and famous men, with decades, eras,
centuries. He was, however, just as familiar with entertainers like
Mel Brooks as with the classics and could go from Thucydides' huge
tragedy to Moses as played by Brooks.'' Bellow might be describing
himself, but isn't - he is describing his late friend Allan Bloom,
the model for Bellow's character, Abe Ravelstein. Like Bloom,
Ravelstein was a debt-plagued academic who wrote a book that sold
like crazy and made him rich (in Bloom's case, (beginitalic)The
Closing of the American Mind(enditalic).) The narrator is Chick,
the Bellow persona whose friendship with Ravelstein is built on
intellect, rivalry and affection. Chick has wives, and Ravelstein
has a boyfriend and a disease, but the core of this novel is the
wise interplay between the friends as they face Ravelstein's
mortality.
</P>
<P>
   How to Manage &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your Mother
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alyce Faye Cleese &QL;
</P>
<P>
   and Brian Bates
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $24)
</P>
<P>
   The title is a gimmick. Cleese and Bates actually make a
heartfelt effort to explore the volatile mother-child relationship
that haunts so many adult lives today. They interviewed a wide
range of people about their experiences with their mothers,
discussing mothers as martyrs, mothers who interfere with their
children's lives, mothers who don't listen and mothers who withhold
approval. Many people, they discovered, received much of their
mothering from women other than their mothers. Another finding: Our
mothers often do not expect from us all that we think they do. The
authors advise you to keep a sense of humor about your mother,
confront the issues that divide you and communicate with her. Most
of all, you should remember that ``managing your mother is really
about managing yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0628EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
