<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 06:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2012 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      05-01 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-SECONDARYSLUG-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    WEBS&AMP;MAGS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in the ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are reviews of 2 Websites and current magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITES
</P>
<P>
   Misheard Song Lyrics
</P>
<P>
   www.kissthisguy.com and Mondegreen  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (www.enteract.com/ &UR; ~jessicar/lyrics/)
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just hate when you get the words to a song wrong? We
do, too. So we consulted a couple of Web sites that catalog
commonly misheard song lyrics and give the right words at the same
time. Great for those bar bets, and good for a chuckle as well.
</P>
<P>
   The first site is named after the most commonly misheard lyric,
from (beginitalic)Purple Haze(enditalic) by Jimi Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   The real lyric: ``'Scuse me, while I kiss the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   The misheard lyric: ``'Scuse me, while I kiss this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then hilarity results. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, both sites have huge lists of commonly misheard
songs. Kissthisguy also has people fessing up, telling embarrassing
stories about when their friends made fun of them for singing the
wrong lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mondegreen's favorites is from the Bob Dylan tune,
(beginitalic)Blowin' in the Wind(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   The real lyric: ``The answer my friends, is blowin' in the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   The misheard lyric: ``The ants are my friends, they're blowin'
the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, hilarity results. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE REVIEWS:
</P>
<P>
   American Heritage
</P>
<P>
   Offers yet another chapter in the most overcovered story of the
presidential season, namely John McCain's temper. Article tries to
gauge the boiling points of former presidents, ranging from Nixon's
rants caught on tape to LBJ's ornery behavior around his aides.
Calvin Coolidge apparently bullied his wife and played practical
jokes on his staff, while John Adams once called George Washington
a ``muttonhead.'' Main piece names most overrated/underrated things
from American culture, from books to movies to obscure things like
French heroes of the American Revolution. Inexplicably, their movie
expert picks (beginitalic)The Godfather (enditalic)as most
overrated film. In the book department, the author chooses
Melville's (beginitalic)Moby-Dick (enditalic)as the most overrated.
As the most underrated, they pick another tale of the sea, Herman
Wouk's (beginitalic)The Caine Mutiny. (enditalic)They also note
that Humphrey Bogart was ``awesomely perfect'' in the movie
version. Dude!
</P>
<P>
   Archaeology
</P>
<P>
   Purists might go for the story on ``curious urns'' found in the
Amazon (undoubtedly the site of an ancient Sam's Club), but my
favorite was a relatively short article on the archaeology of a pet
cemetery. The lead is really catchy: ``Like Persephone, I walk half
my life among the living and half (the professional half) among the
dead.'' The author spends most of her time on humans, researching
how memorials reveal diversity within ethnic groups. While looking
at the National Military Cemetery at the Presidio in San Francisco,
she stumbled over its pet cemetery. There's also an interesting
article on the vast network of pillboxes, roadblocks and trenches
that awaited a German invasion of Great Britain, which never came.
A sidebar notes that the indefatigable British have converted some
of the old pillboxes into bat roosts, garden sheds and a peacock
house, whatever that is. One couple even painted their pillbox
pink. Blimey!
</P>
<P>
   Harper's
</P>
<P>
   Includes a fascinating piece of journalism this month - a
profile of the U.S. government's favorite arms dealer, a German
named Ernst Werner Glatt, who lives on a sprawling farm at the
foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains in Virginia. According to
this well-researched piece, Glatt has been involved in most of the
nation's covert arms deals of the past quarter-century, secretly
funneling weapons to American-backed guerilla forces during the
Cold War. There's an also interesting piece on radicals in the
Pacific Northwest, though the author wastes valuable real estate at
the top of the story describing his mundane plane ride to Portland
and his bus trip to Eugene. The magazine's centerpiece notes that
the Olympic Park in Sydney is built on the site of an old toxic
waste dump, near a contaminated creek, a waste treatment plant and
the ``dioxin capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys&AMP;Indians
</P>
<P>
   Great cover this month. After all, who's more of a cowboy than
Dylan McDermott, the star of (beginitalic)The Practice(enditalic),
a TV show about lawyers in Boston? Oh well. He's still a handsome
diablo, and he's also in a new movie called (beginitalic)Texas
Rangers. (enditalic)And, no, they couldn't resist the ``Marshal
Dylan'' headline. In the real cowboys section, there is an
interesting feature on the Professional Bull Riders circuit, which
has adopted a pro-wrestling approach - only with real bulls.
Instead of wooden stands and a corn pone announcer, PBR shows are
filled with laser shows, rock music and gouts of flame. Bull riding
is one of the fastest growing sports in the U.S., with 1.5 million
viewers each week on TNN. There's also some nice photos from a West
Texas ranch but, alas, no captions. Oh well, I think those are cows
in the background.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 06:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2013 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      05-01 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-SECONDARYSLUG-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    WEBS&AMP;MAGS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in the ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are reviews of 2 Websites and current magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITES
</P>
<P>
   Misheard Song Lyrics
</P>
<P>
   www.kissthisguy.com and Mondegreen  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (www.enteract.com/ &UR; ~jessicar/lyrics/)
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just hate when you get the words to a song wrong? We
do, too. So we consulted a couple of Web sites that catalog
commonly misheard song lyrics and give the right words at the same
time. Great for those bar bets, and good for a chuckle as well.
</P>
<P>
   The first site is named after the most commonly misheard lyric,
from (beginitalic)Purple Haze(enditalic) by Jimi Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   The real lyric: ``'Scuse me, while I kiss the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   The misheard lyric: ``'Scuse me, while I kiss this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then hilarity results. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, both sites have huge lists of commonly misheard
songs. Kissthisguy also has people fessing up, telling embarrassing
stories about when their friends made fun of them for singing the
wrong lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mondegreen's favorites is from the Bob Dylan tune,
(beginitalic)Blowin' in the Wind(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   The real lyric: ``The answer my friends, is blowin' in the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   The misheard lyric: ``The ants are my friends, they're blowin'
the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, hilarity results. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE REVIEWS:
</P>
<P>
   American Heritage
</P>
