</P>
<P>
   AR: National monuments would be, obviously, an important legacy
of your time at Interior. And the CARA bill could also be an
important legacy. (CARA is the Conservation and Reinvestment Act,
which would provide $900million a year for federal conservation
projects and land acquisition.)
</P>
<P>
   I have a press release from Sen. (Frank) Murkowski (R-Alaska)
that I was reading it to somebody, and they said, ``This looks like
extortion to me.'' Murkowski is saying, ``Well, you can have one or
the other.'' He says plainly, if you continue to go forward with
more monuments, then this CARA bill is going to get bottled up. Is
this extortion?
</P>
<P>
   BB: I don't think it's appropriate to respond to threats of
blackmail. I think we should consider policies on their merits.
That's all I have to say.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Do you have a sense of how many more monuments might be
designated in your tenure? I saw from the Wilderness Society some
speculation about the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, Oregon
Steens Mountain and Soda Mountain, the Canyons of the Ancients in
Colorado, the Missouri Breaks in Montana. Are these under active
consideration?
</P>
<P>
   BB: The answer is, I have been out on the landscape in all of
these places. In Oregon, for example, I am meeting regularly with
the entire Oregon delegation in an attempt to work out a
legislative proposal for Steens Mountain. My interest in that is
well known. We're trying to do it legislatively. There's another
place in Oregon called Soda Mountain, where -
</P>
<P>
   AR: When you say legislatively, you mean you have to do it in
Congress?
</P>
<P>
   BB: Do it in Congress, through legislation.
</P>
<P>
   There's another place, Soda Mountain in Oregon, where I think
there's general consensus that a presidential proclamation is
appropriate. The governor supports it. There is extensive support
in the local community, and I believe that that's high on the list
of ones that I am actively considering recommending to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   So it all depends. There are two in Oregon. One we're looking at
(would be) a presidential proclamation, the other one we're working
with the delegation to do legislation. I think that the important
thing is not the label. It's the protection for the label.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Let's talk just about the CARA bill, then. How significant
is it that you would have this automatic $900 million a year for
land and water conservation. How significant is that that you have
that automatically triggered instead of having to haggle over it?
</P>
<P>
   BB: It's an important legislative objective.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Is that significant in terms of the Babbitt legacy or the
Clinton legacy? And does this bill fit into that?
</P>
<P>
   BB: We're not in the business of ranking things around here. We
leave that for historians and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   AR: OK. I want to talk about the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   BB. Sure.
</P>
<P>
   AR: How far are we from seeing the rail system?
</P>
<P>
   BB: My major concerns about the Canyon have been protecting the
true Grand Canyon. That's what the national monument was all about,
was trying to get the Grand Canyon co-extensive with its
hydrographic areas, number one.
</P>
<P>
   Number two, managing visitation. I am pleased with the progress
of the mass-transit proposals. They are enormously complicated. We
made it a priority, starting in 1994. I'm satisfied that it's now
on a track to completion{hellip}.
</P>
<P>
   The third issue, of course, has been airplanes. We are
continuing this sort of endless, uphill struggle against the tour
operators over in Las Vegas. I think we've made some progress,
though. We're not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   AR: The latest plan that was just announced, the restrictions on
flights. That still doesn't quite put you where you want to be?
</P>
<P>
   BB: No, we're not. But it's a forward step.
</P>
<P>
   AR: When you became Interior Secretary you gave a talk about
mining and grazing. Could you assess both mining and grazing, where
you would like to be versus where, in fact, you are. Are there
disappointments that you haven't been able to accomplish as much
you might have liked?
</P>
<P>
   BB: I'm not in the disappointment business. I can tell you what
we've managed to do. (He describes the restoration of riparian
areas in the state). And you know, the major obstacle has been a
United States Congress, which, on these issues, is simply a doormat
for the livestock industry and the mining industry. So we've had
very little help from Congress{hellip}.
</P>
<P>
   AR: When you look back at your tenure in Interior, how will you
regard the independent counsel investigation?
</P>
<P>
   BB: It was not a pleasant experience. It was a part of the
witch-hunting mentality of this town. It had one positive aspect,
and that is, it caused me to focus on what I really wanted to do.
It sort of improved my vision about what it is that I really wanted
to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Did it focus you because you concentrated that much harder?
</P>
<P>
   BB: When stuff like that comes, your inevitable kind of reaction
is to take a step back from all the sort of day-to-day routine
stuff. (You ask yourself), ``What does the schedule today amount
to? Why am I making six public appearances today? What does it have
to do with what I was given, invited here by the president to do?''
</P>
<P>
   AR: Is there any message you'd want to impart to the independent
counsel about the way the investigation was conducted?
</P>
<P>
   BB: The statute expired. It's all gone. I mean, the statute was
an absurd piece of legislation that contributed to this kind of
witch-hunting environment. Everybody in Congress recognized that.
So there isn't any more independent counsel. I guess I can console
myself by saying, ``Well, maybe I was the poster child for the
repeal of the independent counsel statute.''
</P>
<P>
   AR: If Al Gore were elected president, would you consider
staying on as Secretary of Interior if he asked you to?
</P>
<P>
   BB: You never say never. But I think, in life, it's important to
get off the stage while the audience is still applauding. That's
one reason why, after two terms as governor - there were no term
limits - I said it's time to move on{hellip}. I've been here eight
years. Eight years is a nice bracket. I learned that being
governor. Four years is not enough, because you can start a lot of
things, but it's hard to work them into the sort of institutional
culture. And that's really been true around here.
</P>
<P>
   AR: You said you were an empty-nester now, the last time I
asked. And I remember writing a story and they put the headline on
it: ``Bruce and Hattie: The Reluctant Power Couple.'' You weren't
too big on the dinner-party scene in Washington at the time because
you had kids at home and you wanted to be home. Do you venture out
more?
</P>
<P>
   BB: There was a year in which, all of a sudden, both children
were away at college and the dog died - all in the same one-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been about four years ago. And that has
obviously left us a little more time to, you know, kind of dip into
the Washington social scene. We're still not big players. We've
actually made a few friends now.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, I'll tell you something. The price that you pay by
raising a family, with both of us as professionals - you really
have no social life. That was true in Phoenix. We had no social
life other than our family and our immediate friends.
</P>
<P>
   We're doing a little better now. And there's lot of interesting
stuff in this town. There really is. I'm working right now on a
little dinner that we're having at Ford's Theater in two weeks as
part of a Park Service symposium on the Civil War. I'm really
interested in the Civil War and how we interpret it in the
(national) parks.
</P>
<P>
   So when you invite people, they come. I invited John Keegan, who
is the world's leading military historian. He's a Brit who likes
the Civil War. His (beginitalic)A Mask of Command (enditalic)is one
of the great classics of the 20th century. So I invited him. I
invited James McPherson, who wrote (beginitalic)Battle Cry of
Freedom(enditalic), the big Civil War thing. And Eric Fromer, who
is the outstanding historian of Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   So I invited them to dinner, sort of. We're going to have a
little dinner before the conference at Ford's Theater. This is the
sort of thing that I've never had the time to do. There are nice
little things like this. I still don't go to press functions. I
still don't go to the Gridiron, or the White House Correspondents'
(Dinner), or any of that stuff. They are still as uninteresting as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   But I - well, we get around a little more.
</P>
<P>
   AR: I could count, but how many of the Cabinet members have been
in for the duration?
</P>
<P>
   BB: Three of us.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Three? (Health and Human Services Secretary) Donna
Shalala{hellip}.
</P>
<P>
   BB: Shalala, (Education Secretary Richard) Riley and myself.
</P>
<P>
   AR: At one time - this was years ago when I spoke to you - you
mentioned that you were sometimes awakened late in the evening by
the president calling you to chat about something or another. Does
that still happen?
</P>
<P>
   BB: Yes. You know, so far as I'm aware, he never sleeps.
(Laughs.) And certainly it never seems to be a serious discussion,
except the most interesting discussions take place in - really, in
two areas. One is in the middle of the night, when he's at the end
of his day and all alone and thinking about it. And the other one
is traveling - usually on the home leg of an Air Force One trip,
(when) he gets gregarious and likes to hang around and talk.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Is he seeking your counsel, or is he just chatting about
whatever's on his mind, or both?
</P>
<P>
   BB: Well, the answer's both. The answer is both. And usually in
a - you know, in a free-flowing, a very free-flowing mix.
</P>
<P>
   AR: I get the sense, and tell me if it's true, that that was
part of the reason when you were being considered for the Supreme
Court - that he not only didn't want to lose you at Interior, but
he didn't want to lose those 2 a.m. phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   BB: Well, I think that's part of it. I'm not flattering myself
by saying it's so. Another reason is that he doesn't like to pick
fights when he makes judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   AR: Have you thought about what comes next, then? Do you want to
stay in D.C.? You want to live in Arizona?
</P>
<P>
   BB: Well, I've thought about it; haven't gone very far. I can
tell you what I don't want to do. I'm not going to go back to the
practice of law. I'm not going to be a lobbyist. I'm not going to
run for office. That leaves a wide world, except that Hattie
reminds me - you know, it's not clear what else you're qualified to
do once you exclude all those things.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you'll be seeing a lot more of me in Arizona now. I mean,
you know, people have asked me, ``Why is it that you are involved
so deeply in these growth and open-space issues in Arizona? And you
know, do you have some kind of agenda? Are you coming home to run
for governor again?''
</P>
<P>
   My answer is: I'm out of politics, but I am back to Arizona. And
this stuff that we're working on with these growth and land issues,
that's not because I'm a member of the president's Cabinet. There
are plenty of legacy things to do, land exchange in Arizona being
one of them. It's because I really - I've been away from Arizona
for a long time. I'm a little bit homesick. I want to re-engage in
Arizona as a citizen.Associated PressInterior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt has an ambitious list of goals he hopes to accomplish in
his final months in office.Arizona will ``be seeing a lot more of
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
