<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, May 7)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending April 22 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. WE'LL MEET AGAIN, by Mary Higgins Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $7.99.) A woman tries to free herself
</P>
<P>
   of people's suspicion that she murdered her
</P>
<P>
   husband.
</P>
<P>
   2. BLACK FRIDAY, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A secret militia lays siege
</P>
<P>
   to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   3. CARNAL INNOCENCE, by Nora Roberts. (Bantam, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A concert violinist visiting Innocence, Miss.,
</P>
<P>
   becomes enamored of a man suspected of being a serial
</P>
<P>
   killer.
</P>
<P>
   4. FORTUNE'S HAND, by Belva Plain. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young attorney's ideals are tested when he joins a
</P>
<P>
   prominent law firm.
</P>
<P>
   5. TOM CLANCY'S NET FORCE: Night Moves, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Computer terrorism in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   6. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager finds help and caring in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town.
</P>
<P>
   7. JOINING, by Johanna Lindsey. (Avon, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1214, an Englishwoman changes her feelings
</P>
<P>
   about her partner in an arranged marriage.
</P>
<P>
   8. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   10. WORST FEARS REALIZED, by Stuart Woods. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) A police officer turned lawyer seeks a serial killer
</P>
<P>
   he once knew.
</P>
<P>
   11. ON MYSTIC LAKE, by Kristin Hannah. (Ballantine, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman who has been betrayed by her husband is reunited with
</P>
<P>
   her first love.
</P>
<P>
   12. A NEW SONG, by Jan Karon. (Penguin, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A clergyman and his wife move 600 miles, creating
</P>
<P>
   new friendships and maintaining old ones.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE CIDER HOUSE RULES, by John Irving. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Life in a Maine orphanage in the first part of
</P>
<P>
   the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE DEVIL'S TEARDROP, by Jeffery Deaver. (Pocket Star,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) On Dec. 31, 1999, a diabolical scheme involving
</P>
<P>
   a robotic assassin threatens Washington.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) BITTERSWEET, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman copes with a midlife crisis: Should she
</P>
<P>
   pursue her old career as a photojournalist?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   3. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   4. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $15.) A presentation of superstring
</P>
<P>
   theory, which attempts to mediate between
</P>
<P>
   quantum mechanics and general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   An American remembers a spring and summer spent in the
</P>
<P>
   romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8. THE ONION'S FINEST NEWS REPORTING, edited by
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dikkers and Robert Siegel. (Three Rivers, $16.)
</P>
<P>
   A collection of humor pieces.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) YESTERDAY, I CRIED, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A counselor tells how she turned painful
</P>
<P>
   experiences into hope. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) TRAVELING MERCIES, by Anne Lamott. (Anchor, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A chronicle of the author's journey toward faith.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
