<SLUG> BC-R-RELIGION-REFERENCES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY COW! OHIO HAS A MOTTO PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By JANE FRITSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is OK for the federal government to print ``In God We Trust''
on umpteen billion pieces of currency, but it is by no means OK for
the state of Ohio to use the motto, ``With God, All Things Are
Possible'' on its official seal or anywhere else, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ruled the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati
last week in a 30-page decision that reads like
Thomas-Aquinas-takes-the-bar-exam. Lesser minds may have trouble
following the logic, but in the end it comes down to something like
this: References to a particular religion are forbidden; general
references to God are not.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's slogan is a quotation from the New Testament and is
therefore clearly Christian, the court said. ``In God We Trust''
comes from ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' by Francis Scott Key and is
not a reference to a specific faith.
</P>
<P>
   The latest skirmish over the separation of church and state has
its roots in 1959, when the Ohio Legislature approved ``With God,
All Things Are Possible,'' as the state's official motto. It had
been the idea of a 12-year-old Cincinnati boy who was concerned
that Ohio was the only state without a motto.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio had a history of motto trouble. In 1866, the legislature
had approved the motto ``Imperium in Imperio,'' Latin for ``An
Empire Within an Empire.'' But there was a great outcry over the
``pretentious feudal meaning'' of the phrase, according to the Ohio
Historical Society, and the legislation was repealed a year later.
Ohio remained motto-free for almost 92 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 1959 motto languished in obscurity until 1996, when Sen.
George Voinovich, a Republican who was then the governor of Ohio,
returned from a trip to India, where he noticed the slogan,
``Government Work Is God's Work'' on a public building. He began
pushing to have Ohio's motto inscribed on a building at the state
Capitol, prompting the American Civil Liberties Union to file a
lawsuit to have it banned.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Columbus ruled that the motto could be used,
as long as the state did not cite its Christian origin. But the
appeals court overturned that ruling in its 2-1 decision last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the words of Jesus speaking about salvation,'' said Mark
Cohn, the lawyer who handled the case for the ACLU. ``It's an
expression of Ohio looking favorably on Christianity. It's not the
same as `In God We Trust.' No one knows what that means.''
</P>
<P>
   As the length of the opinion suggests, this was not an easy call
for the appeals court. Quoting from a 1972 Supreme Court case about
public financing of private schools, the opinion noted that the
line of separation between church and state, ``far from being a
wall, is a blurred, indistinct and variable depending on all the
circumstances of a particular relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous court decisions, and there have been many, have
approved the use of the words ``under God'' in the Pledge of
Allegiance, the decision noted. And it was long ago settled that
prayers could be recited at the opening of Congress. For a public
body to invoke divine guidance is not a step toward the
establishment of a religion, one ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   The mottos of some states include the word ``God,'' the opinion
said, but Ohio's is the only one that contains a direct quotation
from either the Old or New Testament of the Christian Bible. It is
taken directly from the Gospel of Matthew, Chapter 19, Verse 26, in
which Jesus is quoted as saying, ``It is easier for a camel to pass
through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the
kingdom of God.'' Asked who, then can be saved, Jesus replied,
``With men, this is impossible, but with God all things are
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU argued that the motto, therefore, constitutes an
endorsement of the Christian religion, but lawyers for the state
contended that the origin of the words is irrelevant. In fact, they
said, few people know the origin of the motto, which was intended
only to encourage hope and acknowledge the humility of Ohio's
government and its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the line, the appeals court ruled, the state of Ohio
had crossed it. ``While the words of the motto might not overtly
favor Christianity,'' the court said, ``as the words of Jesus,
they, at a minimum, demonstrate a particular affinity toward
Christianity in the eyes and ears of a reasonable observer.'' The
Ohio Legislature, the court added, ``in following the suggestion of
the 12-year-old boy who suggested the words of Jesus as the
official motto of the state, has given an unconstitutional
preference to Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   It is probably unnecessary to mention that the state of Ohio
plans to appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
