<HEADLINE>
HOW TO POOH-POOH $70 MILLION WAR CHESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ For anyone living inside Washington's Beltway during
an election year, it often appears as though political campaigns
are taking over the country. The hinterlands complain loudly about
the number of advertisements on television and radio. Fund-raisers
raise seemingly enormous sums.
</P>
<P>
   But drive 525 miles northwest to the Motor City, home to some of
the world's largest companies, and the perspective changes. In a
typical year, the auto industry spends more than 100 times as much
on advertising as the presidential candidates combined. Even the
nearly $70 million that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas raised before
the first vote was cast in the New Hampshire primary on Feb. 1
seems like spare change in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't even get the attention of a top auto executive about
anything less than $250 million,'' said Gerald Meyers, a former
chairman and chief executive of the American Motors Corp. ``They
drool more down the sides of their mouths at breakfast than $70
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry ad spending is enormous _ $1 in every $7 of all
advertising spending in this country _ because the companies are
huge. General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler each have about
eight times the annual sales of the Microsoft Corp., and are each
considerably larger than all the world's airlines put together.
Years of budget cuts in Washington, coupled with mergers in the
auto industry, have left few government departments operating on
the same scale as the automakers; the nation's annual military
budget is now only 74 percent larger than GM's annual revenue,
although the armed forces are still able to employ far more people
because soldiers earn much less than auto workers.
</P>
<P>
   With some Americans increasingly inured to advertising, media
manipulation has become more important. The media operations of
automakers dwarf those of the presidential campaigns. GM has 150
press officers worldwide; the Bush campaign has only four. Both
also have many media assistants who are not authorized to talk to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   While auto shows do not yet attract the 15,000 journalists who
show up for the Democratic and Republican conventions, they are
drawing more attention, like the 4,000 journalists who have shown
up for New York's auto show, which ends April 30. More than a third
of the 5,700 journalists who covered Detroit's auto show in January
were from overseas, because mergers have made the industry more
global.
</P>
<P>
   There are some differences, of course, between the political and
automotive press. Newspapers and TV networks pay the bills for the
political journalists who troop on and off campaign buses. But
automakers pay for many journalists covering the introductions of
new models at auto shows and elsewhere; a few organizations,
including The New York Times, decline free trips.
</P>
<P>
   The automakers put reporters up in luxury hotel rooms costing up
to $600 a night, often inviting spouses and domestic partners, too,
although the manufacturers have cracked down to prevent journalists
from bringing along dirty laundry to be cleaned at $5 a shirt and
up. And while the political campaigners trudge to places like Des
Moines and Manchester, N.H., the automakers compete to fly
journalists to exotic settings that will provide unusual backdrops
for photography: BMW's Land Rover showed off its Discovery sport
utility vehicle by shuttling writers and photographers to the Gobi
Desert in Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   If politicians get their message across on surprisingly small
budgets, do automakers get their money's worth as they try to
establish their brand images through much more extensive
advertising and public relations? The executives say they have
little choice about the spending, and that their ads are not just
another part of the ``white noise'' of American culture. There are
two dozen automakers in this country, some selling scores of models
_ 75 in GM's case _ so it takes much more advertising than it does
to promote a few presidential candidates. News coverage also
reinforces political campaign advertising and the public's
awareness of politicians' names in a way auto executives can only
dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Negative ads may be cost effective for politicians, but they are
rare in the auto industry. Any given car competes with so many
other models that it is hard to criticize all of the alternatives
even with a big ad budget. Auto executives also change jobs often
enough that they do not want to hit a potential future employer too
hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a gentleman's club _ they don't like to beat each
other to death,'' said Jack Trout, a marketing consultant in
Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced marketers like Roger Adams, who made his name at
PepsiCo by reviving Mountain Dew and is now general manager of GM's
Buick division, unsurprisingly contend that auto ads are better
than campaign ads. ``A lot of political advertising is a blatant
sell, and that turns people off,'' said Adams, who has begun to
revive Buick by hiring Tiger Woods, the golfer, as its ad pitchman.
``If I see another Bush ad, I think I'll scream _ it's all `I've
done this, I've done that.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
