<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2025 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-YUGOSLAVIA-REVIEW-N     05-01 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-YUGOSLAVIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YUGOSLAVS, THE PAST KEEPS GETTING BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Twenty years after the death of Tito,
Yugo-nostalgia wafts through the remnant of the Yugoslavia he
created. And everywhere here, despite the continuing sway of
Slobodan Milosevic, there is a strong feeling of fin-de-regime,
that another era of personal rule is coming to a close.
</P>
<P>
   A mysterious radio station called Radio Nostalgia, its owners
and finances unclear, plays songs of the Tito era and has become
one of the most popular in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Prompt anyone over 30 about the past and they will immediately
talk about how respected Yugoslavia used to be, how wonderful were
the summers on the Croatian coast, how easy it was to travel the
world without a visa, how shopping trips to Italy were common and
how often young people were sent abroad, to the United States or
Europe, for vacations and school.
</P>
<P>
   To be the pampered buffer between East and West, anti-Soviet and
anti-imperialist and members neither of the Warsaw Pact nor NATO,
meant easy access anywhere. Yugoslav Communism was relatively
liberal and relatively rich, and could seem a form of model for the
rest of Eastern Europe. Tito helped found the nonaligned movement,
which had real meaning in a world of competitive superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   So when Tito died on May 4, 1980, after a long illness, millions
of people wept _ as millions of Russians did when Stalin died in
1953 _ for an uncertain future without the nation's guiding star.
But Yugo-nostalgia is not the same sad plaint as Communist
nostalgia in the rest of the East. Yugoslavia is the one place in
Europe that was almost surely better off in the past, closer then
than now to acceptance and inclusion in the West and further,
politically, from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in this incredibly shrinking country, when even tiny
Montenegro talks of independence, there is a continuing sense of
bewilderment, poverty and farce, of helplessness as the Milosevic
era goes through its lengthy death throes.
</P>
<P>
   With ethnic wars, Western sanctions and visa restrictions, most
people under 30 have barely traveled, not even to Croatia.
Milosevic himself, indicted for war crimes, cannot travel abroad.
He cannot even go to Montenegro, Serbia's sister republic that he
titularly rules as the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and his influential wife, Mirjana Markovic, present
his defiance in the face of Washington and NATO's bombing as the
act of a new Tito, the founder of a new bloc of anti-hegemonistic
nations _ like Russia, China and Belarus _ that will stand up to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serbs are sophisticated enough to take this as pathetic
nonsense. They know they are associated with a group of countries
that care less about Yugoslavia than Yugoslavia cares about them.
</P>
<P>
   While China has helped the regime greatly with credits, loans
and investments, and the Russians have helped with deliveries of
energy, both have much more business to do with the United States.
Vladimir Putin won the Russian presidency, not a Communist, and he
has met with the Serbian opposition leader Vuk Draskovic. Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov has even urged Belgrade to be more reasonable
toward the U.N. mandate in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Tito _ Tito!'' was the reassuring but empty slogan in
the years that followed his passing 20 years ago, an era when a
clumsy collective presidency ran the country and decentralization
seemed to be an answer to disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of Communist ``brotherhood and unity,'' a new
form of enforced multiethnicity, Tito had tried to draw a line
under Yugoslavia's bloody past. But nationalism stayed alive in
people's minds, to emerge with vengeance after 1989, when the rest
of Communism was disintegrating.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalism was the simplest alternative ideology for Communist
parties seeking to keep their hold on power. Even though he kept a
portrait of Tito in his office until 1991, Milosevic tried to ride
the new tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic originally saw his role as a Serbian Tito, running a
Yugoslavia that the Serbs would dominate. ``His main miscalculation
was to think the West would never allow the disintegration of
Yugoslavia,'' said Aleksa Djilas, a historian and political
analyst. ``If we had a time machine, and could go back to 1990
knowing what we know now, I'm not sure the West would have allowed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, no one even thinks ``After Milosevic _ Milosevic!''
Instead, one graffiti scrawl in Belgrade, referring to Tito, reads:
``And even the lockmaker was better.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fecklessness of the so-called democratic opposition
to Milosevic, the circles around the regime _ held together by
money, privilege, corruption and power _ are edgy, if not yet
disloyal. Even those who believe that the Socialists can remain on
top understand there will have to be a different leader. But the
problem with Milosevic handing over to a loyalist is that the West
has indicted his most trusted allies.
</P>
<P>
   Disaffection with the regime is widespread, undermined only by
fear of the future and of the opposition's chaotic rivalries. Yet
any fair election _ and there will be local and federal elections
this year and vital Serbian elections before the end of next year _
seems sure to deliver a stinging blow to the regime.
</P>
<P>
   Some here like to quote Markovic, who once warned opponents that
the Communists came to power through armed struggle, not
negotiations, and will leave the same way. But the country has
choked on blood and fratricidal wars that have brought it only
disintegration and decline. And Milosevic cannot be sure, if he
tries to override a clear loss in elections, that the army and
police will back him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when his term as Yugoslav president expires next year, he
could take another role _ possibly as Yugoslav or Serbian prime
minister, or remain as Socialist Party leader _ to keep influence
over the country and over his own fate, especially in the face of
Western demands that he be extradited. In any event, Djilas
believes that Milosevic is a legalist who will not only hold
elections but also abide by them if the results are clear enough.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the finest novel by Ivo Andric, the Bosnian-born
novelist most famous for writing ``Bridge over the Drina,'' is
``Bosnian Chronicle.'' Set in the Napoleonic era, it is a story of
Western power and rivalries, represented by the French and Austrian
consuls, played out in a small outpost of a relatively indifferent
Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   As Napoleon finally begins to suffer defeat after defeat, the
French consul, Daville, finds that he is treated differently. Even
in his own mind, there has been a sudden shift that leaves him
feeling ``only a great emptiness,'' as he comes to think about life
``without Napoleon as the basic assumption.'' He was, Andric
writes, ``sharing the experience of thousands of French people at
that time, exhausted in the service of a regime that had in fact
been defeated long ago, because it had been obliged to ask of
people more than they could give.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, 20 years after Tito's death, Serbs feel what Daville
felt. The Milosevic regime has exhausted them and itself through
one sacrifice after another, some self-inflicted, some imposed.
While no one foresees the end, everyone feels it coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
