<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 08:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-GAMBLING-REVIEW-NYT     05-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GAMBLING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCE ENCOUNTERS :  WHO SAYS GAMBLING IS A SCOURGE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating (The Week in Review) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The prospect or hope or threat that a big new casino may be on
the way to the Catskills, just 90 miles from Manhattan, stirs mixed
emotions among New York's casino frequenters. Residing within 90
minutes of the Monticello Raceway, the proposed site of yet another
gambling enterprise, means reducing by almost half the time it
takes to get to the action in Atlantic City or in Connecticut. That
is the promise. The threat is identical: In an hour and a half you
can be dropping the family savings into the latest in slot machines
or at old-style craps, blackjack and like diversions.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of gambling shows little sign of abating. Along with
most casino patrons, I remain agnostic about the moral and social
considerations. Granted, gambling may not be the most edifying of
pastimes; gamblers could assuredly broaden themselves by reading
best sellers and watching wrestling instead of whiling away the
hours in clockless rooms. On the other hand, whose business is it
if adults find pleasure in throwing away their money, and why
shouldn't it be thrown away in New York instead of Connecticut or
New Jersey? (Compulsive gamblers no doubt require treatment, but
not, most players must agree, at the expense of everyone else or as
an excuse for crackdowns by busybodies.)
</P>
<P>
   What needs to be added in favor of casinos, moreover, is an
appeal that goes beyond the basic ``gaming,'' as its promoters
prefer to call gambling. Casino visitors find themselves part of a
welcoming community with one thing on its collective mind. Along
with the opportunity to take a flier against the odds on a
sprinkling of roulette numbers, there is admittance to a
camaraderie of hope in opposition to fate's negative forces.
</P>
<P>
   That is what you can see in the busloads of anticipation that
roll up to the casinos every morning. That is what you can hear in
the cheers, hollers and squeals for a craps shooter in the throes
of a hot roll or when the dealer goes bust against the whole
blackjack table or when the slots light up and the coins clang in
their jolly fashion. It is not just the joy of winning, but of
winning as part of a team. The relationships are not enduring, but
they offer a sort of stimulation that workaday existence rarely
provides. Those heady moments of unity and celebration keep players
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   In my own preferred casino pastime, poker, the situation is
different from most other games, since the patrons compete against
one another, and the house takes its cut regardless of who wins.
But here, too, the contestants, though competitors, are united in
the action.
</P>
<P>
   Poker players tend to spend more time with one another than
players at other casino games; it is not unusual for an enthusiast
to fiddle with his chips and study his down cards for 10 hours at a
stretch. After a couple of shift changes, players and dealers are
on a first-name basis. If you weaken and drop out around midnight,
be assured that on your return for the early-morning activity, you
will find some of the companions you left behind still at it.
</P>
<P>
   But morning or night, when you join in, you immediately become
part of a small, dedicated fraternity, bound like Freemasons by the
rules of the society. There is a sense in the poker room of being
among the anointed, at several degrees of separation from the
robots at the slots or the suckers battling the odds at games with
names like Caribbean Stud, which bear a deceptive resemblance to
real poker but which the poker vet scorns as inventions that give
the house a considerable edge.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say a poker table is always a convivial place;
tension can make for testiness. But it is not unusual for a player
who has just lost a big hand to a worthy competitor to offer
sincere congratulations to the winner. Conversation at the table is
not wide ranging and initiates tend to be careful about giving
offense. Politics is generally avoided and racial or ethnic slurs
are definitely out. The main subject, a safe one, is about the
straight you didn't make or the miracle flush that you caught on
Fifth Street. Everyone can share in the lamentation or rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   But set aside snobbery; even slot-machine addicts feel they are
part of a club. Whatever game you favor, the casino makes it easy
to join up. Women and men, blacks and whites, the disabled and the
able bodied _ all are welcome. Democracy prevails: Among these
strangers, the player finds a home. As the poker regulars like to
say, all you need is a chair and a chip.
</P>
<P>
   That is the special lure of the casino, be it upstate or
downstate or on the reservation. For your time at the table or at
the machine, loneliness is abolished; you are among a cadre of the
like minded. Win or lose, the world seems a friendlier place.
</P>
<P>
   All right, if you win, it is a little more friendly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
