<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2027 &Cx1f; var-z
u p BC-R-KEY-STATES-REVIEW-2     05-01 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KEY-STATES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING THE TARGET IN THE BATTLE OF VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By ROBIN TONER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look closely at a few typical events on the campaign trail these
days and the true targets of this presidential election quickly
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Al Gore recently talked about education (a major
concern to suburban mothers) in Columbus, Ohio (the swing city in a
swing state). George W. Bush unveiled his new ``compassionate
conservative'' agenda on health care, home ownership and tax cuts
(another bid for the center, especially women, who rank health care
high) in Cleveland and St. Louis (both in traditionally swing
states with a combined total of 32 electoral votes). Gore went to
the drug store with an older woman who lacks prescription drug
coverage (big, big issue with the elderly).
</P>
<P>
   Every presidential candidate at this stage of the game swears he
would fight for every state and every vote in this richly diverse
country. But the ugly little truth is that some states are more
important than others, not just because they are big (with a lot of
electoral votes) but because they are up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   As the primary season was dominated by New Hampshire, the
general election campaign will most likely be ruled by an arc of
big industrial states, including Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan,
Illinois and Missouri. Or, as a gleeful David Leland, chairman of
the Ohio Democratic Party, puts it: ``Bush was here yesterday and
Gore was here last week. I suspect we'll see a lot of both.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a demographic corollary: Some groups of voters will get
more attention than others _ like elderly voters, the legendary
800-pound gorillas of politics, who used to be reliably Democratic
but in recent elections have swung toward the Republicans; married
suburban mothers, an important part of the Clinton vote but now a
battleground between Bush and Gore; and Catholics, once the
quintessential Reagan Democrats, pulled one way by their cultural
conservatism and another by their instincts on domestic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the strategic thinking in the parties these days
revolves around these groups and these states. For example, Celinda
Lake, a Democratic pollster, talks about ``the Reagan seniors, aged
60 to 70,'' who tend to be more affluent than older retirees but
also very responsive to the idea of expanding Medicare to cover
prescription drugs _ which many of them suddenly need.
</P>
<P>
   Put the geography and the demographics together, and a
65-year-old woman (a high likelihood of voting) in a Macomb County,
Mich., suburb, with an affection for the Bush family (a Republican
advantage), a concern for the country's values (ditto) and mounting
medication bills (a Democratic advantage) can look like ground zero
in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This targeting also explains why some candidates for the vice
presidential nomination become so compelling _ like Gov. Tom Ridge
of Pennsylvania, the popular Catholic governor of a battleground
state, who suddenly appeals to so many Republicans. Some Democrats
say Bush has a problem with white Catholics, not just because of
the criticism over his visit to Bob Jones University in the primary
season, but also because of the Southern conservative dominance of
the party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge would neatly provide geographic and cultural balance,
although his support for abortion rights carries risk for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the effort will be confined to those states in the
middle, of course. For some time to come, each candidate will be
probing for weaknesses and targets of opportunity in the other's
base. Most notably, Bush is making forays into California, which
the Democrats carried by wide margins in the last two elections;
the Republicans are running advertising aimed at Hispanics, hoping
that Bush's appeal to that voting bloc in Texas is transferable.
And Gore is paying attention to Florida, a Republican-leaning state
whose governor, Jeb Bush, has a personal stake in the election.
</P>
<P>
   But most experts see the electoral map as pro-Republican in the
South and Mountain West, pro-Democratic on the West Coast and
Northeast, and up for grabs in much of the industrial heartland.
Charles Cook, who publishes a nonpartisan political newsletter,
said, ``They don't have strong liberal tendencies like the
Northeast or the West Coast and they don't have strong conservative
tendencies like the Southern and Rocky Mountain states.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Teeter, a pollster long active in Republican politics, said
of that arc of battleground states: ``Because they're big, they
have all the elements in them that the country has _ they have
rural areas that are Republican, small towns that are Republican,
suburbs with a lot of swing votes, big cities with union members
and blacks that are Democratic.'' This long-running role in
presidential politics, he added, has given rise to the axiom that
no Republican has ever been elected president who didn't win Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-KEY-STATES-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &QL; 
UNDATED: win Ohio.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This political map can change, and has. Most notably, the once
solidly Democratic South realigned to the Republicans in
presidential voting in the late 1960s. For much of the 1980s, the
Republicans were considered to have an ``electoral lock'' on the
presidency because of their strength in the South and California.
But California, which has 54 electoral votes, began turning to the
Democrats in 1988, when Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
nominee, lost it narrowly in what was nationally a sweeping defeat
for the Democrats. In the last two elections, Democrats have
anchored their victories on the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The important demographics can also shift. The over-60 vote went
to the Republicans by a surprising margin of 10 percentage points
in the 1998 midterm elections, according to the exit polls.
``Senior women are anywhere from 12 to 15 percent of the
electorate,'' said Linda DiVall, a Republican pollster. ``They will
vote at an 80 to 85 percent clip.''
</P>
<P>
   Many pollsters say the tug of war for older voters will be
between their attraction for Republican leadership on values _
including Bush's promise to ``uphold the honor and dignity of the
office'' and a general concern over the country's moral direction _
and Democratic promises to protect Medicare and Social Security.
``Once very specific Medicare and Social Security issues go off the
table, values concerns come back,'' said Stan Greenberg, a
Democratic pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Bolger, a Republican pollster, grumbled that at the height
of the campaign, ``Democrats wake up every day saying, `What is it
we gotta do today? Oh, yeah, scare seniors and make sure the black
vote gets out.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer moms'' have become almost a cliche in presidential
politics, but married mothers are, if anything, likely to be more
important in this election than in years past. In large part, this
reflects Bush's greater personal appeal to this group and his
careful courtship on issues and style; from the start, his promise
of compassionate conservatism and emphasis on issues like education
showed his determination to close the gender gap.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press
showed how much better Bush was doing among mothers than the last
Republican nominee. In April 1996, 60 percent of mothers said they
were backing Clinton, while 37 percent said they were backing Dole.
Last month, 41 percent of mothers said they were backing Gore,
while 52 percent were backing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the soccer mom cliche,'' Cook said, ``but I have to
tell you that middle- and upper-middle-income white women who
economically ought to be Republicans but on social and cultural
issues _ abortion, guns, education and health care _ gravitate to
the Democrats, will be important.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the demographic trends that cut across state lines,
states also have their idiosyncracies. The auto industry's
dominance in Michigan, for example, makes it almost inevitable that
the Bush campaign will try to paint Gore there as an environmental
extremist.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the focus on swing voters, the cardinal rule of
politics is to cultivate your base. Still, as this unusually long
post-primary, pre-convention political season drags on, the
battlegrounds are clear. And assuming the election stays
competitive, it will only get worse. ``If you want to know what
hell is like for a voter, it's a swing presidential state with a
key Senate race and an open congressional race,'' Bolger said.
``They're going to see so many political messages that there won't
be any actual news _ just 30 minutes of 30-second spots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 0837EDT &QL; 
