<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: failing grade.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Long Last, Gene Therapy
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of hype and dashed hopes, after more than 4,000
patients with more than a dozen diseases were treated
unsuccessfully in hundreds of studies, gene therapy has finally
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in France reported that they inserted new genes into
cells of three babies with a rare genetic disease that prevents
them from growing immune systems. Without treatment, the babies
would be killed by microorganisms that ordinarily pose no threat.
With gene therapy, the babies developed normal immune systems and
went home from the hospital to live openly in the microbe-laden
world.
</P>
<P>
   Ritalin for Nasdaq?
</P>
<P>
   To economists, financial markets are efficient price discovery
mechanisms. But after watching the Nasdaq stock market soar and
plunge, then plunge and soar during the month of April, investors
and the general public may be wondering if the folks who bought and
sold technology stocks knew what they were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the 10 biggest one-day gains in Nasdaq history came
during April. So did four of its biggest one-day declines. In the
19 days it was open during April (markets were closed April 21 in
observance of Good Friday), the Nasdaq lost 1 percent or more of
its value 11 times, according to Birinyi &AMP; Associates, a stock
market research firm. It rose more than 2 percent seven times. The
selloffs were more severe than the rallies: For the month, the
Nasdaq fell by more than 15 percent, even after rising 6 percent
for the week that ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's Big Decision
</P>
<P>
   The New York Senate race was thrown for a loop, as Rudolph
Giuliani, the mayor of New York and presumptive Republican nominee,
announced that he had been diagnosed with prostate cancer. The
disease, Giuliani said, was caught in its earliest stages, when,
medical professionals noted, chances for a cure are excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's announcement stirred speculation that he would sit
out the race against Hillary Rodham Clinton, but the mayor said he
would put discussion about his political future on hold until he
and his doctors had decided on the best course of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Killers From Outer Space
</P>
<P>
   A killer rock from outer space is a new suspect in the greatest
murder mystery of all time, a mass extinction a quarter-billion
years ago that wiped out most animal species on earth, including
trilobites, the three-lobed predators that once ruled the seas.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in the April 15 issue of Earth and Planetary Science
Letters announced the discovery in Australia of a previously
unknown crater about 75 miles wide, one of the largest ever found.
Its dating, while imprecise, tentatively ties it to the sudden
disappearance, 247 million years ago, of trilobites, other marine
invertebrates and early reptiles. The demise of the dinosaurs 65
million years ago has also been linked to the collision of a huge
cosmic object with Earth, so all chicken littles should start
scanning the skies with renewed anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The Universe's Baby Steps
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, astronomers have taken clear pictures of the
infant universe. To make the pictures, a balloon-borne telescope
called Boomerang captured traces of radiation emitted from the
roiling gases of the cosmos some 13 billion years ago, when it was
a mere 300,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cloudy shapes in the pictures confirmed cosmology's
leading theory: that the universe was born in a fiery explosion.
But they did not reveal other features that must have existed if
the theory, called inflation, is correct. Scientists are waiting
for better pictures and furiously recalculating.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire at the National Zoo
</P>
<P>
   A gunman opened fire Monday at the Washington's 111-year-old
National Zoo, wounding seven children, one critically. Police
arrested Antoine Jones, 16, on Tuesday and are holding him without
bail. Prosecutors said they intend to try him as an adult on
attempted murder charges. If found guilty, he could face life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were not certain what provoked the shootings at
one of Washington's most popular tourist attractions, but community
leaders noted a pattern of violence against schoolchildren in the
District of Columbia, at least 17 of whom have been killed this
school year.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity at the Ballpark
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball players aren't known for political
activism, but the Elian Gonzalez case spurred more than a dozen
players and coaches to sit out games last Tuesday, in support of a
work stoppage by Cuban-Americans in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Mets shortstop Rey Ordonez and coach Cookie Rojas, both
Cuban-born, left Shea Stadium before the Mets' game with the
Cincinnati Reds, while Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez, a Cuban
defector, wore street clothes in the dugout at Yankee Stadium. Reds
outfielder Alex Ochoa, whose parents are Cuban, played because his
team was riddled by injuries. ``They need me to play.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
