<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A blow to demagogues' rights
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Constitution has just ducked another bullet, but beware the
ricochet. This being a big-time election year, the Constitution
remains in danger from the politicians who are sworn to uphold it.
</P>
<P>
   The near miss this time was an amendment championing so-called
victims' rights. The amendment was pulled by its sponsors at the
last minute when they found putative supporters jumping ship.
Enough senators had figured out that the amendment was such an
unholy mess that even the temptation of easy demagoguery couldn't
keep them aboard.
</P>
<P>
   You can't be sure this monster won't walk again, however. Its
authors have retired only to the cloakroom to work on their
skittish confreres out of public sight.
</P>
<P>
   There's a perfectly good case for legislatively enumerating some
rights for crime victims _ rights, for instance, to be notified of
trials and probation hearings, to be told a prisoner release is
imminent and more.
</P>
<P>
   But 47 states already have constitutional provisions or
legislation that either explicitly or in effect sets out rights for
crime victims. (Who are, in any event, the implied concern of the
criminal justice system from the get-go.)
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, muddle the Constitution with gratuitous complications
whose broad implications would be uncertain and whose applications
would ignite years of contentious litigation?
</P>
<P>
   You almost have to feel sorry for the politicians who have been
working the law-and-order hustle for decades. Crime has been
falling sharply for several years. We have a bigger proportion of
our people in jails and prisons than any other nation except
Russia, that model of social enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in short, getting hard to sell criminals to the
electorate, so hawking victims' rights is the new product from the
same old pitchmen.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that the states aren't adequately funding their
victim programs. If so, then the federal remedy, if any is called
for, would be matching grants to incite more statehouse effort.
There's no call to gum up the Constitution over this evolving and
unstable area of law.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the ineptness of the amendment that it is
wordier than the whole Bill of Rights _ a rhetorical thicket oddly
dangerous to prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment could allow angry or impatient victims to demand
overwrought charges and trials before cases are well-prepared. It
could block plea-bargains in favor of hopeless trials. Where there
are multiple victims, their contrary demands could produce wildly
disparate prosecutions for the same crime.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Constitution has been attacked by
showboating pols out to force prayer into public schools, deny
women abortions, require balanced budgets, limit elected terms and
criminalize flag-burners. April alone saw further sallies at the
Constitution to require super-majorities for tax increases and to
exempt campaign funding reforms from free-speech considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution, repeatedly menaced, could use a few victim's
rights itself.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
