<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-HISPANICS     05-01 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-HISPANICS-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRED GENERATION: HISPANICS ONLINE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JEFF D. VITUCCI and HILLARY LEON  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hispanics are fast becoming an online economic power.
 &HT;    A recent Hispanic Business/Zogby International poll found that
almost one-half (49 percent) of Hispanics have made an online
purchase in the last three months, compared to 34.7 percent of
Anglos, 31.3 percent of African Americans and 14.9 percent of
Asians. The same poll found that Hispanics are more likely to spend
larger amounts on the Web compared to other groups. About 38
percent of Hispanics surveyed spent more than $100 in the past
three months, compared to 16 percent of Anglos, 11 percent of
Asians and 6 percent of African Americans.
 &HT;    In a study of 2,000 Internet-ready U.S. Hispanics, commissioned
by Espanol.com, 76 percent of respondents reported having made
purchases online, with 62 percent having done so in the last 12
months. The study found that average purchases range from
approximately $325 to $550 per year.
 &HT;    In terms of specific purchases, 65 percent of Hispanics surveyed
reported buying software upgrades, 52 percent purchased CDs and
music tapes and 48 percent purchased books and magazines.
 &HT;    The trend may be attributable in part to an increased effort on
the part of online retailers to market specifically to Hispanics,
says David Morse of Cultural Access Group, a marketing consulting
firm.
 &HT;    ``Presently, there is a concentrated effort to market to ethnic
groups. The sudden interest in the Hispanic market stems from the
growth in their population and in their per capita income,'' Morse
said.
 &HT;    Corresponding increases in computer ownership and Internet
access also have helped fuel Hispanics' embrace of e-commerce.
According to a recent U.S. Department of Commerce National
Telecommunications and Information Administration study, about 26
percent of Hispanic households in the United States owned a
computer in 1998. The percentage constitutes a doubling of computer
ownership among Hispanic households from four years earlier.
 &HT;    The Department of Commerce reports that the disparity between
the computer ownership rate among Hispanics and that of Anglos _
roughly a 2 to 1 ratio _ largely disappears at higher income
levels. For example, while about 80 percent of all households with
an annual income greater than $75,000 own a computer, the figure
drops only slightly, to about 75 percent, for similarly affluent
Hispanic households.
 &HT;    Because the Internet is relatively new, historic data on
Internet use are lacking. However, according to the Department of
Commerce study, approximately 12.6 percent of Hispanic households
use the Internet, compared to 11.2 percent of African American and
29.8 percent of Anglo households. The study indicates that 72.5
percent of Hispanics who are online are using the Internet for
e-mail, 60.5 percent for information searches, 43.5 percent for
taking courses, 17.4 percent for job searches and 28.3 percent for
other purposes.
 &HT;    The Tomds Rivera Policy Institute put Hispanic Internet
connectivity at 15 percent, and other studies suggest the rate is
even higher.
 &HT;    While the connectivity rate in the Hispanic community is
comparatively low, those who are online are purchasing at a higher
level than that for the overall population. One reason may be the
Hispanic tradition of bargain-hunting.
 &HT;    ``Latinos are very price-conscious, and the best deals are
online. We like a bargain,'' says Yaz Colon, co-founder and chief
marketing and merchandising officer at Espanol.com.
 &HT;    A contributing factor may be the Internets relative
affordability as a communications tool, especially among Hispanics
with relatives in Latin America.
 &HT;    'We are finding that Hispanics like an international focus. They
want to read, chat and retrieve information from their hometowns,''
Morse said.
 &HT;    Perhaps more importantly, Hispanics do not appear to be afraid
to use Internet technology. According to the U.S. Department of
Commerce study, 31.6 percent of Hispanics are not concerned about
Internet confidentiality, compared to almost 23 percent of Anglos,
28.4 percent of African Americans and 24 percent of Asians.
 &HT;    ``Non-Latinos prefer to surf the Web on their own, while Latinos
expect a lot in customer service, including online chat instant
help, and toll-free numbers. Latinos value communication, and we
give them every avenue to do so,'' Colon said.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Jeff Vitucci is the director of research service/chief
economist for Hispanic Business magazine, where Hillary Leon is a
research assistant.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic Business 
