<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2103 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-TRIBUTE-T     05-01 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-TRIBUTE-TO-GOV-MICKELSON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW SOON WE FORGET GREATNESS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By TIM GIAGO (NANWICA KCIJI)  
 &HT;    The people of America are usually pretty fastidious about
celebrating the dates of important historical happenings. One such
event occurred in South Dakota 10 years ago, but one would never
know it happened if one waited for the mainstream media to bring it
up.
 &HT;    In 1989, Gov. George Mickelson (R-S.D.) came to my newspaper,
The Lakota Nation Journal, to cut the ribbon for the grand opening
of our new building in Rapid City. He gave a speech to my employees
and some friends who had come to help celebrate the occasion.
 &HT;    In his speech, Mickelson said that 40 years ago when he was
about 12 years old, he asked his father, who happened to be
governor of South Dakota at the time, about the most difficult
thing he had to contend with as governor. His father replied, ``The
bad relationship between Indians and whites.''
 &HT;    I took this message to heart. The year 1990 was to be the 100th
anniversary of the Massacre at Wounded Knee, a very infamous time
in American history. I wrote a column and suggested to the governor
that Indians and whites come together in 1990. I wrote that, just
as the Lakota planned a ``Wiping Away the Tears'' ceremony on Dec.
29, 1990, the date of the massacre, perhaps the whites and Indians
could use this special year and special ceremony to do likewise and
make it a Year of Reconciliation.
 &HT;    In a special editorial to my newspaper he wrote that he would do
everything in his power to see it happen. He did make it happen. A
proclamation was passed, making 1990 ``The Year of
Reconciliation.'' And more than that, he did something no other
state in the union would dare attempt: He got the state legislators
to pass a bill making Oct. 12 _ Columbus Day in the rest of America
_ Native American Day in South Dakota.
 &HT;    Ten years later, South Dakota is the only state in the union
that celebrates Native American Day in lieu of Columbus Day.
 &HT;    Mickelson didn't just talk the talk, he walked the walk. He
actively set out to begin the dialogue between Indians and whites.
Unless you've lived in South Dakota (or any of the states with
large Indian populations), it would be hard for you to understand
the anger and bitterness that exists between the races.
 &HT;    Recently, I had lunch with a representative of a South Dakota
senator who had just paid a visit to Corson County and was shocked
at the hatred the white population of that county displayed against
the Lakota (Sioux) people. She was so taken aback at the vocal
abuse heaped upon the Lakota that she nearly resigned from her job.
 &HT;    One could almost feel the change happening in South Dakota
during the Year of Reconciliation. Indians and whites were talking.
Both races were ready to sit and talk about the good, the bad and
the ugly in this state.
 &HT;    And then a terrible thing happened. Mickelson died in a plane
crash. With him died the Year, and the Century, of Reconciliation.
 &HT;    It is such a sad thing to not only lose a great governor, but to
see the tiny window he had opened slammed shut after his death.
 &HT;    It has been 10 years since the Year of Reconciliation became an
active proclamation in South Dakota. And yet, the silence about it
is deafening. No one in the media wants to bring it up. It was an
historic time when truly great things were happening and when peace
could have come between the races.
 &HT;    The American people are usually overzealous about celebrating
anniversaries, but this one is now four months old and not one item
has appeared in newspapers or on television in South Dakota. Is it
because we now have a governor who would just as soon keep this
anniversary in the closet?
 &HT;    A few weeks ago, Gov. Bill Janklow (R-S.D.) trashed the Civil
Rights Commission's Report on racism in South Dakota as
``garbage,'' and it is this hostile and primitive attitude that
feeds the proponents of racism here. Many covert racists are only
too eager to follow the governor's lead.
 &HT;    But all of that aside, why has there been no white leader in
South Dakota willing to pick up the torch of reconciliation once
held high by Mickelson? The Indians have talked about it and
wondered, but it requires strong leadership on the other side of
the fence.
 &HT;    The people of South Dakota, white and red, lost a tremendous
opportunity to lead America out of the depths of racism by serving
as an example of how people can come together for positive change.
Perhaps 1990 was not the year, and perhaps the races were not ready
to come to the table as friends. The years since would surely point
to that as racism continues to grow and fester.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Tim Giago (Nanwica Kciji _ ``Stands up for Them'') is an Oglala
Lakota. He is editor and publisher of the weekly newspaper, The
Lakota Nation Journal. He can be reached at: P.O. Box 3080, Rapid
City, S.D. 57709-3080 or e-mailed at: editor at
lakotanationjournal.com
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Tim Giago 
