<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES TARGET WOMEN SURFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Targeting the influx of women who surf the Internet, a growing
number of Web sites promise to save busy mothers and career women
time and money, with one-stop shopping for everything from birth
control pills to housewarming gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Women make up about 50 percent of Internet users, and the number
of women online jumped 32 percent between February 1999 and
December 1999, according to a Nielsen report released this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Web sites are looking to grab market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women really are just the fastest-growing segment of
e-commerce shoppers and users,'' said Melinda Halpert, senior vice
president of marketing for the Women's Consumer Network in
Washington, D.C. It launched a site about a year ago to help busy
women find good values on everything from disability insurance to
child care to new cars.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites, including WCN's, charge a membership fee; others
offer free registration. But they all say it's worth the effort to
sign up, considering the discounts members enjoy and the time they
can save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many busy working women are trying to juggle so many
responsibilities for our homes, our jobs, our life,'' Halpert said.
``We're helping to save time in the kind of primary comparison
shopping that a lot of women do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sites even promise to deliver dry cleaning, stamps,
flowers, and United Parcel Service packages, as well as the
groceries that online supermarket delivery services have already
carved out as a niche.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Web pages make passing references to men, but they
clearly focus on women as the ones in the household who are pressed
for time and responsible for shopping for everything from the
perfect birthday gift to designer clothing.
</P>
<P>
   But the sites acknowledge that women want to do more than just
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Some provide advice about relationships, health, and beauty;
others offer a virtual community in the form of a message board or
chat room. And some offer links to information about the
presidential campaign and financial planning.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, their bread and butter is still helping women to
shop. For example:
</P>
<P>
   --www.womensconsumer.net _ For $21.95 a year, you get discounts
on what the Women's Consumer Network has found to be the best of
everything, from birth control pills to debt-collection services
for chasing alimony and child support payments.
</P>
<P>
   The site promises unbiased research, group buying power, and
exclusive discounts, although the network receives commissions from
the companies, based on members' use of the recommended services or
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``No company, no provider can pay for our endorsement up
front,'' Halpert said. A company is not approached unless it meets
the network's standards for value, and a recommendation is not
based on how much commission a company is willing to pay, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of products and services WCN compares before
making a recommendation: Banking services, legal services available
by telephone, health and disability insurance, Internet service
providers, emergency cellular phone service, child care, and gift
basket delivery services.
</P>
<P>
   The site says it can save members hundreds, if not thousands, of
dollars on such major purchases as a car.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, membership also includes an e-mail newsletter, a
``Customer Care'' gift every month, and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   --www.iVillage.com _ While the focus of this site, subtitled
``The Women's Network,'' is ``busy women sharing solutions and
advice,'' it also lets them shop for baby doll dresses at
gapkids.com and beauty supplies at gloss.com.
</P>
<P>
   Free membership as an ``iVillager'' allows women access to
bargains, a personal shopper to find the perfect gift, and a
newsletter with ideas for kids' gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Members can create online shopping lists to keep track of all of
those gift ideas for birthdays, baby showers, anniversaries, and
other special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   At ``Shopping Central,'' women can link to reviews of Web stores
that sell everything from knitting supplies to greeting cards; find
sales in their local areas by designer, store, or type of
merchandise; and search for items by such topics as art and
collectibles, astrology, baby goods, and career women.
</P>
<P>
   The Web store reviews are notable because they say whether the
businesses are owned by women.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're really pressed for time, you can link to a
selection of ``gifts you can get in a hurry,'' including gift
certificates for everything from spa visits to restaurant dining.
</P>
<P>
   And iVillage.com offers ``channels'' on astrology, health,
beauty, book clubs, money, and the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   There are also online tools for planning menus, picking baby
names, and checking your financial and physical health _ along with
a ``pregnancy calendar,'' so you'll know what to expect during
those nine months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
