<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT KIDS DON'T KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's good for kids to learn something about money. But what are
they learning in a society obsessed with the buck?
</P>
<P>
   A recent Junior Achievement poll found that 25 percent of
teenagers surveyed believed they'd be millionaires by age 40. The
dollar signs were even bigger for the 15 percent who believed
they'd be earning more than $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The national survey questioned 1,302 students in grades 6 though
12, and pollsters consider 25 percent high, particularly when only
about 7 percent of the US population are millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Achievement, dedicated to educating young people about
business, winced at the unrealistic view of life and work in what
it calls ``the millionaire generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation has grown up in extremely prosperous times,''
says Monte Lutz, spokesman for Junior Achievement Inc. in Colorado
Springs, Colo. ``They have the idea that anything they can imagine
or think can actually happen. Their life experience, combined with
a society fascinated with fame and fortune, have convinced them
that all they have to do to be a millionaire is show up and play
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The message blasts not only from television and newsstands, but
also from a growing list of children's money books. Titles such as
``Coin Country,'' ``KidBiz,'' ``Fast Cash For Kids,'' and ``The
Totally Awesome Money Book'' outline everything from the history of
money to how to set up a lemonade stand.
</P>
<P>
   There's some useful information here, and the books talk about
the need to be responsible with money. But the sheer number of
titles _ about 15 at the Borders bookstore in Braintree _ combined
with the popularity of stock market clubs, computer games called
``Gazillionaire'' and ``Profitania,'' and summer business camps,
just might be sending the message that greed is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are bored,'' says Mike Caslin, chief executive of the
National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship, which runs
business camps. ``They want to know why they're in school.
Entrepreneurship gives them the why.''
</P>
<P>
   His organization works with teens ages 14 to 18, many
underprivileged, and has a fine reputation for inspiring young
people to start businesses and get their lives together.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't something vital missing from a society that considers
money a stronger motivator than the excitement of learning?
Shouldn't the words of Shakespeare, Jefferson, and Maya Angelou
always light a fire hotter than any economy?
</P>
<P>
   John Dacey, professor of developmental psychology at Boston
College and author of the book ``Your Anxious Child,'' says the
economy is often too hot for a kid to handle and the money flowing
from parents and from employers eager for hourly workers is putting
a lot of pressure on teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's possible to keep up with the Joneses, to buy the
coolest thing,'' he explains, noting that anxiety ratchets up when
kids aren't sure what that coolest thing is. ``We've all heard
about the kid who was killed for a coat or for his sneakers. What
we don't hear about is the kid ostricized for not wearing the right
shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens buy status when they buy presents for each other. ``They
don't buy a girlfriend or boyfriend a tape or CD anymore,'' Dacey
says. ``They buy a leather coat. And I'm not just talking
Wellesley. I'm talking Roxbury. A generation of kids is taking on
adult responsibilities of spending and choices when they don't yet
have the judgmental ability to handle them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hello, parents? The school investment workshop, the games, and
the books aren't enough. Kids need to talk with adults about values
as well as price tags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents come in younger and younger and ask, `What do we teach
our kids?' says Joan Indursky DiFuria, who cofounded the Money,
Meaning &AMP; Choices Institute in San Francisco with psychologist
Stephen Goldbart. The organization helps people define their values
and gain perspective on the staggering wealth that has become
commonplace in the high-tech boom.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake is making things too easy and ``shielding
our children from what helped make us mature adults,'' says Janine
Bempechat, assistant professor at the Harvard Graduate School of
Education. She's the author of the book ``Getting Our Kids Back on
Track: Educating Children for the Future.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the perfect companion volume for the how-tos of a
cash culture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
