<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE SALE COULD HELP RETIREES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I had to retire last year for health reasons. I will collect
disability checks until 65, then $1,470 monthly from Social
Security. In May, I will receive the first of four checks from my
former employer's ESOP, eventually totallin $82,300. My husband
plans to retire in three years at 55. We will sell our primary home
and move to our vacation home; our plan is to have little or no
mortgage obligations by the time my husband retires. As long as
he's working, I plan to contribute the maximum $2,000 a year to a
Roth IRA. By the time I hit 65, how healthy do you think our
retirement savings might be?
</P>
<P>
   S.R., East Sandwich, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Almost certainly, you'll have enough in savings to make up
the difference between your disability income and the lower Social
Security benefit. If you continue your contributions to the Janus
fund accounts, plus fully fund your Roth IRA for the next three
years, plus add the ESOP payments to your savings _ and if you
achieve average investment gains of 10 percent _ you would have
$325,054 in three years when your husband retires. Adding the final
ESOP payment at the end of the next year, you would then have
$379,541 at the end of the fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   If you then discontinue contributions to your accounts and
simply let the accounts grow for the following 11 years, you would
accumulate $1,174,809 by the time you reach age 65. The second
calculation also presumes 10 percent investment returns, and that
you will pay any taxes that result from the Janus accounts from
other funds. (These calculations do not include the value of your
insurance policies.)
</P>
<P>
   Such an accumulation would, of course, be a whole lot more than
you would need to make up for the difference between $3,364 in
monthly disability income and $1,470 in Social Security payments.
But it would only be a little more than adequate to deal with
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   When you first retire, you will have an income stream of $81,368
a year. But by the time 12 more years have passed and you switch
from disability income to Social Security, you will need $123,708
to buy what $81,868 bought in 2003, presuming that inflation runs
at a 3.5 percent average clip.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, instead of needing $19,488 a year to cover the difference
between disability and Social Security, you will need about $65,000
a year. (It's silly to make an exact projection here, because the
amount of Social Security benefits will indubitably rise modestly
over the next 17 years, so the shortfall is likely to be
considerably smaller.) Also, you would be in a much better
situation if there is a cost-of-living adjustment in your husband's
pension. And if your husband, too, will qualify for Social
Security, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, given the relentless power of inflation to gnaw
away at savings, consider whether you might continue some additions
to the Janus portfolio early in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   If you were able to come out of the move to your remodeled
vacation home without a mortgage and with cash to boot, it would
help a lot. If you achieve 10 percent investment returns (and pay
the taxes from other funds) you could expect that every dollar you
could cull from the real estate swap would grow to $4 by that
critical stage at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   Your investment choices seem solid. I especially like the
addition of Vanguard Health Care to what is otherwise an all-index
rollover portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am satisfied with the funds to which my employer
contributes. I am not afraid of risk and fear I am missing out on
higher returns from the more aggressive funds available. What about
adding a new fund and transferring the balance from the Wellington
and/or Windsor positions to one of the following Vanguard funds:
Mid-Cap Index, Growth Index, Morgan Growth, PRIMECAP, Explorer,
Capital Opportunity, Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   S.G., Cambridge, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I agree with your thinking when it comes to Wellington, but
not necessarily Windsor. Wellington is a fine fund, and the kind of
thing you'll want to be thinking about in 20 years. But for now,
the ticket should be stocks, stocks and more stocks. I suggest you
transfer the entire balance in the Wellington holding to new funds,
putting $3,600 each into Vanguard Health Care and Vanguard Capital
Opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Then, realign your contributions so that 30 percent goes into
Vanguard Index 500, 20 percent each to Windsor and Growth and
Income, and 10 percent each to Health Care, Capital Opportunity,
and a new position in Vanguard Mid-Cap Index.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand your temptation to pull the trigger on Vanguard
Windsor, but its doldrums of the past few seasons are simply a
function of a market in which the value stocks, which are Windsor's
staples, are out of fashion. I would expect the fund to return to
its very solid long-term trend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. I recently had a CD mature and was not notified. I suspect they
didn't send me one because last time I had an IRA CD mature I put
the proceeds in a money market account rather than another CD,
because I wanted to combine several accounts to make it easier for
me in a couple of years when I turn 70 1/2 and will need to make
withdrawals. If I had remembered the CD was maturing I would have
moved the money to another bank to get a full 1 percent additional
interest. Are they obligated to send reminder notices?
</P>
<P>
   M.B., Beaumont, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A certificate of deposit is, at bottom, a contract. The terms
are precisely what is spelled out in the certificate itself _
nothing more. Read the document carefully; you may be out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, these people don't impress me as particularly
hot bankers. Go to the branch manager or one of the highest
officers. Most bankers, I think, would be willing to come to some
sort of accommodation. But I suspect that as a matter of law or
regulation, you have no recourse, save to complain and hope for the
best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
