<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BANKS A HAVEN FROM HIGH FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes where to find web banking text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Chute has some advice for consumers getting bounced around
right now in the banking equivalent of musical chairs: Try an
Internet bank.
</P>
<P>
   Chute has tried Netbank.com out of Georgia for the last six
months and has found little to complain about. Netbank pays him a
rate of interest on his checking account that is six times what
most bricks-and-mortar banks offer, charges him no fees for writing
checks or making online bill payments, and requires no minimum
balance in his account.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the sort of treatment that disgruntled
FleetBoston and Citizens Bank customers have been demanding from
their banks in the wake of recent mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like your bank, switch,'' said the 26-year-old
Chute. ``And for those people who are afraid of the Internet or
don't have access, you don't need it. You get a monthly paper
statement mailed to you and you can handle most of your banking
over their 800 customer service number.''
</P>
<P>
   Chute has a point. Internet banks have some disadvantages _ ATM
charges and deposit delays are drawbacks _ but their potential is
enormous. No one likes to stand in line at a bank (Chute says he
hasn't been inside a bank in three years), and increasingly, with
ATMs and direct deposit, there is less and less reason to go.
</P>
<P>
   Internet banks say they can afford to pay higher interest rates
and charge fewer fees than traditional banks because they don't
have branches or ATM networks to pay for. For example,
Lighthousebank.com, which recently received its final regulatory
approvals, expects to open in June with just 25 employees, about
what three FleetBoston branches employ.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for an Internet bank is fairly easy. You have to read
the fine print just like you would with a regular bank, but the
product offerings of most Internet banks are strikingly simple and
similar. It took me about two hours to compare the product
offerings of six banks. It's a lot more confusing with traditional
banks, which seem to delight in customized account features that
make comparisons difficult.
</P>
<P>
   A simple checking account at an Internet bank generally requires
a low minimum balance or no balance at all, while paying as much as
4 percent interest and offering free online bill payments.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston, by contrast, offers a self-service checking account
that has no minimum balance requirement, but it offers no interest
and charges monthly fees of $7 ($5 with direct deposit) plus $4.50
for online bill payment. It also charges $2 if a teller or a phone
service representative is used to do a transaction that could be
done electronically.
</P>
<P>
   To get an interest rate of 0.5 percent, a customer would have to
sign up for a FleetOne Classic account, which requires a $2,000
balance in checking or a $4,000 combined balance to avoid a $10
monthly fee. The $4.50 fee for online bill payment would still
apply. To avoid that fee, a customer would have to sign up for a
FleetOne Gold account, which would require parking $10,000 in
various Fleet accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Certificates of deposit are also more attractive at Internet
banks. The six banks I surveyed were all offering rates of more
than 6 percent for six-month CDs with a minimum deposit of $2,500.
By contrast, the Boston average of banks surveyed by Bank Rate
Monitor is just 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internet banks have some limitations. Most don't have extensive
ATM networks, so customers are forced to use the ATMs of other
banks and absorb their surcharges. Some Internet banks reimburse
customers for some surcharges ($5 to $7 a month is typical), but
not all of them do.
</P>
<P>
   Depositing money is also more difficult. Direct deposit, wire
transfers, and ATMs, if they happen to be owned by the Internet
bank, are all options. But in general Internet bank customers have
to rely on the US mail to deposit a check. That may not be too big
of a burden if the check is going to someplace local, but if it's
going to Oakland or Atlanta it can take a lot longer. Although
Internet banks provide postage-paid envelopes, Chute said deposit
delays in dealing with Netbank in Georgia have been the biggest
downside for him.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from ATM fees and deposit delays, officials at FleetBoston
say consumers simply feel more comfortable in dealing with a bank
where they can talk to someone in person if they need to. Since
banking is not the same as buying a book online, the officials said
customers prefer a ``clicks and mortar bank'' like Fleet, where
they can get all the benefits of an Internet as well as a
traditional bank.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Wolfson, director of interactive banking at Fleet, said few
customers shop for a checking account based on pricing factors such
as interest rates and fees. What they want, he said, are financial
options, including having the same institution provide their
banking, brokerage, and credit card services. That type of
integration is hard to find at Internet banks today, although it's
coming.
</P>
<P>
   Although Internet bank deposits are insured the same as deposits
at traditional banks, Wolfson raised doubts about whether many of
the Internet banks popping up today will be around in years to
come. Big players, including General Electric and Wall Street
brokerage houses, are getting into the business and there may be a
shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a known entity,'' Wolfson said. ``People know Fleet will
be around in two years. An Internet bank is somewhat of an
unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, but I suspect 10 years from now the dynamics
may be far different. In the meantime, the rates offered by
Internet banks are enough to get anyone's attention, especially at
a time when fees are on the minds of just about every banking
customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the perfect solution for the FleetBoston and Citizens
customers,'' said Thomas Venables, a former community savings bank
executive who is now president and chief executive of
Lighthousebank. ``Traditional banking is going to keep losing
market share.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Another glitch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Essential.com, which sells energy and communications services
online, suffered another customer service glitch recently. The
Burlington, Mass. company responded admirably, but the incident
renewed concerns about whether the company's customer service
problems are behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Essential.com has forthrightly acknowledged its customer service
had lagged badly as its customer base soared. Company officials
detailed a number of initiatives they had taken to correct the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
