<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESHOP-SAFETY0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savvy shoppers learn the rules before they begin
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Before you start your e-shopping adventures, here are some key
points to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   1. SECURITY: Most reputable Web retailers have secure ordering
forms to protect your personal information. They'll let you know
you are ordering via a secure connection. They also offer detailed
information about their security policies. If you aren't sure if a
site offers security, think twice before placing an order.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good idea to check with your credit card companies
about security options they offer. For example, American Express
will not hold card members responsible for unauthorized charges
online. Nor are you responsible for the first $50 in unauthorized
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   2. PRIVACY POLICY: Technically, there's no law preventing any
Web site from giving out personal information about you to anyone
who asks. However, most retailers are sensitive to shoppers'
privacy concerns. Make sure each site you visit has a privacy
policy. Most of them do.
</P>
<P>
   3. CUSTOMER SERVICE: Most sites have automated e-mail systems
that tell you when they received your order, when they sent it and
when it is expected to arrive. Some e-tailers will send you postal
tracking numbers for your reference if there's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   4. UNDERSTAND THE ORDER PROCESS: Remember, your order isn't
final until you hit the ``submit'' key. If your Internet connection
seems slow, or nothing seems to be happening, you might be tempted
to keep hitting ``submit'' as you would the buttons on an elevator
that just won't close. Don't do it! Each time you tap submit, you
could be creating another order. One click is all usually all you
need.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
