<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOING-CYBER0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web opens new doors for stores
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Going Cyber!''
</P>
<P>
   The handwriting is a bit crooked and hard to make out from a
distance, and yet the sign on the front door of ``The Family
Jewels'' in downtown Decatur, Ga. speaks volumes. Next week, the
13-year-old antiques and collectibles store will become an
online-only operation, joining a host of other businesses for whom
the Internet is the greatest thing to come along since customers
with unlimited lines of credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can move anywhere in the world and I'll always have my
inventory with me,'' enthused owner Lisa Cohen. ``My computer is
the world!''
</P>
<P>
   The Family Jewels isn't going out of business. Only
``shifting,'' according to the hand-lettered sign. It's just one
more sign of these times, when countless business owners are using
the Internet to discover and develop their rightful niche in the
new economy.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's a matter of staying right where they are, offline
and behind a counter. Others, like Cohen, come to see that they and
their customers would be better served by ``going cyber''
completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like a beautiful Lalique bowl could sit in the store
for years because maybe only five people who came in knew what it
was and they didn't collect it,'' said Cohen, who's selling on
Yahoo and eBay and will do business by e-mail
(famjewlinc(at)aol.com), and her own Web site
(http://members.aol.com/famjewlinc/collect2/index.htm). ``But I put
it on the Internet and get 500 people who'll see it in seven days
and who'll know what they're looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2142 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-ME-STORE0502-COX     05-01 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ME-STORE0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doing it my way, sort of
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnosk.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It might have been the nearly silent episode of ``Law
&AMP; Order'' that finally did it.
</P>
<P>
   The sound on my television set had been faltering for quite a
while; now, when it practically went mute in the middle of
Detective Lenny Briscoe cracking wise, I decided it might be time
to buy a new one.
</P>
<P>
   This was not some lighthearted whim. I'd had that TV since
leaving college _ long enough that the cable company didn't even
have the right, suitably archaic, equipment to hook me up.
</P>
<P>
   Long enough to confirm the accuracy of a friend's observation
the year I went 13 weeks without owning a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have,'' he sighed, just before heading out to buy another
cold beer, ``a fear of commitment to new appliances.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the appliances so much as the actual shopping for them
that gives me agita. In fact, when it comes to shopping for almost
anything but basic essentials, all I can come up with are reasons
not to:
</P>
<P>
   _ The staff will be too dumb or too devious to sell me the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   _ The traffic will be horrible, the parking nonexistent and my
car (7-years-old, ahem!) might need gas.
</P>
<P>
   _ What if I can't find what I want? (Worse, what if I can ?)
What if I have to return something?
</P>
<P>
   Why even bother?
</P>
<P>
   Why not just create the Me Store instead?
</P>
<P>
   It hit me the next morning, when I opened the yellow pages to
``Televisions'' and instantly felt overwhelmed. If only I could do
all my shopping online, I thought, I'd never have this problem. I
could buy exactly what I wanted, when I wanted, without ever having
to get into my car or out of my pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the perfect store. The ``Me Store.'' Always open,
always stocked with exactly what I wanted, never about another
human being's needs except mine. All mine!
</P>
<P>
   One month later, I'd bought a whole lot and learned even more.
Neither the Internet nor human nature is 100 percent predictable,
and so the complete Me Store may be something of a pipe dream _ for
now, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But it sure was fun trying. I shopped at many more sites than
the eight bookmarked below, but they're all representative of
something I learned along the way.
</P>
<P>
   So, where'd I finally end up buying that new TV? Well, just keep
reading .
</P>
<P>
   THE SITES
</P>
<P>
   www.amazon.com _ Everyone's heard of this behemoth hawking
everything from books to buzz saws. What few people realize is that
it has only one customer: Me! Seriously, I bought one measly thing
from them, and all of a sudden they couldn't stop thinking about
me. They greet me by name each I log on. They're constantly
compiling lists of books, videos and CDs they think I'd enjoy. I
sometimes get the feeling they're all just sitting around, waiting
for me to order something.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Flattery will definitely get you somewhere in
the Me Store.
</P>
<P>
   twinings.com _ The last time I cut myself, I bled Earl Grey. Not
all grocery stores carry English-made Twinings Teas but they
should. Even the Queen drinks nothing but! The site featured
Twinings teas I'd never even heard of, let alone seen in Kroger,
and a chart to determine which blend to drink when (``after
dinner'') and why (``to help with a cold or flu''). It even
converted your total order from pounds to dollars. Unfortunately,
the bloody thing crashed every time I tried to actually place an
order for two days, so I finally gave up and headed for Kroger.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Parts of the Me Store may not always be open.
</P>
<P>
   zabars.com _ What am I, chopped liver? Like New Year's Eve
celebrations and mob hits, the chopped chicken liver from Zabar's
is something we'll never quite see the likes of here. I'd rather go
without than go without Zabar's, so imagine my glee when the
venerable Upper West Side deli and gourmet food shop put up a Web
site. Even the fact that it's not yet set up to handle Internet
orders (you have to fax or phone) didn't deter me from droolingly
scanning the offerings: Corned beef, bagels-and-schmears, smoked
salmon, rugelach ... What, no chopped liver?! I fired off a
distraught e-mail and four days later, received a polite (well, for
New York) response to the effect that I had to phone, ask for
personal shopping and pay an extra $7.50 for what is, let's face
it, the guts of a chicken. Except for very special occasions, I
guess I'll have to do without.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Parts of the Me Store may still be under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   drugstore.com _ I'm getting awfully tired of wandering through
huge drug ``superstores,'' wondering why it's easier to find potato
chips than Q-tips and how come they can process film in an hour,
but you have to stand in line all day to buy Chap Stick.
Fortunately, there are huge drugstore Web sites I can wander
through, wondering whether I really want to go through all this
bother just to buy Chap Stick. Well, yes, since they also gave _
gave! _ me $20 worth of ``bath and spa'' products suitable for
washing away any lingering trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Zabar's, schmabar's ... Who says there's no free
lunch?!
</P>
<P>
   endlesspools.com _ I am a firm believer in the benefits of
regular exercise. Just so long as I don't have to, you know,
actually stand up or go outside to do it. Enter the Endless Pool, a
``counter-current swimming and water exercise machine'' _
basically, a teeny-tiny little swimming pool they build inside your
den or wine cellar so you can paddle in place. If you even have to
ask how much one of these babies costs (the Web site doesn't quote
prices), you know you can't afford it _ in my case, I'd have to
include the cost of buying a house, since I doubt my landlord would
let me install one in my apartment. If I walked into a store they'd
instantly have me pegged as a relatively impoverished poseur, but
what does a Web site know? They're sending me a free video,
brochures and ``other materials.'' Heck, it's only a matter of time
until I fake them into sending me a free pool!
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: I can be whoever I want in the Me Store.
Including Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ivillage.com _ My niece is about to turn 11 in San Francisco and
she likes (in no particular order) clothes, baseball, the
Backstreet Boys and Nancy Drew mysteries. Stumped for a gift to
have sent to her (the operative phrase), I consider calling my
mother, but I know she's not home and besides, I'm really not up to
hearing about how she ran into some old boyfriend of mine (unless
he's fat and bald) and his wife (ditto). But this Web site that
bills itself as ``The Women's Network'' provides real human
``personal shoppers'' free of charge. Within the promised 48 hours,
Leslie e-mails me information about a San Francisco museum's
exhibition on ``The Science of Baseball.'' She also directs me to
ivillage's toy department. Leslie, I love you for trying, but the
ideal gift for an 11-year-old lies somewhere between toys and a
museum visit.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Call your mother. No, wait, there's more: The Me
Store really can't do your important thinking for you.
</P>
<P>
   delias.com calyxandcorolla.com _ Being a reporter pretty much
boils down to finding the right people to talk to, and then making
them talk. So it should be easy for me to complain to stores about
their products or services, right? Hah! You know the drill: You
talk to some teen clerk, who says you need to talk to the manager,
who vaguely promises to pass it along to ``corporate.'' If only the
big cheeses at ``corporate'' could hear from you directly about how
they done you wrong. Now, with e-mail, they can. Endlessly. While
it took Delia's six days to respond to my e-mail questioning their
handling of the aforementioned niece's birthday present, other Web
vendors seem to realize they've put a lot of eggs in the e-commerce
basket and are quite good about saying ``so sorry.'' Some are truly
spectacular about it: Calyx &AMP; Corolla didn't just apologize for
messing up an order; in a prompt e-mail that included (mistakenly,
I think) their interoffice communication about me, this purveyor of
gorgeous flowers gave me a whopping $75 credit. Hey, maybe I'll
send them flowers!
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: The customer is always right in the Me Store.
And the wronged customer can usually be bought off.
</P>
<P>
   circuitcity.com _ So, remember what started this whole thing? I
spent several days e-shopping for TVs: Flat TVs, fat TVs, TVs with
the VCR built right in. There were no traffic jams to suffer
through and no salespeople to feel stupid around; there was even
circuitcity.com's empathetic acknowledgment that ``Buying a TV/VCR
can be complicated with all the choices available today.'' My
feelings having finally been validated, I decided to click and buy.
That is, just as soon as I figured out what color I wanted. And the
screen size. VCR, inside or out? V-chip, yay or nay? Have it
delivered right to my door within days, or get in my car (aargh!)
and pick it up today at a Circuit City store near my home? Come to
think of it, my old TV wasn't so bad _ in fact, if I put my ear
right up against it and listened hard, I could actually hear
something, though it might just have been the sound of my heart
pounding at the mere thought of having to commit to a new
appliance.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: You can't fight human nature, not even in the Me
Store.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
