r f BC-TECH-KIDGEAR0502-COX     05-01 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGEAR0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Croc2: Newer isn't always better
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   For gaming with kids, the original Croc was a fun romp with lots
of eye candy and a cute little backpack-wearing crocodile. And
though the sequel, Croc2 (Fox Interactive, $20, for PC and
consoles), is fun, some unfortunate changes have robbed the concept
of a lot of its zip. As in the original, Croc must battle little
red imps and an array of cartoonish monsters in a silly-scary but
beautiful 3-D world, whacking them with his tail and a loud
''kerpow!'' Croc2 also adds fun new vehicles such as go-carts and
speedboats, as well as a larger-feeling world. But overall it's a
step down from the straightforward fun of Croc with its misguided
attempt at simplifying the controls _ you simply have less control
_ and annoying conversations with characters that interrupt play.
Also frustrating are bugs that make some simple tasks impossible
and the removal of the original camera controls. The bottom line is
that Croc2 is still a fun game, but somewhere on a corporate
flip-chart at Fox Interactive are a lot of mediocre ideas that
somehow made it into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
