<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-VINTAGE-BOOKS-ONLINE0     05-01 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINTAGE-BOOKS-ONLINE0502O-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vintage bookstore's horizons expanding
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a mid-17th century Bible for sale and copies
of every Life magazine issue ever printed. Recently, an urgent
request came in for ``any and all pre-1960 poultry books.''
</P>
<P>
   Something interesting's always happening at Atlanta Vintage
Books, though the most intriguing development of late doesn't
involve what's on the shelves: Some of the store's best, most loyal
customers have never set foot in the place.
</P>
<P>
   They're cybershoppers. And contrary to conventional wisdom, they
may be helping rather than hurting independent stores savvy enough
to see venturing onto the Web as one more way of keeping their
doors open.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part of the business is steadily growing,'' said Alice
Otten, who took Atlanta Vintage Books online soon after buying the
store four years ago. ``Originally, 20 to 30 percent of our sales
in dollars were over the Internet. That's already up to about 40 to
45 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not simply a case of customers who once visited the
12-year-old store in search of Santayana or Tom Swift now logging
on instead. Otten said its Internet presence actually allows
Vintage Books, which is renowned for its children's, aviation and
African-American book areas, to reach new customers all over the
world. On a recent Friday morning employee A.R. Swan logged on and
found 21 e-mails waiting to be read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're totally expanding our customer base,'' said
Swan, who is primarily responsible for maintaining Vintage Books'
presence on five Internet sites and responding to e-mail orders and
inquiries. ``Very few of our online sales are to locals, and many
are repeat customers.''
</P>
<P>
   What those Internet shoppers may never get to see is a cozily
eclectic shop where the glass case filled with illuminated
manuscripts lies just beyond bookshelves labeled ``Nazi Germany''
and ``Whales,'' but before ``Success'' and ``Climate.'' Where the
47-volume, circa-1898, English Classics collection of Shakespeare's
works is, alas, not signed by the author, but Suzanne Somers'
poetry book is.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Internet users everywhere could react
instantly when a copy of ``The Duke Kahanamoku Story'' recently
washed up at Atlanta Vintage Books. Priced at $65, the bio of the
circa-1920s Olympic gold medal swimmer, early surfer, sometime
movie actor and later, sheriff in his native Honolulu, was sold
within 10 minutes of being listed online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got over 100 calls and e-mails,'' Swan laughingly recalled.
``Surfer guys saying, `Heey dude!,' people from the South Pacific.
I don't think it ever even made it onto the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon _ sometimes called ``clicks-and-mortar,'' refers
to the blending of computer-based sales within traditional
bricks-and-mortar shops. The impact of clicks-and-mortar on used
bookstores is undeniable, helping savvier owners sidestep many of
the problems ``new'' bookstores face from huge Internet and chain
competitors who can outstock them and reach customers around the
world. The number of used bookstores in the United States increased
14 percent between 1995 and 1999, according to a study conducted by
Book Hunter Press; Internet sales ranged from 10 percent to 50
percent of gross sales at stores online during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``While media reports have chronicled the Internet's negative
impact on new bookstores, the opposite is the case with used
bookstores,'' the report concluded. ``The Internet has enabled many
used booksellers to expand their customer base to the entire world,
and at the same time, it has provided used bookstores with an
additional revenue stream that supplements their in-store traffic
and other non-Internet mail order sales.'' Instead of relying on
word-of-mouth, expensive catalogs or print ads that may or may not
be seen by customers, used bookstores can join others listing their
stock on searchable sites like Advanced Book Exchange
(www.abe.com), Bibliofind (www.bibliofind.com) or even Internet
uberforce Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Potential drawbacks for ``bricks-and-mortar'' stores include the
time and expense of maintaining their Web site lists and responding
to e-mail, while continuing to run a store. Atlanta Vintage Books
lists the same 5,000-plus books (out of an inventory of about
60,000) on all the sites it uses, including one it just joined at
an annual cost of $185.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only went on there because one of our very good customers,
who we've never met, asked us to,'' Otten explained while Swan
worked through a minor glitch in the first order via that Web site.
``When I looked it up, there were about 35 orders we'd gotten from
(the customer) in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   If clicks-and-mortar operations like Atlanta Vintage Books
ultimately succeed, it likely will be for the most old-fashioned
reason: Customers think they can count on the people who run them.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hawkins is such a customer. The Greenville, S.C., Top 40
radio disc jockey was referred to Vintage Books by another store. A
collector of volumes in a particular biographical series and by
``Tarzan'' creator Edgar Rice Burroughs, he still goes online
occasionally to do research and look for books. Increasingly,
though, he finds himself dialing the phone to speak directly with
Atlanta Vintage Books manager Carrie Stikeleather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like calling your family and saying `I need this,'''
Hawkins said fondly about the store and staff he has never laid
eyes on. ``Everyone there has been great. I know I can trust
Carrie. If she says I need it, I need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Should he ever venture to Atlanta, Otten vows, the store will be
there. For her, the Internet could never entirely replace spending
time in a shop where every customer or book is potentially a good
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to make a lot more money doing this,'' Otten said
on a recent weekday morning when the people in the store included a
woman checking out a book of dog drawings she had seen described
online, and a book ``scout'' offering a carton full of Nabokovs and
Ferlinghettis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could make a fortune on the Internet and I'd just have to
hire someone to type up orders all day,'' Otten said. ``But that's
not the type of store any of us want.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
