<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-WEB-LIST0502-COX     05-01 2862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-LIST0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool sites for your home and garden
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   GET COOKIN': Groceries and gourmet food
</P>
<P>
   webvan.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: When it launches officially May 1, webvan.com
will sell most everything you'd find in your local supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: You mean there's something to like besides the
fact that they'll deliver to your doorstep, whenever you want? Cool
weekly menus that offer suggestions for dinner _ you can buy
prepared dishes or simply click on the recipe link and make it
yourself. You pay for your order online by providing your credit or
debit card information during checkout, so you don't have to worry
about paying when the delivery gets there _ and couriers are
instructed not to accept tips or gratuities. Delivery is free for
orders of $50 or more and only $4.95 for orders under $50. However,
from now through July 31, delivery is free for all orders.
</P>
<P>
   cooking.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Everything a cook could desire. Heavy on the
cookware and appliances. Big selection of specialty foods, too.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Easy to navigate. A real clear site. You can shop
by category _ bakeware, housewares, outdoor entertaining, for
instance. Or by brand _ All-Clad, T-Fal, KitchenAid.
</P>
<P>
   tavolo.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Specialty foods, cookbooks, kitchen and
tableware.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: The cooking tips. You just type in a word such as
artichoke, and you get advice on how to trim those beasts.
</P>
<P>
   GET HOME: Furnishings and accessories for your house
</P>
<P>
   living.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Home furnishings and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: One of the coolest things about this very smooth,
very thorough site, is the Stylefinder. Click on one of the
``rooms'' _ Classic, Urban, Mission, etc. A bigger photo comes up,
with a list on the right side, of everything in the room. When you
move your mouse to a word, say ``end table with drawer,'' a yellow
box on the photo moves over to indicate which is the end table.
Pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   goodhome.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: They've got lots of stuff, free shipping and free
swatches.
</P>
<P>
   netsetgoods.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Apparel, home design, watches, bags, music, tech
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Sometimes you should go to a site just because
it's cool. And this site has really neat, well-designed stuff _
that goes from the inexpensive to the obscene. Where else can you
get a soap dispenser that looks like one of those novelty birds
that bobs for water? From Germany? For $18? Or a Japanese Weather
Clock for $72 that gives you the time and weather. A hairbrush for
$23? Yes, but it's such a perfectly designed hairbrush.
</P>
<P>
   GET FIXED: Home improvement sites
</P>
<P>
   homewarehouse.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Hardware, tools, paints, housewares.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: If you can't find it here _ we can't help you. An
extensive selection for the home fixer-upper. Even if the extent of
your weekend activity is a home cookout, you can find a new
barbecue here.
</P>
<P>
   amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Tools and hardware, lawn and patio, and more.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: We're so used buying books and videos here, we
almost overlooked the fact that it sells drill presses, gaskets,
vacuum cleaners and painting supplies.
</P>
<P>
   sears.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Tools, parts, appliances, home services, lawn
and garden.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: You can buy the same products Sears offers at its
stores, without the hassle of going to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   GET IN THE YARD: Gardening info, tools and accessories
</P>
<P>
   garden.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Plants, seeds, tools, accessories and more.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Lots of information and a respectable selection of
stuff to stick in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   burpees.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Burpee's seeds and plants for vegetables,
flowers, herbs, accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: That we can select from the venerable seed
catalog's 59 varieties of tomatoes online!
</P>
<P>
   underwoodgardens.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Heirloom and rare seeds.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Grow a garden just like Grandma's with older
varieties of herbs, vegetables, flowers and fruits.
</P>
<P>
   GET MOVING: Sports gear for men, women, children
</P>
<P>
   gear.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Sporting goods and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Looking for a bargain? This site sells closeout
name brand gear at discount prices ... and shipping is 25 cents per
item.
</P>
<P>
   kidesport.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Sporting goods and apparel for children.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: This site was founded by parents who couldn't find
high-quality sports products for their kids. It offers kid-size
gear and apparel for everything from archery to X-country skiing,
with more sports promised. It also offers information on child
health issues and tips on coaching.
</P>
<P>
   lucy.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Women's sports apparel.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: It's a familiar story. Several women, frustrated
by lack of options in sportswear from traditional retailers, start
a specialty outlet online. But hey, it works. This has a nice
selection of styles, sizes and prices.
</P>
<P>
   mvp.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Men's, women's and children's sporting gear and
apparel.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Nothing much differentiates this site from other
sports sites except its investors _ John Elway, Wayne Gretsky and
Michael Jordan. Now, you can click close to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   thesportsauthority.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Sporting goods, apparel, footwear.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: This online extension of the Sports Authority
stores offers free shipping on purchases over $50, and you can
return merchandise you bought online to your nearest store.
</P>
<P>
   GET DRESSED: Clothes and accessories for men, women, children
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN: bluefly.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: What don't they? Top designer clothing for men,
women, teens and kids, plus house and gift items.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: First of all it's all up to 75 percent off. And
what do you get? A stylish Vera Wang party dress ($895). Men's
Gucci loafers for $139.99. A funky Mark Snider silk throw pillow
($49.95). An Ephemera candle ($26.95) and candleholder ($22.95). If
you like to shop by design(er), this is a great site.
</P>
<P>
   styletrek.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Clothing, accessories, jewelry, pet, apothecary,
home.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: The fact that you won't end up looking just like
your neighbors _ most of the goods on this site can't be found in
metro stores. What you find are fashionably funky threads from
designers Isadora Story and Mo Mo Falana; arty accessories by
designers including Amy Chan and Ipa-Nema; and body care products
by Kathleen Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   pieceunique.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: An online classified marketplace of recent and
vintage fashions from top designers.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: It's sort of an eBay for buyers and sellers of
such names as Armani, Chanel, Karan, Versace, Prada, Gucci, Hermes
and more. Recently, a Calvin Klein ``mint condition'' silk
sleeveless navy blue dress, size 6, that retailed for $895 was
going for $425.
</P>
<P>
   baonly.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: A personal shopping service for custom-designed
fashions from New York.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: You fill out a customer profile form and get a
personalized home page where baonly's shoppers will post pictures
and descriptions of items they think will interest you. Then you
call or e-mail for more info or to order.
</P>
<P>
   MEN: intmale.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Men's swimwear, apparel, shoes and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: The longtime International Male fashion catalog
has an impressive Web site. One cool thing is that when you go to
``tops,'' for instance, you get a choice of short sleeve, long
sleeve, sleeveless, tank, novelty and sweaters. You don't have to
plow through a zillion choices.
</P>
<P>
   etuxedo.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Discount tuxedos, shirts and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: This site is inexpensive and delivers fast. You'll
just need to take the suit somewhere for alterations. The site also
links to eSuits for discount suits, sport coats, slacks and
blazers.
</P>
<P>
   MEN AND WOMEN: jcrew.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Men's and women's clothes and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Once you select ``his'' or ``hers,'' you get an
extensive directory of clothing at a glance. And even after you've
clicked your way deep into the listings of skirts, for example, you
can return to this directory with a single click.
</P>
<P>
   brooksbrothers.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Men's and women's clothing and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: When in doubt, there's always Brooks Brothers _
and their Web site makes it real easy to buy their always timeless
clothes. Our favorite thing? When you click on any item for an
enlarged view, you still get links to options in that category
(blazers, shirts, shoes) on the left side of the page.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS AND TEENS:
</P>
<P>
   delias.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Teen girls' clothing and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: First, that the girl on the home page when we were
shopping looked like a real teenager _ not too skinny, not
unrealistically glam. The prices are low, the choices plentiful.
And, even the strictest parents may rest at ease: Most of the
clothes, even the flirty dresses, are appropriate for your little
girls.
</P>
<P>
   gapkids.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Clothes for boys and girls _ not as extensive a
selection as in the store, but you don't have to fight the traffic
at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: The sales pages, which are usually pretty full of
options, and you don't have to struggle through those jam-packed
sales racks at the stores.
</P>
<P>
   GET RICH: Or, at least, get some help managing your money
</P>
<P>
   doughnet.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Financial services and advice for teenagers (and
their parents).
</P>
<P>
   What we like: That it's a site for teenagers to learn to manage
their money. The site also links to online merchants and when it's
time to check out, doughnet.com takes over and reminds the shoppers
how much they have in their accounts, what the balance will be
after the transaction, and if they'd like to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Financial planning services.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Lots of advice. Invest in the market, refinance
your mortgage, check your bank statements online, compare insurance
rates, or plan for your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   GO LUXE: Jewelry and luxury sites
</P>
<P>
   miadora.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: High-quality jewelry for the high-maintenance
person with a budget to match. You can buy a simple 18K diamond
ring for $375, or upgrade to the 18K platinum diamond ring for
$1,625. Or how about an elegant Cartier diamond baignoire
wristwatch for $12,990? You know you deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ashford.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Watches and clocks; vintage watches; diamonds
and bridal; designer jewelry; writing accessories; leather goods
and handbags; ties and scarves; fragrances bath and body; and
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: This site advertises ``all the stuff you really,
really want,'' and if money's no object, you'll find it here. But
if you're on a budget you can still find some reasonably priced
items. For example, sorting by price, a Pierre Cardin man's
wristwatch at half price, just $40. At the other end of the scale,
there's an RGM Automatic Chronograph 105S men's wristwatch for
$26,000.
</P>
<P>
   luxuryfinder.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: With a name like that, what do you think?
</P>
<P>
   What we like: In fairness, let's point out that you can buy many
fine products here for $125 or less. But what fun is that? Let's
look at some of the big-ticket items: A signed first edition of
``Finnegans Wake'' by James Joyce, $10,500. An early 19th century
Regency Period cut glass chandelier, $96,315.
</P>
<P>
   GET PAMPERED: Beauty sites
</P>
<P>
   gloss.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Beauty products and advice, a virtual makeover,
magazine and gift center.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: This site is about to become the online outpost of
Estee Lauder, which bought the site a few weeks ago. Gloss.com will
still offer a variety of products including Bobbie Brown Essentials
and MAC. It also has a decent selection of products for men.
</P>
<P>
   GET OUT OF TOWN: Travel and travel accessories
</P>
<P>
   ebags.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Luggage, backpacks and other bags for all
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: You need a new gym bag, your spouse needs a
suitcase and your kid wants a knapsack for school. Here's one place
to get 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   expedia.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Travel plans _ from airfare to car rentals to
hotels
</P>
<P>
   What we like: It's really good one-stop shopping. Go to the
hotels page and you have links to travelscape.com, which offers
hotel room at up to 70 percent off standard room rates around the
world. The Vacation Wizard helps you choose from hundreds of
packaged trips based on your specific criteria, including
destination, price, and activities.
</P>
<P>
   air4less.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Discounted airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: No fuss, no muss. Whereas expedia.com is a
behemoth, all-purpose site, air4less.com makes it easy ``in just 3
clicks'' to reserve tickets.
</P>
<P>
   travelocity.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Travel plans _ from airfare to car rentals to
hotels to cruises.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Extensive listings, easy to use. Plus listings of
bargains and specials.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Travel arrangements, vehicles, home financing,
groceries, yard sale items.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Aside from those annoying William Shatner
commercials, this is a good sight for serious bargain hunters. You
specify what you want to buy or when you want to travel, and how
much you want to pay for it. The site looks for a match and replies
within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   HOT GIZMOS: Cool gadgets for you and your home
</P>
<P>
   homegameroom.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: New and refurbished game machines from this
Tampa, Fla., company.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: How about a Rock-Ola Bubbler juke box with a Betty
Boop theme (it plays CDs) for $6,795? A Twister II foosball game,
$695. A Pacman videogame machine, $995. An ``Elvira and the Party
Monsters'' pinball machine, $1,895. A Valley Coin-op electronic
dart game, $2,695. A Valley Black Cat pool table, $1,695. Your
house will become Guy HQ for the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   iGadget.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: High-tech gadgets of all kinds
</P>
<P>
   What we like: What's not to like about a site that identifies
itself as ``Where 007 does his shopping''? If you're looking for a
Viper Night Vision Goggle System, you can get one here for $399.99.
Or a Global Positioning System unit, pocket-sized, for $179.99. Or,
to be more practical, a Panasonic Linear Drive Electric Shaver for
$189.99.
</P>
<P>
   ART SMART: Where to buy cool pieces
</P>
<P>
   guild.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Art, jewelry, furnishings, gifts, books.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: An impressive variety of original art and gifts,
with a selection of new artists and paintings under $500.
</P>
<P>
   art.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Fine art and photography, prints and posters.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: This is the art site for the masses _ a little
less highbrow than guild.com. Heavy on the reproductions and
posters, which fill the home page.
</P>
<P>
   GIMME! GIMME!: Cool gifts for weddings, graduations, Mother's
and Father's days, whenever
</P>
<P>
   redenvelope.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Personal and corporate gifts.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Clean, lots of choices, upscale too. Buying is
easy because the categories are clear and useful.
</P>
<P>
   della.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: There are two sites _ a wedding gift registry
and gifts for other occasions.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: Very clear, very upscale, very creative. Lots of
cool options _ gifts you may never have thought of _ and some you
have. For weddings, everything from a Simon Pearce glass from
Gump's to a REI Trail Dome 2-person backpacking tent. For other
gifts, options from New York's Museum of Modern Art to Gump's to
Amazon. Teen gifts, for example, include Urban Decay Body Paints to
Go from Eve.com for $12, the Backstreet Boys' ``Millennium'' CD
from Amazon.com for $13.28, and a St. Johns Marathons 1919 baseball
cap by Blue Marlin for $29.99 from Fogdog.
</P>
<P>
   maryscorner.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: This site, named for CEO Mary Spear, promises
``exceptional goods for extraordinary living.''
</P>
<P>
   What we like: It's imaginative and fun to browse. Pamper
yourself with a hydrating body mist ($12), keep time on your hands
with a ring watch for $29.50, accessorize your activities (Miro
Tapestry Bag, $38); please your pooch with a doggy chew toy (Big
Mean Kitty or Cat Burglar, each $13.50); or satisfy your chocolate
cravings (Belgium Dark Chocolate Sauce, $16.95). For men, the
offerings aren't great _ so, guys, head for a sporting goods site.
</P>
<P>
   giftemporia.com
</P>
<P>
   What they sell: Gifts from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   What we like: The fact that metro Atlanta is represented. Forget
driving: buy a Lady Bug Light, $192, from City Art Works in
Atlanta; Gardenview table accessories, $40 - $55, from The
Chandlery in Roswell; a Dedham Strawberry Sorbet Rabbit figure for
$68 from Hospitality House in Atlanta; an elephant-shaped
footstool, $199, from Affairs for the Home in Duluth.
</P>
