<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2150 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-E-COMMERCE0502-COX     05-01 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major retailers going online
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to e-shopping strategies, there are
typically two ways a company can turn. Either build a Web site and
manage it in-house, or outsource all or part of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smaller dot-com start-ups or niche retailers are in that zone
where it's attractive to them to have it outsourced,'' said Steve
Simpson, a partner in the e-retailing group of Deloitte &AMP; Touche in
Atlanta. ``But some of the more mature retailers have built up
large IT capabilities and can handle it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Some metro Atlanta companies think it's better to source out
their e-commerce needs because it's less labor intensive and less
costly to keep up with technology if someone else is doing the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Home Depot, prefer handling their own
cyberstores.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Home Depot has decided to build its own e-commerce
site and the company plans to manage it. The Web site will have a
comprehensive inventory that closely matches the home improvement
retailer's stores. That's about 50,000 products, with potential for
up to 300,000 products, said spokesman Don Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that tallies up quite an undertaking to bring this
online,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The home improvement retailer plans to do a market by market
roll-out starting this summer. Though Home Depot has not revealed
which markets will come first, shoppers can expect to start surfing
Home Depot's site sometime in July. The retailer is using IXL
Enterprises Inc., an Internet strategy company, as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 7-month-old Figleaves.com wants to leave the Web site
development to the experts. The Atlanta-based intimate apparel
start-up, which began selling undergarments on its site last
December, is in discussions to outsource its e-commerce work to
Deloitte Consulting. Deloitte would build and host Figleaves.com's
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figleaves is in the `soft wear' business, not software,'' said
Ari Straus, the company's chief executive officer. ``The concept of
shared risk created the hot application service provider market.
Today, these solutions support the needs of young, growing
companies like Figleaves. Tomorrow, they'll actually support
businesses like Home Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers are finding that combining strategies is the way
to go. Such is the case with Wolf Camera.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Camera reached an agreement with Outpost.com in late March.
While Wolf Camera maintains control over its Web site in-house,
Outpost.com will handle any fulfillment and customer service needs
when shoppers click on the Wolfxpress.com site listed on
Outpost.com. Outpost.com also has a wider audience to help Wolf
Camera reach more of the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Camera spokesman Wayne Freedman said having their functions
in-house means employees understand the company's objectives and
missions.
</P>
<P>
   The linkup with Outpost.com puts orders in customers' hands
faster, Freedman said. That's an advantage, he added, to know
Outpost.com can fulfill orders until 9 p.m. and guarantee that
customers would have it on their desks by the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   The latest snapshot for what's to come for e-revenues points to
big growth online until 2004. U.S. consumers are expected to spend
$38.8 billion in online purchases in 2000, according to Forrester
Research of Cambridge, Mass. By 2004, that figure will be $184
billion, or 7 percent of all retail sales, the report says.
Forrester predicts that online shopping will hit a spending plateau
in 2004, until Generation Y creates the next surge in e-commerce
around 2010 _ when they hit their prime earning years. In the
meantime, the industry expects a major shakeout of less-successful
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, retailers and e-tailers are trying to reach
their customers any way they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control how people shop,'' said Evan Schwartz,
author of ``Webonomics'' and ``Digital Darwinism,'' two books on
e-commerce. ``They're going to shop in different channels provided
you offer the same products, the same prices and return policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have learned the hard way that consumers want to buy
what they want, when they want, where they want, and at the price
they want _ whether it's online, in-store, or by catalog, mail
order or phone.
</P>
<P>
   Does the ``customer is always right'' come to mind?
</P>
<P>
   But that message isn't getting through to some retailers.
Haverty's Furniture for instance, has a Web site, but it's a
browsing tool, not a cyberstore where you can place orders for that
new four-poster bed. John Slater, president and chief executive of
the furniture chain, said that 15 percent of all delivered
furniture is canceled or exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is one of the most wonderful tools to come along
for consumers and retailers _ it's right up there with
television,'' Slater said. ``But I don't believe that sales of
big-ticket items that are personal can be made over the Internet
without first sitting in that product.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich's, another Atlanta-based retailer, has a Web site, but does
not plan to expand it to sell apparel, shoes or furniture online.
But its sister chain, Macy's, does offer goods online at Macys.com.
Both chains are owned by Federated Department Stores.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers are taking a cautious approach to their
e-commerce strategies because the formula for profitability is
still being hammered out. And Wall Street is still waiting for
online giants, such as Amazon.com, to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional retailers have responded at least fairly
well,'' Schwartz said. ``But I still think a lot of them are
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
