<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0502-     05-01 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bringing home the bacon a brand new way
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They've done it. They have finally done it. They have
come up with a gimmick to lure men into grocery shopping. It's
called shopping for groceries using Priceline.com, a kind of
win-win lottery that turns buying diapers into a game.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com, familiar to many of us as the outfit that
auctions airplane seats and hotel rooms, has a new idea.
</P>
<P>
   Hooking up with Winn-Dixie and Bi-Lo here in metro Atlanta,
Priceline now has us bidding for baby carrots, live lobsters and
Folgers coffee.
</P>
<P>
   I can testify that just a little time and practice has me
trimming 25 percent and more off food and grocery items and having
a lot more fun than sitting on the floor clipping coupons.
</P>
<P>
   There are several online approaches to shopping _ some, like
Peapod and Webvan, aimed at meeting the needs of busy, working
households. The Priceline service, however, focusing on cost
saving, addresses the pocketbook issue that is precious to many
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process struck me at first as kind of clunky and slow,
even on my speedy computer, but with some practice _ and
considerable savings _ I warmed up. Saving money makes you patient,
and while it has limitations and is not the whole answer to grocery
shopping, the Priceline game clearly could gain fans among the
computer crowd _ especially those whose minds may not turn to
groceries until midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out in a ``guy'' way, I figured the smartest approach
to this grocery auction business was to go for the commodities, the
big-ticket items that are consumed heavily _ the detergents, paper
towels, toilet tissue and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad idea. I bid successfully for three 92-ounce boxes of
Tide at $3.55 each and three triple-roll packages of Brawny paper
towels at $1.57 each, which experienced shoppers will recognize as
a saving of nearly half.
</P>
<P>
   Getting bolder, I went for an immediate need, kitty litter, and
wrestled away three 14-pound containers of Tidy Cats Scoop Cat
Litter for $4.52 each, though they sold off the shelf for about
$6.50.
</P>
<P>
   On a roll, I have now gone for coffee, juices and bottled water.
I'm even eyeing those live lobsters. What fun!
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works.
</P>
<P>
   First you take out a membership, obtain a Priceline card and
submit a credit or debit card that is stored in the system's
memory, allowing you to pay online, in advance, for items as you
strike deals.
</P>
<P>
   Then you go to the main shopping page and begin compiling your
shopping list, cruising the cyber-aisles and making choices. When
you select an item, the bargaining begins with a pop-up screen that
offers three or more brands, all of the same size.
</P>
<P>
   It tells you the going shelf-price range of the items and
invites your bid, advising that you have a ``great chance'' to get
your choice with an offer of 85 percent of the list price. It's a
good chance at 66 percent, a fair chance at 50 percent and a poor
chance at 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing rejection, you tend to go high as a beginner, but later
you take chances and learn that if you are rejected at a low price,
you can always inch back upward.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement comes when you have compiled your list and
submitted the collective bids.
</P>
<P>
   A suspenseful minute passes as an on-screen display that looks
like a slot machine spins, alternating ``yes'' and ``sorry'' next
to each item, and then finally the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   You confirm your acceptance of the sales prices; your bank
account or charge card, as you prefer, is automatically debited,
then out prints your shopping list.
</P>
<P>
   You then go to the store, pick up your items from the shelf,
where you can see plainly how much you saved on each, and then you
check out, running your Priceline card through the slot. It
dutifully reports you have already paid.
</P>
<P>
   When you pick up your groceries, you begin to learn how and why
this is worthwhile for the retailers.
</P>
<P>
   First, I have never picked up the items without also picking up
other items that catch my eye. So luring me into the store results
automatically in additional sales, either from impulse or from me
remembering empty spots on the pantry shelf.
</P>
<P>
   The system is not for everybody. It is very slow and
time-consuming at times. Many favorite brands or product sizes are
not offered, even though they are in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that battle to limit yourself to the bargains,
and the fight not to give in to picking up additional impulse
items. But there is appeal, a novelty, that could catch on. But
what's the reasoning behind the grocery auction?
</P>
<P>
   Karen Brown, senior vice president of the Washington-based Food
Marketing Institute, gives a grocer's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about going after all the types of customers out there,''
she said. ``It's about searching for ways to help and enhance a
shopping experience, using all of the technologies and other
approaches at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While many consumers are drawn to the convenience of Peapod and
Webvan, services that deliver goods to the home at a price, others
are interested in bottom-line savings, as reflected in the ardent
pursuit of discount coupons in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The Priceline approach, which is being adopted in partnership
with supermarket chains all across the country, adds a bit of the
glitz and glamour of gamesmanship, tapping into an experience that
many online shoppers recognize from eBay and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose organization represents supermarkets and online
retail services, says the Priceline service is one of many
experiments in progress as the volume-sensitive grocery business
struggles to build traffic in stores and online.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing in retail as the average customer,''
Brown said, ``but we do what we can to pull together all of the
segments.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the cost of the bargains to the retailers?
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the cost is being borne now by wholesalers and
retailers in an effort to build the volume, though there are
obvious questions about how long the sizable discounts can last.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Blodgett, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, says he is
optimistic about Priceline's possibilities in near term but wonders
what will happen when the ``grand opening'' sale runs its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is what happens when the discounts narrow and the
consumers won't be getting such a great deal,'' Blodgett said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow that all seems far away. For now, let's go after those
live lobsters for next weekend!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
