<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An eBay trip offers lots of information for browsers
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Whether you do it online or at a real-world flea
market, there's nothing quite like the thrill of buying something
you want and not having to pay full price for it.
</P>
<P>
   There's a discount clothing chain that uses the slogan
``Everybody loves a bargain.'' At the moment, some of the hottest
sites on the Web are auction sites that let you bid on anything
from vintage china and dolls to airline tickets and toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Online auctions bring the thrills and chills of bidding on rare
and unique items to people who used to think auctions were all
about society matrons in mink and pearls bidding on impressionist
paintings in fancy New York auction houses.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone. You don't have to be a millionaire to go
online and bid on everything from vintage Wedgwood china to compact
discs. Bargains abound, and for novice collectors it can be
educational, too.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one example: Not too long ago, I went to a flea market
and bought a set of vintage china for what I was pretty sure was an
outstanding bargain.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine was more skeptical. ``You should get on eBay
and see what it's really worth,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   I went straight to eBay the first chance I had. I scrolled
through three pages of pictures and descriptions of my new china.
Judging by the auctioneers' prices and the current bids, I'm happy
to say I did get a pretty good deal.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear exactly when Web auctioneer eBay (www.ebay.com)
became the last word on flea market bargains. However, there is no
doubt that eBay was one of the founders of the ``name your price''
craze sweeping the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just this past week eBay showed Wall Street that
there's gold in all those pages of what may look like junk.
First-quarter operating results for the online auctioneer exceeded
expectations as the amount of merchandise sold on its site
surpassed $77 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of Fiestaware.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been to eBay in a while, this might be a good
time to take another look. The site has been completely redesigned
to make the virtual flea market experience much easier than it used
to be. Users can click on a tab called ``gallery'' in their
selected area and just view pictures and current bids on the items
they are interested in. You can find out what a certain collectible
is going for on the eBay market or just browse the selection of
goods available.
</P>
<P>
   This is much better than the old eBay, which was just a text
list. You took a chance that the item you clicked on would be
something you might want. This was time-consuming and, unless you
were a very serious collector, not that much fun.
</P>
<P>
   The new method lets you see the dishes, watches, oriental rugs
or whatever captures your fancy before you decide to find out more
about the item or even place a bid.
</P>
<P>
   While I was making sure my flea market china was truly a
bargain, I also learned a lot about my new china as I read the
descriptions the sellers posted with their items. Some of the
auctioneers were dealers who had shops in cities and towns across
the country and offered links to related sites, collectors' clubs
and other points of interest. If you want to begin a collection,
eBay can help you learn about various items and how much you can
expect to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Passing time on eBay doesn't have to be about shopping. It's a
great place to play your own at-home version of the hot PBS series
``Antiques Roadshow.'' Here's all you have to do: Find an item in
your house you think might be worth some money. Then head over to
eBay to see if there is a matching category for your collectible.
</P>
<P>
   You might be pleasantly surprised, as was my friend Alex after
browsing eBay's Beatles section. To her great surprise, she found
that a book about making the film ``A Hard Day's Night,'' which she
had bought in a dollar store, is fetching nearly $50 on eBay. Think
about that the next time you see a bin of remaindered books.
</P>
<P>
   So, whether you have a couple of million or just a couple of
hours, online auctions can teach you about fine art or oriental
rugs or just help you figure out how much that strange bowl in your
grandmother's living room is really worth.
</P>
<P>
   It's e-commerce with a kick.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
