<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Domain name isn't hard to get
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I'm interested in getting a domain name and business going on
the Internet. I've contacted a domain registrar, and they quoted a
price of $19.95 for a year. Is that in the ballpark? I'd like more
information about registering and hosting.
</P>
<P>
   _Ernie M. Margate, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Ernie isn't the only one with domain name questions.
There are lots of you. Right off the bat, let's define ``domain
name.'' Finding something on the Internet can be like trying to
find a contact lens or the back of an earring. A domain name was
invented to make it easier.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: A domain name corresponds to an address _ or string of
numbers like a Social Security number _ that identify and locate a
computer or server on the Web (Yahoo.com vs. 204.71.200.243). The
domain name is meant to be catchy and easy to remember so that
surfers can find Web sites and send e-mail to a familiar name
without having to commit numbers to memory or tattoo them on their
foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Why would someone want a domain name? Well, do you have a
Web page on the hard drive of your computer that you want to share
with the world? Like Ernie, do you want to start a business on the
Internet? Registering a domain name is the first step.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You want a name that springs to mind quickly, isn't hard to
spell. And, if you're starting a business, gives you some sort of
name branding. Pick an alternate or two because domain names gotta
be unique, so you gotta be creative.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Got five minutes? Let's register. Check the availability
of your preferred domain name with InterNIC (www.internic.net/).
Domain registrars have sprung up all over. InterNIC has a great
list. Heck, we also did a yahoo.com search on ``domain
registrars.'' Take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Prices to register are all over the map. $12 a year. $34 a
year. $60 for two years. Do research. Some will just register the
name. Others wrap registration, monthly hosting and e-mail
account(s) into a Web hosting package. Look to your own ISP for
registration and hosting options.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You may end up tacking on charges depending on the size
and type of site. If you'll be running a business like Ernie, you
may want e-commerce features. E-commerce packages allow people
visiting your Web store to make purchases. Visitors can fill up a
shopping cart with merchandise and check out with a credit card.
Sites like Amazon.com, Sundance.com, etc., allow online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Know what? You don't even need to be a Web developer to
create a Web store. Hosts can make it as easy as a few clicks. They
walk you through registering, setting up and designing your site,
and making it ``e-commerceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
