<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-Q&AMP;A0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _Q: I wonder whether you
<TEXT>
could get some information about how to contact the agency that
keeps the official time for our nation?
<P>
   _ J. S.
</P>
<P>
   A: To hear the U.S. Naval Observatory master clock ticking, call
(202) 762-1401 or visit tycho.usno.navy.mil/what.html. The Web site
receives ``hundreds of thousands of hits a day.'' Write USNO, Time
Service Division, 3450 Massachusetts Ave. N.W., Washington, D.C.
20392
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have about 35 unused earphones, the kind you use with small
portable radios, etc. I hate to throw them away. Anyone who would
like to have them can.
</P>
<P>
   _ D. B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Good day to read the paper. If you can use these freebies,
e-mail Montoro728(at)aol.com. Enjoy!
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw somewhere a wedding-planning Web site that served as a
gift registry. That's pretty common, except that this one lets
guests go there and contribute toward the honeymoon as a gift. Can
you find this?
</P>
<P>
   _ T. K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Honeymoon bucks from Spirit of the West Travel (218-8742,
800-405-3606, Ext. 74 or www.weddingwire.com) or from After I Do
(www.afterido.com or 800-956-4436). Older couples find such
services a palatable way to ask for money for the big trip. Gifts
may be made in any amount, and the card announcing the guest's
generosity is sent to the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a cat that just started some bad out-of-litter-box
behavior. Do you know a cat behaviorist? Also, what is the most
effective product for eliminating cat urine odor?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Diana Smith of Heart and Paws reports cats are sensitive to
any changes in their environment (new family members, company,
litter brand or reupholstered furniture). Such changes may lead to
bad litter box behavior. Keep the litter as clean as possible and
confine the feline to a small area, like a laundry room. The cat
will have no choice but to go in the box. Pick up a pint of
Nature's Miracle or spritz a solution of 2 tablespoons vinegar to
one cup water to eliminate the cat urine odor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several other non-Texans and I have noticed ``members of the
house party'' in some wedding announcements. We have never heard of
this custom. Could you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Suzanne H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Welcome to the Lone Star State. The house party is an
invention peculiar to the Deep South. Traditionally, the ladies
(relatives, close friends) who assist the bride with various tasks
_ serving cake, manning the guest book, etc. _ were thanked by
being dubbed members of the house party, reports RSVP Parties and
Particulars' Missy Harris. Now caterers and other vendors have
taken over these duties. So the house party has become a collection
of bridesmaid-also-rans who are honored by being escorted into the
church just before the couple's grandparents and parents. They may
or may not stay at the bride's home. Just like the groom's cake,
the house party is a wonderful Southern addition to any wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have more than 100 empty inkjet cartridges and don't want
to throw them away. I've heard that there might be places that will
pay some money for them so they can be remanufactured. Any way you
can help me out? Recycling is cool.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.B. A: Albaat Ink Jet buys empty cartridges (with a print
head) for about $2 each and fills them. Mail the cartridges
courtesy of Albaat by downloading the mailing kit at
www.albaat.com. A bulk rate for offices and companies is available.
Q: Armadillo shells are very fragile, as I found out when I was
cleaning one. What's the proper method for long-term preservation
for display?
</P>
<P>
   _Z.N.
</P>
<P>
   A: Armadillo shells left out in the wild (sun, rain, heat and
humidity) are more fragile than ``fresh'' ones. Dan Lansford of
Professional Taxidermist advises that you start with a fresh shell
with little or no tissue for best results. Rub the interior with 20
Mule Team Borax, which dries the shell and acts as an insecticide.
Follow with a coating of boiled linseed oil on the outside of the
shell as a dressing. Wipe off excess. The shell should last
``longer than you will,'' just like an antler or bone, adds
Lansford. Store the 'dillo out of direct sunlight in moderate
temperatures (e.g. inside on the dining room table). Q: What really
happens if a tax return is postmarked a day late?
</P>
<P>
   _Tim T.
</P>
<P>
   A: You really could be charged a late fee. Postmarks are checked
and noted. The envelope is stapled to the return as proof of the
tardiness in case ``the IRS may assess a late fee,'' says spokesman
Kenneth Vargas. The late filing penalty is 5 percent a month (with
a maximum 25 percent plus interest) of the outstanding balance.
Refund due? No problem, five percent of $0 is $0. Vargas notes 70
percent of filers receive refunds. Remember, after three years, you
lose the right to claim any refund.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We received a wedding invitation that is addressed to my
husband and myself. It does not mention children or family. Is it
appropriate to take them anyway?
</P>
<P>
   _J.O.
</P>
<P>
   A: No. If the children were invited, their names would have been
on the carrier envelope or inside envelope of the invitation.
Traditionally, children older than 13 receive separate invitations.
Get a sitter and enjoy!
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter's best friend has been accepted to MIT. Needless
to say, I am impressed, since I could barely get my senior to get
her college applications in on time. I wanted to give her friend a
slide rule. I called several places, but they did not know what a
slide rule was.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa D.
</P>
<P>
   A: The slide rule was the product of many mathematical minds.
Edmund Gunter is credited with drawing a line on which numbers were
proportional to their logs, and William Oughtred combined two of
Gunter's lines, sliding them relative to each other. Voila! The
slide rule.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the advent of the calculator, slide rules have lately
disappeared from university bookstores. Neither the University
Co-Op nor the MIT bookstore stocks them. I have found a source for
you _ the Slide Rule Emporium. Prices range from $34.50 for the
basic Pickett Pocket Log/Log Rule to $395 for the Pickett 4 Foot
Power Log Exponential. Call (480) 661-8277 or visit
hometown.aol.com/sciant/index.html to order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Over the last four years, I have been restoring and
customizing a 1975 Corvette. While shopping for parts, I came
across a pair of custom headlights that are supposed to have come
from Farrah Fawcett's Corvette. I would like to send her a picture
of my car, finished with her headlights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Armand G.
</P>
<P>
   A: I am sure she would love to review her old headlights. The
National Corvette Museum in Bowling Green, Ky., was not able to
confirm that the Charlie's Angels star owned the automotive icon
(by the way, the museum is available for special events and
weddings). But write to Fawcett in care of Nigro Karlin &AMP; Segal,
10100 Santa Monica Blvd., Suite 1300, Los Angeles, Calif. 90067
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a question concerning the Lorenzo de Zavala flag.
Which way does the star point, and how is the lettering arranged
around the star?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: This flag has a white star against a blue field with one
point straight up. The letters T-E-X-A-S are between each star
point. The T is immediately to the right of the upward point.
Lorenzo de Zavala, ``a Texan by adoption and by choice,'' designed
this first official Lone Star National Flag of the Republic of
Texas, according to Mamie Wynne Cox's ``The Romantic Flags of
Texas. UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   Want to view the nominated short-subjects and animation films
from the 72nd Academy Awards? ``The Road To the Oscars'' is a mere
$19.95 and is available at www.atomfilms.com or by calling
AtomFilms at (206) 264-2735. Enjoy!
</P>
<P>
   Thrifty? Frugal? Cheap even? Cut paper napkins in half? Wash and
reuse Q-Tips? Use cereal box linings instead of wax paper? Scavenge
for twine on the Hike and Bike? Shave your legs with hair
conditioner? Cover leftovers with free hotel shower caps? Send me
tales from the thrift (yours or someone else's) for an upcoming
Greig Files on people and frugality.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due
to the number of inquiries, Jane can't respond to every request.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
