<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV-Turnoff Week didn't work for meBy Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I thought about participating in National
TV-Turnoff Week last week. Really, I did.
</P>
<P>
   But then I realized I would have to miss the season finale of
``Once &AMP; Again.'' How could I deprive myself of the dramatic
conclusion to Rick and Lily's first season of romance?
</P>
<P>
   Then I thought, OK, I'll cheat a little. I'll join the boycott a
day late. But then I realized I would have to miss new episodes of
``NYPD Blue,'' ``The West Wing,'' ``Law &AMP; Order'' and ``ER.'' I
would have been miserable on a personal level and irresponsible on
a professional level. How can a TV critic assess the TV season
without full knowledge of the final few episodes of the best drama
series?
</P>
<P>
   That's my excuse, and I'm sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   I also would have missed: filmmaker Paul Stekler's ``George
Wallace: Settin' the Woods on Fire''; the first part of ABC's
entertaining ``Arabian Nights''; and countless must-see news
programs, especially Ted Koppel's interview with Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   To tell the truth, I only considered TV-Turnoff Week (Apr.
24-30) for a nanosecond. This annual bashing of the tube, now in
its sixth year, has always struck me as ridiculous. Why should we
turn our backs on a fountain of knowledge and entertainment sitting
right there in our homes?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of turning off the TV, we should dedicate ourselves to
watching only the good stuff. And that means not using the TV for
baby-sitting, background noise or vegetating. Don't turn on the TV
like a light when you walk into the room, and don't sit through a
terrible show just to get to the one you like. Use the TV listings.
Choose thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of TV-Turnoff Week is noble _ except for the turning
off part. Sponsored by the Washington-based watchdog group TV-Free
America, cold turkey week is supposed to ``encourage children and
adults to watch less television in order to promote healthier lives
and communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine and dandy. Only an idiot would disagree with that mission.
But does turning off the TV for a week really accomplish that goal?
Watching less is automatic when you're selective. Watching smarter
is altogether different from not watching.
</P>
<P>
   Every year TV-Turnoff Week sends out enough press releases and
faxes to be endorsed by politicians, educators, doctors and scouts.
But the Nielsen folks say the impact on ratings is little to none.
A noble yet futile gesture.
</P>
<P>
   During TV-Turnoff Week we are told to read a book, take a walk,
play a board game, bake cookies instead of staring at the tube.
Know what? If you don't plop down the minute you get home from work
or school and watch non-stop until bedtime, there's plenty of time
for those things along with an hour for your favorite program.
</P>
<P>
   I love the wildly simplistic tips TV-Free America comes up with
for dealing with life after TV-free rehab:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Move your TV set to a less prominent location in your
home.'' When was the last time you tried to pry your 150-pound TV
set out of the massive home entertainment center wedged in your
den? And don't forget inhaling a pound of dust while unhooking the
cable and VCR. Absolutely not. The TV stays right where it is. If
it helps you watch less, throw a towel on it.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hide the remote control.'' We have two, and they're usually
lost anyway. The one without the dead batteries is probably lurking
beneath the sofa cushions, along with puffs of dog hair and
year-old jelly beans.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Remove TV sets from children's bedrooms.'' Parents who care
about what their young children are watching shouldn't put TV sets
in kids' rooms to begin with, so this one's a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Keep the set off during dinner.'' Well, duh. Dinner is for
eating and talking. Everybody knows that. (Unless there's a new
episode of ``The Simpsons'' on Sundays, then normal decorum is out
the window.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Limit children's viewing.'' Well, double-duh. And ``limit''
should include time of viewing and programs watched. This one is
basic. And obvious, even to rotting couch potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Television has always been the scapegoat for what's wrong with
America. Gunfire breaks out in the National Zoo, and it's TV's
fault. Kids are fat? TV, not high-calorie foods or lack of
exercise, is the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   We have a love-hate relationship with The Box, and sometimes the
love is secret. Almost every day, someone at work or in ``the real
world'' goes out of their way to tell me they never watch TV.
Usually they add, with noses tipped skyward, ``I only watch a
little PBS and news.'' But then in casual conversation, many of
those anti-TV snobs let slip from their pursed lips evidence to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that guy on 'Millionaire' was pathetic last night, wasn't
he?'' Or, ``Did you see this year's dance number on 'Drew Carey?'
What a hoot!''
</P>
<P>
   Like dessert, television itself isn't bad for us. It's how much
and what we choose that determine our health.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
