<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Open the frozen food door, Hal
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ My social isolation is about to become
complete.
</P>
<P>
   I no longer spend much time at the gas station standing in line
behind the lottery players and listening to the guys around the
coffee pot. I pay at the pump, pump my own and am out in two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I don't go to the post office very often. Almost all my
correspondence is in the form of e-mail and some of my bills are
now automatically deducted from my bank account.
</P>
<P>
   I don't go inside my bank's office anymore. My paycheck is
automatically deposited and I don't believe I've ever seen the
bank's lobby unlocked. For all I know, it never opens. It might
just be there for show. Instead, my financial dealings occur
exclusively through bank machines or on financial auto-pilot.
Tellers are dim childhood memories along with barred teller windows
on marble counter tops.
</P>
<P>
   Government offices? Haven't seen one in years except when I'm
working on a story. I renew my auto tag by mail and get a postcard
</P>
<P>
   from the county that tells me my homestead exemption has been
renewed. I receive tax forms on the Internet and update my address
</P>
<P>
   on Web sites. I sigh over my checkbook and pay manifestly unjust
traffic tickets by mail.
</P>
<P>
   I seldom see movies in theaters. I wait for the tape.
</P>
<P>
   I can even do much of my work on a home computer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm to the point where there's hardly a reason to get dressed
and leave the house in the morning. Except for one thing. The
grocery store. It's the last remaining place where I bump into
people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even the grocery store may recede from my life.
</P>
<P>
   Publix Super Markets Inc. last week said it plans to launch a
system for Internet grocery shopping in Florida and Georgia. Not
this minute, but sometime around 2001. (Open the frozen-food door,
Hal.)
</P>
<P>
   You'd click around on the cereal, milk and cat-food icons, click
the plastic or paper bag symbols, hit return, and the bag will be
delivered to your door or waiting for you at a store. This would
shave hours off a week of running errands.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it seems wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   No more falling into a supermarket-aisle trance and forgetting
what you need to buy.
</P>
<P>
   No more cursing people who can't maneuver their supersized SUVs
in supermarket parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   No more frustration because the supermarket systematically moves
every last can on every shelf just to confuse and annoy you.
</P>
<P>
   No more arguing with children who want to buy colorfully
packaged things they will never really eat.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, it would give you the ability to tell kids,
``If you don't let me on the computer right now, nobody will eat
tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   I do not consider shopping to be recreation. This is progress.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch. There's always a catch.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery store ranks up there with libraries, churches, $2.99
breakfast places and hardware stores on Saturdays for running into
</P>
<P>
   people at random.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers, neighbors, the schoolmate of the kids who has taken
to wearing three earrings per ear but whom I still remember as the
</P>
<P>
   cute kid in the preschool photographs, the guy who always shouts
``hustle!'' at softball games, the pretty woman who used to live a
few apartments over, folks I only half remember from somewhere,
maybe high school ... the Internet would make them all disappear
from my life.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there's the problem of starving to death should my
phone line go dead. After years of shopping on-line, I surely will
have lost
</P>
<P>
   the ability to count change, find out where milk bottles are or
know for sure whether I want plastic bags or paper. (Both have
definite
</P>
<P>
   advantages, you know.)
</P>
<P>
   I'd be thrown into confusion.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from safety considerations, I know I'm just not social
enough to go out and track people down. That's why I value chance
</P>
<P>
   encounters.
</P>
<P>
   But I frequent fewer places these days because it's faster to
get things done on-line or by mail. Don't get around much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Publix's ambitious plans for the Internet haven't been launched
yet, but already I'm feeling my world shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
