r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0502-CO     05-01 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mushroom madness
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's that time of year when a man's fancy
turns to _ morels. At least that's the way it goes here in our
village.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the other thing they're supposed to be hankering for in
the spring doesn't matter. It does, but for a couple of weeks at
least, it comes limping in a poor second because the only thing on
these men's minds right now is MUSHROOMS.
</P>
<P>
   It's a morel frenzy with all the intrigue of an Agatha Christie
weekend in the country. Grown men, some of them grandfathers and
even a sprinkle of great-grandfathers, are skulking through the
woods. No matter where you go, there's only one topic of
conversation. ``How many did you find?'' and ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   Then it gets down and dirty _ like this morning at the cafe. By
the time I got there, six of my retired farmer coffee-drinking
buddies were already huddled in the corner, speaking in hushed
voices. ``What's up?'' I asked looking stupid enough to convince
them I really didn't know what was going on _ because I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Cal wrinkled into a huge chuckle. ``He's lyin' again,'' he said
pointing a gnarled finger at Amos, his best friend since one-room
schoolhouse days. They fought WW2 together, stood up at each
other's weddings, and farmed adjoining land for over 60 years, but
that cuts no ice right now _ not during MUSHROOM season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clown's trying to tell me he found a whole sack of morels
out behind his barn this morning,'' Cal explains, ``and I know he's
lying because that's the first place I looked and there weren't
any.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What were you doing looking behind my barn?'' Amos wants to
know. ``You stay ta' home and look behind your own barn or I'm
going to oil up the shotgun for you.''
</P>
<P>
   About that time Benny walks in with a baggie, a big grin, and an
announcement. ``Look'a here!'' he says holding up a skinny bag with
six pitted pale things in it. ``Found 'em this morning.
MUSH-A-ROONS! Whoppers.'' He passed his treasure around for all to
admire. Puffed up bigger than his morels, Benny offers to buy
coffee. The guys pass the stash from hand to hand with appropriate
comments. They could have been admiring a first grandchild from
what I heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' Amos says innocently enough followed by an
uncharacteristic congenial slap on Benny's shoulder, ``ya' find
these in your woods?'' Benny gives him a sideways look that asks,
How stupid do you think I am? and pushes Amos's hand away. ``You're
not sweet-talking me into leading you to my spot.'' Amos denies any
such motives and goes back to his coffee. Conversation picks up
where it left off _ biggest liar wins.
</P>
<P>
   Location is the major topic. Someone says around the apple trees
out at White Star park. Another says he heard somebody found a
``mess of 'em'' out behind Jim Batcher's place. Rose, the waitress,
leans over and tells us her sister says the place to look is in the
woods behind the old Lutheran cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   I plunk my buck on the table for coffee and tip and stand up to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell our secrets,'' Cal urges. I tell him they haven't
got any and nobody cares about a bunch of fungus anyway. They stare
like maybe I'd just spoken in Swahili. ``She ain't from around
here,'' Amos explains.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later I'm walking into the grocery store right
behind Brady Petersen. ``Hey, Brady! How many did you get?'' the
cashier asks. Brady shakes his head and says it's too early but
he'll be going back in the morning. He turns to me and explains.
``MUSHROOMS.''
</P>
<P>
   I cross the street to the bakery, order up a loaf of rye, and
Donna behind the counter asks if I've found any yet. MUSHROOMS. I
shake my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on out for chicken on the grill,'' Steve invites from his
car phone. When I get there he's waiting triumphantly in the middle
of his drive holding up a four-inch morel and almost dancing a jig
of delight. ``MUSHROOM!'' he bubbles. ``I found it right out here
under the trees,'' then trails off into a detailed narration of its
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he fries it up in butter and shares it with his wife and
me. Lots of lip smacking.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you folks, it's absolute morel madness _ right here
my own village.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
