<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL ABUSE IS ALLEGED AT BOSTON SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The US Department of Education is investigating
allegations that Cape Verdean children were subjected to racist and
abusive treatment by a teacher at James Condon Elementary School in
South Boston, and that school officials tried to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   The probe focuses on charges that a veteran fifth-grade teacher
physically abused the pupils and called them derogatory names, a
source familiar with the investigation said. Former pupils said
that they were hit, slapped, and pinched, and that their ears were
pulled. They also said they were called names such as ``burro,''
``monkey,'' and ``nappy-haired.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Maria Mullaly, is also accused of seating pupils by
skin color, with lighter-skinned children at the front of the class
and darker-skinned children at the back, according to several
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Mullaly, 66, has taught at the Condon school since 1975 and
apparently was never disciplined for her alleged actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classroom was run with threats and intimidation and
physical abuse of the students,'' said the source familiar with the
investigation. ``Students of color were singled out for abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are pursuing allegations that school
officials covered up the alleged abuse by telling children to lie
and parents to stay silent when the state Department of Social
Services inquired about Mullaly's classroom behavior two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The DSS investigation uncovered no evidence of wrongdoing,
according to documents obtained by the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   But federal investigators have evidence of a pattern of abuse
repeated for many years, sources said. Some Cape Verdean students
who sat in Mullaly's classroom decades ago said they still remember
being traumatized by her.
</P>
<P>
   Mullaly, like many of her students, is Cape Verdean. She is
light-skinned and spoke disparagingly about dark-skinned people,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullaly, on leave from the school after a car accident last
year, could not be reached for comment. Daniel Walsh, who was
principal at the Condon school when much of the abuse allegedly
occurred, also did not return phone calls from the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged abuse came to light after complaints by Viana
Mendes, 33, a teacher at the school during the 1997-1998 school
year who also is Cape Verdean. Mendes told investigators that she
witnessed many incidents of physical and verbal abuse directed at
the darker-skinned pupils.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, conducted by the federal Office of Civil
Rights, has been underway for 11 months, spokesman Rodger Murphy
confirmed. Investigators have interviewed more than 25 pupils,
former students, parents, and school officials, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy declined to speculate on the outcome of the inquiry. But
sources said investigators will meet with school officials next
month to present the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues they must resolve are allegations that school
officials permitted racial discrimination, violated school policies
that forbid corporal punishment, misled government investigators,
and violated the civil rights of several pupils.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Lynch, a spokeswoman for the Boston School Department,
said city officials learned Wednesday that the Office of Civil
Rights has reached some conclusions about the case, but they have
not been told what they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say anything until we know more,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with the Globe, Mullaly's former students told
tales of mistreatment at her hands and said they still bear scars.
</P>
<P>
   Valdir Pires, 13, said he remembers standing at the blackboard
in Mullaly's class two years ago, struggling to figure out a math
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Pires, a special-needs student whose family comes from Cape
Verde, said Mullaly yelled ``Burro!'' and hit him twice on the side
of the head. Humiliated, Pires said he turned red and went back to
his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so embarrassed,'' he said last week, looking down at the
floor of his apartment with his head in his hands. ``Everyone was
looking at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes said she witnessed that incident and reported it to
investigators. Pires said Mullaly later told him to deny it
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Pires and several other students also said they were subjected
to Mullaly's seating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was like the A team and the B team,'' said Ana do
Souto, 27, a fifth-grader in Mullaly's classroom in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the darker-skinned pupils always got the worst treatment
from Mullaly, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria, who asked that her last name not be used, was one of
Mullaly's pupils in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   She dreamed of becoming a flight attendant, but Mullaly told her
she didn't have the right sort of European look, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said I was too black, too big-lipped, and nappy-haired,''
Maria recalled. ``And she made fun of my clothes. She'd say, `Don't
wear that again, you look raggedy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mullaly constantly encouraged the lighter-skinned children, she
said. ``She'd hug 'em, give 'em compliments. To us darker ones, the
best she'd say is, `Can't you do better?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maria said her self-esteem took a nose dive. Today, she's a
happily married homemaker with four children, living in Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I grew up, I felt like I couldn't do things,'' she said.
``Being a stewardess was the main thing I always wanted to do, but
I kind of erased it out of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Fernandes, 29, described himself as the darkest boy in
Mullaly's class in 1982, when South Boston still simmered with
tension over court-ordered busing. In contrast, he said, the
atmosphere inside Mullaly's classroom didn't seem so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what bothered me was (Mullaly's) favoritism toward
whites,'' he said. ``If everybody was disciplined the same way, I
wouldn't have minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Do Souto, a statuesque Cape Verdean who owns a hair salon in
Boston, said she will never forget Mullaly, then Maria Gomes.
</P>
<P>
   Newly arrived from her homeland in 1985, do Souto desperately
wanted to fit in at her new school. She said she was mortified when
Mullaly hit her on the head, pulled her ears, and called her names
like ``bruta,'' ``stupida,'' and ``dummy,'' and said she'd be
pregnant before she was 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected that from a teacher, who is supposed to set
an example,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Mullaly threatened her with an ``F'' in behavior if she told
anyone about the treatment, do Souto said.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes visited Mullaly's classroom regularly to pick up pupils
for tutoring, and, as a young teacher, was also assigned to observe
the class. She said she was appalled by what she saw.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was ostracized at the school after telling
superiors she had observed Mullaly mistreating pupils. Her teaching
contract was not renewed for the 1998-1999 school year.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believes school officials permitted the abuse
because some of the pupils were immigrants who had recently arrived
and who had difficulty fitting into their new surroundings or had
behavior problems. Mullaly, a bilingual teacher, could keep them
under control.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes said she did not report the abuse for several months
because she considered Mullaly a friend. Mendes also said that in
Cape Verde, physical punishment of students is more accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was horrible what was happening to the kids,'' she
said. ``They were being damaged psychologically. I reached a point
where I couldn't walk away any more.''
</P>
<P>
   A DSS investigation in the spring of 1998, triggered after
Mendes filed a 51A, or report of suspected abuse, failed to support
her charges, according to documents obtained by the Globe. DSS
spokesman David Van Dam would not comment on the matter, saying it
was confidential.
</P>
<P>
   After the DSS probe ended, Mendes contacted various officials,
including teachers' union representative Carol Pacheco and the
offices of Superintendent Thomas W. Payzant and Mayor Thomas M.
Menino.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendes said the complaints were not taken seriously, so she
appealed to the civil rights office. The federal investigators
began their probe last May.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mendes worked as a substitute teacher in Boston and
has since moved on to another school district in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Mendes says she feels bad about going to the authorities
about Mullaly. But she said what she witnessed in Mullaly's
classroom was unlike anything she had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was shaming the kids, hitting them, and humiliating
them,'' Mendes said. ``Every time I left the classroom, I'd feel
bad for the kids and guilty that I wasn't doing anything about it.
I reached a point when I knew the truth had to come out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
