<HEADER>
A2174 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-TEETH0502-COX     05-01 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-TEETH0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby teeth _Who needs 'em? You do!
 &HT;    By Jan Roadarmel Ledford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Knock-knock! Who's there?
</P>
<P>
   Dishes. Dishes who?
</P>
<P>
   Dishes the Tooth Fairy. Lost any teeth lately?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Starting at about age 6, your teeth are doomed to
fall out.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry. You won't have to eat oatmeal the rest of your
life. Most mammals (warmblooded animals with hair, like humans)
have two sets of teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The first set, called the primary, or baby, teeth, comes in the
early years. The second set, or permanent teeth, erupts later. Even
your dog and cat have primary and permanent teeth.
</P>
<P>
   In humans, the tooth buds for the baby teeth are in the gums
when a person is born. These teeth start pushing through the gums
when the baby is 6 to 8 months old. By age 2, all the primary teeth
usually are present. Underneath the primary teeth, hidden in the
gums, are the buds that will grow into the permanent teeth.
</P>
<P>
   As a permanent tooth develops near the surface, it causes the
root of the baby tooth to shrink. Once the root is gone, the baby
tooth falls out. Baby teeth usually start falling out at about age
6. This continues until all the baby teeth are gone at about age
12. There are 20 baby teeth and 32 permanent teeth. So in your
whole life, you'll have 52 teeth. (That's unlike a shark, which can
grow thousands of replacement teeth during its life.)
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S A TOOTH MADE OF?
</P>
<P>
   A tooth has two parts. The part you see is the crown. It is
covered with enamel, the hardest substance in the human body. The
part below the gum is the root. It is covered with cementum
(pronounced see MEN tum). In the center of the tooth is the pulp,
which contains blood vessels and nerves. Under the enamel is the
dentin. The dentin is what makes up most of the tooth. It is harder
than bone but softer than enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Even though enamel is hard, it can be damaged. Cavities are
caused by bacteria in your mouth. The bacteria coat your teeth if
you don't brush or floss them. Bacteria, which get a free meal
every time you eat or drink, especially love sweet stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The gross news is that the waste products of bacteria are
chemicals that eat your enamel, causing cavities. Cavities can
destroy a tooth. So if your baby teeth are going to fall out
anyway, who cares if they get cavities? YOU should!
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the baby teeth hold a space for the permanent
teeth. If too many baby teeth are lost early, the permanent teeth
might not have a good place to come in. Also, the jaw may not grow
right.
</P>
<P>
   And the decay from a baby tooth can damage the permanent tooth
below.
</P>
<P>
   You can see how important it is to take care of your baby teeth.
You also must pamper your permanent teeth. If one rots away, you
don't get another!
</P>
<P>
   Proper dental care includes brushing twice a day, flossing
daily, seeing your dentist regularly and eating a healthy diet
without lots of sweets.
</P>
<P>
   Also be sure not to smoke, dip or chew tobacco. Keep those
pearly whites clean!
</P>
<P>
   ENTER THE TOOTH FAIRY!
</P>
<P>
   Having a baby tooth fall out isn't such a bad deal. Not only is
a permanent tooth waiting under your gums to take its place, you
also may get a visit from the Tooth Fairy!
</P>
<P>
   The going rate for a tooth is about $1. Ever wonder where the
Tooth Fairy gets the money? One theory is that she has helper
fairies who find money that people lose.
</P>
<P>
   So if you ever see a quarter under the picnic table, maybe you
should leave it there for all the tooth-losing children in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   We want to know about your Tooth Fairy traditions. Do you leave
your tooth under the pillow? Are the front teeth worth more than
the back? Write us at nfk(at)ajc.com with all your Tooth Fairy
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
