   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, May 2,
2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the
current week. This layout is available Tuesday after 2 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0502 -- Netscape 6 is not fun. It's big, busy,
flashy and can be just plain annoying. Netscape took two years to
dream up this mishmash of features, pull-down menus, wacky toolbars
and icons. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a
4-column color photo of a screenshot of Netscape's new browser.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GADGETS -- Rand McNally, the map people, have developed a
mapping and global positioning system (GPS) device designed to work
with the Palm III and Palm V organizers. (Cummings, Dayton Daily
News) Art includes a 1-column color photo of product in use.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSCENE -- When it comes to reading information in
other languages, most of us are at a loss. There is help for you on
the Web. If you're an experienced user, you probably know that
there are free online translation services available. (Husted,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GAME CORNER -- The new ``Star Trek'' game adventure is
like an episodic TV-caliber adventure _ not a virtual extravaganza
on par with the blockbuster movies.(Staff, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes a 1-column color photo of video
game box.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY -- The delete key remains one of your best
defenses against junk e-mail. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column color sig of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ When it comes to e-shopping strategies, there are
typically two ways a company can turn. Either build a Web site and
manage it in-house, or outsource all or part of the work. (DeGross,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   VINTAGE-BOOKS-ONLINE _ ATLANTA _ There's a mid-17th century
Bible for sale and copies of every Life magazine issue ever
printed. Recently, an urgent request came in for ``any and all
pre-1960 poultry books.'' Something interesting's always happening
at Atlanta Vintage Books, though the most intriguing development of
late doesn't involve what's on the shelves: Some of the store's
best, most loyal customers have never set foot in the place.
They're cybershoppers. And contrary to conventional wisdom, they
may be helping rather than hurting independent stores savvy enough
to see venturing onto the Web as one more way of keeping their
doors open. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ME-STORE _ ``It would be the perfect store. The ``Me Store.''
Always open, always stocked with exactly what I wanted, never about
another human being's needs except mine. All mine!'' For those who
prefer to shop from home, this reporter has compiled a list of web
sites she hoped to meet her every need. Some deliver, some don't.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GOING-CYBER _ ATLANTA _ ``Going Cyber!'' The handwriting is a
bit crooked and hard to make out from a distance, and yet the sign
on the front door of ``The Family Jewels'' in downtown Decatur, Ga.
speaks volumes. Next week, the 13-year-old antiques and
collectibles store will become an online-only operation, joining a
host of other businesses for whom the Internet is the greatest
thing to come along since customers with unlimited lines of credit.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ESHOP-SAFETY _Before you start your e-shopping adventures, here
are some key points to keep in mind. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WEB-LIST _ Shopping sites for you, your garden, and your home.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GEAR _ The latest in digital game gear. This week: Nyko's
Viper PSX. (Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LINK _ Your link to some of the best and most interesting
sites on the Web. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDGEAR _ Games for children. This week: Croc 2. (Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE _ Weekly centerpiece on personal technology,
from products to trends to advancements. This week: Priceline.com.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Windows ME. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Microsoft Office 2000.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Buying on Ebay.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Internet auction
sites. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SAVVY _ Question and answer column focusing on using
computers and other technology as tools to get jobs done.
(Cleere/Rudd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-IMPLANT _In September, 8-year-old Louie Carter's life
changed forever, with a car accident that left him paralyzed from
the waist down. This week, a computer chip may alter the outcome of
that disability. He'll become the first Georgian, and one of only
eight people in the world, to get the implant in an operation in
Philadelphia. If the surgery is successful, the chip will bypass
his spinal column to allow his brain to send signals to nerves in
his legs, and the Milner youngster might be able to walk again _
not unassisted, but with a walker or crutches. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS, GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Three or four briefs of world and national news,
written for kids to understand. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NFK-FEATURE _ A feature about a celebrity kid, kid's event, or
big news story explained for kids, for papers' kids or family
pages. This week: All about teeth. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN _ Observations on the television industry from
a leading commentator. This week: National TV-Turnoff Week
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
