<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   COMPLETE STORY OF ELIAN GONZALEZ'S FAMILY AND RESCUE FROM WATERS
OFF FLORIDA COAST AVAILABLE FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE.
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   Because of continuing interest in the Elian Gonzalez story, The
New York Times Syndicate has just transmitted a SHORTENED VERSION
of the New York Times Magazine story ``Just Another Cuban Family
Saga,'' which appeared in the April 23 issue.
</P>
<P>
   The article is free to clients of The New York Times Syndicate's
Centerpiece package.
</P>
<P>
   In the story, Times staffer Tim Golden describes the wedge that
split the family as some chose Communism and others freedom. The
family background may be of special interest when the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the 11th Circuit rules on Elian's case on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   ALSO INCLUDED: A FREE GRAPHIC of Elian's family tree, created in
Adobe Illustrator. It will be available starting Saturday, April 29
and can be sent to you electronically. Simply e-mail Peter Trigg,
Communications Director, at nytsf(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   AN EXCERPT ...
</P>
<P>
   ```Papa, my mama got lost in the sea,''' Juan Miguel remembers
his son saying. ``I told him: `Don't worry. You will be right back
here with me.''' Later that night, Juan Miguel said, his Aunt
Caridad called. ``She told me: `With all this, your life is set
here.'' Several of his other aunts and uncles called with similar
pleas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Lazaro and Delfin (the father's uncles) called, and they
started to offend me,'' Juan Miguel said. ``They started telling me
how bad the government here is, all that. And me _ I have my
ideals. They never said a thing about the boy staying there _ they
were just insisting that we should go there.''
</P>
