<SLUG> BC-AMANDA-SCHULL-IN-CENTER-STAGE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOTTA DANCE: AMANDA SCHULL TAKES `CENTER STAGE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Amanda Schull dancing with Ethan Stiefel
and Sascha Radetsky in a scene from ``Center Stage.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's not exactly Lana Turner being plucked from obscurity while
sipping soda at Schwab's Drugstore, but ...
 &HT;    Barely 12 months ago, aspiring ballerina Amanda Schull was at
the San Francisco Ballet School, rehearsing for an end-of-the-year
performance. Her most ambitious dream was to plie her way to a
contract with the school's parent company, the San Francisco
Ballet.
 &HT;    By chance, she encountered one of many casting agents dispatched
across the country by the producers of the upcoming dance movie
``Center Stage,'' assigned to scout both professional and student
dancers for the pivotal role of Jody Sawyer. The agent invited
Schull to read for the part.
 &HT;    ``I read the next morning,'' Schull says. ``I'd just come from a
rehearsal. She had a little camcorder, and I was beet-red, dripping
with sweat, out of breath and inarticulate. I was beside myself. I
was too excited.
 &HT;    ``She said, `We'll speak to you in about three weeks,''' the
21-year-old recalls, ``and I heard from her in three days. I got
flown down to Los Angeles to read for the director, Nicholas
Hytner, and I met the producer. Then they flew me to New York to do
a screen test, and I got myself a movie.''
 &HT;    And so it is that Schull, a Hawaiian-born blonde with blue eyes,
a lithe dancer's body and precious little attitude, came to head
the cast of ``Center Stage,'' which opens nationwide on May 12 and
is best described as a cross between ``Rocky'' (1976) and ``Fame''
(1980), set in the world of ballet.
 &HT;    Though the film focuses on three young hopefuls _ Schull as the
naive newcomer, Zoe Saldana as a girl with an attitude and Susan
May Pratt as a self-destructive prima donna _ it also makes time
for a smug star (Ethan Stiefel), the pompous artistic director
(Peter Gallagher) threatened by the smug star, a respected teacher
(Donna Murphy), a gay black dancer (Shakiem Evans), Jody's two
would-be boyfriends (Sascha Radetsky and Eion Bailey) and a stage
mother (Debra Monk) vicariously living a dream through her
daughter.
 &HT;    ``I think it's very realistic,'' Schull says during an interview
at New York's Regency Hotel. ``For the screen test they only gave
me a couple of scenes, and they were realistic to me. I had no idea
what to expect and, of course, I thought, `Hollywood is going to
glam it up. It's going to be totally outlandish.'
 &HT;    ``But when I read the whole thing,'' Schull recalls, ``I was
really impressed. They touched on so many different things that it
gives a really general view of all the elements that go into the
life of a dancer, the whole process of becoming a dancer.
 &HT;    ``Nick Hytner was very instrumental in the authenticity,'' she
adds. ``He was constantly asking us for our perspective. `Would you
do this? Would you say this? Would you wear this?' He was always
making sure that we confirmed every single element of the whole
film.''
 &HT;    That's a lot of elements _ backstabbing, underhanded alliances
between competitors, stage mothers from hell, bulimia ...
 &HT;    ``I've seen everything this movie touches on, to the umpteenth
degree,'' Schull says. ``I've seen anorexia, I've seen bulimia,
I've seen stage moms. I've dealt with jealousy and backstabbing.
It's unfortunate, but because there are so many dancers and so few
roles, there is a lot of backstabbing and a lot of unfortunate
experiences.
 &HT;    ``That's another reason the film was nice,'' she says, ``because
they didn't try to hide any of the unglamorous parts. The curtain
goes up and you see all the pretty ballerinas in their tutus and
you think, `Wow, that was just beautiful. Wow, they're just
beautiful.'
 &HT;    ``But you have no idea what goes into the day of a dancer _ you
have no idea what we put our minds through, what we put our bodies
through, what we put our lives through.
 &HT;    ``It's really nice to bring that to a larger audience,'' Schull
concludes, ``so people will hopefully be able to appreciate and
respect our art more.''
 &HT;    Making the film, the young dancer says, was pretty painless.
Acting came fairly easily, because she had her personal experience,
her co-stars and Hytner to draw on for guidance.
 &HT;    Watching herself, though, was another matter.
 &HT;    ``It was me, on the screen,'' she says, cringing. ``I'd never
seen myself dance on a screen that big.
 &HT;    ``Artists always criticize their own work,'' she says with a
grimace. ``Of course, I found little things wrong, with my
shoulders off that way or my foot not pointed right.''
 &HT;    After completing ``Center Stage,'' Schull returned to the San
Francisco Ballet, with which she has a one-year contract. However,
she's not center stage there _ simply a member of the corps de
ballet, one of the unheralded dancers who help make the star look
great.
 &HT;    ``It could have been a lot harder if the people in San Francisco
weren't so amazing,'' Schull says. ``They're very supportive, and
they're curious and interested.
 &HT;    ``I had people say during the movie, `You're so spoiled here,
and when you go back you're just going to be an apprentice,''' she
adds. ``But it wasn't like I was expecting flowers to be thrown at
my feet. It hasn't been hard.''
 &HT;    In part, that's because Schull still thinks of herself as a
dancer, not an actress.
 &HT;    ``I have no idea what the future holds for me, but I've been
working really hard my whole life to be a dancer,'' she says. ``I
started at the age of 4, and I've overcome a lot of obstacles. If I
were to give everything up right now on the off chance I had a
possibility in Hollywood, I wouldn't be paying myself any justice.
 &HT;    ``It's also my first year as a professional dancer,'' Schull
says. ``It's not like I'm jaded or anything. The dancing is still
new and interesting to me. But of course this was an amazing
experience, and I'm not going to close any doors.
 &HT;    ``I just don't want to count my chickens, I guess.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
