<SLUG> BC-JOHN-TRAVOLTA-IN-BATTLEFIELD-EARTH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIENATION: JOHN TRAVOLTA IS THE BAD GUY IN `BATTLEFIELD EARTH' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of John Travolta with Christian Tessier and
Barry Pepper in a scene from ``Battlefield Earth.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Fighting off the aliens was hard, but getting the movie made was
almost impossible.
 &HT;    ``Listen, it's been a 15-year struggle to get this movie done,''
says John Travolta, star and executive producer of ``Battlefield
Earth,'' which will open nationwide on May 12. ``I'm bringing a
historic book to the big screen.''
 &HT;    The delay, of course, was caused by the fact that the movie is
based on a 1982 novel by L. Ron Hubbard, who also founded
Scientology, the controversial religious sect of which Travolta is
a high-profile member.
 &HT;    But the actor insists that ``Battlefield Earth'' isn't about
Scientology in any way, shape or form _ that it might have been
written by an author of any religious orientation.
 &HT;    ``It's just a classic science-fiction story,'' he says. ``This
is an action film based on one of the biggest science-fiction books
ever. The novel is right up there with `Dune.' It belongs on the
screen.
 &HT;    ``I just can't wait for the people to be able to see this
movie,'' the soft-spoken actor says, relaxing in a suite at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons hotel, casually dressed in gray pants and a
matching sweater. ``I've already heard the film dubbed this
summer's `Star Wars.'''
 &HT;    Travolta optioned the novel in 1984, planning to play the film's
young hero, Johnny Goodboy Tyler, who in 3000 A.D. leads a revolt
against the alien Psychlos who have taken over the world and
enslaved humanity. By the time he got the film made, however, he
had aged out of the role, and was forced to cede it to Barry
Pepper, most recently seen in ``The Green Mile'' (1999).
 &HT;    It's a pity, the actor says, because there's a lot of
interesting aspects to the role of Johnny.
 &HT;    ``Humans have actually become hunters and gatherers again to
survive,'' Travolta says. ``They live this harsh existence, just
trying to keep a piece of their planet. But it's not exactly easy
on them.''
 &HT;    As for himself, Travolta plays Terl, an 8-foot-tall Psychlo with
lots of hair and one bad attitude.
 &HT;    ``He's a very theatrical character,'' Travolta says. ``I almost
think of him as someone Shakespeare could have created. It's all
about manipulation and blackmail for this character _ he is truly
the most evil character I've ever tried to play.''
 &HT;    And the ugliest, to boot.
 &HT;    ``The movie required an amazing physical transformation,''
Travolta says. ``I wear a tall-head apparatus with strange hair. I
have amber eyes and talons for hands. It's quite remarkable.''
 &HT;    After spending much of the shoot teetering on 4-foot stilts to
capture a Psychlo's stature, Travolta professes unconcern about the
possibility of religious controversy over the movie.
 &HT;    ``The e-mail and fan mail since this picture was announced as a
go has been extraordinary,'' he says. ``I've never been involved
with a picture that got this amount of pre-excitement.
 &HT;    ``In fact, since we could only film half of the 1,050-page book,
the studio is so high on the project that we're even already
talking about a sequel for 2002,'' he adds. ``That's how much
confidence there is in the project.''
 &HT;    He's even pondering making movies of two other Hubbard novels,
``Mission Earth'' (1991) and ``Fear'' (1992).
 &HT;    ``I would love to add science fiction to my body of work,''
Travolta says. ``It's the one genre that I've missed. But I'd like
to do sci-fi in a more realistic way _ you should keep it grounded
in some sort of reality.''
 &HT;    Since resurrecting his film career with ``Pulp Fiction'' (1994),
Travolta has been on a roll, snagging one choice role after another
and earning $20 million a picture. About all he needs to round
things off is an Oscar.
 &HT;    ``Of course, you don't want to build yourself up too much in
case it doesn't happen,'' he says. ``But I've been really proud of
the work I've done in the last few years. I was extremely proud of
`A Civil Action' (1998) and `Primary Colors' (1998). I think these
were pivotal points in terms of my acting career. I think that's
where you see the growth as an actor.''
 &HT;    He doesn't claim any tremendous thespian talent, however, giving
most of the credit to the writers of his films and to his own
legendary work ethic.
 &HT;    ``It's just a matter of the material and what you put out
there,'' Travolta says. ``Your popularity really does depend on
doing good work. Above all, I know for a fact that it can all go
away in a moment.''
 &HT;    That sense may lie behind the barrage of movies Travolta has
cranked out since ``Pulp Fiction,'' and he shows no sign of slowing
down. Later this summer he'll be seen opposite Lisa Kudrow in Nora
Ephron's ``Numbers,'' a comedy about a lottery scam. He is also
signed to do a thriller called ``Domestic Disturbances'' and an
action film called ``Swordfish,'' and he's admitted that the idea
of doing another musical _ his first since ``Grease'' (1978) _
intrigues him.
 &HT;    ``I just want to continue to work at the highest level and
always get better as an actor,'' Travolta says. ``I think there are
many challenges left in this life. Finding an exciting character to
play is the ultimate work challenge, but I also have challenges in
aviation. And the ultimate challenge is to take care of my family
and my 40 employees, whom I love very much.''
 &HT;    That family includes wife Kelly Preston, who plays a female
alien in ``Battlefield Earth,'' their 7-year-old son Jett and a
newborn daughter.
 &HT;    ``I haven't been the same man since I became a father,''
Travolta says. ``Mostly, I'm more vulnerable. You don't ever quite
feel about anyone the way you feel about your child _ you worry
more than you're used to worrying. You get sad when you're not with
them. And it's a vulnerable feeling being a parent.''
 &HT;    Travolta is a hands-on parent, playing Santa each Christmas and
even accompanying Jett around the neighborhood trick-or-treating
last October.
 &HT;    ``I was the Grim Reaper,'' he says, laughing at the memory. ``It
was a way to hide my face. I wore this big hood so no one knew it
was me, until I couldn't breathe under the mask. I finally had to
take it off, and then I was just Jett's dad in this big robe.''
 &HT;    Well, not just that. He is, after all, one of Hollywood's
personifications of cool _ which he admits to, without taking any
credit for it.
 &HT;    ``I'm often asked the secret of this so-called `cool,''' he
says, laughing. ``I don't know what `cool' means. When I was a kid,
`cool' meant wearing a turtleneck and a beret. You held a cigarette
_ that was kind of cool. Now I'm called `cool' all the time, but I
don't know what it means.
 &HT;    ``My characters are cool in `Broken Arrow' (1996) and `Get
Shorty' (1995) and `Battlefield Earth,''' he concedes. ``But as a
person, I feel like this big, goofy guy.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
