<SLUG> BC-HEATHER-GRAHAM-IN-COMMITTED-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COMMITTED' TO COMEDY: HEATHER GRAHAM GOES FOR LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Heather Graham in a scene from
``Committed.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Sure, she can be as sexy as she wants to be, but Heather Graham
would rather make you laugh.
 &HT;    She scored her breakthrough by skating naked as the porn star
Rollergirl in ``Boogie Nights'' (1997), got explicitly passionate
with Robert Downey Jr. in ``Two Girls and a Guy'' (1997) and was
hilariously raunchy as Felicity Shagwell in ``Austin Powers: The
Spy Who Shagged Me'' (1999), so it's understandable if you don't
think of her as a comedienne.
 &HT;    But the actress says that her first starring vehicle,
``Committed,'' now playing nationwide, actually comes closer to the
real Graham.
 &HT;    ``When my boyfriend saw the movie,'' she says, ``he told me,
`That's more like you on the screen, because you're more cute than
sexy.'''
 &HT;    Graham's boyfriend is, of course, actor/writer/director Ed
Burns, best known for making ``The Brothers McMullen'' (1995) and
``She's the One'' (1996) and then starring in ``Saving Private
Ryan'' (1998).
 &HT;    Burns has felt conflicted about watching her past love scenes,
Graham admits.
 &HT;    ``In some ways he finds it a pain in the neck,'' she says.
``But, on the other hand, it's probably an ego boost for him. It's
kind of a double-edged sword _ you don't want the person you love
making love with someone else, but you don't mind watching them on
the screen because you're going to get them in real life.''
 &HT;    Joline, her character in ``Committed,'' is a woman who won't
take ``no'' for an answer. When her husband (Luke Wilson) leaves
her, she sets out to get him back, leading to an odyssey that takes
her from New York to El Paso, Texas.
 &HT;    ``I was actually afraid to show the script to Ed,'' Graham says
with a laugh. ``It was right at the beginning of our relationship,
and I didn't want him to get nervous. I thought he might think I
completely identified with this girl who was so totally committed
to staying married that she seemed just a little bit crazy.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, she admits, she sees some of herself in the
character.
 &HT;    ``I am a committed person,'' Graham says reflectively, ``and I
like the idea that marriage is forever. I'm just not as committed
as Joline.
 &HT;    ``I did understand that feeling of being passionate about
something and just giving yourself over to it,'' the actress says.
``I think we all wonder how far we'd go to keep a promise. In her
case, it's `till death do us part.'
 &HT;    ``I think I also identified with Joline's growing realization
that life doesn't always turn out how you expect it to.''
 &HT;    It certainly didn't for Graham, who thought she'd broken through
as a dramatic actress when she played a teen-age drunk in ``License
to Drive'' (1988) and went on to play a junkie who dies from an
overdose in Gus Van Sant's ``Drugstore Cowboy'' (1989). But it
wasn't until the surprise hit ``Swingers'' (1996) and, especially,
``Boogie Nights'' that Graham suddenly ``made it,'' hitting
magazine covers and sexiest-women lists nationwide.
 &HT;    That image was something new for the actress, who had a Catholic
upbringing as the daughter of an FBI agent and a schoolteacher so
strict that they deemed ``The Love Boat'' too racy for their
daughters to watch.
 &HT;    ``I was the Goody Two-Shoes,'' she recalls, ``and I wrestled a
lot with thoughts about sex, because my religion made me feel it
was horrible and I would go to hell.
 &HT;    ``I think that I had to work through a lot of things because of
my upbringing,'' the actress adds. ``I don't know if it put a
burden on me _ I guess everyone has certain things from their
upbringing that they need to work out.''
 &HT;    Graham is currently estranged from both the Catholic church and
her parents and sister, but she doesn't want to discuss it.
 &HT;    ``I haven't spoken to my family in something like five years,''
she says with a shrug. ``It's my choice. All I'll say is the reason
has nothing to do with the fact that I'm an actress.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, she bonded immediately with Burns' parents.
 &HT;    ``I love his family,'' Graham says. ``They're really funny. They
have the same kind of sense of humor that Ed does, giving each
other a hard time and teasing. And they're reminiscing fools _
they'll sit and talk about every single thing that's happened in
their lives from their childhood on.''
 &HT;    Next to her acting, her relationship to Burns seems to define
her life. And she doesn't mind saying so, either.
 &HT;    ``I was thinking, `God, look at all these celebrities that
refuse to talk about their relationships. Like, am I making a big
mistake here, like, talking about it?''' she says. ``But I just
think I'm in love, and I've never been this in love, and I think
there's something really kind of beautiful when Ed reads what I say
about him.
 &HT;    ``I think there's something really sweet and romantic about
that,'' she adds. ``He loves it. Every time he reads an article and
I talk about him, he is like, `I love it. This is so great _ I
can't wait for my friends to read this.'''
 &HT;    The two spend huge amounts of time together, Graham reports,
without ever getting tired of each other.
 &HT;    ``We love to do stuff together,'' she says. ``Ed watched a video
of `Swingers' and got a kick out of the swing-dancing parts. He
decided he wanted to learn, so now we're taking dancing lessons
together, everything from the tango to the foxtrot.''
 &HT;    One thing they don't do together is talk about acting, however.
Burns may be a director, she says, but he never has any tips to
offer on her performances.
 &HT;    ``His acting philosophy is, `I don't know,''' she says with a
laugh. ``He's always saying about his acting, `I suck.' But I think
he's really good.''
 &HT;    Particularly gratifying to Graham is Burns' apparent
indifference to the fact that, for all his success, his girlfriend
usually attracts more fan attention than he does.
 &HT;    ``Last year Ed did a movie with Robert De Niro,'' she says,
``and I would visit him on the set. One day De Niro said, `I hope
Heather is coming tomorrow, because my niece and nephew are going
to be here, and they really want to meet her because they loved
`Austin Powers.'
 &HT;    ``Then I was late, and De Niro kept saying to Ed, `Is she here
yet? We're waiting for her,''' Graham says, laughing. ``I thought
it was so bizarre that De Niro was waiting for me.''
 &HT;    Continuing her preference for comedy _ and following up her
critically praised performance in ``Bowfinger'' (1999) _ Graham is
currently at work on the Farrelly brothers' ``Say It Isn't So''
opposite Chris Klein.
 &HT;    She recently celebrated her 30th birthday as one of Hollywood's
hottest stars and says that, in retrospect, she's glad that she
didn't reach that level any earlier.
 &HT;    ``I think all your mistakes add to your wisdom,'' the actress
says thoughtfully. ``In the beginning, I had a real lack of
confidence, and I thought everyone else knew more than I did. I
really kept my opinions to myself.
 &HT;    ``Then I figured out that, whether you do something wrong or
even stupid, it's all right _ it's all part of growing,'' Graham
says. ``I think that really helped me.
 &HT;    ``I only wish I had figured it out earlier.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
