<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-TREK-VOYAGES-ON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLDLY GOING, BUT WHERE? `STAR TREK' FACES AN UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the cast of ``Star Trek: Voyager,''
including Kate Mulgrew, Garrett Wang, Roxann Dawson, Tim Russ,
Robert Beltran, Robert Duncan McNeill, Robert Picardo, Jennifer
Lien and Ethan Phillips.) 
 By BRIAN HARTIGAN  
 Includes a 300-word sidebar. 
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before May 21. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't believe the hype _ ``Star Trek'' is not dead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impending end of television's ``Star Trek:
Voyager,'' the lag in the creation of a new series and problems at
the feature-film box office, the ``Star Trek'' franchise is doing
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a baseball manager might say, this is a rebuilding
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Voyager'' will air its season finale on May 24.
``Unimatrix Zero'' marks the return of the Borg and its queen,
played by ``Once and Again's'' Susanna Thompson. However, if
Internet reports are to be believed _ and we're not saying they are
_ Part One may also feature the assimilation of one or more main
characters, a plot used to huge success by ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' for its season-ender 10 years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   More important, perhaps, is that the conclusion of this week's
episode, airing some time next fall, will mark the beginning of the
end for ``Voyager'': Paramount has confirmed that next season, the
show's seventh, will be its last.
</P>
<P>
   That begs a question that fans have been asking since ... well,
since the show debuted in 1995: When will the Voyager make it home?
</P>
<P>
   In a word, soon _ maybe even sooner than expected. While many
have assumed that the Voyager's return to earth would highlight the
final episode, ``Trek'' analysts and at least one cast member _
Robert Picardo _ are speculating that the voyage home will end
sometime next November, with the sweeps-week airing of a previously
announced, two-hour-long ``Trek'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   The timing would be perfect, after all, leaving half a season
for the characters to readjust to Earth and rejoin the Federation,
setting up possible future ``Voyager'' television movies or feature
films.
</P>
<P>
   But that brings up another nagging question: Just what are the
plans for future television movies and feature films?
</P>
<P>
   After ``Star Trek: Deep Space Nine'' ended last year, there were
rumors that the cast would reunite for a television movie, as
happened with ``Babylon 5.'' So far, however, no launching pad has
been erected.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising, perhaps, there hasn't been a peep from
Paramount regarding a 10th ``Star Trek'' feature film. Indeed,
Majel Barrett Roddenberry, widow of ``Star Trek'' creator Gene
Roddenberry, recently told Cinescape magazine that she wouldn't be
surprised if there were no immediate plans for a new film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't think there is going to be another movie
for a bit,'' she said. ``There are just so many questions about
what cast they want to use or if they want to start over with a new
group of actors.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that the last movie, ``Star Trek: Insurrection''
(1999), garnered poor reviews and a paltry $70 million at the
American box office. Some have suggested that the feature-film
goose may have laid its last golden eggs for now.
</P>
<P>
   There's definitely a future for ``Star Trek'' on the small
screen, however. Paramount and ``Trek'' bigwigs Rick Berman and
Brannon Braga are even now mulling over ideas for the long-promised
fifth television series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you much about the new `Star Trek' series, except
that there will be one,'' Braga told fans at the Star Trek Grand
Slam Convention in California last month. ``We haven't nailed down
a concept yet, but we intend to do something that captures the
essence of `Star Trek,' but is completely original and new.''
</P>
<P>
   Braga and Berman are shooting for an early-2001 launch date for
the new series, which would enable it to build on what is expected
to be substantial buzz over ``Voyager's'' grand finale in May 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In short, even without anything official on future ``Star Trek''
movie or television projects, the development wheel is turning. No
one is ready to give up on a billion-dollar industry just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the low ratings, diminished box office and perceived
creative snags. ``Star Trek,'' in all its forms, is alive and well
and will undoubtedly live long and prosper. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; SIDEBAR: `STAR TREK: RUMORVILLE' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Television has a new, unnamed ``Star Trek'' series in
development, but so far the powers that be are keeping their cards
very close to the vest as to what the setting for that series might
be, whether it would involve existing characters or even in what
time frame it might be set.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, however, that hasn't stopped Internet-based
Trekkers from speculating and offering their own ideas. Here are
seven of the hottest rumors, presented with the understanding that
_ like almost anything on the Internet _ they probably aren't worth
the screens they're downloaded onto. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: EXCELSIOR.'
</P>
<P>
   There's a strong fan movement afoot to create a series around
Captain Sulu (George Takei) and his U.S.S. Excelsior crew, as seen
in ``Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country'' (1991) and the
``Voyager'' episode ``Flashback.''
</P>
<P>
   Takei is all for it, of course.
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: THE PREQUEL'
</P>
<P>
   One early scenario involved a series that would serve as a
prequel to the original ``Star Trek,'' featuring the very first
crew of the Enterprise, which is established as having been led by
Capt. Robert April.
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: ACADEMY'
</P>
<P>
   Imagine seeing Kirk, Spock and McCoy as Starfleet Academy
cadets. That would be the idea behind a widely disseminated
scenario called ``Star Trek: Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of the ``Next Generation'' episode ``Tapestry.'' But
casting the three lead roles/cultural icons would be
extraordinarily difficult.
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: FLIGHT ACADEMY'
</P>
<P>
   Think of ``Top Gun'' (1986) in outer space. That's the idea
behind this projected scenario, which would star hotshot
wannabe-Starfleet pilots in a style much like the ``Next
Generation'' episode ``The First Duty.''
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: SECTION 31'
</P>
<P>
   5) Another scenario, one of the most removed from the basic
``Trek'' format, has a group of top-secret Starfleet investigators
solving crimes and thwarting conspiracies in the previously
established Section 31. Something like the ``DS9'' episode
``Inquisition,'' in short.
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: YOUNG GUNS'
</P>
<P>
   Young Starfleet officers commanding a ship is another approach
being tossed around, taking inspiration from the ``Next
Generation'' episode ``Lower Decks'' and the ``DS9'' episode
``Valiant.''
</P>
<P>
   + `STAR TREK: ALIENS'
</P>
<P>
   Two other theories postulate entire shows being based around
either Klingons or Ferengis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brian Hartigan is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
