<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ENDANGERED-JOURNALIST     05-01 1686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDANGERED-JOURNALISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE JOURNALISTS PAYING FOR COVERAGE WITH THEIR LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Veton Surroi was an ethnic Albanian and
Slavko Curuvija a Serb, but still they had a lot in common. Both
were journalists who believed a free, robust press was the most
powerful weapon against tyranny. Both used their talents to report
on the repressive regime of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, the difference between the two courageous
journalists could not be greater.
</P>
<P>
   Surroi, who publishes the paper most read by ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, lives in a society run by international peacekeepers and
enjoys freedoms unthinkable a year ago. Curuvija, who published a
magazine and newspaper critical of Milosevic in a capital full of
Serb secret police and paramilitaries, is dead.
</P>
<P>
   And while Serbian journalists endure continuing intimidation,
harassment, and fines, the only people Surroi has to fear are the
ethnic Albanian extremists who threatened him after he called for
an end to revenge killings against the few Serb civilians left in
the province.
</P>
<P>
   The fates of these two men, and of the societies in which they
operate, provide a particularly clear-cut example of the
consequences that flow from attempts to repress, and to protect,
free expression. But in Russia, Sierra Leone, Colombia, and
numerous other countries, journalists are paying with their lives
for reporting on official corruption and civil strife.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths of working journalists rose last year to their highest
level since 1994, according to the Vienna-based International Press
Institute, which is holding its world congress in Boston this week.
According to the institute, 65 journalists and 21 support staff
were killed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Committee to Protect Reporters had somewhat
lower totals but also registered its first sharp upswing in
killings of journalists since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the old movies. People nowdays are deliberately
targeted,'' said Johann P. Fritz, director of the institute. ``If
you use an armband or marked car that says press, this will insure
they kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   In countries where corruption and civil strife are rampant,
``drug dealers, corrupt military men, corrupt people in public
administration or civil business _ they really fear the
investigative journalist,'' Fritz said. ``It starts with
harassment, proceeds to intimidation, and if that doesn't succeed
in repressing you, it ends up in murder.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore his point, Fritz noted that more than 200
journalists have been killed since the breakdown of the Soviet
Union _ compared with about 100 killed in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for a free press in Russia say the trend has been
toward greater government control of the media since the rise of
President-elect Vladimir V. Putin, a former officer of the covert
intelligence agency. Oleg Panfilov, of the Russian Journalists'
Union, said the government's desire to control information about
the war in Chechnya, in particular, has led to a marked decrease in
press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The number of journalists imprisoned for their work worldwide
declined last year, to 87 from 118 in 1998, according to a tally by
the Committee to Protect Journalists. But this does not indicate
improving conditions, just a shift in tactics, as authoritarian
regimes turn to trumped-up civil charges and fines to stifle
critical inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Ann K. Cooper, director of the Committee to Protect Journalists,
said authoritarian regimes are increasingly using tax laws,
controls on newsprint and access to printing houses, and influence
on advertisers to pressure critical journals and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be just as effective as burning down the office or
throwing the reporters and editors in jail,'' Cooper said. ``It
makes (the repression) not look so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, intimidation and prosecution of journalists is part
of a wider campaign aimed at students, intellectuals, opposition
politicians, and anyone else the government deems to be a potential
dissident, says Holly Cartner, executive director of Human Rights
Watch's Europe and Central Asia division.
</P>
<P>
   Aryeh Neier, president of the Soros Foundation network of
organizations promoting open, civil societies, says ``freedom of
the press is one of the most sensitive barometers for the situation
in a country generally. When a country is very dangerous to the
media, it tends to be very bad for freedom and human rights
generally.''
</P>
<P>
   Such danger is evident throughout much of the world, among them
the following three areas:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern Africa &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Press freedoms have been increasingly under threat as war and
political uncertainty have shaken countries across southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In Swaziland, where a constitutional reform process stalled in
December, the country's main newspaper was shut down in February
after a contentious battle with the state. The Swazi Observer had a
reputation for exposing corruption and police brutality. The
closure followed efforts by police and government officials to
force two reporters and two editors to reveal their sources behind
a series of stories about police investigations into a 1998 bomb
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time the Observer was shut down, nearly 30
editors in neighboring South Africa were issued subpoenas to answer
allegations of racism in the media. The summonses, which carried
the threat of six months in jail, were repealed following an
international outcry.
</P>
<P>
   Two countries in the region have been especially and
increasingly intolerant of press freedoms. On March 31, reporter
Rafael Marques was convicted of defaming Angolan President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos and sentenced to six months in prison. The
proceedings were closed to the public, and Marques was denied legal
representation.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists also face increasing threats in Zimbabwe as
President Robert Mugabe struggles to hold on to power through
violence. Local and foreign reporters and television news crews
have been harassed, intimidated, and beaten up by government
supporters who have invaded white-owned farms and disrupted
opposition political rallies. The country's only independent
newspaper, the Daily News, was rattled by a bomb attack last week.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe's most troubling case, journalists from the weekly
Independent, Ray Choto and Mark Chavunduka, were abducted and
tortured by police in January 1999 after refusing to reveal their
sources behind a story indicating a possible military coup attempt.
More than a year later, the two remain charged under the Law and
Order Maintenance Act, a relic of the colonial era that allows the
president wide latitude to act against dissenters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Middle East &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In much of the Middle East _ outside of Israel, which has an
almost totally free domestic media _ journalists are constrained by
official regulations, unofficial harassment, and self-censorship.
</P>
<P>
   In Syria and Iraq, all media are state-run, and criticism is
banned. Other countries, like Egypt, tightly restrict the media not
only by licensing news outlets but also by controlling newspaper
printing and distribution. Yemen, Jordan, and the Palestinian
Authority maintain strict press laws, employ criminal, libel, and
``state security'' regulations or rely on threatening visits and
phone calls by security men to keep the media compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions in the region between advocates of a freer press and
backers of continued tight controls have been exemplified in Iran,
where President Mohammad Khatami is trying to open up the media and
allow critical voices to emerge. Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei, calls such media ``bases of the enemy,'' and since
last summer, 16 pro-reform publications have been shut down by the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority may be the newest government in the
region, but so far it has employed old methods when it comes to the
media. Press monitors say that Yasser Arafat's administration does
not tolerate dissent or criticism by the press. Reporters and
editors who critically touch on sensitive issues _ like official
corruption, human rights violations, Arafat himself, and the peace
process _ face the threat of arrest or having the media outlet
closed down.
</P>
<P>
   Television, especially from satellite stations, is the one area
in the region where the old restrictions no longer apply. The most
popular station in the Middle East is al-Jazeera, a Qatari
satellite station that offers uncensored, independent news coverage
of the region. Its programs are watched throughout the Arab world
and offer people the chance to hear views and news that are not
reported in their own countries. Its coverage of the Middle East is
so hard-hitting that its reporters have been at times barred from
some Arab countries, including from Bahrain, Kuwait, and Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colombia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm one more. Like the intellectual, like the reporter, like the
human-rights activist, like the displaced person. Like Pacheco.
Nothing more and nothing less. I have to abandon my native land, my
life, my soul, my country.''
</P>
<P>
   So began the March 12 column of Francisco Santos, news editor of
El Tiempo, Bogota's largest daily. Santos wrote the piece as he was
preparing to leave Colombia following threats on his life. A vocal
critic of human rights violations, Santos had been followed by
hired assassins for days, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   His departure followed days after the flight of a popular
television personality, Fernando Pacheco, and several weeks after
the kidnapping of Pacheco's cousin, a television news director.
They are the most recent in a long list of Colombian journalists
caught in the unforgiving gears of the 36-year conflict that has
grown more complicated and more violent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the seven journalists killed there in 1999, 24
were kidnapped and 15 forced to flee the country, acording to the
Bogota-based Press Freedom Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     05-01 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW REPORT SHOWS RACISM IN JUVENILE JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (Editor's note: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, received awards from the National
Council on Crime and Delinquency in 1998 and 1999.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Across this nation, race plays a major role in who's locked up
in juvenile detention centers and for how long. If a teen-ager
belongs to a racial or ethnic minority, he has a much greater
chance of spending time in a detention center or adult prison than
his white counterpart, according to a new report released on April
25.
</P>
<P>
   The National Council on Crime and Delinquency (NCCD), the
nation's oldest criminal justice think tank, prepared the report
for a group of organizations affiliated under the name Building
Blocks for Youth. These organizations include the Youth Law Center,
the Juvenile Law Center, the Justice Policy Institute and the
American Bar Association's Juvenile Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``And Justice for Some: Differential Treatment of
Minority Youth in the Justice System,'' presents a devastating
picture of how racial prejudice at every level of the juvenile
justice system weighs against minority youth.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, when white and minority teen-agers with
no prior arrests are charged with the same offenses, blacks are six
times more likely to be incarcerated in public facilities than
whites. And although the figures are somewhat muddy because those
with Hispanic backgrounds are often not listed by ethnicity, Latino
teens are at least three times more likely to be incarcerated than
white teens.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Schindler, staff attorney for the Youth Law Center in
Washington, D.C., considers the figures regarding comparable
offenses by teens who had not been arrested before to be startling.
Those statistics had not been reported before, he said. ``And if
you look at the breakdown by offense, for instance, for drug cases
particularly, African Americans are 48 times more likely to be
incarcerated than white kids for the same offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers leave no argument that black and brown kids are
just committing more crimes and therefore more are locked up. These
disparities are so glaring that there's no way that can explain the
disparity. There's something else going on here. The obvious factor
appears to be the race impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Black teens represent the largest racial/ethnic proportion of
youth held behind locked doors. And they are confined for longer
periods of time than white teens for the same crime.
</P>
<P>
   Minority youth represented only 34 percent of the total U.S.
population in 1997 _ yet they represented 62 percent of the youth
incarcerated in adult and juvenile facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Currently all 50 states and the District of Columbia allow
juveniles to be incarcerated in adult jails for some crimes. And
between 1992 and 1997, the District of Columbia and all but three
states made it easier to transfer teen-agers as young as 13 from
the juvenile justice system into the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, under the ``get tough on crime'' standard, 7,400 minors
were sent to adult prisons. Three-quarters of those young people
belonged to racial or ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler considers sending young teen-agers to adult prisons
``analogous to a death penalty for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we transfer a youngster into the adult criminal justice
system,'' Schindler said, ``and then subsequently incarcerate them
in adult prisons, we have thrown those kids away. We have ended
their lives as children, some as young as 13, 14 and 15 years old.
We are essentially saying that we, as a society, are giving up on
13- or 14-year-olds, that nothing can be done other than put them
in an adult prison. That's a terrible, terrible indictment on our
society _ to say we can't do anything about those kids. That
they're unredeemable.''
</P>
<P>
   The report points out that minority children are more likely
than their white counterparts to be involved in the juvenile
justice system and that their over representation will increase at
each stage of the process. For the same offenses, a higher
proportion of minority children will be arrested than whites; a
higher proportion of minority children will be charged with crimes
than their white counterparts and a higher proportion of minority
kids than whites will end up incarcerated in public detention
centers than private ones.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, in every category of criminal offenses
_ against a person, against property, drug dealing, and against
public order _ a substantially greater percentage of black children
were detained by police than white children.
</P>
<P>
   The juvenile justice system is tilted dramatically against those
of color in our society. Not surprising, unfortunately. Now, with
this report, we cannot close our eyes to it and pretend it doesn't
exist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Congress amended the Juvenile Justice and Delinquency
Prevention Act of 1974 to include a mandate for states to study and
attempt to correct the problem of disproportionate minority
confinement (DMC). These studies were used to prepare the NCCD
report. Without these state statistics, the problem of racial bias
in the treatment of juvenile offenders would have been impossible
to quantify or even define properly.
</P>
<P>
   Yet last year, Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Jeff Sessions,
R-Ala., introduced a juvenile crime bill that would have eliminated
the requirement that states keep records on disproportionate
minority confinement.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor of the Senate, Hatch stated that racism has nothing
to do with the disproportionate arrest rates for minority teens.
Those are the kids who are selling drugs to our children, he said.
``Those'' meaning black or brown kids, ``our'' meaning white kids.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be a surprise that the NCCD report shows that in
Utah one out of 12 black children will be incarcerated by the age
of 18. That's the highest rate of confinement for a minority group
anywhere in this nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Hatch-Session's bill did not pass last year; however, it is
still pending in a Senate-House conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Based upon the findings of the NCCD report, the Building Blocks
for Youth coalition asks Congress to strengthen the
disproportionate minority confinement mandate to address the stark
racial and ethnic disparities in confinement. The coalition also
asks that Congress appropriate at least an addition $100 million
for the Department of Justice to address this issue throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The report should be a call to action for anyone of social
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Racism is an ugly reality anywhere it is met, but it is
especially monstrous when it parades as a system of justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      05-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMICAL, YET DISTURBING, TAKE ON BRITISH NATIONALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Al Murray was only a few minutes into his routine, but
a trio of middle-aged Americans had heard enough, interrupting the
show as they made a hasty and conspicuous exit from the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, sir, you all right?'' Murray asked solicitously from
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're fine,'' came back the unmistakably American
monotone. ``But we're leaving. There's too much profanity. We
didn't expect this kind of language.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray nodded sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' Murray said. As the Americans got to the door,
Murray waved, saying, ``Ciao, mother (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   To Al Murray, cursing is a form of intercourse. In fact, he uses
the vulgar word for sexual intercourse as a noun, verb, adjective
and, somehow, an adverb in his show, dispensing the outrageous
views of an English pub owner.
</P>
<P>
   His one-man show ``The Pub Landlord'' has been lauded by critics
and audiences alike, and is currently on an extended run in the
West End's Playhouse Theatre. Last year, his show led him to being
named comedian of the year at the Edinburgh Arts Festival, the most
prestigious award for comics in Britain and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Part comedy, part social commentary, Murray's rant is both
hilarious and disturbing. The audience laughs, sometimes
uncomfortably, at his sexist, racist, Neanderthal diatribes. But
behind the practiced ignorance is a savage attack on the xenophobia
and bigotry that parades itself as British nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair, Britain's prime minister, sometimes appears
self-righteous when he regularly denounces ``the forces of
conservatism,'' as if anyone with right-leaning sympathies is
immoral and responsible for all of Britain's woes.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray's pub commentary is a far more revealing, and funny,
take on modern Britain. As Archie Bunker once held up a mirror to
American society, the pub landlord's prejudices are actually a
scathing indictment of British intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   As Shay Duffin did in his one-man play on Brendan Behan, the
Irish playwright who drank himself to death at 41, Murray manages
to consume prodigious amounts of beer during his performance. If he
got intoxicated, it only added to the effect. He started to spit
his p's, literally, showering the front row with saliva that made
him appear rabid. Some of his characters' opinions are: Foreigners
are hopelessly inferior to the English, he maintains. The Germans
are passionless automatons, prone to dominating their fellow
Europeans. Murray underscored this point by screaming ``I love
you!'' in German, in a maniacal voice that made it sound more like
``I'm going to kill you!''
</P>
<P>
   The pub landlord's wife left him for a Frenchman, which added an
especially vicious streak to the antipathy that many Englishmen
feel for their neighbors across the channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do the French have a Foreign Legion when they're all
foreigners anyway?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the suit jacket and tie he wore on stage, Murray's bald
pate and virulent ignorance made him resemble the archtypical
English soccer hooligan, who, despite stereotypes, is as often
educated and middle-class as a no-hoper from some desolate housing
project.
</P>
<P>
   He was a vision of modern British hell. Check that. English.
Because as Murray said, when people say British, 90 percent of the
time they mean English, because the English make up about 90
percent of Britain's population.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you'd know it living here, he said. The English are
self-loathing wimps, he said. They've let their empire disintegrate
all in the name of being nicey-nicey to foreigners. Why, he asked,
didn't the Brits colonize the moon? And why don't Brits call it
``Great'' Britain anymore? Wimps, he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Murray picked on people in the audience, reserving particular
venom for those 20- and 30-somethings making big money in the
Internet industry. The pub landlord is not on line.
</P>
<P>
   While the audience was allowed to have drinks at their seats,
Murray insisted that women refrain from drinking beer. Men drank
pints. Women didn't. The subtitle to his show is ``And A Glass Of
White Wine For The Lady,'' which is what many paternalistic
Englishmen order for their women companions.
</P>
<P>
   When Mary Swanick, a Pennsylvania native living in London with
her husband and three children, dared to sip a beer in the second
row, Murray climbed down from the stage and confiscated it,
chastising her, ``Ladies don't drink beer.'' He compensated her by
pouring a white wine from the makeshift bar on stage, carrying it
to her with his thumb holding the inside of the glass. Swanick
walked to the back of the theater, bought another beer for herself,
then marched back to her seat, defying Murray to try to take it
again. Murray, who had spoken to her earlier, just nodded, almost
approvingly, accepting defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put up with this?'' Murray asked Swanick's husband
incredulously. Mike Swanick, an accountant, shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans,'' Murray said, rolling his eyes, and then he was
off again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen is chief of the Boston Globe European Bureau, based in
London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
