u a BC-FATHERS-SUICIDE-BOS &LR;      05-01 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHERS-SUICIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS UNDERSTAND DEVOTED FATHER'S SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ Family friends will tell you that William
Stewart was the most devoted of fathers long before his son David
came down with a rare and deadly form of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a carpenter, was the dad who created the coolest tree
house, the biggest sandbox, and the giant yellow model propeller
plane so large it scared the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   He was the dad who brought home bunnies and chicks and even a
goat for his four children to play with.
</P>
<P>
   Once his son David was sick, he became the dad who dropped his
job to become the boy's constant caretaker and companion, to talk
his son to sleep every night, to run to the store for chips in the
middle of the night if David had a craving.
</P>
<P>
   When David lost his battle with cancer and died in his father's
arms, Stewart became the dad who refused to leave his son's side,
even in death.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the 12-year-old passed away at home on Friday,
Stewart, 43, reportedly hanged himself in a friend's backyard on
Cape Cod, leaving a hastily written note for his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he wanted David to be alone,'' said Bob Peredna,
a close family friend. ``This was his way to be with David, and
who's to say that's wrong? Certainly not me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barnstable district attorney's office confirmed it is
investigating Stewart's death as a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just got so close to David that they were one,''
said Peredna. ``I think I can understand why this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Peredna, a builder in Hanover, is a longtime neighbor whose son
was a close friend of David's. The Stewart family moved from
Hanover to Sandwich about a year ago, to be near relatives during
David's illness, Peredna said.
</P>
<P>
   Peredna and his family described Stewart as a quiet, reserved
man who did not often share his emotions. However, they said the
father did not seem depressed. Stewart always clung to signs that
David's condition was improving, they said, rarely entertaining the
possibility that experimental treatments would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was divorced, was on his own raising David and his
three siblings: Talia, 8; Rita, 13; and Duncan, 15. The children
are currently with their mother, Linda Stewart, Mary Peredna said.
The mother has been involved in the children's lives and hopes to
be able to take care of them, said Peredna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he felt the rest of the kids would be taken care of _
it's not as if they would be alone,'' Mary Peredna said. ``I
wouldn't say it was the right thing, but it's almost like a more
relaxing feeling knowing the two of them are together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``David was afraid of dying, and you could see where Bill wanted
to be with him,'' Mary Peredna said. ``It's not like you would ever
see it coming, but you would know Bill wouldn't let David go by
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Peredna's son Michael spoke to David by phone just days before
his death, and visited him on Cape Cod about a month ago. When they
spoke last week, David sounded sad, explaining that he could no
longer walk on his own, Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other family members, William Stewart was an
aggressive advocate for his son's medical care. The state Medicaid
program refused to pay $93,000 for an experimental chemotherapy
regimen that doctors said was David's only hope for survival after
conventional treatments, such as radiation and a bone marrow
transplant, failed.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was able to fly to Seattle and receive the chemotherapy,
thanks to a fund-raising drive that garnered $160,000 from
corporate executives to elementary school children pitching in
their lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Robert J. Nyman, a Hanover Democrat, saw
William Stewart testify before a state Medicaid hearing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I witnessed that man fighting for his son, and we could all
see that he was going to do everything he could to make David
better,'' Nyman said Sunday. ``I guess that fight took its toll on
him as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Center in Seattle told the
family that even with an experimental cancer drug, CMA-676, David's
chances for survival were slim.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart refused to focus on the negative as he gave David
his unwavering attention, Bob and Mary Peredna said, sleeping by
the boy's side every night and encouraging him to get up and play
every morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He devoted himself to the point that he was going to cure
David,'' Bob Peredna said. ``He was going to find a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, just as he was boarding a plane for Seattle, Stewart
said, ``As long as there is a little bit of hope there, I can make
it into all the hope in the world, even if it's just a little bit
of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Pending on Beacon Hill is the ``David Stewart bill,'' which
would set aside $2.5 million a year to fund experimental health
care for children with catastrophic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   David Stewart was a boy who laughed readily, and loved to play
outside, build models with his father, and watch the television
show ``The Simpsons,'' said 10-year-old Michael Peredna. In his
last month of life, the boy cried in pain just from standing up,
Michael said. But David still went outside to play whenever he
could, even though it meant layering on four jackets and wearing a
hospital facemask.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral for both father and son was scheduled for Monday
morning at St. John the Evangelist Church in Pocasset.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart suffered a rare form of childhood cancer called acute
myeloid leukemia. Only 40 percent of victims with this type of
cancer survive, while 70 percent of children with a more common
strain of childhood leukemia survive.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he knew the prognosis, William Stewart may not have
been entirely prepared to deal with his son's death, Peredna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're close to someone and you hear that something bad
might happen, you always say this won't happen to them,'' Peredna
said, ``and when the inevitable happens I think your window of
reality is very narrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
