<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r a BC-FAIRCHILD-FLOWER-POWE     05-01 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-FLOWER-POWER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLES FLEURS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By PATRICIA REYNOSO  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Flowers have long been admired in paintings and verse for their
physical beauty, but they also work their art on the olfactory
senses.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, they've been rediscovered on the beauty scene. Dedicated
sybarites and wishful escapists looking to unwind after a hard day
at the office swear by the scent of blossoms and the curative
effects of petals. Stated simply: Blooms are primo when it comes to
pampering.
</P>
<P>
   Immerse yourself in flowers or their essence and you will truly
be transported. Spa treatments that use flowers to envelop the
senses _ if not literally, then figuratively _ abound.
</P>
<P>
   At the Aqua Spa in Santa Monica, Calif., the aromatherapy
manicure and pedicure start off with a blissful soak in lavender,
rose or geranium oil.
</P>
<P>
   The ``aromatic facial'' at Spa Internazionale at Fisher Island
in Florida features custom-blended oils from plants and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan's cozy and quiet Carapan Urban Spa, many of the
treatments use the spa's new body collection called Plateau, which
contains luxurious oils of lavender, patchouli and bergamot.
</P>
<P>
   For the Plateau Body Massage, for example, Carapan's clients get
to experience the Plateau Body &AMP; Massage Oil.
</P>
<P>
   At Aida Thibiant European Day Spa in Beverly Hills, one of the
most requested body treatments is a stress-melting soak in a 47-jet
hydrotherapy tub with Tahitian Milk Bath, a sumptuous product with
Monoi de Tahiti, a medley of petals from the rare tiare flower
soaked in oils.
</P>
<P>
   Tahitian Milk Bath is also sold at the spa for at-home revelry,
as are several newer products with Monoi de Tahiti, including a
sensuous dry oil spray and exfoliating and moisturizing body scrub.
</P>
<P>
   And if there was ever any doubt that flowers are among the most
luxurious treats in the world, consider that Christian Dior's new
skin-care line, Dior Prestige, features the nectar, or the sap, of
100 kniphofia buds, a flower that blooms on the island of
Madagascar only during June and July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers will transport you to another place,'' says Robert
Isabell, the florist and party planner who launched Perfumes
Isabell, a collection of body products and candles based solely on
flowers. ``They calm and bring great peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As the mastermind behind such lavish bashes as the recent
Costume Institute party at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, and
society weddings including those of Caroline Kennedy and Aerin
Lauder, the subject of flowers is very dear to his heart. Isabell
counts water lilies, tuberose and jasmine among his favorites
because of their intoxicatingly powerful scent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers simply capture all the senses,'' he says. ``I know a
woman who always has fresh ones by her bedside. She treats them
like friends.''
</P>
<P>
   While the physical beauty of flowers has never been in question,
the therapeutic benefits are also impressive _ and well documented
throughout history.
</P>
<P>
   In ancient times, the Romans would spritz dinner guests between
courses with rose water from tiny pipes installed under the table.
</P>
<P>
   Up until the 19th century, rose was the prominent ingredient in
remedies that treated everything from depression to infertility.
</P>
<P>
   In Renaissance Italy, rose water was used for rinsing the hands
and some even drank alcohol-based perfumes as breath fresheners.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers were also commonly used for beauty purposes _ crushed
rose petals are a centuries-old secret for rosy, glowing skin.
</P>
<P>
   Today, technology has taken over most of these tasks, but this
does not mean that flowers should be relegated to the garden. Far
from it. Flowers contribute plenty to the pampering process and
spas and beauty firms are always looking for new ways to exploit
their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Close, owner of the Naturopathica Spa and Holistic
Health Center in East Hampton, N.Y., has built both her day spa and
product line on the premise that botanicals, including flowers, are
a vital ingredient in the quest for beauty and well-being.
</P>
<P>
   One of the line's cult products, a rose-water facial spritz
called Rose Hydrolat, is ideal for sensitive, irritated skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fabulous,'' declares Scarlett Messina, owner of the
Scarlett Beauty Emporium in New Hope, Penn., which also sells
Close's Orange Blossom Hydrolat and Lavender Hydrolat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose is perfect for calming sensitive skin,'' Close says. ``I
recommend it for people with ruddy complexions.''
</P>
<P>
   Her spa is a veritable haven for those seeking natural beauty.
There's even a computer system that explains the benefits of
various floral ingredients and a custom blending bar that allows
customers to spike their favorite shampoo or body lotion with a
specific essential oil.
</P>
<P>
   These oils can be pretty pricy, Close says, but they're worth it
when you consider that approximately 2,000 pounds of rose petals
are needed to make just one pound of essential oil.
</P>
<P>
   If rose appears to be one of the most popular flowers among
beauty aficionados, it's no accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rose is known in the flower kingdom as the queen,'' says
perfumer Sarah Horowitz, whose company, Creative Scentualization,
creates custom fragrances. ``Rose is used in aromatherapy for many
things, including skin replenishing. It's also used as an
aphrodisiac and to open the heart chakra promoting love.''
</P>
<P>
   The perpetually beautiful rose is at the center of other
skin-care products and spa treatments. The popular French treatment
line Guinot has added musk rose oil, which balances the complexion
and works as an anti-inflammatory, to its new Refreshing Cleansing
Milk and Refreshing Toning Lotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Guinot, our philosophy is to coax the skin back to a state
of homeostasis, to an ideal state of health,'' says Remy DeVere,
director of education for Guinot.
</P>
<P>
   Rare Bulgarian rose is the main ingredient in the
ultra-expensive Joy fragrance from Patou. It also features
prominently in new night creams created by Thibiant.
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett's Messina considers the rose soap from the Two Girls
Brand to be the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scents the whole room and creates an experience,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Equinox Spa in Manhattan, a new treatment
called the Yogi Scrub combines rose water and rose oil with yogurt
for maximum exfoliation and softening.
</P>
<P>
   Equinox also uses the Floral Mask from a professional French spa
line called Phalgo that is a mix of white clay, rose and lavender.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers may also be beneficial when ingested. Roses are said to
be higher in vitamin C than citrus fruits.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, people in countries like Pakistan and India have
been drinking flowered teas. (A modern example is the trendy chai
tea that is sold alongside cafe latte at Starbucks. Its main
ingredient: rose.)
</P>
<P>
   Yael Alkalay and Victor Silveira, the founders of a line of
candles and teas called Red Flower, consider flowers a ``life force
that you can smell and breathe,'' adding, ``flowers encourage the
enjoyment of simple experiences in a beautiful way.''
</P>
<P>
   One of their teas features roses from Spain, bilberries and
hibiscus. The other is a lavender tea with rosemary, spearmint and
peppermint. Both varieties are pretty enough to display.
</P>
<P>
   Chamomile, another flower that reigns supreme for its
anti-allergenic properties, is better known as a soothing tea. But
it, too, is being discovered by aestheticians and beauty companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian skin-care line Jurlique is ripe with chamomile,
as is Nectar of the Gods, an Italian collection of hair care
products.
</P>
<P>
   Essentiel Elements, the line of natural spa products, has
created three separate skin-care collections around chamomile,
lavender and geranium.
</P>
<P>
   Chamomile was chosen for its calming effect on inflamed and
irritated skin, lavender for its ability to detoxify and geranium
for its super-hydration abilities.
</P>
<P>
   The star product of the Essentiel Elements skin-care collection
is Intensive, pure essential oil of either chamomile, lavender or
geranium, blended with almond oil. Several drops massaged lightly
on pressure points, namely the temple, behind the ear lobes and on
the bridge of your nose, can do wonders for a weary soul.
</P>
<P>
   Eradicating stress and its irritating symptoms is yet another
benefit of the essential oils of flowers. Lavender and chamomile
are probably the most recognized in this area, but many others are
beneficial as well.
</P>
<P>
   Expensive but potent jasmine has a calming and uplifting effect
on the nervous system, while neroli, or orange blossom oil, helps
with many kinds of stress, including insomnia and panic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   For even more severe cases of malaise, those in the medical
profession have prescribed bergamot essential oil for help with
drug withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a treatment at Manhattan's Paul Labrecque Salon &AMP;
Spa called the ``antidepressant facial.'' Administered with the
Gisele Delorme skin-care line, the active ingredient is petitgrain
oil, a woodier version of neroli that is known to reduce tension
headaches and treat less serious depression and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   It makes perfect sense that flowers would give the skin a boost.
Beautiful blooms, so naturally intoxicating, have been lifting the
psyche since Eve discovered them in the Garden of Eden. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Patricia Reynoso is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
