space and luxury that one couldn't touch in a hotel at twice the
price. Since every rental comes with a kitchen or kitchenette,
dining out is an option, not a requirement.
 &HT;    Rentals are especially ideal for families or couples traveling
together. With four or even six people, the savings are even
greater.
 &HT;    The Parker Company has properties like Il Colombaiolo, in
Montepulciano, Tuscany. This luxurious three-bedroom house sleeps
six and is priced from $1,800 to $2,070 per week, which costs out
from $257 to $296 per night. Split among three couples, it's a
modest amount.
 &HT;    Group rentals also permit travelers to extend their buying
power, not merely save money. Those fabled villas with pools,
tennis courts and vast gardens become a reasonable buy, not a mere
romantic indulgence.
 &HT;    To find a rental, contact an agency by phone or visit their Web
site. When choosing a property, note that location is crucial. For
a city apartment, a quiet residential neighborhood can be a bonus,
especially for the noise-conscious, who may not want a rental on a
main city street. In rural areas, rental cars are essential, and
have to be factored into the overall cost.
 &HT;    Every good rental agent should provide a checklist of amenities
that are included with the rental, from linens to access to a
washer and dryer.
 &HT;    It's important to know how frequently the unit will be cleaned
and whether a deposit is required for the telephone. It's also
essential to have a nearby contact in case a pipe bursts or the
stove won't work, preferably someone who speaks some English.
 &HT;    Note that the minimum rental period is usually one week and that
prime properties in Italy and France should be booked months in
advance of high season.
 &HT;    Shoulder season is usually 20 to 30 percent less, and low season
can offer great value. But don't forget to factor in the weather.
November brings the chilly Mistral wind to Provence, while rural
England is not as delightful when it's cold and rainy.
 &HT;    Here are some major rentals companies.
 &HT;     At Home in France  (P.O. Box 643, Ashland, Ore., 97520;
541-488-9467; www.athomeinfrance.com/ahif.htm) focuses exclusively
on France.
 &HT;     The French Experience  (370 Lexington Ave., Suite 812, New
York, N.Y. 10017; 212-986-3800; www.frenchexperience.com) has
hundreds of ``gites,'' rural French vacation homes, as well as
Paris apartments.
 &HT;     Homes Away  (34 Park Road, Toronto M4W 2N4, Ontario, Canada;
800-374-6637; www.homesaway.com) offers a handful of carefully
chosen properties in Italy and France.
 &HT;     Italian Villas  (8 Knight St., Suite 205, Norwalk, Conn. 06851;
800-700-9549; www.italianvillas.com) specializes in Italy.
 &HT;     The Landmark Trust  (707 Kipling Road, Dummerston, Vt. 05301;
802-254-6868) offers rentals in restored historic residences
throughout Britain.
 &HT;     Paris Sejours Reservations  (875 N. Michigan Ave., Suite 3214,
Chicago, Ill. 60611; 800-582-7274; www.psryourhomeinParis.com) is a
specialist in Paris apartments.
 &HT;     The Parker Company  (Seaport Landing, 152 Lynnway, Lynn, Mass.
01902; 800-280-2811; www.parkercompany.com) is devoted exclusively
to Italy.
 &HT;     Vacation Rentals by Owner  (PMB308, 4255 South Buckley Road,
Aurora, Colo. 80013; http://vrbo.com/) is an Internet rental site
that brings independent homeowners together from around the world.
They have extensive European listings, from Swiss apartments to
Italian villas.
 &HT;     WIMCO  (P.O. Box 1461, Newport, R.I. 02840; 800-932-3222;
www.wimcovillas.com) has rentals in England, Scotland, France,
Italy and Ireland.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
