<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2275 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF &LR;      05-01 2275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE WEST WAS FILMED 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By KATHRYN JONES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monument Valley has been used as a backdrop for so many movies,
car commercials and magazine advertisements that its rock
cathedrals, craggy spires and wind-sculptured buttes are
immediately recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the credit goes to the director John Ford, who filmed
the 1939 western classic ``Stagecoach'' there and returned to make
seven more westerns.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, I watched so many of those old movies that Monument
Valley came to symbolize the West for me. The valley's stark
landscape, with its looming red-rock monoliths, some of which rise
1,000 feet from the desert floor, haunted me for years. They looked
like giant pawns scattered on an ancient god's chessboard.
</P>
<P>
   I had to see the place, which I did for the first time in the
mid-1980s. And then I had to go back.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, I had viewed Monument Valley from a distance.
My vacations in the Four Corners have tended to be jampacked:
Durango, Colo., one day, then Mesa Verde National Park, then Canyon
de Chelly. There's so much to see and do in the area that my
husband, Dan Malone, and I would make a quick run in our car to
Monument Valley's edge, take some photographs of the famous
outlines of spires and buttes and head on to other destinations in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Those small tastes, though, left me hungry to see more. In early
March, we finally made a sojourn into the valley's heart for a
two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   Monument Valley, on Navajo land, straddles the Utah-Arizona
border. Until recent decades, the 2,000-square-mile area was hard
on travelers, with mostly dirt roads and rough accommodations.
Goulding's Lodge, where Harry Goulding, a Federal sheep inspector
from Mancos, Colo., and his wife, Leone (nicknamed Mike), settled
in 1923 on the Utah side of the border, was originally just a
trading post with a spectacular view over the valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Gouldings and their Navajo neighbors suffered terrible
hardships, including a lack of food and cash during the Great
Depression. So when the Gouldings heard in 1938 that Ford was about
to make a new western, they went to Hollywood to persuade him to
shoot ``Stagecoach'' in Monument Valley and bring jobs to the
impoverished area. They were successful, and Goulding's became the
headquarters for Ford's films. At the time, it had the only
accommodations in the valley _ tents.
</P>
<P>
   Dan and I had originally planned to stay in the largest town
close to Monument Valley _ Kayenta, Ariz., 24 miles south _ until a
friend in Durango told us that Goulding's had expanded into a
full-fledged motel and lodge with modern accommodations. We changed
our plans and had no trouble getting a room in the early spring
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   One begins to appreciate Monument Valley's remoteness when
planning how to get there. We started our trip in Durango, 188
miles to the northeast, and drove a leisurely five hours to the
valley, stopping to take photographs and investigate shops selling
silver and turquoise jewelry and kitschy souvenirs in the scattered
small towns along the way.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in Monument Valley on a blustery afternoon. A light
snow dusted the russet rocks. The spires shimmered in golden
sunlight and cast long dark shadows on the red earth.
</P>
<P>
   Goulding's Lodge is about a mile off U.S. Highway 163, near the
turnoff to the Navajo Tribal Park headquarters, the official
entrance to Monument Valley. Situated at the base of towering
sandstone cliffs, the long, two-storied coral adobe motel faces
east, toward the formations. In the off-season, it was quiet, with
only a few guests, many of them Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   The original two-story stone trading post has been turned into a
museum that gives a feel for the history of Goulding's. The cabin
occupied by John Wayne's character in Ford's ``She Wore a Yellow
Ribbon'' (1949), Capt. Nathan Brittles, has been preserved, too,
behind the old post. There's also a campground, a convenience store
and a gas station adjacent to the motel.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge was expanded and modernized in 1985; it is still the
only large accommodation in Monument Valley. Our room (like all of
Goulding's 62 rooms) opened onto a small balcony, overlooking
formations about five miles away with colorful names like Eagle
Mesa, the Stagecoach and the Bear and the Rabbit. It had a
king-size bed, a television with VCR, a small refrigerator and a
coffeemaker. The bedroom was decorated in the same desert hues we
saw through the sliding glass doors to the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   That evening we dined on grilled trout at the lodge's Stagecoach
Dining Room, which has a long picture window facing the valley.
It's staffed by Navajos and decorated with pottery and native
weavings.
</P>
<P>
   The food is basic _ steaks, hamburgers, chicken, a salad bar _
but quite good. Navajo tacos _ shredded beef, chilies, lettuce,
tomatoes and cheese in a big round piece of fry bread (like a puffy
tortilla) _ are a specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Monument Valley is a sacred place to the Navajo Nation, the
largest American Indian tribe, with about 155,000 members and a
reservation of almost 16 million acres, including the Four Corners
area, larger than West Virginia. The Navajo are believed to be
descendants of Athabascan-speaking tribes from the Pacific Coast,
Canada and Alaska that arrived in the Southwest at least 1,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known exactly when the Navajo first settled Monument
Valley. Others came before them: Anasazi sites and ruins in the
valley date from before 1300. Navajos have lived in the valley for
generations, herding sheep and livestock and raising small crops.
</P>
<P>
   Religious ceremonies and practices are an essential part of
traditional Navajo daily life. There is no worship center: the
people consider the world around them holy.
</P>
<P>
   That belief is reflected in the names the Navajos gave to
Monument Valley's formations. One wind-sculptured monolith is
called the Yei-Bi-Chei, an important holy figure among Navajos. Cly
Butte is named for a chieftain buried there with his worldly
possessions, including his cattle, goats, sheep, horse and saddle.
</P>
<P>
   There's even the core of an ancient volcano that the Navajo call
Agathlan, renamed El Capitan by Kit Carson, the cavalry soldier who
starting in 1863 waged what some historians call a ``war of
extermination'' against the Navajo people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1864, 8,000 Navajo were marched across New Mexico to Fort
Sumner on the New Mexico-Texas border and imprisoned for four
years; the survivors _ about 25 percent are believed to have died
on the march _ were allowed to occupy part of their old homeland
under a treaty signed in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1940s, when Hollywood discovered Monument Valley and
tourism started to become a business, Monument Valley was
primitive, largely empty and a difficult place for living or
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   While the area is more accessible now in terms of paved roads
and comfortable accommodations, a non-Navajo faces restrictions
seeing it. There are basically two options: going on a guided tour
or driving a self-guided 17-mile loop that starts at the Tribal
Park headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Goulding's and several independent Navajo guides offer daylong
or half-day tours in open-air sightseeing vehicles, in
four-wheel-drive jeeps or on horseback. Some tours take visitors to
Mystery Valley, a section of southwestern Monument Valley with
natural arches, pictographs and Anasazi ruins.
</P>
<P>
   We prefer to explore places on our own and at our own pace, so
we decided to take the self-guided drive. After paying $2.50 each
at the park entrance (the fee has since gone to $3) and receiving a
map of the loop, we headed off on the rutted dirt road.
</P>
<P>
   We had rented a Ford Explorer, but the road was dry and not so
bumpy that we needed to engage the four-wheel-drive (although it
might be needed if the roads were muddy).
</P>
<P>
   Visitors aren't allowed to go beyond marked roads and designated
points for viewing the landscape, except with a Navajo guide, to
protect tribal burial grounds and holy places. There are no hiking
trails, although hiking can be arranged with a guide.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was the off-season, we passed only a few vehicles as we
wound around the mesas and buttes. Some of the formations have been
photographed so often that they seemed familiar _ like the Mittens,
two eroded buttes with thumblike spires.
</P>
<P>
   Other monoliths and pillars sport colorful and descriptive
names, too, like Castle Butte, the Sitting Hen, the Three Sisters
(a trio of spires standing close together, almost gossiping;
they're said to resemble three Catholic nuns in habits) or the Big
W, Totem Pole and the King on his Throne.
</P>
<P>
   Driving through the desert landscape with its sculptured rocks
was a sharp contrast to our trip from Durango through the snowy,
heavily forested Rocky Mountains. Yet Monument Valley was formed
from the Rockies, or, more specifically, their detritus.
</P>
<P>
   As material eroded from the Rockies millions of years ago, it
was deposited in layers and cemented into sandstone. Underground
pressure produced an uplift that made the surface bulge and crack,
forming canyons. Over millenniums, wind and water carved the hard
and soft rock into the striated orange and red natural wonders that
seem to pop out of the desert floor.
</P>
<P>
   We got out at several points and walked around a bit at the
designated viewing points. One of the most dramatic views came near
the end of the trip, at a place called the North Window.
</P>
<P>
   The loop drive consumed several hours because we stopped at all
11 scenic viewing points. At John Ford's Point, we parked in a lot
where several Navajo families had set up tables to sell silver and
turquoise jewelry. We followed a short trail to a finger of rock
jutting into an abyss.
</P>
<P>
   The director supposedly liked to film from this vantage point
with its sweeping views of the valley. On the day we visited, the
cameras were still rolling at John Ford's Point _ only now they
were video cameras held by French and German tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But to visit Monument Valley is also to realize that the
big-screen images and Technicolor can't do the place justice. It
takes the human eye to capture the 360-degree views and record the
way the valley changes color during the day, turning from lavender
and pink at dawn to gold and terra cotta in the late afternoon. Or
the way the monoliths cast long, ghostly shadows at dusk and become
otherworldly silhouettes against the blue twilight.
</P>
<P>
   For a place that has remained the same for so long, Monument
Valley remakes itself with every take.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR A SACRED LAND, AND NOT BECAUSE JOHN WAYNE SLEPT HERE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The entrance to Monument Valley is at the Monument Valley Navajo
Tribal Park headquarters, 22 miles north of Kayenta, Ariz., off
Route 163 just over the border in Utah. It is open daily except
Christmas Day, 8 a.m. to 7 p.m., till 5 p.m. in winter; (435)
727-3287.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, low temperatures are generally in the 20's and 30s,
with highs of 50s and 60s. In summer, temperatures get into the
80's and fall near 60 at night. There are few trees in Monument
Valley and the sun is intense reflecting off the rock and sand, so
protection is important.
 &UR; GETTING THERE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The closest airport to Monument Valley served by major airlines
is in Phoenix, 310 miles away. America West, (800) 235-9292, and
United Airlines, (800) 241-6522, serve Durango, Colo., 190 miles
away. Major car rental agencies operate at both airports.
 &UR; HOW TO SEE THE SIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It costs $3 a person to drive the 17-mile loop road for a
self-guided tour. The visitors center at the tribal park has a
complete list of tour operators and road conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Goulding's Lodge offers tours lasting two and a half hours to a
full day with Navajo guides, costing $25.50 to $60.50. Information:
(800) 874-0902, or www.gouldings.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sacred Monument Tours leads guided hiking tours, as well as
tours by jeep or horseback; a four-hour jeep tour is $45, a
full-day tour $100. Group rates available; (435) 727-3218 or
www.sacredtoursmv.com.
</P>
<P>
   Scenic Airlines, (800) 634-6801, flies from Las Vegas daily at 6
a.m. to Monument Valley for a tour and lunch, with a stop at the
Grand Canyon. Tickets are $423.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kathryn Jones, who lives in Fort Worth, is working on a
biography of the late western actor and cowboy Ben Johnson.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
