</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALING-AFRICA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICA'S TWIN SCOURGES: AIDS AND MALARIA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In the rich world, AIDS, though still incurable, seldom nowadays
means imminent death, and malaria kills hardly anyone. In the poor
world, however, AIDS kills about 2.5 million people a year and
malaria another 2 million, maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the deaths are in Africa, and they are increasing in
number. In the wars against these two pestilences, the bugs are
winning.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS and malaria are different diseases, with different causes,
but they have this in common: they cause dreadful human misery,
with huge economic costs.
</P>
<P>
   And they would be attacked with far greater energy and
effectiveness if most of their victims lived not in Africa but in
Europe or America.
</P>
<P>
   Few Africans can afford the expensive medicines that mitigate
the effects of AIDS; and few drug companies will spend the
quantities of money necessary to develop a malaria vaccine if most
of the people likely to want it are too poor to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed is a market for the medicines that can already be
produced, and the certainty that it will still exist if and when
new drugs or vaccines are discovered.
</P>
<P>
   This idea _ the creation of a market _ is not new. Jeffrey
Sachs, of Harvard University, suggested it in The Economist last
August, and it has won praise from, among others, U.S. President
Bill Clinton and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks largely to the World Health Organization, now at last
playing a useful role under the leadership of Gro Harlem
Brundtland, a Global Alliance for Vaccine and Immunization has been
set up, with backing, financial as well as verbal, from
philanthropists such as Microsoft's Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is welcome. The market, however, remains an idea,
not a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs argues that, were the rich countries to provide $1 billion
a year for an indefinite period, they could help to pay not just
for drugs, insecticides and bed nets _ one of the most effective
means of combating malaria _ but also for a fund that could be
drawn upon once any malaria vaccine were developed.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits in saving lives would be huge. So would the
economic gains.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term costs of malaria, Sachs believes, are greater
than the 1 percent or so of GDP traditionally attributed to the
disease, and the compounded costs over 15 years are therefore
nearly 20 percent. An annual flow of $1 billion in anti-malaria aid
would, he says, benefit sub-Saharan Africa's combined GDP by $3
billion-12 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Two changes are needed. One is the recognition by donors that
this would be money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in Abuja, Nigeria this week, there were signs that
the World Bank might indeed find $300 million-500 million a year to
fight malaria, which would at least be a start. But even that would
achieve little if it were not spent in the right way.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the second needed change: a readiness by African
governments to agree on programs regionally, not state by state,
and a willingness to pursue tried-and-tested methods that work.
</P>
<P>
   Here the evidence is mixed. Some countries, such as Senegal and
Uganda, have put in place conventional anti-AIDS programs to
dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet South Africa _ a late-comer to the war on AIDS, with the
result that it has more new infections than any other country _
remains skeptical about the treatments that have been used
successfully elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Only this month President Thabo Mbeki wrote to Clinton and other
western leaders to defend his willingness to contemplate heterodox
theories about AIDS and to seek African solutions to a ``uniquely
African catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the mood in Abuja this week was very different. No
one got a bigger round of applause there than Ghana's president,
Jerry Rawlings, when he reminded delegates that public health was
once taken far more seriously in Africa; indeed, in colonial days,
householders would be liable to fines if they allowed pools of
water to collect in which malaria-carrying mosquitoes could breed.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to bring back colonialism _ but everyone should
want to see AIDS and malaria rendered no more lethal in Africa than
in richer places. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
