<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BUSH-BLEEDING-HEART-E     05-01 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BLEEDING-HEART-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST HOW `COMPASSIONATE' IS GEORGE W.?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 175-word trim; 1,075 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Just how compassionate can a Republican get before he has to
leave the GOP and join Vegans for Global Justice? George W. Bush
seems bent on finding out.
</P>
<P>
   One moment he is holding a get-to-know-you meeting with a bunch
of gay Republicans. The next he is holding forth on education or
the environment or some other squishy-squashy crowd-pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   It is enough to make a red-blooded conservative choke on his
spotted-owl drumstick.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago compassionate conservatism lay slaughtered on
that great red carpet at Bob Jones University. Now it is enjoying a
second life.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not only insistently telling Americans that he is a
``uniter, not a divider.'' He has also produced a wodge of policy
statements and five-year plans, a concept for which he has more
enthusiasm than anyone since Uncle Joe Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about housing for the poor? Bush has a five-year plan to
encourage private developers to build in poor areas. Worried about
the future of Medicare? There's a five-year plan for that too.
</P>
<P>
   This compassion offensive is discombobulating people at both
ends of the political spectrum. Bush is sidelining the sort of
Republicans who seized control of Congress in 1994. And he is
challenging the Democrats on their home turf.
</P>
<P>
   He is not just willing to talk about subjects _ notably
education _ that escaped Bob Dole's attention in 1996. He is even
willing to sanction the expansion of the dreaded federal government
if that helps America's poor.
</P>
<P>
   So far it is paying off. Several opinion polls put Bush back
ahead of Al Gore, a position he lost when he moved to the right
during the primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One poll even puts him in front of Gore on the core Democratic
subject of education. And the Los Angeles Times reckons he is
beating Gore among women by 41 percent to 39 percent (Dole lost the
fairer sex by a landslide).
</P>
<P>
   Can Bush sustain his compassionate image? The Democrats will
keep replaying the film of Bush embracing Bob Jones III until it is
burned into America's subconscious. And, even if he holds steady,
can he really drag the party of Rush Limbaugh back to the left
without causing a revolt?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the first question is mixed. Bush has time on his
side: when America goes to the polls in November, it will be nine
months since that foolish embrace on the red carpet.
</P>
<P>
   He also has his less-than-weighty-intellectual reputation:
trying to paint the jovial frat boy as a dour moral conservative
could backfire, just as it did with the smiling Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   But against that you have to reckon two things. The first is the
country's ingrained suspicion of Republicans when it comes to
social reform, particularly when they offer to cut taxes by $483
billion over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The polls still show Bush trailing Gore on most social issues,
and Gore is blasting his rival's ``casino economics'' on the
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   The second is the fact that Bush is governor of the state that
happens to be the country's pollution and execution pacesetter.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate Bush is likely to spend almost as much time dealing
with ``bigot eruptions'' as Candidate Clinton once spent dealing
with ``bimbo eruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks he has been embarrassed by a Texan police chief
who referred to blacks as ``porch monkeys'' and a health chief who
despaired about Hispanics' proficiency at breeding.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is on safer ground when it comes to avoiding the
intra-Republican feuding that plagued his father in 1992 and Bob
Dole four years later. So far, conservative leaders have bitten
their tongues as he has fudged on abortion and strayed on federal
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made it clear all along that he is a middle-of-the-road
conservative rather than a right-wing messiah. And the fact that
his party is desperate for the White House after eight years
outside it helps him to redefine conservatism as he sees fit.
</P>
<P>
   But what if Bush sees fit to redefine conservatism as just
another sort of Clintonism? The Republican Party might be in danger
of making itself electable only at the price of losing its soul.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities between compassionate conservatism and
Clintonism are indeed remarkable. Clinton talked tough on
``Republican'' subjects such as defense and law-and-order. Bush is
talking compassionately on ``Democratic'' subjects like education
and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton burnished his image as a moderate by denouncing the far
left. Bush waggles his eyebrows at the right-wing cavemen of
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been so successfully vague about abortion that
abortion-rights advocates have had to remind people that he is a
right-to-life man.
</P>
<P>
   He has also shown Clintonian zeal in borrowing ideas from his
opponents. His suggestions on a whole range of social issues _ from
tax credits to help the uninsured buy medical coverage to
individual retirement accounts for workers _ have been lifted
straight from the Progressive Policy Institute, a think-tank that
helped Clinton's New Democrats rise to power. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   But it is necessary to be careful about pushing the comparison
too far: there is both less and more to compassionate conservatism
than there is to Clintonism.
</P>
<P>
   There is less because Bush has been pretty meek in taking on
entrenched interests. There was no Sister Souljah moment over the
Confederate flag or the Miami Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is so unreconstructed on the subject of guns that he
supported a measure to legalize the carrying of concealed handguns
in his state.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also more, because compassionate conservatism is
not quite the self-contradiction it sounds. The New Democrats have
had to fight bare-knuckled against a tradition in their party that
worships big government and bureaucratic planning.
</P>
<P>
   But compassionate conservatism reaches back to one of the oldest
conservative principles in the book: the belief that voluntary
organizations _ what Edmund Burke called ``the little battalions''
_ are often better at solving social problems than distant
bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   It tries to use markets rather than governments to solve these
problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,075) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bush is an imperfect carrier of the message, of course, and all
his schemes may yet turn to dust. But at least he is trying to
fashion a conservative case on social policy rather than losing the
argument by default, as his two unfortunate predecessors did. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
