<HEADER>
A2321 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-PRI-NO-SHOO-IN-MEXICO     05-01 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRI-NO-SHOO-IN-MEXICO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S PRESIDENTIAL RACE GETS `MUY CALIENTE' AFTER ALL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note July 2 election, Mexico)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 1,050-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The vote is not until July 2, but as the campaign
for Mexico's presidential election got under way in earnest this
week, two things confirmed that it will be unlike any other in the
country's history.
</P>
<P>
   The first was an opinion poll showing that Vicente Fox, the
candidate of the opposition National Action Party (PAN), seems
close to drawing level with Francisco Labastida of the long-ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
   The second was a television debate between the candidates in
which it was Labastida, not Fox, who behaved like the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Routine stuff for democracies, even Latin American ones. But not
for Mexico, where the PRI has held power since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Mexican campaigns were lengthy processions. Since
the outcome was rarely in doubt, their purpose was to introduce the
outgoing president's chosen successor to the PRI's grass roots and
to the country.
</P>
<P>
   When all else failed, the PRI could rely on a government-run
electoral system: many Mexicans believe that in 1988 fraud secured
victory for Carlos Salinas against Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a left-wing
PRI dissident.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas's successor, Ernesto Zedillo, won an undisputed victory
in 1994, but the size of his vote may have been inflated.
</P>
<P>
   Today, things are different. For a start, the PRI has chosen its
candidate openly, in a primary. Secondly, thanks to a reform put in
place by Zedillo, the Federal Electoral Institute (IFE) is now
autonomous.
</P>
<P>
   Ballot papers will have anti-forgery features, and voting booths
will have proper privacy. Results from each ballot box _ verified
by all the parties' representatives at the polling station _ will
go straight to the Internet for all to see, to prevent the
``electoral alchemy'' of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, back in November, the outcome of this year's election
seemed the familiar foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, Zedillo's grey former interior minister, stood at 50
percent in the polls. The opposition vote was split between the
PAN's Fox, a feisty campaigner who is less conservative than his
party, and Cardenas, making his third bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But Labastida's rating, boosted by the publicity surrounding the
PRI's primary last November, proved to be temporary. Though
individual polls vary, the trend has been clear.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has slowly drooped; Fox has risen; and Cardenas has
stayed a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published this week by Reforma, a Mexico City newspaper,
showed Fox within three points of Labastida. That underlines Fox's
success in turning the campaign into a referendum on the PRI's
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Little divides the two front-runners on the big issues of
policy, such as education, crime and poverty. Fox's macroeconomic
goals are more ambitious, but also less credible.
</P>
<P>
   Both men play the same nationalist tune, Fox having hastily
retreated from a proposal to privatize Pemex, the creaking state
oil monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fox, a former Coca-Cola manager, portrays himself as
the man to end a corrupt system. He promises a government of
national unity, to complete the transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's droop has forced him to indulge in some conventional
electioneering. Hitherto, he has played on the voters' fear of the
unknown after seven decades of one-party rule.
</P>
<P>
   But in the televised debate on April he awkwardly tried to
present himself as standing both for stability and for change. He
criticised Fox's vulgarity, and his habit of resorting to personal
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The towering Fox has poked fun at his opponent by calling him el
chaparrito (shorty) and la vestida (the drag queen). He could drop
such epithets, Fox replied, ``but you and yours will never stop
being devious, bad governors, and corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant telephone polls showed that Fox ``won'' the debate.
However, such polls tend to reflect the views of the better-off,
whereas the PRI has the edge among poor and rural voters.
</P>
<P>
   A second debate due next month, this one uncluttered by minor
candidates, may help Fox more. Many voters remain undecided. Some
polls indicate that most of those who have made a choice this year
have plumped for the PAN.
</P>
<P>
   But several factors still help the PRI. Labastida can play up
the government's recent achievements; the PAN has no record except
those of a few state governors.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Labastida, Mexico's steady economic growth _ 5
percent a year, on average, since 1996 _ is at last starting to put
cash in voters' pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Real wages have been rising since late last year, though they
are still below their level before 1994's peso crash.
</P>
<P>
   A second advantage is media coverage. This is fairer than in
previous elections. According to IFE's monitoring of television and
radio news, all three leading candidates get roughly equal
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   But Mund Opinion Services, a polling company, which did its own
independent monitoring in February, found that Labastida got about
four times as much news coverage as his opponents that month on TV
Azteca, one of the two biggest television stations, and in general
was more favorably portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party's other advantage is more nefarious.
Traditionally, it has co-opted voters through its intricate
grass-roots network, using a mixture of gifts and threats.
</P>
<P>
   The government's anti-poverty and agricultural-subsidy programs,
which involve small payments to millions of people, lend themselves
to subtle pressure: PRI officials in some districts have already
been accused of threatening to withhold payments to anyone who
votes for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The IFE is encouraging voters to denounce such tricks. But it
cannot do much: illegally pressing voters is a matter for the
courts, not the IFE.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how many cases of voter coercion have been
denounced to the attorney-general's office, investigated, tried and
convicted in the past three years?'' asks Juan Molinar, one of the
IFE's nine councillors. He answers his own question by putting his
thumb and forefinger together in a big round 0.
</P>
<P>
   A study of local elections in Tlaxcala state last year estimated
that voter coercion, of one kind or another, had inflated the PRI's
vote by 3-5 percent. Fox has claimed that he will not accept defeat
with a margin of less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, he might be more flexible. But a truly close result
would certainly be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Much is at stake for Mexico's incipient democracy in the next
two months. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
