<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2328 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-NISSAN-XTERRA-HN     05-01 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-NISSAN-XTERRA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NISSAN RACES AHEAD OF SUV COMPETITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good luck finding one.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can, and the dealer isn't adding several thousand
dollars to the sticker as some California dealers have, then you
might find that the all-new Nissan Xterra sport-utility vehicle is
a real bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced last spring, the Xterra is about to enter its second
year of production, and sales continue to be brisk _ beyond plant
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   I know that the Xterra's affordable price is driving the
majority of sales, but there is more to this new SUV.
</P>
<P>
   And for Nissan dealers, the Xterra is a godsend. Beleaguered
dealers have seen their sales slide for the past several years as
Nissan fell on hard times and failed to roll out interesting new
vehicles. Now, though, they are having to take orders for the
Xterra and explain to customers that they must wait their turn to
get one.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like just yesterday that Nissan dealers were having a
hard time getting anyone into their showrooms, even though there
was a good (if not great) lineup of vehicles to choose from. That
has changed too, as Nissan has introduced a variety of outstanding
new vehicles in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Many prospective customers who don't buy the SUV are turning to
the other new products, including the excellent Maxima and Altima
sedans, the Frontier Crew Cab pickup and, now arriving, the 2001
Pathfinder sport-utility.
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't afford a Pathfinder or one of its
competitors, such as the Toyota 4Runner and Ford Explorer, the
Xterra is a great choice, with prices under $18,000 for a basic
two-wheel-drive model.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the chassis of the Frontier compact pickup, the Xterra
combines the roominess of a midsize sport-utility with the prices
you would pay for one of those little toys, such as the Toyota RAV4
or Honda CRV.
</P>
<P>
   And let me tell you from my experience driving these SUVs on-
and off-road that there is no comparison. The four-wheel-drive
Xterra is a true go-anywhere, do-anything vehicle, rugged enough
for California's Rubicon Trail and refined enough to drive to
suburban soccer practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Xterra isn't short on space, either. It is the same length
as the Pathfinder, Explorer and Mitsubishi Montero Sport and longer
than the Jeep Cherokee, Isuzu Rodeo/Honda Passport and Chevrolet
Blazer/GMC Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   And even the stripped-down model really isn't stripped. It's so
well-equipped that many of us could live with it if we didn't need
four-wheel drive for serious off-roading.
</P>
<P>
   The base two-wheel-drive XE model, complete with
air-conditioning, antilock brakes and a nice AM/FM/cassette audio
system, lists for just $17,349 with a 143-horsepower, 2.4-liter
four-cylinder engine (with five-speed manual transmission), or
$18,499 with the same 170-horsepower, 3.3-liter V-6 that comes in
the Pathfinder and Infiniti QX4, Nissan's luxury SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you can buy a stripped-down Jeep Cherokee four-door with
four-cylinder engine for about the same price, and a base
four-cylinder Isuzu Rodeo is configured about the same way as the
base Xterra for just over $18,000. But the Cherokee doesn't have
the best reputation for reliability and longevity, and the Rodeo's
price quickly escalates to more than $21,000 when you upgrade to a
V-6 engine. The comparable Xterra V-6 model is nearly $3,000 less.
</P>
<P>
   If you do need four-wheel drive _ and I heartily recommend it if
you plan to have some fun off the beaten track _ prices start at
just $20,499.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry that you're getting something cheap here. This is no
$17,000 Kia Sportage. It's a Nissan, and it is built tough and
solid. Its muscular styling turns heads everywhere it goes, and it
comes with a variety of options that let consumers tailor it to a
lot of different needs, such as carrying mountain bikes, ski
equipment or kayaks. It even has a first-aid kit built into the
rear door.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you doll one of these up with lots of extras, it's a
bargain when compared with a similarly priced Explorer or
Pathfinder. The completely loaded two-wheel-drive model, the SE,
lists for just $23,549 with automatic transmission, and the same
vehicle in four-wheel drive is priced at $25,549. You would pay
more than $30,000 for the Explorer, Pathfinder, 4Runner and others
in this class.
</P>
<P>
   We tested one of the high-end models, the SE-V6 four-wheel-drive
version (base price $25,549 plus $520 transportation), and it came
with only one option, floor mats for $79. Total sticker was a very
reasonable $26,148 (including transportation).
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was lacking. Ours came with the V-6 engine,
four-speed automatic transmission, four-wheel antilock brakes,
air-conditioning, power steering/windows/mirrors/door locks,
limited-slip differential, four-wheel drive with automatic locking
front hubs, tubular roof rack with removable gear basket, flip-up
sun roof, premium AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc stereo with six
speakers, cruise control, leather-wrapped tilt steering wheel, and
lots more.
</P>
<P>
   You will appreciate the way Nissan has configured all of the
Xterras for rugged use. Every model _ even the two-wheel-drives _
has underbody skid plates to protect the transmission, oil pan and
fuel tank. The two-wheel-drive models have even higher ground
clearance than the four-by-fours _ well over nine inches in the
uplevel SE model and 8.7 inches in the base version.
</P>
<P>
   Why call it Xterra? The name was chosen to ``reinforce the
connection to Earth (terrain) and the adventurous lifestyle of its
target buyers,'' Nissan says.
</P>
<P>
   The Xterra is aimed at people with active lifestyles. Those of
you with kids who play soccer and such will like the ample cargo
space. The cargo area behind the rear seat holds more than that of
most of the competition, and among the options are mountain-bike
racks for inside the car and the roof rack that came on our test
vehicle, complete with a special removable basket that holds up to
30 pounds of wet or dirty gear under a protective net.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, there are bucket seats with a center console, complete
with functional cup holders. The rear seat is stadium style, which
means it rises above the front seats so rear passengers have a
clear view ahead. The overall design and interior seating
arrangement are similar to those of the $38,000-plus Land Rover
Discovery II.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the V-6 model with automatic
transmission are 15 mpg in the city and 19 mpg on the highway. The
tank holds 19.4 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
