<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2330 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-4-DOOR-PICKUPS-H     05-01 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-4-DOOR-PICKUPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRUCK MAKERS COMPETE TO ADD MORE SEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBER WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Four real doors. No real competition.''
</P>
<P>
   You might have seen that statement on billboards advertising
Nissan's new Frontier Crew-Cab pickup.
</P>
<P>
   And for a while, the statement was true.
</P>
<P>
   But in the auto world, like many other highly competitive
industries, exclusivity can be a fleeting thing.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan introduced the Frontier Crew-Cab at the Los Angeles Auto
Show in January 1999, and the truck went on sale in late spring '99
as a 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first compact pickup to offer a real bench seat in
the rear, with normal-size doors for the rear-seat passengers to
use _ one on each side of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the best we had seen from the compact segment were
the three-door models that most brands have been offering the past
three or four years. But the third door offered on some of the
extended-cab compacts is narrower than a real door, and opens to
the rear, like the suicide doors on older Lincoln Continentals.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner had Nissan rolled out the Frontier Crew-Cab, and
paid for a zillion of those billboards, than DaimlerChrysler
introduced the Dakota Quad Cab, its own version of the compact
pickup with four _ count 'em, four _ real doors. The Dakota Quad
Cab went on sale in December as a 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be left behind in the Frontier and Dakota's dust,
Chevrolet and GMC Trucks introduced their new crew-cab compact
pickups, the S-10 and Sonoma, respectively, at the Chicago Auto
Show in February. These two new trucks will go on sale late this
year as 2001 models, and they will have four real doors, too.
</P>
<P>
   For now, consumers who want a big back seat and four regular
doors in a compact pickup must choose between the Dakota and the
Frontier, and it is a tough choice to make. Both are outstanding
products, and both have their own lists of attributes.
</P>
<P>
   What they have in common is a real back seat, with normal doors
that allow for easy entry and exit.
</P>
<P>
   In some pickups, adding the little third door meant you lost one
of the tiny jump seats in the extended area of the cab, because
those jump seats fold down from the side of the cab. The door left
no place to put a jump seat.
</P>
<P>
   Many people buy compact pickups because of their low prices and
versatility. It's often cheaper to buy a small pickup than a
compact car, and for a lot of consumers, the compact pickup offered
a chance to buy an affordable new vehicle. First-time car buyers
have flocked to the compact truck just for that reason, and many of
them had no real need for a truly usable back seat _ they were
either single or young married couples with no children.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, of course, that children do come along, and
people who found themselves with a small truck with no room for the
kids had to trade up to a bigger truck or a traditional car,
sport-utility or minivan.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan solved that problem by becoming the first to offer a
compact pickup with a real back seat, large enough even to haul big
kids or adults around (those jump seats in the extended-cab
compacts never were intended for adults).
</P>
<P>
   But if roominess and power are your top priorities, the Dakota
Quad Cab offers the most space and the most horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   The Dakota's wide-opening rear doors have full roll-down
windows, and the seating area offers more shoulder and hip room
than the Frontier or the new Chevy/GMC models.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dakota is offered with the broadest range of engine
choices in its class. They include the standard 3.9-liter V-6
Magnum with 175 horsepower and 225 foot-pounds of torque, and two
optional V-8 engines. The 4.7-liter Magnum V-8 is rated at 235
horsepower and 285 foot-pounds of torque. For even more power, a
5.9-liter Magnum V-8 has 245 horsepower and a whopping 335
foot-pounds of torque. This is the most powerful engine in the
compact class.
</P>
<P>
   Some people claim that the Dakota really is in a class by
itself, too large to be a compact and too small to be considered
full-size. Some of DaimlerChrysler's own advertising touts that
idea, calling the Dakota a midsize pickup. But the company also
refers to the Dakota as a compact in ads comparing it with the
Frontier and others in the compact segment.
</P>
<P>
   Base price of the four-wheel-drive Dakota Quad Cab is $21,615
(plus $520 transportation), which takes it out of the realm of the
affordable compact, however. We drove one whose sticker topped out
at $28,010, which included the 5.9-liter Magnum V-8. The
two-wheel-drive models start at $18,970 (plus transportation).
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the Frontier Crew Cab, which comes only with a
170-horsepower V-6 engine, begin at $17,290 (plus $520
transportation) for the two-wheel-drive model and $19,890 (plus
transportation) for the four-wheel-drive version.
</P>
<P>
   The Dakota Quad Cab comes in two-wheel drive or a choice of
part-time or full-time four-wheel-drive models. Dakota's full-time
four-wheel drive system delivers power to all four wheels for
maximum traction in dry or wet conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we built the Dakota Quad Cab, we were already working
with the underpinnings of a best-in-class compact truck,'' said
John Felice, vice president for truck-platform engineering at
DaimlerChrysler. ``But because Quad Cab will appeal to a wider
range of buyers than conventional trucks, including many first-time
truck buyers, we wanted to make sure it had the performance and
features they're accustomed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The truck holds five full-size adults in relative comfort, and
those in the back seat can sit there for an extended trip without
cramping up, DaimlerChrysler says.
</P>
<P>
   A disadvantage is the decreased maneuverability of the Dakota
Quad Cab when compared with the smaller Frontier, S-10 and Sonoma.
The Frontier is 193.1 inches long vs. 214.8 inches for the Dakota.
The Frontier also benefits from the established, outstanding
durability of Nissan's line of compact pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, little separates the fuel-economy ratings of the
5.9-liter V-8 Dakota Quad Cab and the V-6 Frontier Crew Cab. The
Dakota is rated at 14 mpg in the city and 18 mpg on the highway,
while the Frontier is just marginally better at 15 mpg in the city
and 19 on the highway for the four-wheel-drive models.
</P>
<P>
   All Frontier Crew-Cabs are built on the heavy-duty four-wheel
drive Frontier chassis, giving the two-wheel drive versions the
same structural rigidity, ride height and ground clearance as the
four-wheel-drives. The bed is about 18 inches shorter than the
standard Frontier bed.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Frontier Crew-Cab combines the comfort and
convenience of a pickup, with many qualities of a sedan. It offers
more rear passenger room than any extra-cab compact truck.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Dakota and Frontier allow for the installation of a
child safety seat in the rear passenger area, something lacking in
today's extended-cab compact trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Frontier, no V-8 engine will be offered in the Sonoma
or S-10 crew cab. Both will be powered by General Motors' 4.3-liter
Vortec V-6 engine, cranking out 190 horsepower and 250 foot-pounds
of torque.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike the Dakota and Frontier, the S-10 and Sonoma crew
cabs will be offered only with four-wheel drive. They will be
equipped with the GM Insta-Trac system, which besides its handy
push-button actuation includes low-range gearing for climbing or
descending steep grades or driving through deep snow or mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chevy S-10 Crew Cab pickup complements and enables
virtually any active lifestyle,'' said Debra Kelly-Ennis, GM's S-10
pickup brand manager.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike most full-size crew-cab pickups, the new compact crew
cabs are designed to fit easily into the average residential
garage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
