<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-HUMANRIGHTS-050     05-01 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HUMANRIGHTS-0502-1STLD-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: new 15th graf, with more on Kamm's business; trade debate
...
 &HT;    CHINA INVITES RIGHTS ACTIVIST IN TO DISCUSS POLITICAL PRISONERS
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Just a few weeks before Congress is to vote on
permanent normal trade relations with China, Beijing has for the
first time invited an American non-profit organization for a visit
to discuss the plight of political prisoners in China.
</P>
<P>
   Although it suspended official dialogue with the United States
on human rights last year after the bombing of the Chinese Embassy
in Yugoslavia, in late March China quietly resumed responding to
the San Francisco-based Dui Hua Foundation's requests for
information on prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Executive director John Kamm has made more than 50 visits to
Beijing over the past 10 years to ask officials about prisoners of
conscience, but for the first time, he said, China has given him a
formal invitation to do so. An April 29 fax from the Ministry of
Justice invited him to Beijing May 18-20 for an ``exchange of
views.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about it,'' Kamm said in a telephone
interview from Washington, D.C., where he is to testify Wednesday
before the House Ways and Means Committee urging the normalization
of trade ties with China. ``In some respects it's something I've
been waiting 10 years for.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamm said Chinese also confirmed in the letter that two
laborers, Chen Gang and Zhang Jingsheng, who took part in
pro-democracy demonstrations 11 years ago are in prison.
</P>
<P>
   He said the explained their prison terms and said when both are
due to be released.
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Justice letter was the first direct comment from
the government on the two men's cases since they were jailed _
along with many others _ for demonstrations centered on Beijing's
Tiananmen Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Kamm said the letter explained that Chen and Zhang were arrested
in separate incidents in southern Hunan province in 1989 and that
both men are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, Kamm, a businessman who lived in Hong Kong for 23
years before moving to San Francisco, has used a
non-confrontational approach to ask the Ministry of Justice for
information on hundreds of political prisoners, then sought to meet
with officials in Beijing. Sometimes he was rebuffed. Other times,
they responded with detailed accounting of a prisoners' status.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with grants from the Smith Richardson Foundation and
the International Republican Institute, Kamm created the Dui Hua
Foundation, which means ``dialogue'' in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Other human rights groups praised Kamm's work but suggested that
Beijing's timing, so close to the controversial trade vote in
Congress _ a major hurdle to membership in the World Trade
Organization _ made its motives suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John would be the first to say that this is certainly
connected to the fact that he has good relations with members of
Congress, and this is likely to be seen positively over there,''
said Sophia Woodman, a Hong Kong-based spokesperson for Human
Rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   Although she thought Kamm's trip would be a positive step, she
said it was more important for the Chinese government to have a
dialogue with human rights activists in its own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they raise their voices and ask to engage with the
government in a peaceful manner, what happens is they get
arrested,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kamm, who was a vice president at Occidental Chemical Co. in
Hong Kong and now does consulting in industrial raw materials, said
the annual debate over trade with China is not an effective tool to
influence China's human rights situation. He said they view the
debate merely as an irritant and, although Congress threatens to
revoke its trade privileges every year, China has grown confident
that it won't lose them.
</P>
<P>
   Kamm said he knows China's communist government may be willing
to make some concessions for PNTR but said the United States can
use that to its own benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is a developing country, a poor country. They're always
going to want something,'' he said. ``We need to figure out how can
we use that to prompt them in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In his upcoming visit, Kamm intends to submit a new list of 51
prisoners. To come up with the names, Kamm, along with three
researchers in Hong Kong, combs through libraries, bookstores and
other publicly available sources. They focus on four crimes:
endangering the social order; endangering state security; revealing
state secrets and counterrevolution; which was abolished in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight months, Kamm said he had uncovered about 1000
names, more than three-quarters of which were previously unknown by
anyone outside China. Prisoners include labor and democracy
activists, as well as Christian evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   Officials told Kamm at the end of 1997 that China has more than
1,900 prisoners convicted of counter-revolution. He estimated less
than one-fifth are known to foreign organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's considered mundane and often denigrated, what I do, the
prisoner list business,'' said Kamm.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the lists have had an effect. Of 100 names he
submitted in 1995, he has received information on 47. Of those, 31
were in prison at the time, but 17 have since been released on
parole or had their sentence reduced.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao' email address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
