<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-STEVE-YOUNG-HNS &LR;      05-01 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEVE-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUNG VISITS 49ERS CAMP, BUT QB'S FUTURE STILL MURKY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Never mind the lack of a formal
invitation. Steve Young was a surprise visitor at last weekend's
San Francisco 49ers minicamp, making it clear that he still sees
himself as very much a part of this team, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Players had been on the field for an hour and 10 minutes Sunday
when Young, wearing gray sweatpants and a wrinkled T-shirt,
strolled out of the locker room gripping a football in his left
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers quarterback didn't actually take part in practice, but
greeted teammates, the few he recognized, and visited with coaches
on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here 15 years ago Eddie hugged me and said `You're
home,'' Young said, referring to former owner Edward DeBartolo. ``I
have felt that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's visit did little to clear up his status with the team.
He said he met with general manager Bill Walsh on Thursday and was
to have talked with coach Steve Mariucci later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 38, hasn't played since Sept. 27, when he incurred his
fourth concussion in three years during a game against the Arizona
Cardinals. Walsh has made it clear the team is prepared to move on
without Young, and the quarterback was not asked to join the 106
players at the three-day minicamp that ended Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to stop me?'' Young said of his surprise visit.
Not Walsh, who wasn't at the team's practice facility Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh hasn't ruled out Young's returning, but has repeatedly
hinted that _ with difficult salary cap issues as well as the need
to rebuild the faltering team _ life would be simpler without Young
and 37-year-old Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Bill has postured a lot in the spring, without any
input from me,'' Young said, adding, ``I probably made a mistake in
not conversing with him earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said last week's meeting was productive and
marked the beginning of a serious dialogue on his football future.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have is a sense we're going to be able to talk it
out,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Walsh had expressed concern about his two aging
superstars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill doesn't want to have Jerry and I flopping around the last
few years of our careers,'' he said, noting Walsh had referred to a
number of players in other sports who ``played too long and their
careers idled or fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he agreed. ``That's an important part of it. That's
something I'd have to answer with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Young also said he shared Walsh's concern about his health but
that medical tests show he has recovered from his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   With so many new faces on the team, Young said he didn't
recognize many of the younger players. But he did spot a few
familiar faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group of guys you recognize are the (offensive) linemen,''
he said. ``We've played together before and we're all friends.``
</P>
<P>
   He declined to criticize the 49ers recent draft, which
essentially ignored the team's needs along that aging line _ a unit
critical to Young's well-being should he return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft needed to go that way,'' he said, referring to the
need for immediate help on the defensive side.
</P>
<P>
   Without much coaxing, Young was able to see a place for himself
on this young team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is in a different place,'' he said. ``It needs
leadership. This team is devoid of leadership, save a couple guys.
... One scenario has Jerry and I finishing our careers and showing
leadership and sharing with a boatload of players, if not more,
what the 49er mystique was all about, helping bridge the past and
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, who played in 11 postseasons with the 49ers and led them
to one Super Bowl championship, was asked how he'd feel about
playing for a team that probably will fall well short of those
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those philosophical questions are some of the things
I'll be brooding on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for repeated rumors he would go to the Denver Broncos or
become a television commentator on Monday Night Football, Young
laughed without commenting specifically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I catch wind of it every once in a while,'' he said of the
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Young is clear on one issue: he still relishes the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juices flow,'' he said. ``It's a complex issue, being
older and the team is in a place it hasn't been before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
