<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GHOST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONDAATJE'S GHOST STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ANIL'S GHOST 
By Michael Ondaatje. Knopf. 
311 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Ondaatje's fierce and tragic vision is made bearable,
even transcendent, by his suppleness of form. He is a choreographer
of images, finding within the darkening plain of history a forest
of infinite possibility _ evidence of dreams turned into anguish,
of innocence tarnished into action. Heir-unapparent to Faulkner and
Garcia Marquez, he delivers stories that often seem like collisions
in time and space _ four strangers in an abandoned, war-torn villa;
an Englishman alone in the desert, clutching Herodotus to keep him
warm. What gives Ondaatje's writing (four novels and 11 books of
poetry) its particular weight and magic is the labyrinthine
consciousness at its center. This is a man beholden to the Greeks
but partial to American Westerns; he has written with equal agility
about jazz, Billy the Kid, a bomb-disposal squad in World War II.
In ``Anil's Ghost,'' he returns for the first time in his fiction
to his birthplace of Sri Lanka, and the resulting novel feels as
specifically wrenching as it is both mythic and doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Ondaatje was a boy when he left Sri Lanka (then called Ceylon)
for England, and then Canada. He wrote about his verdant, chaotic
homeland in a 1982 memoir, ``Running in the Family''; the work is
so steeped in geographically lush surrealism that it partly
explains Ondaatje's affinity with the South American magical
realists. ``Anil's Ghost'' has about it a similarly fecund mystique
from the moment its namesake and protagonist, Anil Tissera, lands
in the predawn heat of the airport near Colombo. Having left Sri
Lanka when she was 15, Anil is now a Western-trained forensic
anthropologist, returning as part of a human-rights commission to
investigate murders on the island: rumors of missing citizens and
mass graves. It is the late 1980s, when Sri Lanka's civil war was
dictated by three distinctly unpredictable forces: the insurgents
in the south, the separatist guerrillas in the north, and a
government who detached purported death squads _ sanctioned and
illegal both _ to hunt down its detractors.
</P>
<P>
   But if politics are always the present-tense manifestation of a
moral universe, archeology holds the summary truth about its past,
and it is here that the great, dark core of ``Anil's Ghost'' lies.
Ondaatje wisely sketches the outlines of Sri Lanka's civil strife,
then moves quickly to the heart of the matter: the young men who
disappear from schoolyards, the grieving families who cannot bury
their all-but-certainly dead, the hideous warnings for the living _
murdered victims' heads on stakes _ to stop their inquiries about
lost relatives. Anil is slotted to work with a state-sponsored
archeologist, Sarath Diyasena, but she doesn't know if she can
trust him. For Anil, the truth is permanently recorded in the
bullet wounds and broken bones of the skeletons she examines,
``same for Colombo as for Troy.'' Older and wiser, balancing on the
sharp rocks of survival, Sarath fears that Anil's blessed truth is
but ``a flame against a sleeping lake of petrol.'' They are both
right, the idealist poised against the fallen hero, with the
ensuing tension between them providing the pivotal nexus for their
shared journey into the past.
</P>
<P>
   The not-too-distant past, as it turns out. Studying the
skeletons from a government-guarded burial site, Anil discovers the
remains of what seems to be a recent victim of murder; if she can
determine his identity, she believes, she will have some palpable
proof of the state's culpability. This is the outline of action for
``Anil's Ghost,'' which barely hints at the tributaries, moral as
well as geographical, that Anil and Sarath will have to travel. And
if ``Sailor,'' as they call their nameless skeleton, is the first
ghost of the novel's title, both Anil and Sarath have others to
contend with _ old lovers and broken pacts and, always, the dead
and legacies of the dead that surround them. Ondaatje's characters
tend to be both besieged by the past and in awe of it; their most
intense relationships belong either to memory or to a platonic,
nonromantic present. Burdened by yesterday, they rarely move
unfettered through the world; instead, they stagger beneath the
weight of history and then, for a moment, try to dance under its
waning light.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in this small patch of understanding (an ironic spin
on ``The truth shall make you free'') is a mythic place outside of
time, much like the realm inhabited by the four lost souls of
Ondaatje's last novel, ``The English Patient.'' Here it's an
abandoned monastery in the forest where Sarath's old teacher has
gone to die: the ``grove of ascetics'' where only the rocks and the
memories they hold can stand up against the eternal facts of death.
Counseled against graven images by the old man, Sarath and Anil
find their clues and half-truths through the maps and symbols
wrought upon the natural world, and ``Anil's Ghost'' is full of
them _ pietas of mother and child, brother and brother, a woman's
shoulder stilled by grief. And staying awake for the impact _
whether of a bomb or of a work of art _ may be the only common
denominator. ``The important thing,'' says one crisis connoisseur,
``is to be able to live in a place or situation where you must use
your sixth sense all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Vastly sensual, ``Anil's Ghost'' is nonetheless an unsettling
novel. Like its predecessors, it offers imagery of terrible beauty
_ a corpse with hands frozen in a position of prayer _ and depths
of such gravitas that it is difficult to argue with anything about
it. And yet there's something oddly evasive about the entire story.
One of its rich corridors of detail is the description of the
ancient ritual of eye-painting in Sri Lanka, where an honored
artisan must paint the eyes of the Buddha image only by viewing it
through a mirror _ no human can look upon the Buddha directly while
it is being given life. Ondaatje's vision, too, feels rendered here
as a devout but sidelong glance. Meeting Anil at the airport, an
official comments on her coming home after 15 years: ``The return
of the prodigal.'' Half-awake, she snaps back at him, ``I'm not a
prodigal.'' Neither is her creator, we are immediately reminded,
and that resolute distance may be what Ondaatje needed to approach
his homeland at all. In any event, it has given him a novel of
exquisite refractions and angles: gorgeous but circumspect, trying
to capture the essential truth by always looking first to its
reflection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
