BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Something in the Soil'' by Patricia Nelson Limerick (Norton,
$27.95). Essays on the history and historiography of the American
West, by a leading maverick. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Selected Poems'' by Nguyen Duy (Curbstone, $15.95). The work
of more than 25 years, by one of the premier poets of Vietnam. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Way Out There in the Blue'' by Frances FitzGerald (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $30) reframes the achievements of the Reagan presidency
through the prism of his relentless pursuit of a ``Star Wars''
missile-defense system. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil and Sonny Liston'' by Nick Tosches (Little Brown,
$24.95) tells the rags-to-riches-to-rags tale of a tough-guy boxer
whose life never went right for long. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Decembers'' by Edna O'Brien (Houghton Mifflin, $24). Set
in timeless rural Ireland, this is an old-fashioned story of
discord and destiny, masterfully written. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I Will Bear Witness'' by Victor Klemperer (Random House,
$29.95). The second volume of this astonishing document, a German
intellectual's diary of the Nazi years, focuses on flight and
escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
