<SLUG> BC-VIET-ADOPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM ADOPTEES REVEL IN THEIR COMMON BOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ One by one, they took the microphone, just to tell
everyone their names and hometowns. And one by one, they found
themselves choking on their words, or fighting back tears, or
recounting their stories.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time most of the young men and women assembled
at a church in downtown Baltimore Saturday had ever been with so
many of their own _ fellow adoptees who had been flown out of
Vietnam during Operation Babylift 25 years ago _ and, for most, the
experience was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, maybe for the first time, I really feel like I really
fit in,'' said Tia Keevil, 28, who was 3 1/2 when she left an
orphanage in Saigon for a new life as Charles and Hannah Teevil's
daughter in Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came because I was curious, to be honest,'' agreed
Jamie Dooley, 25, of Tewksbury, Mass. ``But I discovered all these
people who I have a common bond with, who have a story similar to
mine. . . .It's a first for me, definitely; it's a feeling of
connection that's different from any I've had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Keevil, Dooley, and about 100 other 20-somethings came to
Baltimore from all over the country for a weekend billed as ``The
Reunion of the First Generation of Vietnamese Adoptees.'' Also
attending were dozens of the adoptees' parents, officials from the
orphanages and adoption agencies that dealt with them as babies in
Vietnam and the United States, and military personnel, nurses, and
others involved in the airlift _ most of whom also were seeing each
other for the first time in a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers put together a formal program, with sentimental
presentations and evocative ceremonies including a visit to the
Vietnam War Memorial in Washington. It was less a sense of history
than the simple act of interacting with other people who innately
understood them, however, that the adoptees generally cited as
having had the most profound effect.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some participants who have visited their homeland, or
even found their birth mothers, said that coming together with so
many other Vietnamese refugees was at least as powerful an
experience. At the same time, like a growing number of adoptees of
all nationalities in the United States, the ones here said that
greater openness and fewer stigmas about adoption today _ as
evidenced by the celebratory nature of the reunion _ made them want
to know even more about their native culture and their biological
families.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Delahunt, for example, was among a dozen Vietnamese
babylift orphans who returned to Vietnam this month for the first
time. Her parents, US Representative William Delahunt of Quincy,
Mass. and his former wife, Kati, had long urged her to reconnect
with her roots, but their daughter wasn't sure she wanted to do
much more than see Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   After an emotionally turbulent visit to such sites as the
hospital where she was born and the orphanage in which she lived
the first 4 1/2 months of her life, and then getting the
unlikeliest infusion of support this weekend in Baltimore,
Delahunt, 25, quietly yearned for more. ``I will do a search for my
biological parents,'' she said. Asked to compare her two-week trip
to Vietnam with the hours she'd spent with her fellow adoptees, she
added, ``In a way, it is more overwhelming to be here. . . . It's
such an important time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese adoptees' reunion was organized by
Pennsylvania-based Tressler Adoption Services, Holt International
Children's Services of Eugene, Ore., and the Evan B. Donaldson
Adoption Institute in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for this weekend's activities was the 25th
anniversary of one of the most heartening and heartbreaking aspects
of the US departure from Vietnam: Operation Babylift, in which
about 2,000 orphans were flown out of Saigon; approximately 90 of
them, along with about 50 adults, died when their transport plane
crashed in a rice paddy soon after takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Aune, who was the medical crew director on that flight
and was among 178 survivors, recalled the moments after the C-130
transport went down. Aune said she was too busy rescuing screaming
babies to even think about what was happening at the time, and she
said that she had often recounted the episode with the same sense
of detachment.
</P>
<P>
   Then she walked into a reception at the Lutheran Center across
the street from Baltimore's Inner Harbor. There, milling around,
she said, were many adult adoptees _ some Vietnamese, others the
mixed-race offspring of black or white American soldiers who had
long since gone home to other other families and other lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started to cry,'' said Aune. ``I was totally surprised
by that.'' The sight of the adoptees helped her understand, she
said, after the inglorious US exit from Vietnam and all the pain
that preceded it, ``that, for their sake, it was all worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of these adoptees, like their counterparts
from other nations, were adopted by Caucasian couples and grew up
in predominantly white neighborhoods. As a result, most said they
experienced racism growing up and wrestled with identity problems
related not only to their adoptions but also to culture or race.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their most jarring experiences, many said, have come
during trips back to Vietnam. While they agreed that their journeys
had been worthwhile, even transforming for some, they also said
that the Vietnamese sometimes viewed them as odd _ either because
they were of mixed race or because they looked Vietnamese but acted
like foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``People looked at me, how should I put this, in an intriguing
way,'' said Joshua Baschnagel, who grew up in Hanover, N.H., and
now lives in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the attendees, whatever their experiences or
desires to reconnect with their pasts, said they viewed their
American families as their ``real'' families. During their
self-introductions in the church, one after the other expressed
love and gratitude to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the adoptive mothers and fathers who traveled
here unanimously said they had taught their children about their
backgrounds and had encouraged them to do their own explorations,
to visit their homeland, and even search for their biological
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a normal, natural fact of life . . . for parents
to want their kids to know who they are and where they come from,''
said Karen Santella of Malden, who came to Baltimore with her
husband, Edward, and son Joshua.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
