<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-GIRLS-ART-BOS &LR;      05-01 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GIRLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 `GIRL, INTERRUPTED' RELEVANT TO THE ISSUES OF TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gracing the cover of ``The Bell Jar'' is a fuzzy picture of
Sylvia Plath, a girl in white who looks as though she is about to
disappear into the mists of history. The jacket of ``Girl,
Interrupted'' is more modern, featuring a close-up of a model's
face, cut in half by type and somehow reminiscent of the bare
midriffs so popular among teenage girls today.
</P>
<P>
   These jackets, of course, don't explain why Susanna Kaysen's
``Girl, Interrupted'' is fast replacing Plath's ``The Bell Jar'' as
a must-read for young women in high school and college. But they
offer a compelling metaphor for how _ and why _ the newer book is
finding a place on more and more high school and college reading
lists.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a classic, ``The Bell Jar,'' published in 1963, is
mostly assigned these days in college-level history or American
studies classes as a window on the late '50s, just prior to the
women's movement. ``Girl, Interrupted,'' as contemporary in outlook
as its cover, is capturing a broader niche. It shows up in English,
psychology, and creative writing courses, from a yearlong
psychology seminar at Brandeis University to a memoir-writing class
at Wellesley College to an English class in Newton South High
School's Turnaround program for troubled students.
</P>
<P>
   Many teenagers read the book long before they encounter it in
class, just as a previous generation of young women were drawn to
``The Bell Jar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both books provide evidence of the struggle to craft an
identity for a young woman in our culture,'' agrees Joe Cunningham,
chairman of the psychology department at Brandeis, who uses ``Girl,
Interrupted'' in a seminar. ``Susanna's experience of not fitting
in may speak to more teenagers today. But they both say something
about the courage to be honest about who you are, even when it
doesn't fit in with how people want you to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can identify with what Susanna is going through,'' says Mia
Medina, 21, a Brandeis senior from Istanbul who is in Cunningham's
seminar. ``Her book is the equivalent of `The Bell Jar,' but for
this day and age.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Bell Jar,'' Plath was rebelling against the strictures
of the '50s, which prohibited her from inviting young men to her
dorm room and required that she wear gloves to afternoon tea in
college. The novel chronicles a young woman (a stand-in for Plath)
as she plunges into mental illness, attempts suicide, and
eventually recovers. As the world knows, Plath went on to become a
brilliant poet, then killed herself at the age of 30 just as her
poems were achieving renown.
</P>
<P>
   Kaysen, the real-life protagonist of ``Girl, Interrupted,'' is a
misfit of the '60s who rebels against her academic parents (her
father was an MIT professor) by flunking out of school. She is
barely 18 when, after a 20-minute interview with a psychiatrist,
she ends up hospitalized at McLean Hospital in Belmont for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't happen nowadays,'' says Ayelet Lipton, 17, a
senior at Newton South High School, adding that she has read
``Girl, Interrupted'' ``three or four times'' and considers herself
an authority on the book. ``Two years is way too long to be
hospitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipton first read the book for an assignment in her English
class, which spent some time discussing how the mental health care
system has changed since 1967. But the reason she ``loves'' the
book has more to do with the universal themes of adolescence that
Kaysen explores. ``It's so close to home,'' she says. ``I think all
teenagers get confused at some point in their lives and (Kaysen)
lets you understand what's behind it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipton moved from a small kibbutz in Israel to Newton four years
ago. Like Kaysen, she says she wasn't sure she wanted to go to
college. At first, she thought about enlisting in the Israeli army
after graduation in June. But instead, she has decided to
participate in an Outward Bound program next year and then go to
college.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lipton and her classmate Victoria Francis, 18, say they
have friends who have experienced depression or been hospitalized.
``Girl, Interrupted,'' they say, gave them an insider's view of
what it's like to be hospitalized. ``It taught me not to judge
people,'' says Francis, who is also graduating in June from Newton
South. ``I didn't understand before like, why my friends had to be
put in the hospital. After reading the book, she adds, ``I could be
a better friend to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bell Jar'' also gives readers an inside look at a mental
institution, and Plath's depiction of her character's suicide
attempt is haunting. But perhaps because it was written so soon
after Plath's breakdown, her book does not explore the kind of
inner psychic conflict that is a hallmark of Kaysen's memoir, which
was published in 1993, more than two decades after her
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sylvia Plath was really a lot sicker than Susanna Kaysen
was,'' says Janice Bryan, a psychologist in Lexington who uses
``Girl, Interrupted'' in the continuing education psychology
seminar she teaches at Radcliffe. ``She may not have had the
ability to reflect on her own experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan has used both books in her Radcliffe seminar, which she
has taught for more than 20 years _ and for much the same reason.
They both show how dramatically the therapeutic environment has
changed since Plath and Kaysen were hospitalized. She says she uses
``Girl, Interrupted'' instead of ``The Bell Jar'' today, mainly
because the former is of a more recent vintage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the HMO model we have in place now, both women would have
been hospitalized but only for three days at the most,'' Bryan
says. ``And they probably would have been put on meds and not have
received psychotherapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kaysen is critical of the hospital staff who cared for
her, and the way in which she was essentially tricked into
hospitalization, her readers come away with the clear impression
that in the end, ``she actually appreciated that period of time in
McLean Hospital,'' says Cunningham, the Brandeis psychologist.
``She sort of regathered herself and came out with a different
sense of acceptance about who she was.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the way Kaysen explores that inner process of change that
young readers seem to appreciate most. ``I really liked the way she
described the parallel universe that she saw, and the situations
she had to face,'' says Ani Yanachkova, 18, a Newton South student
who moved here from Bulgaria when she was 10. ``A lot of problems
she faced are problems that teenagers today face. And she admitted
it and was a lot better off for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
