<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FUR FLIES OVER `CAT INDOORS DAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A major observance for American bird lovers is just around the
corner: National Keep Your Cat Indoors Day.
</P>
<P>
   The cat lobby supports the May 13 event in principle, but is
somewhat ambivalent: It conveys a negative image of Fluffy as the
murderer of Tweety Bird, they say.
</P>
<P>
   National Keep Your Cat Indoors Day is the brainchild of the
American Bird Conservancy of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to raise consciousness among cat owners that
free-roaming cats kill birds and other wildlife,'' said Linda
Winter, director of the Conservancy's Cats Indoors program.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in the United States and Britain have shown that
cats, both feral and domestic, kill birds, but they disagree on how
many. The best guess is that birds comprise about 20 percent of the
diet of free-ranging cats.
</P>
<P>
   The Cats Indoors program has the support of the National Audubon
Society, humane societies, animal shelters and bird conservation
groups. Curiously, it also has some support among major
organizations of registered cat lovers, but not because they are
worried about the fate of our feathered friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's common sense, really,'' said Susie Page, director of the
American Cat Association of Panorama City, Calif., the nation's
oldest cat registry. ``With all the cars and trucks and
insecticides and antifreeze and dogs and kids, it's unsafe out
there for cats.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the birds? ``I don't care if they kill birds. That, to
me, is nature, part of a natural thing,'' Page said. Besides,
``birds have a short shelf life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is to keep cats indoors,'' said Juanita
Voorhees, recorder of registrations for the Cat Fanciers Federation
of Cincinnati. Keeping cats indoors ``isn't just for the birds.
It's best for the safety of cats (and) they're perfectly happy
indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaming cats for the disappearance of birds is simplistic, said
Carole Hyde, a founder of the Stanford Cat Network, which has
worked to reduce the feral cat population on the Stanford
University campus since 1989. The decline of bird species is a
function of ``the spread of human development,'' including
urbanization and the destruction of the rain forest, she said.
``The Audubon Society is not scientific on the subject. Its
position is facile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
