<HEADER>
A2362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-COLTRANE-BOS &LR;      05-01 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-COLTRANE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILES AND TRANE: IMPROVISING ON MELODY, GOING ON FOREVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listening to everything that Miles Davis and John Coltrane
recorded together is probably the most pleasurable way of grasping
the changes that overtook modern jazz in one of its most vital and
pivotal eras.
</P>
<P>
   A new box set, ``Miles Davis &AMP; John Coltrane: The Complete
Columbia Recordings, 1955-1961'' (six CDs on Sony or nine LPs on
Mosaic), goes a good distance toward providing both the pleasure
and the understanding.
</P>
<P>
   From their first session (for the album ``Round About
Midnight''), which extended the pulse of be-bop, to their
penultimate (for ``Kind of Blue''), which opened up whole new
realms of freedom, the sonic saga of Miles and Trane is the story
of how jazz evolved and reinvented itself just as the tried and
true formulas turned stale.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were not quite 30 when their collaboration began. (So
much for the hyped novelty of today's ``young lions.'') Davis had
already played a role in two revolutions _ in 1947-48, as the
trumpeter in Charlie Parker's quintet; then, in 1949, as the leader
of a nonet that marked ``the birth of the cool.'' In 1955, as this
box begins, he had just kicked a heroin habit, and staged such a
hot comeback at the Newport Jazz Festival that Columbia Records
signed him up on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Coltrane, at the time, was an obscure tenor-sax sideman, the
first of many demonstrations of Miles's brilliance as a talent
scout.
</P>
<P>
   The two formed a perfect pair _ not, in the usual manner, for
how closely they meshed, but rather for how tensely they clashed:
Miles, the walking-on-eggshells economizer, stretching and spacing
each note for its maximum purity of essence; Trane, the
sheets-of-sound expressionist, probing and twisting a phrase in as
many ways as his restless mind could conceive.
</P>
<P>
   A larger canvas was needed to accommodate the conflicting
contrasts, and Miles found it in a musical form called modalism.
The be-bop of Charlie Parker and Dizzy Gillespie, from which Miles
(and every other modern jazzman) sprang, was built around the
chords of a ballad or blues. Modalism, on the other hand, worked
off the patterns of a scale or a melody.
</P>
<P>
   Miles himself spelled out the implications in an interview with
Nat Hentoff: ``When you're based on chords, you know at the end of
32 bars that the chords have run out and there's nothing to do but
repeat what you've just done, with variations.'' But when you
improvised on melody, he added, ``you can go on forever.'' Less
emphasis was placed on speed and technique _ more on mood and
timbral colors.
</P>
<P>
   This box set documents, above all, the playing-out of this new
approach and _ as the musicians gradually realized its implications
_ the evolution of a new kind of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The music is presented in the order in which it was recorded,
which is often different from its order on the original albums.
This is the case with many box sets on the Mosaic label, and it is
a much-criticized practice. Albums, after all, are artistic
packages in their own right; simply reproducing the tapes
chronologically often violates artistic intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of Blue,'' one of the greatest jazz albums ever, is
certainly a package; to hear ``Freddie Freeloader'' before ``So
What'' (the original album has the order reversed) is
disconcerting. Then again, it is also one of the best-selling jazz
albums ever; 41 years after its release, it remains on the jazz
top-10 charts. How many people who bother to buy this box _ how
many who have bothered to read this far _ don't already own a copy?
A different perspective is hardly a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And the stunning thing is that this box lets me hear ``Kind of
Blue'' _ which I've heard hundreds of times _ in a new way: not as
a miracle dropped from the sky, but as a logical culmination of
what Miles and his band were doing the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a museum retrospective, where you not only enjoy
the paintings but gain insights into how the artist's style
evolved. You hear Miles and Trane settle into their differences,
hone the contrasts, and bounce off them to ever-riskier heights.
</P>
<P>
   The pinnacle of their risk-taking comes with the 1958 sessions,
``Jazz Track'' and ``Jazz at the Plaza,'' where Coltrane starts to
experiment with the ultra-fast, play-everything style that he would
perfect on his own a few years later. In this light, ``Kind of
Blue,'' recorded in 1959, comes as a simmering after the boil,
where the idiosyncrasies of each band member have been sifted into
a distinctive group sound and they can all now move to the next
step _ pure modalism _ in effortless synch.
</P>
<P>
   (The box's producers made one serious mistake by
uncharacteristically placing the '58 sessions after the cuts from
``Kind of Blue'' and the 1961 ``Some Day My Prince Will Come.''
They should be heard before, in chronological order.)
</P>
<P>
   One new discovery from this box _ we've all known it, but not to
this degree _ is the supremely crucial role played by the pianist,
Bill Evans, whose Ravelian flair for colors and tone clusters
pushed, and allowed, Miles to abandon his Charlie Parker patterns
altogether. He could not have done this with Red Garland or Wynton
Kelly, the straight-ahead bop pianists whom Evans (briefly)
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   A key moment is heard one minute into a false start of ``Freddie
Freeloader,'' the first tune recorded for ``Kind of Blue.'' Miles
stops the music, turns to Kelly (who started as the date's
pianist), and barks, ``Look, Wyn, you don't play no chords going
into A-flat.'' The band started over and finished the tune, but
Miles put Evans on the rest of the album.
</P>
<P>
   Other new things in this box: the ``Milestones'' album in real
stereo for the first time (the stereo master tapes had long been
lost); a snatch of dialogue in which Miles makes merciless fun of
Leonard Bernstein; and a dozen previously unissued alternate takes,
none of them better than the issued versions, but hey, we are
talking a dozen new Miles and Trane solos here.
</P>
<P>
   One complaint about these alternates: They should have been put
at the end, all together on a final disc; as is, they disrupt the
flow, especially for those who aren't interested in museums and
just want to hear the music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
