<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ROSE-BOS &LR;      05-01 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ROSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOA, ONCE REMOVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HIDING PLACES 
A Father and His Sons Retrace Their Family's Escape from the
Holocaust 
By Daniel Asa Rose. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 380 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his book ``Hiding Places,'' Daniel Asa Rose sets out to do
something very brave, or some might say foolhardy. That is, write a
kind of Holocaust memoir without having experienced the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Rose grew up in the 1950s, a privileged Jewish boy from a WASP
town in Connecticut. His family was thoroughly assimilated: his
father a psychoanalyst at Yale, his mother a gallery owner who
filled their home with every kind of art except Jewish. Daniel went
on neighborhood Easter egg hunts, listened to music through his
radio earpiece during High Holy Day services, and remembered the
Jewish year was 57-something only because Joe DiMaggio wore number
5 and Mickey Mantle 7 for the New York Yankees. But there were
distant dark shadows in his family, in the form of a number of
great-aunts and uncles who had escaped Hitler's Europe, tattooed
arms and all. They lived 40 miles away in Manhattan, and served as
a nagging but frightening reminder to young Daniel that life was
more than the World Series _ it was world horror.
</P>
<P>
   There were shadows, too, in the form of tales told by his mother
that ``seeped out of her by accident'' about her Belgian relatives
with names like Shasha and J. P. He heard about relatives who,
while hiding from the Nazis, had to make impossible choices like
smothering an infant to keep from being found and killed, or had to
live in a chimney all winter while people dropped food down the
flue. They were people, he writes, who ``were still hobbling around
Europe with backs crooked from bending and with hearts broken from
smothering their babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Daniel grows up, becomes a writer (he is a former
travel columnist for Esquire and currently travel editor of Madison
magazine). He marries a WASP, has two sons, gets divorced. And
that's when it all starts to hit him. He has no center, no
historical identity, no religious ties. He is terrified of being
disconnected from his sons, ages 7 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   So he takes the boys on a roots trip that is also the Ultimate
Travel Story _ a trip to Europe to rediscover the connections that
haunted his childhood memories. They actually track down J. P.
(born Jacov Pesach Morganstern), a doleful but lovable old Brussels
diamond dealer, his mother's second cousin, and use his journal to
guide them through his war experiences in Belgium and France. They
found his hiding places and relived _ at least in their
imaginations _ the horror J. P. must have known when his beloved
twin daughters were killed by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's travel writing background serves him well in his quest.
His eye is sharp, his wit and humor acute, his curiosity hard to
satisfy. His prose actually manages to sustain itself for nearly
400 pages, though at times his Connecticut boyhood stories seem a
touch overworked, and irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, somewhat predictably, Rose finds what he was looking
for. A connection. An affiliation. ``I haven't felt such clarity
for decades,'' he writes. And his boys? They seemed to weather the
trip well, with curiosity and enthusiasm and even humor. (We'll
leave it to their autobiographies, in 30 years or so, to assess the
deeper effects of the adventure.) Their father, for his part,
admits to some anxiety on this point: ``What kind of father,'' he
asks himself, ``would shove his sons' noses in the most terrifying
experience of the century?''
</P>
<P>
   A daring one, that's for certain. Rose has delivered what might
be called an alternative kind of Holocaust book _ a deliberate
attempt, as he has said in an interview, not to affect the tone of
other Holocaust books. ``I had to lighten it for a new generation,
while at the same time pay homage,'' he has said. ``I set myself an
almost impossible challenge _ to walk the razor's edge between
irreverence (in the form of two rambunctious pre-teenage American
kids) and dolefulness (the traditional approach to the
Holocaust).''
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, you have to applaud Rose. ``Hiding Places'' has
broken new ground in at least one way: It demonstrates that the
effects of the Holocaust are playing themselves out in unexpected
ways, in unlikely individuals still one generation further removed
from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand: yikes. Lightening it for the next generation?
What next? Holocaust: The Video Game. Consider this excerpt:
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to sleep in this inn where J. P. hid from the Nazis,
amid imagery that's twisted Grimm's into Hieronymus Bosch, I admit
to myself that I'm Jewed out at last. Jewed to the gills! I'm so
sick of subtlety! Of acuity! The curse of Jewish brainpower! I
can't take the alertness anymore! It's the alertness of the weak
and frightened, of small darting animals in the woods, breathing
with their entire bodies. Their fervency has gotten under my
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice prose, but you know something? Passages like this make me
think: Who cares about Rose and his clever perceptions? Best to
leave the Holocaust legacy where it belongs: in the hands of those
who truly knew it. Not people who are looking for a clever device
for telling a story, who are reaching for a link to the Holocaust
via their mothers' distant relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiding Places'' is in many ways a compelling story,
effectively delivered. But in some ways Rose is breaking ground I'm
not sure really needs to be broken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
