<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BLUES-BOS &LR;      05-01 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BLUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CHESS BROTHERS' MOVES PUT EARLY ROCK ON RADIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SPINNING BLUES INTO GOLD 
The Chess Brothers and the Legendary Chess Records 
By Nadine Cohodas 
St. Martin's, 358 pp., illustrated, $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History has it that in 1948, when Leonard Chess first heard
Muddy Waters sing, he just didn't get it. In a honey-thick
Mississippi drawl, indecipherable to the unseasoned ear, the
singer-guitarist poured out his heart in a blue torrent of passion
and pain in such songs as ``I Can't Be Satisfied'' and ``I Feel
Like Going Home.'' Chess, then a partner for the tiny Aristocrat
label, stared in confusion and annoyance, asking, ``What's he
saying? What's he saying?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Chess may not have appreciated this music, he did _ as
a onetime Chicago nightclub owner _ know its lure and recognize its
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't understand the music he was hearing . . . he did
understand a few important things,'' writes Nadine Cohodas in her
smart, entertaining history of Chess Records, the legendary label
that Leonard founded with his younger brother, Phil, in 1950.
``People loved music, and they would spend money for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spinning Blues Into Gold'' tells the improbable,
only-in-America tale of two Polish immigrants who made their
fortune selling black rhythm and blues, music fostered in the deep
South, carried north, and raised proper in Chicago. As Cohodas
writes it, Chess was a company built ``on the convergence of
outsiders'': Jewish immigants and black Southerners such as Chuck
Berry, Bo Diddley, Etta James, Willie Dixon, and Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Lejzor (Leonard) and Fiszel (Phil) Czyz (their father Joseph,
born Yasef, Americanized the family name to Chess), came to Chicago
in 1928, part of a wave of European Jews seeking a better life in
America. The city was also a prime destination for blacks seeking
sanctuary from segregation (although they would soon discover it
was one of the nation's most racially divided cities), as well as
job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1940s, Chess and his sons operated a junkyard
across the street from a small black church, and the brothers often
heard the jubilant music from ``the hand clappers,'' as Phil called
them. When Leonard grew weary of the junk business, he bought a
liquor store with a bar and jukebox, and soon opened the Macomba
Lounge, which became a favorite nightspot in the city's ``black
belt.'' The popularity of live music convinced Leonard that
producing records could be even more lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of their deals involved both Chess brothers, it
was Leonard who drove the business. He was a profane, hardcharging
man who was involved in just about every aspect of their burgeoning
enterprise. He handled bookings, distribution, and promotion of his
latest releases _ which eventually landed Chess Records in the
middle of the payola scandals of the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It was common practice for label chiefs not only to pay disc
jockeys to play their records, but to give them writing credits,
ensuring them a cut of the royalties; hence, they had a vested
interest in helping the song become a hit. For example, Alan Freed,
once one of the country's most influential disc jockeys, was listed
as a cosongwriter on Chuck Berry's ``Maybelline'' _ without Berry's
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Leonard was making deals in the service of success, he
apparently did not tell the individuals most affected _ the
recording artists _ what he was doing,'' Cohodas writes. ``This was
paternalistic at best, deceitful at worst, even if neither was
Leonard's intent.''
</P>
<P>
   While never descending into stereotypes, Cohodas deals directly
with the racial realities of an industry where, overwhelmingly,
company owners were white, the talent was black, and ``deals
between the two parties were not the negotiations of peers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Chess brothers prospered, the same could not be said for
their artists, whose salaries sometimes resembled allowances.
Several artists _ including Waters, Diddley, and Dixon _ would
later file lawsuits demanding back royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Cohodas's greatest feat is, for all the detail she's
unearthed, she never overlooks her book's true heartbeat _ that
brawny, beautiful music born in cotton fields: from the incessant
throb of ``Bo Diddley'' to Berry's playful ``School Days'' to
James's gutsy, insinuating ``Tell Mama.'' It's a story of luck and
chutzpah, of immigrants carving out their piece of the American
dream. But it also witnesses the raucous birth of rock 'n' roll,
and celebrates the artists who ushered it from South Side juke
joints to the rest of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-REZNOR-BOS &LR;      05-01 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REZNOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENT REZNOR HAMMERS OUT HIS OWN TURF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thumbing through a recent Billboard magazine proved to be a real
downer for Trent Reznor of Nine Inch Nails. Reznor has never been
known as rock's resident optimist, but he was genuinely depressed
upon seeing the number of mindless, lowest-common-denominator rock
bands and teen acts that rule the top of the charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a terrible situation right now,'' says Reznor,
whose continued effort to bring an artistic sensibility to rock 'n'
roll comes at a time when artlessness is king.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to sound like the bitter, crotchety guy whose
record didn't sell as well as somebody projected it would,'' says
Reznor, ``but the lack of intelligent music or challenging music or
anything that is risk-taking is really frustrating, aside from the
occasional hip-hop track that is inventive, then is ripped off by
everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything in rock that has excited me
lately,'' he adds. ``The bands that are somewhat exciting seem to
be playing it safe and repeating themselves. I'd say Rage Against
the Machine is an example of that. They're a really good band, but
they keep writing the same song. I hold them in high regard, but I
don't hear anything that's really making people think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And, sadly, the business climate that bands have to deal with
now is horrible for creativity. Creativity is not encouraged and
it's certainly not rewarded. It's all about finding your niche in
the demographic of the people that you're going to sell your
product to. It has nothing to do with art or integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   And then comes this verbal coup de grace:
</P>
<P>
   ``If the public likes what's on MTV and on the charts right now,
then I don't want to appeal to those people,'' says Reznor.
``That's not the demographic that I care to ship units to. I want
to appeal to people who demand and expect more.''
</P>
<P>
   Reznor's art/industrial rock machine, Nine Inch Nails, is still
selling concert tickets in high numbers _ witness a sold-out date
at the Worcester (Mass.) Centrum Centre this Tuesday. But its
record sales have tapered off with ``The Fragile,'' a stunning, if
sometimes confusing, double album that has sold less than a million
copies, versus the 4 million of NIN's previous disc, ``The Downward
Spiral'' (1994), and 3 million of its debut, ``Pretty Hate
Machine'' (1989).
</P>
<P>
   Critics have generally embraced ``The Fragile'' _ Spin magazine
dubbed it the album of the year in 1999 _ but many consumers have
been standoffish. They are apparently unwilling to wade into the
dark despair of some of Reznor's musings, even though the lyrics,
overall, are more positive than on the wrenching ``Downward
Spiral.'' While there are songs like ``The Big Come Down'' and
``Into the Void'' (``tried to save myself but my self kept slipping
away''), there also are rays of hope in the single, ``We're in This
Together'' (``we will make it though somehow''), and the title
track, which declares, ``I won't let you fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know as a person I was in a much better, healthier mind
space than I was when I did `Downward Spiral,' '' says Reznor,
speaking from a tour stop in Grand Rapids, Mich. ``Every record has
just been a mirror of where I've been at the time I've done it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Reznor, who grew up in a small town in
Pennsylvania but now lives in New Orleans, where he operates his
famed Nothing Studio, realizes that some people might find him to
be a ``pretentious ass.'' He admits, ``I struggled with that when I
was finishing `Fragile.' I thought, `Is this palatable? Is this
intriguing? Will someone give it a chance? Or is it just a load of
self-indulgent crap?' I was trying to check myself on that. I'll
let others be the judge on how well I've succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Reznor sticks by his instincts. When asked if it
might have been wise to shorten the record to a single album
instead of a double album, he refuses to budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could do it again, I would keep it the way it is,'' he
says. ``There is an argument that could be made that a more concise
record that is more focused and more song-oriented rather than
spatial may have been easier for a short-attention-span public to
bite into. But that's not what I chose to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have maintained that ``The Fragile,'' with its
grand, techno-rock sweep balanced by heart-piercing ballads and
instrumental interludes, was Reznor's attempt to update Pink
Floyd's ``The Wall'' for the new millennium. He even brought in
producer Bob Ezrin, who had worked with Pink Floyd, to sequence the
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Pink Floyd has been an influence,'' he says. ``To
me, `The Wall' was kind of the blueprint for the concept album. And
people are still interested in that record because it had a pretty
cohesive and interesting plot. But with `Fragile,' I really went at
it from a purely subconscious level and that's what flowed out of
me. `The Downward Spiral' was more of an attempt to make a
plot-line album, a concept album.
</P>
<P>
   ``But `Fragile' was more sprawling. I wanted to see what was in
me and let it come out. But it was Ezrin who said, `Oh, by the way,
there is a narrative to a degree going on here _ and here are some
themes that you keep repeating.' It was interesting to be analyzed
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Reznor is now grappling with how many songs from ``The Fragile''
to include in NIN's live show. ``We're doing a pretty good chunk of
it _ I'd say seven, eight, or nine songs. But I now have to judge
`Fragile' from its commercial performance. I have to think, `OK, do
people want to hear stuff from this album or should it be a
greatest-hits show?' But, really, I love this album and it's the
reason I'm out touring right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned every song on the record and really could perform
it, but there are a lot of songs in the same tempo range that
wouldn't work in a live environment. I'm just trying to figure out
how much to do, because I've also been a fan who goes to see shows
and thinks of the band, `Oh, God, more stuff off the new album? I
want to hear your old favorites.' So I try to make it a satisfying
balance for all.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-known studio perfectionist, Reznor tries to translate
that same work ethic to NIN's concerts. The set design was done by
Mark Brickman, who has also worked with Pink Floyd, though it was
completed by Roy Bennett, who worked on NIN's ``Downward Spiral''
tour. ``We've had some personnel changes,'' admits Reznor.
``Brickman is a talented guy, but his sensibility was in sharp
contrast to mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The visual highlights of the show, for Reznor, are the mid-set
videos done by Bill Viola, an acclaimed figure who does not do rock
videos, but instead specializes in video installations in museums
and art galleries. This is his first partnership with a rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just like to elevate the concept of a rock performance,
rather than have it be the same thing all the time in a venue
designed for sporting events,'' says Reznor. ``I'm just trying to
notch up the intellect a couple of levels. That's what appeals to
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
