A2367 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      05-01 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' It's as cheesy as the
first ``Flintstones,'' but no less cheerfully campy. What story
there is in this prequel, about the courtship of Mark Addy's
lunchbucket Fred and Kristen Johnson's upper-crust Wilma, seems
lifted from old movies. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!! ``Frequency'' It risks disaster, but this thriller about a
sad cop who makes contact via ham radio with his firefighter dad
(who died 30 years before) and rewrites their lives is both
original enough and emotional enough to survive a diminishingly
ordinary serial-killer showdown. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``The Last September'' Gorgeously autumnal evocation of a world
about to vanish _ the estate-based life of English gentry living in
Ireland in 1920. One could wish that the great Michael Gambon and
Maggie Smith had more to do as lord and lady of the manor about to
be reclaimed by Irish freedom fighters, but Fiona Shaw's worldly
houseguest is sublime. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FL) !! ``Where the Heart Is'' Pallid adaptation of Billie Letts's
novel about a young woman who journeys from Tennessee to a Wal-Mart
in Oklahoma, where she gives birth to a baby after being ditched.
Her growth into self-empowerment, aided by two big-hearted older
women, is rendered with disappointing superficiality. Natalie
Portman is too cultivated to project that trailer-park je ne sais
quoi. Matt Williams's direction is only sitcom-deep. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``Winter Sleepers'' This film by ``Run, Lola, Run''
director Tom Tykwer has the same theme _ the role of chance in the
criss-crossings of five lives _ but it plays out quite differently
in a Bavarian Alpine resort. Its dreamy, luxuriant patterns of
fatefulness falling into place recalls Kieslowski's ``Red,'' and is
just as engrossingly rendered. (Unrated)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
