<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-LOCKHART-BOS &LR;      05-01 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LOCKHART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEITH LOCKHART PREVIEWS THE POPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Keith Lockhart, wearing a shirt as blue as his eyes,
leaned forward and talked seriously about the Pops.
</P>
<P>
   The Pops conductor, now 40 and about to begin his sixth season
in that role, has never been one to resist the peripherals of his
position _ the onstage jokes and the outrageous album covers. He
didn't balk for an instant at a photographer's recent request to go
up on the Symphony Hall roof and stand behind a Pops sign. Like the
Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli, Lockhart works hard to be popular
because he knows that popularity is the lever he needs to make it
possible to do the things he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change at the Pops is a very slow process,'' Lockhart admits.
``The Pops is only one cog in a very large machine _ although it is
a highly successful cog. The logic always seems to be not to tamper
with the status quo because the status quo has become so remarkably
successful. But the Pops has never been about rehashing what it did
last year; it can't afford to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart is justifiably proud that he and his colleagues have
succeeded in continuing the Pops' prominence in recording, five
albums to date, plus a compilation of greatest hits, despite the
general collapse of the classical record business. ``Runnin' Wild''
has sold a very respectable 250,000 copies since its release in
1996; his least popular record, unsurpisingly, is his most serious,
``American Visions'' (1997), which has sold 50,000, still
substantially more than most orchestral recordings sell these days.
</P>
<P>
   RCA/BMG, which records Lockhart and the Pops, is in the middle
of a major upheaval, and no one can confirm whether such successful
long-term recording stars as Evgeny Kissin, James Galway, and
Richard Stoltzman will be able to continue with the label. Lockhart
and the Pops, however, will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pops cannot afford to take too many risks,'' Lockhart
says. ``But in terms of content, our recordings are very different
from what the Pops was doing before. Our job is to keep coming up
with projects that will keep us in the position of putting out
things people want to buy. We knew the trouble at BMG was going to
happen, but we were assured that we would be fine because our
recordings are still profitable. These days the costs of making an
orchestral recording are so prohibitive that for a non-crossover
disc like `American Visions' to sell 50,000 copies is nothing short
of a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of what does sell in the crossover category,
it's terrifying _ look at Charlotte Church, for example, the
teenage Welsh soprano. What's happened to her is almost child
abuse, and it is certainly music abuse; there's something about
that story that's very dark. And that's what most people today
think classical music is _ Charlotte Church or Sarah Brightman. In
a world where people admire performers like that, where do Renee
Fleming and Bryn Terfel fit in? Believe me, we will not feature
Charlotte Church or Sarah Brightman at the Boston Pops.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart is excited about this season's recording project, a
Latin album that he hopes will be as successful as the Celtic album
recorded two years ago. ``We are still working on getting
arrangements of everything we want to use; we'll be recording the
album at the end of May and the beginning of June. There will be
music by Copland, `El salon Mexico,' which I conducted on one of my
audition concerts for the Pops back in 1994, and music by such
South American composers as (Alberto) Ginastera and Batuque and a
composer with a great name, Mozart Camargo! We'll be joined by
Peruvian folk musicians, a mariachi band, and Afro-Cuban
percussionists.''
</P>
<P>
   The album will also return to the first Pops recording to sell 1
million copies, back in 1935, ``Jalousie,'' by Jacob Gade. ``Arthur
Fiedler made that piece known all over the world, and it's even
been adopted in Argentina, where the musicians thought it was a
pretty good tango, even if it did come from Denmark. We've
commissioned a new arrangement of `Jalousie' for this season that
bridges two eras _ it pays homage to the Pops' historic version,
but it also places the piece in the context of authentic
Argentinian tango.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the actual Pops season, which opens Tuesday
night at Symphony Hall, Lockhart says, ``One of the big things for
me is the season-long tribute to Aaron Copland on his 100th
birthday. We will also have a Copland program for `Evening at Pops'
that will stretch the envelope a little bit, the way our
Shakespeare show did last year. Jubilant Sykes will be with us to
sing the `Old American Songs' and Dawn Upshaw is coming up to sing
Laurie's aria from `The Tender Land.' We also will use some footage
we have of `Hoedown' from `Rodeo.' I hope the whole package will be
instructive and entertaining. During the convention of the American
Symphony Orchestra League, which is in Boston this spring, we will
be performing a new work, Robert Maggio's `Skylines,' which has
been written as a musical tribute to Copland.''
</P>
<P>
   The other season-long event will be a ``Tribute to the Great
American Songbook.'' ``We were looking for something else to run
through the entire season, and this was one area in which our
library of arrangements was very strong. We can bring out a lot of
old things and we're also adding something new, a Paul Simon
tribute that will continue to add a link to the chain.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Copland program, the television events
include ``Elmo and the Wolf,'' a project with the creators of
``Sesame Street.'' ``The music is pretty much our old friend,
Prokofiev's `Peter and the Wolf.' `Sesame Street' is taped in a
studio in Queens, and I've already been there to tape some of the
backstage bits; the amount of talent in that room is amazing,'' he
says. ``In our version, Papa Bear will bring Baby Bear to Symphony
Hall and she will show how music can tell a story. The show will
combine Symphony Hall scenes with Baby Bear's fantasy journey. This
will ultimately become a commercial video release.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pops conductorship, of course, is now a part-time job for
Lockhart, as it was for his predecessor, John Williams. Lockhart
just finished his second season as music director of the Utah
Symphony with a concert and television show featuring Andre Watts.
``I also got to meet our principal guest conductor, Pavel Kogan,
and talk to him for more than five minutes for the first time _
he's the son of the famous violinist Leonid Kogan, and he conducted
the orchestra for the Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow when my
wife, Lucia Lin, was there. This season we did some great stuff in
Utah, like Britten's `War Requiem.' Hilary Hahn came and played the
Brahms Violin Concerto, and I conducted Strauss's `Also sprach
Zarathustra' for the first time. Next season, I will lead Mahler's
Third Symphony and the Verdi Requiem. Opportunities like these make
me feel like a kid in a candy store.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart has bought a home in Salt Lake City. ``This was very
important to the community there, and it's nice to live in your own
home rather than in a hotel suite, especially when you are there
for 17 weeks a year. And you can say that houses are cheaper out
there than they are here! My house is a beautiful place, about 15
minutes away from the (concert) hall and 25 minutes away from the
good skiing. The audiences are strong and we are pushing the
envelope in programming _ next season will be our first Mahler in
23 seasons, and we will do Corigliano's First Symphony. For me, it
has been a tremendous growth opportunity; four rehearsals for every
concert is a very different process than trying to do 80 concerts
on 2 1/2 rehearsals, or whatever we are able to do at the Pops!''
</P>
<P>
   One disadvantage is that Lin is occupied most of the time by her
job in the violin section of the Boston Symphony and therefore not
able to spend much time in Salt Lake City. ``That's too bad because
Salt Lake City is a very family-oriented place, but she comes out
when she can, and we try to make sure that's there's some couple
time and some skiing time as well as orchestra time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart and Lin remain active in their chamber ensemble,
Innuendo, which once again will play in the Stockbridge Chamber
Series this summer. ``I've learned another piano quintet,
Dohnanyi's, which we will play this season instead of the Dvorak,
and we will also play a chamber version of Milhaud's `La Creation
du Monde.' At some point, we would like to play closer to town than
Stockbridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the Pops future, Lockhart says, ``I would love
to find more opportunities to do multimedia things. One of our
major donors would like to give us a plasma projection screen, and
we could do some exciting things with that. And I would like to do
more collaborative projects. In 2001, I would like to do a concert
version of a major American musical, something like `Sweeney Todd,'
for example. There is a philanthropist who is eager to help us do
that, and then maybe we could run it out to Tanglewood. It is a
good thing to break out of the box from time to time _ nice as the
box is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
