<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      05-01 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Place and pace, these are what matter to me most in judging a
mystery novel or spy thriller. Character is important, of course,
though in this genre a reader often must suspend disbelief, since
the exigencies of plot frequently demand that a person prove to be
unlike the personality paraded before us through most of a book.
Effective writing is also important, though here one must often be
forgiving, since so many writers first hone their talents on a
mystery or thriller and do not improve.
</P>
<P>
   One who has improved is Paul Bishop, whose place, in ``Chalk
Whispers'' (Scribner, $24), is Los Angeles, and whose pace is fast,
hard, and compelling. An earlier Bishop book sported one of the
best titles in a long while _ ``Tequila Mockingbird'' _ and now
Bishop's prose has caught up with his imagination. ``Chalk
Whispers'' is a first-rate crime novel about police corruption,
child abuse, illegal immigration, and murder, and in it Bishop's
series figure, Fey Croaker, emerges as a convincing, gutsy,
vulnerable figure _ a person of character the reader can bank on.
As with many LAPD crime novels, there is an ensemble at work here,
each figure playing a well-defined and yet somehow fresh role. The
comparisons of Bishop to Joseph Wambaugh that have been proposed
ring true; indeed, I think Bishop is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remembrance Day'' by Henry Porter (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25),
also has plenty of pace and well-constructed places _ the action
moves from London to Ireland to the Allagash in Maine and back
again. Constantine Lindow, Irish but now taking up a post in
Britain after a stint making money as a research scientist in
America, sets out to meet with his brother outside a London tube
station, only to see him killed in an exploding bus. Held by the
police, who suspect he is working for the IRA, Lindow realizes he
must find out why his brother has been killed if he is to prove his
innocence. One copper takes a gamble on Lindow, partly because
British intelligence clearly wants to wrap the entire incident up
by blaming him. With these premises Porter constructs a careful,
logical narrative about terrorism that turns on the use of cell
phones _ one will never unthinkingly call back to an unidentified
number after reading this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Places in the Dark'' by Thomas H. Cook (Bantam, $23.95), also
takes place in Maine, in a small, wintery, coastal town where
everyone knows everybody. Cook writes very well; his tone is sad,
even foreboding, yet almost elegiac, as he weaves tiny bits of
cloth from here, there, and down below into an intricate fabric of
tragedy. One knows the what of the conclusion at the outset; it is
the why that is unraveled for us, concisely, almost in snapshots,
with surprises along the way. Here character is developed and
matters: Two brothers, one a lawyer, the other a newspaper editor,
close and yet quite different, become obsessed with a woman who
appears in their village one day in autumn 1937, and with an
exquisite sense of pace, Cook takes us down the road to the
terminus of those obsessions. Forget the usual comparisons to other
writers, for Cook is sui generis.
</P>
<P>
   So is Harold Adams, who also writes of a time when life seemed
slower and simpler, and who uses pace to keep action in check so
that we can experience the Great Depression as Carl and Hazel
Wilcox do in the upper Midwest, along the St. Croix River between
Minnesota and Wisconsin. The mystery is slim, the people are tired,
and yet Adams makes Carl so real, one realizes that he is giving us
crimes as they really happen. ``Lead, So I Can Follow'' (Walker,
$22.95) is nicely representative of this low-key writer. He slowly
sneaks up on the reader, until one cares more about a body that has
fallen from a riverside bluff than about a terrorist bomb in a
London street.
</P>
<P>
   New to this reviewer, Jessica Speart also uses place to good
effect. Nevada Barr has given us Anna Pigeon, a National Park
Service ranger who encounters death in our national parks; now
Speart creates a US Fish and Wildlife Service special agent,
Rachael Porter, who works to protect endangered species and put an
end to illegal traffic in the nation's wildlife. From New Orleans
(in ``Gator Aide'') through Miami (in ``Bird Brained'') to her
fourth book, ``Border Prey'' (Avon, $5.99 paperback), set on the
Texas/Mexico border near El Paso, Speart tells us a lot why we
ought to care about endangered species _ and along the way provides
a rattling good yarn. Rachel Porter has a mouth on her, as they
say, and she is a very good traveling companion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2371 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CHINA-WTO-BOS &LR;      05-01 1876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-WTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS FACE TEST ON CHINA VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four weeks from now, when the US Congress considers
whether to normalize trade relations with China, Representative
Michael E. Capuano will join the majority of the Massachusetts
delegation in voting no.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vote that doesn't add up. Capuano says so himself.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 250 high-tech firms employing thousands in
his Bay State district. Yet Capuano will oppose lifting
restrictions on technology exports to China. If the curbs are
lifted, the Massachusetts high-tech industry could add hundreds of
millions of dollars in sales a year because of China's huge,
emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   His district is home to Lotus Development Corp., the
3,000-employee Cambridge firm, which is counting on the trade pact
to help it sell software in China without fear that its products
will be illegally copied and pirated. Cambridge is also home to
Polaroid, which covets unlimited access to the vast Chinese
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But Capuano is resolute. China's continuing restraints on
individual freedom, its exploitation of prison labor, and other
human rights abuses are too much to ignore. It is, he says, a
``knee-jerk thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably economically better for my district,'' the
Democrat said. ``But I've always believed that America should be
more than just the bottom line. Human rights is important to me.
And I do think it is important America stand for something more
than the almighty buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Capuano has plenty of company in his willingness to go against
the economic interests of his district and vote against the
agreement. Seven of the 12 people in the Massachusetts delegation
are expected to vote no when the matter comes to a roll call in
late May, even though by some estimates there is no state in the
nation better positioned to take advantage of expanded China trade.
The Boston Chamber of Commerce has predicted that a pact could
nearly triple, to $900 million, business with China among
Massachusetts firms.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the Bay State delegation call themselves
undecided and are being courted heavily by both sides of the vote,
which is expected to rise or fall by a razor-thin margin in the
House. Among the undecided in the Senate, where the measure is
viewed more favorably, is Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who is
expected to vote yes in the end. Only the state's junior senator,
John F. Kerry, has committed himself to the pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a one-sided agreement in favor of the United
States,'' Kerry said in an interview, his first official
announcement that he will favor the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and policy analysts overwhelmingly agree. The
measure, known as permanent normalization of trade relations, makes
numerous demands of China, among them lowering harsh tariffs,
eliminating quotas, and adhering to intellectual property laws. All
the United States must deliver is a guarantee: that it will
maintain normal trade relations permanently, instead of requiring
Congress to vote on it every year as it does now. For that, the
Congressional Research Service predicts, the United States could
reap a $11.5 billion economic windfall.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, like Capuano, money is only part of the equation.
Underlying the debate is the complex nature of globalization
itself. And as lawmakers grapple with a trend in which some see
great advantages and others serious negative side-effects, many in
the delegation are finding themselves pulled in the direction of
caution.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such caution among business leaders like Stephen L.
Brown, chairman and CEO of John Hancock Financial Services in
Boston, who envisions a sea of potential life insurance clients
across the horizon. Currently, the company has a joint venture in
Shanghai, a city of 13 million; if the pact passes, insurance firms
could branch out almost anywhere in China, competing in an industry
that, in some Chinese cities, is doubling every year.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown also sees the business and job potential back home in
Massachusetts. John Hancock employs 5,000 people in the state, and
contributed $700 million to the local economy in 1998. An insurance
boom in China, with US firms in the vanguard, would create jobs and
greater wealth at home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heavy lobbying by the insurance industry, however, that
business proposition has left most of the delegation unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that the state have healthy, growing
companies,'' Brown said. ``I guess they don't agree with my
long-range philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci, a Republican who is firmly
behind President Clinton on this issue, puts it more bluntly. ``In
my view, this is a no-brainer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of Cellucci's alliance with the White House, against
the majority of the delegation, is lost on no one. Administration
advisers have been calling undecided members for months. When US
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright visited Agilent
Technologies in Andover this month, Cellucci half-jokingly promised
to help, saying: ``I'll talk to the Democratic congressmen from
Massachusetts, but they don't always listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The undecided congressmen _ Martin T. Meehan, Edward J. Markey
and Richard E. Neal _ find themselves on the receiving end of a
cacophony of concerns _ to their great political discomfort. Labor
groups have been especially vocal, arguing that free trade with
China will only encourage US firms to move their factories
overseas, at the expense of exploited workers there and lost jobs
here. To make their point, the AFL-CIO staged a rally outside the
Massachusetts office of Markey last week, under the motto: ``No
Blank Check for China!''
</P>
<P>
   Labor officials do not know exactly how many union jobs are in
peril. They make their case using the North American Free Trade
Agreement as an example. Before NAFTA, in 1989, there were 22,500
apparel and clothing manufacturing jobs in Massachusetts. Six years
after NAFTA took effect, less than half still exist. Labor's
concern is not that new jobs will be created by expanded trade, but
that established workers in older industries will be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there are only about 135 textile mills left in
Massachusetts leads traders to urge that the state should be
focusing on areas of growth, such as technology. ``The textile
industry has been fading away in Massachusetts since the 1920s,''
said Andre Mayer of the Associated Industries of Massachusetts, an
employer association representing some 2,500 manufacturing firms.
``What's left are companies that can effectively compete with
anyone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But some congressmen say it is wrong to ignore the concerns of
even a dwindling manufacturing minority, regardless of the overall
economic prospects for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the state's governor and senators, Representative Barney
Frank answers directly to manufacturing workers in New Bedford and
Fall River, even if there are only 18 textile mills left in his
district. Frank, one of the most ardent students of globalization
in Congress, does not oppose free trade with China on economic
grounds; he agrees it could benefit the nation as a whole. And he
realizes that includes businesses in the northern part of his
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people in the south need me more,'' Frank said. Without
protections for low-wage workers, such as guaranteed health care
coverage, Frank said, he cannot vote for the China trade opening.
``I represent people who lose jobs because of trade. For the
country as a whole, it creates more winners than losers. And the
wealthy people gain more at the expense of working people, and I am
not going to support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zandi, an economist at the Regional Financial Association,
explained the delegation's predicament this way: ``Increased trade
with China will be an unambiguous positive for the Massachusetts
economy. . . . The problem is that in any economic change, it's
much easier to identify the losers than the winners. The losers are
much more vocal than the winners. That's why trade policy is so
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several technology firms admitted they have not lobbied
as persuasively as their labor counterparts. In general, the
high-tech community is still finding its political bearings; many
have only recently begun to participate in government affairs. One
official at the Massachusetts Ocean Technology Network, a trade
association representing 17 companies that export to China, said
she had not heard of the trade opening legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the high-tech community has ridden the
boom to great personal advantage, and has not yet taken the
responsibility that goes with that,'' said Chris Gabrieli, chairman
of the New Democrat Network, a centrist political organization.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has it built a reservoir of influence with the delegation,
which has thrived for years on a combination of heavy donations
from labor unions and a liberal political climate. In Capuano's
case, voting against the measure seems an obvious choice: Activists
are everywhere in his Cambridge district, and labor unions have
donated more than $73,000 to his campaign this election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is the issue of human rights. Agreeing to
permanent trade relations would end the annual votes in Congress on
whether to grant China trading rights similar to those of other
nations, a vote often accompanied by a scathing review of China's
human rights transgressions. Activists argue that passing the trade
opening would speed China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, eliminating any US human rights oversight. And
Capuano, who studied Chinese as an undergraduate at Dartmouth
College, said he is unconvinced by the free trade argument: that
simply trading with China will encourage democratic progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this talk about how we're going to change China has been
told a thousand times in Chinese history,'' he said. ``It has never
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   But China is likely to win entry into the WTO with or without a
deal, trade analysts said. If an agreement with the United States
is not in place, many advocates of the deal worry that other
foreign firms will sweep into the giant Chinese market without the
regard for human rights that many US companies press for.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what worries David Lu, a Chelmsford, Mass. businessman.
A native of China, he says greater economic opportunity _ and
contact with Western businesses _ will help spur democratization in
China.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer who launched a firm to help companies sell technical
equipment over the Internet, Lu sees huge opportunties for his
business in China. But he is equally encouraged by what his
business could do for China. He has already hired two employees in
his office outside Beijing; with lowered trade limitations, he
said, he could hire many more. ``It is not only business, it is
democratic ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get exposed to how we work, and how we think. I believe
that is going to help the Chinese democratic process,'' he said.
Then he added: ``If we can lower the barriers on both sides . . .
our business would boom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
