<SLUG> BC-CHILD-NEGLECT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR BOY, 9, AND HIS FAMILY, IT WAS A LIFE IN SQUALOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARWICK, R.I. _ On April 20, a police officer knocked on the
door of 512 Roundhill Court, a condominium unit set in golf-course
green lawn, and ended the Caldwell family's long flight from the
world's attention.
</P>
<P>
   What he found inside was less a home than a filthy nest,
crawling with the sinewy bodies of cats and spattered with feces,
littered with wrecked antiques and wads of dollar bills. The fumes
were so strong that animal control officers wearing bodysuits and
respirators could only enter the place for 10-minute intervals.
Thirty cats would be removed that weekend, not including the dead
ones.
</P>
<P>
   There were also human contents: a 62-year-old woman opened the
door, covered with insect bites. Behind her on a couch lay a
dark-haired boy who, for nine years, had been kept a virtual secret
from the world. The stench of waste had been seeping through the
walls into adjoining units since the fall, neighbors said, and
neither Gretchen Caldwell nor the boy, Nicholas, had been spotted
outside for months.
</P>
<P>
   How the Caldwells passed the days behind their drapes remains a
mystery, as do the impulses that drove them into desperate
isolation. As authorities search for the boy's mother, Denise
Caldwell, 32 _ who allegedly left the family to buy milk three
weeks before, and never returned _ the biggest mystery of all is
how, despite a scaffolding of social services and well-meaning
neighbors, they could have gone unnoticed for so long. What is
becoming clear, though, is how the family routinely deflected
outsiders' attention, and how tragically easy it sometimes was.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever social service agencies, curious neighbors, truant
officers, or anyone outside the family came close to prying open
the Caldwells' secrets, ``the family was able to evaporate in front
of everyone's eyes,'' said Scott Avedisian, the mayor of Warwick.
``What's troubling is you have a 9-year-old, unschooled boy. There
is no trace whatever of this child.''
</P>
<P>
   But seven miles away, five months earlier, it had happened
before. There, in the West Warwick development of River's Edge,
police had broken into an apartment rented by Gretchen Caldwell
after fumes from inside grew so strong that they set off the fire
alarm. What they found inside was remarkably similar to the scene
at 512 Roundhill Court. According to an officer's report, the
apartment had no working plumbing, and ``was covered in feces and
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the family had vanished. Neighbors knew this about
them: Gretchen Caldwell, 62, the only child of a prominent Warwick
executive, had raised Denise as a foster child, and the two had
lived together at least since the time of Nicholas's birth. As
Thomas Iannitti, West Warwick's director of human services, picked
his way through the reeking apartment, he found disturbing
intimations about the boy's life _ especially a roomful of Michael
Jordan memorabilia he knew no child would willingly abandon. He
said it looked to him ``like someone was being held hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Domingues, a neighbor whose children had played with
Nicholas occasionally, reported that Gretchen Caldwell had run from
the house once, saying her daughter was trying to kill her.
Domingues remembers Nicholas looking down at her from the window of
the bedroom where he spent most of his time _ or throwing down toys
for her children that were smeared with feces. And she remembers
the moment she realized that when she saw him in the parking lot
every day, it wasn't because he had come home from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think, well, everybody has something to do during
the day,'' Domingues said. ``Then I realized, this is when this
little boy is let out of this room.''
</P>
<P>
   When Iannitti tried to find school records for the boy, he
discovered, to his amazement, that Nicholas appeared never to have
been enrolled in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't exist,'' Iannitti said.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time, the Department of Children, Youth and Family
was contacted by someone concerned about the child's educational
status. The agency investigated the complaint and found enough to
substantiate it _ a status given to about a third of the 8,500
complaints that are investigated every year, according to the
agency's associate director, Thomas Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   The agency then assigned the case to a social worker from a
private agency in November, but because of ``difficulties in
following up'' _ which could mean the family did not cooperate,
Dwyer said _ the case was sent back to the Department of Children,
Youth and Family in February. On Feb. 29, a social worker from the
department contacted Denise Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   But the mother found a simple enough way to resolve concerns
about the child. Within days, she had received approval from the
Warwick School Department to home-school her son. Even though her
son apparently had never attended school before, school department
officials approved the arrangement without ever asking to meet the
child or the parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school department really can't make a decision about who
is a reliable educator and who is not, based on the current law,''
said Robert Shapiro, Warwick's superintendant of schools. ``When we
received information about home instruction, we follow it, but we
don't go into backgrounds of the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the letter of approval on March 2, Denise
Caldwell passed it on to the social worker from the Department of
Children, Youth and Family, Dwyer said, and the matter was
considered resolved. The social worker made no home visit.
</P>
<P>
   So it would be almost two months before yet another anonymous
tip to the Department of Children brought police to the door at
Roundhill Court. The scene was so horrifying that the police
officers, animal control officers, child welfare advocates, housing
officials and, finally, attorneys who marched through the place
over the course of the weekend could only explain it in terms of
how many years they have been walking into strangers' houses: Not
in 12 years doing this, or not in 35 years, had they seen a
household gone so terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Cats were crawling over the feces-spattered countertop, and in
and out of the open refrigerator, where they defecated, over wads
of stained bedding and the bare mattress where it appeared the boy
and his grandmother slept. Half-eaten food lay everywhere, rotting,
along with fistfuls of forgotten cash, costume jewelry, broken
toys, urine-soaked upholstery, an upside-down television, a litter
of dead kittens. Against a far wall, someone had carefully lined up
a row of baby dolls. Richard Gallant, an animal control officer,
spent Easter Sunday trying to forget the sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just expect that people live a certain way,'' said
Gallant, slowly. ``You think when you go home, people are all going
home to the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wethersfield Commons, a development much admired for its
units' fastidious exterior, neighbors said the residents of 512
Roundhill Court seemed to have disappeared. The three Caldwells had
moved in during the late summer shortly after Gretchen Caldwell's
mother, Gladys Tracy, left the address for a nursing home. They
still spent some time in the West Warwick apartment, according to
neighbors there.
</P>
<P>
   The family kept to themselves in the new neighborhood. Ryan
Miller, 18, remembers answering the door to Nicholas, who came over
asking to play with his little brother. Although other neighbors
said Nicholas was a normal boy, Miller remembered him as being very
strange. ``He wouldn't talk, but he'd yell, he'd make sounds''
while riding his bicycle around, Miller said. ``You could barely
understand him.''
</P>
<P>
   But even when the people stopped appearing, the smell was
impossible to ignore. Property manager Joseph Mirra received a
written complaint from the residents of one adjoining unit about
the smell in November, and the residents of another adjoining unit
also complained. Mirra said he offered to help Gretchen Caldwell
remove garbage from her garage, and although he could not recall
whether she accepted the offer, he said the neighbors' complaints
had been resolved. ``This is a private home. If we see water coming
out of the door, or smoke, or loud music, or if someone had alerted
us to some kind of problem with the child,'' the management company
would certainly have responded, Mirra said. ``You can't just go
banging on people's doors who may be in ill health.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Mirra said, the condominium was put up for
sale, but when realtors knocked on the door, hoping to show the
apartment, they were turned away. A sign on the door read,
``ILLNESS Please Do Not Disturb Thank You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious (Gretchen Caldwell) didn't want anyone in the
house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The house is boarded up now, condemned as unfit for habitation
less than two days after the first knock on the door from a police
officer. And Gretchen and Nicholas Caldwell are back in the world:
Gretchen is in a mental hospital, according to her mother's
attorney, Robert Gates, and the boy is in state custody, where he
is to be examined by doctors and psychologists. Denise Caldwell has
not surfaced, but Warwick police believe she is in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Others are left to wonder whether, in a state where every
citizen is required by law to report suspicions of child abuse,
anyone in particular is to blame for not learning what lay behind
the Caldwells' curtains. The state Child's Advocate has requested
records relating to the child from the Department of Children,
Youth and Family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole thing is tragic. To have a minor child, that
nonverbal, who's not been schooled, is just tragic for our entire
city,'' said Avedisian. ``Any time we have a situation where a
9-year-old boy is basically unknown to anyone is enough to suggest
that there should be reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
