<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (Undated) _ Time Warner Cable has dropped
Disney-owned affiliates from seven big markets, including New York,
Los Angeles and Houston. The move, which comes in the middle of May
sweeps, results from an impasse over transmission rights. By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-REACT (Undated) _ Looking at how viewers in metropolitan
New York, Los Angles and Houston are reacting to the blackout of
their ABC stations.
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS-AD-STRIKE (Undated) _ The Screen Actors Guild and the
American Federation of Television &AMP; Radio Artists, representing
about 135,000 actors, begin a strike, refusing to perform in radio
and television commercials until they get a larger chunk of the
booming cable TV business. Rallies are set for New York, Los
Angeles Chicago and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Looking at what happens next in
the Microsoft antitrust case. Microsoft, which may ask for more
time for its response, is expected to seek full-fledged,
evidentiary hearings on the proposed remedy. What might such
hearings be like? Developing. With reporting by Steve Lohr and Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-INTERNET (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In Indonesia, a
country dominated by corporate dynasties, Edward Soeryadjaya is
famous as the scion who broke his family's bank and cost his family
the car company his father founded, Astra International.
Soeryadjaya has now returned from self-imposed exile as a
entrepreneur planning to build a stable of dot-coms and turn
Jakarta's old airport into Indonesia's Silicon Valley. In the
process, he wants not only to resurrect a fallow property
investment but also to prove at last that he was the victim of a
political conspiracy and perhaps even restore his family to Astra's
helm. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (new York) _ Stocks were higher in early trading. At
11:15 a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 0.70 percent,
the S&AMP;P 500 up 1.34 percent and the Nasdaq composite index up 3.15
percent. Microsoft shares were up 4 percent. Treasury prices were
slightly lower. Most European markets were closed. Hong Kong was
also closed. Tokyo's Nikkei closed up 2.39 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-JEWS (Shiraz, Iran) _ The trial of 13 Jews opens; a court
spokesman says a main suspect has confessed to training under
Mossad in Israel. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ Turkey's Parliament on Monday
failed for a second time to muster the two-thirds vote necessary to
elect the reformist candidate for president favored by party
leaders. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-WORKERS (Rome) _ Preempting trade unions' traditional hold
on May 1st, Pope John Paul II presided over a workers rally Monday
that combined a solemn Catholic mass with a raucous rock concert
dedicated to third world debt relief. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   RED-CROSS-ISRAEL (United Nations) _ Fallout over moves to have
Israel join Red Cross. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup: Texas had amended its sex
crimes law to make it easier to win a conviction, and it was
applied after the fact. An affected defendant won a 5-4 decision
overturning his conviction. Justices Scalia and Thomas in the
majority of this expansionist view of ex post facto changes. The
Supreme Court also rules in a case that asks the question: Can an
employer require workers to use comp time or lose it? The court
answers yes. Plus other court developments. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE-SCHOOLS (Washington) _ A complicated lawsuit involving
Baltimore's schooling for special education students has settled.
What is notable, however, is that it was done with the mediation of
a federal judge not involved in the case, the beginning of a trend
in using judges to do this. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH-DEVELOP (Pittsburgh) _ For this city's strong-willed
mayor, 61 old downtown buildings and 125 merchants in them are
standing in the way of the downtrodden area's renewal and should be
torn down. But the National Trust calls his plan `the most
wrongheaded revitalization proposal to appear anywhere in this
country in the last 30 years.'' In these economic boom times, many
downtowns are undergoing revitalization, but none are creating as
big a political fight. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT19-28 on 4-28; graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins'
``Public Interests.''
