<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEMENS-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIEMENS TO BUY SHARED MEDICAL FOR $2.1 BILLION IN CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER FRIEDLIN   
 TheStreet.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ German industrial giant Siemens (SMAWY:NASDAQ) said
on Monday that it had agreed to purchase Shared Medical Systems
(SMS:NYSE), a developer of services and information technology
systems for the health care industry, in a cash deal valued at $2.1
billion
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Siemens will pay $73 per share in
cash, a 76 percent premium over Shared Medical Systems' closing
price of 41 7/16 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens of Munich said the acquisition would help the company to
expand the range of information technology services it provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strategic perspective, our competencies in medical
technologies and SMS' strength in health care information
technology and networking makes this an optimal fit,'' Erich
Reinhardt, president of Siemens Medical Engineering Group, said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens Medical Engineering provides a full range of products
and services for the health care industry. A division of Siemens,
Siemens Medical Engineering employs 4,500 people in the U.S. and
has annual sales of about $1.8 billion. Siemens Medical Systems is
its U.S. affiliate and is based in Iselin, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Shared Medical of Malvern, Pa., specializes in developing
information technology systems for hospitals. The company has 7,600
employees and generates annual sales of about $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens and Shared Medical expect the tender offer to be
launched within the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Eclipsys (ECLP:NASDAQ) made a $2 billion unsolicited bid to buy
Shared Medical earlier this year but dropped the offer after being
acquired by Neoforma.com (NEOF:NASDAQ).
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
