<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2464 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      05-01 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: A CASE FOR EXPANDING THE DOCTOR'S CHECKLIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What should your doctor know about you even before you have
donned that unglamorous gown and related the reason for your visit?
On a recent first visit to an internist, I was handed a medical
history form that struck me as unusually thorough in exploring
factors that could affect my health or influence any symptoms I
might have. The form reflected some of the most pressing
medical-social issues of our day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the usual questions about my personal and family
medical history, current symptoms or complaints about my health,
allergies, operations, immunizations and personal habits like
smoking and drinking, I was asked:
</P>
<P>
   _Do you wear seat belts?
</P>
<P>
   _Do you wear a bike helmet?
</P>
<P>
   _If there is a gun in your home, is it out of children's reach
and unloaded?
</P>
<P>
   _Do you use drugs (marijuana, cocaine, crack, etc.)?
</P>
<P>
   _Have you ever engaged in any activity which has put you at risk
of getting AIDS?
</P>
<P>
   _Do you wish to be tested for AIDS?
</P>
<P>
   _Have you worked with chemicals, paints, asbestos or other
hazardous materials?
</P>
<P>
   _Are you in a relationship in which you have been physically
hurt (e.g. slapped, kicked, punched, bruised) by your partner?
</P>
<P>
   _Do you ever feel afraid of your partner?
</P>
<P>
   _Do you have a ``living will''?
</P>
<P>
   _Do you have a donor card?
</P>
<P>
   Also, in questioning me about the medicines I take, the form
asks about over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, herbs and other
supplements. Many people treat themselves for all kinds of problems
with over-the-counter supplements, often failing to realize that a
substance with a druglike effect is a drug and can have side
effects, including bad interactions with prescriptions. Also, those
who take megadoses of nutrients may be distorting their metabolism
and inducing deficiencies of important nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Never had I been asked about such matters: the kinds of
questions that should make patients think about how they may put
themselves or their families at risk and what they can do to
improve their chances of living healthfully, ending life peacefully
and passing on their viable organs to others.
</P>
<P>
   As impressed as I was about these queries, I was surprised by
the absence of others. I was asked about coffee, tea and alcohol
consumption, but not about diet or weight-related issues. Nor were
there any questions about exercise or stress reduction.
</P>
<P>
   So while I was delighted to see doctors taking note of items
like seat belts and guns, I was dismayed by the seeming lack of
concern about eating, exercise and stress reduction. Excess stress
can undermine the immune system and render a person susceptible to
conditions like frequent infections, cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that I am asking a lot from doctors. Not only must
they know about symptoms, tests, medicines and a 2,700-page book of
ailments, but also about matters rarely discussed in training. But
evidence shows that the foods people eat, how much they exercise,
whether they are chronically stressed and how well they cope with
stress can affect their health and well-being, including their risk
of developing heart disease, cancer, hypertension, diabetes,
osteoporosis and depression. Thus, it becomes increasingly
important for doctors to bone up on these matters and start asking
about them.
</P>
<P>
   And while doctors may not feel competent to offer nutrition or
exercise advice or tips on stress reduction, they should be able to
refer patients to dietitians, exercise physiologists or mental
health professionals trained to handle such problems.
</P>
<P>
   The medical history questionnaire I completed did ask some other
important questions: the dates of my last Pap smear, my last
mammogram and breast exam, cholesterol check and stool check for
blood. Of course, the question about a prostate exam was not
relevant to me, but is certainly important to every white man over
50 and every black man over 40.
</P>
<P>
   Also important were the questions about family medical history,
particularly health problems with hereditary components. The form
also asked whether any members of my family _ parents, grandparents
and siblings _ ever had the following disorders and at about what
age: cancer, high blood pressure, heart disease, diabetes, strokes,
mental disease, drug or alcohol addiction, glaucoma, bleeding
disorders or any other significant problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although I had long thought I came from pretty hardy stock,
completing this portion of the questionnaire got me thinking twice
about my potential medical vulnerability. My father and grandfather
had heart disease, first diagnosed in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   My mother died from ovarian cancer at 49; her father died of
prostate cancer at 60, and her mother died of esophageal cancer in
her 70s. My paternal grandmother had adult-onset diabetes,
diagnosed in her 50s, and had strokes in her 80s and 90s. My
brother at age 54 has high blood pressure and moderately high
cholesterol, which he is wisely getting treated so that he does not
suffer the same fates.
</P>
<P>
   So, all in all, it was a good idea for me to get a checkup.
Answering those questions reinforced my determination to live a
health-promoting life, which includes a diet rich in vegetables and
fruits and whole grains, the use of olive and canola oils in place
of saturated fats like butter and hydrogenated vegetable oils
(found mainly in processed foods) and moderate amounts of animal
protein, including some lean red meat but also lots of fish.
</P>
<P>
   I do not need encouragement to exercise. I do a brisk three-mile
walk and swim half a mile or more daily and play tennis three or
four times a week. Depending on the season, I ice-skate,
cross-country ski, hike and cycle, and I use my bike whenever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   I even got a shorter haircut so my bike helmet would cause less
havoc. Regular physical activity is my primary means of coping with
the stresses of modern life. I do not meditate or do yoga, but
these are two other effective stress reducers for those who need
some extra calming down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
