<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HN     05-01 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DON'T BLAME ROBINSON FOR SPURS' PLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM DENT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It reminded me of a place far away and a time when
Benny Barnes wasn't the best cornerback in the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   But he was the toughest and clearly the hardest working.
</P>
<P>
   Benny had blown out an ankle, but he wasn't about to let Lynn
Swann score. This happened on a cold day at Three Rivers Stadium
when the Cowboys and the Steelers had the hottest rivalry going in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Down on both knees, Benny started crawling toward Swann, and
managed to tackle him 3 yards short of the goal. It made you want
to shout.
</P>
<P>
   When I saw David Robinson on Saturday afternoon against the
Phoenix Suns, I thought of Benny.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it wasn't the 37 points or the 13 rebounds or the 43 minutes
that he logged. It was the relentless effort.
</P>
<P>
   I had scribbled on my game notes ``powerful'' and ``a real
force'' and ``I can't believe this is David.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, in a place they call the Valley of the Sun, I hereby title
him the Desert Ox.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't David Robinson dilly-dallying with that pretty
16-foot jumper. This was the Desert Ox in the paint, in your face,
on top of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   This was the San Antonio Spurs center with four guys around him,
each trying to pound his bones into desert sand.
</P>
<P>
   This clearly was a man trying to carry a team, a city and a
championship trophy on his wide shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   This was David Robinson with the hammer down.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, during that 32-15 comeback run, the Suns
didn't take the game away from the Spurs. They had to wrest it from
the fingers of Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   This is what I suggested to Robinson: I told him that it wasn't
his greatest statistical game, and certainly it was the most
important contest that he had ever graced.
</P>
<P>
   But in the real big picture, it might have been his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best game ever?'' he said. ``I don't know about ever. It
was a good all-around game.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and relented. ``It's my best game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the comparisons to Benny Barnes end with the mettle
both men displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Benny was sent packing in the early 1980s, never to be heard
from again. At least by me.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, when he retires, is headed for the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked Suns coach Scott Skiles if he was surprised about
David's big game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprised?'' he said with a touch of salt. ``How can I be
surprised about David Robinson? He is one of the greatest players
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Suns are trying to do is pound Robinson until he pulls
out of the paint. That's why he attempted 18 free throws. To the
Suns' chagrin, he made 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do with David is make him work for
everything he gets and therefore he will be a little tired by the
end of the game,'' Skiles said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he scored only four points in the fourth quarter as the
Suns blew past the Spurs like a racehorse past an ox.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same strategy they will employ Tuesday night in Game
4. I submit that Avery Johnson and Antonio Daniels need to be on
the floor at the same time in order to increase the offensive flow.
</P>
<P>
   Let A.J. run the offense, let Daniels blow past the Suns with
that quick first step.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan, by the way, is not coming back this season. We can
all forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   He said Sunday: ``I want to be out there when I feel good. I
want to be out there on the floor when I don't think I will hurt
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   So it will be David vs. Goliath on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound trite. But true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
