<HEADER>
A2471 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-N     05-01 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATTERNS: The Brain Cells That Make You Sleepy
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in France and Switzerland have isolated the brain
cells that may bring on sleepiness and traced part of an intricate
chemical back-and-forth between substances that promotes alertness
or lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's issue of Nature, the researchers described the
``sleep-producing neurons'' as standing out from the surrounding
tissue through their triangular shape, unusual cycle of electrical
activity and, most importantly, through their unusual reactions to
certain brain chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies have shown that the region at the base of the
brain where these neurons are found is active whenever the brain is
asleep.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the team, Thierry Gallopin, a neurobiologist in
Lyon, determined that for the brain to wake, these neurons had to
be suppressed by the action of noradrenaline and other substances
known to excite brain activity. At other times, the action of the
sleep-producing neurons appears, in turn, to suppress the release
of those ``wakeful'' substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sleep-producing cells and those in the waking systems are
able to inhibit each other,'' said Professor Michel Muehlethaler of
Geneva. ``A person will fall asleep as soon as the sleep neurons
become activated and inhibit the neurons in the waking systems.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the deeper mystery _ what causes the balance to
swing toward sleep or alertness _ remained.
</P>
<P>
   REACTIONS: The Blanket Approach to Pediatrics
</P>
<P>
   A child's favorite blanket can be as effective as a parent in
comforting a 3-year-old on a visit to the doctor, a study published
last month in the Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians sometimes prefer to examine a child without a
parent present. But that raises the problem of managing the natural
anxiety reaction among small children left alone with a relative
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gabriel Ybarra and Dr. Richard Passman, researchers at the
University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee, randomly assigned 64 children
to doctor visits accompanied by their blankets for comfort, their
mothers, both and neither.
</P>
<P>
   They found that blankets for children known to be attached to
them appeared to mitigate anxiety as much as a mother's presence
and that there was no additional benefit when a child had both.
</P>
<P>
   For moderately upsetting medical procedures, the researchers
wrote, ``blankets can function as appropriate maternal
substitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   STANDARDS: When the Label Doesn't Measure Up
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of ephedra supplements, an herbal remedy sold as a
decongestant, energy booster or diet aid, found significant
differences between what their label said and their actual contents
in half the samples examined, according to researchers, who also
found that some contained hazardous combinations of substances.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, from the University of Arkansas for Medical
Sciences, tested 20 supplements with ephedra alkaloids, which they
said had been linked to hundreds of adverse reactions and several
deaths. They found that in 10 cases, the discrepancy between the
label and the contents was greater than 20 percent, far more than
the amount that would set off a recall of regulated medications.
One product contained no ephedra alkaloids; one had 154 percent of
the amount listed, the researchers reported in May in the American
Journal of Health-System Pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   The study's lead researcher, Bill Gurley, concluded that the
survey showed that ``poor quality control may contribute to the
problems associated with the safety and efficacy of ephedra
supplements.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Blumenthal, executive director of the American Botanical
Council, said he questioned some study methods and thought
ephedra's potential danger was exaggerated, but he agreed that a
clear ``lack of quality control'' existed in much of the
supplements industry.
</P>
<P>
   Until the government establishes guidelines, he recommended that
consumers buy supplements from well-respected companies,
particularly those linked to companies in Europe, where herbal
products are more rigorously regulated.
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION: Putting On the Sunblock, the Right Way
</P>
<P>
   A survey presented last week to a conference of the American
Academy of Dermatology found that many parents applied sunblock to
their children then left them in the sun longer than they normally
would have, the equivalent of a driver going faster because a car
has antilock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. June Robinson of Loyola University in Chicago, said the
survey she conducted identified other common mistakes and
misperceptions about sunblock. In an interview, she offered these
suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _Sunblock is not enough. Even with it, try to limit time in the
sun to no more than two to three hours during the peak sunburn
hours, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _Use enough. Most parents surveyed used half the recommended
amount _ one ounce to cover exposed skin _ sharply cutting the
protection, Robinson said. Colored sunblocks may be easier to apply
evenly. Remember the easily overlooked spots, like the tops of ears
or feet.
</P>
<P>
   _Put it on before leaving the house. Sunblock takes 20 to 30
minutes to bind properly with skin, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   _Reapply it every two hours, or after the skin gets wet from
swimming or sweating.
</P>
<P>
   _Use a broad spectrum block that protects against ultraviolet A
and B rays.
</P>
<P>
   _Do not use sunblock on children younger than 6 months. Because
they dehydrate quickly, they should not be exposed to direct sun
for any extended time.
</P>
<P>
   _Set an example. Children who see their parents wearing hats and
remembering the umbrella are more likely to develop habits to
reduce their risk of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to hide under the porch,'' Robinson said, ``but
seek shade whenever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   TREATMENTS: Guidelines for Attacking Migraine Pain
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can do more now to help migraine sufferers, but the
condition still goes underdiagnosed and undertreated, the American
Academy of Neurology said last week in announcing new guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Silberstein, a neurologist in Philadelphia and
co-director of the U.S. Headache Consortium, which developed the
guidelines, called migraine an extraordinarily common disorder
affecting 18 percent of women and 6 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Silberstein said the first misconception the
guidelines intended to dispel was that people had to be ``seeing
flashing lights or be bedridden for a headache to be migraine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has a disabling headache _ one that interferes
with the ability to function _ particularly if accompanied by
nausea or sensitivity to sound, light or odor, should be considered
migraine until proven otherwise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines also say that expensive brain scans used to rule
out more serious headache causes are usually unneeded in otherwise
healthy people.
</P>
<P>
   Once a diagnosis is made, Silberstein said, a doctor should
educate the patient about the condition, now considered to result
from changes in blood flow in the brain caused by improperly
functioning nerves. Then a treatment should be developed,
alternating medicines until the most effective are found.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, doctors should work with patients to change their
habits to lessen contributing factors, like fatigue or stress, and
to use techniques like biofeedback and exercise to help keep the
headaches from coming on in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
