<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hope for Old Abba Discs
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart's got nothing on the researchers at the Royal
Institute of Technology in Stockholm. They've come up with a novel
home crafts project: turning that old Monkees' Greatest Hits album
into a lens for an X-ray microscope.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays, particularly the higher energy kind known as hard
X-rays, can be bent _ or refracted _ by a lens, just as light beams
can (though X-ray lenses are not made of glass). X-rays are
refracted only slightly, though, so the only practicable refractive
lenses have been compound ones, made up of many lenses in a line.
And these lenses have parabolic surfaces, which can make them
difficult to fabricate.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish researchers, writing in the journal Nature, have
described a new way of making a lens that has straight surfaces. In
theory, the lens could be made of two two-inch strips cut from a
vinyl LP, joined at one end and separated slightly at the other so
that the strips with their grooves resemble the open jaw of an
alligator, viewed from the side. X-rays entering at the closed end
would skim across the hills and valleys of the grooves, refracting
slightly as they passed through each succeeding hill and eventually
coming to a common focus.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, however, the researchers found that the grooves on
a record were too shallow (about 25 microns deep), and that there
was too much material between them, to make a useful lens. So they
made their own record, with a uniform groove that is 90 microns
deep, about four times as deep as those on an LP. But don't look
for it in record stores anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Mangle That Tune
</P>
<P>
   In the old television game show ``Name That Tune,'' contestants
vied to see who could identify a popular melody faster (``I can
name that tune in five notes, Tom,'' a contestant would tell Tom
Kennedy, the host of the 1970s version of the show).
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Cambridge in England haven't
been competing for cash prizes or even seven-piece bedroom sets,
but they have been using a nightmarish version of the game in order
to test a theory about how the brain recognizes a tune. Their
theory, as described in the journal Nature, is that when the brain
initially experiences a melody, a template of pitch and time is
formed that is then used as a basis for comparison when the melody
is heard again.
</P>
<P>
   The research subjects listened to some or all of the first 18
notes of Mozart's ``Eine Kleine Nachtmusik'' with increasing
numbers of random notes _ tens to hundreds of them _ added. The
researchers, who noted that their results were only preliminary,
found that the subjects could tolerate greater numbers of ``noise''
notes (and still identify Mozart's melody) as the number of correct
notes increased. This supports the template idea, the researchers
said, in that the more notes that match the template, the better
the brain can name that tune.
</P>
<P>
   Physics With Mass Appeal
</P>
<P>
   Physicists are no doubt sleeping better these days, thanks to
some precision measurements by researchers at the University of
Washington. They've reduced the uncertainty in Newton's
gravitational constant, a fundamental value that enables
measurement of the mass of the Earth and other planets.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was first measured by Henry Cavendish in 1797, the
constant, represented as G, has been known only to varying levels
of uncertainty. The latest internationally accepted value had an
uncertainty of .15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For their measurements, which have an uncertainty of about .0015
percent, the University of Washington researchers used an improved
version of a torsion balance. It consists of a pendulum that
rotates on a turntable between a set of ``attractor'' masses,
precisely milled stainless steel balls.
</P>
<P>
   Using the result, the Washington scientists also announced a new
value of the Earth's mass: about 6 sextillion metric tons. That's a
6 with 21 zeros after it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
