<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-LYMEDISEASE-LIFEBEAT-1166&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFICULT TO DIAGNOSE, LYME DISEASE CAN ALSO BE DIFFICULT TO CURE 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Annie Berthold-Bond writes about solutions for nontoxic living
and is the author of ``Better Basics for the Home'' and ``The Green
Kitchen Handbook.''
 &HT;     &HT;    
 By ANNIE BERTHOLD-BOND as told to JOSEPH V. AMODIO 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   It all started four summers ago, back in June 1996: the crushing
headache, a high fever, a circular rash under my armpit and
excruciating jaw pain every time I opened my mouth. After four or
five days of this agony, I went to see a nurse practitioner, who
diagnosed the jaw pain as sinusitis and prescribed an antibiotic.
She attributed the rash to an infected mole, which she removed.
Then, giving a thought to Lyme disease, she asked whether I had
been bitten by a tick. ``Not to the best of my knowledge,'' I
replied. Within 12 hours of starting the antibiotics, I was feeling
better.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, I was experiencing myriad small complaints _ a
stiff neck, unusual fatigue, general malaise. Burdened with
demanding work deadlines, I ignored these health concerns until
large, red circular rashes developed all over my skin _ a symptom,
I would later learn, indicating that Lyme-disease bacteria had
disseminated throughout my body.
</P>
<P>
   I was constantly thirsty and started having dizzy spells. At the
time, I was traveling in New Hampshire, where the disease is a
rarity, and I became quite a sensation when I showed up at
Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in Hanover. It was there that I
was finally diagnosed _ both clinically and with the traditional
antibody tests _ with Lyme.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered taking a walk in late May in the woods near my home
in Dutchess County, N.Y., one of the hot spots for the Lyme
epidemic. That's when I must have fallen prey to a deer tick, which
can transmit the Lyme-causing corkscrew-shaped spirochetal
bacterium (Borrelia burgdorferi) to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Infection by this bacterium is especially tricky because it is
able to mimic symptoms of many other illnesses, which makes Lyme
difficult to diagnose and treat. And tiny as the ticks are in the
spring during their nymphal stage _ the size of a pinhead _ the
bite was easy to miss.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-day course of oral antibiotics often stops early-stage Lyme
if it is diagnosed and treated within two weeks of the bite.
Symptoms _ which include flulike aches, fever, jaw pain, headaches
and, in two-thirds of cases, a bull's-eye rash _ usually surface
within four to 30 days of a bite. The spirochetes, however, can
spread throughout the body within two weeks after symptoms first
appear, entering the joints and organs and making antibiotic
treatment more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that was the case for me. I developed painful
joints, crushing fatigue and debilitating short-term memory
problems. At my worst, I stuck Post-its to my sleeve to remind me
of what I needed to do.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of my official Lyme diagnosis, I had to go through
an 18-month regimen of antibiotic shots and pills. To support my
body during this time, I turned to alternative therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Because high doses of antibiotics can disrupt friendly
intestinal flora _ and bring on yeast infections, an upset stomach
and diarrhea _ I took acidophilus, a ``probiotic'' supplement that
replenishes the body's stores of beneficial bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   I also refrained from eating sugar and such yeast-containing
foods as breads and vinegars whenever possible. In addition, I went
to an infrared sauna, used in hospitals and sports-medicine
facilities, for a 45-minute session every day for a year. This
sauna, which operates at temperatures lower than those in the
traditional type (102 degrees is said to be effective), mimics the
radiant heat of the sun and penetrates deep into the body.
</P>
<P>
   My doctor, Richard Horowitz, the assistant director of medicine
at Vassar Brothers Hospital in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., and an internist
who specializes in treating Lyme, believes that raising body
temperature in this way increases the potency of antibiotics,
stimulates the immune system, can alleviate aches and pains and may
help destroy toxins created by the spirochetes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, tick-borne diseases don't end with Lyme, and
antibody tests confirmed that I also had both babesiosis and
ehrlichiosis, the two co-infections most commonly seen in Lyme
patients. Treating these co-infections is critical in helping
patients fully recover, Horowitz says, because they exacerbate Lyme
and make it harder to eradicate.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms for these ailments _ which manifest themselves within
several weeks of a tick bite _ are similar to Lyme's and, if left
untreated, can persist for years: Ehrlichiosis, caused by the
ehrlichia bacterium, is marked by a high fever, headaches and neck
and/or joint pain. Babesiosis, caused by a malaria-like
red-blood-cell parasite, can bring on malaise, fever, muscular pain
and headaches. I had a particularly bad case of the latter
infection, which accounted for my exhaustion. Horowitz treated me
with more oral antibiotics for the ehrlichiosis, plus quinine and
other antimalarial drugs for the babesiosis.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the effects of these pharmaceuticals on my body
and still suffering fatigue, joint pain and short-term-memory loss
when my antibiotic treatment was completed, I consulted Bonnie
Tarttier, M.S., a holistic nutritionist in New York's mid-Hudson
Valley. She tailored a treatment aimed at strengthening my immune
system so that it would have a better chance of fighting off the
host of diseases ticks can carry.
</P>
<P>
   To find the right supplements for me, she used an acubiofeedback
computer, which, she explained, detects viruses, heavy metals,
parasites, pesticides and other bodily stressors by measuring the
energy of the body at various acupuncture meridian points. My Lyme
disease, babesiosis, and ehrlichiosis all registered on the
machine, whose database of natural remedies pinpointed the right
ones for me.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the computer's findings, Tarttier recommended
homeopathic remedies as well as homeovitic ones (vitamins given at
homeopathic dosages), to eradicate the parasites and bacteria;
horsetail tea, to strengthen my kidneys; and antioxidants
(including vitamin E and grapeseed extract), to enhance immunity.
She also prescribed an herbal formula specifically designed for
Lyme disease sufferers called Spirolyd (available through
health-care professionals). Containing sarsaparilla rhizome,
guiaiac wood, prickly-ash bark, hyssop herb and stillingia root,
Spirolyd acts as an antibacterial and anti-inflammatory agent,
especially when taken in conjunction with a
body-temperature-elevating therapy such as the infrared sauna.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours of being on these remedies, I experienced
dramatic improvements in terms of energy and the ability to focus
and was able to resume full-time work on a book project.
</P>
<P>
   Today, four years after I first fell ill, I feel absolutely
fine. I avoid walking in the woods in early spring when the deer
ticks are out in full force, sticking instead to pebbled paths
where grass won't brush against my legs. I don't want my family,
who watched my struggle with this illness, to live in fear of
ticks, so I encourage them to get outside often. And I check my
daughter and my dogs very carefully when they return home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEWARE THE BUG'S BITE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your best defense against Lyme disease is to avoid the deer
tick's primary habitat _ tall grass, brush, or woods. If you do go
for a wooded walk, take the following precautions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cover up. Wear light colors (which make spotting a tick on
your body easier), long sleeves and long pants; tuck your pant legs
into your socks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a nontoxic tick repellent. To make your own: Place 10
drops of rose-geranium essential oil in an ounce of vegetable oil
and dab a few drops on your clothing and your dog's collar; be sure
to avoid eyes. If you're short on time, try Quantum's 100% Natural
Tick Repellent (800-348-0398), available in health-foods stores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check your skin as soon as you return home. Do frequent spot
checks for ticks on yourself, your children and your pets. If you
find one, remove it immediately by pulling it up and out with
tweezers. Watch for symptoms of infection (bull's-eye rash, joint
pain or fever) and contact your physician immediately if any
develop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE LYME-LIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reports of new Lyme disease cases remain abundant, but
innovative tests and therapies are making the condition easier to
treat. Some developments on the horizon:
</P>
<P>
   _ According to ``The Journal of the American Medical Society,''
a test that can detect the spirochetal bacterium itself should be
available this fall. (Traditional antibody tests are notorious for
false negatives, since it takes four to six weeks for antibodies to
develop _ and, in some cases, they may never develop at all.) The
new test can be used as early as a week after a tick bite,
distinguishes between active and past infection and is reported to
be 96 percent accurate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Still in the research stage, the use of hyperbaric (high
pressure) oxygen is showing promise as a therapy. A patient
breathes pure oxygen 60 minutes a day for two months. Researchers
speculate that the oxygen reaches and kills hidden bacteria that
have been left unaffected by antibiotics. Early results from tests
at Texas A&AMP;M University suggest that this therapy can relieve the
joint pain, neurological symptoms and other complications of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new Lyme disease vaccine may make sense for anyone who
spends a lot of time in the woods. Administered in three shots over
three to 12 months, LYMErix is 50 percent effective after the first
two doses and 78 percent effective after the third (an annual
booster is advised). The vaccine won't protect against other
tick-borne diseases, however. It is currently not generally
recommended for pregnant women or children under age 15.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
