<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S MORE EXPENSIVE _ EDUCATION OR IGNORANCE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush should begin a serious public
dialogue on how to reduce dramatically the financial burden of
escalating college tuition and fees, at least for medium- and
low-income American families.
</P>
<P>
   Never in history has spreading college education broadly been so
essential to a nation's future. Strength in the global society is
knowledge, not arms.
</P>
<P>
   America's cutting-edge businesses are importing educated
employees with technical skills from Asia and Europe while U.S.
youngsters go begging for the high-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Never has higher education been so indispensable to a young
person's future. Students graduating this spring with bachelor's
degrees will earn, on average, about $1 million more in their
lifetimes than their contemporaries with only high school diplomas.
Graduate degrees add even more.
</P>
<P>
   But never, sadly, has the price for obtaining higher education
in the United States risen so rapidly as since 1980. Even when
adjusted for inflation, the cost of four years in college has more
than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   During the past nine years, I've served on the board of trustees
for Texas Wesleyan University and taught a course at Texas
Christian University. I've watched two grandsons finish state
universities and two others graduate from private universities.
</P>
<P>
   In that decade I've lectured at 35 institutions of higher
learning _ from the University of Maine to San Diego State, from
Gonzaga to the University of Florida. I've talked with a lot of
college students.
</P>
<P>
   Varied student aid plans help many get the schooling that they
crave, but thousands of other desirous youths are falling through
the cracks each year, unable to meet higher education's rising
costs. The loss is not theirs alone, but the nation's.
</P>
<P>
   In one tax-supported Texas school, a professor laments: ``In the
last six years tuition has tripled, faculties have received no pay
raise, not even COLAs, and campuses have been physically
deteriorating for want of maintenance funding.''
</P>
<P>
   An award-winning Ph.D. professor with 25 years' experience tells
me that he makes $28,000 annually at a state-supported college and
cannot afford to send his own child to college.
</P>
<P>
   The share of family income required to pay college expenses has
increased markedly for middle-income families, and even more
frighteningly for those on the lower economic rung.
</P>
<P>
   According to the College Board, middle-income families paid
about 13 percent of their earnings to sustain one student in a
public four-year college in the 1970s, or 26 percent for a private
university that would cost 44 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   For working families that earn less than median income _ below
$35,000 annually _ the picture is even scarier. To maintain one
student in a state-supported university in the 1970s would have
cost such a family about 37 percent of its income (barely doable),
but a prohibitive 61 percent in the current school year.
</P>
<P>
   The average private university? Forget it! That would take 162
percent of the average low-income family's total earnings for one
student this semester.
</P>
<P>
   All this bodes ill for the future. It turns America's history in
a counterclockwise direction. Our distinguishing national
characteristic has been an ever-broadening field of opportunity and
an ever-improving lifestyle for the average American.
</P>
<P>
   The GI Bill of Rights that followed World War II provided
history's greatest single stimulus to upward mobility. From the
1940s to the early 1970s, the percent of our college-age generation
that was able to finish four years of college more than quadrupled,
growing from 4.5 percent to 21 percent. President Lyndon B.
Johnson's continuing insistence on expanding educational
opportunity kept that momentum going.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that upward spiral in America's educational level
was stymied beginning in 1981, when Reagan budget cuts began
hacking away at federal educational assistance. Through the 1990s,
federal support has inched upward almost imperceptibly but hasn't
recovered the slack caused from lost momentum in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton made an effort at the beginning of his
first term with AmeriCorps. That bold initiative was harshly
truncated by a penurious Congress, reduced to a tiny experimental
level and never allowed to approach its potential.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to give free tuition in exchange for specific
public service rendered on officially approved public projects
(similar to the Depression-era WPA or CCC, except that the payoff
would be education rather than wages).
</P>
<P>
   With the right start and enthusiastic support, that initiative
could have worked. It still might. Trading opportunity to ambitious
kids from working families, it could have been as big as the Peace
Corps _ almost as big as the GI Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rapidly escalating tuition and fees across America are not the
results of poor university management or slothful spending, or of
declining philanthropic gifts. They're the unavoidable results of
shrinking state and federal financial participation.
</P>
<P>
   The statistical review presented by the College Board reveals
that private gifts and grants covered 5 percent of college costs in
1980 and 6 percent in 1996. Local government contributions remain
steady at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal role fell to only 12 percent, and state
governments reduced their share of university support from 31
percent down to 23 percent. The only thing left to take up the
slack has been to raise student-paid tuition and fees. That is
throttling the dramatic expansion of higher education that the
times increasingly demand.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, taxpayers collectively ante up about $42,000 a year
for each prisoner in our burgeoning penitentiaries, but only about
$3,200 for each student in our state institutions of higher
learning.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody once complained to then-Sen. Lloyd Bentsen that public
higher education was an expensive burden to the taxpayer. ``That's
right,'' replied Bentsen, ``but not half as expensive as
ignorance!''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
