u a BC-GIULIANI-CANCER-FUTUR     05-01 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-CANCER-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: PUTTING CANCER IN ITS PLACE AND FEELING IN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Will Mayor Rudolph Giuliani pursue his Senate
campaign now that he has prostate cancer?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question many are asking right now, and mostly the
matter is being analyzed in political terms. You have no doubt
heard the theories. The prevailing one: That maybe Giuliani will
not run because he was never all that fired up about being a
senator anyway. Others say that of course he will run, that he is
even stronger now, more sympathetic and acting more congenial. The
mayor will not decide about the campaign for a few weeks, after he
selects a course of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly do not presume to have any insights into his
thinking. But I will presume to make a few informed predictions,
the central one being that the mayor's decision will not be
political. It will be deeply personal. And if his prognosis remains
favorable and his cancer is treatable, as his doctors now say, then
for sure he will continue his campaign for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions can be risky. But I do not think this one is, for a
reason about as basic as you can get: the force of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted with a life-threatening disease, people
overwhelmingly want to do precisely what they were doing before
that awful day in the doctor's office when they got the news.
</P>
<P>
   Unless hit with an incapacitating condition, most patients want
normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   Some may choose to go on a world tour, or, as a friend did
temporarily, indulge a desire to write poetry. Some collapse under
the pressure. But most want things to be the way they were, because
that helps you feel normal at a time when nothing else does.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre went back to managing the Yankees after his treatment
for prostate cancer last year. Ed Koch went back to being mayor
after he had a minor stroke in 1987. David Letterman returned to
his television program after his quintuple bypass surgery in
January. A dear colleague who recently died of AIDS-related
pneumonia stayed on the job, choosing to work his regular night
shift as an editor, after his diagnosis years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, a freelance writer, celebrated when she got a
routine magazine assignment while she was in chemotherapy for
breast cancer. She could be herself again, she said.
</P>
<P>
   I remember feeling the same way when, after a lumpectomy for
breast cancer seven years ago, I continued to work while I
underwent radiation and chemotherapy. It's not that you want to be
heroic. It's that you want to prove _to yourself more than to
anyone else _ that you are still you.
</P>
<P>
   That a few errant cells wreaking havoc on your body had not
impeded your ability to function as ever you had.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, too, being resentful of the cancer's frightful
power. When you have a serious illness that you cannot control, you
want to control what you can, especially your daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working gives you strength, brings you back into the world,''
Barbara Barrie, the actress, said the other day. She appeared in a
starring role in Anne Meara's ``After-Play'' during her
chemotherapy treatments for colo-rectal cancer in 1994. ``I
instinctively knew that working would help my recovery,'' said
Barrie, who wrote about her illness in ``Don't Die of
Embarrassment'' (Scribner, 1999). ``George Bernard Shaw called it a
life force _ what you experience as a human being, a determination
to get back into life, be a part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's life is politics. It is very possible that he does
not relish being one of 100 senators; that, facing the end of his
mayoral tenure next year because of term limits, he decided to run
for Senate by default. He would probably rather be governor,
running things. But Gov. George Pataki may run again in 2002 and
that would leave Giuliani in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   That was clearly the mayor's calculation when he decided to try
for the Senate. The betting here is that, prognosis permitting, he
will return to sparring with Hillary Rodham Clinton after he
recovers from his course of treatment _ not because his illness
changed the political calculus, though it might.
</P>
<P>
   But because, despite his often fierce demeanor, Giuliani is not
all that different from the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, he, too, will want to thumb his nose at cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, will want to feel in control, connected to the world
and his prediagnosis life. When he got the bad news last Wednesday,
he was a politician running for office. He still is.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Rudy run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
