<SLUG> BC-PETS-DOGS-TRAINING-LIFEBEAT-803&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A BETTER RELATIONSHIP WITH YOUR PUP, THINK LIKE A DOG
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Toni Gardner is a contributing editor of ``Country Living''
magazine.
 &HT;    
 By TONI GARDNER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Once, all the experts advised us to ``obedience train'' our
dogs. Now, in a trend that stresses communication, they encourage
us to ``understand their minds'' and discover the depth and
richness possible in the human-animal relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, training remains a necessity: For their own safety,
dogs must learn to sit, lie down, stay and come on request. They
also need to be taught to respect people and other pets so they can
participate comfortably within the structures of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   But training no longer requires a struggle for dominance. When
you have developed a rapport with a dog and established realistic
expectations, training becomes a lot more fun for both owner and
dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be predictable, but not rigid with our pets,'' says
Dr. Karen Overall, director of the Behavior Clinic at the
Veterinary Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania, in
Philadelphia. ``Why should we be so obsessed with walking our dogs
on a perfect heel? We ought to allow dogs some autonomy, to respect
their inherent needs. Let them sniff the sidewalk. All that yanking
and yelling just leads to problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Boss, owner of Best Friends Dog Obedience in Baltimore,
Md., supports the trend toward relaxing strict obedience standards.
``In the ideal situation,'' says Boss, ``we should be able to use
our voice and our body to communicate with our dogs in order to
shape their behavior without having to rely on clickers, treats,
extreme jerking or yelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs thrive on positive training,'' explains Boss. ``They like
knowing the rules, and they want to please you. Humans must take
the role of leader, but being the 'boss' doesn't mean being an
ogre.''
</P>
<P>
   Training a dog begins by delving into the workings of the canine
mind. From the bevy of books currently available, select and read
more than one. Once you've sorted through some of the prevailing
theories and have developed an educated point of view, consider a
class.
</P>
<P>
   Classes _ puppy kindergarten, basic obedience or the newer
companion-dog classes _ can add depth and dimension to your
new-found insight. While executing the theories and practices
you've read about, you'll have a professional on hand to guide you,
peers will encourage your progress and your dog will be interacting
with people and other dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Observe a class before signing up. ``If they won't let you sit
in,'' warns Boss, steer clear. Watch for any rough handling or
hitting. Praise should be emphasized over correction, because
successes lead to good habits.''
</P>
<P>
   Praise is an important element of any behavior modification.
You'll need to find the level that works best for your dog, so that
the dog is neither overstimulated (and loses focus) nor
underappreciated (and loses interest). If you can anticipate the
dog's behavior, and praise encouragingly while manipulating and
guiding it, rather than overcorrecting, you'll build that positive
and most rewarding foundation for appropriate behavior and a strong
bond.
</P>
<P>
   While starting a class with a newly acquired puppy is the
traditional wisdom, older dogs can learn new tricks in a basic
obedience or companion-dog class. ``We've had dogs that were 10
years old in our classes,'' says Boss, ``and today more and more
people are adopting 'secondhand dogs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some dogs respond to training more quickly and easily than
others. For many, progress in training is cumulative, moving in
bits and pieces rather than in huge leaps _ a factor that often
leads to impatience or frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every dog should have some kind of manners training, but if a
class isn't working, don't force it,'' advises Overall. Some dogs
just aren't suited to certain settings. Many basic obedience or
companion-dog classes are becoming more flexible and incorporating
playtime into the lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Overall frequently advises dog owners to try agility classes,
where dogs utilize the basics of obedience training while engaged
in directed activities that will let them thrive and have fun. And
Boss is introducing practical lessons into her puppy classes, such
as ``polite walking'' (instead of formal heeling), sitting still
for vet exams and fetching as a positive outlet for all that puppy
energy.
</P>
<P>
   However we decide to train our dogs, they are observing us all
the time. Everything we do with, or to, our dogs affects their
attitude and behavior _ from the way we let them out in the morning
to where they sleep at night.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we look upon dogs as children, entertainers, equals or
heroes, dogs expect and ardently desire for us to become their
kindly leaders. Investigating and tapping into a dog's potential
can pay off in a long and rewarding relationship. But there's an
extra benefit, too. ``Making an effort to understand the dog,''
Overall believes, ``will make you into the kind of person your dog
already believes you to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARNING BY THE BOOK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some books to get your understanding of dogs off on the
right foot. ``Kinship with All Life'' (HarperSanFrancisco; 1954;
$12), by J. Allen Boone, is a seminal book for animal lovers. Also
look for Desmond Morris' ``Dogwatching'' (Three Rivers; 1986; $8);
``Manners for the Modern Dog'' (Perfect Paws; 1994; $9.95), by Gwen
Bohnenkamp; ``Mother Knows Best or Second-Hand Dog'' (Howell; 1985
and 1988; $22.95 and $6, respectively), by Carol Lea Benjamin;
``The Tao of Bow Wow'' (Dell; 1998; $9.95), by Deborah Wood; ``The
Perfect Puppy'' (Readers Digest; 1995; $19.95), by Gwen Bailey;
and/or ``The Dog Whisperer'' (Adams Media; 1999; $10.95), by Paul
Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
