<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MOUNTAIN-BIKING-LIFEB     05-01 1625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNTAIN-BIKING-LIFEBEAT-1,542&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRIFIED AND AWED, A MOUNTAIN BIKER HITS THE SKI SLOPES
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Ken McAlpine is a freelance author who writes frequently about
health and fitness.
 &HT;    
 By KEN McALPINE 
 c.2000 Ken McAlpine. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Three hundred and seven miles northeast of Los Angeles, smack
dab in the Sierra Nevadas, Mammoth Mountain is one of California's
premier ski resorts; 15,000 skiers swarm the slopes on a good
weekend, and anyone who has ever strapped on skis knows that all of
them would be standing ahead of you in line.
</P>
<P>
   Not today. Ahead, empty gondolas swing up to Mammoth's
11,053-foot summit. Below, the slopes are bereft of skiers, this
being mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   I share the gondola with a goateed, 20-something fellow who
doesn't say a word until we roll our mountain bikes out onto the
summit. A cool wind whips in our ears. Distant mountain ridges,
many of them still capped with snow, ring us.
</P>
<P>
   Now my fellow adventurer speaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insane,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Had you approached ski resort owners 20 years ago and suggested
they open their slopes to mountain bikers in summer you might have
received the same assessment. Today, ski resorts have discovered
that summer has meaning too _ which is why there are currently over
150 resorts, including Mammoth, that entertain mountain bikers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a natural marriage. Lifts are already in place to ferry
bikers to various summits. Cross-country ski trails and access
roads already ribbon the slopes. Mammoth hosts professional
mountain bike contests and anywhere from 200 to 1,000 recreational
riders a day
</P>
<P>
   Bike rangers trained in emergency aid patrol the trails (there
are few serious injuries but lots of scrapes), and at the base of
the mountain, you can sip cappucino at the Gearhead Cafe, or buy a
trail pass, rent a bike, grab a trail map or poke through glitzy
bike gear at the Bike Center next door.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is nice. But in my mind, mountain biking's real
appeal is the chance to escape this stuff, to explore and see
supernatural beauty via two-wheel quiet _ and with 70-plus miles of
groomed single-track trails lacing 3,500 acres of slope and forest,
Mammoth offers plenty of opportunity for that.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, many of the trails can be negotiated by riders
with minimal off-road skills. Those that demand more are clearly
marked in black on the trail map and anointed with telltale names
such as Skid Marks, Brake Through and Kamikaze, the latter being a
legendary teary-eyed, snot-smearing, 4.5-mile fallaway from Mammoth
Mountain's summit that sees skilled riders hit speeds of 60-plus
mph.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that mountain biking was founded by adrenaline freaks.
But the sport has since been taken up by droves of conventional
folk who understand that life insurance policies don't cover
free-falling down crevices, and that's mostly who the
ski-cum-mountain bike resorts cater to.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to lure more business, they offer attractive packages,
too. You might enjoy a two-night hotel stay (including breakfast),
two days of mountain bike rental, a park pass and several hours
with a guide for under $300. My guide, Chris Hosking, was a
transplanted Englishman and one-time member of England's national
mountain bike team. It didn't take Hosking long to read my needs
and my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use your brakes as much as you want and take time to enjoy the
views,'' he said when we met in front of the Bike Center on a
Wednesday morning. ``Go slow, and if you get to something that's
too difficult, get off.''
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious Hosking knew teaching too. Rather than sit in
front of the Bike Center, we immediately set off down an easy
downhill trail called Paper Route so that he could judge my
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Hosking began reviewing basic off-road dos and
don'ts. Don't jam on the front brake (you'll go over the
handlebars). Don't attempt sudden directional changes in soft dirt
or mid-turn (you'll go down). Do move your butt out over your back
tire during steep descents to keep the rear wheel planted firmly on
the ground. Do scan the trail ahead (unaddressed rocks, tree roots
and drop-offs abruptly enliven a ride). Do exercise caution.
</P>
<P>
   I tried hard to focus on what Hosking was saying, but I must
confess I found it difficult to pay attention. Single track is
roughly a foot wide (and often narrower), and most of Mammoth's
single track was well groomed, at points even cupped into a sort of
smooth half-pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Riding Paper Route, a long gradual decline, was like descending
a curvy luge track. We swooped down through a tunnel of pine,
piercing cool shadows and flickering sunlight. Well, Hosking
swooped. But even my liberal use of brakes didn't dilute the magic.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually we found ourselves back at the base of the mountain.
It was time for Hosking to go, but before he did he nodded at the
summit and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can do it,'' he said, ``and now you know how to use
your brakes.''
</P>
<P>
   He surveyed the dark clouds planing overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd ride the Kamikaze now. Those clouds are going to
build. There's a risk of the gondola being closed because of
thunder and lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   I squandered as much time as I could, but the weather refused to
cooperate _ which is how I found myself standing at the summit with
my goateed friend, our noses pointed into a black sign proclaiming
``You are at the start of the Kamikaze, the West's Most Outrageous
Ride''.
</P>
<P>
   This only served to heighten Goatee's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radical,'' he grinned.
</P>
<P>
   Mounting up, he adjusted his helmet and nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you at the bottom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only if he pitched a tent. Because the important point is this _
no hill is terrifying if negotiated properly. And so my descent was
bereft of the shrieking of brakes except when I stopped, which I
did often. The view was shockingly wonderful, a head-spinning,
360-degree panorama of mountain crags and glinting lakes and great
green valleys, quilt-work squares of pine and forest and grass.
</P>
<P>
   It was so wonderful that I took the gondola back to the summit
first thing the next day. This time I descended via a tamer route
called ``Off The Top.'' I junked the map _ Mammoth's trails are
well marked with neat wooden signs _ and simply rode where my nose
led me.
</P>
<P>
   The sun warmed my face, a soft wind moved the pines. I crossed
white, bright sand and skirted tiny, round lakes, the bike's wheels
crunching merrily beneath me. I dropped through dark corridors of
pine and stopped to look at empty chairlifts swaying and creaking
in the sun. In four hours, I saw five other riders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Chris had told me it would be hard to get lost but I
did, which is how I happened on a lovely trail, soft with pine
needles and split by streams edged with purple-flowered stalks and
forded by mossy, wooden footbridges.
</P>
<P>
   Even now I can't find the trail on the map _ which is precisely
the point.
</P>
<P>
   SKI SLOPES FOR BIKING
</P>
<P>
   Over 150 ski resorts entertain mountain bikers in the United
States alone. (For a state-by-state listing, visit the National Ski
Areas Association's Web site:
www.nsaa.org/MemberUpdate/mtnbiking.htm). Many offer mountain bike
packages, complete with hotel stay and bike rental. Or you can
bring your own bike and ride off for as little as $8 for a trail
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth Mountain, Mammoth Calif., in the Sierra Nevadas, with
70-plus miles of groomed trails, lives up to its name. There are
plenty of easy trails for the novice (even a shuttle service that
leaves every 30 minutes from the Daily Grind to run you, your bike
and your homemade muffin back up to the base of the mountain).
1-800-626-6684, or www.mammoth-mtn.com
</P>
<P>
   The Killington Ski Area, Killington, Vt., has 45 miles of
lift-serviced trails and five mountains from which to descend.
Pedal to the top of 4,241-foot Killington Peak (or save your wind
and take the K1 Express Gondola). Rent bikes, enjoy guided tours
with instruction. Killington Mountain Bike Center, 802-422-6232.
For mountain bike packages, 1-800-621-MTNS. Or
www.killington.com/summer/biking.html
</P>
<P>
   On a clear day, from the top of 11,000-foot Hidden Peak at the
Snowbird Ski Resort, Salt Lake City, Utah, you can see over 100
miles. It's a happy coincidence that the rugged Wasatch Mountains
fill much of that view. Enjoy cascading waterfalls and riots of
summer wildflowers. Also, this is your chance to preview this site
for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 801-742-2222, or www.snowbird.com
</P>
<P>
   At the Chestnut Mountain Resort, Galena, Ill., you may only be
able to pedal up to 3,500 feet (this is Illinois), but you can do
so while overlooking the mighty Mississippi. As a nice bonus, you
can also ride the Twilight, a diesel-powered Victorian-style
riverboat that plies the river. 1-800-397-1320, or
www.chestnutmtn.com
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
