<SLUG> BC-SCI-ELIAN-PSYCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT TALK ABOUT BOY STIRS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By ERICA GOODE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long after the courts untangle Elian Gonzalez's future, mental
health professionals may still be pondering the meaning of their
own involvement in the Cuban boy's American odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrists and psychologists have taken an active, and often
very public, part in the unfolding drama, advising government
officials, voicing their opinions on talk shows and in news
accounts, escorting Elian on his flight to Washington and even, in
one case, assisting Diane Sawyer in her interview with the
6-year-old on ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the field are happy that their oft-maligned profession
is receiving serious notice. And they note that the experts helped
government officials make informed decisions and provided context
for a public riveted by Elian's plight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pressures of intense publicity and political interest,
others feel, at times led experts into uncharted and risky
territory.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the professionals directly involved were not
acting as Elian's doctors, bound by strict confidentiality
requirements, but as ``examiners'' or ``consultants'' hired by
third parties, a role similar to that of experts who testify in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Such functions, said Dr. Thomas Gutheil, an expert in psychiatry
and law at Harvard University Medical School, are governed by
different, often broader, ethical and clinical considerations.
</P>
<P>
   A medical escort, for example, like the government psychiatrist
who accompanied Elian on the airplane, is acting ``as a simple
observer, and is not incorporating a treatment relationship,''
Gutheil said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other mental health professionals argue that the public is
not always able to make such distinctions. And they worry that the
public discussion of Elian's case, while it may have fallen within
ethical bounds, may ultimately harm their profession.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Dr. Gunther Perdigao, a child psychoanalyst who
speaks Spanish, during the ``Good Morning America'' interview, for
instance, has stirred some controversy within the American
Psychoanalytic Association, which, at ABC's behest, recommended
Perdigao for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Perdigao said his role was to make sure Sawyer ``wasn't doing
anything that would be hurtful or damaging to the child.'' He
offered advice on how to talk to Elian, translated and suggested
the drawing exercise in which Elian drew pictures of his boat trip
from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a child therapy session,'' Perdigao said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Robert Galatzer-Levy, a psychoanalyst in Chicago, said
that he was not sure the public could tell the difference and that
the analyst's presence might have lent authority to an interview
some criticized as exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern was that it is of the greatest importance that
people, when they are talking to a mental health professional, know
that their communications are confidential,'' Galatzer-Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leon Hoffman, chairman of the psychoanalytic association's
public information committee, said members would discuss the
decision to provide an expert for the program at meetings later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Public statements about Elian's situation by professionals who
had not interviewed him personally, including the team of experts
engaged by the Immigration and Naturalization Service, also raise
difficult questions, some observers feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly legitimate for the government to seek expert
advice in complex situations,'' said Dr. Paul Applebaum, chairman
of psychiatry at the University of Massachusetts Medical School in
Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not clear to me,'' Applebaum said, ``that there is
any substantial benefit to sharing those conclusions with the
public, and there may be harm _ harm to child and harm to the
integrity of the mental health profession, resulting in the false
impression that most professionals are so quick to draw conclusions
they are willing to do so even if they haven't laid eyes on the
person.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the American Psychiatric Association
discourages psychiatrists from speaking publicly about cases
involving people they have not evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Irwin Redlener, the pediatrician who organized the team
of mental health experts for the INS, said that given what was at
stake for Elian, the fact that the consultants were acting as
government representatives and the extraordinary public scrutiny of
the case, the public comments made by the professionals were
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to be very, very careful about the words they
used,'' he said. ``And the opinions were critically germane at
virtually every step of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, many aspects of professionals' participation in
the case could benefit from some ``really thoughtful analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was so far outside the norm,'' Redlener said. ``There was
a kind of tacit approval by society to allow this unbelievable
exposure of what should have been a private matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
