<HEADLINE>
HANDMADE SIGNS, AN EARLY FORM OF ADVERTISING, NOW CHARM COLLECTORS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    ART ADV: (Photos of antique and reproduction signs available in
JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Debra Muller Price writes for ``Country Living'' magazine.
 &HT;    
 By DEBRA MULLER PRICE 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   There's something heartwarming about a hand-lettered sign that
advertises farm-stand peaches, fresh eggs or a small town ice-cream
parlor's flavors of the day. Whether it's nostalgia for
old-fashioned goods or the simplicity of the message, these
colorful pieces of Americana have long been magnets for collectors
and for artisans who strive to replicate them.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising is as American as apple pie _ and older than the
nation itself _ but Colonial trade signs relied more on symbols
than on words to relay their messages. As the nation flourished and
literacy spread, simple hand-lettered signs began to advertise the
staples of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most signs were made individually, so they're one of a kind,''
says Aarne Anton, president of the American Primitive Gallery, in
New York City. ``Each piece is a work of art. That's part of the
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The finest placards were the work of professional sign painters,
who found steady work as America became increasingly mobile
throughout the 19th and early 20th centuries. When the Gold Rush
lured people out West in the 1840s, new saloons and other
enterprises created an explosion in sign making. Decades later,
automobile travel gave rise to roadside ads, and technical
developments like the ability to lithograph pictures and messages
on tin allowed signs to be mass-produced.
</P>
<P>
   Most signs were designed to hang outdoors, where they took a
real beating from the elements. But even indoor signs endured
scratches and discoloration over time. It is this aged appearance
that today's collectors crave, and which contemporary artisans go
to great lengths to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Wood fished out of Boston Harbor gives Massachusetts craftsman
Robert Stella's signs a weathered appearance. Mary Thompson, of the
Wyoming company, Games People Played, painstakingly ages her
agrarian-themed placards with elbow grease and ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apply paint by hand and then begin the aging process, using
everything from rainwater to mud,'' she says. ``I try to mimic the
wear that would appear on a sign that has been nailed to a fruit
stand for several seasons. Creating things that look old gives my
work a connection with the past.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many artisans like Stella and Thompson who pride
themselves on the care that they take to age each of their
old-fashioned signs. The drawback to their expertise is that
unscrupulous or uninformed dealers can pass off reproductions as
valuable antiques.
</P>
<P>
   To purchase antiques with confidence, deal only with trusted
sources and learn as much as you can about the look and feel of old
pieces. Examine the front and back of a sign. Each should bear
signs of age, but the back will typically be less worn than the
front, since it most likely hung against a wall. Vintage signs also
display nail holes, screw holes or special hardware that attached
them to a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's just a board with lettering on it, you have to
question how it was attached,'' antiques dealer Aarne Anton
advises.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat emptor. Buyer beware.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUYER'S GUIDE ANTIQUES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desirable hand-lettered signs from the 19th and early 20th
centuries range from about $200 to several thousand dollars,
depending on condition and graphics. Simple mid-20th century signs
can often be found for less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEALERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ANTIQUES: &LR;  American Primitive Gallery, Aarne Anton, 594 Broadway,
205, New York, NY 10012; (212) 966-1530. Paula Rubenstein, Ltd., 65
Prince St., New York, NY 10012; (212) 966-8954. John
Sidelli/Melissa Greene, P.O. Box 1234, Sheffield, MA 01257; (413)
229-8424. Other sources include the Indianapolis Antique
Advertising Show, held three times a year in Indiana (for
information, write to P.O. Box 495092, Garland, TX 75049), and the
annual Adirondack Antiques Show, in Blue Mountain Lake, NY
(518-861-5062).
 &UR; REPRODUCTIONS: &LR;  Cabin Creek Farm, 25 Public Sq., Elizabethtown, KY
42701; (270) 234-8845. Mummert Sign Co., P.O. Box 69, East Berlin,
PA 17316; www.mummertsignco.com. Robert Stella, 186 Hayward St.,
Braintree, MA 02184. Games People Played, P.O. Box 1540, Pinedale,
WY 82941; (307) 367-2502. Jeri Wright Signs, 108 Middle Rd.,
Newbury, MA 01951; (978) 463-7446.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS: Annual dues of $35 entitle members of the Antique
Advertising Assn. of America (P.O. Box 1121, Morton Grove, IL
60053; www.pastimes.org) to six newsletters per year.
</P>
