<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ARMPIT-EFFECT-ART     05-01 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ARMPIT-EFFECT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNIFFING OUT THE RELATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the woes of Oedipus and cuckolds of every species attest,
there are many instances in which it would be useful to know just
how closely related other individuals are to oneself.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so great are the evolutionary benefits of being able to
dole out goodies like food only to one's close relations or to
avoid inbreeding by choosing mates from among nonrelatives that
some biologists have predicted that animals may evolve the ability
to recognize kin with just a sniff or a look _ a phenomenon known
as the ``armpit effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in a new study from Cornell, researchers report what some
call the first solid evidence to support this controversial
phenomenon. In the paper, published last month in the Proceedings
of the Royal Society, Dr. Jill Mateo, an animal behaviorist, and
Dr. Robert Johnston, a psychologist, concluded that golden hamsters
could recognize relatives they had never met from a group of
hamster strangers, simply by giving them a good long sniff. Never
having smelled relatives before, the hamsters, researchers say,
appear to be using their own body odor as a reference for what
family smells like, exactly as the armpit effect predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists say the logic behind the armpit effect is that some
characteristics, including smell, should reflect an animal's
genetic makeup. The closer the relationship, the more genes are
shared and the more similar, for example, the body bouquet of the
two parties should be. But the armpit effect has been difficult to
demonstrate and some experts dismissed it as impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most convincing demonstration that I've ever seen
of the armpit effect,'' said Dr. Wayne Getz, mathematical biologist
at University of California, who has looked for the armpit effect
in honeybees. The phenomenon got its colorful moniker when the
evolutionary biologist Richard Dawkins suggested that humans would
most likely compare underarm odors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Sherman, behavioral ecologist at Cornell, who was not
involved with the new study but has looked for the armpit effect in
ground squirrels, said, ``This is exciting. It's a viable way of
recognizing relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Some biologists said the new work suggested that the armpit
effect _ in which animals can compare not only their own smells,
but appearances or sounds to that of others _ could be widespread
among animals, perhaps even humans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, researchers say the new study could help explain a
number of curious phenomena like the so-called T-shirt study. In
that experiment, women were shown to prefer the smells of T-shirts
of men who were more genetically dissimilar to them, possibly in
unconscious attempts to avoid inbreeding. Scientists now say these
women may have been comparing the T-shirt smells to their own as a
way of identifying unrelated mates.
</P>
<P>
   In the armpit effect _ an animal uses only itself as a reference
not the look or smell of family members. Previous studies had been
unable to rule out the possibility that animals might be using
their family's smells as the gold standard, rather than their own
in order to claim kin.
</P>
<P>
   To keep hamsters from experiencing the smells of their real
family, researchers removed the tiny hamster pups from their nest
within hours of birth, well before they were thought to be able to
smell. Having been raised with different-smelling stranger
hamsters, the hamsters were then presented with the smells of true
siblings or foster siblings. The hamsters only sniffed briefly, an
indication that they recognized the smells as family. In contrast,
they dashed over to and then lingered much longer at the smells of
unrelated strangers _ a typical response for hamsters in defensive
mode or in search of mates.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it is astonishing that these hamsters were able to
distinguish smells of siblings at all because all the hamsters were
closely related to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all descended from four hamsters caught in the
1930s,'' said Mateo. ``If they can do it, natural populations
should be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists had predicted that animals might evolve such keen
powers of discrimination because they allowed one to reap
potentially huge evolutionary benefits. Animals that can sniff out
or spy kin can then provide food or protection to their closest
relatives only, even in proportion to the blood-tie closeness.
</P>
<P>
   Because closer relatives share more genes, animals that provide
for their close kin are helping promote the survival and
reproduction of their own genes, exactly what natural selection is
all about. In addition, many animals _ including humans _ appear to
avoid inbreeding, making identifying nonrelatives critical.
</P>
<P>
   Just what golden hamsters are using their keen powers of
genealogical discrimination for in nature remains unknown.
Well-known as a laboratory species, golden hamsters have been
poorly studied in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   The new study may also help explain a curious discovery in
peacocks. Male peacocks gather in groups to display to females to
entice females to mate. In other species, such cooperative males
have been found to be closely related, probably because often only
one male gets all the matings. But researchers studying peacocks in
Whipsnade Park in England, did not expect to find the birds to
gather with relatives, since these birds were not raised with
relatives and had no way of learning who their relatives were.
Somehow though, the peacocks recognized their kin and tended to
display with them _ something researchers say might now be chalked
up to the armpit effect.
</P>
<P>
   Other research suggesting that humans may use the armpit effect
include studies in small, closed religious groups showing that
people tend to avoid marrying genetically similar people. In
addition, those couples that were more genetically dissimilar also
tended to have fewer miscarriages, suggesting that humans do avoid
inbreeding _ perhaps with the help of the armpit effect _ and for
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The only definitive way to test whether these people, or the
women in the T-shirt studies, were using their own smells as clues,
as opposed to the smells of their families, would be to do the
experiment as was done with the hamsters. Babies would need to be
removed at birth, raised with nonrelatives and then tested for
their ability to smell out a T-shirt or a mate. Such a study
clearly presents more than a few ethical and logistical
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much controversy about the armpit effect. Dr.
Richard Alexander, behavioral ecologist at the University of
Michigan, has repeatedly criticized past studies that tried to show
the effect, pointing out their weaknesses. And, he has suggested
that on theoretical grounds, such capabilities are unlikely to
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander also questioned what the hamsters were doing when they
became excited by the smells of strangers, but not kin. Alexander
said they might be simply ignoring the smells of relatives,
thinking that those were just their own smells. ``They're just
making a mistake,'' he said. ``They think, `Oh, that's me.'''
</P>
<P>
   But other researchers say mistake is a misnomer. All that
matters, they say, is that the hamsters, for whatever reason,
distinguish between kin and nonkin solely by their own smells.
</P>
<P>
   The new study also raises interesting questions about smells and
recognizing relatives. For example, if smell figures so importantly
in keeping humans from inbreeding, why is it that humans spend so
much on things like deodorants, which hide their message-carrying
odors? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
