<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C.   CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cat's Mad Dash
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do cats periodically run around madly as if they were
chasing a fire engine?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``I think it is more evolutionary than anything physiological
like a melatonin drop,'' said Dr. Katherine Houpt, a veterinarian
with a Ph.D. in behavioral biology, who directs the Animal Behavior
Clinic at Cornell. ``I think it is a form of play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden sprint is possibly related to hunting techniques,
Houpt suggested. ``You don't usually see it in farm cats, who have
to work for a living,'' she said. ``Their predatory behavior
involves sitting beside a mouse hole for hours, then pouncing.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the mad dash is often seen among well-fed, secure,
happy house cats. ``They often seem to be stimulating themselves
like a child on a swing,'' Houpt said.
</P>
<P>
   Cats are crepuscular animals that hunt at dawn and dusk, and the
run around often coincides with the time they would ordinarily be
hunting, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The tearing rush ``is not a problem for most owners unless it is
associated with attacks on any moving foot or it culminates in a
run up the silk draperies,'' Houpt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is a problem,'' she suggested, ``try interactive play
with a pouncing toy and see if doesn't stop or reduce the fire
engine behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
