<SLUG> BC-WESTERNSWING-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL IS BECOMING THE COUNTRY MUSIC EQUIVALENT OF
SANTANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABILENE, Texas _ To appreciate the slice of fame Asleep at the
Wheel has carved for itself, it's a good idea to be standing here,
as the sun goes down and the band _ sequestered in its big, comfy
tour bus _ prepares to take the stage.
</P>
<P>
   A rock band that had been around 30 years and won eight Grammys
(including two this past February) would probably be preparing to
play Dallas' Starplex or Reunion Arena. There would be legions of
fans hoping for a glimpse, a lavish backstage buffet, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Wheel, though, can look forward to none of this. A gig is a
gig is a gig, and this one is headlining the Celebrate Abilene!
festival: One stage, a few booths, the locals sitting at rows of
tables, chomping on big plates of steak.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep at the Wheel is the most famous western swing band
working. Last year's ``Ride With Bob,'' a tribute to Bob Wills and
the Texas Playboys, has become their biggest record, and in
February the CD's leadoff track, ``Bob's Breakdowns,'' won the
Grammy Award for Country Instrumental of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep just finished opening several dates for Bob Dylan in the
Northwest, at Dylan's request. On Wednesday, they'll be up for two
awards (Album of the Year and Top Vocal Group) at the Academy of
Country Music Awards. And this summer, they'll be playing stadiums,
opening for big fan George Strait.
</P>
<P>
   And yet here they are: no buffet, no adoring fans at the
backstage gate, and only a too-small, windblown stage, congealing
food in takeout boxes and a long drive back to Austin after the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Such is mega-success, western swing-style.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, no complaining in the voice of the group's
founder, Ray Benson, as he sits on the bus and warms up on guitar.
A large man with a voice and hands to match, Benson is the band's
mouthpiece, lead singer, guitarist and mastermind.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy who came up with the idea of teaming Asleep with 20
country and pop stars, from Merle Haggard to Don Walser to the
Squirrel Nut Zippers, and in the process did for his band what
``Supernatural'' did for Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Right now he's searching for a guitar tuner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's all show business,'' he says, tucked into a booth
and limbering up with some jazz riffs. ``Up and down, up and down,
or else up and down and you're out. We got into this to play music
and bring back older music that's been forgotten and I think we're
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson is taking success in stride _ probably because he's seen
so many years when Asleep at the Wheel was a cult act, loved by
hard-core western swing fans and unknown to everybody else. He can
say he never got into this to be famous without being disingenuous
because, frankly, no matter how influential western swing has been
on generations of musicians, it hasn't been country's hip sub-genre
since Wills and his Playboys.
</P>
<P>
   Benson and his band (steel guitarist Cindy Cashdollar, fiddler
Jason Roberts, bassist David Miller, drummer David Sanger, 20-year
vet Michael Francis on saxophone and newest member John Michael
Whitby on piano) may never be able to change that completely.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no question that by fusing the old tunes with young
hotshots such as the Dixie Chicks and established stars such as
Haggard, Willie, Tim McGraw and Reba McEntire, Asleep is
introducing western swing to a new audience, and rejuvenating
longtime fans.
</P>
<P>
   To Benson, this just makes sense. He grew up with country music
before falling under the spell of Wills (as well as Count Basie,
Big Joe Turner and Louis Jordan) as a teen; he formed Asleep at the
Wheel in 1970 in Virginia and, three years later, relocated to
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Texas, and it was Willie,'' he says. ``Willie said,
`Hey, you need to be down here' and boom, here we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, Benson never regretted the decision: Gigs in Austin
were plentiful, and the band had arrived just as the outlaw-country
movement took over the town and changed the face of country music.
</P>
<P>
   Their third LP, 1975's ``Texas Gold,'' broke them to a national
audience with a mix of standards such as ``Trouble in Mind'' and
originals such as ``Bump Bounce Boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   But just five years later, bad times arrived. Slick country-pop
took over, and between 1981 and 1984 the band didn't have a label.
</P>
<P>
   Benson produced numerous artists, from Willie to Aaron Neville
to Bruce Hornsby, but those were lean years: People would bump into
him on the street and ask if the group had broken up, even while he
was doing 120 or so (mainly low-profile) gigs per year and
wondering when, or if, he'd get another shot.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, though, Asleep at the Wheel was, and is, a major
country act and influences numerous musicians, not just for its
music but because the band has shown real staying power as the
winds of country taste have blown this way and that.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is like our uncle in the country music business,'' says
Dixie Chicks lead singer Natalie Maines. ``He's taught us so much
about the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Ann Womack, who grew up going to Alseep gigs in West Texas,
says the band is ``just so good at what they do _ they're not
chasing something anybody else is doing. That's why they're so
important. They've never changed what they do _ they stand for
something. And Ray taught me by example, the way Merle and Ray
Price did, about just being about the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Epic gave the band its second shot with 1987's ``Asleep at the
Wheel 10,'' which scored via two hits, ``House of Blue Lights'' and
``Way Down Texas Way.'' ``String of Pearls'' won the Grammy for
Best Country Instrumental Performance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the group released ``A Tribute to the Music of Bob
Wills &AMP; the Texas Playboys.'' The blueprint for ``Ride With Bob,''
it featured contributions from Garth Brooks, Vince Gill, Strait and
Dolly Parton, among others.
</P>
<P>
   And five years later, Benson picked up the phone and told
DreamWorks' general manager and head of label operations, Wayne
Halper, that he wanted to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said, `Let's do volume two' and I said, `I'm in, my
friend,''' Halper says. ``What Asleep at the Wheel does for country
music is put a smile on people's faces _ they're goodwill
ambassadors. I've known Ray for 20 years. I don't know anybody that
doesn't like Ray Benson and doesn't owe him a favor. I signed them
in the summer of '98.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson was aware of the changes in country music, and that
during the five years between records, there had been numerous new
acts on the rise, and numerous older ones, such as Don Walser,
finally getting some much-deserved attention. He'd be able to hit a
whole new audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create in our own little way the whole legacy of
western swing,'' he says. ``There were three criteria _ being
interested in western swing, being from Texas, being a friend of
mine. Preferably all three.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Benson began recruiting people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dixie Chicks did `Roly Poly' in their shows, so that was a
good fit,'' he says. ``Some of 'em I asked if there was a
particular song they wanted to sing and some of 'em I said, `This
is what I hear you doing _ how 'bout it?' And they all said yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack teamed with the band to cut the 1960 hit ``Heart to Heart
Talk'' because it was her father's favorite song.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd always wanted me to do that song,'' she says. ``I ran
into Ray somewhere and he asked if I would participate and I asked
if I could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, two months after the Grammys, Benson plays down the
comparisons to Santana and how recruiting young blood was
instrumental in ``Supernatural'' selling 11 million copies and
counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think, `God, I wish I could sell as many records as he
does,''' he says of Santana. ``We both play guitar, we both wear a
hat, we've both been around 30 years. We both play the same 12
notes _ just a little different. And we're both still around.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, ``Ride'' slots into the current landscape of country
music: The range of guests artists is wide enough to entice fans of
mainstream and alternative country; both camps can see it as hip,
and everyone can enjoy the kitschy cover and CD booklet, which won
the band a Grammy for Best Album Packaging.
</P>
<P>
   And back in Abilene, all that comes together where real country
music always does _ on the dance floor. The band starts off with
``Cherokee Maiden,'' with Benson, Roberts and Cashdollar trading
solos, and then moves through older material such as ``Miles and
Miles of Texas'' and ``Amarillo by Morning'' and the ``Bob'' cut
``Roly Poly.'' The band is tight, Benson's baritone is smooth, and
Cashdollar and Roberts shine as slyly inventive, playful soloists.
</P>
<P>
   Out in front, the street quickly fills with couples _ first the
over-40s, then younger folks, all circling the soundboard as they
two-step and waltz. Suddenly the wind doesn't seem so bad, and
there's a genuinely festive air to the proceedings. Asleep at the
Wheel will play better shows, and certainly ones in front of more
people, but they're giving at least three generations of country
fans the good time that they promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I feel like we've been rediscovered,'' Benson says. ``I
was 12 years old when I got into this stuff, so it just makes sense
to me now that a teen-ager would like it. I mean, it was old music
when I heard it for the first time, and I knew that I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Academy of Country Music Awards'' will be broadcast 7 p.m.
CDT Wednesday on CBS. Hosted by Dolly Parton, the show will be
broadcast from the Universal Amphitheater in Los Angeles. Asleep at
the Wheel will perform ``Roly Poly'' on the program.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
