<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT IN AMERICA? OFFICIALS' SEIZURE OF ELIAN HITS CLOSE TO HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez's words after federal agents seized Elian
from her home in Miami on Easter weekend hang like a weight on
Marylyn Daniel's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez reportedly yelled, ``To have a 6-year-old crying,
`Don't take me, don't take me.' ... This is not America.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can vouch for the fact that it happens in Texas,'' she said.
``When they took (Elian) out of that house, I could see my grandson
hollering for his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way between the Cuban-American neighborhood known
as Little Havana and Azle, just west of Fort Worth, where Daniel
lived with her daughter, Cynthia, and her two grandsons.
</P>
<P>
   But the tears and anguish played out in the media over the five
months since Elian was plucked from the Atlantic have personal
significance for Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   Her own grandson, Michael, was snatched from her and her
daughter more than five years ago in a custody dispute with the
child's father.
</P>
<P>
   One moment he was playing in their back yard in Azle. ``And the
next, a constable was taking him from the our house, screaming just
like that little boy, Elian,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grabbed him, threw him in the police car, locked the
door, and came back and handed us court papers. I asked them where
were they taking him, and they said, `Here's the paper, get you a
lawyer.'''
</P>
<P>
   And they did.
</P>
<P>
   That was Feb. 1, 1994. Marylyn Daniel hasn't seen Michael since.
And his mother, Cynthia Daniel, has been allowed only supervised
visits. That is, when she can afford to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Like most custody disputes, the Daniel case is a tangled web of
charges and countercharges. The father accused Cynthia of
physically and emotionally abusing Michael, and the court granted
him custody. Cynthia Daniel denies the charges, but Michael has
been caught in the middle ever since.
</P>
<P>
   You may or may not recall reading about Daniel and her
daughter's fight to regain custody of the boy in this space more
than three years ago. Michael is 11 now; he was 7 then.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Cynthia Daniel hadn't seen or talked to her son
since June 1996 because she couldn't afford to pay the $35-an-hour
fee charged by the Tyler agency that supervised her visits.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a whole other story.
</P>
<P>
   In another round of court battles soon after my first column,
the court granted Cynthia Daniel a reprieve. Now she pays $5 an
hour for up to a three-hour visit.
</P>
<P>
   But Cynthia Daniel faces more hurdles. When she reported the
father to Child Protective Services because she believed he failed
to get medical attention for Michael when he suffered a head injury
recently, the father decided to limit her visits to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a three-hour drive between Daniel's home in Fort Worth and
Tyler, where Michael lives, but for Cynthia, the trip is worth it.
Even for just one weekend a month. Even for just 30 minutes, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much time to do much of nothing,'' she said.
``We play a little. We talk.''
</P>
<P>
   But in between the visits, there's nothing. No pictures, no
letters, no gifts. Michael's father won't allow it.
</P>
<P>
   And so Cynthia Daniel and her mother, Marylyn, just keep hiring
attorneys in an effort to regain custody of Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Daniel said that when she sees her little boy, he seems
happy to be with her, even for the short time they are together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells me that he loves me, and I tell him that I love
him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marylyn Daniel wishes she could be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
