<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF ARPAIO RUNNING TV STUDIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   about the harsh condition of his jails, Maricopa County Sheriff
Joe Arpaio often boasts that he's not running a country club.
</P>
<P>
   He's right.
</P>
<P>
   He's running a TV studio.
</P>
<P>
   For three nights last month, anyway, when Bill Maher brought his
late-night comedy gabfest Politically Incorrect to town, filming
two shows from inside the lockdown at Estrella Jail and four inside
Tent City for the May ``sweeps'' rating period.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing new there, as Arpaio proudly points out.
</P>
<P>
   `Everybody else has been here, around the world,` he said,
before taping the second of two shows on which he appears as a
guest. `Why should I discriminate? This is just another television
crew that's here.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not, not really. While topical and smart, the emphasis
of Maher's show is on comedy. This isn't an investigative look at
conditions inside Tent City, nor a cop show championing green
bologna, female chain gangs and pink underwear.
</P>
<P>
   It's a funny show set, for the next week anyway, inside a jail,
with prisoners serving as audience, topic of discussion and,
frequently, the butt of jokes. (`It's great to be here,'' Maher
told the inmates during one monologue. `I mean for me, not you.''
The inmates' response, heard often, went something like, `Ha-ha-ha
- hey, wait.`)
</P>
<P>
   So who, really, is being served here?
</P>
<P>
   In part, the answer's easy - viewers. The six episodes of
Politically Incorrect that will air over the next week are great
television. The razor wire encircling the guests might have been
for show, but the razor wire on top of the fences behind them
wasn't. That setting provided an energy not found inside a
Hollywood studio, and Maher and his guests, who included David
Spade, Paul Rodriguez and a host of inmates, fed off it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet watching the taping, I couldn't help pondering a basic
dilemma: Was this entertainment or exploitation?
</P>
<P>
   `Obviously someone could make that claim, that there is
exploitation going on,'' Maher said. `But I would say that it is
probably better for those on the inside to have their story get out
to the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a message out is the reason most everyone gave for
participating. For Arpaio, Politically Incorrect was a forum to
reach a different audience, he said. Ditto William Schulz, the
executive director of Amnesty International USA and a frequent
Arpaio critic, who jousts with the sheriff on one of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all they did - joust. Neither Arpaio nor Schulz
resolved anything. Which is fine. Politically Incorrect is, after
all, a funny TV show, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one group of guests managed to get its message across in a
meaningful way - the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   `It's absurd the way we have to live,'' John Conley, an inmate
and guest, said, to the predictable cheers of the incarcerated
audience. `We're in America, where people don't expect to be
treated the way we're treated in this jail system.''
</P>
<P>
   After the taping wrapped, Conley made it clear why he thought
Arpaio allowed Politically Incorrect in.
</P>
<P>
   `For Joe, it's just another opportunity for him to show his
animals,'' he said. `Because that's what they basically treat us
as.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's nothing at all funny about that.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8974. j
</P>
</TEXT>
