<HEADER>
A2517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SENIORS-HOUSING02-COX     05-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-HOUSING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MANY HOMES NOT SUITED FOR OLDER RESIDENTS, SURVEY FINDS
 &HT;    With SENIORS-DATA.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly one-fourth of Americans age 45 and older
predict that they or someone they live with will have difficulty
getting around in their home within five years.
</P>
<P>
   As Baby Boomers and their parents age, more Americans face the
prospect of living longer in houses not designed to meet their
needs, according to the survey by AARP, the nation's largest
organization of people 50 and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they built houses in the past, they're not built for
the way people live,'' said Leon Harper, AARP senior housing
specialist. ``The message you have to get to people is that 'it's
not you, it's the house.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 100 million housing units in America, fewer than
10 percent have significant features for universally accessible
usage such as wide doorways, entrances without steps, stairwell
handrails, grab bars in bathtubs, and light switches at the top and
bottom of stairs, said Richard Duncan, director of training for
North Carolina State University's Center for Universal Design.
</P>
<P>
   Among the largest impediments to elder-friendly housing are
bedrooms on a second floor, entryway steps, narrow doorways,
overhead kitchen cabinets, and high-sided bathtubs without grab
bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such problems can greatly reduce the quality of life of older
people and increase the costs for society,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all older Americans have made minor modifications to make
their homes safer and more livable, such as installing night
lights, adding non-skid strips to the bathtub or shower, using
high-wattage light bulbs and using double-sided tape to secure rugs
and carpets.
</P>
<P>
   The AARP housing attitudes survey is the fifth such poll it has
conducted since 1986. Each time, it has gradually lowered the age
of those included. This telephone survey of 2,000 Americans 45 and
older also included an extra-large sampling of blacks and
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey's findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Older people generally have a greater desire to remain in
their current homes than younger people. Among those 45 to 54 years
old, 75 percent want to live in their present house as long as
possible. Among those 75 and older, 95 percent want to do so. That
may be because older people are more likely to have lived in their
current residence far longer than Baby Boomers, said Ada Helen
Bayer, AARP acting associate director of research.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among the three-fourths of Americans permitted to make changes
to their residences _ about a fourth cannot because they rent their
house or apartment _ seven out of 10 had made at least one
significant modification. Of those, two-thirds believe the
modifications will allow them to remain in their house for another
decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   _ The major reasons for not making wanted home modifications are
cost and the inability of homeowners to make the alterations
themselves. Other reasons include mistrust of home contractors,
inability to find anyone to make the repairs, and inability to go
to a store to purchase supplies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Minorities are less likely to want to remain in their current
residences for as long as possible and are more likely to live in a
place where they are concerned about themselves or a friend or
relative getting around.
</P>
<P>
   With the beginning of May marking both the federal Older
Americans' Month and AARP's ``Independent Living Week,'' the
organization for the elderly is waging a public information and
lobbying effort to convince builders to voluntarily make new houses
more friendly to an aging population.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Atlanta and Austin have both adopted
``visit-ability'' ordinances requiring any new housing built using
local subsidies _ such as city-owned public housing _ to have at
least one entrance way that meets wheelchair accessibility
standards, Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pushing for a model ordinance along those lines for
other localities to adopt,'' he said. ``Getting state or national
(laws) right now is practically out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: AARP Research: www.research.aarp.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
