<HEADER>
A2520 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FROZEN-METEORITE-     05-01 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FROZEN-METEORITE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE FROZEN METEOR THAT FELL TO EARTH IN CANADA MAY HOLD PRIMORDIAL
WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) (ART ADV: Photo  NYT 6  is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rock that fell in northwest Canada in January may preserve a
bit of the primordial solar system, little changed from what it was
4.5 billion years ago. During the early morning hours of Jan. 18, a
fireball exploded over the Yukon: a meteor from outer space burning
up in the Earth's atmosphere, with sonic booms heard in Alaska and
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the meteor burned up, though. A local resident
collected about two pounds of fragments, which resemble burnt
charcoal briquettes, placed them in plastic bags and stored them in
a freezer. Although the fiery journey through the atmosphere heated
up the outside of the surviving rocks, the inside would have
remained cold, giving researchers hope that delicate organic
molecules trapped within the meteorite remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorite turns out to be a type known as carbonaceous
chondrites, which contain sizable quantities of carbon and organic
molecules. Carbonaceous chondrites are rare _ only about one in 50
meteorites found on Earth is a carbonaceous chondrite _ because
they burn up easily, and pieces that survive re-entry weather away
quickly. It has' been 31 years since a carbonaceous chondrite has
been recovered soon after its arrival, and never a frozen one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This meteorite is our first chance ever to look at volatile
organics,'' said Dr. Michael E. Zolensky, a cosmic mineralogist at
NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston. About a pound of the
fragments are on loan to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typically a lot of organics, including amino acids,''
Zolensky said. In addition, ``Probably there's water inside, we're
betting.''
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists believe such meteorites seeded Earth with water
and organic molecules, the building blocks of life.
</P>
<P>
   The original meteor was probably the size of a bus, Zolensky
said, and probably spent most of the last 4.5 billion years
orbiting at the outer part of the asteroid belt near Jupiter. Its
chemical composition is likely to have changed little over that
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BO     05-01 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
