 ART ADV.: Photos with CHILD-NEGLECT and BOOKS-GIRL, and a graphic
with ENDANGERED-JOURNALISTS are being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ENDANGERED-JOURNALISTS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ In Russia,
Sierra Leone, Colombia, and numerous other countries, journalists
are paying with their lives for reporting on official corruption
and civil strife. By Kevin Cullen and Charles A. Radin. 1700 words.
GRAPHIC: 34 picas x 8 inches, ``Freedom and the press.''
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (London) _ A one-man show has taken London by
storm, but raises disturbing questions about cloddish British
nationalism. By Kevin Cullen. 880 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WTO (Washington) _ A belief by many members of the US
House that free trade with China is bad for their districts may
doom the issue when comes to a vote in a few weeks, destroying a
centerpiece of the Clinton Administration plan to establish a
secure relationship with China. By Anne E. Kornblut. 1950 words. (w
and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BIAS (Boston) _ Federal civil rights investigators probe
racial discrimination and harassment of dark-skinned Cape Verdean
students at South Boston elementary school by a 5th grade teacher,
who allegedly hit them and called them ``burro'' and
``nappy-headed'' and seated her students according to skin color,
light-skinned in front and dark-skinned in back. By Judith Gaines.
1590 words.
</P>
<P>
   FATHERS-SUICIDE (Sandwich, Mass.) _ He was a carpenter who doted
on his children. And when his son died from leukemia, it was only
hours before he took his own life. By Marcella Bombardieri. 1040
words.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-NEGLECT (Warwick, R.I.) _ Inside the gated community of
Wethersfield Commons, where an overflowing garbage can mobilizes
action from the neighbors, a little boy spent months trapped with
an unstable, elderly woman in a condominium whose squalor has
haunted every officer and child welfare professional who has seen
it. By Ellen Barry. 1700 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SELLING-THE-STARS (Undated) _ It's the nastiest star wars yet:
the squabble over who has the right, or if anyone has the right, to
sell astronomical naming rights. By Beth Daley. 1300 words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIET-ADOPT (Baltimore) _ A group of Vietnamese adoptees who just
returned from visits to Vietnam meet in Baltimore to share their
experiences. By Adam Pertman. 1150 words.
</P>
