<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, May 2. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Ned Kilkelly; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
kilkelly(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup. The Supreme Court on Monday
took an expansive view of the Constitution's bar against
retroactive legislation, overturning a Texas man's sex abuse
conviction on the ground that a change in state law had made it
easier for the prosecution to prove its case than at the time the
crime was committed. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (Undated) _ Millions of television viewers
found themselves without access to ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and many other popular television programs Monday as
the country's two biggest media companies, Time Warner and Walt
Disney, fought over the cable television rights to stations owned
by Disney's ABC network. The dispute has its roots in an argument
over how much money Disney should receive for carrying its channels
on Time Warner's cable systems, but it involves larger issues
dealing with the distribution of media content _ including the
longstanding antipathy between the cable and broadcast industry,
the growing competition between cable and satellite companies and
Disney's opposition to the proposed merger between America Online
and Time Warner. It also concerns how much power the new company
will wield in a television industry that is merged with the
Internet. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developing. Microsoft,
fighting to defeat the government's proposal to break the company
in two, plans to ask the trial judge next week for broad authority
to obtain thousands of pages of state and federal records on the
case, and for permission to bring a long list of witnesses to court
who will argue that the proposal is unwarranted and out of bounds.
By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROSTATE-TEST (Undated) _ In announcing on Thursday that he
had prostate cancer, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani paused to make
a pitch that all men have the PSA test that revealed the early
signs of his disease. Two new studies have provided strong, though
not conclusive, evidence that PSA testing can reduce deaths, and
most prostate cancer patients, like Giuliani, are glad they had the
test. Yet many medical organizations and experts on prostate cancer
remain equivocal about when, or even if, the screening test should
be given. Their uncertainty reflects a continuing debate about
whether the test is worthwhile given that, especially in older men,
prostate cancer can be an indolent disease unlikely to cause
lasting harm to the health, while its treatment can often produce
serious side effects like impotence and incontinence. By Kenneth
Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIEST-HUMANS (Undated) _ The book of Genesis mentions
three of Adam and Eve's children: Cain, Abel and Seth. But
geneticists, by tracing the DNA patterns found in people throughout
the world, have now identified lineages descended from 10 sons of a
genetic Adam and 18 daughters of Eve. The human genome is turning
out to be a rich new archive for historians and prehistorians, one
whose range extends from recent times to the dawn of human
existence. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BLONDE-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ She muscled her way into the
neighborhood in the 1920s, when nobody thought she belonged there.
Now here she is again, trying to squeeze in uptown with those ample
hips of hers, looking for a spot among the witty Brits and singing
animals and dancing gymnasts. And isn't she a sight for glazed
eyes? Stand up, boys, and take your hats off. Mae West is back on
Broadway. Miss West has returned in a compact Rolls-Royce of a
vehicle called ``Dirty Blonde,'' a new play written by and starring
Claudia Shear. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT10,11.
</P>
<P>
   ROTH-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Philip Roth's Pulitzer-Prize
winning 1997 novel, ``American Pastoral'' _ the first installment,
it would turn out, of a trilogy devoted to postwar American life _
triumphantly demonstrated that he could move beyond the solipsistic
presentations of self he had been practicing for years to create a
capacious chronicle of American innocence and disillusion. Though
the second installment of that trilogy (``I Married a Communist,''
1998) was something of a throwback to Roth's old mirror games, his
latest novel, ``The Human Stain,'' is not only a philosophic
bookend to ``Pastoral'' but another large and stirring book as
well. Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
