<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2527 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-AUTHORS-ROBBINS-SPI &LR;      05-01 2326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-ROBBINS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM ROBBINS COMES CLOSE TO REVEALING REAL SELF IN NEW NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA CONNER, Wash. _ This town's most famous resident sits at a
picnic table by the Rexfield Grocery on the outskirts, his perch
not far from his aging albino Jaguar and only 50 feet from the
highway where tourist cars swoosh by toward the technicolor tulip
fields. Writer Tom Robbins, just another roadside attraction.
</P>
<P>
   A pretty woman approaches and asks, ``Could you tell us how to
get to La Conner?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep going straight,'' Robbins says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks very much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're welcome,'' replies Robbins, who, once the woman has
walked away, immediately adds, ``I probably should have sent her in
the opposite direction.''
</P>
<P>
   This exchange is classic Robbins, the politeness born of his
youth in the South, the mischievous comment afterward reflecting
his ol' trickster ways. But this also may be the first time in his
63 years of devilish life that Robbins has ever advised anyone to
``keep going straight.''
</P>
<P>
   An encounter a half-hour later gives another glimpse of Robbins.
He hails a friend who is heading into the little country store that
has been spiffed up and now purveys a ``writer sandwich'' (tuna
fish with kimchi) to honor La Conner's premiere kimchi head.
</P>
<P>
   The two men of similar vintage are soon exchanging pleasantries,
the effects of too many loud rock concerts on their hearing, the
too many friends passing away in recent months. Then, the man spies
Robbins' book on the picnic table, with its cover the color of a
tangerine dream, so striking, yet unfamiliar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When did that come out?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't,'' Robbins replies. ``It will be out May 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The man nods, starts to walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be the first in line to get one,'' Robbins says, with a sly
laugh. ``Be the first in your neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   A laugh burbles up from Robbins' gullet, erupts through his
goatee, before he yells, ``Nice to see ya, Johnny.''
</P>
<P>
   This is another side of Robbins, who, amid the playful banter,
is plumb earnest about his new book (and most things, too).
</P>
<P>
   The laureate of La Conner is a comic writer who is doornail-dead
serious about what he does. He is also a slumgullion of
contradictions: celebrity and recluse, romantic and visionary, rake
and aesthete, fantasist and stickler for accuracy, Timbuktu
globe-trotter and hunkered-down Northwest homeboy here and in
Seattle..
</P>
<P>
   Robbins considers himself proud and unbowed, thankful for the
many loyal readers who have turned his books into sure
best-sellers, and semi-amused that a California fan has long
operated a Robbins' Web site, although the author would never visit
himself out of fears of becoming ``too self-conscious to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robbins remains tired as old pajamas of being typecast and
clearcut by critics (whom he contends he almost never reads). He
traces this chronic mistreatment back eons to his first book,
``Another Roadside Attraction'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been crucified,'' Robbins stresses, ``on the cross of
whimsy ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some faint hope that the new book may help change that.
``Fierce Invalids Home From Hot Climates'' (Bantam, 415 pages,
$27.50), with its title taken from a poem by French bad boy Arthur
Rimbaud, is Robbins' first book in six years and his longest book
ever. It will soon to be the subject of a cross-country book tour
in which Robbins will worry once more about ``whether my tongue
will turn into a Prestolog when I stand up at the podium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fierce Invalids'' is indeed different in some signal ways from
his past work.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins is still the Houdini of unchained similes and metaphors.
``Fierce Invalids'' includes such doozies as ``her eyes were like
chocolate-dipped cherry bombs with their fuses lit'' and ``a
mist-bearded Saturday morning, gray as a ghoul and cool as clam
aspic.'' But such Robbinsesque verbal escapades, as addictive as
crack to his fans, are parsed out in dwindling supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably fewer metaphors and similes in this book
than my previous ones,'' Robbins concedes. ``I don't know exactly
why that is, although I do think the ones that are there are some
of the best that I've ever done. This book has a little more of a
narrative thread. It relies more on a fast-moving narrative than my
previous books.''
</P>
<P>
   A Tom Robbins' novel where, strange to behold, plot takes some
precedence. And not only plot, but a male protagonist! And not only
a male protagonist from a writer known for his spunky, randy female
leads, but a male protagonist who the author admits ``is my most
autobiographical character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fierce Invalids'' focuses on Switters, a CIA agent without a
first name, but with the same birthday as the writer who created
him. Switters is smart, savvy, sassy, semi-successful, a dervish of
dazzling contradictions himself. Loyal government servant with
free-agent tendencies. Moralist with burning lust for his teenage
stepsister. Techno-whiz with distaste for cyberia. A veggie
gastronome with ``an appetite for bold gestures and burned
bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, in a passage that seems to include some
self-descriptive elements, says of Switters: ``He projected the
air, falsely or not, of both a learned man and a rogue, innately
exhibitionist yet deeply secretive, a powerful figure who
habitually thumbed his nose at power _ and thus might lead one,
were one to fall under his spell, off in directions opposite those
that one had been conditioned to recognize as prudent, profitable,
or holy.''
</P>
<P>
   Switters sets off on a South American mission, including what is
supposed to be a brief detour to liberate his grandmother's pet
parrot in the Peruvian rain forest. But a disastrous encounter with
a indigenous medicine man, soon has Switters eating something like
crow and consigned to a wheelchair by what may be a death-dealing
curse.
</P>
<P>
   Switters repairs to Seattle, licks wounds, lays low, hangs out
at the Pike Place Market, grows enamored with the ``Art Girls''
from the design school down Elliott Avenue. He finally departs on
another mission, no longer in government employ, this time to the
Middle East where he finds himself ensconced in an embattled oasis
convent of rogue nuns (including the captivating Sister Domino) who
might just know the secret of the missing prophesy of the Virgin of
Fatima.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly an example of express train plotting taught in
Thriller Writing 101. ``Fierce Invalids'' is a tangled garden of
madcap, satire and strangeness grown slowly in Robbins' fervent
imagination from such seeds as a long night's drink with a CIA
agent in Southeast Asia, ``Terry and the Pirates'' comic books, an
entry in one of Bruce Chatwin's journals, the partially read
``Finnegans Wake'' on his bedside table, the interplay of opposites
in the universe and various other things that, as he puts it,
``flicked the spark in my Zippo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the themes of this book,'' Robbins relates, ``is
whether it is possible in today's world to live a life of
free-wheeling sensuality and romantic adventure combined with a
life of serenity and deep wisdom and full consciousness. It's
tricky. I think Switters succeeds at that _ and maybe I was working
out my own conflict and that particular dichotomy as I was writing
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing was done in the usual Robbins style of tightrope
wordsmithing without safety net. No outline, at the start or later.
``Only the vaguest sense of plot.'' No characters to begin with.
Just some themes that had been tornadoing inside his head for the
past few years. Then a piece of blank paper. A pen. Intense
concentration. Words finally. The start of his book and his trek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write books the way a glacier would write books,'' Robbins
says, with a smile. ``... I hold auditions for characters and a
character or two will show up. Then I'll take a character and put
him or her into a situation, an opening gambit. I'll put him or her
in a little boat and shove them into the current and I'll just
follow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a literal trip, a literal journey. I go very, very
slowly because to work that way you have to go very slowly and you
have to stay extremely focused. The challenge, and the thrill of
it, is to take those disparate themes, which have no connection to
one another, and to take the characters, which have no connection
to one another either, and make them come together in such a
seamless way that the reader would believe that the whole thing,
part and parcel, was in my head when I began.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the organic, yet painstaking process that begat ``Even
Cowgirls Get the Blues'' (1976), ``Still Life With Woodpecker''
(1980), ``Jitterbug Perfume'' (1984), ``Skinny Legs and All''
(1990), ``Half Asleep in Frog Pajamas'' (1994). And it has gotten
no easier for Robbins with successive books _ his deteriorating
eyesight has actually made it harder _ since each still requires
starting smack dab at ground zero and trusting the fickle muse of
creative juice.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins brings similar care to the ideas underpining his work.
There are elements of Eastern religions throughout his novels,
especially the Tibetan concept of ``crazy wisdom,'' references to
assorted Greek myths, plus fevered embraces of sensuality and sex.
His practice of meditation and yoga usually comes into play. There
are also point-blank attacks on what strikes Robbins as
conventional wisdom, forced consensus, political correctness, rigid
doctrine or pomposity of any kind. His subversive weapons of choice
are satiric humor and unrepentant joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I try to do in my work is to somehow marry
the terrible truths of life on this planet with a sense of
wonder,'' Robbins says. ``I don't think I'm that different than
Kafka in my outlook, my world view. It's just that Kafka let it
make him miserable and I refuse. Life is too short for that. I'd
like to think there's an afterlife, but I certainly have no
empirical evidence. So I'm operating as if this is my only shot at
it. That's why I insist on joy in spite of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   What strains that joy for Robbins, as much as anything, are
critics who continue to describe him as ``a hippie novelist''
(``it's like referring to Tolkien as a dwarf novelist or an elf
novelist because of the characters he writes about'') or critics
who dare wave that old red cape of ``whimsy'' in front of his face.
</P>
<P>
   Being named one of ``The 100 Best Writers of the 20th Century''
by Writer's Digest was some soul salve to Robbins, as was being
deemed a Northwest artistic treasure by the Bumbershoot arts
festival in 1997, as was being called ``the most dangerous writer
in the world today'' by Fernanda Pivano, noted Italian critic. But
just the whisper of ``whimsy'' still turns Robbins into a raging
longhorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That word used to be applied to my work a lot and I have grown
to despise it with a loathing that I share only for Jesse Helms and
the Los Angeles Lakers,'' Robbins stresses. ``My work is not
whimsical at all. It's playful. There is a huge difference. ... I
may have done things in an off-hand way in some of my earlier work,
but it was never, ever done on a whim. Playfulness involves an
engaged consciousness. The wisest men and women I've ever met in
this world, and I've met a few, all seem to have that in common _ a
playful attitude toward life.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that playfulness may be traced to one of the key
influences of Robbins' life, the arrival of the circus or the
carnival in the small Southern towns where he grew up. So fond are
those memories that the writer has long collected vintage circus
banners, some 10 feet long and 7 feet high, and used them to
decorate his walls and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   The banners are one of the reasons, too, that Robbins and his
third wife, Alexa, are in the midst of a massive remodeling project
linking his two small homes with a large addition. The resulting
hacienda is being dubbed ``Villa de Jungle Girl,'' in honor of the
leopardskin-clad damsels that grace many banners.
</P>
<P>
   None may quite hold a searchlight to the 11-year-old circus
lovely named Bobbie Beers who so beguiled the 13-year-old Tom with
the blond hair that cascaded down the middle of her back, the
knee-high patent leather boots, the riding breeches, the pet black
snake coiled around her bare arm, the little snake bites that ran
up and down that fetching appendage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the most exotic creature I had ever encountered in my
life,'' Robbins recalls. ``I've never gotten over her, really.''
</P>
<P>
   That the teen Tom was able to convince his parents to let him
travel with the circus run by Bobbie's parents for a few weeks may
have been the greatest act of Robbins' word magic in his life. As a
result, he got to help set up the menagerie tent, water nasty
llamas, scrub algae off an alligator's back, plus fantasize about
Bobbie from some proximity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too shy to do anything more,'' Robbins admits. ``Kissing
Bobbie would have been like exchanging a kiss with Marlene
Dietrich. She was way out of my league.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, though, that colorful circus banners and powerful
circus memories still ignite the imagination of this grandson of
two Southern Baptist preachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small towns in the rural South tend to get pretty drowsy in
the summer and then one day these trucks would pull into a dusty
vacant field,'' Robbins remembers. ``By nighttime, there would be
tents up and colored lights everywhere. Elephants would be walking
about and there would be music, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did that enliven my childhood summers, it instilled
that notion of transformation _ that something that's dull and
dreary could overnight be transformed into an area of enchantment.
It has shaped my psyche, to a certain extent, and my literary
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Robbins, astride the high wire, still strives to keep the
circus alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
