</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOMINO-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOMINO TRANSPLANT: A MAN GETS NEW ORGANS AND GIVES HIS LIVER
AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.D., Mich.)   (The Science Times) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The call came in the early morning hours of April 11 to the
Watertown, S.D., home of Barbara Hubbard, who had just gone back to
sleep after walking the dog and having a snack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a liver. Are you interested?'' Hubbard remembers the
caller asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``How soon do I have to be there?'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   The call came about the same time for Al Cawley of Waterford,
Mich., whose wife woke him up to come to the phone. This time the
message was a little different: A liver had just become available,
as had a heart and a kidney. Was he available?
</P>
<P>
   By about that hour the next day, Cawley, whose plane took off in
a snowstorm to rush him to the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., had
his three new organs, and Hubbard, who was driven there through the
night by a friend, had her liver.
</P>
<P>
   The twist was that the liver put into the South Dakota woman had
come from Cawley in a rare, multipatient procedure known as a
domino transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple-organ transplants are highly unusual: 1989 was the last
time one like Cawley's was done in the United States, according to
a national organ-donation network. But domino transplants are rarer
still. Only a handful have ever been done in this country, while
about 40 have been done around the world, mostly in Europe, Mayo
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   There are few cases in which it makes medical sense for a
patient who needs a new organ to give up one of his own.``The
situations are few, but where it is appropriate, I think it's a
great utilization of a very scarce resource,'' said Dr. Joseph A.
Dearani, the heart surgeon who was part of the team that operated
on Cawley.
</P>
<P>
   In Cawley's case, as with most domino transplants, a rare
genetic condition created the circumstances in which he was given a
new liver _ only to have his own put into another patient. A
58-year-old lawyer, Cawley had familial amyloidosis, a disease in
which the liver produces an abnormal protein that destroys many of
the body's organs.
</P>
<P>
   The liver itself, however, works fine.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Mayo, with one of the world's largest amyloidosis
treatment centers, say they cannot be sure how the diseased liver
will behave in another patient. But because amyloidosis take
decades to do real damage, they expect it will be many years, if
ever, before any symptoms are seen.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Spieldenner, a spokesman for the United Network for
Organ Sharing, which runs the country's organ-donor distribution
system, said it was important that the patient receiving the
donated organ realized the potential risks. ``You have to be sure
that the patient fully understands what's going to happen, and that
they're comfortable with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, a 58-year-old registered nurse, put it simply. When the
call from Mayo came, she had been suffering from liver disease for
about 10 years, and her condition had gotten worse.``It was hope
for a new life, and I wasn't about to turn it down.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other ethical issues, said Dr. Andreas G. Tzakis,
co-director of transplantation at the University of Miami's Jackson
Memorial Hospital, who has been involved in six cases where an
amyloid liver was given to another patient.
</P>
<P>
   What, for example, should a hospital do if an emergency liver
failure case comes in as doctors are about to perform an elective
domino procedure? Who should get the liver? Should amyloid livers
in general be treated like any other donated organ, and placed into
the general distribution system?
</P>
<P>
   ``It might sound like hair-splitting,'' Tzakis said, ``but the
truth of the matter is: In this day and age, a lot of people die
for a liver. This question is going to come up more and more as the
procedure becomes more frequent.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how these issues are resolved, even though domino
transplants will do little to reduce the backlog of people waiting
for new organs, each one creates a kind of ripple effect,
Spieldenner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're able to help another patient out,'' he said. ``Instead
of just one person getting transplanted, you're helping two. That
not only helps those patients, but helps those patients who
continue to wait, because that's one less person they have to
compete against.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cawley, whose father died of amyloidosis at age 62, the
domino transplant did not raise ethical issues so much as help
resolve them. When he initially went to Mayo, the plan was for him
to receive a new heart and a new liver. But as time went on, it
became clear that he would also need a new kidney. Those organs, he
recalls thinking, could help three different people, and one
question kept going through his head: ``Is it fair?'' He seriously
considered saying no to the transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles B. Rosen, Mayo's director of liver transplantation,
said that doctors were intending to ask Cawley if they could give
his liver to someone else, but ``he brought it up first.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cawley learned that his liver would help someone else, he
agreed to the surgery. ``I couldn't be happier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was just a question of waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Early on April 11, doctors at Mayo received a call telling them
that there might be organs available from a young trauma victim in
the region. (To protect confidentiality, doctors did not disclose
more information about the donor.) They immediately put Cawley and
Hubbard on notice, and sent two procurement teams to the hospital,
where the patient was on life-support.
</P>
<P>
   At about 11 that morning, surgeons at Mayo's St. Marys Hospital
began work on Cawley, beginning with his heart. They then replaced
his liver, and finally a kidney. Hubbard, meanwhile, was being
prepared at Rochester Methodist Hospital, also part of Mayo.
</P>
<P>
   After removing Cawley's liver, doctors flushed it with a
preservative solution and had it driven the the short distance to
Rochester Methodist. Three hours and 19 minutes after it had been
taken out of Cawley, the liver was placed in Hubbard. In all, the
whole process took about 14 hours, involved at least two dozen
medical workers, and cost easily $500,000, Mayo officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Cawley and Hubbard have yet to meet each other, but say they
hope to do so. Both are reported to be doing well, but will have to
take anti-rejection drugs for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Cawley said he planned to return to his law practice, but
Hubbard said she had been advised that working in a hospital might
no longer be a good idea for her, because of the risk of infection.
As unsettling as it is, she said, she is enjoying trying to figure
out her next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 10 years,'' she said, ``I thought I was just going to die.
So there was no future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
