<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 7)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Festival Celebrates Black Artists
</P>
<P>
   An eight-month arts festival about the black experience in
America, which began in January, has a full calendar of events in
spring and summer. ``Spirit and Splendor: A Celebration of the
Sights, Sounds and Soul of African American Arts and Culture'' is
being presented by the Woodruff Arts Center in Atlanta. Music,
drama and dance performances and art exhibitions are being staged
at museums and cultural centers throughout the city. The festival
will run through Sept. 24.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A central component is the exhibition ``To Conserve a Legacy:
American Art from Historically Black Colleges and Universities,''
to be shown at the High Museum of Art and Clark Atlanta University
from June 20 to Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Other exhibitions include ``From Africa to America: Honoring our
Ancestors,'' June 1 to Nov. 11 at the Atlanta International Museum,
and ``The David C. Driskell Collection: Narratives of African
American Art of the Twentieth Century,'' from June 13 to Sept. 24
at the High Museum of Art.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Performances include a concert by the jazz pianist Billy Taylor
at the Rialto Center on May 20, dance by Ballethnic at East Point
Auditorium on May 20 and dramas by Dael Orlandersmith, Billy Hicks
Jr. and Rebecca Ranson.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Spirit and Splendor'' celebration of black culture also
includes city-sponsored events. The Atlanta Jazz Festival runs from
May 22 to 29 at Piedmont Park, followed by the Montreaux Atlanta
Music Festival from Aug. 28 to Sept. 4, with an array of jazz,
hip-hop, rhythm and blues, soul, rock and blues.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirit and Splendor'' vacation packages featuring
accommodations and tickets are available through Marriott Hotels.
Call (800) 327-5166.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A complete calendar including ticket information is available by
calling (404) 733-5279, or visiting www.woodruffcenter.org.
</P>
<P>
   New Pass to Cover All National Parks
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service is selling a new $50 pass that admits
the holder, and everyone else in the same car, to all National
Parks for one year from month of purchase. The Park Service put the
pass on sale last month in cooperation with its nonprofit partner,
the National Park Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Separate entrance fees at the most popular parks have risen in
recent years. Since 1997, the top price has been for a week's entry
for a car into Yosemite, the Grand Canyon or Yellowstone-Grand
Teton: $20 each. At Acadia National Park in Maine, a year's pass is
$20.
</P>
<P>
   When these fees were announced, the government said that the
added revenue would be used to make repairs and reinstitute
programs that had been lost in budget cuts. Eighty percent of the
yield from the new pass, which features a picture of bison in the
snow at Yellowstone, will be dedicated to support programs to
protect animals, rebuild trails and conduct research, the park
service said.
</P>
<P>
   For those arriving on foot, the pass admits the purchaser,
spouse, parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   The new pass can be bought at national park visitor centers,
through the Web at www.nationalparks.org or by calling (888)
467-2757. By mail, a check for $53.95, including mailing, should be
made payable to National Park Service and sent to National Park
Pass, 27540 Avenue Mentry, Valencia, Calif. 91355.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Age Pass, which covers all the parks for life, costs
$10, and is available to people over 62. Golden Access, for the
disabled, is still free.
</P>
<P>
   As the Walls Talk: Two Tours in Newport
</P>
<P>
   This summer visitors will be able to hear about the Gilded Age
as well as see its Newport, R.I., setting. The Preservation Society
of Newport County is offering new guided and audio tours. The
Victorian Cottages Walking Tour of Bellevue Avenue is a three-hour
guided program providing an architectural as well as social history
of the town's most illustrious street from Kingscote to
Chateau-sur-Mer. Kingscote was the first ``summer cottage'' built
along what was then a dirt road in 1839. Chateau-sur-Mer, designed
by a local architect, Seth Bradford, was built in 1852 and
renovated  &QC; by Richard Morris Hunt in 1872. Tours of both of these
Victorian landmarks will be included.
</P>
<P>
   Walking tours will run from Memorial Day weekend to Columbus
Day, stepping off daily at 10 a.m. at the Preservation Society's
offices at 424 Bellevue Avenue; $25, $9 ages 6 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   Also new this year is a self-guided audio tour, Sights and
Sounds of the Gilded Age: Life at The Elms, focusing on the coal
magnate Edward Julius Berwind's Bellevue Avenue estate. Built at
the turn of the century by the Philadelphia architect Horace
Trumbauer, The Elms _ a National Historic Landmark _ is considered
to be a faithful interpretation of the Chateau d'Asnieres near
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The tour includes the voices of curators and historians, former
house guests and family members of the Berwinds and their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Elms is open daily year round 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. The audio
tour, which replaces the guided tour, costs $9, $4 ages 6 to 17. A
guided tour of the work areas (from laundry to boiler room) is
available, for $12, $4 ages 6 to 17. Information for the audio and
walking tours: (401) 847-1000.
</P>
<P>
   St. Maarten Gets Its Own Dialing Code
</P>
<P>
   St. Maarten, the Dutch territory in the Caribbean, may not have
its own island (it shares it with French St.-Martin), but it now
has its own international dialing code for its telephone system.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone calling from another country must dial the international
access code 011, plus the island's five-digit code, 599-54, and
then the local number. For calls within St. Maarten, the number 54
must precede all local five-digit numbers. The tourist board
suggests practicing by calling (599-54) 22337 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   New in Chicago: a T. Rex Called Sue
</P>
<P>
   On May 17, visitors to the Field Museum in Chicago will have a
chance to meet Sue, the largest, most complete and best preserved
Tyrannosaurus rex ever found.
</P>
<P>
   About 67 million years ago, Sue stood more than 13 feet tall and
roamed the Black Hills of South Dakota. The seven-ton reptile had
serrated teeth that were up to a foot long. She measured 42 feet
from her snout to the tip of her tail and has a skull that is 5.2
feet long and weighs 750 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Over millions of years, Sue fossilized so perfectly that most of
her more than 250 bones have been found, and it is still possible
to see where muscles, tendons and other soft tissues were once
attached. Sue remained hidden in western South Dakota until Aug.
20, 1990, when Sue Hendrickson (after whom the T. rex is named), a
fossil hunter, discovered her.
</P>
<P>
   In celebration of Sue's arrival, the museum is playing host to a
series of opening-day and weekend educational programs including
Create-a-Saurus, where visitors can build dinosaurs using foam and
wire; Dino-Time for preschoolers; a musical premiere; and film
presentations (accompanying the exhibits) with dinosaur themes.
</P>
<P>
   Sue's skull will be on display on a second-floor balcony (it is
too heavy to fit onto the assembled skeleton), and visitors can get
a close look at it. Nearby will be touchable casts of Sue's teeth,
of the tip of her tail, of one of her forelimbs and of her
wishbone; interactive Web stations, and a room dedicated to
dinosaur facts and theories. For example, it is known that Sue has
two forelimbs with ``hands,'' but scientists don't know what they
were used for or what color they were.
</P>
<P>
   While her real skeleton (with lighter version of her skull) will
remain at the Field Museum permanently, two full-size cast models
will tour the country this summer, starting in Honolulu at the
Bishop Museum and in Boston at the Museum of Science.
</P>
<P>
   The Field Museum, 1400 S. Lake Shore Drive, is open 9 a.m. to 5
p.m. daily except Christmas and New Year's Day. Admission is $8, $4
for ages 3 to 11, students with ID and seniors. Free on Wednesdays.
Call (312) 922-9410. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
