<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 7)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Motorcycle Tours
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are interested in motorcycle trips in the
United States, Europe, Costa Rica, New Zealand, etc. We are looking
for an upscale trip with top accommodations. We would like a guide
and chase vehicle with air-conditioning for my wife to ride in. _
Kenneth Sher, Syosset, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. For those seeking primarily superior accommodations,
Edelweiss Bike Travel offers tours in the Alps, Spain and
California _ each of which operates twice a year. Among the places
at which participants are scheduled to stay are the Carlton in St.
Moritz, Switzerland; the Parador de Cardona, in a ninth-century
castle near Barcelona; and the Fairmont in San Francisco. Note that
while the Edelweiss brochure describes the lodgings in the Alps and
California as first class or deluxe, it calls those in Spain
``comfortable to first class.''
</P>
<P>
   As for air-conditioning in a chase or support vehicle, it is the
exception for major tour operators. While you might get one
stateside, there's no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, tour operators point out, support vehicles are
intended primarily for transporting luggage and coming to the aid
of weary riders. They also say that the route and schedule for such
vehicles may differ from the motorcyclists'; so this kind of
vacation may not result in a fully shared experience. One final
point underscored by operators: These trips are designed for
experienced and alert cyclists.
</P>
<P>
   Charges are based on double occupancy and do not include air
fare. The rates are based on one cyclist's riding solo. Itineraries
do not list every stop.
</P>
<P>
   To provide a rough basis for comparison, here are details on
Alpine tours run by three companies.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Austria-based Edelweiss Bike Travel, whose North
American representative is Tri-Community Travel, Post Office Box
1974, Wrightwood, Calif. 93297; (800) 582-2263 or (760) 249-5825,
fax (760) 249-3857; www.edelweissbiketravel.com. All the cycles for
Royal tours are BMWs, with the model determining the cost. If your
wife travels in a separate vehicle, the cost is the same as two
people riding a single bike and sharing a room.
</P>
<P>
   Alpine, 16 days. Itinerary: Munich, Salzburg, the Dolomites in
Italy, Switzerland, the Arlberg region of Austria, Liechtenstein
and Germany. Total mileage: 1,000 to 1,800. Rest days: 7. Cost per
person: $3,970 to $5,090. Departs June 3 and July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish Castles, 16 days. Itinerary: Barcelona, Andorra, a
corner of France. Total mileage: 1,700. Rest days: 3. Cost: $3,985
to $5,140. Departs Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   California, 8 days. San Francisco, Little River, Mendocino and,
in Napa Valley, Boyes Hot Springs. Total mileage: 400. Two rest
days and one day of warm-up loops. Cost: $2,570 to $3,340.
</P>
<P>
   Beachs Motorcycle Adventures, 2763 West River Parkway, Grand
Island, N.Y. 14072; (716) 773-4960, fax (716) 773-5227;
www.beachs-mca.com. Itinerary for 15-day trips that arrive in
Munich on May 28, June 18, July 9 and 30 and Aug. 20 includes
Salzburg; Arabba, Italy; Interlaken, Switzerland; Imst, Austria.
Rest days: 2. Total mileage: 1,350. Cost: $4,150 for the solo
rider, $3,250 for the passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Another operator you can try, although it does not have a chase
vehicle for its Alps trip, is the American Motorcyclist
Association, 13515 Yarmouth Drive, Pickerington, Ohio 43147; (614)
856-1900, fax (614) 856-1921; www.amadirectlink.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to Lourdes
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the best way to travel to the Shrine at Lourdes in
France, near the Spanish border? Is it easier to travel from Paris
or somewhere in Spain? _ R. Roberts, Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   A. As the crow flies, Lourdes is clearly closer to Barcelona and
Madrid than it is to Paris. But once you take into account the
Pyrenees, the picture is very different: It's a 10-hour train trip
from Madrid and a bit less from Barcelona vs. 5 hours and 35
minutes on the TGV from the Montparnasse Station in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have lots of time _ three more hours, in fact _ you
will not want to leave from the Austerlitz Station in Paris. The
cost from both stations is the same: $116 first class. $91 second
class. Information: (800) 438-7245 or www.raileurope.com.
</P>
<P>
   A plane from Spain to Lourdes should be faster than a train. But
it's not, because flights to the Ossun-Lourdes Airport (LDE is the
code) from either Barcelona or Madrid go to Paris first. On top of
that, most Iberia and all Air France flights bound for Lourdes from
Barcelona and Madrid arrive at Charles de Gaulle Airport but leave
from Orly.
</P>
<P>
   As for cost, flying from Paris costs about $109 for a 75-minute
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Other than someone trying to get into the Guinness Book of
Records, who would spend 4 hours and 40 minute to fly from
Barcelona via Paris or an hour less from Barcelona? Both flights
are $290 one way.
</P>
<P>
   For guidance on lodgings, check www.tourismalourdes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy in Prague
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am planning a trip to Prague in the fall and would like to
know when Vladimir Ashkenazy will be conducting at Dvorak Hall. _
Marilyn F. Rothstein, Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ashkenazy will conduct the Czech Philharmonic in eight
concerts from September to the end of the year at Dvorak Hall in
the Rudolfinum. It was Antonin Dvorak who conducted the orchestra's
first concert in 1896. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 28 and 29 two works by Mozart _ his Overture to ``Don
Giovanni'' and, with the soprano Barbara Bonney as soloist,
``Exsultate Jubilate'' will be performed _ as will Suk's Serenade
and Bartok's Dance Suite. Scheduled for Nov. 9 and 10 are the
Sibelius Violin Concerto with Ida Haendel as soloist and Strauss'
``Ein Heldenleben.'' On Nov. 16 and 17, the program will be
Martinu's ``Frescoes of Piero della Francesca,'' Berg's Lyric Suite
and Strauss' ``Symphonia Domestica.'' And on the program for Dec.
14 and 15 are the Brahms Piano Concerto No. 2, with Evgeny Kissin
as soloist, and Alexander von Zemlinsky's Lyric Symphony, with
soloists to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Next season's prices have yet to be set, but tickets for this
season are $5.90 to $12.85, at the rate of 38.22 crowns to the
dollar. They can be bought at the box office, corner of Ulice 17
Listopadu and Namesti Jana Palacha. It is open 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
weekdays and one hour before the concert; closed weekends. (All
performances start at 7:30 p.m.) Or you can write to the Czech
Philharmonic Orchestra, Alsovo Nabrezi 12, 110 01 Prague 1;
telephone (420-2) 248 93 352, fax (420-2) 23 14 110;
www.czechphilharmonic.cz.
</P>
</TEXT>
