<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PARTICLE-PHYSICS-     05-01 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PARTICLE-PHYSICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY: SEARCHING FOR DARK MATTER, WITH BOTH EYES CLOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times) 
 By MICHAEL RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years ago this month, I flew from Boston to San Francisco
with another MIT graduate student, eager to begin physics research
on a new, two-mile-long atom smasher at Stanford. Just west of
Chicago, we passed above a circular gouge in the earth four miles
around _ the footprint of another particle accelerator then under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Working with these cutting-edge tools, physicists in the United
States shocked the scientific world with the revolutionary
discovery of quarks, the elementary particles at the heart of the
atomic nucleus. It was my good fortune to be a foot soldier in this
grand upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Those heady times came to mind recently after I learned about
surprising results from an underground experiment in Italy.
Although much debated, the results suggest that physicists are
closing in on the mysterious dark matter, believed to be a vast
halo of subatomic particles swirling surreptitiously throughout our
Milky Way galaxy and holding it together gravitationally.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of these particles may in fact be whizzing harmlessly
through my body every second. If certain cherished theories hold
true, they are but the lightest members of a large clan of exotic
bits of matter that mirror the electrons, protons and other
garden-variety particles of everyday existence. They are the
shadows of creation, ghostly remnants of the Big Bang birth of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   But particle physicists in the United States are ill prepared to
join their European colleagues in following up these stunning
results, should they turn out to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The best instrument to pursue this research, a huge particle
smasher known as the superconducting super collider, suffered an
early death. Had it been built as originally planned, this $10
billion machine, designed to speed protons around a 54-mile track
and collide them, would now be producing results.
</P>
<P>
   But because Congress killed it in a deficit-reduction measure in
1993, there are no data, only a long tunnel, filling up with ground
water, beneath the plains of North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Although sensitive subterranean and satellite-borne detectors
have taken great strides in the past decade in unraveling the
fabric of the heavens, they are no substitutes for the precise,
controlled experiments that physicists perform with powerful
particle accelerators or colliders. Such sophisticated detectors
may glimpse the Big Bang's afterglow and sift through its ashes,
but these big particle smashers can mimic its fire.
</P>
<P>
   To recreate the primordial conditions in which the universe was
born, researchers must generate and clash two beams of high-energy
particles. Physicists in the United States already do this kind of
work on colliders at Fermilab in Illinois and at Stanford. But
concentrating enough energy to create the ultraheavy ghosts
believed to exist will require a mammoth machine, a
multibillion-dollar investment. There is no cheap alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the super collider's demise, however, graduate
students entering particle physics will soon be unable to work at a
machine in this country that can probe the far frontiers of their
chosen field. For the next several years, they can do interesting
research at Fermilab and Stanford, but these now-aging laboratories
will be eclipsed around mid-decade.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Large Hadron Collider, a 16-mile proton smasher to be
built near Geneva, starts churning out results after 2005, particle
physicists from the United States will have to cross the Atlantic
if they wish to continue doing forefront research. By pooling their
resources across national borders and patiently building advanced
instruments at this site for half a century, European physicists
have established a laboratory that is about to assume unchallenged
leadership in a prestigious field their counterparts in the United
States had pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   Another type of particle collider able to create such extreme
conditions is on drawing boards in Europe, Japan and the United
States. Accelerator builders have been designing miles-long,
arrow-straight machines to collide trillion-volt beams of electrons
with their antimatter opposites, known as positrons. Violent
electron-positron collisions can provide physicists a complementary
and clearer picture of what occurred in the primordial fire. This
gargantuan ``linear collider'' is the natural next step for
particle physics.
</P>
<P>
   Although American physicists pioneered this alternative, they
are now struggling to assure financing for the conceptual design of
this machine, which would stretch some 20 miles and cost more than
$5 billion. Last year, with memories of the super collider debacle
still fresh, Congress almost slashed federal support for the linear
collider design effort. Its future remains precarious.
</P>
<P>
   Given its hefty cost and the fact that scientists of many
nations will have access to it, this huge machine must be built as
a truly international project. That is one obvious lesson of the
super collider, which was widely viewed as a U.S. national project
that later came begging for foreign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Since our government will probably have to pay a substantial
part of the new machine's cost, it should be in, or at least near,
the United States. By far the deepest pool of expertise in building
and operating linear colliders exists right here in America.
</P>
<P>
   If this nation hopes to remain an active player in particle
physics, it must support such a quark-busting machine, sharing the
burdens of this enormously expensive research. Sending all our top
practitioners overseas will never suffice if Americans are to be
equal partners.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a healthy particle physics program in the United
States needs a major new collider that can serve as the common
focus for theorists, experimenters and accelerator builders while
promoting scientific exchanges with other countries. Insights
gained on one continent can then be confirmed (or, perhaps,
rejected) and extended on the other. Science thrives when there are
multiple competing points of view.
</P>
<P>
   But after the super collider's inglorious demise, other nations
regard the United States as a capricious scientific partner.
Congress finances major construction projects on a year-to-year
basis and jealously guards its option to terminate them. Building a
truly international scientific center on American soil will be a
truly challenging enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, particle physicists in the United States face a difficult
future. There is a wealth of exciting research begging to be done
on the dark matter particles _ and their kin _ thought to
contribute most of the mass of the universe. And to observe the
intense primordial fire that forged them requires that we build a
new multibillion-dollar machine.
</P>
<P>
   The United States possesses a dismal record of international
cooperation on scientific megaprojects. Unless its record improves
drastically, this physics will soon be done elsewhere. The next
generation of American particle physicists will not enjoy the
research opportunities I was so lucky to have had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
