<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A slow-moving area of low pressure in central Oklahoma will lead
to numerous showers and thunderstorms Tuesday. Some of these storms
will produce heavy amounts of rainfall as they move very slowly.
Meanwhile, low clouds and patchy showers in West Texas will keep
readings below seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will decrease across the Northeast in the wake of a cold
front. The abundant sun will combine with warm breezes from the
west to yield mild readings along the Northeast coast. Clouds will
linger from North Carolina to the lower Ohio Valley as the same
front becomes nearly stationary.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine will promote very warm conditions in the
deserts of the Southwest, where readings will reach triple digits.
Meanwhile, the Northwest will be cool with showers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DEPARTING SNOW
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, weather observers in Alaska noted that much of the
winter snowpack near Fairbanks had melted away. Recent satellite
observations have also shown a much reduced snowpack in southern
and central Canada, with only the higher elevations of western
Canada and woodlands of Quebec carrying snow. As large tracts of
snow in northern sections of the hemisphere succumb to the
strengthening sun, the breeding ground for winter chill disappears.
Consequently, by May, cold fronts sweeping south from Canada are no
longer able to herald the harsh chill of midwinter.
</P>
</TEXT>
