<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS LAUNCH NEW CELL PHONE HEALTH STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scientists are launching a new series of studies to
determine whether radiation from cell phones sparks maladies such
as leukemia, cancer, birth defects, reproductive ailments in women
and diseases in children.
</P>
<P>
   The studies include a surveillance program that will search for
clusters of cell phone users suffering particular illnesses. The
goal of the program is to determine whether the devices were the
cause or a contributing factor to the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The group also will study whether the federal government's
existing guidelines for cell phone radiation exposure are stringent
enough to protect users.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Carlo, a lawyer and epidemiologist who directs the
Washington-based Health Risk Management Group, will manage the new
effort. Private individuals and cell phone companies have supplied
seed money, Carlo said. He estimated it could take a year or more
to raise the $60 million he says is needed to conduct the studies.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo declined to name the backers but stressed that his
organization is not accepting money from plaintiffs lawyers, who
could profit if a conclusive link is demonstrated between cell
phones and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo previously headed a five-year, $27 million project funded
by the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association, the
industry's trade association, that found possible health problems
associated with cellular phones use.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo said the new studies _ expected to last four years _ would
be farmed out to research and academic institutions around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The surveillance aspect of the research is unique among studies
that assess cell phone health risks, according to Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, nobody in the world is looking for specific health
problems'' possibly associated with specific brands of cell phones,
Carlo said. For the surveillance study, the idea is to get as many
cell phone users as possible to fill out detailed questionnaires
and allow themselves to be monitored by researchers on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists will watch for ``clusters'' of disease _ large
numbers of people suffering from a particular ailment who may also
share the same type of cell phone. ``If we have a cluster, we'll
send out a team into the field to do in-depth interviews. That may
lead us to making some type of conclusion in terms of a risk or may
lead to a follow-up research study,'' Carlo said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Nelson, a spokesman for the CTIA, said he was not
familiar with the planned studies. But he stressed that the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration and international health organizations
``thus far concluded that wireless phone use has no impact on
public health.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA says there is no scientific basis for concluding that
cell phones are unsafe _ or safe. The only way to conclusively
answer the safety question is through ``a significant research
effort,'' the FDA says.
</P>
<P>
   That effort is scheduled to get underway later this year when
the FDA and CTIA are expected to announce a joint research effort
to determine if there are cell phone health risks. The National
Cancer Institute and the UN's World Health Organization also are
conducting major studies about whether cell phones spark diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Federal safety regulators are concerned about findings released
last year from two industry-sponsored studies managed by Carlo's
organization.
</P>
<P>
   One of the studies _ conducted by the American Health Foundation
in New York _ found an association between cell phone use and a
rare type of brain tumor. The other study, conducted by Integrated
Laboratory Systems in Research Triangle Park, N.C., found that DNA
in human blood cells breaks down when exposed to large doses of
cell phone radiation, possibly laying the genetic groundwork for
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   With over 86 million cellular phone users in the United States
alone and 30,000 new users signing up daily, ``this translates into
a potentially significant public health problem, should the use of
these devices even slightly increase the risk of adverse health
effects,'' the FDA says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
