<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CAMBODIA-OTHELLO-NYT &LR;      05-01 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-OTHELLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHMER DANCE IN A LESSON FOR KHMER ROUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ At the end, the murdered Desdemona in her
pinnacled gold headdress rises again to gaze at her fate as her
desperate husband and killer, Othello, kneels before her in a
silent plea not for forgiveness but for punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus concludes a new retelling of Shakespeare's ``Othello'' in
the refined and ancient vocabulary of classical Khmer dance, and it
confronts Cambodia's tortured society with a difficult message:
Take responsibility for your evil deeds.
</P>
<P>
   This month, in the still-ravaged and poverty-ridden capital of
this tiny Southeast Asian nation, an expatriate Cambodian dancer
and choreographer has returned from the United States with a jolt
of modernity cloaked in the rigidly beautiful forms of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The stated aim of the choreographer, Sophiline Cheam Shapiro,
32, is to build a cultural bridge between her two worlds by
presenting a story from classical Western culture in the great
classical art form of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samritechhak,'' which means ``Dark Prince,'' is a homage to
her teachers and her tradition as well as an attempt to enrich the
nation she left nearly a decade ago with the vision she has gained
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With a $30,000 grant from the Irvine Foundation in California,
she is staging her creation with about 30 dancers, musicians and
singers from Cambodia's Royal University of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Her venture has been received with a cautious welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``A monkey in a cage is not as smart as a monkey in the
forest,'' she quoted her uncle, a leading dance teacher and patron
of the arts, as counseling her on her journey. But at a recent
rehearsal, dressed all in white and fluttering a black bamboo fan,
her uncle, Chheng Phon, remained quietly reserved about the
production of his young protege. ``It takes courage to try this,''
he said, speaking in French. ``For now I have no opinion. I await
the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro bows to his opinion. One quality she has not lost in her
transition to the West is reverence for her elders and her culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a young Cambodian artist I do not have the privilege to
change anything,'' she said. ``My ancestors created something
unique to history. I only have the privilege to try to make it
better. I think I would be a criminal if I did anything to destroy
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a remark that did seem to reflect the vibrant artistic
scene of her new home, California, she said she hoped to ``expand
the vocabulary of dance, to make it relevant and significant to
Cambodian audiences of today.''
</P>
<P>
   The choreography of Shapiro's ``Othello'' is exquisitely true to
the ancient form, with its complex and difficult movements, its
glittering costumes that send bouncing sprays of reflection onto
the walls, and its rhythmic, quavering melodies.
</P>
<P>
   She has adapted the story to be sung by a traditional chorus,
but even here she has used only familiar traditional melodies. Her
boldest innovation in the form itself, Shapiro says, is to lengthen
the rhythmic step of the dancers just the tiniest bit to suggest
the rocking of ocean waves.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how fixed the art form, every new artist brings
himself to it. And like everyone of her generation, Shapiro has
lived through one of the greatest traumas in her nation's history,
the brutal reign of the Communist Khmer Rouge, which was
responsible for the deaths of more than a million people from 1975
to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Now, perhaps as a result of her experience in America, perhaps
not, she has something to say to her countrymen. Cambodian men who
have seen her production say they find Othello's suicide a sign of
weakness, particularly in a military leader, Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been thinking about this, and there is probably
something Cambodians can learn from `Othello,' and that is that you
have to be responsible for your actions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Khmer Rouge today never say they were responsible for
killing millions of Cambodians. `Othello,' regardless of his
accomplishments in his military career, punishes himself severely
for his mistake in killing an innocent person. And in the story the
last word Othello says is not, `Please forgive me.' It is `Punish
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is a strong statement to make in today's Cambodia, where
powerful men are rarely punished. Most of the aging leaders of the
Khmer Rouge remain free, and most of society's leaders accept their
suggestion to ``let bygones be bygones.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's introduction of a foreign story, not to mention what
many here see as a foreign notion of accountability, troubles some
Cambodians. In a recent interview, a reporter from the daily
newspaper Rasmei Kampuchea repeatedly asked her about her
introduction of alien elements into an art form that has been
handed down painstakingly from teacher to pupil over the
generations. ``This is not just my concern but the concern of many
people,'' the reporter said.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro responded that Cambodian classical dance itself had
roots in India and that the central stories it recounts _ with
their many similarities to the themes of ``Othello'' _ are taken
from the Ramayana, the great Indian epic.
</P>
<P>
   She is not an alien to Cambodian culture. She was a child during
the time of the Khmer Rouge, and she was one of the first
youngsters to be trained in dance in the early 1980s when the few
surviving court dancers struggled to bring their art form back to
life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 she married an American writer, John Shapiro, and moved
to California, where she has devoted herself to Cambodian culture
as a dancer, teacher and administrator of cultural programs in Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had carried a sense of guilt for leaving her
teachers and fellow dancers behind in the threadbare academy. Her
production of ``Othello'' is in part an effort to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Cambodian artist, I feel somehow guilty that I left,''
she said. ``After the Khmer Rouge time my teachers worked so hard
to teach my generation, and they hoped that we would take over
responsibility for preserving the dance here. And then I left. They
were wasting their energy because their student was not useful to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I thought, well, I'm not the best dancer in school.
Probably I can learn something more in the United States, and in
the future I can serve Cambodia better.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ideas emerge most strongly at the end of the dance she has
choreographed. Aware that it is not proper in Cambodian tradition
for characters to die at the end, she resurrects them in a moment
that challenges both traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end they rise and become like sculptures,'' she said.
``Their decay is only physical. I want to say that Desdemona moves
on, whether she forgives Othello or not. Her meditative expression
contains deep resentment. That is the Cambodian people of today.
They are moving on, but they are not forgiving the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Othello is at her feet, taking responsibility for his
actions, unlike other Cambodian leaders, who just point their
fingers at each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
