<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-UPSHAW-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     05-01 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPSHAW-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAWN UPSHAW SALUTES A KINDRED SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN    
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  NEW YORK _ Dawn Upshaw seems to think less about individual
recital programs than about expansive celebrations of song that
require several concerts and lead her listeners through a maze of
styles and themes. As a soprano who is widely admired for the
beauty of her voice, her perceptive and communicative
interpretations and the inventiveness of her programming ideas,
Upshaw has the clout and the drawing power to hold the stage for a
series rather than an individual concert. She was thinking in
series terms a dozen years ago when her career was at an earlier
stage and before performer-driven series were as common as they
have been at Lincoln Center and Carnegie Hall these last few
seasons.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upshaw's current series, ``Images of Dawn,'' will make its way
to exotic new music and American popular song before it ends on May
20. But its first installment, on Sunday afternoon at Alice Tully
Hall, was a more conventional concert of French art song, with a
slight thematic twist. Upshaw offered it as a tribute to Jane
Bathori, a French mezzo-soprano who flourished in the early decades
of the 20th century and gave the premieres of dozens of works,
including the songs by Debussy, Ravel, Milhaud, Satie, Hahn,
Honegger, Roussel, Tailleferre and Koechlin that Upshaw sang. The
program largely replicated her recent Erato disc, ``Hommage a Jane
Bathori, the Inspiring Muse,'' which she recorded in a Paris
concert last year. Her superb accompanist on that recording, Jerome
Ducros, was also her collaborator on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Upshaw sees a kindred spirit here: like Bathori, she
sings and commissions a good deal of new music, and perhaps at the
back of her mind is the hope that a future soprano will recall her
with equal generosity. The program, after all, could have stood on
its merits without a unifying patron saint. And Upshaw is her own
singer, not a re-creator of a past style.
</P>
<P>
   Her interpretive view of the French song repertory is admirably
flexible, and although its overriding characteristic is an ear for
chromatic nuance it also had a playful side. That may not suit all
tastes: although her use of a slightly pinched ``child voice'' in
Satie's ``Dapheneo'' and some of Hahn's settings of Robert Louis
Stevenson poems was certainly supportable, given the texts, those
readings veered uncomfortably toward preciousness.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the dramatic and sometimes theatrical flair that
Upshaw brought to most of her readings had an enlivening effect,
particularly in Honegger's evocative ``Clotilde,'' ``Automne'' and
``Les Choches'' from the six Apollinaire settings and Roussel's
exquisitely emotional ``Adieux.'' Ducros matched Upshaw's fluid
readings at every turn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
