<HEADER>
A2575 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-01 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOREIGN POLICY INEXPERIENCE DOESN'T MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore points out correctly that
Gov. George W. Bush lacks experience in foreign policy, compared to
Gore's own extensive knowledge. So what?
</P>
<P>
   Presidential history shows that prior experience dealing with
international leaders and issues has very little to do with how
well presidents manage foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Far more important are the president's ability to analyze events
and use good judgment, the quality of advice from his experts and
the accuracy of the information available at decision-making time.
</P>
<P>
   History may sometimes repeat itself, but it never does so
precisely. Every problem the new president will face will be
different than the ones his predecessor confronted. Some may be
continuations of old issues, but the personalities and
circumstances that frame them will have inevitably changed.
</P>
<P>
   President John F. Kennedy, for instance, served on the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee for three years before he entered the
White House, giving him access to much insider information. But we
came to the brink of nuclear war during the 1962 Cuban missile
crisis, the result of Kennedy's shallow performance at his first
summit with Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev, who so underestimated
Kennedy he thought he could sneak Soviet missiles onto Cuban soil.
Kennedy saved the day by being tough-minded, but the crisis was his
fault in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Kennedy who expanded our military presence in Vietnam
beyond the handful of ``advisers'' sent in by President Dwight
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   As a former Senate majority leader, President Lyndon Johnson
also was an experienced foreign policy hand, yet he drastically
escalated the war in Vietnam. He bears most of the political burden
for that bloody disaster, which ruined his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon, a former vice president, prided himself on his
understanding of global affairs. He campaigned in 1968 with ``a
secret plan to end the war'' in Vietnam. Yet the war raged on until
a vague, humiliating settlement in 1972 called for U.S. withdrawal.
It was not until 1975, after Nixon's resignation over the Watergate
affair, that the United States went home.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's claim to foreign policy expertise rests mostly on the
opening of diplomatic relations with China during his
administration. Although Nixon and Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger would have us believe that their remarkable vision
accomplished this, it was really their good timing. China was in
economic trouble, its leadership was aging, and a little political
relaxation seemed in order.
</P>
<P>
   President Gerald Ford was in office so briefly he pretty much
got a pass on international problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter, a former governor like Presidents Reagan, Bush and
Clinton, wasn't so lucky. It may or may not have been his
inexperience that compounded the mess that was the Iranian hostage
crisis and the bungled rescue operation. The revolution in Iran
spun out of control when the U.S. embassy was seized, and it is
unlikely any training could have adequately prepared a president
for what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, who came to office with a legendary ignorance of
foreign affairs, lucked out with the formidable Secretary of State
George Shultz and the unraveling of the Soviet Union. The latter
had more to do with internal communist timing than with an American
president's dramatic rhetoric, although that and an overstuffed
military budget didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's personal role was more shadowy than substantive and
that saved him from taking the fall for the illegal contra war in
Nicaragua which was run from the White House basement by Oliver
North. That secret enterprise was the stuff of impeachment but when
investigated, Reagan was able to claim, apparently correctly, total
ignorance. Lesser officials were convicted instead.
</P>
<P>
   Then came George Bush, the most experienced foreign policy
expert of the era, having served as ambassadors to China and the
United Nations, and as director of the Central Intelligence Agency.
His quick invasion of Iraq and rollback of Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait was a triumph, with few American casualties. But when he
took the troops home without marching on Baghdad or getting rid of
Saddam Hussein, he left behind an angry sore in the Middle East
that plagues us still.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is no genius on foreign policy, but on the
whole he has managed things satisfactorily. The lid has been kept
on the potentially most dangerous problems.
</P>
<P>
   The crises in Bosnia and Kosovo have been handled shakily but
steadily, with allied partnerships, and kept at a publicly
acceptable level of violence. Middle East peace negotiations are
dicey as always, but no more scary than before. Terrorism from
rogue states, global environmental issues and international drug
traffic remain unsolved but nobody expected they would be.
</P>
<P>
   So it may not matter a great deal if Bush is a tad naove when he
meets with, say, a world leader whose name he could not recall in a
campaign interview. On the other hand, it may.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
