<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH PARLIAMENT FAILS TO ELECT LEADING PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The Parliament failed Monday for a second
time to muster the two-thirds vote necessary to elect the reformist
candidate for president who is favored by party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The chosen candidate, Ahmet Necdet Sezer, finished far ahead of
other candidates, with 314 votes. The next ballot is scheduled for
Friday, and in that round just a simple majority of 276 will be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sezer is supported by the leaders of all five parties
represented in Parliament, including Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's
organization, he has been considered a shoo-in for election. Many
Turks who are campaigning for a more open political system hope
that he will win, and they remained optimistic after the vote
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who support him are confident,'' said Orhan Erisen, an
executive who works with grass-roots groups. ``He's going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But although Sezer, who is the chief justice of the highest
court, remains the heavy favorite, influential figures with various
motives are reportedly conspiring quietly against him. Several
newspapers have reported that military commanders, who wield
considerable power, are less than thrilled with Sezer's candidacy.
He has advocated the repeal of laws that limit freedom of speech,
and senior officers have said in the past that those laws are
necessary to prevent Turks from advocating separatism, religious
fundamentalism or other subversive causes.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer has also asserted that the decisions of every government
agency, without exception, should be subject to judicial review.
The military regularly cashiers officers whom it considers
sympathetic to fundamentalism, and it denies them the right to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders have not publicly expressed opposition to
Sezer. One newspaper reported Monday that they were making no
visible efforts to block him because they considered it ``quite
impossible'' that he could turn his ideas into law.
</P>
<P>
   Another reported center of behind-the-scenes opposition Sezer is
the Islamic-oriented Virtue Party. Its leading figure, former Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan, is said to have told his friends in
Parliament that he dislikes Sezer because in a court case in which
he was a witness, Sezer refused to order a recess for prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Some Parliament members consider Sezer too liberal. Others may
resent his role in decisions that invalidated laws that would have
given them with lucrative pensions. Still others apparently hope to
promote members of their own parties rather than vote for a
lifelong independent like Sezer.
</P>
<P>
   Under Turkish law, Parliament may cast only four ballots in the
race, with a simple majority being enough to elect a candidate in
the third or fourth round. If no candidate wins a majority after
four rounds, Parliament is dissolved and new elections are called.
Members are thought to want to avoid this at all costs. So if no
candidate wins a majority on Friday, one is expected to be chosen
on the fourth and last ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In a fourth ballot, only the candidates who finished first and
second in the third ballot would be allowed to compete. Sezer could
find himself facing the speaker of Parliament, Yildirim Akbulut,
who finished a distant second in the balloting Monday with 88
votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
