<HEADLINE>
EVEN FLOODS AND MUDSLIDES CAN'T DIMINISH VENEZUELA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ The main luxury hotel is still being used
as a military barracks, and tractors and earth-moving trucks now
provide the only traffic along the main drag that used to bustle
with nightclubs and restaurants. Four months after floods and
mudslides devastated the Caribbean coast just north of here,
tourism in Venezuela's main beach playground zone remains crippled.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster was the worst in the modern history of this South
American nation of 23 million people, killing several thousand
people and leaving an additional 150,000 homeless. But the toll to
the economy and infrastructure has also proved immense, and
recovery efforts throughout the coastal state of Vargas have been
slowed by the inability of authorities to marshal money,
organization, personnel and equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to government statistics, tourist arrivals in
Venezuela fell by more than 25 percent in 1999, with the sharpest
decline coming at the end of the year, normally the busiest period
here. Figures for the first quarter of this year haven't been
announced, but tour and hotel operators say they will be even more
discouraging. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit by the rivers of mud that came cascading down Mount
Avila, which separates this capital of 6 million people from
coastal resort towns, were dozens of hotels and time-share
condominiums that had sprung up along the shore. The luxury
Sheraton Macuto, where army troops are now lodged, is expected to
reopen this year, but some smaller hotels built on gullies are not
expected to reopen, and the timetable for others is unclear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation continues to be difficult, with some hotels
still buried in mud,'' said Hugo Arrioja, president of the Hotel
Federation of Venezuela. ``We have to recognize that some of the
smaller ones are going to be closed for good, but we hope that the
majority will be able to re-establish themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arrioja acknowledged that the disaster zone's beaches, its main
lure, are also ``totally damaged'' and that tourism there is going
to have to find a new focus, such as mountain climbing or fishing.
While no one knows for certain how many people died in the floods
that began Dec. 15, it is assumed that hundreds or even thousands
of bodies were entombed under the avalanches of mud, boulders and
other debris that engulfed and destroyed several popular beaches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disaster also forced the closing of both Venezuela's main
international airport at Maiquetia and the nearby port of La
Guaira, used by cruise ships, for several weeks. Both have now
reopened, and while there is nothing for visitors to see in the
immediate vicinity other than tent cities and reconstruction work,
Venezuelan officials emphasize that the rest of the country was
unaffected by the calamity and remains open for business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be five years before tourism can resume in the 25-mile
coastal strip that was damaged,'' said Maria Eugenia Loriente,
director of Corpoturismo, the government tourism agency. ``But we
still have more than 1,500 miles of coastline that were unaffected,
as well as Amazon jungles, Angel Falls and plains teeming with
wildlife, all of which are hundreds of miles away from the disaster
zone and are of greater interest to foreign tourists anyway.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, visitors from abroad still seem to be staying away
from this country, which is larger than Texas. Linda Sonderman, an
American who runs Alpi Tour, a travel agency here specializing in
adventure tourism, estimates that her bookings are down 40 percent
this year and places the blame on lack of information and
publicity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuela is still as spectacular as ever, but the fact is
that people are still worried and nothing has been done to dispel
the idea that this disaster was not localized,'' she said. ``It
shouldn't be affecting things any more, but it is, and we are just
beginning to recover.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tourism industry here was already confronting difficulties
before the December mudslides, so not all of the decline can be
attributed to the disaster. Perhaps the most expensive country in
South America, Venezuela has a currency that economists say is
overvalued by as much as 50 percent, making accommodations and
meals more expensive than in neighboring countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One side effect of the disaster, travel agents here said, is
that many middle-class Venezuelans who in the past spent their
holidays in the affected zone are now heading for nearby Caribbean
destinations such as Aruba, Curacao and the Dominican Republic. As
a result, fewer hotel rooms than usual may be available there, they
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
