<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AARP-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE AGING WANT TO STAY HOME AS LONG AS POSSIBLE, SURVEY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The vast majority of baby boomers and the elderly
don't want the flavor of home sweet home to turn sour, and many are
taking steps to modify their homes for use far into their
retirement years, according to a survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons's national survey of
housing and home modification _ ``Fixing to Stay'' _ found that 83
percent of those surveyed said they want to stay in their current
homes as long as possible. In an effort to mix in the views of
soon-to-retire baby boomers, the survey questioned 2,000 persons
age 45 and above.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the survey at a press conference Monday kicked off
the organization's ``Independent Living Week.'' With over 34
million members, the AARP is sponsoring activities aimed at helping
older people live in their homes longer, as well as raising
awareness among soon-to-retire people that it's never too early to
start senior-proofing a home.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Harper, AARP's senior housing specialist, said seniors can
take steps that would help solve such classic problems as slipping
and falling in a tub or on the stairs, or turning faucets on and
off.
</P>
<P>
   Simple changes in a home can sometimes make the difference
between staying put or moving to a nursing home, Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message we've got to communicate is that `it's not you _
it's the house,''' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was the fifth report since 1986 covering the
relationship between housing and aging. This survey differed from
previous ones because it included _ for the first time _
respondents between ages 45 and 55, and a specific sampling of
African Americans and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The older people get, the more likely they are to want to stay
put, the survey found. While 75 percent of those between 45 and 55
said they hoped to remain in their current home as long as
possible, 95 percent of those 75 and older want to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The answers by members of minority groups tracked closely with
the answers from non-minority group members, with one exception:
Minorities were six percentage points less likely than
non-minorities to want to stay in their current residences.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that many respondents have made at least
one modification that makes the home easier for older people to
live in it. The modifications range from non-skid strips in tubs,
showers and on stairs, levers in place of faucet knobs, and
nightlights in dark hallways and bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   They also included major renovations such as adding handrails
and grab bars in bathrooms, widening doorways and converting a
first floor to living quarters.
</P>
<P>
   At age 64, Harper found he had to convert his basement into a
living space after recent knee surgery. The experience heightened
his awareness of what obstacles senior citizens face in their later
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My house was probably a good design for architects and the
Peter Pan-type population,'' he said. But as far as anyone who is
aging goes, ``it's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those unable to add new features, 37 percent said they were
unable to do it themselves and 36 percent said they could not
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-FISH-ART-NYT &LR;      05-01 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FISH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S GREATEST LAKE AND ITS MOST POPULAR DENIZEN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 14 and 15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISTVYANKA, Russia _ Almost any resident of this village can
tick off the seemingly endless string of superlatives about the
great lake _ inland sea, really _ that laps insistently against the
town docks. Lake Baikal is the biggest, the oldest, by far the
deepest, the clearest lake on earth. Were it empty, all the world's
rivers would have to flow for an entire year to fill it. It has
more than 1,500 plants and animals found nowhere else, including
the world's only purely freshwater seal.
</P>
<P>
   But press a resident to say what he loves most about Baikal, and
he may cast his lot with the nondescript, gray, oily, foot-long
fish that dwells therein.
</P>
<P>
   Siberians love the lowly omul. They love it fried, dried,
smoked, baked, grilled, salted, stuffed, with internals and without
internals, with and without scales. Residents of the eastern shore
even like it slightly decayed _ ``with odor,'' they call it.
</P>
<P>
   In warm weather _ which is to say above freezing _ they sell it
from dozens of roadside stands along the shore, their portable
cookers belching the smoke of burning alder, with rows of cured
fish on the tables, waiting to be wrapped in newspaper and carried
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``'The stands are a relatively new thing,'' said one 31-year-old
omul-hawker, who would identify himself only as Mikhail. ``In
Soviet times, you could hardly find any fish. The rumor was always
that the catch went under a contract to Czechoslovakia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days we sell a hundred; some days 10,'' he added. ``It
depends on the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Life has not been kind to the little fish, a distant cousin of
the lake herring that inhabits the Great Lakes. Experts at the
Russian Academy of Science's Institute of Limnology _ limnology is
the scientific study of lakes _ say the population has risen and
fallen in tandem with wars, famines and other events that forced
people to turn to this reliable food supply.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, fishermen took so many omul that netting them was
briefly banned. When a hydroelectric dam was built on the Angarsk
River, Baikal's only outlet, the lake rose, causing a change in
water temperature that led to a drastic decline in the fry that are
the omul's main meal. The result has been a smaller and,
presumably, hungrier omul than in past decades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains the great lake's most abundant fish. Up to
150,000 tons of omul live there, although the numbers are said to
have declined in recent years, and the the government limits the
annual take to 10,000 tons. Served in a decent restaurant, the
omul's abundant, light gray meat tastes not unlike flounder, bland
and only slightly fishy. Smoked, it acquires an almost sweet
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   But to an outsider, the omul's main selling point seems not
taste, but price. Just about any stand will sell one, smoked until
its cellophane-thin skin turns golden, for between 7 and 15 rubles
_ about 25 to 50 cents _ depending on its size.
</P>
<P>
   The wharf at Listvyanka, the main stopping point for travelers
from the nearby big cities of Irkutsk and Angarsk, is prime
territory for the omul merchants, and it appears to be flourishing.
On the steep hill behind the shore, steam baths and vacation homes
have sprung up with spectacular views of the snowcapped Khamat
Dabar mountains to the east, across 30 miles of water.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen or so omul sellers who had set up their smokers and
tables on the wharf said they were increasingly visited by tourists
from Germany, Japan and the United States. But one day recently, a
cold wind blew in off the ice-covered lake and customers were
scarce, so they entertained a visitor with some of the more exotic
omul recipes.
</P>
<P>
   There is raw salted omul _ the fish is placed in a pile of salt,
organs intact, and left for 12 hours before being washed and eaten.
And there is pressed omul, in which layers of salt and gutted omul
are alternated, lasagna-style. There is hot smoked omul, roasted
for 40 minutes, and cold-smoked omul, bathed in cool alder smoke
for three days. Lightly salted and dried _ its innards are pried
open and exposed to the air with tiny matchstick-size crossbeams _
``you can take it anywhere,'' one merchant said. ``It will last
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the overwhelming preference is for gutted fish, some
customers prefer hot-smoked omul with the organs intact, and
generally wolf it down, scales and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like it with organs because it's juicier that way,'' said
Yana Borodina, a 23-year-old woman who tended one table.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there is omul ``s dushkom'' _ with odor _ the
delicacy of Baikal's mountainous eastern shore and a traditional
dish of the Buryat, the Mongol-related people who live there.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe is fairly simple: Catch an omul, place it in warm
sunlight until it begins to smell _ generally 10 to 20 minutes _
and eat it, scales, organs and all. ``Each according to his
taste,'' a grimacing Borodina said, then told a joke: It seems that
a man from the east went into a market and asked the owner, ``Is
the fish fresh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' the owner said. ''In that case,'' the man
replied, ``I'll go somewhere else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
