<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2595 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-KENT30-AZR &LR;      05-01 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENT30-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECHOES OF KENT STATE: SHOOTINGS TOUCHED OUR INSULATED LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - On May 4, 1970, National Guard units at Kent State
University opened fire on students protesting the war in Vietnam:
Four dead in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   That little holocaust 30 years ago brought to its knees months
of protests on student campuses across America and even touched our
serene pastures at the University of Iowa, a campus usually removed
from the radical fields of Berkeley, Madison and eastern Ohio. My
now-graying generation was shaped by such events, whether we were
then burners of draft cards, flags and bras, or whether we prefered
to light our fires with more mainstream incendiary devices like
lava lamps.
</P>
<P>
   Down with protests. Up with People.
</P>
<P>
   Kent State was a seminal event in our lives, like the
assassination of John F. Kennedy, like Woodstock. We share a common
generational memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1970, I was a freshman at Iowa, which had
hosted a meager but respectable offering of demonstrations -
candlelight vigils, Friday brown-bag protests on the main square of
buildings known as the Pentacrest and the repeated busting of
windows at the very Establishment campus book store - officially
named Iowa Book &AMP; Supply, dubbed Iowa Book &AMP; Crook by the
anti-capitalist counterculture.
</P>
<P>
   Our own state troopers, the Iowa Military Police Battalion, were
called in from time to time to quell disturbances. Protesters
burned a bus. A World War II-era building housing the rhetoric
department and graduate student offices was torched. Student
strikes were called.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution had come slowly to Iowa City. The flow of agitation
arrived in the Heartland as a trickle that became a stream, led by
drifters from Students from a Democratic Society and the Weathermen
and freelance activists who traveled from campus to campus like
itinerant preachers with their own fold-up pulpits and Bibles
written by Marx, Mao, Lenin and Lennon. In the peace and civil
rights faith, they were junior clergy, serious about their
religious convictions but temperate in the execution of those
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   No blood was spilled. Across the state at Iowa State University
in Ames, we heard, someone dumped a vial of pig's blood as a
symbolic gesture befitting farm country.
</P>
<P>
   Ours were puny events, though, compared to the clash between tin
soldiers and anti-war protesters wielding daisies at Kent State. In
the blink of an eye, like thunder suddenly reverberating on a sunny
day, the flower children were met with 13 seconds of gunfire aimed
at their free assembly. Who ordered the peaceful protest to turn
violent and who signaled the first shot to be fired has remained a
mystery. One minute there was singing, and the next minute bodies
were falling.
</P>
<P>
   Four children fell dead on the ground, nine were wounded, and
one teenager became the most famous runaway in America when a
photographer caught her look of horror as she knelt over the body
of one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa City, I was one of the non-activists who saw the horror
only as it was reflected in the faces of the truly committed. I was
a fledgling journalist and Republican sorority girl looking on
anti-war events with no more than idle curiosity. Hippies. I would
pass the weekly lunchtime vigils on my way to freshman English and
barely take notice of students in khaki jackets and blue jeans who
ate sprout sandwiches on Roman Meal bread and mulled the latest
body counts in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, they hoped, perching weekly on the cold metal railing
that surrounded the Pentacrest would convince archenemy Richard
Nixon to pull out of Saigon. Did Nixon keep abreast of events in
Iowa City? Twenty-year-olds wearing peace signs believed that he
did.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Kent State shootings, collateral damage two continents
away had little impact on America's silent majority. It had little
impact on our student body until the president of our university,
hoping to avoid a similar tragedy along the banks of the Iowa
River, announced the spring semester would end prematurely and all
students would be asked to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   That left Iowa City in the hands of summer school students and
our own personal pack of outside agitators who milled around
college campuses in those days looking for a cause. Their cause was
most often Richard Nixon's aggression in southeast Asia, a policy
that did not sit well among college students, especially those at
risk for drawing low draft numbers and being sent to the boot camps
of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   When our college president announced the closing of campus, I
telephoned my brother, a senior at Iowa, sobbing that I didn't want
to leave school. I loved college. I had heard the drumming at Kent
State, but Iowa City marched to a different beat. I was pleading.
Let's not over-react. Let cooler heads prevail. Let the little
sorority girl stay. Free me. Up with me. Ban the bomb, but let me
stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   My big brother was only a little sympathetic to my despair, more
sympathetic to the anti-war cause. The next fall he would be one of
those young men who drew low draft numbers from the Selective
Service lottery and months later received his conscription notice.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home to my parents' house in upstate New York in May
of 1970, I languished in front of the television set watching
Marcus Welby and the Beverly Hillbillies. I took a summer job in
the bed and bath department at JC Penney. When a high school
classmate home from Kent State told of the sober mood that had
fallen over her campus after the tragedy, I commiserated. Thanks to
those trigger-happy Guardsmen, I had had to leave school early. I
had my own pain to deal with. Wasn't I a victim, too?
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that way when I was 20.
</P>
<P>
   Those were heady summers. In the summer of 1969, I worked at JC
Penney while the original Woodstock festival made history at
Yasgur's farm in downstate New York and Neil Armstrong walked on
the moon way, way, way upstate. In the summer of 1973, I worked at
JC Penney while President Nixon squirmed through the Watergate
trials and fought to save his legacy. In the summer of 1974, I was
working at my first job in newspapers when Richard Nixon resigned
the presidency and left his legacy in the hands of historians. For
Nixon and the war in Vietnam, Kent State had marked the beginning
of the end.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1988, I had developed a perspective about the
events of 18 years before. If not a radical, I was at least now a
Democrat, an older but wiser journalist, a little jaded as this
profession sometimes makes its people. My brother had served his
stint stateside, unscathed, and was raising a family of three
daughters, with one more in his future. His politics and mine had
finally converged.
</P>
<P>
   In May that year, a friend and I went to Washington, D.C., and
visited the stunning Vietnam War Memorial. As Baby Boomers who knew
men who had served in the war, we were sobered by the sight of 96
panels of black granite inscribed with the names of 58,000
Americans killed in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-eight thousand dead Americans. Two million dead
Vietnamese. Four dead in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   As we stood there awed by the panorama of names, a group of
teenagers on a field trip came by, acting silly, giggling,
irreverent. We were irritated. This younger generation. Don't they
know their history?
</P>
<P>
   We tried to shame them with a glance, but they were too giddy to
consider life can end in an instant even for college students
speaking their minds. They had years to go before they would
discover war not only kills warriors but also the hearts of
presidents and children picking flower.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the truth, and it made me feel old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
