<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KENT-CUSELLA-COX     05-01 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENT-CUSELLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. RUNS with KENT-REVISITED
 &HT;    At 12:24 p.m. on May 4, 1970, Ohio National Guardsmen ended four
days of anti-war demonstrations at Kent State University with a
13-second burst of rifle fire that left four students dead and nine
other people wounded.
 &HT;    For 29 years, anniversaries of the 1970 killings at KSU have
been marked with songs, poems, prayers and speeches. The 30th
observance is Thursday. It will be the most elaborate of them all.
 &HT;    For the next four days, the Dayton Daily News will examine what
happened at Kent State ago through the eyes of the people who were
there, and those whose lives were touched by it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the evening of May 4, 1970, as other Kent State University
students were hurriedly packing their belongings and heading for
home, Lou Cusella was alone in the basement of the a morgue,
waiting to identify the body of his friend and roommate William
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the students killed on the campus that day by Ohio
National Guardsmen _ Sandra Scheuer, Allison Krause and Jeffrey
Miller _ had already been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The body of the fourth victim lay on a gurney in the room next
door to where Cusella was sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked a few questions by the people at the morgue, then
they told me to stand up,'' he said. ``They slowly opened the door
to the next room and I saw a white light gleaming down from the
ceiling onto the body. There was no question in my mind. It was
Bill Schroeder.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusella, now a communications professor at the University of
Dayton, was a third-year communications major at KSU in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   A transfer student from Lorain Community College, he had grown
up within a block of Schroeder in Lorain, which is about 20 miles
west of Cleveland. He and Schroeder, 19, lived with four other
students in a house at 603 Franklin Ave., a two-block walk from the
KSU campus.
</P>
<P>
   Cusella believes the tone of the violent four days that ended
with the shooting of the four students was set Friday night in
downtown Kent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first really warm weekend of the spring quarter,
and the bars along Water Street were packed with people,'' he said.
``Most appeared to be students, but I also saw some motorcycle-gang
types in the crowd. Early on, the mood was cheerful, but as the
evening wore on, it changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The partiers eventually poured into Water Street, making it
difficult for motorists to pass. Then a large metal trash can was
placed in the middle of the street and set afire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew the Kent police would be coming, and when they
did they were wearing riot gear and carrying nightsticks,'' Cusella
said. ``As the police dispersed the crowd with tear gas, some store
windows were broken. That's when it became an us-vs.-them
situation, and that set the stage for what was to come.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after Kent officials requested that the National
Guard be sent to the city, the university's ROTC building was
torched by students. When firefighters arrived, their hose lines
were cut and they were pelted with rocks. On Sunday, hundreds of
students were driven off with tear gas after they gathered on the
university Commons.
</P>
<P>
   Cusella observed many of the violent acts of the weekend. ``If
you were involved in any way with campus life, you couldn't help
but run into something that had to do with the anti-war
demonstrations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When National Guardsmen opened fire on students at 12:24 p.m.
Monday, Cusella was standing at the back of Taylor Hall, which
housed the school's journalism and architecture school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was among those running from the bullets'' he said. ``It was
chaos. Students were screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting stopped, Cusella retraced his steps to the
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I walked, I heard sirens,'' he said. ``Crossing the parking
lot near Prentice Hall, I saw Jeffrey Miller's brain matter and
blood splattered on the pavement. ``
</P>
<P>
   Cusella returned to the house where he lived. He spent the next
several hours trying to locate his roommates.
</P>
<P>
   ``One by one they turned up _ everybody but Bill Schroeder,'' he
says. ``Nobody knew where Bill was. ``
</P>
<P>
   Cusella turned on the television and watched as a Cleveland
station reported the shootings. ``The station had the names of
Scheuer, Krause and Miller, but the fourth victim was identified as
'James Schneider.' The report said he was a non-student from New
York. That chilled me because Schneider sounds a lot Schroeder.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Cusella got a telephone call from a friend who was in his
dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's Bill?'' the friend wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, how's Bill?'' Cusella asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been shot,'' the caller replied. ``I helped lift him into
the ambulance. He was shot in the upper body, but he spoke to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusella phoned Robinson Memorial Hospital in Ravenna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them if they had a shooting victim there that hadn't
been identified, and the man I was talking to said, `Yeah. Do you
think you know who he is?' I told him, `I think I might.' The man
took my name and telephone number and told me he'd call me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he received a call from an Ohio senator who said he'd heard
Cusella might be able to identify one of the slain students. He
asked him if he'd be willing to go to the morgue. Cusella said he
would. About the same time KSU officials shut down the campus and
sent the students home, a Portage County Sheriff's cruiser carrying
two deputies pulled up at his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took me to a large building in Ravenna,'' he said. ``We
went to the basement, they led me into a room and told me to sit
down. A few minutes later, two men came in. One was a soft-spoken,
Italian-looking man who reminded me of my uncles, who lived in
Buffalo. He asked me, `What does your roommate usually wear for
pants?' When I told him Bill almost always wore denim jeans, he
looked relieved and said, `This man was wearing orange corduroy
bell bottoms.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when my heart sank. Bill's favorite pants were a pair
of orange corduroy bell bottoms. He called them his `Brian Jones
pants.' Jones was one of the original Rolling Stones. Later, after
I'd identified Bill, I lost it. I cried.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1975 Justice Department report, Schroeder was at
least 335 feet from the troops when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   On the 25th anniversary of the shootings, Cusella was invited to
the university to talk about Schroeder. ``I described Bill as a
blossoming Renaissance man,'' he says. ``He was an Eagle Scout. And
a high school honor student. He played baseball and ran track. He
had a great sense of humor, and he loved serious talk about serious
issues. For a long time, he'd planned to be a geologist, but then
he changed his major to psychology. Oddly, Bill was at Kent State
on an ROTC scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   After that 1995 visit to Kent State, Cusella vowed he would
never go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I'd seen all of Kent that I wanted to see ... and
that the only way I'd go back is if someone told me May 4, 1970,
never really happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cusella has changed his mind. On Thursday afternoon he'll
return to the campus to talk again about Schroeder at the 30th May
4 Commemoration sponsored by the student-run May 4 Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to go because nobody else offered to talk about
Bill,'' he said. ``My speech will be short, then I'll come home.
I'm not going back to Kent to reconnect with my past, or anything
like that. I'm doing it for Bill's mother.'' And probably, too, for
Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Bob Batz by e-mail at bobbatz(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KENT-REVISITED-COX     05-01 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENT-REVISITED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. RUNS with KENT-CUSELLA
 &HT;    At 12:24 p.m. on May 4, 1970, Ohio National Guardsmen ended four
days of anti-war demonstrations at Kent State University with a
13-second burst of rifle fire that left four students dead and nine
other people wounded.
 &HT;    For 29 years, anniversaries of the 1970 killings at KSU have
been marked with songs, poems, prayers and speeches. The 30th
observance is Thursday. It will be the most elaborate of them all.
 &HT;    For the next four days, the Dayton Daily News will examine what
happened at Kent State ago through the eyes of the people who were
there, and those whose lives were touched by it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Vet got news of Kent State from Hanoi Hannah's show
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was May 4, 1970 and Jim ``Doc'' Perry was celebrating his
18th birthday with 11 other members of the 5th Infantry in a damp,
dimly lighted underground bunker in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the DMZ _ the area between North and South Vietnam
_ and the day before we were hit pretty hard by Charlie, so we were
spending the evening drinking Budweiser and listening to rock music
on a North Vietnamese propaganda radio station,'' Perry says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A song ended, then the host of the show _ we called her 'Hanoi
Hannah' _ broke in and said something like, 'Now the Americans are
murdering college students who don't want to go to war.' That's how
I found out about the shootings at Kent State University.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment Perry and the other men in the bunker just stared
at the radio. Then the jokes began.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the guys said, 'Can you believe it? All those National
Guardsmen and they could kill only four college students?,''' Perry
recalls. ``We all laughed. I know it sounds cruel, but you have to
remember what was happening then. There we were, ready to lay down
our lives for our country, and college kids all over America were
pretending to preach peace by burning buildings and cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, 47 and vice president of the 137-member Chapter 97 of the
Miami Valley Vietnam Veterans of America, was 17 when he enlisted
in May 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us were young. Real young.'' the former combat medic
says. ``At first, we were awed by the whole war thing. Then we
settled in.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry enlisted at 17 because serving in the military is a family
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six generations of Perrys served their country, starting with
my great-great-grandfather,'' he explains. 'We were in the Civil
War, the Spanish-American War, World Wars I and II, the Korean War
and Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days immediately following the killings at Kent State,
Perry and other members of the 5th Infantry got most of their
information about the shootings from the enemy radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened to Hanoi Hannah instead of Armed Forces Radio
because she played better music,'' Perry says. ``Besides, our own
people weren't telling us anything about the war. We were under
strict orders to destroy all of our mail after we read it. And we
weren't allowed to carry anything that would identify us because
the enemy had people in the states and they could make trouble for
our families.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those precautions, letters written by American fighting
men and women fell into enemy hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Hanoi Hannah used them against us every chance she got,''
Perry says. ``She'd deliver 'Dear John Letters' to the troops.
She'd get ahold of a letter with some guy's name on it and she'd
come on the air and say 'Dear so-and-so, your mother has been
killed in a car accident in Cleveland.' Propaganda radio was hard
to deal with because it got into your head. And you can't fight a
war with stuff like that in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry wrote many letters to his mother in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I didn't realize it at the time, my mail was being
censored,'' he says. ``If I wrote that two guys were killed
yesterday, somebody would blot it out with with a felt pen. ``
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``One time I ran out of writing paper, so I wrote a
letter to my mother on a cardboard carton that had held spaghetti
and meat balls. When Mom sent me her next letter, she included five
packs of stationery.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who had two tours of duty in Vietnam, was wounded twice.
On Christmas Eve 1970 he was injured by a rocket-propelled grenade
while treating two wounded soldiers. In September 1971 he was hit
twice by enemy bullets during a helicopter rescue mission to the Ho
Chi Minh Trail in Laos. The chopper then crashed, killing the pilot
and crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combat medics spent a lot of time retrieving bodies,'' he
says. ``We didn't handle the small stuff. We saw major trauma.
There was lots of bleeding. Lots of dying. The Viet Cong had all
sorts of ways to kill you. If the mortar fire didn't get you, there
were booby traps and pointed punji sticks smeared with human
excrement. If you took one of those in the leg, it had to be
treated in a matter of hours, or you'd lose the leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry believes time has mellowed the feelings of some of the
Miami Valley's more than 31,000 Vietnam War veterans toward the
1970s war protestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, we thought anything anti-war was anti-us,'' he
says. ``But we're older now, and more educated. I'm a former altar
boy. My parents raised me to be forgiving. I can't bring those four
dead students back any more than I can recapture the innocence I
had when I celebrated my 18th birthday in that bunker on May 4,
1970. But life goes on. I really don't think those National
Guardsmen wanted to kill those kids at Kent State.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry pauses, then adds: ``One thing hasn't changed for me
though. I still hate Jane Fonda. I won't even watch her movies on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
