<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-MOZAMBIQUE-COX     05-01 1852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOZAMBIQUE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wright State University medical residents give aid
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lake below their helicopter was littered with treetops
pointing straight up.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a lake. The emergency medicine residents from
Wright State University knew that. The repeated flooding in
Mozambique was the reason they went to this country in southeastern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   They interrupted their lives for nearly three weeks last month
to address the desperate need for doctors, food and medical
supplies in a country that is one of the world's poorest and least
healthy in the best of times. The floods that left water marks nine
feet high on one town's schoolhouse brought infection, starvation
and homelessness cascading into an already bleak landscape where
about 30 percent of the people are infected with HIV, only seven of
every eight babies survive their first birthdays and the per-capita
telephone rate would scatter about 3,000 of them through
Montgomery, Greene, Miami and Clark counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of any other residency program in the country
that has ever done anything like this,'' said Dr. Roger Pacholka,
who connected the medical residents with funding from Humedica, a
Christian disaster-relief agency in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters were receding by the time residents arrived in
late March, but Drs. John Henner, Frank Lee and Brian Loveridge
still saw furniture on the rooftops of city houses and roofs on the
ground alongside rural huts, their waterlogged reeds now limp as
spaghetti. They treated patients who had walked for two days and
visited others almost too weak to blink while their government
officials sold donated food and supplies for cash.
</P>
<P>
   They saw the bloated bellies of malnutrition that have become
icons for relief agencies. They saw some of the world's deadliest
strains of malaria, carried by mosquitos that were bred by the
acres of impromptu ponds. They saw people with oozing skin
infections who were too weak to brush the flies away from their
pus. They saw parasitic worms big enough to turn patients' hips and
stomachs into bas-relief maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw about 60 to 150 people each day,'' Henner said last
week, back at the Wright State School of Medicine's emergency
medicine headquarters on the grounds of Kettering Medical Center.
On some days when they didn't split up, Loveridge said they would
see 300 people in line when they arrived, treat all of them and
more, and see another 300 people waiting when they left. But they
also knew the floods had chased more than 360,000 from their homes
and drowned thousands more, according to estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treated very few people in the big picture,'' Henner said,
``but at least for those few people, I think we made a huge impact
on their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveridge had spent two years in Brazil on a Mormon mission. ``I
thought I knew what poverty was,'' he said. ``Mozambique just
doesn't compare to that. The floods made things worse, but a lot of
their problems were just part of everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacholka, a Wright State emergency medicine alum now working at
Miami Valley Hospital, has been going to Mozambique and nearby
Swaziland for several years. He's there now with his wife, Katy, a
nurse at Greene Memorial Hospital. They established the In His Name
mission a year ago and were planning to expand their work to
Central America when Pacholka heard from one of his Mozambique
friends last month.
</P>
<P>
   The man had barely escaped the flood that overran his home in
Xai Xai (pronounced ``shy shy''). Pacholka called Dr. Glenn
Hamilton, the emergency residency department's chairman, and Dr.
Scott Doak, its director, asking for help. Thirty hours later about
half of the program's 36 residents had volunteered. Eight residents
and three faculty members were chosen for three separate trips.
</P>
<P>
   Other residency programs aren't flexible enough to undertake
such a journey in place of the training that had been planned,
Pacholka said, ``but Glenn and Scott know these experiences will be
very beneficial.'' What is emergency medicine, after all, but
quickly treating an unpredictable variety of severe medical
problems? Mozambique was just the extreme version.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw a lot of the same stuff we see here, but at such an
advanced state that we never see it here,'' Doak said, looking at a
picture of a boy whose scabies seemed to blister his entire back.
They saw a few examples of the oozing, deaf ears that result from
letting repeated ear infections go untreated. They saw countless
people who had been blinded by trachoma, a common eye infection
easily treated with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end of our trip, we started looking into every
kid's eyes that we saw, just to make sure they didn't have
trachoma,'' Lee said. The residents won't see that in the United
States because a preventive ointment is applied to the eyes of
every newborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably costs a penny,'' Doak said.
</P>
<P>
   Exploding crocodiles, makeshift clinics
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, malaria was most prevalent near the original river
banks, while fungal and other skin infections were more common out
in the country. A common fungus was transmitted from cows to humans
by flies. ``It would get into their hands and fingers and swell up
with pus,'' Henner said. ``Some people looked like they had Mickey
Mouse hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The natives, from Bantu tribes, had their own traditional
medicine for these infections. ``Then the infections got really
bad,'' Henner said, because their treatment consisted of packing
the wounds in a compound of dried leaves and cow feces.
</P>
<P>
   Microbes weren't the only danger spread by the flooding.
Mozambique endured 18 years of civil war until 1992. International
agencies had marked hundreds of thousands of land mines since then.
The floods not only washed away the markers, they also dislodged
many of the mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a crocodile farm with about 7,000 to 10,000
crocodiles, and they got loose when the farm was flooded,'' Henner
said. ``We were told one of them swallowed a land mine and blew
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the crocodiles went downstream until they reached
Xai Xai on the Indian Ocean. Tasting salt, they fled the water and
wound up roaming the town, along with the snakes who also disliked
saltwater. ``I treated one woman with vision problems,'' Loveridge
said. ``A cobra had spit into her eyes from the ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Xai Xai sits on the mouth of the Limpopo River, which originates
in nearby South Africa. At midnight on the morning of March 17,
nearly six weeks after the region's flooding began, Henner said
South Africa's government decided to open its flood gates in order
to keep its levees from breaking. The wave it unleashed was nearly
10 feet high, crashing through Mozambique as its residents slept.
</P>
<P>
   The Wright State doctors stayed upstream from Xai Xai in
Chibuto, a city of 150,000 before the flooding submerged half of
it. With the phone lines, electricity and running water knocked
out, they filled their generator with black market gasoline for
$5.50 a gallon and took cold showers from rainwater they had
stored.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, they boarded a helicopter from Helimission, one
of many relief agencies in Mozambique, and flew to remote settings
with medical supplies and the locals they had quickly trained as
assistants. They set up in churches or below tree branches, used
piles of flour sacks for operating tables and examined lines of
people that never ended.
</P>
<P>
   There was a hospital in Chibuto, but the helicopter had only so
much room and the doctors saw 50 or 60 people a day who would have
been admitted without question back home. ``You'd see somebody at
10 in the morning and you'd have to say, `If you're still the
sickest person I've seen at the end of the day, I'll take you
back,''' Henner said.
</P>
<P>
   `You have to rely on your own judgment'
</P>
<P>
   No one was coordinating the food and medical help, no one
telling the doctors where they were needed next. ``It was word of
mouth, random acts of kindness,'' Henner said. ``When people first
got there, they tried coordinating with the government, but that
didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Only by accident did the residents learn that four tons of food
and medical supplies meant for Chibuto had disappeared. ``There's a
huge problem with government corruption,'' said Loveridge, who
spoke the country's official Portuguese but used interpreters for
the tribal language. ``Nobody knew the hospital was in such dire
straits.''
</P>
<P>
   The residents found out because a woman's propane stove had
exploded, burning her breasts so badly she couldn't feed her
five-month-old baby. They took the mother and child to Chibuto's
hospital, which had 200 patients with 30 kids in its malnourishment
unit. The hospital also had food for only 15 people a day, and no
baby formula at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A doctor there had never seen formula,'' Loveridge said, ``but
so many mothers had quit producing milk from malnourishment. And
World Relief had a storage of formula 30 minutes away.''
</P>
<P>
   The residents might become better doctors for having understood
the rarely appreciated value of food and antibiotics. They probably
will be better doctors for having treated so many new diseases,
especially because all three are military doctors who could wind up
stationed in Third World countries. And they certainly will be
better for having worked mostly with their hands and eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't order blood tests or X-rays on anybody there,''
Pacholka said. ``You have to rely strictly on your own judgment,
and that makes for a very good doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical dollars would have been spent more efficiently by
simply treating everyone for malaria, trachoma and the most common
parasites, Henner said, ``and then teaching good hygiene and giving
them clean water supplies.'' There's a limit to what modern
medicine can do when the same river serves as a latrine, a laundry
and a drinking fountain.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the residents noticed the one oasis from infectious
cholera and dysentery was a refugee camp where an Austrian group
set up temporary water filtration. They've gone, though, and other
groups will follow them as Mozambique fades from the headlines.
Things will get worse, the Wright State group said, because the
floods also destroyed a year's worth of crops.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be watching for that news. Now they have a stake in the
people of Mozambique, as represented by the friendly, appreciative
and resolute folks they met. ``They had next to nothing, but they
kept on going,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   More than their medical skills, the doctors said the feeling of
uplifting each other was their reward for the vacations they gave
up, the health risks they took, the sacrifices their families made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last day, there was a guy in the hospital who just started
laughing,'' Loveridge said. ``He couldn't stop. He pointed down. He
said, `That's my house.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't see anything but water.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kevin Lamb by e-mail at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
