<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER02-COX     05-01 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush: bigger say in retirement funds . . .
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush plans to push for a fundamental overhaul of
Social Security soon, reopening an issue that could be among the
most combustible and bitterly debated of the presidential campaign.
In the next month, his aides say, Bush intends to begin pressing
his case for the establishment of individual investment accounts
within Social Security, a change that would be the most
far-reaching in the program since it was established during the
Depression. Under the plan, workers would be allowed to invest a
portion of their Social Security payroll taxes in stocks and bonds,
taking advantage of the economy's prosperity and ensuring the
national retirement systems's long-term viability.
</P>
<P>
   . . . GORE: BUT IT COULD BE LIKE ROLLING DICE
</P>
<P>
   To Al Gore, creating individual investment accounts is
tantamount to abandoning Social Security's role as the provider of
a guaranteed benefit for the elderly. Gore's aides said they would
portray Bush's approach as too risky because it would leave their
retirement security exposed to the ups and downs of the stock
market. They expect that argument to play strongly if Wall Street
remains as volatile as it has been in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   MORE LIKE SOCIAL INSECURITY?
</P>
<P>
   The White House also dismissed George W. Bush's plan for
overhauling Social Security as too sketchy and set ``in a world
where budgets don't exist.'' White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart said Bush needed to provide more details on his proposal
and ``stop talking about campaign promises in a vacuum, in a world
where budgets don't exist.'' Lockhart said the outline indicates
that Bush's program could push Social Security toward insolvency
rather than preserving it.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN POLICY EXPERIENCE CARD
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of hands-on diplomacy at the White House, Al
Gore believes he outshines George W. Bush in foreign policy
expertise and is taking aim at what he sees as a Bush
vulnerability: Gore charges that Bush's thinking on national
security is ``noticeably blank'' on issues such as terrorism,
narcotics trafficking, the global environment and international
family planning. Addressing the International Press Institute's
congress of foreign journalists in Boston, Gore cast Bush as a
puppet of ``right-wing'' ideologues such as Sen. Jesse Helms
(R-N.C.) and dangerously fixated on the Cold War past.
</P>
<P>
   OK, SO HE'LL STUDY UP
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, seeking to shore up that area of perceived
weakness, is spending a lot of time learning about foreign policy
in depth, said Condoleezza Rice, Bush's main foreign policy adviser
says. Rice, who served on the National Security Council under
Bush's father, the former president, said in a Reuters interview
that the Texas governor was delving into the history behind the top
issues in U.S. foreign policy, including the Balkans, Russia and
the Middle East. ``We've been spending a lot of time since the
primaries talking in depth about some of the big issues,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   SO MUCH FOR THE SYMPATHY VOTE
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll out today showed Hillary Clinton and Rudy
Giuliani in a statistical dead heat, with no change for Giuliani
since last week's announcement that he has prostate cancer. The
latest telephone poll, conducted from Monday of last week through
Sunday by the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute, had Clinton
leading 46 percent over Giuliani's 44 percent. That is
statistically unchanged from an early April Quinnipiac poll that
had Clinton up 46-43 percent. The poll has a 3 percentage point
margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI EXPECTED TO STAY IN RACE . . .
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani's campaign manager expects his candidate to stay
in the New York Senate race because his prostate cancer has not
spread. ``It's not only my hope, but my expectation, that he will
run,'' said Bruce Teitelbaum. ``Hopefully he'll pick a course of
treatment that will give him a cure, a complete cure and then we'll
be able to move forth aggressively, with a winning campaign.'' John
McCain also thinks Giuliani will stay in the race against Hillary
Clinton. McCain's offered to campaign for Giuliani while the mayor
meets with doctors, but said he's sure Giuliani will be campaigning
himself soon. Giuliani played golf with his son Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND SEE ANOTHER COMPETITOR
</P>
<P>
   If Rudy Giuliani does stay in the New York Senate race while
undergoing cancer treatment, he could find the race a little more
crowded. A former congressman, Joseph DioGuardi, told the New York
Times he's going to try for the nominations of three parties:
Conservative, Right-to-Life and Independence. DioGuardi, 59, an
accountant, repeatedly assailed Giuliani as out of step with
conservative-minded Republicans. ``We have two social liberals in
the race,'' DioGuardi said. ``There's a clear need for a
conservative alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   UNLIKE HIMSELF? THAT COULD BE MOST ANYONE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore says he's looking for a vice president who's someone
unlike himself _ and hasn't ruled out tapping a Republican. ``It's
most unlikely, I don't want to mislead you,'' Gore said. ``But I
don't completely rule it out.'' Earlier, Gore had talked about
bipartisanship: ``My natural instincts are to reach out and create
bipartisan coalitions.'' But Gore also insisted on keeping silent
about who will be No. 2 out of deference to the candidates who will
be vetted by former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who is
heading up Gore's search for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   THE ONLY GAME IN TOWN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain said he'll endorse George W. Bush even if they don't
agree on campaign finance reform, as he expects, when they meet
next week. Overhauling federal campaign finance laws was the
signature issue of McCain's unsuccessful presidential campaign.
McCain said he and Bush agree on other areas in need of change,
including Social Security, the military, education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   HEIGHTENED FOCUS ON AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Africa, a continent long ignored by the developed world and long
troubled by famine, civil war and disease, would enjoy a new and
heightened focus by a Gore administration. Al Gore said so himself
in an interview with the Boston Globe. Africa ``has tremendous
potential. And there's too much suffering. And in partnership with
the European Union and others, I think we can help awaken this
renaissance in Africa with democracy and free markets.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS BE HANGED! L.A. COMES FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Leading his city in playing host for the Democratic National
Convention, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan may end up the one
Republican whose praises Democrats sing this year. ``The Democratic
convention is a huge plus for the city of Los Angeles, and that's
my first love,'' Riordan said. ``My first love is not the
Republican Party.'' Riordan already has called the Aug. 14-17
convention his top priority and even participated in a high-profile
Beverly Hills fund-raiser with President Clinton that drew director
Steven Spielberg and other Democratic Party stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT TILL THE NRA GETS HOLD OF THIS
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarian Party says it is ``baffled'' by a proposal to
have the city of Annapolis, Md., buy back toy guns. They don't know
whether to ``support the program or snicker at it,'' the group said
in a prepared statement. Last week, Annapolis Alderman Cynthia A.
Carter proposed that the city start a program to buy back water
pistols, cap guns and other toy weapons to curb ``violent
behavior''among children. The Washington Times reported that
Carter, a Democrat, argued that children ``can't distinguish
between a real gun or a play gun''and said she would eventually
like to make all toy guns illegal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda, Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
