<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-METHODIST-MEETING-NYT     05-01 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODIST-MEETING-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHODISTS PREPARE FOR POTENTIALLY DIVISIVE CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARY McMULLEN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a family reunion that brings together kissing cousins and
in-laws that snap at the sight of each other, the United Methodist
General Conference promises to be potentially bitter. The recurrent
issue of homosexuality is threatening to leave delegates with
bruised feelings, even if it is unlikely they will make major
changes to church policies on gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-day conference gets under way Tuesday at the Convention
Center in Cleveland. It will draw 992 delegates from 66 regional
conferences across the United States and 52 in Europe, Africa and
the Philippines. About 2,500 visitors are also expected.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church is the third-largest religious body
in the United States with 8.4 million members, behind only the
Catholic Church and the Southern Baptist Convention. The General
Conference, its policy-making assembly, meets every four years.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Methodists have been a moderate and tolerant
bunch, emphasizing the generosity of God toward sinners and
welcoming all sorts into their churches. A historical insistence on
personal holiness has tended to fall by the wayside. And like
society generally, the church is struggling to find common ground
in the midst of increasing geographical, racial and philosophical
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates will take up legislation affecting moral questions
and pastoral duties, how local churches will be assessed to support
the denomination's administrative and mission work, and whether its
structure should be changed to reflect its global membership.
</P>
<P>
   They will participate in yet another act of public repentance by
a religious body, for mistreatment of blacks over the centuries.
And, for the first time they will be addressed by the archbishop of
Canterbury, the primate of the church from which they split 215
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The conference's first five days will be devoted to committee
meetings, in which delegates will consider a staggering 2,000
petitions to modify the Book of Discipline, the church's policy
manual. The following week, the committees will submit proposed
legislation to delegates meeting in plenary sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Although they point to a number of issues they consider more
important, delegates regretfully concede that homosexuality
probably will dominate discussions and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sure have spent a lot of time and money on it, and that
sickens me,'' said the Rev. Riley Short, pastor of First United
Methodist Church in Lakeland, Fla., a delegate in 1996 and a
reserve delegate this year.
</P>
<P>
   Controversies surrounding the issue have occurred at every
General Conference since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The church's official position is that the practice of
homosexuality is ``incompatible with Christian teaching'' and
sexually active gays and lesbians are prohibited from being
ordained as deacons or ministers. Church policy also states that
God's grace is available to gays and lesbians, that they are
equally deserving of the church's ministries and that their civil
rights should be protected. United Methodists have condemned
violence against gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   This year, most of the attention is focused on a rule adopted in
1996 that prohibits ministers from performing ``holy union''
ceremonies for gays and lesbians. That rule was tested on four
occasions, and two ministers were charged with violating it. The
Rev. Jimmy Creech and the Rev. Gregory Dell were convicted in
church courts in separate cases. Creech was removed from the
ministry, and Dell was given a one-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But the case that caused the most strain occurred in Sacramento,
Calif., in January 1999, when 68 ministers participated in a
same-sex union service, as a deliberate act of disobedience. In
February, an investigative committee decided not to press charges
against the ministers, a decision supported by Bishop Melvin
Talbert of the California-Nevada Conference, who has been an
outspoken opponent of the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative congregations and advocacy groups within the church
were outraged, and while some threatened to split from the
denomination, others vowed to strengthen the prohibition and find
ways to ensure that disobedient clergy and bishops are held
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Those who advocate the church's current position say it is a
matter of maintaining the authority of scriptural teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scripture is the norm in matters of faith and practice. In our
day and age, you see talk shows where people spill their
experiences, and that becomes so powerful it almost presents a
tyranny. So society has tended to lose its sense of principle. I'm
not willing to give up the teaching of scripture,'' said the Rev.
Dan Johnson, pastor of Trinity United Methodist Church in
Gainesville, Fla., who will be a delegate for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of change say the policy contradicts the openness
that has been the hallmark of Methodist theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of the Discipline creates outcasts, a
second-class citizenry. It says that gays and lesbians are less
than heterosexuals. So the basic theology that God loves all and
welcomes all doesn't fit,'' said Marilyn Alexander, program
coordinator for Reconciling Congregations, an advocacy group for
Methodist gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The General Conference will pause Thursday for a worship service
designated ``An Act of Repentance for Reconciliation.'' The service
will include representatives of the African Methodist Episcopal
Church, the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church and the
Christian Methodist Episcopal Church, three black denominations
that split from the Methodist church in the 18th and 19th centuries
over claims of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Charlene Kammerer of the Western North Carolina
Conference said the service, intended to confess past sins of
racism, will be the most important event of the General Conference.
``It's going to be very profound,'' she said. ``Until we have a
public step of confessing and naming our sins, we can't move
forward. And it has to come from the privileged, white part of the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Other items on the conference agenda include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A revision of the already-complex formula by which money is
assessed from local churches. Regional per-capita income, operating
costs and worship attendance would be factored in. Some pastors
favor the revision, but delegates from regions with high costs of
living, like California, opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   _ A proposal to spend $20 million on a national media campaign,
``Igniting Ministry,'' including television ads as well-produced as
those from the Mormon Church, which are much admired.
</P>
<P>
   _ A May 10 ecumenical worship service at which George Carey, the
Anglican archbishop of Canterbury, will preach. The Methodist
Church began as a movement within the Anglican Church, led by a
priest, John Wesley. A conference in 1784 in Baltimore marked the
separation of Methodists from the Church of England.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
