<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HUMANRIGHTS _ BEIJING _ Almost a year after China
suspended official dialogue with the United States on human rights,
it has invited a private American businessman to Beijing to discuss
the status of political prisoners. Although John Kamm has visited
China dozens of times in the last few years for talks with the
Ministry of Justice, this is the first time China has formally
invited him to do so. Some say Beijing timed the visit next month
to influence Congress' vote on normalizing trade relations. (Chao,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-VIEQUES _ VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ With the dust still
flying from the Elian Gonzalez case, federal officials are
preparing for another controversial confrontation with protestors,
this time at the U.S. Navy bombing range on the island of Vieques,
near Puerto Rico. The long-simmering dispute over the range flared
a year ago when a wayward bomb killed a Puerto Rican security
guard, prompting protestors to occupy part of the range. That
prompted massive protests in San Juan and near unanimity among the
island's fractured political parties that the Navy must leave
Vieques for good. A deal brokered between the Clinton
Administration and P.R. Gov. Pedro Rossello calls for a phased
withdrawal and a referendum, but protestors have rejected the deal
and vow to stay until they are forcibly removed. (Williams, Cox
News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE _The lake below their helicopter was littered with
treetops pointing straight up. But it wasn't a lake. The emergency
medicine residents from Wright State University knew that. The
repeated flooding in Mozambique was the reason they went to this
country in southeastern Africa. They interrupted their lives for
nearly three weeks last month to address the desperate need for
doctors, food and medical supplies in a country that is one of the
world's poorest and least healthy in the best of times. (Dayton
Daily News) WITH PHOTOS MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WEST-WING _ WASHINGTON _ On Saturday, it was life imitating art,
as President Clinton and White House spokesman Joe Lockhart played
themselves in a pair of
</P>
<P>
   videotaped skits. By Monday, it was art imitating life, as
Martin Sheen and other cast members of the television hit ``West
Wing'' showed up in the White House briefing room, opening
Lockhart's daily press gaggle with an impromptu
</P>
<P>
   performance by the actress who plays a Lockhart role on the TV
show. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-HOUSING _ WASHINGTON _ AARP releases a survey showing
the ``attitudes and behaviors of mid-life and older Americans
regarding their current and future housing situations.'' The survey
also focuses on home modifications that will enable older Americans
to remain living independently as they age. (Lipman, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-REPORT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As a five-member commission
today prepares to describe why the 1999 A&AMP;M bonfire collapsed, some
Texans not associated with the university may wonder how such a
large and dangerous activity could take place under student
supervision. It's tradition, Aggies explain. Students and graduates
alike say bonfire teaches leadership and comraderie. And it will
continue, drawing thousands of Aggies each year. (Copelin, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NC-PRIMARY _ Former Charlotte Mayor Richard Vinroot, a
Republican, and Attorney General Mike Easley, a Democrat, are
expected to be among the top vote-getters in their parties'
gubernatorial primaries today. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ After 38 years of flying on top of
the South Carolina State House dome, the Confederate battle flag
may be on the verge of coming down. The full House takes up debate
on a compromise bill sent to it by the Senate. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RAY-LEWIS _ATLANTA _ Attorneys for Ray Lewis and co-defendants
argue over pre-trial motions, including severance and motion to
supress statements LEwis gave to cops before being charged.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-TALKS _ Governors from Georgia, Tennessee, Alabama and North
Carolina are expected be among representatives from several states
at the Appachalian states Moutain Air conference Tuesday (May 2) at
Stone Mountain. The conference will examine air quality problems in
mountain areas, including the beleagured Smoky Mountains National
Park, because of pollution from power plants and smog drifting in
from urban areas like Atlanta. We advance the conference.
(Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KENT-REVISITED _ One of a series by Bob Batz, who covered the
shootings in 1970 for the Dayton Daily News. (Batz, Dayton Daily
News) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
