<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PA-INTRUDERS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE DAY-TRIPPERS WILL NEVER KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7) 
 By JAN BENZEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fox hunters were out, jodhpurs freshly cleaned, boots
polished, riding their plump mounts across the winter-brown fields
silvery with frost. I was on foot, rounding the last leg of the
loop I run whenever I visit this southeastern Pennsylvania
countryside I grew up in.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this horse-dotted landscape, equestrian events like
steeplechases and the hunt have a devoted, eccentric following.
People drive around staking out spots where they might catch a
glimpse of riders and hounds coursing over the hills. They'll spend
the morning sitting in a car and be gratified by a sight that might
last all of a minute and a half.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As I approached the turnoff to my parents' house, I slowed,
leery of a parked pickup truck and a couple of grizzled guys
smoking cigarettes and stamping their feet in the cold. ``Can I
help you?'' I asked, drawing myself up and summoning up as much
property owner's authority as I could, on my parents' behalf.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fox huntin', missy,'' said the one in the heavy, faded
plaid shirt, making his claim to the land. ``You know anything
about fox huntin'?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I didn't stop to explain my own claim, that I'd lived up the
road from the kennel where the hounds sometimes howled all night,
that I'd seen foals born and horses die, that I'd known some of the
riders since they were kids, that I'd ridden a yellow school bus to
this very spot countless times 35 or so years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I realized that he took me for one of the multiplying arrivistes
who now whiz around the country roads on fancy bicycles or in
high-tech running shoes and neon microfiber outfits. He resented
me.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I understood. Although I had moved away, choosing an urban life
over a rural one, I expected that that rural life would be there
when I needed it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But nearby cities have thrived and spread. Farmers whose
children, like me, have made lives elsewhere are selling their one
asset _ their land _ when they can no longer keep it up
themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First the area became a playground. One orchard opened a general
store, offered pick-your-own pumpkins and strawberries and
sheep-petting photo ops. Put a quarter in a machine, get a handful
of nuggets and the sheep will lick your fingers. A freight-bearing
train reinvented itself as scenic railroad, taking its passengers
through leafy green glens in summer and blazing maple and oak in
fall. It ran along part of the narrow, winding Brandywine River,
upon which parties of canoeists float when the water is high
enough. A local triathlon _ of partners who walk, bike and canoe _
that started years ago as a quirky low-key fall event snowballed
into a competition for which people train, seriously scouting the
terrain ahead of the date, puffing up hills and quaking when farm
watchdogs bark. An old, rickety cow barn, freshly painted, is the
site of a summer folk festival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My father used to drive our family to Lancaster, Pa., for the
day, when he needed to shop for a piece of tack or get a saddle
repaired. We'd marvel at the ways of the Amish, and at the same
time be glad we were there with a purpose, not just to gawk. The
fishbowl aspect of their lives even then was in part calculated,
but despite the boon of tourism, I thought of the intrusion they
must feel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The place where I've got the deepest roots is now similarly
becoming a destination. Richly historic, it's drawing ever more
people these days. Tasteful but prominent brown signs have been put
up to point the way to the major attractions like Winterthur,
Longwood Gardens, the Brandywine Battlefield.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what draws the Sunday drivers and other visitors to the
landscape that Andrew Wyeth made so familiar is in danger of
vanishing. Those who used to come for a day in the country now want
a piece of it for themselves. Outsized houses are sprouting like
weeds on any available hilltop, loudly architectural. The
centuries-old houses and gorgeously worn stone and red-painted
wooden barns seem embarrassed by their new, unsightly neighbors.
The open fields are shrinking.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I comfort myself sometimes by thinking of the secrets the
newcomers and tourists won't ever know about this land: Where the
May apples and jack-in-the-pulpits grow in the many microclimates
of the woods. How to spot the fox that doesn't get caught,
streaking up the hillside after the horses and hounds have
thundered past. Summer afternoons spent poking along with friends
by those railroad tracks or hunting for bullfrogs in the creeks.
Life here can also be rugged; more than once tornadoes have ripped
the tin roofs from sheds, sent huge trees crashing through houses.
Deer menace the roads, ravage the gardens. Lyme disease is a
plague. A rainstorm can ruin a field of cut hay.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once my husband and I played tourist for a weekend. We went out
to dinner and to a museum and tried out one of the proliferating
bed-and-breakfasts. A refugee from New York had bought and
painstakingly restored an old stone farmhouse, furnishing it with
locally scavenged antiques. He also ran a furniture store across
the road, and the pieces in the rooms were for sale, too: discreet
price tags dangled on the sides of the beds and dressers. When we
went down into the big, open living area for breakfast, I realized
why I'd been feeling so strange: the house smelled just like one
I'd spent dozens of nights in, on sleepovers at my childhood friend
Jennifer's farm: damp, a bit like dogs, comfortingly warm and old.
People _ we _ were paying for the experience of sleeping for a
night in my own past.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer I went to a little town on Lake Michigan, where 15
of us settled in for a week's celebration of my parents-in-law's 50
years of marriage. I set out one day on a bicycle, and soon found
myself in rolling farmland, where the hills were gentle and fields
of crops ripening in the July sun stretched on both sides of the
road.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the distance I saw an orchard. It looked incongruously
space-age, with each young tree festooned in strips of silver Mylar
glittering in the breeze. Three men were working just off the main
road, and, ready to give my legs a rest, I stopped to ask them
about the silvery stuff. A man about my age told me it was to ward
off the deer. ``We've tried everything,'' he said. ``This seems to
scare them off a little, especially if there's a moon out.'' He
proudly reeled off the kinds of apples they were planting, more
varieties than I had ever heard of.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the other two men, looking gentlemanly with snow-white
hair and brand-new denim overalls, was his father. The land had
been in the family for generations. Deer were a minor threat in the
grand scheme of the farm. ``We deal with all kinds of varmints,''
they told me. ``Groundhogs, bugs _ if it's not one it's another. Or
the weather can damage a whole year's crop.'' The younger man, in a
mood to talk, was hoping he'd be able to pass it on to his own
three sons, but was struggling to be able to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of migrant pickers, he said, were dwindling, as the
workers now more often chose jobs in fast-food restaurants than in
the fields. Selling produce wholesale yielded little income. So he
was planting pick-your-own crops, and his wife was selling pies at
a stand down the road in an effort to hold out against what he
called ``going into the real estate business,'' cashing in on the
land and abandoning his family's tradition. ``My sons might sell
it, but I want to give them that choice,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I didn't want to keep them from their work, so I wheeled the
bike back onto the hardtop and got ready to pedal away. ``You take
care on that bike,'' said the older man, with a wave and a smile.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I would have stopped for a pie _ I love pie _ but I didn't think
I could manage it on my bike. Months later, I still worry about
that farm, and how, besides the vagaries of weather and varmints,
its owners will now have to factor in the whims of day-trippers
like me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1800EDT &QL; 
