<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2609 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GLOBAL-TERRORISM-HNS &LR;      05-01 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-TERRORISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STATE DEPARTMENT SAYS TERRORIST ATTACKS RISE BUT CLAIM FEWER
VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The number of terrorist attacks increased by more
than 40 percent from 1998 to 1999 but deaths from acts of terror
fell significantly, the State Department reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in releasing the
report that there were ``terrorists caught, plots thwarted and
lives saved'' in 1999. Still, she said, ``we cannot relax our
global full-court press on against terror.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, 233 people were killed in terrorist
attacks last year, down from 741 in 1998, while the number of
attacks worldwide rose from 274 in 1998 to 392 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Five U.S. citizens were killed and six wounded in international
attacks last year. Three were kidnapped Feb. 25 and killed by a
terrorist group in Colombia while working with an Indian tribe in
the northeast of the country. A Rwandan group kidnapped and
murdered two Americans on March 1 in the central African nation of
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say a potentially large loss of American lives was
averted in December with the arrest of an Algerian man, Ahmed
Ressam, while he was crossing the border from Canada into Port
Angeles, Wash. The State Department report said Ressam's vehicle
contained explosives and detonating devices that were intended for
use in bombing millennium celebrations in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Albright reported that terrorists are receiving more funding
from private sources, and less from foreign governments, than they
did a few years ago. However, the State Department has maintained
since 1993 that the governments of Cuba, Iran, Iraq, Libya, North
Korea, Sudan and Syria provide a ``safe haven'' for terrorists or
``plan and sponsor'' terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling Taliban militia of Afghanistan is believed
to harbor terrorists as well, the nation was not placed on the list
of state sponsors because the United States does not recognize the
Taliban as a ruling government.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sheehan, the State Department's coordinator for
counterterrorism, said ``we had a good year in 1999.'' For
instance, he said that ``in Egypt for the first time in many years
there were no terrorism-related deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   But the threat of terrorism ``remains very real,'' he said.
``There are no guarantees in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the State Department identified Pakistan as
part of the growing South Asian terrorism center. The report cites
Pakistan as ``one of only three countries that maintains formal
diplomatic relations with ... Afghanistan's Taliban.'' It also
alleges the Pakistani government aided rebels in Kashmir, a
disputed region that both India and Pakistan claim.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheehan said Pakistan is considered a friendly state and was
therefore not placed on the list of governments that sponsor
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The report says South Asia became the ``locus of terrorism
directed against the United States'' in 1999 in a shift from past
conglomerations of foes in the Middle East. Afghanistan and
Pakistan were the only two South Asian nations identified by the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Albright noted that protection of U.S. and international
interests does not come without money.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is ``gravely concerned'' by congressional proposals
to cut more than $2 billion from President Clinton's international
affairs funding request. She urged Congress to approve the
president's full request of $22.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
