<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-SEARCH-HNS &LR;      05-01 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAN POLICE STOP PEOPLE FROM ENTERING THEIR HOMES? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide
whether police can stop people from going into their own homes
alone while the officers attempt to get a warrant to search the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it would hear an Illinois case in which police in
the town of Sullivan prevented a man suspected of possessing drugs
from entering his trailer alone. The police said they were
concerned that he would destroy any evidence inside.
</P>
<P>
   Both the state trial court and the 7th District Circuit Court of
Appeals in Chicago ruled that the police had violated the
constitutional ban on unreasonable searches and seizures by
temporarily keeping him outside at the request of an officer while
the police sought a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The case began in 1997, when John Love, assistant police chief
in Sullivan, accompanied Tera McArthur to a trailer owned by her
husband, Charles. Tera wanted to move out but was afraid her
husband might become violent. She asked the police to be present to
keep her husband from trying to stop her from moving out.
</P>
<P>
   Love waited by the door until Tera had removed all of her
belongings. When she was finished and the two were outside, she
told Love that her husband had a bag of marijuana under the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Love knocked on the door and McArthur came outside. When asked
about the marijuana, McArthur denied having any drugs inside.
Suspicious, Love sent another officer to seek a search warrant for
the trailer and refused to allow the defendant back into his home
alone.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour wait, Love allowed McArthur to go inside
twice to get cigarettes and to make a telephone call _ but always
in the company of an officer.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the warrant, the police searched the trailer and
found marijuana and drug paraphernalia. McArthur was charged with
possessing less than 2.5 grams of marijuana and possessing drug
paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   But at his trial, McArthur asked the judge to suppress the
evidence. Although admitting that he would have destroyed the
marijuana if allowed inside alone, McArthur said keeping him
outside his home was a violation of the Fourth Amendment's
protection against unreasonable search and seizure.
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed and dismissed the case. Two years later, the
appeals court affirmed that decision, saying what the police did
amounted to an ``eviction of the defendant from his residence.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court noted that other courts have let police keep
someone outside when the person was under arrest, subject to arrest
on arrival, or when the person consented to stay outside.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief to the high court, Deanne F. Jones, a Chicago
attorney representing McArthur, said that the police had no ``hard
evidence'' that the client had done anything wrong. ``Police should
not be able to stop you from re-entering your own home without any
evidence that you've committed a crime,'' Jones wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors argued in their filing to the court that the
police needed to prevent McArthur from destroying evidence, and
that the appeals court ruling would make it nearly impossible for
police to ``secure evidence'' when the defendant was still at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was probable cause to believe he had this contraband in
his house,'' said Colleen Griffin, assistant Illinois attorney
general. Love had ``no choice'' but to seize the house while he
waited to secure the warrant, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``A seizure is not necessarily unconstitutional for the period
of time necessary to secure the warrant,'' Griffin wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will hear arguments in the case this fall, and a
decision is expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
