<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ADD02-COX     05-01 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Study into causes of ADD promising, expert says
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. John Ratey, a national expert in attention deficit
disorders, will be the keynote speaker at the National Conference
on Attention Deficit Disorders being held this weekend in Atlanta.
The conference, which is open to the public, will feature
discussions that can help patients, parents and physicians
recognize, treat and overcome the disorders. Ratey, a Harvard
Medical School associate professor of psychiatry, talked to medical
writer Diane Lore about new research into the disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What exactly are scientists seeing in the brain chemistry of
ADD patients vs. that of the general population?
</P>
<P>
   A:We're seeing that they actually have genes that are different
from the norm, and many of those (genes) are associated with a
person's dopamine system. (Dopamine, a chemical messenger, is
similar to adrenaline. It affects brain processes that control
movement, emotional response, and ability to experience pleasure
and pain.) We are finding that dopamine transporters _ these
enzymes that put dopamine into the nerve cells _ are too active.
It's like you're trying to bail out water that's flooding a boat
and the transporter keeps pumping it back in. That process messes
up a lot of the brain's operations, especially the parts that help
people remember, learn or concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How will this information about a biological basis for ADD
change treatments?
</P>
<P>
   A:Well, as we get more sophisticated, I believe we'll be able to
develop better drugs that not only correct the dopamine levels, but
correct the genes themselves. I believe that's where we're headed.
I also believe we will be able to create better environments for
people suffering with ADD _ know, for example, exactly what
exercises and what kind of structures these patients work best in.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So, even if scientists prove that ADD is a biologically based
disorder, there will be a need to develop strategies beyond handing
out a pill?
</P>
<P>
   A:Definitely. Just like you need to change the environment of a
blind person to make it more accessible, you need to create an
environment to help those with ADD. With children, that probably
means stricter, more structured home lives. And because dopamine is
affected by aerobic exercise, it means getting more physical
activity in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q:It almost sounds as if the two philosophical camps of ADD
could find common ground as science learns more about the
disorders. That those who complain that the disorder is linked to
parenting could find their strategies being used in conjunction
with new medications.
</P>
<P>
   A:Absolutely. We're not that far apart. We cannot separate
nature from nurture. Even though we're crazy about the genes and
the dopamine and how the brain works, we've always got to be
cognizant of how that relates to the patient's environment.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So, where will attitudes and research be in a decade?
</P>
<P>
   A:I think we will be much better at making correct diagnoses.
And we will have a much better sense of how to create exercises,
computer games and structures that these kids need. As far as
attitudes, I think we're in a period right now where we have a lot
of people making blanket statements about there being too much
Ritalin. We have a lot of people who say, `You're going to change
your kid's brain.' But people still don't realize that untreated
ADD in a youngster can be much worse than anything a drug could do.
A drug might be a brain changer, but trust me, so is feeling like
you're stupid. Feeling like you're no good. That ruins the brain
too, along with the life and the soul. And people just don't see
that equation.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is being held Friday through Sunday at the
Atlanta Airport Hilton and Towers; walk-up registration is $200.
For more information, call the National Attention Deficit Disorder
Association at 1-847-432-2332; to learn more about ADD, visit the
association's Web site at www.add.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
