<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revitalized George eyes Elian et al.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When John F. Kennedy Jr. died in a plane crash last year, the
outlook for the future of his magazine, George ($3.95), was gloomy.
Magazine and ad sales had stagnated, and its financial backers were
losing confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's death may have saved the publication. Newsstand sales
increased by nearly 150 percent and copies of the October 1999
tribute issue became a collector's item that sells on online
auction sites for $50 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to new editor Frank Lalli to continue the momentum
and, from the looks of his first issue, he just might succeed. The
May issue has two covers. The newsstand cover shows Elian Gonzalez
and his mother and refers to a fascinating article by Ann Louise
Bardach about the other survivors on Elian's ocean journey.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers, meanwhile, will get a cover on ``Will the Biggest
Liar Win?,'' which examines the extent to which Al Gore and George
W. Bush have distorted the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Other articles include a good mix of celebrity political topics,
from an excerpt from Betty Friedan's autobiography revealing that
her husband beat her, to Heather Locklear's advice to Rudolph
Giuliani on how he can defeat Hillary Rodham Clinton in New York's
U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Politics and prose: Speaking of Giuliani, The New Yorker ($3)
looks at the effects of the New York mayor's recently diagnosed
prostate cancer on his Senate campaign. As David Letterman learned,
there's nothing like a life-threatening illness to win sympathy
from even your harshest critics. Also in this issue, editor David
Remnick talks with Philip Roth about his new novel, ``The Human
Stain,'' and his turbulent life.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another coat of paint: The third installment of John Grisham's
serialized novel, ``The Painted House,'' is worth the price of the
May/June issue of The Oxford American ($5.95), but several of the
other articles won't disappoint, either. Diane Roberts offers a
brief history of Florida's electric chair, ``Old Sparky,'' John T.
Edge writes about the beauty of biscuits, and John Jeremiah
Sullivan examines the life and teachings of Trappist monk Thomas
Merton.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kinder and gentler: Forget everything you saw in Kirk Douglas
epic film, ``The Vikings.'' According to Time ($3.50), these Norse
warriors did more than rape, loot and pillage. They were also
craftsmen, explorers and proponents of democracy. A new exhibit at
the National Museum of Natural History in Washington offers
examples of the Vikings' skills as artists. By the way, Time notes,
only those who went on raiding parties were called Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The millennial generation: Vikings are not the only group to
get a bad rap; so have teenagers. In a new poll of the group
between 12 and 20, Newsweek ($3.50) finds that 28 percent of teens
feel angry, 78 percent say their parents don't spend enough time
with them, and 59 percent are worried about violence. The second of
a four-part ``New America'' series also includes an essay by
Hillary Rodham Clinton on the upcoming White House summit on teens.
Despite all their protest and swagger about being independent,
writes the first lady, ``teenagers need _ and want _ the everyday
love, involvement and discipline of their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: The second issue of Real Simple ($2.95) offers
more suggestions for reducing the stress in your life, such as tips
on how to create pantry dinners and advice on how to clean your
kitchen quickly. Donating unneeded items to charity is one way of
simplifying your life; having a house fire is another. Laurie J.
Flynn writes poignantly about how the destruction of her home
caused her to rethink her priorities.... GQ ($3) devotes most of
the May issue (with the exception of a revealing layout of actress
Estella Warren) to the money culture. Alan Deutschman offers new
guidelines to help you determine if your salary is what it should
be (4,000 times your age is the new formula), and Adam Sachs
profiles Pierre Omidyar, the 32-year-old founder of eBay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Farewells: The final issue of Life ($3.99) hits the stands
this month with a look back over the magazine's 64-year history and
a touching cover story about the medical struggle to keep premature
babies alive. ... Mirabella ($2.95) will disappear after the June
issue. President Jack Kliger blamed a lack of advertising support
for the demise of the women's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
