<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PUERTORICO-VIEQUES-05     05-01 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-VIEQUES-0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VIEQUES PROTESTERS WATCH, WAIT FOR SHOWDOWN WITH FEDS OVER
ISLAND'S FUTURE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ The protestors huddle in their rough-hewn
cabins and under makeshift tarps, hiding from the scorching
Caribbean sun, watching and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   A few look up as a U.S. military helicopter beats through the
sky overhead. Others scan the vast azure blue horizon, peering out
to sea, where early Monday a sleek gray U.S. Navy ship steamed
past.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of rhetoric and protests, a showdown appears to be
finally drawing near over a bomb-scarred, bullet-strewn strip of
land on this tiny island.
</P>
<P>
   For 60 years, the U.S. Navy has used the eastern tip of Vieques
as a bombing range, but now many of the island's 9,000 residents _
and thousands more of their fellow Puerto Ricans _ want the war
games to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bastante,'' said Noel Garcia, 57, a distribution manager for a
San Juan newspaper who took his month-long vacation to join the
protestors at their remote camp. ``Enough. The people here on
Vieques have not been able to live normal lives. The bombing has
destroyed the environment and held back the island's development.
All of Puerto Rico believes this must end.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Washington, D.C. swirled with reports that three U.S.
Navy ships and 1,200 Marines were headed for Vieques Island in
order to set up a perimeter following a law-enforcement action in
which U.S. Marshals and FBI agents would move in to arrest and
remove the protestors.
</P>
<P>
   Unnamed administration sources have said the action might take
place this week. But coming on the heels of the widely-publicized
raid to take Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami
relatives, some here question whether the U.S. government can
afford to mount another heavy-handed action so soon.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted by the rumors, Vieques is now swarming with media, with
television crews from Puerto Rico and the mainland filling the
island's few hotels and hiring fishermen for the 8-mile boat-ride
to the remote bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   If the raid takes place, some of the 50-70 protestors on the
range vow to scatter into the hills away from their camps on the
beach, hiding in the brush. Others say they will not resist arrest
_ but promise that more protestors will quickly come to take their
places.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Associated Press, a source close to the Coast
Guard said they were preparing to blockade waters around the
two-thirds of Vieques that is federal land _ the eastern bombing
range and a munitions store in the west _ to prevent threatened
demonstrator reinforcements from reaching the protest area by sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here in peace,'' said Bishop Juan Vera, head of the
Puerto Rican Evangelical Council of Churches, which has sent
ministers on a rotating basis to the protest camps. ``Our moral
witness is the most important thing. If we are taken away, others
will come here to take our place. We are following the tradition of
Ghandi and Martin Luther King Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   An army barge also arrived carrying three vans of Puerto Rico's
anti-riot police, who are to provide crowd control during the
operation. On board a dozen men in green uniforms were visible. In
a channel farther out from Vieques a destroyer anchored Monday,
carrying two U.S. Coast guard helicopters, with blue-overalled
crews checking their aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, the three warships steamed off to Roosevelt Roads
Naval Station on the main island of Puerto Rico, about 1 1/2 hours
away given the glass-calm sea, and the barge deposited the police
vans on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The Vieques bombing range dates back to the years of World War
II, when the sleepy U.S. possession of Puerto Rico suddenly took on
a new strategic military importance.
</P>
<P>
   Although the residents of Puerto Rico and Vieques were U.S.
citizens, there was little protest when the Navy condemned 22,000
of Vieques' 33,000 acres, moving small farmers and sugar cane
workers off their land at either east or west end, and to the
island's center. Many residents left, seeking work on Puerto Rico
or going to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But resentment simmered.
</P>
<P>
   In April of last year, the controversy boiled over after a
wayward bomb dropped by a Navy jet killed David Sanes, a Vieques
resident who worked on the range as a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, small groups of protestors set up camps on the
range, halting all military exercises. Soon they were issuing press
releases and giving media interviews, claiming that the decades of
bombing and strafing _ at times with uranium-tipped bullets _ had
rendered the range an environmental nightmare. They also cited
health studies showing an unusually high rate of cancer on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   As the protest camps grew to a few dozen in strength, the issue
swept like a wildfire across the neighboring island of Puerto Rico,
with thousands joining protests in the streets of San Juan. Outrage
over Vieques managed to unite the island's normally fractious
political parties, with dozens of elected officials joining in the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy, however, stood firm, saying that the Vieques range is
essential to the combat-readiness of U.S. forces. For decades, most
Navy battle groups have conducted live-fire war games on the range
immediately prior to overseas duty, with pilots, Marines and ship
crews all participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vieques is unique because it's the only place in the United
States that we can bring all of the elements of an integrated
battle group together for training,'' Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Bob
Garcia said last year.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiation, President Clinton and Gov. Pedro
Rossello of Puerto Rico signed an agreement Jan. 31 aimed at ending
the festering conflict. The deal calls for the Navy to leave
Vieques by May 2003 if island residents vote to expel the military.
The vote would come sometime next year, and the Navy was supposed
to resume bombing practice _ although only with dummy munitions _
in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   But the protestors were outraged by the deal, and have vowed to
stay in place until the U.S. military agrees to an immediate and
permanent pullout.
</P>
<P>
   They are counting on the backing of more than 2 million Puerto
Ricans now living in the United States. Thousands will vote in the
upcoming November elections in New York, where first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton is a candidate for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they are removed, the protestors believe the issue will
be kept alive by more protestors sneaking out to the range by boat
or slipping through the fence that surrounds the Navy land and
making their way in by foot.
</P>
<P>
   And they believe they will ultimately win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already obtained a great victory,'' said Ruben
Berrios, head of the Puerto Rico Independence Party, who hasn't
left his camp at the bombing range in the past year. ``There have
been no bombs for one year, and we have demonstrated the moral
force of the Puerto Rican people. Whatever happens, we think it is
only a matter of how and when the Navy leaves for good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' email address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
