<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LAMB-ABORTION-COX     05-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMB-ABORTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laws collide with medicine in partial-delivery abortion
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An awful lot of energy has been devoted to a procedure that
accounts for less than 0.06 percent of all abortions. Imagine if
that energy had been directed toward an effective adoption system
that would reduce both abortions and heartbroken infertile couples,
two goals that stir hardly any controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But the abortion issue has grown far beyond the question of
whether an embryo's right to be born trumps a pregnant woman's
right to control her body. Just last week, as the Supreme Court
heard arguments about this rare procedure, abortion cast its broad
shadow over several aspects of what role the government should have
in practicing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate committee debated whether to pay for promising research
that could cure such horrifying disorders as Alzheimer's disease
and paralysis by using stem cells from discarded human embryos.
Another Senate committee discussed whether doctors' ability to
treat severe pain should be limited for the purpose of outlawing
assisted suicide. A federal agency raised the question of whether a
patient's right to privacy should be sacrificed for society's right
to identify possible alcoholics by using imprecise blood tests.
</P>
<P>
   And the Supreme Court's case boils down to whether a safer
abortion procedure should be outlawed in favor of procedures that
kill the fetus less gruesomely.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the partial-delivery procedure call it
``partial-birth abortion,'' a term that's meant to inspire outrage
about this technique for killing fetuses and not to undercut their
thesis that life begins at conception and therefore is never
partial.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one states have passed laws against this procedure,
medically called ``intact dilation and extraction,'' or D&AMP;X. Most
of those laws have been struck down by courts as being so vague as
to also cover the most common abortion procedure, called ``dilation
and evacuation'' or D&AMP;E. Ohio's Legislature recently passed a
second try at this law. The Supreme Court will settle the issue
next month by ruling on Nebraska's typical law.
</P>
<P>
   The laws have been poorly written because neither side of the
abortion issue really cares much about the one of every 1,800
abortions done by D&AMP;X.
</P>
<P>
   There are two morally unambiguous positions that can be taken on
abortion. Abortion-rights advocates maintain all abortions are
legal until the fetus is able to survive outside of the womb. The
anti-abortion side maintains all abortions constitute the illegal
murder of a life that began at either conception or implantation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the laws have been written by the groups that don't see
much distinction between D&AMP;X and the other 99.4 percent of
abortions. Murder is murder, after all, the argument goes, so it's
no wonder they're writing laws that prohibit more than just D&AMP;X.
From their perspective, we might as well be asking them to write
laws declaring murder to be legal when the weapon is a knife or a
rope.
</P>
<P>
   It's the middle majority, opposed to outlawing all abortions,
that wants D&AMP;X to be illegal. This opposition can only be based on
a belief that it is more repulsive to cut and empty a fetal skull
while most of its body is in the birth canal than to cut and empty
the skull while the body is elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The middle majority needs to get past this distinction. All
abortions are gory, but as long as they're legal up to the fetus'
viability _ and no court has shown an inclination to change that _
then only the doctors should be choosing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Undisputed Supreme Court testimony called D&AMP;X one of the safest
abortion procedures for the woman, primarily used when she has
heart disease, diabetes or other conditions that make other
techniques needlessly dangerous. The reason President Clinton
intends to veto a bill against ``partial birth abortions'' for a
third time is that Congress keeps making exceptions only if other
techniques would endanger the woman's life, not if they would
endanger her health.
</P>
<P>
   So it's possible to write a law forbidding D&AMP;X except in
narrowly defined cases.
</P>
<P>
   It's more desirable to create the infrastructure _ bureaucratic,
social, medical and psychological _ that would make it as practical
as possible to carry unwanted children to full-term for adoption.
That would eliminate a lot more than 0.06 percent of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that abortions in general and the
partial-delivery procedure in particular have become no less than a
cultural battleground between the liberal value of permissiveness
and the conservative value of shame. Twenty-five years ago, this
country abandoned a similar surrogate battle between free
enterprise and communism. It was the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb is the Dayton (OH) Daily News health writer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
