</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ When it comes to e-shopping strategies, there are
typically two ways a company can turn. Either build a Web site and
manage it in-house, or outsource all or part of the work. (DeGross,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   VINTAGE-BOOKS-ONLINE _ ATLANTA _ There's a mid-17th century
Bible for sale and copies of every Life magazine issue ever
printed. Recently, an urgent request came in for ``any and all
pre-1960 poultry books.'' Something interesting's always happening
at Atlanta Vintage Books, though the most intriguing development of
late doesn't involve what's on the shelves: Some of the store's
best, most loyal customers have never set foot in the place.
They're cybershoppers. And contrary to conventional wisdom, they
may be helping rather than hurting independent stores savvy enough
to see venturing onto the Web as one more way of keeping their
doors open. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ME-STORE _ ``It would be the perfect store. The ``Me Store.''
Always open, always stocked with exactly what I wanted, never about
another human being's needs except mine. All mine!'' For those who
prefer to shop from home, this reporter has compiled a list of web
sites she hoped to meet her every need. Some deliver, some don't.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GOING-CYBER _ ATLANTA _ ``Going Cyber!'' The handwriting is a
bit crooked and hard to make out from a distance, and yet the sign
on the front door of ``The Family Jewels'' in downtown Decatur, Ga.
speaks volumes. Next week, the 13-year-old antiques and
collectibles store will become an online-only operation, joining a
host of other businesses for whom the Internet is the greatest
thing to come along since customers with unlimited lines of credit.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ESHOP-SAFETY _Before you start your e-shopping adventures, here
are some key points to keep in mind. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
