<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, May 2, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COLD-CAN _ Envision a day at the beach, sun beating down
mercilessly and throat parching in the balm. You reach for a soft
drink can boiling in the sand. But with a simple click, the drink
converts from feverish to frigid. No ice, no problem. It may sound
like a sun-drenched mirage, but a Florida-based company believes
it's close to making it happen. Bradenton, Ga.-based Tempra
Technology has created a self-refrigerating beverage can that can
drop a soda, beer or other drink by 30 degrees within a few
minutes. The temperature keeps dropping after that. Prototypes have
fallen to 35 degrees and remained at that temperature for more than
an hour. A can that pops out of a vending machine is typically 38
to 45 degrees. (Fernandez, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELLS _ NORCROSS, Ga. _ Business is black and white at
Norcross-based Mitchell's Formalwear. ``All transactions are
perishable,'' said Joe Doyle, chief executive officer of the
nation's largest tuxedo rental company. ``It's either right or
wrong.'' Done right, the payoff could be big profits, considering
the burgeoning population and the prospect for more proms, weddings
and other special occasions. (Degross, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MCI _ MCI WorldCom Inc. said Monday it will provide
</P>
<P>
   Group Information Services Inc., an Atlanta-based start-up
venture, with network and service support under a $316 million
partnership agreement. Group Information Services plans to offer
fully integrated nationwide voice mail and e-mail services
supported by MCI WorldCom networks. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS _ The manager of the Enterprise Growth fund talks
about the market and what stocks he'd been buying or selling. First
of an occasional series. With list of 10 largest holdings.
(McNaughton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LODGIAN _ In the middle of a battle over control of the company,
Lodgian hotels report twice-delayed earnings. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the
current week. This layout is available Tuesday after 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0429: NETSCAPE'S NEW BROWSER _ Netscape 6 is not
fun. It's big, busy, flashy and can be just plain annoying.
Netscape took two years to dream up this mishmash of features,
pull-down menus, wacky toolbars and icons. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 4-column color photo of a
screenshot of Netscape's new browser.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GADGETS _ Rand McNally, the map people, have developed a
mapping and global positioning system (GPS) device designed to work
with the Palm III and Palm V organizers. (Cummings, Dayton Daily
News) Art includes a 1-column color photo of product in use.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSCENE _ When it comes to reading information in other
languages, most of us are at a loss. There is help for you on the
Web. If you're an experienced user, you probably know that there
are free online translation services available. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GAME CORNER _ The new ``Star Trek'' game adventure is like
an episodic TV-caliber adventure _ not a virtual extravaganza on
par with the blockbuster movies.(Staff, Austin American-Statesman)
Art includes a 1-column color photo of video game box.
</P>
