<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release TUESDAY AMs, May 2, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Camp Montieth, Kosovo) -- At major US Army base
where troops have set up the infrastructure for a small city, the
top US commander says entrenched ethnic strife means NATO will have
to keep troops in place ``for a generation.'' By John Donnelly.
1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTIONS (Mexico City) _ The expulsion last month of a
US-based human rights director is raising concerns that Mexico may
hinder foreign monitoring of its July 2 presidential elections, in
which the PRI fears it could lose the presidency for the first time
in 71 years. By Richard Chacon. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   POLICY-RIGHTS (Boston) _ Foreign policy experts and leaders
debate whether making human rights a component of foreign policy is
an altruistic impulse or just another way to play realpolitik for
national foreign policy goals. By Charles Radin. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TECHNOLOGY (Boston) _ NBC news anchor Tom Brokaw says
changing technological and economic models for journalism are
hurtling the news business to a largely unknown ``destination.'' By
Mark Jurkowitz. 650 words. (i and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEX-OFFENDERS (Undated) _ Personnel at New Hampshire's sex
offender registry say convicted sex offenders are moving east
across the state border to Maine, where the vast majority of them
are not required to register. By Ellen Barry. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEB-HEALTHCARE (Undated) _ Harvard Medical School is said to be
the major partner of Intelihealth, Aetna US Healthcare's site for
health information on the Internet. Financial details were not
disclosed, but Aetna US Healthcare said the school will be the
flagship medical content partner for the Web site, which was
launched in 1996 and attracts about 1 million visitors a month. By
Stephanie Stoughton. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-BIAS (Boston) _ The Massachusetts Commission Against
Discrimination awards $200,000 in emotional damages plus interest
to a former Northwest Airlines employee after finding that the
airline refused to make accommodations for her disability because
she cooperated with a sexual harassment investigation. By Diane E.
Lewis. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIER (Foxborough, Mass.) _ The Patriots' new head
coach, Bill Belichick, saying it was an ``unpleasant thing for me
to do,'' fires controversial player acquisition manager Bobby
Grier. By Ron Borges. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
