<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-NATO-BOS &LR;      05-01 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL SEES LENGTHY ROLE FOR NATO TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP MONTIETH, Kosovo _ After a thank-the-troops tour by Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen to two American bases that have already
become self-sufficient towns, the top US commander in Kosovo
predicted Monday that NATO peacekeepers will have to remain in the
Balkans for ``at least a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment by Brigadier General Ricardo Sanchez, commander
of Task Force Falcon, in an interview with the Globe, was made as
many members of Congress have expressed increasing displeasure with
the open-ended US deployments to Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, senators questioned Cohen about the US troop
commitment. Senator Ernest F. Hollings, a South Carolina Democrat,
told Cohen and General H. Hugh Shelton, the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, to stop ``whistling Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to stop kidding each other,'' Hollings added, as he
urged the leaders of the nation's military to give ``a realistic
appraisal of where we are headed'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The defense secretary acknowledged then that US troops in the
Balkans will not be pulled out during his final months in office,
and possibly not during the time of his successor.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez's comments went much further, noting that the two US
camps in southwestern Kosovo, Montieth and the sprawling Bonsteel,
were being built to support and house US troops for at least three
to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easily it could be that long,'' he said as soldiers nearby
swarmed around Cohen and the secretary's wife, former Boston
television personality Janet Langhart Cohen. ``It order to
guarantee the safety of all the people here, we're talking at least
a generation for NATO's commitment to secure the Balkans region.
I'm not saying troop size would be the same. But it's a long-term
commitment for NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   About 39,000 NATO troops, including about 5,600 Americans, are
currently trying to keep the peace in Kosovo, which continues to be
wracked by ethnic violence. Following NATO's air campaign last
spring that eventually pushed Yugoslav troops out of the Serb
province of Kosovo, ethnic Albanians have committed the majority of
crimes, many directed at the remaining Serb villagers.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Bosnia, about 6,000 US troops remain as peacekeepers,
down from the initial 1995 deployment of 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who has traveled to Kosovo three times in the last 10
months and has made it a priority to visit US troops around the
world, said the Kosovo situation remains tense and volatile. But he
said it represented a ``rather remarkable'' improvement from a year
ago, when the province had 50 murders a week. Now the number
averages about five weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too many . . . but in not a great amount of time,
we're making a good deal of progress,'' he told reporters during
his flight to Europe. ``But we need to have more police. . . . We
need to have more judges, more courtrooms, more civilian-run
institutions organized by international institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Americans have dug in for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   They seem determined not to repeat the mistakes of Bosnia, where
troops slept in tents for month after month. In Kovoso, the
military chief ordered wood-framed dormitories with floors.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is America's footprint here more visible than at Camp
Bonsteel. What was once a field of mud in springtime, and a sea of
growing wheat in summer, today looks like a city in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsteel is home to about 4,000 troops. They eat in two huge
dining halls or in a Burger King, sleep on mattresses rather than
cots, watch recently released movies such as ``The Green Mile'' and
``Dogma'' from plush maroon theater seats, pray in two chapels,
work up sweat in two gyms, mail letters at a post exchange and
flush toilets linked to one of the two most advanced sewage
treatment systems in all of Kosovo. The other military camp is at
Montieth, about 15 miles north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Kosovo,'' said Major George Linka, after reading a
list of what has been built in the last year at the 755-acre
Bonsteel camp.
</P>
<P>
   But from this safe and relatively comfortable haven, US troops
are dispatched, some of them daily, to areas of Kosovo where
violence is a constant presence.
</P>
<P>
   One is Military Police Specialist Jeremy Bailey, 19, of
Braintree, who has been here since November, enough time that death
has lost its shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things get pretty wild,'' Bailey said outside the theater
where troops were lining up to have their pictures taken with Cohen
and his wife. ``You just expect to see certain things, like dead
bodies, or people stepping on land mines. That kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the quality of life has been outstanding. I get
to take a shower. I eat chow every day. Hot chow. This morning, I
had French toast with maple syrup and an omelette.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he doesn't expect the job to become much easier for those
soldiers who will take his place here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generation upon generation upon generation of taught hatred is
going to take a long time to go away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment seemed uniform among the soldiers, underscoring
Sanchez's forecast of a long NATO commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Bosnia. In Bosnia, people could go to whichever
side they live on. Here, you have no side to go live on,'' said
Lieutenant Colonel Thomas L. Rousseau, executive officer for the
3rd Brigade and a Burlington, Vt., native.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much harder in Kosovo,'' where ethnic Albanians and Serbs
live among each other, he said. ``Half of the town, the Albanians,
waves to me when I go by. The other side flips me off. We see it,
we live it, every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain John Gossart, 29, of Washington, a Boston College
graduate, was more optimistic. He said he believes the situation is
``getting better every day. I got here about five months ago, and
it's more safe and secure, and it has more freedom of movement.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We're not there yet. The problem is 800 years
old, and it's going to take time to solve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
