u i BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-EUROP     05-01 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMITED U.S. MISSILE DEFENSE PLAN RAISES CONCERN AMONG NATO
ALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The foreign policy chief for the European Union,
Javier Solana, said Monday that European officials are concerned
about the potentially damaging effect the Clinton administration's
plan for national missile defense could have on Europe's security
ties with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If Europe were not protected by the missile shield, such a
system could lead to ``decoupling'' _ a splintering in military
ties _ between the United States and its NATO allies, Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were not to be defended by the United States, that may
risk the beginning of `decoupling,''' Solana told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, the former secretary-general of NATO, is now leading the
European Union's efforts to build a defense force that would
complement NATO. He said that if the American missile system moves
ahead it must not ``strain trans-Atlantic links'' or provoke a ``a
major crisis with Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana is here meeting with senior Clinton administration
officials to discuss the European Union's defense plan and to learn
about the Clinton administration's talks with Russia over the
planned missile defense. President Clinton is scheduled to attend a
summit meeting of the European Union in Lisbon before meeting with
the Russian president-elect, Vladimir Putin, in Moscow in early
June. In both arenas, missile defense will be a major topic.
</P>
<P>
   Western European leaders _ some more than others _ have publicly
questioned the necessity of the administration's plan to construct
a limited national defense designed to protect against the missiles
of ``rogue'' states like North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans question the depth of the threat from these
countries, some of which _ like Iraq, Iran and Libya _ are much
closer to Europe than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Karsten Vogt, a senior foreign ministry official,
said recently that the limited missile defense planned by the
Clinton administration _ which would protect the United States but
not Europe _ would lead to a weakening of the military ties between
the United States and its European allies. Vogt also said that
Germany did not agree with the American assessment of the
seriousness of a threat from the ``rogue'' states.
</P>
<P>
   In London last month, Prime Minister Tony Blair, who was visited
by Putin, publicly said that his government would try to help
resolve the differences between Russia and the United States on
missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Putin has opposed the Clinton administration's efforts
to amend the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty of 1972, considered the
basis of Cold War arms control, to allow for a missile defense
system. The ABM treaty prohibits defense systems like the one now
being tested, and in order to forge ahead with its plan, the
administration must persuade Putin to amend the treaty or the
United States must pull out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Blair played a constructive role
with Putin by both asking him to think seriously about the threat
from ``rogue'' nations and also emphasizing that the administration
wants only a modest change to the ABM treaty that would keep the
spirit of the treaty intact.
</P>
<P>
   The British position on missile defense is a critical one for
the administration. Behind the scenes, British officials have been
deeply skeptical of the plan and questioned why Washington would
want to push ahead with a scheme that would protect the United
States but not Britain.
</P>
<P>
   And although it would not protect Britain, an American early
warning radar located in Britain designed to monitor Russian
missiles would have to be modified under the American plans so that
it could detect missiles from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk with reporters, Solana, a physicist, said he
understood the compulsion politicians feel about moving toward
missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a country and you have risks and you have the
technology, it's very hard for a leader not to use it,'' he said.
But, he added, ``You have to weigh the consequences for the rest of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the worries for Europe if the United States proceeds with
the missile defense system is not only a deterioration of relations
with Russia but also with China. Europeans also worry that the
defense system could lead to a spiraling arms race that the ABM
treaty was designed to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said Monday that missile defense had not yet reached the
front burner of public debate in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But he appeared to be reflecting an undercurrent of concern that
if the United States put such a system into effect, Europe would be
left more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article, Ivo Daalder, a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution who specializes in arms control, described
the European quandary this way, ``Either they differentiate their
security from that of the United States, thus bringing about the
very decoupling they fear, or they acquire a similar degree of
protection by deploying missile defenses of their own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
