<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A REAL WHITE HOUSE STAFF, AND THEY PLAY ONE ON TV
 &HT;    280&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does art imitate government, or is it the other way
around?
</P>
<P>
   It has been hard to tell at the White House lately.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton stepped into an unaccustomed role to film a
humorous video skit that was screened Saturday night at the annual
White House Correspondents Association dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The same soiree featured a tape of White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart starring in a self-effacing satire with the cast of the
NBC television hit ``West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Martin Sheen, Allison Janney and other members of the
show's cast dropped into 1600 Pennsylvania Ave. to nose around the
real West Wing with Lockhart and a few other real White House
staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, who plays fictional President Josiah Bartlet in the TV
series, took a seat alongside astonished reporters in the briefing
room as Janney stepped up to the podium to open the midday press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment today, but I will take questions,'' the
actress announced as her real-life counterpart stood by and the
press corps played along with the gag.
</P>
<P>
   UPI correspondent Helen Thomas, the 79-year-old grade dame of
the White House press corps, served up a softball about the
president's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he doing any work?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment,'' replied Janney.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Lockhart reasserted his briefing room authority,
and was quickly asked whether he was troubled by an apparent
blurring of the lines between Hollywood and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let me tell you,'' Lockhart replied, ``I spent some time
looking at a group of actors in the fake briefing room in
Hollywood. And, looking out at you _ no, not at all. Not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton brought down the house at Saturday's black tie gala
before about 2,600 attendees (about 1 percent of whom actually have
much to do with covering the White House) with a tongue-in-cheek
video showing him stumbling around an empty White House with little
to do as his term expires.
</P>
<P>
   In the parody, titled ``The Final Days,'' Clinton played a
likeable but lonely prisoner in the twilight of his administration,
alternately passing the time by watching Disney reruns with First
Dog Buddy, coaxing ice cream sandwiches from a reluctant vending
machine or washing the presidential limo.
</P>
