u f BC-MEXICO-BANKS-NYT &LR;      05-01 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN CONGRESS HELPS BANKS EASE THEIR CREDIT CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FINEREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Mexican Congress has passed new legislation to
replace bankruptcy and loan guarantee laws dating to the 1940s,
boosting hopes that Mexican banks could begin issuing new loans to
needy businesses after a five-year credit crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which was approved last week, should help banks
recover their loans when debtors run into financial difficulties,
banking analysts said. One law streamlines bankruptcy procedures
and creates a federal institute to referee legal battles between
debtors and creditors. The other allows borrowers to use the goods
they produce or the assets they buy with the loan as the collateral
on the loan itself.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts said the new laws are a step in the right
direction, but warned that other weaknesses in the banking system
will slow the renewal of business lending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks are coming out of intensive care, but they remain in
a very delicate condition,'' said Mauricio Gonzalez Gomez, director
of the Grupo Economistas y Asociados, a Mexico City consulting
firm. ``These laws provide a more secure legal framework for
lending.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it could take several years for bank lending to catch up
with the needs of an economy that has been starved for credit for
half a decade, Gonzalez Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   After the December 1994 peso crisis, interest rates topped 100
percent, causing millions of debtors to default on loans. Previous
laws made loan recovery cumbersome, and banks responded by cutting
off credit to most Mexican businesses. Over the years since,
bankers lobbied for new laws to make it easier to seize assets held
as collateral on past due loans.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the new laws were originally written by aides to
President Ernesto Zedillo, and they were biased in favor of the
banks when first proposed to Congress, people familiar with their
legislative history said.
</P>
<P>
   During months of legislative work on the bankruptcy bill,
lawmakers from several parties, including Zedillo's own
Institutional Revolutionary Party, made at least 150 changes.
Representatives of the banks and several business associations said
that after this vigorous rewrite, the language of the final
bankruptcy law was fair to both creditors and lenders. The
500-member Chamber of Deputies approved it last week in a 355-13
vote. Other lawmakers were absent or abstained.
</P>
<P>
   The loan guarantee law did not undergo such extensive
legislative evolution, although the leftist Party of the Democratic
Revolution proposed a series of major revisions. It passed the
chamber last week in a 289-128 vote. Senators from Democratic
Revolution criticized the law as too generous to bankers before it
was put to a vote on Sunday, but the Senate passed it by a broad
margin anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the new legislation may be muted at first because
the problems facing Mexican banks are far broader than simple
difficulties with loan collection, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Many banks have been so weakened by the years of crisis that
they have little money to lend, and virtually all carry a
significant number of non-performing loans in their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Mexico has few creditworthy businesses, so banks
with capital to lend face the challenge of identifying projects
that are financially sound, said Ursula Wilhelm, a bank analyst at
Standard &AMP; Poor's in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Not only the banks remain wary. Millions of Mexicans are still
paying off debts incurred during the peso crisis, and many are
reluctant to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the laws eliminate legal loopholes that debtors have
abused, said Hector Rangel Domene, the president of the Mexican
Bankers' Association. Under Mexico's previous laws, companies in
debt could seek protection under Mexico's version of Chapter 11
before creditors could even recover the collateral the companies
had put up to secure the loans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers could often prolong bankruptcy proceedings for 10 years
or more, while companies in debt proceeded with business as usual,
he said. The new legislation should allow credit flows to increase
moderately during the second half of 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we aren't going to know just how effective the new laws
are until they're put to the test in the real world,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1852EDT &QL; 
