<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      05-01 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, May 2 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Ned Kilkelly (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (Undated) _ Millions of television viewers
found themselves without access to ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and many other popular television programs Monday as
the country's two biggest media companies, Time Warner and Walt
Disney, fought over the cable television rights to stations owned
by Disney's ABC network. The dispute has its roots in an argument
over how much money Disney should receive for carrying its channels
on Time Warner's cable systems, but it involves larger issues
dealing with the distribution of media content _ including the
longstanding antipathy between the cable and broadcast industry,
the growing competition between cable and satellite companies and
Disney's opposition to the proposed merger between America Online
and Time Warner. It also concerns how much power the new company
will wield in a television industry that is merged with the
Internet. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLLUTION-CREDITS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The New York state
legislature has passed a bill that would radically reduce the
amount of air pollution that has for years drifted from Midwestern
and Southern states into New York. The bill would forbid New York
companies from selling pollution credits they earned by cleaning up
their own smokestacks to polluters in other states. The legislation
directly challenges the 1990 Clean Air Act, which set up a
marketplace in which companies could trade the right to pollute in
the form of credits, as a commodity. Gov. George Pataki is expected
to sign the measure, which would make New York the first state to
ban these exchanges. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-DONATIONS (Washington) _ More big companies are
deciding not to give large ``soft money'' donations to political
parties. But many are not telling anyone why they're not giving _
or even acknowledging that they've stopped. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-JEWS (Shiraz, Iran) _ One of 13 Jewish men charged with
espionage went on trial Monday and Iranian authorities immediately
displayed him on television and had him admit that he had spied for
Israel. The defendant, Hamid Tefileen, made the public confession
came after the government had adamantly refused to allow family
members, human rights groups or the public to witness the opening
of the politically charged trials of the 13, who are to be tried,
one by one, in coming weeks. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Undated) _ Two members of Congress were back
in Washington Monday after one of the most expensive lobbying
efforts ever undertaken by the Clinton administration, if measured
on a per-vote basis. Hoping to sway legislators who remain
undecided on whether to grant China permanent normal trade
relations, President Clinton set aside funds earlier this year to
fly wavering lawmakers to China where they could gauge trade and
human rights conditions for themselves. But when the group, led by
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, left last week, there were only
two undecided congressmen. So began the education of Rep. Gregory
Meeks, D-N.Y., and Rep. Ruben Hinojosa, D-Texas. They were treated
royally in Beijing where they met with a vice premier and watched
the sun rise over the Great Wall. In Shanghai, they had a private
audience with China's chief negotiator with Taiwan. And in Hong
Kong, they met with the chief executive of China's newly reclaimed
territory. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-CENSUS (Detroit) _ For more than a month, a giant pair
of eyes has peered down from a billboard along several of this
city's expressways with the warning: ``DETROIT All eyes are on
You!'' The billboard was intended to remind residents to mail their
2000 census forms. But the sign is also a stark symbol of a
decade-old fear that Detroit could become the first American city
of more than 1 million people to have its population fall below
that number. The city, long dogged by its image as a rusting auto
giant, barely made it over the million marker in 1990, and then
only after a recount. Staying at a million is a point of pride.
Census anxiety runs so deep here that Mayor Dennis Archer began
drafting his battle plan four years ago. He determined that a
couple of public appearances would not be enough. So he has taken
the unusual approach of treating the census as a political
candidate would, stumping all over town on its behalf and imploring
residents to view their participation as a vote for Detroit's
future. By Nichole M. Christian.
</P>
</TEXT>
