<HEADER>
A2682 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     05-01 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL HELP ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 7)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Society of Travel Medicine has spent hours of
its biennial conventions since it was formed in 1989 debating how
to tell people that travel in the developing world is not like
being in Kansas: that malaria is a reality in particular areas,
that motor-vehicle crashes are a more severe hazard than Japanese
encephalitis, that diarrhea is a frequent problem in the tropics.
Slips inserted into airline ticket jackets were discussed, as well
as in-flight filmstrips, data sheets to be distributed by travel
agents or even folders for brochure racks.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seemed to overcome the reluctance of the natural
intermediaries _ airlines, travel agents and tour operators _ to
cloud their ``fly with me'' message by saying that paradise has a
few bugs in it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Internet. And the same popular tools that
prospective travelers use to shop at 1 a.m. for interesting
itineraries and cheap fares and hotel rooms provide access to
medical information, good and bad, without intermediaries.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As always on the Web, sorting out the authoritative sites from
the sea of information is not always easy. But when medical Web
sites are reliable and backed by solid research, they are a no-cost
source of vital information and searchable lists of travel clinics
where one can get inoculations, prescriptions and post-travel help.
They also permit shopping online for gadgets or books, and link
into government Web sites that offer help, both medical and
practical _ where to get a visa, for example.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web has changed the way experts deliver travel medicine,
according to Dr. Bradley Connor of New York, head of the public
education committee of the International Society for Travel
Medicine. ``I can get an e-mail from a client in Indonesia,'' he
said, ``and give him help easily. It is so much better than the 3
a.m. phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a guide to a choice few sites on travel health.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Book
</P>
<P>
   The mother lode in this field is ``Health Information for
International Travel,'' researched and issued by the federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. In print, it
is known as the Yellow Book. Online, at www.cdc.gov/travel, its
home page is slicker, with tropical fish and blue panels.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because this material is in the public domain, it is the
resource travel writers draw on first. It hews to U.S. rules in not
recommending, for example, medicines or treatments not approved by
the Food and Drug Administration.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The current edition is 1999-2000, and Dr. Martin S. Cetron,
acting deputy director of the division of quarantine at the CDC,
said that a hard issue was whether to update the online version
with, for example, later immunization decisions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cetron is in negotiation with several dot-com companies that
want access to the Yellow Book beyond a simple hyperlink, which is
provided now on some Web sites _ www.travelmed.com, for example.
``We have progressed from giving advice on the voice phone to
providing faxes upon automated phone order to going online,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cetron said that the government could not enter into an
exclusive agreement with any company, and so he was talking to all
the major players. This includes www .medicineplanet.com, a
brand-new Web site, and www.ijet.com, a site that will not emerge
until fall.
</P>
<P>
   As it is now, the online Yellow Book has many bonuses for
travelers: the Green Sheets, giving scores on government
cruise-ship inspections, and the Blue Sheets, which update cholera,
yellow fever and plague reports. The site is searchable by
destination and by disease.
</P>
<P>
   For those still in fiber mode, the book, stock number
017-023-00202-3, costs $22 from the Superintendent of Documents,
Washington, D.C. 20402; with a credit card, (202) 512-1800.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Medicineplanet
</P>
<P>
   Www.medicineplanet.com opened officially in mid-March. It is
large, with articles on a wide number of issues, including, as an
example, emergency contraception. This article, under Women's
Travel Center, by Dr. Susan Anderson, a clinical assistant
professor at the Stanford Medical School in California, is detailed
and includes charts with dosages and timing. This is not a topic
the Yellow Book touches.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medicineplanet is focused in the San Francisco area; its chief
executive officer is identified as Dr. Jordan Shlain, Lufthansa's
medical director in California. Editorial material is approved by
Dr. David Shlim, who directed a clinic in Nepal for years and is a
recognized authority on high-mountain illness. The editorial board
includes Dr. Martin Wolfe, a State Department consultant who is
considered the father of travel medicine as a discipline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web site was created and set up with venture capital. It has
three partners: American Express, which is selling travel medical
insurance, but not trip-cancellation coverage, on the site;
SelfCare.com, some of whose online catalog items are being offered,
and Ericsson Australia, a branch of the cell phone company, that
expects by the Olympics this fall to offer information from the
site to users of its telephones in Australia. Ann Trunko,
Medicineplanet marketing director, said that this service would
enable Ericsson clients in a pharmacy to dial a number to learn
what name to use for a drug known only by its United States name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web site is easy to use. The authors are well identified,
and the country-specific information on infectious diseases is
extensive. Dr. Stephen W. Hargarten, chairman of the emergency
medicine department of the Medical College of Wisconsin in
Milwaukee, was less enthusiastic about the information on vehicular
safety, which he found too generic. Hargarten, whose specialty is
travelers' injuries, said that www .asirt.org, (Association for
Safe International Road Travel) had road information for many
countries. This site was established by Rochelle Sobel, whose son
died in a bus crash in Turkey five years ago and is maintained as a
volunteer effort. Updating seems to be sporadic; sample material on
Turkey had not been revised for some time. Reports from other
countries are available, and users are asked to sign up and make a
donation.
</P>
<P>
   Other Specialists
</P>
<P>
   The Web simplifies the search for a travel clinic, although all
the sites with searchable lists add warnings that they do not
guarantee the care provided. Trunko said medicineplanet's list was
compiled from other lists and then checked by telephone. The
International Society of Travel Medicine now maintains its list,
sorted by country and by state within the United States, on the Web
only, at www.istm.org.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also on the association site are articles from the Journal of
Travel Medicine, a peer-reviewed publication. The most recent issue
includes an article about young volunteers who contracted dengue
fever in one of the British Virgin Islands and others, elsewhere on
the island, who did not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene also has a
clinic list at www.astmh.org. Most of the major problems in travel
occur in the tropics, although high-mountain sickness, diphtheria
in Russia, hypothermia in cold climes and injuries anywhere are
part of the picture. Tropical medicine specialists often have an
additional specialty, or, like Wolfe, end up counseling people
going almost everywhere.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Medicine Inc. in Northampton, Mass., was created 10 years
ago by Dr. Stuart Rose to publish his book, ``International Travel
Health Guide,'' now in its 11th edition. The organization's Web
site, www .travelmed.com, noted above as one with links to the CDC
book, sells the Rose book and a number of travel items like
insecticides. This organization is taking over publication of the
Traveling Healthy newsletter, edited by Dr. Karl Neumann, a
pediatrician. The newsletter will appear on the Web in the near
future, Neumann said. Neumann frequently leads travel medicine
panels on children and insect repellents.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of the International Association for Medical
Assistance to Travelers, an organization that exists on voluntary
contributions, does not put everything on line at
www.sentex.net/iamat. It includes good samples of its literature,
including maps and color diagrams. But the material most people
want is the directory of English-speaking physicians around the
world who agree to modest fees, from $55 for an office visit up to
$95 for house calls at night and on Sundays and holidays. This
directory is not online; it is mailed to new members with an appeal
for help to build a center for the study of travel and geographical
health.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   M. Assunta Uffer-Marcolongo, thewidow of the founder, Dr.
Vincenzo Marcolongo, continues the group's work as a memorial to
him and others who helped set it up. The old-style mail address is
417 Center St., Lewiston, N.Y. 14092 or 40 Regal Rd., Guelph,
Ontario, Canada N1K 1B5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
