<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE-EUROPE (Washington) _ The foreign policy chief
for the European Union, Javier Solana, said Monday that Europe was
concerned about the potentially damaging effect the Clinton
administration's plan for national missile defense could have on
Europe's security ties with the United States. By Jane Perlez. (825
words)
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-DOCTOR (Mozdok, Russia) _ When Dr. Hasan Baiyev was
summoned to his hospital in the Chechen town of Alkhan-Kala on Feb.
1, he quickly learned that it was not for an ordinary case. As
Russian troops tried to take the capital, Grozny, Chechen rebels
had begun on Jan. 31 to fight their way out. Now hundreds of
bloodied militants were waiting for treatment in Baiyev's village
southwest of Grozny. They included Shamil Basayev, the most
notorious of the Chechen warlords, who was wounded as he led his
fighters through a Russian minefield. After administering a local
anesthetic, Baiyev, a surgeon, amputated Basayev's right leg. And
soon after that, the rebels whisked their leader to safety in the
Caucasian mountains. Baiyev's life has not been the same since. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FISH (Listvyanka, Russia) _ Almost any resident of this
village can tick off the seemingly endless string of superlatives
about the great lake _ inland sea, really _ that laps insistently
against the town docks. Lake Baikal is the biggest, the oldest, by
far the deepest, the clearest lake on earth. But press a resident
to say what he loves most about Baikal, and he may cast his lot
with the nondescript, gray, oily, foot-long fish that dwells
therein. Siberians love the lowly omul. They love it fried, dried,
smoked, baked, grilled, salted, stuffed, with internals and without
internals, with and without scales. Residents of the eastern shore
even like it slightly decayed _ ``with odor,'' they call it. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT14,15, and map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ENVOY (United Nations) _ On the wall behind Ambassador
Volkan Vural's desk at the Turkish mission here is a reproduction
of a 1923 Time magazine cover featuring Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, who
forged modern Turkey out of the wreckage of the Ottoman Empire.
This summer, Vural is scheduled to return to Ankara to take up a
new post that presents a challenge almost as daunting. His job will
be to demonstrate to the European Union that Turkey merits
membership and to convince his countrymen that joining the club is
worth the painful admission price. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``w'' news file.)
