<HEADLINE>
`FRONTLINE' EXPLORES JEFFERSON'S LASTING LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It begins with Thomas Jefferson _ Founding Father, author of the
Declaration of Independence, president, prince of the Enlightenment
and father of several children by his slave mistress, Sally
Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson-Hemings story may be familiar to most Americans,
largely because so many viewers watched a CBS miniseries about
them, heavily garnished with dramatic license, three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the best ``Frontline'' of the season revisits the
DNA evidence that proves, beyond all but the tiniest doubt, that
Jefferson fathered Hemings' children.
</P>
<P>
   Hemings herself was the half-sister of Jefferson's wife, and
three-quarters white. The children she bore by Jefferson were
seven-eighths white, yet they were enslaved until Jefferson's death
in 1826.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the fractions seem silly. But they aren't, because race
and racial identity are still at the core of American life.
</P>
<P>
   That's where producer Thomas Lennon and guest correspondent
Shelby Steele, a well-known author and fellow at the Hoover
Institution at Stanford University, make this ``Frontline'' so
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontline'' visits Virginia, where the Monticello Association
will meet this weekend for another discussion about conceding that
Hemings' descendants are part of the official Jefferson family.
</P>
<P>
   But the provocative part of the 90-minute program is in Ohio,
where generations of Hemings descendants have resided since the
early 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   They live, in effect, in separate clans. There are ``white''
Hemings and ``black'' Hemings. It's a matter of self-identification
more than physical traits. Some of the ``black'' Hemings have blond
hair. Some of the ``white'' Hemings choose to conceal their African
American lineage.
</P>
<P>
   They're the living legacy of a long-lasting but historically
murky affair between a white slaveholder and his mixed-race lover.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's own conflicts over race and his refusal to admit the
obvious _ he never openly acknowledged that he fathered Hemings'
children _ are echoed among his descendants two centuries later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontline'' finds one family, named Cooper, painfully divided
over two sisters' recent discovery of their black heritage. At
least one of the sisters is eager to seek out her relatives among
the ``black'' Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't. The sisters' father, descended from Jefferson and
Hemings, has lived as a white man his entire life. He wouldn't talk
to ``Frontline''; the program even blurs his face in photos. Like
his famous ancestor, he is safeguarding a racial secret.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Frontline'' becomes, increasingly, Steele's personal
essay. He ponders skin shadings _ black, white, light-skinned
black. He notes that Jefferson himself tried to devise a
mathematical formula for how many generations it takes to cross
racial lines. What makes someone white or black? Why must we choose
a racial identity?
</P>
<P>
   Steele wonders why it all matters, but never if. In this country
it does matter, positively or negatively, in Jefferson's time and
today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Frontline'' closes on an upbeat note from Steele, who
co-wrote and narrates the program.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of Jefferson's hypocrisy and tacit denial was
procreation and possibly love. The flip side of the Cooper family's
anguish is that most of the Hemings descendants embrace and
celebrate their ties to Jefferson, Hemings and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this story shows the pains caused by racial identity,''
Steele says, ``it also shows that they are finally not enough to
keep us from being human.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
