<SLUG> BC-STONE-WEBSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STONE &AMP; WEBSTER STOCK OFF 53 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shares in Stone &AMP; Webster Inc. fell 53 percent Monday,
a day after the company disclosed a cash crunch that has forced it
to put most of its assets up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the engineering and construction firm said a cost
overrun at one project has created liquidity problems, forcing it
to restate 1999 results and to try and renegotiate payments. If its
efforts aren't successful, the company said, its accountants think
its ``ability to continue as a going concern will be brought into
question.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems could also lead to default with lenders including
Bank of America, though Stone &AMP; Webster said it exepcts to enter
into a ``forbearance agreement'' with banks in case of such an
event.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster stock closed Monday at $6.25 on the New York
Stock Exchange, down $6.9375. The stock was trading as high as
$28.625 a share in September _ still far below its record high of
$54.875 reached in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster is best known as a builder of power plants but
has struggled in the competitive industry in recent quarters. To
raise cash, it had already agreed to sell its office building in
downtown Boston and put its refrigerated-storage business up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Salomon Smith Barney analyst Tobias Levkovich said
bankruptcy ``is a possibility'' for Stone &AMP; Webster if it can't
arrange a sale or some other extensive partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a real confidence crisis in the business,'' said
Levkovich, who said the company could have troubles drumming up new
contracts. ``I wouldn't be brave and buy the stock here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster wouldn't say with whom it is holding talks to
sell assets including its engineering and construction business,
the majority of the company. Boise, Idaho-based Morrison Knudsen
Corp. had previously explored a purchase of Stone &AMP; Webster but
opted to buy Raytheon Co.'s engineering and construction business
instead last month. A spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Levkovich mentioned Fluor Corp. of Aliso Viejo, Calif. and
Jacobs Engineering Group Inc. of Pasadena, Calif. as possible
bidders; spokesmen for both declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's $6.25 closing price, the company has a total market
value of about $89 million. In its results for the three months
ended March 31, the company listed total assets of $888 million and
shareholders' equity of $320 million.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the most recent cost overrun, related to work on
an undisclosed domestic power project, Stone &AMP; Webster's cash
position had fallen dramatically. It listed $36.9 million in cash
and equivalents at the end of March, down from $106.5 million at
the same time a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Stone &AMP; Webster spokesman said the company plans to file
restated 1999 earnings within several weeks. The company had about
7,000 employees worldwide late last year, but now has about 4,100
employees, apparently related to the completion of several major
projects, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
