<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TECHNOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKAW WARNS OF RAPID CHANGES IN NEWS BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ NBC news anchor Tom Brokaw suggested Monday that rapid
changes in the technological and economic models for journalism are
hurtling the news business at ``warp speed'' to a largely unknown
destination.
</P>
<P>
   One perhaps surprising consequence, Brokaw and a panel of
broadcast executives agreed, is that in the new media world _
marked by mega-conglomerates, print and broadcast partnerships,
digital anchors, all-news cable networks, and the rampaging
Internet _ the consumer is king.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fundamental shift . . . in the relationship between
those of us conveying the news and people who are receiving it, a
shift toward giving individual consumers a choice,'' said ABC News
president David Westin, who recently endured a journalistic flap
over ABC's use of actor Leonardo DiCaprio to interview President
Clinton. ``I think audiences have said we want to make those
choices, and I don't think that's reversible.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate on the future of media took place as part of the
International Press Institute's World Congress in Boston. The other
panelists included CNN International president Eason Jordan, Voice
of America director Sanford Unger, Henrikas Yushkiavitshus,
assistant director-general for Communication, Information and
Informatics at UNESCO, and Anne-Margrete Wachtmeister,head of the
Media Unit, Competition Directorate General, at the European
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Striking a similar theme in a lunchtime speech at the
conference, New York Times publisher Arthur Sulzberger Jr. said the
``challenges for us are as complex and demanding as anything we
have seen in the past five decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers want ``instant information gratification,'' Sulzberger
added.
</P>
<P>
   During the panel, Voice of America's Unger highlighted that
concern by saying the challenge of new media ``is how to revise,
innovate, and modernize news programming without losing the
authority of the news programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw prodded the participants on that point, asking Westin
whether the DiCaprio episode suggests that programming that is
``popular'' and ``profitable'' is edging out serious news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Leonardo DiCaprio issue is an interesting and
challenging issue but at a different level than was discussed in
the press,'' Westin responded. ``If we stand still, we will be
passed by. That means, I think, that we have to take chances.
Ironically in this new world, some failure . . . is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brokaw asked about the impact of CNN's falling ratings,
Jordan responded that doing the ``right thing'' journalistically is
more important than the numbers. ``Your ratings slip a bit, that's
life.'' But he acknowledged the suddenly crowded universe of
instant news, saying ``we're not just competing with Fox News and
the MSNBC's, we are competing with the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate news synergy _ most evident in NBC's partnerships with
cable news networks CNBC and the MSNBC _ is proving to be another
mixed blessing, said the participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Content becomes a kind of tyrant . . . and reduces the
opportunity then to make an investment in other long-term
projects,'' because of the endless appetite for instant news,
Brokaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Westin lauded ``NBC's business model in the news area,'' but
said ``the real danger . . . is turning news into a commodity.'' In
an brief interview, Westin said ABC is ``exploring actively''
partnerships with regional cable news networks. NECN station
manager Charles Kravetz confirmed Monday that his station has
engaged in preliminary talks with ABC.
</P>
<P>
   During his address, Sulzberger stressed the difference between
news delivery and news integrity. While affirming that ``we are
committed to transmitting the news any way our customers prefer,''
he added that ``the more information that is available, the more
likely it is that people will turn to information they consider
reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also acknowledged the strains of the instant information
age, saying that although journalists ``continue to profess belief
in our basic principles, some of our practices have gotten a little
shaky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
