<HEADER>
A2701 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WEB-HEALTHCARE-BOS &LR;      05-01 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-HEALTHCARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD MED TO PARTICIPATE IN AETNA WEB HEALTH SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard Medical School has agreed to provide consumer
health-care information to Aetna US Healthcare's InteliHealth Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna hopes to draw on the school's expertise to broaden its Web
site, www.intelihealth.com, including more information targeting
minority consumers and the health needs of children.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal, which is expected to be completed
within the next several weeks, were not disclosed. A spokesman said
Monday the medical school does not intend to take an ownership
stake in InteliHealth.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Medical School will replace Johns Hopkins University,
which since 1996 has offered consumer advice, reviews, and articles
written by InteliHealth staff. The relationship ended shortly after
Aetna announced plans to expand its Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our future business interests were not going in the same
direction,'' said Steve Libowitz, director of Hopkins' office of
consumer health information.
</P>
<P>
   Libowitz declined to elaborate, but health-care analyst Ken
Abramowitz speculated that Johns Hopkins, which had owned a
minority stake in InteliHealth, did not want to invest more money
in the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually disputes involve two issues: money or capability,''
said Abramowitz, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein in New York.
``I suspect that Johns Hopkins did not want to put more money in.''
</P>
<P>
   The InteliHealth Web site has more than 1 million visitors each
month and licensing agreements with more than 400 broadcast, print,
and other media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Internet business, attracting more visitors and
revenue does not necessarily lead to profits. And so far,
health-care sites like Drkoop.com have struggled with ballooning
losses and wary investors. Aetna does not release InteliHealth's
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unclear whether there's a sustainable business model in
putting up large numbers of advertisements and providing free
information,'' said Dr. William Hersh, head of the medical
informatics division at Oregon Health Sciences University.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna and other insurers, however, may have a better shot at
becoming large providers of online health-care information, Hersh
said. Unlike sites like Drkoop.com, they can provide consumers with
more services and products.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers say both insurers and their content
providers, like Harvard Medical School, will need to be careful to
avoid potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct tells me this represents potential good, in a
sense that more information is made available to the lay public,''
said Benjamin Moulton, executive director of the American Society
of Law, Medicine &AMP; Ethics. ``But it also represents some conflict
issues that should be well thought out.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Gibbons, a spokesman for Harvard Medical School, said the
school will have ``strict editorial content'' and control over the
placement of advertisements next to its name.
</P>
<P>
   At Johns Hopkins University, professors, nurses and doctors
reserved the right to review and correct any inaccuracies in
Intelihealth's articles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2702 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV07-NY     05-01 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ECCENTRIC TO MICROMANAGER TO DOMINATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Hague, leader of the Tory opposition in the House of
Commons, rose to denounce the prime minister: ``Tony Blair is the
 &UR; control freak &LR;  who has lost control.'' In an editorial about the
devolution of power to Wales, Britain's Daily Telegraph noted,
``Tony Blair has acknowledged that he has occasionally acted like
the  &UR; control freak &LR;  his opponents accuse him of being.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge has equal puissance on this side of the Atlantic. The
Senate Democratic leader, Tom Daschle, used the phrase to describe
his Republican counterpart, Trent Lott. And during the recent
presidential primary elections, The Austin American-Statesman
quoted an unidentified aide to Gov. Jane Dee Hull of Arizona as
derogating Sen. John McCain in these words: ``The senator gets very
heated about things. He's a  &UR; control freak &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The favored political attack phrase means ``one obsessed by the
need to dominate; a person driven by the urge to be in total
command.'' It is not as serious a blast as ``totalitarian'' and
does not carry the sexual overtone of ``dominatrix,'' but _ by
suggesting the control is for control's sake rather than for any
rational purpose _ imputes more neuroticism than ``micromanager.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because  &UR; control &LR;  as a noun has become a double-edged
sword. To be  &UR; out of control &LR;  is to approach what used to be called
``raving mad,'' but at the other extreme is the grim-faced,
white-knuckled  &UR; control freak &LR; , with his obsession to extend
untrammeled authority into every detail of others' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the meaning of the slang noun  &UR; freak &LR;  _ first
recorded in Finley Peter Dunne's 1895 ``Mr. Dooley'' in The Chicago
Evening Post as ``the deluded ol'  &UR; freak &LR; '' _ has also been getting
quirkier with the passage of time. A century ago, it meant
``eccentric'' or ``abnormal,'' as in the carnival  &UR; freak show &LR; 
exploiting specimens of obesity or dwarfism, and later as an
adjectival synonym for ``aberrational,'' ``deviant'' or ``hard to
imagine,'' as in `` &UR; freak &LR;  accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, it was adopted in drug lingo as a verb,  &UR; to freak
out &LR; , meaning ``to rave under the influence of hallucinatory
drugs.'' It was then applied as a noun in  &UR; speed freak &LR;  and  &UR; acid
freak &LR; . In his 1977 book, ``Dispatches,'' Michael Herr, who had
covered the Vietnam War for Esquire magazine, applied the term
 &UR; control freak &LR;  to ``one of those people who always ... had to know
what was coming next.''
</P>
<P>
   The term became favored by Hollywood screenwriters and producers
dealing with that war; it was repeated in the 1978 film ``The Deer
Hunter'' and in the 1979 ``Apocalypse Now.'' By 1986, the meaning
softened to ``enthusiast, aficionado, maven,'' and Steven Spielberg
freely confessed to TV Guide, ``I'm a  &UR; control freak &LR; .'' (In the
same way, language mavens call themselves  &UR; word freaks &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   In current use, the meaning of the combination of  &UR; control &LR;  and
 &UR; freak &LR;  has veered toward ``neurotic.'' In The Boston Globe in
1992, Matthew Gilbert noted how crowds prized the singer Madonna's
`` &UR; control-freakishness &LR; .'' Writing four years later about Barbra
Streisand, The London Sunday Times could not decide whether she was
``America's greatest female singer or a power-mad woman whose
 &UR; control-freakishness &LR;  makes working with her all but impossible
save from a kneeling position.''
</P>
<P>
   That latest interpretation of  &UR; freakishness &LR;  as ``off the deep
end'' is why Daschle, when asked about his use of  &UR; control freak &LR; 
about Lott, hastily backed off: ``I say it in a light-hearted way.
I don't mean he is a  &UR; freak &LR; . I'm just saying he's a  &UR; control
nut &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   In Senate rhetoric, evidently  &UR; nut &LR;  is far less pejorative than
 &UR; freak &LR; . That reflects general usage; to be  &UR; nutty &LR;  is to be mildly
crackbrained and is often used in self-description of too-earnest
advocacy: I readily call myself a ``privacy  &UR; nut &LR; ,'' but would not
flagellate myself as a ``privacy  &UR; freak &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   A  &UR; nut &LR;  is a  &UR; freak &LR;  you kind of like. Loosey-goosey descriptive
lexicographers, with their anything-goes passivity, deride
prescriptive pop grammarians like me as  &UR; control freaks &LR; , but I
look bemusedly at those roundheeled dictionary writers as
common-usage  &UR; nuts &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RIGHT'S WORDS
</P>
<P>
   William F. Buckley announced last month that he has decided to
give up public speaking; in its stead, this pioneering practitioner
of self-mocking rodomontade has endowed his conservative followers
with ``Let Us Talk of Many Things'' (Forum/Prima, $30), a
high-stylish compilation of 50 years of piquant and literate
comment.
</P>
<P>
   His speeches show his easy way of teaching as if in passing. ``I
shall not introduce _ the rhetoricians call this  &UR; paralepsis &LR;  _ the
wonderful woman sitting, appropriately, on my left, Mrs. Robert
Kennedy.'' This is a device of emphasis by pretending to omit (the
old ``to say nothing of'' and ``not to mention'' trick). When you
 &UR; paralep &LR;  like that, but then call attention to your own
emphasis-by-omission, you're subtly instructing.
</P>
<P>
   He also provokes you to teach yourself. Buckley is known for his
delight in using unfamiliar words. He referred to Henry Kissinger
and ``one truth no one can challenge: the petrology of our
association.'' I had to look it up:  &UR; Petrology &LR;  is the study of the
structure of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   So why not say ``the rock-solid quality of our association''?
Because the speaker sometimes wants to push his audience a little.
He is saying: Go look up the word _ work on it a little _ and then
you won't forget it or my point.
</P>
<P>
   He's made those of us in the word trade stretch. ``There is
pleasure in even a little progress,'' he said in tribute to the
conservative thinker James Burnham, ``even among those of us
taught, at our mother's knee, not to seek to immanentize the
eschaton.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eschatology &LR;  is the study of ultimate destiny, the purpose of
life reckoned at the last accounting. The  &UR; eschaton &LR;  is its Greek
root: the last thing, the divinely ordained climax of history, with
its present sense of a final judgment that should inform our lives.
That's the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; immanentize &LR; ? The Latin  &UR; immanere &LR; , ``to remain in,'' leads
us to  &UR; immanent &LR; , ``inherent, intrinsic,'' with a special
philosophical sense of ``confined to the mind.'' It's not a word I
would use, because  &UR; inherent &LR;  does the job and  &UR; immanent &LR;  is too
easily confused with  &UR; imminent &LR; , ``about to take place,'' with a
connotation of danger.
</P>
<P>
   So I admitted defeat and called Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The source of  &UR; immanentize the eschaton &LR;  is the 1952 `New
Science of Politics,' by Eric Voegelin,'' he explained. ``It's a
warning against taking ultimate reality and treating it
pantheistically, rather than as an objective philosophical
phenomenon.'' The conservative pioneer added: ``It was turned into
a bumper sticker by the Young Americans for Freedom. Delicious,
don't you think?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
