<SLUG> BC-SEX-OFFENDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. SEX OFFENDERS SEEK HAVEN IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The traffic across New England's state borders may be driven by
more than 6 percent sales tax or liquor stores' blue laws:
Personnel at New Hampshire's sex offender registry say convicted
offenders are moving to Maine to avoid registering their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Robert McMurray, who oversees the 250 offenders listed
in Manchester, N.H., said since the fall, several offenders had
called to deactivate their files and told him outright that moved
because they would not have to register in Maine because their
crime took place before September 1999. To State Trooper Jill
Rocky, who oversees the New Hampshire registry, the gap between the
two states' laws is large enough to seriously undermine the premise
of sex offender registries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep track of these people, but we're doing it
in a way that allows them to play the system,'' Rocky said.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts from across the border came as news to Maine law
enforcement officers, who say they have seen no evidence that the
number of sex offenders in Maine has been increasing. And some
dismissed the suggestion that Maine has earned an underground
reputation as a comfortable place for convicted sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. Julie Ann O'Brien, Republican of Augusta, was so
disturbed to hear of the offenders' comments that she spent a day
trying to figure out how to bring the states' laws into closer
agreement _ most likely, she said, by broadening Maine's registry
to include crimes committed before 1999. New Hampshire registers
all convictions since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that it's happening, or if it's happening en
masse,'' said O'Brien, who sponsored a tougher registry law last
September. ``But I firmly believe that if it's enough for police
detectives to bring it up, it's enough of a problem that we need to
close any loopholes we might have.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine and New Hampshire's uneven state laws, like 48 others,
issued from one source: the 1994 murder of 7-year-old Megan Kanka,
who was raped and strangled by a repeat offender who lived on her
street. Congress passed a version of Megan's Law in 1997, requiring
that past convictions be made public, but left the states to pass
detailed laws of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky, of the New Hampshire sex offender registry, said the
patchwork of laws is playing right into the hands of pedophiles _ a
highly mobile population skilled at manipulating the system, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And others say local police departments should be doing the work
of monitoring convicted offenders anyway. Portland police chief
Michael Chitwood said his department had done 16 ``neighborhood
notifications'' in the past two years in cases where the offender
was not required to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offended by (the suggestion that) Maine is a place where
sex offenders can enjoy life `the way life should be.' I can just
speak for the city of Portland, but that's not the case here,''
Chitwood said. ``I don't buy that. No, not at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
