<HEADLINE>
DEFINING TERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The State Department's annual report on international terrorism,
released Monday, merits criticism for its inconsistencies. But it
does sketch a useful picture of a threat that is in constant flux.
</P>
<P>
   One of the inherent difficulties of doing such a report stems
from the unending debate about how to define who is a terrorist.
The State Department does not hesitate to call the
Iranian-sponsored Lebanese Shi'ite militia Hezbollah a terrorist
organization because it plants bombs in southern Lebanon, targeting
Israeli soldiers or Israel's local proxies. When the Socialist
prime minister of France, Lionel Jospin, called the Hezbollah
fighters terrorists, however, he was castigated in many quarters of
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Like the guerrilla fighters who train in Pakistan for operations
in Indian-occupied Kashmir or the People's Mujahedeen of Iran who
are headquartered in Iraq and conduct bombings and armed assaults
inside Iran, the Hezbollah are terrorists to some and freedom
fighters to others. For the State Department's report to earn
credibility, it should hew to a definition of terrorism that is
influenced as little as possible by shifting geopolitical
preferences or political opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   This report, like its predecessors, combines dispassionate rigor
with politicized shadings. It says that Syria is now a sponsor of
terrorism but will cease to be so if it makes peace with Israel.
The reality, however, is that the regime of Hafez Assad has
harbored not only anti-Israel groups but others that have targeted
Turkey, Jordan, Iraq, and the PLO.
</P>
<P>
   One lucid observation of the report is that the bloody and
protracted antiterrorist campaigns of Egypt and Algeria, in
combination with political tactics aimed at separating moderate
Islamic fundamentalists from more extreme groups, have greatly
reduced the level of internecine violence.
</P>
<P>
   The most questionable assertion of the report is that ``loose
networks'' rather than traditional state sponsors of terrorism now
represent the greatest threat worldwide. Iraq and Iran still have
the money and the state powers to do far more damage than any small
cluster of zealots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
