<HEADLINE>
DETROIT RALLYING THE CROWDS TO FILL OUT THE FORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., W.Va., Ohio, Ill., D.C., Calif. Colo.)   By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ For more than a month, a giant pair of eyes has peered
down from a billboard along several of this city's expressways with
the warning: ``DETROIT All eyes are on You!''
</P>
<P>
   The billboard was intended to remind residents to mail their
2000 census forms. But the sign is also a stark symbol of a
decade-old fear that Detroit may become the first American city of
more than 1 million people to have its population fall below that
number. A study by the Southeastern Michigan Council of Governments
has estimated the city's population at 970,000.
</P>
<P>
   The city, long dogged by its image as a rusting auto giant,
barely made it over the million marker in 1990, and then only after
a recount. Staying at a million is a point of pride.
</P>
<P>
   Census anxiety runs so deep here that Mayor Dennis Archer began
drafting his battle plan four years ago. He determined that a
couple of public appearances would not be enough. So he has taken
the unusual approach of treating the census like a political
candidate, stumping all over town on its behalf and imploring
residents to view their participation as a vote for Detroit's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we've got great American cities that have less than
a million people,'' Archer said, ``And certainly we're not going to
fall off into the Detroit River if we drop below a million. But I
don't want that to happen. It's a matter of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the city has draped itself in Census 2000
paraphernalia: 13,000 lawn signs, 10,000 bumper stickers and scores
of banners and billboards, all of which were paid for from its own
budget and are independent of the census bureau's promotion blitz.
There is so much census advertising here, it is easy to overlook
the few bumper stickers and banners promoting the presidential
candidates George W. Bush and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   What is more striking here, at a time when census officials
nationally have been worried about low response and lack of
community involvement, is the grass-roots support the mayor's
effort has won. Thousands of people have turned out to his Call to
Action rallies and Census Sunday church meetings. Many _ including
schoolchildren _ have donned Census T-shirts and taken to the
streets promoting the census to anyone who will listen. At the
city's public schools, prizes were awarded to students who brought
their families' completed forms to on-site census coordinators. At
least 7,000 people have signed up to become ``Knowledgeable
Neighbors,'' an initiative that aims to draft one person on each of
Detroit's 11,000 city blocks who can help census counters get
information about neighbors who decline to open their doors. And
long before the government mailed out census forms, the mayor's
staff was out checking the list of addresses. They turned up 17,000
unregistered addresses, and 22,000 where the home had either been
demolished or abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many cities are working with us to make sure they're on top of
the count,'' said Dwight Dean, head of the Census Bureau's Detroit
region, which oversees operations in Michigan, Ohio and West
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't seen a city put in the kind of emotional energy
and human resources that Detroit is investing since the 1970s,''
said Dean, who has also assisted in census mobilization efforts in
Chicago, Washington, Los Angeles and Denver. ``The mayor has the
whole city energized and ready to take personal ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses are stepping up, too. At the mayor's request, several
of the city's top rival advertising agencies volunteered to create
a slogan (``Everybody Wins When You Mail It In) and a slick package
of accompanying television and radio ads. The price tag for such a
package is usually about a half million dollars, say advertising
executives. Owners of beauty salons and coffee shops have partially
converted their businesses into census information centers. Local
McDonald's owners offered unlimited meals throughout April to any
of the nearly 10,000 homeless people here who filled out a census
form and received a yellow ``I'm Important I've Been Counted'' pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Detroit's gone census crazy,'' said Lydia Bolgard,
an assistant at the Coalition of Temporary Shelter, one of
Detroit's largest homeless shelters. ``They've come in here with
census back packs, water bottles, you name it. They're really
taking this seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what has made the census such a priority here is the
memory of the 1990 census, which even the federal government now
concedes undercounted several million people across the country. At
the time, Mayor Coleman Young was so angered by the government's
count, which pegged Detroit's population below 1 million, that he
discarded it and conducted his own census. After his staff found
more than 100,000 more people, the official U.S. census count was
adjusted to 1,027,974.
</P>
<P>
   Equally pressing for Detroit was the fact that its population
has steadily dropped since 1960, though never below a million. And
because some federal aid is based on population, every uncounted
person is a $3,000 loss for the city. Besides that, under a state
law, the city stood to lose hundreds of millions of dollars in aid
if it dipped below 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But in the midst of Archer's planning, the law was rewritten, as
part of a 1998 package of revenue sharing concessions, which
lowered the population requirement to 750,000 and left Detroit with
the authority to increase taxes should its population dip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit's great digit scare is over,'' said Patricia Becker,
executive director of the Southeast Michigan Census Council, an
independent demography consultant. ``If the population is six
digits or seven, it doesn't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, in the eyes of those who live here. ``This is
the Motor City, Motown,'' boasts Maggie Jene Resor, a longtime
resident and census partnership specialist. She is the census
liaison to the city's religious and elderly outreach committee.
``We've given too much to the world to be known as the city that
couldn't keep a million people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is both tangible and anecdotal evidence that Archer's
approach may be working. Sixty percent of the census forms mailed
to the city's 400,000 housing units were returned by the federal
government's April 1 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   That's up 3 percentage points over 1990. U.S. Census Director
Ken Prewitt said he believed the increase was the result of the
Archer's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit is easily in the top half dozen in terms of the
quality of effort and commitment that they've put into this,'' said
Dr. Ken Prewitt. ``They've proven they don't intend to repeat the
1990 census.'' Census counters have until July 7 to find the people
who have not responded by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, it was taboo to even speak of the census in
Southwest Detroit, a largely Mexican enclave and home to many
illegal immigrants. Those who were familiar with it feared it, says
Maria Elena Rodriguez, president of the Mexicantown Community
Development Corp. But this time around, she said, the city and the
local census office have dispatched so many resources _ including
commissioning a mural _ and so many people to the neighborhood that
even some recent illegal arrival have become curious about the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way we would have been so grossly undercounted in
1990 if they had done this kind of outreach,'' said Rodriguez. Her
organization estimates Detroit's Hispanic population at 70,000, a
marked difference from the 33,000 people counted in the 1990
census. ``By putting up a mural, going door to door, and sending
out radio and TV announcements in Spanish, the city has really made
the people feel like `Yes, you count, even if you are
undocumented.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Archer, a co-chair of the Democratic National Committee,
worries. For every breakthrough, a new hurdle awaits, like the
complaints that flooded into his office from residents upset that
their forms arrived with the address of a nearby suburb instead of
Detroit. When census officials explained that the forms were bar
coded and would be counted in Detroit's favor, it raised even more
suspicions, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone to great lengths to assure people the information
is absolutely confidential; the I.N.S. can't get it, the FBI can't
get it. No one,'' he said. But he added, ``This city is 80 percent
people of color and because of that rich diversity a significant
part our population does not trust the federal government. It makes
it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is certain of this much: ``We've done everything we
know how to do to ensure that Detroit stands up and is counted.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
