a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      05-01 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A LONG, FLAT DRIVE FROM HERE TO THE END OF CREATION  
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week brought us the usual ho-hum array of major scientific
breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   More progress on mapping the human genome. New indications that
cloned cells could slow or reverse the aging process. Exciting
advances in the search for a replacement for Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   One particular discovery captured my attention. It sounded like
it might be a riff from an old blues song: The Earth ain't flat,
baby, but the universe is.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you read the story. An international team of scientists,
using an ultra-sensitive telescope hovering above Antarctica, were
able for the first time to observe itsy bitsy ripples of something
called cosmic microwave background radiation.
</P>
<P>
   These ripples, as best I can tell from news accounts, are kind
of like cosmic dust bunnies. They're leftover particles of light
that have been skittering around on heaven's floor since the start
of the universe about 15 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I don't profess to understand all of this _ I was, uh, a couple
of gym credits short of a degree in astrophysics _ but scientists
say the pattern of ripples provides conclusive evidence that the
universe is shaped more like a pancake than, say, a hard-boiled
egg.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm more than a little disappointed.
What they're telling us is that all of creation is one long,
mind-numbingly flat drive. No hills, no stomach-plummeting dips, no
hairpin turns. Not even a tacky souvenir stand, apparently. It's
straightaway dull, from here to the edge of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   What a letdown. Where's the romance? Where's the adventure? Aye
carumba, where's the next exit? I wanna pull over and take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   As bluesy as this news was, however, it could well be the least
of our worries. I have in front of me a much more alarming
newspaper story about a whizbang new gizmo called the Relativistic
Heavy Ion Collider.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like something you might see offered by Ronco on
late-night TV, but it's more than that. Much, much more. Some time
in May _ an exact date hasn't been set yet _ scientists at the
Brookhaven National Laboratory intend to fire up the aforementioned
device on Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to recreate what the universe looked like a few
milliseconds after it was formed. (Flat, but a lot less cluttered,
I'm guessing.)
</P>
<P>
   The collider will hurl subatomic particles at each other at
pretty close to the speed of light. The resulting boom-booms will
create temperatures of a trillion degrees, which is quite a bit
steamier than _ oh, let's see _ the center of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, this is happening. Sort of puts the New York
Senate race in perspective, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Sunday Times of London ran a piece speculating
that this super-duper supercollider could accidentally create a
black hole and suck up the entire universe at roughly the speed of
light. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Another danger, according to the Times article, is that the
collider will generate ``strangelets,'' a new form of matter that
would transform everything it touches, also at the speed of light.
(Transform into what, exactly, the story doesn't say. I'd like to
be skinnier, with either a 100 mph fastball or a good head for
math, but I gather that's not the sort of thing they're talking
about.)
</P>
<P>
   Brookhaven's response to this public display of fretting was to
commission a group of physicists to contemplate doom and, more to
the point, the collider's relative ability to bring it about. They
studied it and reported there's no need to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conclusion is that the candidate mechanisms for
catastrophic scenarios at RHIC are firmly excluded by existing
empirical evidence, compelling theoretical arguments, or both,''
the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Um, OK. Thanks for checking!
</P>
<P>
   The force of the collisions, according to Brookhaven's Web site
(www.rhic.bnl.gov), will cause no more impact than ``a mosquito
hitting a screen door on a summer evening.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a lovely image, but I prefer to think of it as a skeeter
brushing our necks as we drive our hopelessly overwhelmed selves
toward the edge of our flapjack-flat universe.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, I eagerly await news of what Brookhaven will
scrape off creation's screen door this month. We certainly live in
exciting times, don't we? Strangelet days, even.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
