<SLUG> BC-RAY-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis lawyers win big point on allegations
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Defense attorneys for Ray Lewis scored a big victory
Monday when a Fulton County judge denied prosecution efforts to use
prior allegations of assault against Lewis in his upcoming murder
trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of whether Lewis will be tried separately was put
off until later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner disallowed a bid by
prosecutors to enter into evidence three separate incidents in
which the football star allegedly struck women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the same argument (that) if he did it before, he'll do
it again,'' Bonner said. ``I don't find the incidents sufficiently
similar'' to the attacks that occurred Jan. 31 where two men were
stabbed to death in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were attempting to show the incidents _ in which he
allegedly choked a girlfriend, scratched a woman and punched
another in a bar _ show a pattern of conduct and ``rebut his claim
that he was a peacemaker.'' Defense attorney Don Samuel called all
three allegations baseless.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in an unexpectedly quick session where the judge
upheld a police search of Lewis' Baltimore home but left unanswered
until later key issues as to whether Lewis gets tried separately
from his two co-defendants and if his statement to Atlanta police
should be suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   The trial against Lewis and his friends, Reginald Oakley and
Joseph Sweeting, is scheduled to start May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's lawyer, Bruce Harvey, renewed his request for Bonner to
grant immunity to Kwame King and Carlos Stafford, two men who were
with Lewis the night of the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey called the two men ``witnesses/participants'' and said
they can provide testimony to help clear his client. The men have
hired attorneys and have not talked to prosecutors or the defense.
Bonner postponed ruling, asking Harvey to show her if she has
authority to grant immunity to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hearing, Bonner asserted control over the case.
</P>
<P>
   She ordered prosecutors to turn over evidence favorable to the
defense, reminded lawyers about a court-imposed gag order and even
scolded prosecutor Elizabeth Baker for not listening to her while
she spoke. Bonner also told prosecutors that they should now be
preparing their case for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys complained they are still getting evidence
from the prosecution, four weeks after the court-imposed deadline
for both sides to exchange information.
</P>
<P>
   Baker reminded Bonner that the speedy trial demand by defense
gave prosecutors less time than normal to prepare. She was not
swayed by that argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time to stop investigating,'' said Bonner, 59,
who has been a Fulton judge for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The judge appeared to take a practical approach to motions,
mentioning that a prosecution effort to have the jury visit the
scene inside the Lincoln Navigator limousine at 4 a.m. may be
pushing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a convinced that going to the scene will be of
assistance to the jury, especially at four in the morning,'' Bonner
said.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutor Clint Rucker told the judge he could amend the
request so that jurors could visit the Buckhead scene ``when it's
dark,'' Bonner asked, ``Why didn't you do that in the first
place?''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner wondered if the jury could simply be taken to see the
limo in the darkened courthouse parking lot. ``But my thought about
it is we can't make it 20 degrees and Super Bowl night,'' she said,
deferring her ruling until the trial is underway.
</P>
<P>
   The judge upheld a search of Lewis's Baltimore home, which the
defense characterized as ``overbroad,'' noting that police even
confiscated Lewis' little sister's photo album. Prosecutors
countered that Lewis had not been cooperative to police and they
were trying to find photos of potential suspects to include in
police lineups.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, the flamboyant pony-tailed attorney, also filed a motion
to ``level the playing field'' _ allowing him to bypass the gag
order and hold a press conference. Harvey said that he was not
appointed until after lawyers were ordered to stop talking about
the case. And he pointed out that both Lewis's attorneys and
prosecutors had a field day beforehand courting the press.
</P>
<P>
   The judge denied his motion without comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
