<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time could run out for S.C. flag compromise
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the raging row over the Confederate battle flag flying atop
South Carolina's State House dome, there's plenty of debating and
maneuvering left. There's just not much time.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly adjourns June 1, a quickly approaching
finish line for a chamber more comfortable at a tortoise's pace.
</P>
<P>
   While this week is crucial in determining whether the
controversial Civil War emblem remains over the South Carolina
Capitol, it also may be pivotal in shaping similar debates in
Georgia and Mississippi. The Palmetto State's Deep South cousins
incorporate the same battle design in their state flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't crank out something this session, the flag will be
flying for God knows how long,'' said Gilda Cobb-Hunter
(D-Orangeburg), House minority leader in South Carolina and a key
member of the legislative black caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the first day the House theoretically could open floor
debate on a bill that would remove the flag from the Capitol dome,
black legislators will try settling on a proposed amendment to a
Senate plan, which calls for the battle emblem to be flown at a
Confederate military memorial on the State House lawn.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, though, the floor debate will commence next week to
give both sides time to develop their plans, according to leaders
in the GOP-controlled House.
</P>
<P>
   Black leaders say the Confederate banner _ a red flag marked by
a sea-blue ``X'' with 13 white stars _ is a reminder of slavery and
white oppression. Flag supporters see it as a mark of battlefield
heroism and Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
started a boycott of South Carolina's $14.6 billion tourist
industry Jan. 1. The group said the sanctions would remain in
effect until legislators move the battle flag from the State House
dome.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP is stinging from an ironic political defeat Monday:
Gov. Jim Hodges signed a bill that creates a Martin Luther King Jr.
holiday in South Carolina _ the last state to officially recognize
King Day. The NAACP opposed the bill because it also establishes a
permanent holiday honoring Confederate Memorial Day on May 10.
</P>
<P>
   As for the flag, there's urgency to act now, Cobb-Hunter said,
because she doubts the fragile coalition of business leaders,
churches, Republicans and Democrats who want to move the flag will
last into next session. The state Senate already has passed a bill
that would remove the battle flag from the dome and both chambers
of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in South Carolina, the debate is creating
momentum for Georgia lawmakers who oppose the Confederate insignia
on the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   If South Carolina removes the battle flag, it would be a
``victory for America,'' said Georgia Rep. Tyrone Brooks
(D-Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do not,'' said Brooks, president of the Georgia
Association of Black Elected Officials, ``then I think we're going
to be hard-pressed over here to show the nation that we're smarter
than they are, that we can find some common ground, that we can do
the right thing and we can alleviate the necessity of Georgia being
faced with economic sanctions as South Carolina is suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Brooks repeated his warning that civil rights groups,
including the NAACP and the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, would call for an economic boycott of the Peach State
if the General Assembly doesn't change the state flag next year. In
South Carolina, the primary debate is over where to relocate one of
the most recognizable symbols of Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four of 26 black House members oppose the Senate's
proposal because it moves the flag to one of the most prominent
places in downtown Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb-Hunter, the House minority leader, is working for a
``healing waters'' display that flies the Confederate flag as one
of many in a new memorial behind the 37-foot marble tribute to
Confederate soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate plan is not the vehicle we need to use,''
Cobb-Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly the House begins debate may rest with the Rules
Committee, which can set a specific time to consider the bill. It
would take a two-thirds vote by the 15-member committee then a
majority vote by the House to start debate.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker David Wilkins (R-Greenville) and Rules Committee
Chairman Doug Smith (R-Spartanburg) today begin the formal process
of testing the will of committee members. Smith estimates he has a
``solid eight, possibly nine votes'' right now. Since some
Republicans refuse to support any compromise, Smith needs
Democratic support to pass a resolution to start debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what happens through the week,'' Smith said Monday.
``If a new compromise comes in and begins to erode the base of my
party, the Republican Party, then obviously whether we present a
Rules resolution is somewhat in question. I just don't see that a
compromise will be coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
