<SLUG> BC-POLICY-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KISSINGER WARNS OF WORLDWIDE UPHEAVAL AMID `ADJUSTMENTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Former US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger warned
media executives from around the world Monday that while advancing
human rights is a ``totally appropriate'' goal for democracies,
such crusades have the potential to cause massive upheaval without
achieving the desired results.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the world is headed ``into a period of great
turmoil. . .. As a result of globalization and technology, there
will be huge adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to 300 members of the International Press Institute
meeting at Boston's World Trade Center, Kissinger rejected the idea
that human-rights standards and practical foreign policy
considerations would necessarily conflict, but he said that the
problems confronting Western countries in the Balkans illustrate
the dangers of fuzzy thinking about rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have maneuvered ourselves into a situation where we have
not really identified what objective we are serving'' in Kosovo, he
said, and are ``forcing three reluctant nationalities to live
together. . . in Bosnia, when that multiculturalism had failed in
Yugoslavia'' before the West became involved.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger later told faculty and students at Tufts University's
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy that ``statesmen have to
approach their objectives in stages; prophets try to achieve them
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only problem is,'' he said, his voice more gravelly than ever
as he approaches his 77th birthday, ``prophets have caused a lot
more suffering than statesmen because they produced crusades, and
declared all their opponents as evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade relations between the United States and China, currently
one of the hottest issues in US foreign policy, surfaced repeatedly
in the press institute discussion following Kissinger's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Patten, the last British governor of Hong Kong, who
clashed frequently with China over human rights issues in the
closing years of Britain's 150-year rule over the enclave, agreed
with Kissinger that human rights and trade issues ought to be
separated _ a position initially disdained and now embraced by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether China becomes a member of the World Trade Organization
should be decided on trade and commercial grounds,'' Patten said.
Kissinger stressed that it took 400 years to develop democracy in
the West and said China should get some credit for evolving in a
positive direction, rather than being continually confronted with
absolutist demands.
</P>
<P>
   Kishore Mahbubani, Singapore's representative to the United
Nations, challenged what he called the easy assumption that Western
societies engaged in human rights campaigns to benefit others, and
urged that ``you at least consider the possibility that there is
another point of view _ (that the human-rights issue) is a cynical,
self-serving instrument of foreign policy.'' The comment was
directed at foes of normalizing US trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China enters the WTO, it will be transformed in the same
way as other East Asian nations'' that were helped into the world
economic order by Western countries building alliances against Cold
War communism, Mahbubani said.
</P>
<P>
   For all his emphasis on gradualism and practicality, Kissinger
said leaders and foreign policy makers should recognize and react
to the the recent demonstrations against globalization in
Washington, Seattle, and foreign cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like these demonstrations, because I lived through
them in the Vietnam period and their ultimate objective is usually
to undermine the credibility of government,'' he said. ``Many of
the demonstrators don't know . . . what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``they have called attention to an important
problem which should be taken very seriously. . . . The globalized
world is only a small percentage of the global economy. In many
countries, we have a globalized upper level, a national middle
level, and an underclass level. All of these are going to express
themselves politically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The anti-globalizers are calling attention to a real
problem,'' he said, ``and if that problem is not met, we will find
more and more resentments around the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
