<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2720 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-01 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE REAL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The re-reopening of the final final-status talks between
Israelis and Palestinians in Eilat Monday provides an illuminating
snapshot of where Israeli-Arab negotiations are now. To put it
bluntly: The Palestinians want to say yes to a deal but are waiting
for the goods from Israel; and the Syrians, who have all the goods
they could want from Israel, don't know how to say yes.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian leaders know exactly what the outlines
of their deal will be: The Palestinians will get back 90 percent of
the West Bank and Gaza for their own state, and Israel will keep 10
percent _ the 10 percent of the West Bank where 80 percent of
Israeli settlers live. The big question is whether the Israeli and
Palestinian ruling coalitions can hold together for such a tough
compromise. Don't kid yourself _ we're approaching the moment of
truth here, and for both Israelis and Palestinians it could be a
moment of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   True, Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, got off to a slow
start. For a general who said he was not much of a politician,
Barak spent a lot of time looking at polls. His clear preference
was also to get the Israeli-Syrian deal done first _ a deal for
which he had much more of an innate feel, because it is a deal
about how two armies live apart. The Israeli-Palestinian talks, by
contrast, are about how two communities live together. The
negotiations with the Palestinians required the development of
trust; the negotiations with the Syrians were built on the absence
of trust.
</P>
<P>
   But since Syria's president, Hafez Assad, stiffed President
Clinton in Geneva a few weeks ago, Barak has thrown himself into
the Palestinian talks. What happened with the Syrians was that
their foreign minister, Farouk al-Shara, had indicated to the
Israelis and Americans that ``the lake'' _ that is, the Sea of
Galilee in northern Israel _ would remain entirely in Israel's
hands. When Assad met with Clinton, though, he insisted that the
northeastern shore and northeastern portion of the lake had been
Syria's before the 1967 war, and would have to be returned to
Syrian control along with the Golan Heights. Shara said the lake
was Israel's; Assad said the lake was Syria's; Barak said: ``You
can have the Golan back, but no lake. See you later. I'm going to
talk to the Palestinians.``
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Barak has made two key moves. First, he's buying off
the Shas ultra-Orthodox party, a key coalition partner. Shas'
religious schools are bankrupt and it desperately needs state
funds. Barak is offering Shas the money it wants _ if Shas agrees
to deliver its key votes to support any settlement Barak strikes
with the Palestinians. Barak is also moving toward giving Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, full control of the Palestinian
village of Abu Dis, which is just outside the boundary of Jerusalem
and could serve as the foundation for the Palestinians' own capital
in the Jerusalem area _ without Israel's having to redivide the
city in any way.
</P>
<P>
   These moves, which are already being resisted by all the
rightist parties in Israel, are aimed at pressuring Arafat to start
preparing Palestinians for their tough compromise. That means
preparing Palestinians for getting only 90 percent of the
territories back, not 100 percent; preparing them for getting only
a symbolic return of Palestinian refugees _ in the form of family
reunifications _ to pre-1967 Israel; and preparing them for having
their own Jerusalem _ which they can call by Jerusalem's Arabic
name, Al-Quds _ in Abu Dis, rather than in the old, eastern half of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat needs to find a way to take these Palestinian mantras _
Jerusalem, refugees, territory _ and redefine them in a way that
defuses them as political issues for the Israeli public,'' argues
Stephen Cohen of the Center for Middle East Peace. ``If he does
that, he can get 90 percent of the West Bank back, which, after all
these years of struggle, would be amazing. But Barak and the
Israeli people are going to have to be mature enough to understand
that these classic Palestinian mantras can't simply be thrown out
by Arafat, but must be reshaped in a way that Israelis and
Palestinians can both live with.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a test. This is the real deal. Completing it and
implementing it are going to be wrenching experiences for both
societies. Not doing so will be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
