<SLUG> BC-RED-CROSS-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF GROUPS FEAR AMERICAN WITHDRAWAL FROM RED CROSS FEDERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Concern is spreading among international relief
organizations that the American Red Cross may be on the verge of
withdrawing from the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies because the umbrella organization has not agreed
to immediately admit an Israeli contingent under a star of David
flag.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross, under its new president, Dr. Bernadine
Healy, who took office in July, has already withheld $5 million in
dues from the international federation, based in Geneva, which
relief experts say was a significant blow to the organization from
its largest member. The federation serves as a secretariat for 176
national Red Cross and Red Crescent societies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of American participation in the international
federation is expected to be raised at a national conference of the
American Red Cross from May 19 to 21. Several requests for comment
from the American Red Cross headquarters in Washington were not
answered Monday.
</P>
<P>
   American contributions of about $350,000 are also being withheld
from the International Committee of the Red Cross, an independent,
Swiss-based organization that works among civilians in battle areas
and visits prisoners of war, among other functions.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross and Red Crescent societies deal with disaster relief.
The two organizations, while sharing the general goals of one
humanitarian movement, are not related in any organizational way.
</P>
<P>
   Healy, a former director of the National Institutes of Health,
who replaced Elizabeth Dole as Red Cross president last year, gave
almost immediate priority to a campaign for membership for the
Magen David Adom, or Red Shield of David, an organization whose
emblem is a six-pointed star. Red Cross officials say that it was
the United States, not Israel, that pressed the case strenuously in
meetings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in Geneva, the International Committee, the
federation and representatives of governments reopened discussion
on the possibility of a neutral emblem that could serve as an
alternative for those countries _ not only Israel _ that did not
want to use the red cross or red crescent symbols. In the minds of
many, those symbols are linked with religious affiliation, although
the Red Cross argues that its symbol has no sectarian connotations
and is only the Swiss flag with colors reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lingering problem for decades,'' an aid official
said. Other nations have also asked to use their own symbols and
have been refused, he added.
</P>
<P>
   One of the neutral symbols suggested in recent years is a red
diamond, within the outline of which other symbols could be
incorporated. But the step would not be easy to take because the
1949 Geneva conventions would have to be rewritten and a special
international conference called. Only three symbols have ever been
recognized, the red cross, the crescent and a red lion and sun,
which was used briefly by Iran before the overthrow of Shah
Mohammed Riza Pahlevi.
</P>
<P>
   Healy criticized the inconclusive April meeting in Geneva and
has since renewed a demand for an immediate recognition of Israel's
Magen David Adom. A press release from the American Red Cross said
that the necessary diplomatic steps proposed to expand the use of
symbols would, in all likelihood, ``extend endlessly, with no
guaranteed solution for the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Healy's critics within the Red Cross movement, none of whom
would agree to be quoted, say that her hard line is related to
domestic American politics. Healy ran an abortive campaign for a
Senate seat from Ohio as a Republican in 1994, after her contract
at the National Institutes of Health was not renewed by President
Clinton, and her critics say she may be seeking to position herself
for another political race by making this a high-profile issue.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, relief organizations say that they have been
told that Healy will soon announce the withdrawal of the American
Red Cross from the international federation and the end of support
for the International Committee, and will ask her organization's
national convention in Columbus, Ohio, to endorse these moves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
