<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS02-COX     05-01 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Rational market' found to be not so rational
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investor psychology is getting scrutiny these days from the
business press as well as shrinks. They agree on one thing: The
``rational market'' isn't so rational after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A growing body of academic research _ in fields ranging from
psychiatry to anthropology _ explains market behavior in terms of
irrational urges,'' says Forbes (May 15). It cites findings by the
Journal of Psychology and Financial Markets, the first academic
journal devoted to investor psychology, that investors act ``more
like herds of agitated animals'' than rational individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes blames market madness in part on the increase in
individual investors and the relative ease of online trading, which
have made ``wild swings wilder and faster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For sensible investors,'' says Forbes, ``the upside of
widespread investor irrationality is the opportunities it presents
to capitalize on other people's missteps. The bad news: The chances
of your acting rationally are very slim.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Personal Finance (May) cites research that warns
against following your instincts because that undermines your
ability to invest wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors trade too actively, cling to their losers, are
underdiversified and buy stocks that grab their attention,''
according to University of California researchers Terrance Odean
and Brad Barber.
</P>
<P>
   They found that most investors are overconfident and
overestimate what they know and how good they are at investing _
and that it afflicts everybody, even psychologists. One problem
with online investing, they say, is that the computer gives
investors an illusion of control that builds overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   Wiring academia
</P>
<P>
   U.S. colleges and universities once relied on a prestigious name
or winning football team to attract the nation's best and
brightest. Now, says Yahoo Internet Life (May), ``undergraduates
are as interested in a college's Net sources as in its curriculum
or social life.''
</P>
<P>
   Academia has responded: 98 percent allow prospective students to
apply electronically, 68 percent offer Web-based registration, 56
percent offer high-speed access in all classrooms, 41 percent offer
some wireless access on campus, 35 percent provide public computer
equipment or labs in dormitories, and 11 percent even require that
students own computers.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech ranks 15th among the magazine list of 100 ``most
wired'' colleges. The No. 1 institution is Carnegie Mellon
University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   America's inner cities are not necessarily economic dead zones.
Inc. Magazine (May) identified 100 inner-city regions that
collectively provided close to 4,500 new jobs and generated revenue
of $12.2 million. (No, Atlanta wasn't among them.)
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (May 8) profiles Lawrence J. Ellison, chairman of
No. 2 software maker Oracle Corp. After playing second fiddle to
market leader Microsoft, the company has rebounded because the
Internet favors Oracle's software over Microsoft's, the magazine
says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
