<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-DOCTOR-ART-2     05-01 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-DOCTOR-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT IN THE MIDDLE OF A NASTY WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ When Dr. Hasan Baiyev was summoned to his
hospital in the Chechen town of Alkhan-Kala on Feb. 1, he quickly
learned that it was not for an ordinary case.
</P>
<P>
   As Russian troops tried to take the capital, Grozny, Chechen
rebels had begun on Jan. 31 to fight their way out. Now hundreds of
bloodied militants were waiting for treatment in Baiyev's village
southwest of Grozny. They included Shamil Basayev, the most
notorious of the Chechen warlords, who was maimed as he led his
fighters through a Russian minefield.
</P>
<P>
   After administering a local anesthetic, Baiyev, a surgeon,
amputated Basayev's right leg. And soon after that, the rebels
whisked their leader to safety in the Caucasian mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Baiyev's life has not been the same since. He said he was simply
carrying out the Hippocratic oath and that he has treated Russian
soldiers as well as Chechen fighters.
</P>
<P>
   But the operation made him a contentious figure in Russia. And
he soon decided that this would not be a bad time to learn about
medical care in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to recall that I was saving elderly civilians by
the thousands,'' he said in a telephone interview from Washington,
D.C. ``The only thing they remember is that I was the surgeon who
operated on Basayev.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Alkhan-Kala's residents had believed that they could
ride out the war in the separatist southern Russian region,
especially since the rebels had not made the small town a center of
their resistance. But Chechnya is also a place where people can get
into trouble by trying to avoid taking sides.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Baiyev grew up in Alkhan-Kala and was trained in dentistry and
facial surgery in the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk. He worked in a
hospital in Grozny but returned to his hometown in October to
restore an abandoned hospital. He had a small medical team,
including about 20 nurses, but he was the only surgeon in the town
of 20,000, including several thousand refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Baiyev had been harassed by both sides during the earlier war in
Chechnya. And this time, as Russian troops advanced toward the
Chechen lowlands, he initially decided to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents and relatives kept urging me to leave,'' he said.
``But the night before I was supposed to go, I walked through the
village and saw that many people were staying. They thought they
could live through it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Baiyev took his wife, three children, 86-year-old father and
75-year-old mother to safety in the neighboring Ingushetia region
and then returned to his hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the hospital staff nobody would pay us and that
everything they were doing was strictly voluntary,'' he said. ``My
plan was to stay despite the bombs and the shelling, to stay until
the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for the war to come to Alkhan-Kala. In
mid-October, the Russians moved to encircle Grozny and to trap
Basayev and his fighters. Alkhan-Kala was caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 civilians were wounded by a Russian mortar attack, much
of the hospital staff left. But Baiyev stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   There were also tense moments when a band of Wahabbis arrived in
the village. This group of militants, under the command of Arbi
Barayev, profess a strict version of Islam but have been widely
accused of kidnapping people for ransom. They accused Baiyev of
treating Russian soldiers, fired their weapons at the ceiling of
the hospital and threatened to shoot him.
</P>
<P>
   Baiyev's greatest test came, however, when the thousands of
militants tried to escape from the besieged Chechen capital. He
learned about it at 6 a.m. on Feb. 1, when he was summoned to his
hospital to treat more than 300 wounded fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They arrived in the morning,'' he recalled. ``It was news to
us. Nobody expected it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next two days, Baiyev ran a one-man emergency room,
operating without an anesthesiologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was alone and conducted more than 100 operations during the
first 24 hours, including 67 amputations and seven skull
surgeries,'' he said. ``It was very difficult. We were basically
out of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Basayev was the second patent. It was something of a reunion.
Baiyev had grown up in Alkhan-Kala with Basayev, whom he recalls as
a quiet child who liked to play chess and later moved to the
Chechen mountain town of Vedeno.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very modest and never stood out among the school
children,'' Baiyev said. ``He followed our national traditions and
was very respectful toward elders.''
</P>
<P>
   The young Basayev seems to bear scant resemblance to the bearded
commander who led a daring raid on Budyonnovsk, a town in southern
Russia, in 1995 during the first war in Chechnya, and then
spearheaded a rebel invasion of Dagestan, another neighbor of
Chechnya, last August, proclaiming that he would establish an
Islamic state in the region. That attack sparked the current war in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Basayev's roots in the town added a new twist to the story of
his escape from Grozny. The Russians say they lured the rebels into
a trap. A Russian intelligence agent, they say, promised the
militants safe passage out of Grozny in return for a bribe and then
directed them toward a minefield that was bracketed by Russian
machine-guns.
</P>
<P>
   But Baiyev said he believed that Basayev decided to try to
escape toward Alkhan-Kala because he knew the terrain there like
the back of his hand. Either way, the rebel leader paid a heavy
price.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As a phalanx of fighters blocked access to the operating room,
Basayev was brought in on a stretcher. His right foot had been torn
apart by a mine. His fingers were frostbitten because he had been
lying in the snow. He was also blind from the concussion effects of
the explosion, a condition the doctor thinks was probably
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   But Basayev was still conscious. The doctor decided to amputate
part of his right leg to minimize the risk of gangrene and used a
local anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked if it hurt,'' Baiyev recalled, ``He said, `Do your
business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Basayev was taken away by his men. Russian officials here say
their intelligence reports indicate that Basayev is now suffering
from gangrene and is being carried around on a stretcher by Russian
prisoners and kidnap victims. The Russians also say his role as a
rebel commander has diminished as a result of his condition. But
there is no way to confirm those reports.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For Baiyev, the situation in Alkhan-Kala soon went from bad to
worse. The Russians were hot on the rebels' trail, and the town was
in the way. His hospital was bombed, forcing him to move his
operating theater into his home.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, Russian soldiers entered the town. The rebel wounded
who remained there, Baiyev recalled, were taken away by a
pro-Moscow Chechen militia unit under the command of Bislan
Gantamirov, the former Grozny mayor.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the Russians came looking for the doctor, complaining to
him that he had helped the rebels. Later, with the help of the
villagers, Baiyev made his way to Ingushetia and later to Moscow,
where he lived in fear of detention. He finally decided to go to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on his experiences, Baiyev says he was threatened
by both sides for doing his duty as a doctor. He plans to return to
Chechnya, but for now is enjoying his study and relaxation in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a citizen of Chechnya, my tragedy has been to watch my
people suffer,'' he said. ``A hospital should be isolated from
combat operations. We were at the center of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
