A2732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MCI-02-COX     05-01 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta start-up, WorldCom enter $316 million deal with few
details
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Group Information Services Inc., a tiny Atlanta start-up, Monday
announced a contract to buy at least $316 million in services from
WorldCom, part of an ambitious plan to sell communications packages
nationwide this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the five-year deal _ involving a large-sounding dollar
figure for a company with only a handful of full-time employees and
no revenues at all _ was announced with a puzzling fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when such agreements are commonly trumpeted by
publicity-seeking chief executives, the chief executive of Group
Information Services declined to comment on the announcement. In
fact, Vice President Kalpana Finucan declined to name the company's
top officers, saying some, including the CEO, are still working for
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   And the company offered only the barest of details about its
business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Group Information Services will provide ``integrated voice mail
and e-mail,'' said Finucan. ``But the concept is proprietary and we
don't want to reveal too much just now.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement is real, said WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   The $37 billion-a-year Mississippi-based telecom giant confirmed
it has agreed to provide high-speed transmission and other services
to Group Information Services. It also confirmed the value of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But it hadn't agreed to talk about it, said WorldCom spokesman
Paul Adams. ``We do have a contract, we do have a relationship. But
that press release was not authorized by us.''
</P>
<P>
   The news release was placed on the Business Wire, which is used
to transmit corporate announcements to newspapers and analysts at
10 a.m. It was removed by day's end, after discussions between
WorldCom and Group Information Services, which said it had not
understood the behemoth's procedures for approval of news releases.
</P>
<P>
   But Group Information Services stands by its ambitions, despite
its status as a mostly ``virtual company,'' Finucan said. About 10
people are involved, she said. ``Some are full-time. Some, like
myself, will become full-time once the financing comes through.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is trying to raise nearly $10 million, but has no
venture funding to announce at this time, she said. Plans are to
put its marketing and research in Atlanta but corporate
headquarters could end up somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``In about 30 days, we hope to put out a release that tells more
of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
