<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2734 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MUTUAL-FUNDS-COX     05-01 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTUAL-FUNDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manager sees soft landing for economy
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Canakaris finds himself in unfamiliar territory: trailing
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   Canakaris, chief investment officer at Montag &AMP; Caldwell in
Atlanta, manages the Enterprise Growth fund for the Enterprise
Group fund family, also based in Atlanta. The ``A'' class of the
fund is down 4 percent so far this year, while the S&AMP;P 500 index is
off 0.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer haul, the fund has consistently topped the S&AMP;P
500 in total return. The ``A'' fund _ there are three classes _
topped the index in the one-, three-, five-, 10-, 15-, 20- and
25-year periods that ended Dec. 31, excluding the impact of the
fund's sales charge. After accounting for the sales charge, the
fund beat the S&AMP;P 500 in the five-, 10-, 20- and 25-year periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, year-to-date, we've gotten off to a slow start,''
said Canakaris. ``I think what is going to happen in the second
half of the year is that quality stocks are going to start to do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   He bases that expectation on the belief the Federal Reserve will
produce another soft landing for the U.S. economy and that earnings
growth will accelerate. He thinks the beneficiaries will be
companies with international exposure, because they will be helped
by economic growth outside the United States, as well as those with
mostly domestic sales that are able to take advantage of continued
expansion at home.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting stocks for the Enterprise Growth fund, Canakaris
looks for companies whose earnings are growing at least 10 percent
a year, and whose stocks are trading at about 20 percent below what
he and his colleagues at Montag &AMP; Caldwell think is a fair price.
Their calculation of a fair price is based on the present value of
future dividends _ if the company pays dividends _ plus the present
value of what the stock might sell for 10 years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   These are stocks Canakaris recently has bought for the fund:
</P>
<P>
   Beverage company Coca-Cola (ticker symbol KO).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've added to our Coke position because we see a significant
improvement in earnings growth in the second half of the year. The
company is very well-positioned to benefit from improvement in the
global economic expansion,'' he said. ``Next year we think they
could earn as much as $1.80 (a share).''
</P>
<P>
   Health care products maker Johnson &AMP; Johnson (JNJ).
</P>
<P>
   ``We added to Johnson &AMP; Johnson. They have this tremendous
breadth of product (and) strong marketing. We see very strong
earnings growth this year and next. It's very reasonably priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceuticals company Pfizer (PFE).
</P>
<P>
   ``Pfizer is just a very strong company,'' he said, suggesting
the proposed acquisition of Warner-Lambert (WLA) ``is going to make
it just more formidable.'' Canakaris expects annual earnings growth
of 25 percent after the deal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services provider Citigroup (C).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's selling at a very reasonable multiple, 17 times this
year's earnings,'' said Canakaris. Montag &AMP; Caldwell recently upped
its earnings estimate for Citigroup to $3.60 a share this year, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications equipment maker Lucent Technologies (LU).
</P>
<P>
   ``We added to Lucent,'' Canakaris said. ``They had a
disappointment in the fourth quarter, but this quarter they have
gotten back on track and are benefiting from all the interest in
telecommunications.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronics retailer Circuit City (CC).
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't positioned globally, but Circuit City is benefiting
from the transition from analog to digital in consumer products,''
said Canakaris. He estimated the transition represents a 10- to
15-year product cycle that is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Canakaris also has trimmed some of the fund's holdings. The
stake in chip maker Intel (INTC) was reduced as a result of its
price and valuation, freeing cash to buy Lucent Technologies,
Canakaris said.
</P>
<P>
   The MCI WorldCom (WCOM) holding was cut as well, in order in
invest in other stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty fully invested,'' explained Canakaris. ``We don't
have that much in cash. If we're going to be adding something, we
have to trim something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
