<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-INTERNET-AR     05-01 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-INTERNET-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCION OF AN INDONESIAN DYNASTY AIMS FOR A COMEBACK WITH A
CYBERCITY 
</HEADLINE>
 - 2TAKES-NYT  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Just south of a park called Dreamland on an
abandoned airfield surrounded by slums, Edward Soeryadjaya is
testing the Internet's powers of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   In a country dominated by corporate dynasties, Soeryadjaya is
famous as the scion who broke his family's bank and cost his family
the car company his father founded in 1957, Astra International.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Soeryadjaya (pronounced sir-ya-JAI-ah) has returned to the
corporate stage as a high-technology entrepreneur planning to build
a stable of dot-coms and turn Jakarta's old airport into
Indonesia's Silicon Valley. In the process, he wants not only to
resurrect a fallow property investment but also to prove at last
that he was an unwitting pawn of politics and to help restore his
family's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting my future at stake,'' he said in a recent
interview. ``I believe that information technology, as an enabler
for the Indonesian nation, is in line with the development of
technology in the world and has a very good future.''
</P>
<P>
   His vehicle is PT CyberCity Indonesia, a holding company with
what he calls a ``bag of goodies,'' which he hopes will attract
$76.5 million in new investments before listing by year-end. Inside
the bag are stakes in an Internet service, two Web portals, an
incubator for Net-related businesses, a multimedia academy and a
7.5-acre sliver of a 109-acre piece of overgrown airport that he
hopes to turn into a high-technology commercial and residential
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clicks and bricks,'' Soeryadjaya intoned in his sonorous
Indonesian drawl. He says he already has a heavy list of backers,
including the governments of Indonesia, Malaysia and Japan, as well
as Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of naysayers, however, many of whom point
to Soeryadjaya's reputation for financial misfortune. ``I'm always
skeptical about whatever Edward does,'' said Manggi T. Habir,
president of the credit-rating agency Pemeringkat Efek Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   While the Soeryadjayas' influence with Indonesia's new
government has spurred criticism, some skeptics wonder about
Soeryadjaya's high-technology connections. They question the
seriousness of a project that, despite claiming to have set up at
least five different ventures, has yet to establish a corporate Web
site. CyberCity, they say, is more about bailing out a $50 million
project Soeryadjaya was in charge of developing on the site of the
old Kemayoran domestic airport before the colossal failure of the
bank he ran, Bank Summa, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Soeryadjaya is not the only Asian tycoon to become a pioneer of
the new economy. Though brash unknowns have won many of America's
new fortunes, the high-technology start-up scene in Hong Kong, the
Philippines, Malaysia and Thailand is dominated by the rich and
powerful. Skeptics say it is a sign of how much buzz surrounds the
Internet; in Asia, as elsewhere, there is nothing like an Internet
play to give an old-economy stock a new shine. Others say it is a
symptom of economies in which wealth is still tightly concentrated
and local capital markets are developing too slowly to fuel the
speedy growth of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of entrepreneurs who want to start up but
don't have resources,'' said Vasant Chatikavanij, executive vice
president of Loxinfo, a Thai Internet service owned by his family's
conglomerate. ``They end up selling themselves cheap. They sell to
companies like us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia may seem an unlikely venue for dot-com mania. Most
bankers and economists will not even discuss its Internet
potential. This, after all, is a country whose government still
depends on the International Monetary Fund to make ends meet, where
a personal computer costs nearly twice the average annual income.
Only 4 of every 1,000 Indonesians use the Internet, according to
International Data Corp., compared with 14 of every 1,000 Asians
overall. Most people do not even have a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and Internet entrepreneurs like Soeryadjaya say such
statistics show the market's promise. Indonesia, the world's
fourth-most-populous nation, already has more Internet users than
Singapore, and millions of wealthy urban residents with money to
spend online. New and cheaper ways of connecting to the Internet,
like television set-top boxes and mobile phones, they say, will
quickly extend the Net to more of Indonesia's 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a large market coming out of the crisis that has
spending potential,'' said Jonathan Morris, 26, a Bostonian who
dropped out of the Harvard Business School a year and a half ago to
start Indonesia's most popular Web site, astaga.com.
</P>
<P>
   Soeryadjaya, 51, comes to the Internet world with more business
experience _ and, some say, more baggage. The eldest son of William
Soeryadjaya, a respected businessman who built Astra from a small
importer of diesel generators into a $2.4 billion automotive giant,
Edward Soeryadjaya started out as a salesman at an Astra unit. He
then ventured into finance, first with a bank in Germany and later
a finance company in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he bought a small Indonesian bank, renamed it Bank
Summa and expanded rapidly though the Summa Group. By 1991, Bank
Summa was one of the country's largest private banks, with about $1
billion in assets, most in the form of loans to Summa companies and
much of that for property investments.
</P>
<P>
   One such investment was the $50 million Jakarta International
Trade Fair Corp., a joint venture of Soeryadjaya's Griya Nusantara
Pratama, the Indonesian State Secretariat, Jakarta's city
government and a group of Japanese investors. The corporation was
to develop 109 acres of the sprawling old Kemayoran airport, which
had closed in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1990, Indonesia adopted a tight fiscal policy, and
Summa's world began to unravel. The property market tanked, and
Bank Summa was faced with $303 million in losses in 1991.
Soeryadjaya's father moved in to bail Summa out, removing his son
as chairman and pledging Astra shares against the bank's
obligations. The more he struggled to prop the bank up, the lower
Astra's share price sank and the deeper Bank Summa's hole grew. By
late 1992, the central bank closed Summa amid a depositor run. To
help meet the bank's $690 million in liabilities, the Soeryadjayas
relinquished virtually their entire 76 percent stake in Astra to
several businessmen close to President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   That is only half the story, according to a version of events
that Soeryadjaya said could be told only now that Suharto has
fallen. The government set him up, he said, by encouraging him to
lend, only to later impose restrictions and then remove government
pension funds from Bank Summa to precipitate its collapse. He said
his father would eventually spell out who was behind the intrigue
in a tell-all biography. ``I blame ourselves for being naive,''
Soeryadjaya said. ``We refused to be a crony.''
</P>
<P>
   Soeryadjaya suggested he was victimized because his first wife,
who died of cancer the year the family lost Astra, was the daughter
of President Sukarno, whom Suharto ousted in 1965. Astra had long
been uncharacteristically independent of the Suharto clan. Suharto
was reportedly less than appreciative when, in mid-1990 Bank Summa
built a network of banks for rural Muslim communities with a
powerful cleric named Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wahid is Indonesia's president, the Suhartos are fending
off prosecutors, and the Soeryadjayas are rebuilding. In 1998,
Edward Soeryadjaya was reinstated as a board member of Jakarta
International Trade Fair. Last December, his father was named
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
