<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-INTERNET-AR     05-01 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-INTERNET-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
JAKARTA, Indonesia: named chairman.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The family's comeback has forced Wahid to counter accusations
that the Soeryadjayas have become neocronies. Last month, the
president sold his stake in the Muslim finance company he set up
with Soeryadjaya in mid-1990 after it bought a stake in Mandiri
Inti Finance, a company Edward Soeryadjaya took control of last
January.
</P>
<P>
   Mandiri was trying to raise funds for a last-minute bid to buy
back the Soeryadjayas' stake in Astra _ it was on the block after
being seized from the indebted cronies who had bought it seven
years earlier _ before the government sold it to a Singapore-led
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Soeryadjaya denies trying to capitalize on his presidential
connections. ``If I were doing it, why didn't I do it before, when
we were fighting for our existence?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mandiri Inti Finance changed its name to Siwani
Trimitra and said it would start raising funds for CyberCity. But
most of Soeryadjaya's Internet deals have so far been conducted by
L&AMP;M Group Investments, a financially troubled engineering company
in Singapore, which Soeryadjaya's younger brother, Edwin, ended up
controlling after taking over a different Singapore company.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Soeryadjaya remains listed as L&AMP;M's deputy chairman and
his father is chairman; Edward Soeryadjaya became a member of the
board last year and, after slowly building up his stake in the
company, was named chief executive last month.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the tangled shareholdings and cross-shareholdings
that make Indonesian business so nebulous, L&AMP;M owns part of
CyberCity together with Jakarta International Trade Fair and
Soeryadjaya's own Griya Nusantara Pratama, which still owns part of
Jakarta International. Just how much of CyberCity each owns,
Soeryadjaya said, is ``now being arbitrarily decided.'' CyberCity,
in turn, owns only a portion of the five Internet-related ventures
it is involved in.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, L&AMP;M's stock has become a proxy on the project. It
rose 20 percent in November when L&AMP;M announced that MyWeb Inc.com,
an American set-top box maker, would take a 10 percent stake in
CyberCity and help build an Internet service in Indonesia, then
fell 8 percent when the deal fell apart a month later. Soon
afterward, when L&AMP;M said it was in talks to replace MyWeb with
Microsoft, the stock shot up more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   L&AMP;M's share price has drifted down about 28 percent this year,
tracking the decline of Asia's stock markets. But L&AMP;M has also been
dogged by concerns about whether partnerships will materialize. The
company has announced that Singapore Telecommunications' Internet
unit, SingNet, is considering a 30 percent stake in CyberCity, and
that Detecon Marketing Consulting, unit of Deutsche Telekom, will
buy 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, L&AMP;M said it had signed a memorandum of understanding
with SingTel to help develop CyberCity but gave no details. Detecon
said it was in talks but that no deal had yet been reached.
</P>
<P>
   In February, L&AMP;M finally signed a deal with Microsoft _ not to
take a stake in CyberCity but rather to help build a news and
information Web site in return for a share of revenues the site
generates. The site is scheduled to start this month. The only
CyberCity venture that appears to be up and running is the Jakarta
Multimedia Academy, which L&AMP;M established with Malaysian Technology
Development, a government-owned venture capital concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support CyberCity fully, but we're still waiting for
something to be realized,'' said Pandji Choesin, executive director
of the Indonesian Association of Internet Service Providers.
</P>
<P>
   Soeryadjaya wants to sell a 50 percent stake in CyberCity for
$26.5 million by June 28, when he plans to officially introduce it
at an Internet trade show at Kemayoran. He hopes to raise another
$50 million by the end of the year, despite the fact that there are
still no revenue projections for the group. ``From June 28 onward,
I trust that the price tag of our company will be in excess of $100
million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a big capital buildup might not be unusual for an Internet
start-up, but it would represent an especially neat turnaround for
Jakarta International Trade Fair's original airport investment.
</P>
<P>
   Property analysts say prices in Jakarta have fallen at least 50
percent the last 10 years, though with no sales anywhere in two
years it is hard to tell. Soeryadjaya said CyberCity was valuing
its 7.5-acre property at $5 million, a price that would make
Jakarta International's entire 109-acre spread at Kemayoran worth
around $73 million _ a 46 percent paper profit.
</P>
<P>
   Soeryadjaya rejects criticism that his high-technology vision is
a property deal in disguise, though he does not deny that CyberCity
could be good for the local real estate market. ``We know we have
to push it as a cyber initiative because that's where most of the
funds are basing their decisions,'' he said. ``We're not cheating
anybody.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
