A2740 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-01 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AND IN THIS CORNER, BIG PORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETHTOWN, N.C. _ Today we're going to take a break from the
unending excitement of the presidential race to talk about hog
lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial livestock farming is probably not a big problem in
your neighborhood, but really, people, how can you resist a
controversy in which the villain is called Big Pork, and the
possible repercussions include flesh-eating algae? If hog farming
weren't a political issue, it would be a TV movie in sweeps month.
</P>
<P>
   It's already played a role in today's North Carolina
gubernatorial primary. ``If I'm elected governor we're going to end
hog lagoons,'' vowed Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker in a famous TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hog lagoons'' sound like pigs in bathing suits with mermaid
tails, swimming around a la Esther Williams. Actually lagoon is a
fancy term for a humongous pit of manure. It's a critical element
in the brave new world of pork production, in which hogs are often
owned by the packers but raised by contractors in a system that
bears a striking resemblance to a fast-food franchise. One of the
great features of the system is that while the big guys own the
hogs, the little contractors own the waste. It drains into lagoons,
and if one of them ruptures or overflows or leaks, do not go
looking to the packer for restitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different smells to it. One day it might smell like
ammonia. Another day it might have an almost burning-type smell
that hurts your nose,'' said Karen Priest, a North Carolina
homeowner who woke up one morning and discovered that 7,300 hogs
and two lagoons had moved in next door.
</P>
<P>
   In many places you can't put up a tree house without somebody
seeking an injunction. But in North Carolina, thanks to the
tireless efforts of a former state senator named Wendell Murphy,
monster hog farms had free right-of-way into the countryside. By a
remarkable coincidence, Murphy happened to be a major hog producer
himself, as well as a great pal and major contributor to Jim Hunt,
the outgoing governor.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to its hospitable attitude, over the last decade North
Carolina has been inundated with oversized hog farms and their
lagoons, along with the largest meat-packing plant in the world.
They're crammed into the eastern section of the state, an area that
is made up in large part of wetlands and flood plains.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put the hog lagoons in the flood plains. People, is that
great planning or what?
</P>
<P>
   Nitrogen from animal wastes seems responsible for the sudden
appearance of a flesh-eating algae known as Pfiesteria in state
waters. During one particularly grisly period in the mid-'90s,
North Carolinians were discovering piles of fish, laden with sores
and gasping for breath, on the riverbanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see the scientific evidence that says it's swine
waste that creates this problem,'' said Al Tank of the National
Pork Producers Council. There are, of course, other potential
culprits. But except for private golf courses, you'd be hard
pressed to name any that have as little redeeming social value.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the smell and the environmental impact, the big farms
are driving small hog producers out of business. Pork prices for
the consumer aren't dropping. The hogs can't be enjoying their
lives _ ``Where is Kim Basinger when we need her?'' asked Priest.
To top it all off, the jobs created at the contract farms and
meat-packing plants are so lousy that even residents of a poor,
rural area won't take them.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that the candidates for governor would be leaping
over each other to take on this issue. They're all middle-aged
lawyers, so interchangeable that their own mothers might be hard
pressed to cull one from the herd, and this pig thing is definitely
the most interesting aspect to the race. But the two Democrats have
moved on to the more traditional topics of education and character
assassination. The Republicans have kept their distance altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the only thing to do is go national. Next time Al Gore or
George Bush comes to your town, ask him what he'd do to crack down
on hog lagoons. One of them might have an answer, and at least it
might liven things up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
