r e BC-PALIN-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-01 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALIN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALIN DOES PAPA, OR THE OLD PYTHON AND THE SEA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Wed., May 3) 
Our rating: 2{ stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Palin's 1995 novel, ``Hemingway's Chair,'' was a
whimsical story of a timid Brit postman who struggled, mightily, to
attain the level of machismo of his favorite author, Ernest
Hemingway. In ``Michael Palin's Hemingway Adventure,'' the former
Monty Python trouper says he relates to the author's wanderlust;
Papa's works appeal to him because they suggest, ``If you were bold
and fearless, (you) could (live in that) world, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Palin, like his novel's protagonist, ultimately
seems more at home in a comfy recliner than a schooner's deck chair
battling a marlin at the business end of a fishing pole. Palin,
perhaps the most versatile and certainly the most normal-seeming of
the Pythons, makes for a most genial host throughout all his
perambulations, so you certainly enjoy his company.
</P>
<P>
   Over four one-hour episodes, ``Hemingway Adventure'' treks to
places either made famous by Hemingway through his writings, or
places where he spent significant amounts of time, or simply
visited. Sometimes, as when Palin explores the sites of two plane
crashes the writer survived in Uganda, the visit's intent is to
contribute to the understanding of Hemingway's biography; other
times, it's simply to drink in the local flavor or see how the man
left his mark or how he might possibly have spent his time.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the series has a more specious premise than Palin's
previous travel excursions, ``Around the World in 80 Days,'' ``Full
Circle'' and ``Pole to Pole,'' which at least had a built-in
structure and internal logic to propel them. This is a random,
peripatetic trek that brings Palin to different points in America
in three different episodes, including a Montana dude ranch that
can't help but seem pointless, and to Africa twice. Cuba and Spain
also figure prominently in Palin's perambulations.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy who ostensibly wants to understand Hemingway better,
Palin can be awfully bull-headed when it comes to divining
bullfighting's appeal, for one thing. An unabashed animal-rights
activist, he persistently asks hunters and matadors why they do
what they do and whether they feel bad doing it. The gamesmen might
just as reasonably ask him, ``Don't you feel a little guilty
getting paid so well just to take a vacation?'' It's simply what
both parties do; it's part of their enculturation; it's in their
blood. (In the TV series, Palin never succeeds when he joins the
sportsmen, as all of his hunting and fishing expeditions end in
abject failure; the companion book suggests that that may not have
been completely true.)
</P>
<P>
   One certainly wishes that Palin's pauses for comic frippery were
more inspired. In Africa, he offers a weak fashion show of
Serengeti finery and riffs mildly on bathroom accouterments; in
Venice, he trots out, to little effect, the Gumby character from
his Python days; in Cuba, he pretends, half-heartedly, to drink too
much and, more embarrassingly, fashions a series of mock scenes in
which he tries to contact Fidel Castro, with a particularly lame
pay-off.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game, he does hit upon an inspired comic
observation: Many of the places Hemingway either wrote about or
called home have become gaudy tourist traps that no doubt would
have sent him screaming from the place in search of a refuge with
more quietude and, certainly, less amateurish drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Hemingway lookalike contest in Key West; no one is
allowed to touch Papa's possessions in communist Cuba, and, of
course, running with the bulls in Pamplona has become a rite of
manhood for all manner of privileged college drunks who enjoy
taking leave of their senses.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a thought that, despite the potential for comedy, goes
relatively undeveloped. Which seems to be the overriding impression
``Michael Palin's Hemingway Adventure'' leaves the viewer: After
butting heads with bulls in Spain and closing down bars in Key West
and Cuba, the show is a little too fuzzy-headed to posit a coherent
point. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Michael Palin's Hemingway Adventure.'' &QL; 
What: Global travelogue hosted by the former Python, inspired by
the life of the author. &QL; 
Where: KCET. &QL; 
When: 9 to 11 p.m. tonight and May 10. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
