   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ Sheriff's deputies who want extra pay
for working overtime may instead have to settle for paid days off,
the Supreme Court says in ruling that local governments can
compensate employees as they see fit. In another case, a sharply
divided court overturns part of the conviction of a Texas child
molester, saying state prosecutors relied on improper testimony to
secure the guilty verdict. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SEARCH (Washington) _ The U.S. Supreme Court agrees to
decide whether police can stop people from going into their homes
while the officers attempt to get a warrant to search the premises.
Illinois courts have said blocking the entrance into a person's
home violates the constitutional ban on unreasonable searches and
seizures. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   AARP-HOUSING (Washington) _ An overwhelming majority of older
Americans want to remain in their own homes as long as possible,
and many are taking steps to make their homes easier to live in
during old age, an AARP survey shows. But more than one-third said
they could not afford such modifications or could not do them by
themselves. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-TERRORISM (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright reports that the number of terrorist acts from 1998 to
1999 increased by more than 40 percent but total deaths due to
terrorism decreased. The State Department releases its annual
report on global terrorism, maintaining the classifications of
Cuba, Iran, Iraq, Libya, North Korea, Sudan and Syria as state
sponsors of terrorism. By AUSTIN ZALKIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
