<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SCANDALS-(1400)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT INFORMATION SPIN IN JAPAN CREATES DEBATE ON
ACCOUNTABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ When his superiors discovered that an army colonel had
invited civilian friends to an official firing range recently to
have fun shooting guns, they hushed the matter up quickly, saying a
scandal might cause the public to lose trust in the military.
</P>
<P>
   When the director of an orphanage in Kyoto recently found
evidence of child abuse by a longtime employee, he concealed the
crime for nearly a year, explaining later that he had kept silent
``out of consideration'' for the worker's future prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the double-barreled police scandal in the city of
Niigata that was front-page news throughout Japan for weeks
recently. A senior national police official, who was sent to the
town in mid-January to carry out a scheduled national inspection of
the local police department, instead repaired with the Niigata
police chief to a nearby spa for drinks and games of mah-jongg.
</P>
<P>
   Their partying came to light because on that same day, the
Niigata police were dealing with their biggest case in years _ the
discovery of a kidnapped girl who had been missing for nine years _
and questions were raised about why the chief was not on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently to enhance their crime-fighting image, the police
also claimed to have found the girl, but it turned out that she had
been discovered by social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the affair before Parliament, Keizo Obuchi, who was
then the prime minister, shocked many people by saying he felt that
the inspector had merely been unlucky to have been revealed
shirking his duties because of all of the attention suddenly cast
upon Niigata, a normally sleepy city of a half-million inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's comments, and the widespread criticism that followed
them, have fueled a mushrooming debate over what many see as a
crisis of public accountability in Japan. A spate of ill-concealed
scandals has cast a pall over the government and other public
institutions like the police.
</P>
<P>
   The debate had its biggest public airing over Obuchi's own
collapse from a stroke early in April. His condition was hidden
from the public for 22 hours by a government that went on to
dissemble about events surrounding the prime minister's health for
at least two more days.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after his late-night hospitalization, reporters
were told that he was working normally in his residence. The next
evening, the public was told that the prime minister had been
hospitalized for exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Only the day after that, when succession politics had already
been worked out in secret, was it disclosed that Obuchi had
suffered an incapacitating stroke. Bit by bit it emerged that Mikio
Aoki, the caretaker leader who filled the vacuum until a new prime
minister took office, had stated falsely that Obuchi had been
conscious throughout the day of his stroke.
</P>
<P>
   That statement was ostensibly made to lend credibility to Aoki's
claim to have been asked by Obuchi to hold the reins of power on
his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial writers, members of civic groups and experts in
government say that the ham-fisted instances of official dishonesty
in cases like these are eroding the once high level of faith of
ordinary people in public institutions. And they say that this kind
of behavior comes from a bankrupt ethical culture that typically
values appearances far more than the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent national poll in the leading daily newspaper Asahi
Shimbun, for example, 60 percent of respondents said they
distrusted the police. According to the newspaper, in previous
polls, as recently as 1998, no fewer than 69 percent of those who
responded said they had faith in the police.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor of the Parliament in mid-April, the leader of the
opposition, Yukio Hatoyama, drew a direct link between the handling
of the Obuchi's stroke and other recent scandals. The prime
minister's health crisis, he said, had been handled ``without
transparency, with secretive discussions and a mass of
falsifications, and the same could be said of the police
scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many Japanese, the Obuchi affair seemed like yet another
example of the murky way in which power has long been wielded in
this country, contributing to widespread feelings of powerlessness
and apathy about politics.
</P>
<P>
   A venerable expression here about the attitude that governors
should hold toward the governed is not far off the mark, even in
the Internet age. ``We should not inform the people,'' the saying
goes. ``They must depend upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   The most extreme example of this approach involves the death
penalty. A family of a prisoner on death row, for example, is
notified of the execution only after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Another telling sign of how prevalent such attitudes toward
information and public service remains is that the Japanese
language lacks a word to express neatly the idea of accountability.
When the subject comes up here, the English word is most often used
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Even if apathy is prevalent here, a number of commentators have
begun to denounce the culture of concealment and opacity, which
they say is dangerously corrosive to this country's democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an attitude that we don't have to divulge
information,'' Manabu Hasegawa, a journalist and author of a 1993
book, ``The Illness and Death of Politicians,'' said in an
interview. ``A society that preserves the ideal of concealing
information is a society that has distorted democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Common explanations of the way even seemingly innocuous
information is closely held by politicians, corporations and groups
of ordinary people often focus on Japan's insular, so-called mura,
or village culture, which developed over centuries of rural
near-isolation.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to these theories, is a society built from
tightly-knit groups, in which decisions are made by consensus,
where authority is rarely questioned, and where a premium is placed
not on openness, but on avoiding shame or embarrassment for the
group.  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When problems do surface, the preferred solution is typically
ritualized apology, resignation and, in extreme cases, suicide.
Forthrightly dealing with the facts of the wrongdoing is typically
avoided. The Niigata police, for example, finally apologizing for
lying about their discovery of the missing girl, contended that
they were seeking to avoid creating a nuisance for the social
service workers who found her.
</P>
<P>
   Hisatake Kato, a professor of ethics at Kyoto University, cited
the recent nuclear accident in Japan as another example of this
type of approach, contending that everyone knew the proper
procedures were not being followed but remained silent. In the
United States, he said, ``In the case of the Three Mile Island
accident, whistle-blowing helped prevent a far worse disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The dangerous procedures only came to light after an
uncontrolled nuclear chain reaction broke out at the plant in
question, in Tokaimura, last October, killing one worker, and
contaminating hundreds of others in the town with dangerous levels
of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, even if there is some kind of misconduct in an
organization that you belong to, what you are supposed to do in
this culture is avoid leaking the information to the outside,''
said Kato. ``That is what is considered public morality in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   To back up his contention, Kato cited his own research in which
he interviewed scores of workers in downtown Tokyo, asking them if
they would disclose serious wrongdoing in their company if they
came across evidence of it. Ninety-nine percent said no.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply held attitudes like these perhaps explain why, despite
the protests by journalists, there was relatively little popular
outcry following the Government's clearly deceptive handling of the
news of Obuchi's stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of a freedom of information act last spring modeled
on similar laws in the United States has the potential of
revolutionizing people's access to official information in Japan.
But because of the relative lack of public pressure, activists who
helped bring about the law's passage say it's impact has so far
been small.
</P>
<P>
   ``This society has a very low interest in what the Government is
doing,'' said Shigeki Okutsu, director of the Information
Clearinghouse, a group that pushed for the law. ``But also, the
government has very little regard for what people think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
