<HEADLINE>
RADIO SITE OF THE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Radio A Go-Go!'': Host Hal Lifson offers an aural scrapbook of
the '60s, incorporating B-sides, album tracks, rarities, original
commercials and guests such as session drummer Hal Blaine and the
Ventures. A tie-dyed-in-the-wool '60s enthusiast, Lifson's delight
and knowledge of the era shines through. &QL; 
Where: KRLA-AM (1110). &QL; 
When: 7 p.m. Saturdays and 10 p.m. Sundays. &QL; 
Typical segment: ``Alone Again Or,''Love; ``A Mexican Shuffle,''
Herb Alpert &AMP; the Tijuana Brass; ``Jennifer Eccles,'' Hollies;
``Okolona River Bottom Band,'' Bobbie Gentry; ``Stone Free,'' Jimi
Hendrix. &QL; 
Quote: ``A lot of this stuff never made it onto radio in the first
place but it's still great music. Sixties music and culture will
always be ultra-hip.'' &QL; 
Off the air: Lifson doubles as an entertainment manager and
publicist whose clients include Nancy Sinatra. In fact, the singer
of the 1966 chart-topper ``These Boots Are Made for Walkin'''
recently did a concert at the El Rey Theatre to promote ``Radio A
Go-Go!'' which incidentally was just named the city's best oldies
show by New Times. &QL; 
Background: Raised in Encino in the '60s with transistor radio to
ear, Lifson hosted a '60s show at Berkeley's KALX in the early
'80s. He later worked in advertising which is where he realized
'60s culture would always be influential. He launched ``Radio A
Go-Go!'' last year on Glendale's KIEV-AM (870), moving to KRLA in
January. &QL; 
Taking a stand: As more and more oldies outlets add tracks from the
'70s, Lifson won't budge from his '60s playlist. &QL; 
You'll like this if... You like Mega 100, KRTH-FM (101.1). &QL;
</P>
