u i BC-TURKEY-ENVOY-NYT &LR;      05-01 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-ENVOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 4-YEAR ASSIGNMENT: LEAD TURKEY INTO THE EUROPEAN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ On the wall behind Ambassador Volkan Vural's
desk at the Turkish mission here is a reproduction of a 1923 Time
magazine cover featuring Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, who forged modern
Turkey out of the wreckage of the Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Vural is scheduled to return to Ankara to take up a
new post that presents a challenge almost as daunting. His job will
be to convince the European Union that Turkey merits membership and
to convince his countrymen that joining the club is worth the
painful admission price.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a tough job,'' said Vural, who will need his
closeness to Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit and a combination of
persistence and patience. ``We have to convince Parliament, the
ministers and the political parties to support the process of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years at the United Nations and three years as
ambassador to Germany, Vural has developed personal relationships
with many of the European diplomats who will be involved in the
membership negotiations. But in an interview, he was cautious in
his optimism and would not make promises about timing, saying only
that the goal is be ready for formal talks by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Even the timing on his new job is uncertain. While Vural has
been traveling back and forth to Ankara in recent weeks to discuss
European Union issues, the position of secretary-general for EU
affairs has not yet been created formally by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Turkey's enthusiasm for membership is at an all-time
high. After European leaders agreed in December to let Turkey
become a candidate for full membership, a poll for NTV, a Turkish
television network, found that two out of three Turks favored
joining and only one in six opposed it, the same number that had no
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But Vural, 58, a former journalist and director of Turkey's
state-owned radio and television network, is well aware that public
opinion can change and support may ebb as Turkey confronts the
political and economic changes required to conform to EU standards.
</P>
<P>
   Membership offers tantalizing prospects for prosperity and
economic stability, but the costs will be high. For instance, 45
percent of Turkey's workforce is engaged in farming, a number that
must be slashed by half or more to be competitive. Overall economic
growth, which surged last year, is expected to decline this year as
the country battles double-digit inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the often-fractious Parliament will have to completely
overhaul half of the country's laws and regulations to mesh with
the EU in areas ranging from strengthening environmental rules to
abolishing restrictions on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The primary obstacles are not economic, according to European
diplomats, but instead Turkey's wobbly democracy and the treatment
of its Kurdish population. European leaders are troubled by the
influence of Turkey's military in government and the army-backed
crackdowns on Kurdish and Islamic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging room for improvements, some Turkish leaders
complain that EU demands threaten to interfere with internal
matters that are vital to national security.
</P>
<P>
   They also argue that the membership bar is higher for Turkey
than for Eastern European countries that may be less prepared.
Though Turkey's membership application has been pending since 1987,
Poland, Slovakia and other countries that applied more recently
have been moved ahead of it in line.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference on American-Turkish relations in Washington last
month, Turkish officials and business leaders were generally upbeat
about prospects for membership. But they expressed concern that,
even if Turkey meets the EU's goals, membership might remain
outside its grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Turkey does appears to be not enough,'' Ilter Turan,
the president of Istanbul's Bilgi University, said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vural said signs are promising that Turkey will be ready
to open formal membership negotiations within four years and that
ultimately it will join the EU.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound very optimistic, but we have the desire and the
political will to do it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
