<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2751 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-JEWS-NYT &LR;      05-01 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-JEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST JEWISH DEFENDANT IN IRANIAN SPY CASE SHOWN IN TV CONFESSION
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran _ The first of 13 Jewish men who are accused of
espionage went on trial Monday, and Iranian authorities displayed
him on television admitting that he had spied for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The government had adamantly refused to allow family members,
human rights groups or the public to witness the opening of the
politically charged trials of the 13, who are to be tried, one by
one, in coming weeks, on vague charges of spying.
</P>
<P>
   In the public confession, broadcast on Iran's state-run
television as part of the main evening news, the defendant, Hamid
Tefileen, 31, told an interviewer that he was part of a network of
spies who were trained in Israel ``to get information from
Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   Tefileen, described by his family as a simple clerk in his
father's shoe store, was dressed in prison garb decorated with tiny
drawings of the scales of justice during the brief
question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am charged with being a spy for Israel,'' said the
relaxed-looking defendant, who was sandwiched between two
interviewers in a room that appeared to be in the provincial
courthouse here. ``I admit to that charge.''
</P>
<P>
   His public confession was apparently made without his attorney
present. Broadcast just hours after court officials had once again
insisted that the trial of the Jews must be closed for national
security reasons, it did little to convince the foreign envoys who
were in Shiraz to see if the Jews receive a fair trial from a court
system dominated by hard-liners hostile to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is, it's a setup,'' said Vicken Koundakjian,
first secretary in the Canadian embassy in Tehran and one of five
diplomatic observers who had appealed to the judge in the case for
permission to meet with the defendants. ``He's a fall guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision two weeks ago to conduct the espionage
trial behind closed doors had drawn intense criticism from human
rights groups and diplomats, who argued that only an open
proceeding could assure that the defendants were not bullied or
persecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe a TV confession,'' said Elahe Hicks, a
representative of Human Rights Watch in New York, who is in Shiraz
to monitor the trial. ``It's a violation of detainees' rights. If
they wanted to show him, they should have allowed a representative
of the Jewish community, or diplomats or even me, to attend the
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammad Khatami, the leader of a broad reformist
movement that hopes to depoliticize the conservative judiciary, had
pledged that the trial would be conducted according to the rule of
law and human rights. But Khatami does not control either the
judiciary or the state broadcasting system.
</P>
<P>
   Both institutions are under the control of Iran's supreme
leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who is chosen by the senior Muslim
clergy and is the paramount political and religious authority in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Both are also dominated by conservatives, who have recently
mounted a full-scale assault on Khatami's reformist supporters,
closing 16 of their publications, jailing their leaders as
un-Islamic and accusing them of being foreign agents.
</P>
<P>
   Several hard-line clerics and judges have already labeled the
accused Shiraz Jews as Zionist spies. Local court officials,
pressed by reporters and diplomats to justify the charges against
the 13 men, have also maintained that some of the defendants had
confessed during interrogations to being spies for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers said that any such admissions were not valid
because none of the defendants were represented by counsel until a
few weeks ago. They said the only evidence against them are the
transcripts of their interrogations, which were conducted by the
trial judge who acts as both prosecutor and judge under Iran's
legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants _ part-time Hebrew teachers, shop assistants, an
18-year-old high school student and a professor of English _ are
accused of operating a spy network for Israel. If convicted, they
could be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawyers said that several of the defendants have secretly
visited relatives in Israel, but none had access to classified
information or passed any state secrets, as required for a
conviction on espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
   Tefileen spent about four hours with the Revolutionary Court
judge on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's hearing, Hussein Ali Amiri, the head of the court
system in Shiraz, the provincial capital, told reporters that
Tefileen had admitted in court that he had ``connections with the
Mossad,'' the Israeli secret service, and had passed ``confidential
information'' to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Amiri said that for reasons of national security, he could not
describe the nature of the information that Tefileen is supposed to
have turned over. Some Iranian Muslims, he added, provided the
secrets to the Jews and some of them have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he could not explain why those Muslims, who have
never been named by the authorities or seen in court, were released
on bail months ago.
</P>
<P>
   None of the defendants work in positions that would give them
access to state secrets, their families have said. Tefileen's
younger brother, Omid, described him as ``a regular guy.'' Both
work in their father's shoe store, he said. Omid Tefileen is also
charged in the case, but he is one of three defendants who is free
on bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of cases where spies are ordinary people,''
responded Amiri, when asked how a shoe salesman could run an
espionage scheme. ``In all the spy stories you read, the spies are
just ordinary people.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which was set to begin three weeks ago but was
postponed until Monday to give the defense more time to prepare, is
taking place during a wider political conflict between reformers
backing Khatami and conservatives who are using the courts to
undermine and persecute his liberal supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, hostility toward Israel is one of the litmus tests
of loyalty toward the Islamic system in Iran. With many in their
own ranks facing charges of insulting Islam, neither the president
nor his supporters have been willing to interfere in a high-profile
case that involves alleged spying for Iran's archenemy.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has denied any connection with the men, and their
families have said the charges are false and could only be the
result of a misunderstanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
