<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BOYCOTT-COX     05-01 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYCOTT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boycotts have spotty history of success
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Holmes had to go to Columbia for business, but other than a
night's stay in a hotel and breakfast, he kept his money in his
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many times when the director of the Southern
Center for Studies in Public Policy at Clark Atlanta University has
driven by Texaco gas stations and Shoney's restaurants, targets of
past boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar is by far the most effective weapon folks have,''
said Holmes, who is also a state representative.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, high-profile boycotts _ or threats of boycotts
_ have focused attention on a weapon long used by labor unions and
civil rights activists to press for change.
</P>
<P>
   In April, former and current African-American employees called
for a national boycott of Atlanta-based Cola-Cola, which is the
defendant in a racial discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the NAACP is leading a boycott of the state's
tourism industry in an attempt to pressure legislators to remove a
Confederate flag from atop the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina flag flap reignited debate about Georgia's
state flag and its representation of the Confederate battle emblem.
A call for a boycott here is on hold to give the state Legislature
time to act. A tourism official estimates a boycott could cost the
state $100 million in convention and tourist business.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Putnam, founder of the Institute for Consumer
Responsibility in Seattle and a boycott expert, estimates that as
many as 200 boycotts are in progress in the country at any given
time, up from about 50 at a time 15 years ago. Many will fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many boycotts are more symbolic than real,'' said Leon Fink, a
labor professor at the University of North Carolina. ``Sometimes
they're public relations weapons for larger campaigns for a
particular cause. Only in rare cases does it substantially hurt the
company or merchant.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, boycotts are increasingly popular because they can
work. But they are hard to organize and sustain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can stand out on a corner and call for a boycott,''
said Monroe Friedman, author of a book on boycotts and an Eastern
Michigan University professor. ``It's another thing to organize and
implement one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some have clearly been successful, others have clearly
been unsuccessful, and there is a wide range that falls in
between,'' said Friedman, citing the failure of the National
Organization for Women's boycott threats against states that didn't
ratify the Equal Rights Amendment. A successful boycot must appeal
to consumers emotionally and have a clear message and goal, said
Friedman. It also helps to have the support of a well-known
organization. Widely recognized boycotts helped end apartheid in
South Africa, unionize California grape workers in the 1960s and
launch the civil rights movement in Montgomery in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO claims its boycott of Adolph Coors Co. over labor
issues caused Coors' Colorado market share to fall from 47 percent
in 1977 to about 22 percent in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Coors sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know sales were affected, but we can't quantify it,'' said
Joe Fuentes, a company spokesman. Coors' competitors stepped up
advertising at the time. ``We don't know if it was the boycott or
the beer wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the economic effectiveness of a boycott often is
guesswork, and target companies may look for any other explanation
rather than admit boycotts can work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations will tell you that changing their policy had
nothing to do with the boycott,'' said Putnam. ``That's pretty
common, because once you acknowledge the boycott has been
effective, then you make yourself a target for future boycotts.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman refers to boycotts such as the South Carolina campaign
_ targeting the tourist industry to force government to act _ as
``surrogate'' boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory, of course, is that you put pressure on the
surrogate _ businesses _ who will in turn put pressure on the
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, ``the business community forced the government
to change because they were losing market and losing money,''
Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Arizona was the target of a tourism boycott
after the state refused to recognize the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr. holiday. ``The impact was enormous,'' said Brent DeRaad,
spokesman for the Greater Phoenix Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically it was across the board _ not just African-American
groups but groups of all different backgrounds that had been
looking at Arizona decided not to come,'' said DeRaad.
</P>
<P>
   DeRaad estimates the boycott had an economic impact of $189.6
million and resulted in the loss of 170 meetings and conventions
between 1987 and 1992. The biggest blow was the loss of the 1993
Super Bowl. Arizona voters approved a King holiday in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, losses to the state's $14.6 billion tourism
industry already are being estimated at $6 million to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly feel like the boycott has had an impact on the
entire island,'' said Gary Sims, manager of the Holiday Inn
Oceanfront in Hilton Head.
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, at least 20 conventions and events _ with an
economic impact of $3.3 million _ have been canceled since the
boycott started last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have we lost booked business, but you can't even
measure how many meetings and business we've lost because people
won't even consider coming to South Carolina,'' said Amy Ballenger,
a spokeswoman for the Charleston Area Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, flag opponents and business leaders hope the flag
will be changed by the next Legislature, forestalling a threatened
boycott of the state's $18 billion tourism industry. South
Carolina's Legislature is considering a measure to remove its
Confederate flag. Such quick response is more typical of boycotts
now.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam estimated that in 1984 the average boycott needed seven
to 10 years to succeed. ``Most proactive companies are not going to
wait around until they actually start losing money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Georgia Black Chamber of Commerce urged a boycott
against Thomasville-based Flowers Industries because Chief
Executive Amos McMullian was on the board of the Southeastern Legal
Foundation. The conservative foundation had sued to overturn the
city of Atlanta's minority contracting program.
</P>
<P>
   McMullian immediately resigned from the board and said the
company would no longer make donations to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for quick response is that a boycott, especially a
long one, can tarnish a target's image.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, ``there are lingering perceptions out there that
only time will correct,'' said DeRaad. This summer, the National
Association of Black Journalists will host its annual convention in
Phoenix, which DeRaad considers a ``big coup.''
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, Ballenger worries that no matter the outcome,
many consumers will view South Carolina ``as a state full of
racists, when that isn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia tourism officials don't want that to happen here.
Already, there have been calls from concerned convention planners.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Allen Rubin, president of the 800-member
Society for Social Work and Research, spent several days on the
phone trying to get a status report on a boycott of Georgia because
the group planned to hold its annual meeting here in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had a boycott been called, we were going to pull out of the
meeting because we support the cause,'' said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau is among
organizations working to change the flag.
</P>
<P>
   A boycott would ``have a very direct impact over the next couple
of years of potentially $100 million,'' said Bill Howard, vice
president of tourism and public relations. ``But future bookings
and the impact in terms of Atlanta's image and Georgia's image
globally will probably have far more serious consequences than that
of $100 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
