u f BC-FOOL-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      05-01 0250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOL-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE EXECUTIVE TO BECOME CHIEF OF MOTLEY FOOL  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Motley Fool is expected to announce Tuesday that C. Patrick
Garner, a Coca-Cola Co. executive, will become its new chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, 52, was most recently president of Coca-Cola's Southeast
and West Asia division and has spent three decades at the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat comes with a lot of operating experience, brand experience
and tremendous intellectual curiosity,'' said Tom Gardner, a
founder of the Motley Fool. He noted that it had recently added
several experienced executives to its management team.
</P>
<P>
   Created as a newsletter in 1993, the Motley Fool has developed
into a popular personal finance site on the Internet. It features
irreverent stock commentary by Gardner and his brother, David, and
lively participation from the site's thousands of daily users. The
company, which is based in Alexandria, Va., has about 320 employees
and has sites in Britain and Germany. It does not disclose its
annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   While the company has no immediate plans to go public, it
expects to do so at some point, Tom Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardner brothers will continue to serve as co-chairmen of
the company, focusing on strategy and extending the Fool brand in
other countries and venues. ``Tom and David are really the
ambassadors of this business,'' Garner said. Erik Rydholm, who also
helped found the business, will continue to oversee its operations
and production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
