<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-CRIME02-COX     05-01 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CRIME02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE TO UNVEIL ANTI-CRIME PACKAGE IN ATLANTA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore will unveil a comprehensive
anti-crime package in an Atlanta address Tuesday, including $1.3
billion in spending for new police officers and crime-fighting
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will propose that the federal government provide funds to
help local communities hire 50,000 new police officers, building on
the initiative of the Clinton administration to add 100,000
officers to America's streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore package will also include a proposed constitutional
amendment guaranteeing victims' rights in the criminal justice
system, new anti-gang laws, and a requirement that prisoners be
free of drugs before being released from prison.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president will also propose resurrecting a special
trust fund created by Congress six years ago to target violent
crime. The trust fund was part of the 1994 crime bill, but has
since expired.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has criticized Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for
supporting laws allowing private citizens to carry concealed
handguns, the vice president will call for allowing off-duty police
officers to carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore is expected Tuesday to argue that a tax cut promoted by
Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee, would limit the federal
government's attempt to help local governments fight crime.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech is his first major address on crime since securing
the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the second time Gore has chosen Atlanta for a major
policy speech. The first was last year, when he proposed allowing a
greater role for faith-based organizations in providing social
services.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane said Monday night there was
no particular reason why Atlanta was chosen as the site for the
vice president's anti-crime speech.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``Georgia is a critical state in the general
election, and Georgians will see a lot of Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's speech marks a major departure in Gore's comments
about crime in the United States. Until now, most of his comments
on the issue have focused on the proliferation of handguns and his
push for more gun control and safety laws.
</P>
<P>
   There is little new in the Gore package, however. The Clinton
administration secured funding in Congress in 1994 to place 100,000
new police officers in communities across America. But by early
this year, only about half that number of officers had been hired
and deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is currently debating a proposed constitutional
amendment that would grant crime victims and their families the
right to reasonable notice of court proceedings and an offender's
release or escape.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new idea, though, is Gore's proposal to halt the
``revolving door'' involving criminals and illegal drugs. Gore is
calling for about $400 million in drug treatment and testing for
those who enter the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   While providing treatment, the proposal would require an
offender to be drug-free in order to be released from the system.
Once released, parolees would have to undergo drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore will propose funding to help communities
obtain ``crime mapping'' computer software to help them establish
patterns of criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-crime package also calls for new laws giving
communities the authority to seek injunctions and other legal
remedies against gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials could not be reached Monday night for
elaboration of some of the key elements of the package. Bush
campaign representatives could not be reached for reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
