<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITTSBURGH-DEVELOP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PITTSBURGH, A REDEVELOPMENT TOO FAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 19, 20 were sent April 28 to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ There have been so many blockbuster redevelopment
projects in this gritty, resilient city in the past six years that
a corner of Mayor Thomas Murphy's office is cluttered with
ceremonial shovels that gleam with his dig-we-must determination.
</P>
<P>
   Still missing from that proud display, however, is the
groundbreaker spade for one of the mayor's most controversial ideas
_ a plan to raze or gut 61 buildings and displace up to 125
businesses in one fell swoop through the tattered old retail core
of downtown Pittsburgh. In their place, Murphy envisions an
ambitious cluster of trendy restaurants, upscale national stores
and underground parking for 1,000 cars to serve surrounding office
towers and perchance lure affluent suburban shoppers back to their
urban roots.
</P>
<P>
   It is such a sweeping plan that, even beyond the cries of
outrage from longtime merchants still able to make a profit in
Market Place, the area in question, Murphy has drawn no less an
adversary than the National Trust for Historic Preservation, which
calls the plan ``one of the most wrongheaded revitalization
proposals to appear anywhere in this country in the last 30
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the warning of Richard Moe, president of the trust,
which is based in Washington and is the nation's largest private
preservation organization. Moe calls the Pittsburgh plan a
``reversion to the worst of urban renewal in the '60s and '70s,''
when whole neighborhoods were swept away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an anomaly,'' Moe said, describing how the national trend
in most other cities is to selectively revitalize and showcase
time-worn neighborhoods, rather than to replace them wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   From LoDo in Denver to South Beach in Miami, from the Lowerton
district of St. Paul, Minn., to the 7th Street renewal in
Washington, preservationists are citing dozens of less sweeping,
more selective renovation programs across the country as profitable
success stories that Pittsburgh would be wiser to emulate. But the
mayor insists he needs something fast and singular, on the scale of
the Copley Plaza renewal in Boston, to save downtown Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   For all the opposition here and beyond, Murphy offers a smile of
resolve and an encyclopedic accounting of the city's hard-earned
recovery since the catastrophic collapse of its steel mill economy
a generation ago. In $4 billion worth of current projects, he cites
two new ballparks, a new convention center and hotels, office
complexes offering 6,000 new jobs and a dozen other downtown
projects. The weary looking Market Place stretch, he insists, is
``the hole in the doughnut'' that absolutely must be redone to make
the urban whole palatable to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In virtually everything we've done, from building ballparks to
dealing with old industrial properties, we have faced enormous
resistance,'' the mayor said, looking beyond his office shovels at
a master-plan map vivid with splotches of large-scale change.
``Every one of these has been a struggle; it's the nature of
changing.''
</P>
<P>
   To critics demanding a more tempered approach, Murphy, a
56-year-old son of a steelworker who rose from the nitty-gritty of
civic politics to wield mayoral power, replies that the city has
well employed the selective ``Main Street'' style of renewing
building by building in other old neighborhoods. But the Market
Place area, he insists, requires something more extensive and
faster _ a single project of urban renewal that he wants completed
in two to three years rather than 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The urgency we feel,'' the mayor emphasized, is rooted in the
fact that the region has been losing residents for 30 years, with
the city fighting to secure a more eclectic future as its
population fades to 350,000, half of its old blue collar high tide.
</P>
<P>
   Across the executive corridor, City Councilman Jim Ferlo exults
no less in the city's resurgent pattern of fresh development. But
he draws the line at the mayor's Market Place proposal, viewing it
as ultimately more arrogant than ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers there have been paying their tax bills for a hundred
years, and suddenly they're blights on the city?'' said Ferlo, a
Democrat like the mayor in this one-party city.
</P>
<P>
   The councilman complains that some of those very taxes would
subsidize the arrival of national chains that would then enjoy a
monopoly position in the $480-million redevelopment, which would
cover about five acres radiating from Fifth and Forbes Avenues.
Murphy says the plan would involve $53 million in city subsidies,
but opponents estimate it would be twice that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The construction would mean five years of social chaos,''
Ferlo said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like most other opponents, Ferlo agrees that a stylish but far
more measured upgrading is badly needed in the area. It now
presents a tired mix of seedy novelty shops and respected longtime
merchants like the 130-year-old Original Oyster House, one of
several establishments that would be exempted from removal under
the mayor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   But Gabriel's shoe repair around the corner would have to go, as
would other humbler shops revered by neighborhood regulars like
Bernie Lynch, a volunteer leader of the fight against Murphy's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd destroy a real historic district to build a pretend
historic district,'' said Lynch, strolling the neighborhood and
savoring her first-name familiarity with merchants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is offering a leasing agent's dream and a city's
nightmare,'' she said, adding that the Institute for Justice in
Washington was already preparing a lawsuit for the local owners who
would be displaced by national competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor denies Lynch's contention that the project would be a
thinly disguised mall.
</P>
<P>
   He said the three-story scale of the neighborhood would be
retained, along with up to 20 existing building facades. Critics
like Moe concede that there are few pure landmark buildings at
stake. Rather, opponents say it is the overall character of one of
the city's oldest neighborhoods that would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, coalescing as the Golden Triangle Community
Development Corp., has offered a $256 million counterproposal to
rehabilitate facades and modernize the area's dilapidated upper
floors for business and housing. Murphy, trying to finesse the five
votes he needs on the nine-member City Council, recently added some
housing to his plan.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome remains uncertain, with the proposal not yet
formally submitted and some Council members underlining the failure
of an earlier mayoral initiative, the construction of a Lazarus
department store two years ago. It was built downtown with $48
million in public subsidies and a guarantee to pay no city rent
until it reaches $41 million in annual sales, a level it has thus
far failed to approach.
</P>
<P>
   Down at ground zero, Patty Maloney, a local card store merchant
on Wood Street, offered hearty laughter at the mayor's promise to
help relocate the scores of displaced retailers to within a
10-minute walk of their Market Place roots. As president of the
Golden Triangle association, Maloney said she had found only 30
open retail locations for all the displaced, none of them
comparable to what they have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is we own this building, picked the location, took
the risk and built this business up _ we did everything we were
supposed to do,'' she said, asking how a conglomerate of upscale
newcomers given a monopoly franchise could match that investment in
the city and its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chains can't do the things local businesses can do in the
neighborhood,'' Maloney asserted, denying the mayor's complaint
that merchants have let the area drift downward for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people aren't leaving this city because there's no
Banana Republic, no Pottery Barn downtown,'' Maloney argued,
emphasizing the need for high-technology jobs that she said could
be invited by creating office space above existing shops.
</P>
<P>
   But it is this very need for jobs that Murphy insists can only
be solved by the image of a fresh Pittsburgh renewed at its very
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to create a scale of development that changes the
dynamic of downtown,'' he said, warning against the alternative of
incremental change. ``We need to move more quickly,'' he added, at
once treasuring and regretting what he described as the city's
small-town resistance to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old joke we have about ourselves in Pittsburgh,''
the mayor said. ``It goes: If the world ends, you want to be living
in Pittsburgh because you'll have 10 more years to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
