<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-AD-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTORS STOP MAKING COMMERCIALS IN DISPUTE OVER RESIDUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the first time in 12 years, the Screen Actors
Guild and the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists
called on their combined membership of about 135,000 actors to stop
working on all television and radio commercials at 12:01 a.m.
Monday until an agreement could be reached with advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Residual payments for commercial work are at the heart of the
disagreement between the actors _ who rallied Monday here and in
New York, Chicago and San Francisco _ and television and radio
advertisers. For years, actors in commercials used on network
television have received payments every time an ad runs in a
practice known as ``pay per play.'' For commercials on cable
television actors receive a flat rate.
</P>
<P>
   A placard stating ``Please Don't Squeeze the Actor'' summed up
the attitude of an estimated 2,000 actors as they marched Monday
down Wilshire Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the marchers, Frank Simmons, an actor, said the disparity
between the two sides could be vast. For example, he cited the
residual payments he received for working in a recent General
Motors commercial. Over a three-month period on cable, he said he
received a flat-fee payment of $1,100, although the commercial was
shown several times a day. During the same period on the networks,
he said the commercial brought him nearly $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as good as economic times are going to get and
by suggesting to get rid of residuals they're basically asking for
a pay cut,'' said Greg Krizman, a spokesman for the guilds.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial advertisers want the flat-rate used by cable to be
adopted across the board while the unions want to see pay-per-play
extended to cable advertising. Under the advertisers' most recent
proposal, the lead actor's fees for unlimited use of a commercial
on cable in a 13-week cycle would increase 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Actors' representatives say that times have changed since they
negotiated flat-rate portion of their contract. In those days,
cable was a struggling enterprise and unions across the country
were making concessions during hard economic times.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's booming economy, with cable television well
entrenched union representatives say it is time to share the
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They boast of record profits,'' said Todd Amorde, a Screen
Actors Guild board member and joint chairman of the unions' strike
committee. ``We want our fair share. It's very simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers counter that with the decline in network viewership
and an audience dispersed over a greater number of networks, they
must show a commercial more often to reach viewers. They have
contended that the unions' demands would increase the cost of cable
television commercials by 350 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for advertisers did not respond to telephone
requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the two groups broke down in mid-April and
attempts in recent days by federal mediators to bring the two
groups back together were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Screen Actors and American Federation representatives, who have
said they would attempt to shut down production on television and
radio commercials made after the strike began, said they knew of no
production going on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard E. Posell, an entertainment lawyer who represents
production companies, said he knew of no companies that were
shooting Monday and predicted they would not work, at least in the
United States, during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of commercial business is an enormous blow to the
entertainment community and the economy at large particularly Los
Angeles and New York,'' Posell said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that commercial production is estimated to represent
about 60 percent of Screen Actors Guild income, or about $720
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of money,'' he said. ``It's going to effect not
only the production business but I think the economy of Southern
California.''
</P>
<P>
   For the actors, the issue is one of fairness. Along with the
residual payments, they are calling for an independent monitoring
system to track when commercials are shown and they are asking
advertisers to negotiate how actors will be paid for work broadcast
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides were bracing for a long haul. The last strike lasted
three weeks and this is expected to go longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly seem to be at a crossroads situation,'' Krizman
said, ``where we're trying to go in one direction and they're going
in another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
