<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-ASSAULT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ACCUSED OF SOCCER ASSAULT MAY BE DEPORTED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Oscar Peralta's two-month ordeal with the Harris
County District Attorney's Office may have ended with a deal
negotiated by his attorneys Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the alleged soccer-field assailant's problems with U.S.
immigration authorities have just begun.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mexican national was released from the county jail
early Sunday, immigration officials were waiting at the door.
Peralta, whose assault trial ended in a hung jury Friday, was
whisked away to a federal detention facility in Houston, where he
now awaits possible deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the Immigration and Naturalization Service
haven't decided yet, but they say it is unlikely the undocumented
immigrant will be allowed to stay in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's here illegally, he doesn't have a right to stay in
this country,'' said Luisa Aquino-Fine, of the INS.
</P>
<P>
   The INS move to take custody of Peralta served to further cloud
his future. His attorneys expressed concern that their negotiations
with the county might even put them in conflict with the INS.
</P>
<P>
   The county offered a diversion of prosecution, which means
Peralta would be on a sort of parole by performing community
service for less than a year, with no more jail time than what he
has already served, about nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Peralta's attorneys accepted the deal Monday, though it still
must be approved by Harris County Court at-Law Judge James Anderson
in a Wednesday hearing. But if the INS deports him, Peralta would
obviously violate the deal, since he wouldn't be here to perform
the community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the INS going to do now that he's in their custody?''
asked Herman Martinez, one of Peralta's attorneys. ``That's the
battle now.''
</P>
<P>
   Peralta, 20, was involved in a collision with Keith Martin, 17,
during a state youth soccer tournament game in the Houston area
last December. Martin elbowed Peralta in the head, and Peralta then
smacked Martin in the mouth, bending back four of his teeth and
drawing blood.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and his father reported the incident to police, and the
District Attorney's Office filed charges. Police arrested Peralta
at his high school classroom in the Texas border town of Mission on
Feb. 22. He had been in jail ever since, unable to post his $25,000
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Peralta's attorneys complain that he has received unfair
treatment, but prosecutors reject that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea there's some kind of big conspiracy in this case is
a bunch of bunk,'' said Assistant District Attorney Lyn McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said he has no control over the INS, but it will
sometimes wait to deport someone until a case is completed. So,
McClellan speculated, the federal authorities might let Peralta
stay in the country while his deferred prosecution plays out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
