<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISNEY-REACT-NYT &LR;      05-01 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWERS SCRAMBLE FOR A SIGNAL OF THEIR BLACKED-OUT PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sam Ramer, an assistant district attorney in the
Bronx, watches ``Eyewitness News'' on WABC-TV here to keep up with
breaking crime stories and spends late evenings with Ted and Sunday
mornings with Cokie and Sam. He's also a big fan of other ABC
programs like ``NYPD Blue'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't count Ramer among the millions of Time Warner Cable
subscribers across the country who woke up Monday to find that one
of their favorite networks had gone dark. He took action 10 days
ago just to forestall such disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Ramer and his neighbors got together and bought a satellite dish
for their brownstone in the Park Slope section of Brooklyn. Each of
the five families was able to get a service package from Direct TV
for about $40 a month _ $20 less than Ramer was paying for cable
service from Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   For Ramer, the dispute between American Broadcasting Cos. and
Time Warner ``turned out to be a blessing in disguise,'' he said.
``You really think you have only one option,'' he added, ``and it's
not until you are forced into action that you realize that as a
consumer, you have a right to better service.''
</P>
<P>
   But for other television viewers _ whether they are addicted to
one of ABC's long-running daytime soap operas or the surprise hit
``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?'' _ the timing of the blackout was
especially irritating. It arrived just at the start of the May
sweeps period, when the competition for ratings heats up and
viewers can expect special developments _ the return of a
much-missed character of ``All My Children,'' for example, or more
celebrity contestants on ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Satellite providers like Direct TV and EchoStar Communications
hope to capitalize on that unhappiness. They say the disruption is
likely to prove a bonanza, pushing many people who have been
contemplating switching into finally acting. Both companies said
sales had already increased in Houston, where the Time
Warner-Disney squabble first surfaced in March.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing the window of opportunity, Echostar is running an
advertising campaign advising that ABC programs can be seen through
the company's Dish TV service and offering a free dish, receiver
and remote control plus installation to cable customers, said
Judianne Atencio, an Echostar spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the ABC affiliate in Houston gave Time Warner
customers more than 4,000 vouchers that could be redeemed for
Direct TV satellite dishes. The two companies are close to signing
another agreement that would include rebates on both the dish and
the installation, said Robert A. Marsocci, a Direct TV spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back, Time Warner pointed out that subscribers could
still watch ABC programs by installing an A/B switch and an antenna
and offered to reimburse them up to $15 for the cost. Tony
Magoulas, a spokesman for Radio Shack, said it was too early to
tell if the tactic was working. But he said one store in Houston
had reported a tenfold increase in antenna sales.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani scoffed at the antenna idea as ``stupid''
in New York, which has so many tall buildings. Similarly, satellite
dishes are not always a practical option for Manhattan residents _
unless their apartment includes a balcony. Another company, RCN
Corp., hopes to lure some high-rise-dwelling Time Warner customers
into signing up for a package that includes telephone service, a
high-speed Internet connection and cable. RCN now serves 70,000
customers in the 800 Manhattan buildings equipped with the
company's fiber optic cable and is weighing whether to step up its
marketing efforts, said Valerie C. Haertel, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Time Warner Cable offices were flooded with complaints.
By 10 a.m., the company's Los Angeles division had received 300
calls _ half from people who were angry about the service
disruption and half from people who were concerned that their rates
might be affected, said Robert Moel, a Time Warner vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Other people voiced their complaints directly to Soap Opera
Digest, a weekly publication with a circulation of 1 million.
``Think about the investment these people make in their shows _ the
amount of ime they spend and the passion they feel,'' said Lynn
Leahey, the editor in chief. She recalled that when some of the
soaps were pre-empted for the murder trial of O.J. Simpson, some
viewers never came back. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
