<SLUG> BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC IS SET TO OFFER PREPAID SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ark., Iowa, Kan., Mich., Nev., Ore., S.D., Wis., Calif.,
Idaho, Minn.)  (Exclusive)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maintaining its strong drive into the long-distance
telephone market, Bell Atlantic intends to introduce an innovative
calling plan Tuesday that appears less expensive than popular plans
offered by AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint, executives close to Bell
Atlantic said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bell Atlantic plan, to be called SmartTouch, offers
interstate long-distance calls for 8 cents a minute at any time and
without monthly fees or minimum charges. The most attractive
flat-rate calling plans from the established long-distance giants
generally include fixed fees or minimum charges of $5 a month or
more.
</P>
<P>
   The twist is that Bell Atlantic will require SmartTouch
customers to buy long-distance minutes in advance under a system
somewhat akin to prepaid calling cards. Generally using a credit
card, consumers will pay into a SmartTouch account that will then
be drawn down as the user makes long-distance calls. SmartTouch
customers will not receive a monthly bill and Bell Atlantic intends
to describe the prepaid nature of the plan as a way for
budget-conscious consumers to increase control over their
household's long-distance spending, executives close to the company
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Bell Atlantic became the first regional Bell
company to win permission from federal regulators to offer
long-distance service in part of its traditional service region.
Last week, the company announced that it signed up 428,000
long-distance customers in New York in the first three months of
the year. While that represents only about 6 percent of Bell
Atlantic's New York customers, it was nonetheless a remarkably
robust figure.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has not won permission to sell long-distance
service in any of the other states where it is the dominant local
phone company, but Bell Atlantic is free to sell long-distance
products outside of the Eastern Seaboard. Bell Atlantic will
initially offer SmartTouch in Arkansas, Iowa, Kansas, Michigan,
Nevada, New York, Oregon, South Dakota, Texas and Wisconsin. The
company intends to extend the plan to California, Idaho and
Minnesota by the middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
   SmartTouch users will not have to dial extra digits, like a
``10-10'' code, before placing a call. But after dialing a
long-distance number, SmartTouch users will hear a
computer-generated message informing them how much time is
remaining on their account. While some users will welcome the
reminder, others may consider it an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, Bell Atlantic intends to allow users to
automatically transfer money from a credit card to their SmartTouch
account when their calling balance runs low.
</P>
<P>
   The long-distance titans offer plans with per-minute rates lower
than 8 cents, but those plans require monthly fees or minimum
charges. AT&AMP;T, for instance, sells interstate long-distance calls
for a flat rate of 5 cents a minute, but only to consumers who pay
a monthly fee of $8.95.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom offers a plan with no monthly fee, 9-cent calling
during the week and 5-cent calling on weekends. That plan requires
a $5 monthly minimum and asks that customers conduct all billing
and customer service via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's best flat-rate plan with no monthly fee and no monthly
minimum charges 30 cents a minute during the week and 10 cents a
minute on weekends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
