A2781 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     05-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF EFFORT A MYSTERY TO HITCHCOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If it was 1993 and these were the Dallas
Cowboys instead of the Dallas Stars of the new millennium, we'd
know without question or pretense that the head coach was blowing
smoke up our you-know-whats again.
</P>
<P>
   Just another ploy by that master psychologist, Jimmy Johnson,
we'd chuckle. Good ol' Dr. J.J., up to his old tricks. Team plays
well, he rants and raves as if they'd been beaten by three
touchdowns. Team plays sorry, he acts mild and unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early '90s, that was just Jimmy being Jimmy.
Everyone knew what he was doing, but it worked anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But these aren't the Cowboys, this isn't 1993 and this isn't
J.J. manipulating the media by tossing a red herring into our
midst.
</P>
<P>
   It's seven years later, these are the defending Stanley Cup
champion Dallas Stars and when Ken Hitchcock is frowning after a
1-0 playoff victory, usually his favorite kind, then maybe we all
should be pulling a pouty face.
</P>
<P>
   Not to suggest that the normally affable Hitch isn't smart
enough or cagey enough to use the media to get his message across.
He is, and he has. But his concern following Sunday night's
victory, the one that put the Stars up two games to none in the
best-of-seven series, which reconvenes tonight in San Jose, Calif.,
seems genuine enough.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem: Hitchcock has less control of his team this
year than he did at this time last year, and that does not make the
head coach happy.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, in Hitch's mind at least, too many of his players,
particularly the forwards, once again weren't committed to the
program.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly a stop-the-press news bulletin, but it is an
aggravation at this stage of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that the players sometimes buck Hitchcock's
system. There's a reason for that: It's no fun. It's hard work.
It's boring hockey, except maybe for the final minute, when you're
fighting off a full-scale, desperation 6-on-4 frontal assault.
</P>
<P>
   As Hitch likes to say: ``There's a price that has to be paid,
especially against a team like San Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, not enough of his forwards _ Mike Modano being an
exception _ were willing to pay the price. It doesn't take a
telescope to see Hitch's finger pointed then, at people such as Joe
Nieuwendyk, Jamie Langenbrunner, Brett Hull, et al.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter to Hitchcock that the Stars got away with it,
only that at this critical time of year that some still aren't
willing to put everything they have on the ice in every game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, this series is following almost the same blueprint
that the one against Edmonton did in its basic structure. Stars win
the first two at home and hit the road. Now, if this plays out like
the Edmonton series did, they'll split the two games in San Jose to
maintain the home ice advantage, return home with a 3-1 lead and
wrap it up Sunday at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That's the plan anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock knows how difficult a venue San Jose can be. Next
to Edmonton, it might well be the loudest arena in the league.
Eddie Belfour, by far the single biggest reason the Stars hold this
2-0 advantage after brilliant back-to-back shutouts, doesn't
usually play well there.
</P>
<P>
   It's the trend, not the results, that causes Hitchcock to break
out in a cold sweat. Instead of heading home down 2-0 and
demoralized, the Sharks seemed to gain confidence from Sunday's
narrow defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about our effort,'' Sharks center Vincent
Damphousse said. ``I feel bad about the result.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult for the Sharks to change that result if
they don't get high-scoring center and team leader Owen Nolan back
tonight. He played poorly in Game 1, apparently because of an
injured right foot _ don't even ask him what the real problem is
because, under NHL rules, if he told you, he'd have to kill you _
and spent Game 2 sprawled on the trainer's table.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan scored six goals and had two assists in the Sharks'
seven-game upset of the Blues, and if he can't return in this
series then the Fins are probably dead in the water anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the heart and soul of their team,'' Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan's condition doesn't really interest Hitchcock. He's always
said that the Stars need to be more concerned about their own play
than about what the other team might do.
</P>
<P>
   This Stars team is convinced it can turn it on and off at will.
At the end of the regular season, when the Stars were going winless
in their last five games, team leaders asked Hitchcock to back off
and not worry. They said publicly that they could turn the switch
back on when the playoffs began, and they did.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears that at least some of them believe they can even
turn the switch on and off during a playoff series _ it was on
``off'' in Game 3 in Edmonton and in Game 2 against San Jose at
Reunion _ and still survive.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the head coach isn't convinced that approach is the
right one at this perilous time of year.
</P>
<P>
   The only smoke he seems to be blowing is coming off the back of
his neck.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
