r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     05-01 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMITT SMITH HAS BIG EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ It was perhaps fitting that during an off-season of so
many changes for the Cowboys, Emmitt Smith showed up at Valley
Ranch yesterday, for the first time, a married man.
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to say that his April 22 wedding and Baja honeymoon
that followed were extremely important to him, but he also admitted
that it just didn't feel right being away from Valley Ranch during
a three-day voluntary minicamp over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was cheating myself,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   There probably is no one inside the Cowboys locker room who
takes winning and losing more seriously than No. 22. And while he
sees the additions of Joey Galloway, Jackie Harris, Michael Wiley,
et al, as being extremely positive for the Cowboys offense, Smith
also sees the bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happened to be in Washington D.C., this past weekend and saw
part of the Redskins' minicamp on the news,'' said Smith. ``On
paper, these guys look to be unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the Redskins lost out on the Galloway sweepstakes, they
quickly signed the NFL's No. 2 all-time sack leader Bruce Smith and
three-time Pro Bowl safety Mark Carrier to a defense that already
includes the likes of Dana Stubblefield, Dan ``Big Daddy''
Wilkinson, Darrell Green, Champ Bailey, and soon possibly Deion
Sanders, who is expected to be waived by the Cowboys on June 2 for
salary-cap purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, the Redskins look 10 times better than they were
last year,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Redskins added former Jets/Cardinals running
back Adrian Murrell while still trying to come to contract terms
with 1999 NFC rushing champion Stephen Davis, and they've backed up
quarterback Brad Johnson with 10-year veteran Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are the consensus favorite this season to win the
NFC East, if not the whole NFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never seen a `paper' winner win a game,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones' admission that the Chan Gailey offense was a
bad fit for Troy Aikman has brought the Cowboys back to the offense
that won three Super Bowls for them in the '90s. Jack Reilly
(offensive coordinator) and Ernie Zampese (passing-game consultant)
have been brought back after brief absences to mastermind how to
best utilize the double-edge, breakneck speed of Galloway and
Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   James McKnight, Chris Brazzell, Jason Tucker and Wane McGarity
are vying for the third-receiver spot. When the Cowboys go with two
tight ends, which they will much of the time, Harris and David
LaFleur are expected to fill those roles.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the emphasis on upgrading the passing game, the
Cowboys are converting Wiley, a fifth-round pick from Ohio State,
into an all-purpose receiver who can work the middle of the field
either from the slot position or coming out of the backfield,
similar to the role that Chris Warren has filled the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Smith sees the bigger picture. He sees all this opening
up the running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buy into the concept all the way around,'' Smith said of the
return to a more vertical passing attack that is expected to spawn
more big plays in 2000. ``But it's only a mindset until you
actually make the plays. You can throw it as much as you want, but
you have to make the plays to gain the respect \Rof opposing
defenses\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith yesterday recalled Alexander Wright, a world-class
sprinter from Auburn, who came to the Cowboys one pick after he did
in the 1990 draft. Wright was fast, but he was never considered a
big-play threat by opposing defenses because he didn't make enough
big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is coming off both his busiest and his best season since
1995. Despite missing 10 quarters because of injuries
(hand/hamstring), he recorded his most carries (329) and his most
rushing yards (1,397) since the Cowboys' last successful Super Bowl
run in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our running game was looked upon last year as being very
solid, very consistent, while our passing game was looked upon as
being inconsistent ... no big plays at times,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``So while we went out and improved one area of the offense,''
Smith said, ``let's not forget about the other area that we need to
continue working on, the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Redskins?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're loading up to do one thing ... to stop the Cowboys,''
Smith said. ``And so I guess that means, hey, we ain't too
shabby.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
