<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, May 2, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Dennis Liff at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS-STRIKE (Los Angeles) _ Actors strike against advertisers,
refusing to perform in radio and television commercials until they
get a larger chunk of the booming cable TV business. The first
major Hollywood strike since writers walked out in 1988 began
Monday with actors marching to the Wilshire Boulevard offices of
several ad agencies. By Dominic Berbeo. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DRACULA-BRADBURY (Los Angeles) _ Science fiction master Ray
Bradbury, author of ``The Illustrated Man'' and other classics,
testified he owes his career to one man: ``Dr. Acula.'' Bradbury,
recovering from an illness and confined to a wheelchair, told a Van
Nuys Superior Court that Forrest Ackerman, also known as ``Dr.
Acula,'' discovered him in the late 1930s and gave him a forum, his
Famous Monsters of Film Land magazine. It is Ackerman's
contribution to this magazine that is the focus of a defamation
lawsuit filed against the new publisher. By Jesse Hiestand. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-ABC (Los Angeles) _ Time Warner says it's Walt Disney
Co.'s fault, and Disney is blaming Time Warner. Meanwhile, some
350,000 households lost their ABC and local KABC programming
Monday, just a few days into the highly competitive May ratings
sweeps period. By Valerie Kuklenski. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
