<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SEEKS TO SUMMON WITNESSES TO CHALLENGE BREAKUP PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY and STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fighting to defeat the government's proposal to break the
company in two, Microsoft plans to ask the trial judge next week
for broad authority to obtain hundreds of pages of government
records on the case, and for permission to summon witnesses to
argue that the proposal is unwarranted and out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their extreme request for relief invites questions on how they
came to the the observations and conclusions in their
declaration,'' William H. Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel, said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The effort could take many months, ``well into the fall,''
Neukom said. Government officials call this simply a stalling
tactic, possibly intended to delay the ruling on a remedy until the
next administration takes office. Microsoft denies that intent, and
outside experts note that the company might not gain any particular
advantage from a delay.
</P>
<P>
   If a new administration is more sympathetic to Microsoft, it
could in theory settle or drop the federal case at any time _ even
if an appeal was before the Supreme Court. But the case brought by
the 19 state attorneys general who are the Justice Department's
partners in the case would remain active. The attorneys general
have repeatedly said they will persevere no matter what the Justice
Department does.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it has lobbied both Vice President Al Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush to counter lobbying from its competitors. Bush
has made a few unspecific comments about the case sympathetic to
Microsoft, while Gore has declined to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 17 state attorneys general filed
their remedy request with the court in Washington on Friday. It
asks Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to split the company in two. One
company would hold the Windows operating system and the other,
Microsoft's application programs. The proposal also would impose a
range of restrictions on conduct while the breakup is being carried
out. Two states declined to join in the breakup proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is to file its response by May 10 and will make its
request for discovery and witness testimony. The government says
proper discovery can be accomplished in two or three weeks. But
while Neukom said Microsoft earnestly wanted to move the case to
the Court of Appeals as soon as possible, he said Microsoft would
need the extra time.
</P>
<P>
   Of the discovery request, one person who is close to the
government's case said, ``If a person is convicted of bank robbery,
does he have the right to find out how the prosecutor came up with
his sentence?''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's stock took a beating last week after the
government's intention to seek a breakup was reported. But Monday,
in the first trading session since the government plan was formally
submitted, Microsoft gained $3.6875, closing at $73.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Once the judge receives Microsoft's request, he is not bound to
accept it. Jackson has said he wants to complete the remedy phase
quickly. Microsoft made a similar request for months of delay to
prepare for the opening of trial two years ago and Jackson rejected
it.
</P>
<P>
   The request for discovery and witnesses is just one of the
company's tactics for defeating the remedy request. Microsoft notes
that the government proposal makes expansive claims for the
increased competition likely to come from a breakup. Company
lawyers call that sheer speculation. But the government, Microsoft
says, ignores the efficiency benefits that come from having an
integrated company making both the Windows operating system and
Office applications.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Hall, an economist at Stanford University who advised
the Justice Department on an earlier Microsoft case, predicts that
the company's lawyers will investigate that issue in court.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, he notes, is a breakup, but the economics are
similar to those of two companies in adjacent markets that have
merged. And the Justice Department's own guidelines, Hall notes,
call for the government to give relatively more weight to
efficiencies in such mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a thoughtless neglect of efficiencies in the
government's analysis, and I think that will be an attractive
target for Microsoft,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argues that the government's breakup proposal will
make it far more difficult, if not impossible, for the company to
develop innovative products that result from putting together a
wide range of software technologies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Microsoft's Pocket PC software for hand-held
computers combines Windows software and Office technology in one
product. Similarly, its planned computer game product, the X-box,
to go on sale next year in competition with Sony, Nintendo and
Sega, uses technology from both Microsoft's operating-systems and
applications divisions.
</P>
<P>
   But a government official said nothing would prevent the two new
companies from collaborating on a product in most circumstances,
though the proposal does include specific anti-collusion
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The government's plan says the company's software tools
programs, which are used to create other programs, would go to the
applications company _ even the developers making tools for
Windows. That might seem to be an inefficient step, but it may not
be the wayward move it seems, according to some computer experts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cusumano, a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and co-author of ``Microsoft Secrets,'' noted there was
already a lively market for makers of development tools for
Windows. Though skeptical that the government proposal will bring
much new competition, Cusumano is also skeptical about some of
Microsoft's arguments about the lost efficiency the software
industry may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be enormous incentives for the two companies to
work together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with those arguments, Brad Smith, deputy general counsel
for Microsoft, has extensively researched previous antitrust cases
and said none of them offered a clear parallel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's remedy proposal, and in public statements since
then, Justice Department officials pointed to the breakup of AT&AMP;T
as a precedent. But Smith argued Monday that the precedent was two
sided.
</P>
<P>
   While AT&AMP;T was broken up as part of a settlement in 1984, the
government also lifted decades-old government regulations that had
governed AT&AMP;T's business practices. ``And it was that
anti-regulatory aspect of the decree that allowed AT&AMP;T to enter new
markets and grow,'' Smith argued, ``while this proposal puts into
place many regulatory restrictions on our behavior'' in the
short-term conduct remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom added: ``Comparisons to AT&AMP;T are just wrongheaded.'' He
said the May 10 filing would make this point. A government official
noted, however, that new government regulations were also imposed
on AT&AMP;T and its former subsidiaries in 1984, many of which remain
in place today.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom also pointed to another piece of research from Smith's
work. ``Never,'' he said, ``has there been a litigated antitrust
case at the end of which a federal court has been asked to order
the divestiture'' of part of a unified company.
</P>
<P>
   In all of the previous cases, he and Smith said, the government
has split up a company along clear divisional lines _ AT&AMP;T and its
local phone companies, Paramount Pictures and its chain of movie
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in contrast, is a single company with different
products but less clear internal divisions. The government notes,
however, that the proposed split falls across a clear divisional
line at Microsoft. In the past, Microsoft executives said there was
a ``church-and-state separation'' between the operating system and
applications companies.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Neukom said, ``The court should proceed
cautiously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
