 NOTES-TEX 
Thompson back on DL 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Rangers, while hoping Justin Thompson can
resume throwing soon, have taken him off medical rehabilitation
assignment and placed him back on the disabled list. The move
allows Thompson another 30-day rehab assignment when he's ready to
pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is coming back from shoulder surgery, and the Rangers
had hoped he could pitch Sunday against the Oakland Athletics. But
that plan was scratched when Thompson felt pain in his left
shoulder while throwing in the bullpen eight days before that
scheduled start.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is planning to play catch today and have a light
throwing session in the bullpen tomorrow. If that goes well, he
will throw again in the bullpen Friday and then possibly return to
the minor leagues to pitch in a game.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin spoke with team physician John
Conway and Dr. James Andrews, who performed the surgery Aug. 27,
and they still feel Thompson suffered only a minor setback. There
are no plans for him to undergo further examination or a
magnetic-resonance-imaging exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both felt at this time it wasn't necessary to do that,''
Melvin said. ``If he still doesn't feel good, we may have to do
that.'' SIERRA GETS MINOR DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Unable to find a left-handed hitting outfielder, the Rangers
signed Ruben Sierra to a minor-league contract and assigned him to
Triple-A Oklahoma. Doug Melvin said he's basically on a two-week
trial to see if he can play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He begged us to play and give him an opportunity,'' Melvin
said. ``We had nothing to lose letting him go down there and see if
he can bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra, 34, was playing for Cancun in the Triple-A ]Mexican
League, hitting .355 with three homers and 12 runs batted in in 16
games. He was released by the Cleveland Indians in spring training
and played for Atlantic City in the independent Atlantic League
last year, hitting .294 with 28 homers and 92 RBI in 112 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him it could be a very short time,'' Melvin said. ``It
might be two weeks. It might be less. If Rusty Greer comes back in
10 days or so like we expect, it probably goes for naught. We're
back to where we were originally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians were the fourth major-league team to release Sierra
since the start of the 1997 season. He also failed to keep a job
with the Cincinnati Reds and Toronto Blue Jays in 1997 and the
Chicago White Sox in 1998. He has been mainly used as a designated
hitter because of his poor defense, but Melvin said he must show
the Rangers he can still play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra played for the Rangers in 1986-92 and was twice named to
the American League All-Star team. But his career started going
downhill in 1992 when he, Bobby Witt and Jeff Russell were traded
to the Oakland Athletics for Jose Canseco. RODRIGUEZ HONORED
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez was named the club's player of the month
for April. Rodriguez won the award for hitting .333 with nine
homers, a club record for April, and 25 RBI. PAYROLL WATCH
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are considering pitching either Doug Davis or Matt
Perisho Sunday against the Oakland Athletics. If they do, they
could have approximately $30 million of their $70 million payroll
sitting around doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   That's the combined salaries of the Rangers' six starting
pitchers _ Justin Thompson, Mark Clark, Kenny Rogers, Rick Helling,
Esteban Loaiza and Darren Oliver _ and closer John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hard part about this game when you put money into
pitching,'' Melvin said. ``That's going to happen. Atlanta is
probably the same way. At least if you put it into position
players, they're out there trying to help you win games.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
