u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIER-BO     05-01 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING GRIER, BELICHICK SEEKS `A NEW DIRECTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Whispers at the NFL owners' meetings in Palm
Beach, Fla., last month had Bobby Grier gone after the draft. The
whispers turned into a loud and clear message Monday when Patriots
czar Bill Belichick, who officially holds only the title of head
coach, fired Grier, the vice president of player personnel, and his
longtime assistant, national scouting director Dave Uyrus, in what
was described as a ``change of direction in the personnel staff.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks Belichick and Patriots higher-ups have said that Grier
and the new coach could survive together. Belichick went out of his
way to say how wonderfully the two had worked together in 1996, the
year Belichick came aboard as an assistant and Bill Parcells was no
longer allowed to ``shop for the groceries.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Belichick, Grier set up the board for this year's
draft, and all went smoothly in the Patriots' room that weekend.
Team vice president Jonathan Kraft said on Patriots.com that it was
one of the team's smoothest drafts in years.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, who was rarely seen or heard after Belichick was hired
this year, patrolled the field during minicamp. A sign of things to
come was the territorial positioning of new executive Scott Pioli
on one side of the field and Grier, Uyrus, and head of college
scouting Larry Cook on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, for now, has survived.
</P>
<P>
   Grier declined comment on his dismissal. He was in the final
year of his contract, and though criticized heavily for his drafts,
he had his best in 1999 when he landed Damien Woody and Andy
Katzenmoyer in the first round, and later picked up Kevin Faulk,
Tony George, Michael Bishop, and Sean Morey.
</P>
<P>
   But Grier had failed to come up with useful players in '97; six
of the nine players he drafted that year _ including first-round
pick Chris Canty _ are no longer with the team. A seventh, Ed
Ellis, might be the next casualty after a bad experience in NFL
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Grier defended his drafts toward the end of last season, in an
interview that seemed to do more harm than good. He was hurt by
reports that players were sneaking up the back stairs to him to
complain about former coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said over the weekend he was going to sit with Grier
early in the week, and evidently the conversation didn't go well.
Grier had said that if he were replaced on personnel matters, he
would step aside, but he never got the chance to do that. Grier's
son, Chris, is a scout with the team whose future could be in
doubt. Likewise for Andre Tippett, the former great Patriots
linebacker who assisted Grier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in and basically told Bobby we were going in a
different direction,'' said Belichick of the afternoon meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said the move was not the result of any specific
incident. He also would not characterize Grier's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't be fair of me,'' said Belichick. ``That's a very
private expression that only Bobby should speak about.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Grier had an excellent relationship with the Kraft
family, it didn't matter in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick previously fired another assistant who was close to
Kraft, strength coach Johnny Parker, whom Kraft had signed to a
seven-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   So what's next?
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Pioli's powers will grow. Belichick will be the
coach and personnel man, and Pioli the major non-coach in the front
office. The team recently hired Ernie Adams, a former coach and
administrator with Belichick with the Browns and Giants. If Cook is
replaced, Belichick may go with one of his old standbys from the
Browns or Jets to direct college scouting. Also expect another
hiring or two of executives who can help Belichick on personnel
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just happened,'' said Belichick. ``I haven't made any
calls. I don't have anyone else in place. Over the next couple of
days, I'll think about how we go about it, but right now I'm not in
the position to be able to announce anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier, 57, spent 18 years with the Patriots, first joining the
team as running backs coach under Ron Erhardt in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots tackle Bruce Armstrong was given a clean bill of
health by doctors at Massachusetts General Hospital. He's already
running and working out . . . Henry Thomas worked out for five days
here two weeks ago. He'll continue to work on his own through the
offseason . . . The Patriots will be making a push for former
Eagles center Steve Everitt, who can also play guard.
</P>
</TEXT>
