<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST TO PAY DAMAGES FORMER BAGGAGE HANDLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination has
ordered Northwest Airlines to pay $200,000 plus interest in damages
to a former baggage handler after ruling the company refused to
make accommodations for her disability because she cooperated with
a sexual harassment investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The finding, released Monday, came five years after Deborah
Mazeikus maintained she was wrongfully fired for written testimony
she gave to state investigators in support of a sexual harassment
complaint brought by the family of Susan Taraskiewicz, a
27-year-old colleague who was found dead in the trunk of her car in
1992. The family, which settled its case with Northwest Airlines in
1995, claimed Taraskiewicz had been repeatedly harassed on the job
before her death.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, MCAD chairman Charles Walker ordered 12 percent interest
on the fine be assessed to Northwest for every year since 1995,
when Mazeikus' complaint was filed. The ruling also requires the
company to submit, within 60 days of the decision, a detailed plan
for training managers and supervisors in Massachusetts how to
respond to issues relating to people with disabilities. The actual
training must take place within 120 days of the MCAD order, and the
company will be required to hold another session next year.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines said in a written statement: ``The company
acknowledges the claim occurred at a difficult period of time in
the Boston operations, including the tragic, and as yet unsolved
murder of a Northwest employee, but it is confident it acted
appropriately in the matter involving Ms. Mazeikus.''
</P>
<P>
   A tearful Mazeikus, who will discuss her case Tuesday during a
press conference at her lawyer's office, said she was ``so happy
that I am on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so many different emotions,'' the 46-year-old former
airline employee added. ``This decision is wonderful. It says that
a person can come forward and do the right thing, can go against
one of the biggest airlines in the country and still get this type
of ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Mazeikus said after she submitted her affidavit
in support of the Taraskiewicz sexual harassment complaint, people
she had long valued as friends stopped speaking to her. ``People
were afraid to even call and talk to me,'' she said. ``I was
recuperating from back surgery and it was devastating. It led to
tremendous stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal records indicate Mazeikus' problems began several months
after the September 1992 death of her friend, Susan Taraskiewicz,
who was one of a handful of women employed as a ground crew
supervisor for Northwest Airlines at Logan Airport in Boston. The
night she died, Taraskiewicz had left her post in the middle of the
night shift to pick up sandwiches for herself and some colleagues.
They never saw her again.
</P>
<P>
   A day and a half later, Taraskiewicz was found dead in the trunk
of her car, the victim of stab wounds, strangulation, and a brutal
beating. Although the company offered a $10,000 reward for
information leading to the arrest of Taraskiewicz's attacker, the
killer was never found.
</P>
<P>
   While state investigators searched for clues to the case,
another investigation concerning a credit-card scam at Northwest's
Boston site was unfolding, Walker noted in his ruling. The leader
of the credit-card scam was later identified as one of
Taraskiewicz's &UR;  &LR; chief harassers. He also was a suspect in her
murder but was never charged. He was, however, convicted of charges
stemming from credit-card fraud and was incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   Five months after her friend's death, Mazeikus slipped and fell
on the job, injuring her back. According to the MCAD ruling, she
took several weeks' paid leave and then returned to work. But she
again injured her back in June 1993 on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after receiving paid medical leave, Mazeikus applied
for disability benefits. She also underwent back surgery to remove
a portion of her lumbar disc. Following the surgery, she asked to
be allowed to return to work as a trainer, but her request was
denied.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Mazeikus filed one of several anonymous affidavits in
the Taraskiewicz case, in which she discussed the harassment she
either had witnessed or had discussed with her friend Susan
Taraskiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   Mazeikus maintained that later in 1995, after a story in the
local press made it clear she had filed one of those affidavits,
she received a letter informing her that her employment would be
terminated on July 30. She also was told she could reapply for
positions at the company, but there was no guarantee she would be
chosen. Moreover, she could do only light duty work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many other jobs available at the time, but the
company never referred her to any of them,'' said attorney Susan
Howardscq, who represents Mazeikus. ``Yet Northwest Airlines found
ways to accommodate other employees (with disabilities).''
</P>
<P>
   MCAD concluded Taraskiewicz had been the target of ``hostile''
sexual harassment. It also found probable cause to believe
Northwest Airlines had done nothing to stop a group of male
coworkers from harassing her.
</P>
<P>
   The agency made its findings after receiving affidavits from
several Northwest employees, including Mazeikus, a veteran worker
with 15 years on the job who testified that sexual harassment had
long been a problem at the airline. Mazeikus also told
investigators that she had seen the word slut scrawled in black
marker in her workplace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
