<SLUG> BC-BBC-CANNING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M SUFFERING BIG 12 GROWING PAINS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an assistant and then head baseball coach, Mark Johnson has
been at Texas A&AMP;M for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   This one is the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, no question about that,'' said Johnson, who watched
his team rally Sunday to salvage the third game of the Texas
series, virtually assuring themselves of a berth in the Big 12
Tournament, which is scheduled for May 17-21 at the Bricktown
Ballpark in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   With a week off for exams, the Aggies (23-30, 11-16) have three
games left, against Missouri. The bad news is that even if they
sweep, they will finish the regular season with the school's first
losing record since 1960. The good news is that even if they are
swept, they are in the tournament unless lowly Iowa State (6-18)
somehow wins its last six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that would be something, at least ... a chance to
participate in a little postseason play,'' Johnson said. ``We
haven't achieved a lot of the goals we set. It's been a rough
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Johnson was expecting a third consecutive Big 12 title
after reviewing his losses from a 52-18 team that reached the
College World Series. A catalog of the departed includes six
starters _ Shawn Schumacher (.374, 11 HR, 53 runs batted in), Dell
Lindsey (.305, 14, 59), Steve Scarborough (.326, 6, 41), John
Scheschuk (.363, 10, 54), Steven Truitt (.345, 19, 60) and Erik
Sobek (.314, 7, 29) _ plus the entire weekend pitching rotation of
Casey Fossum (12-7), Chance Caple (8-5) and Matt Ward (8-1).
</P>
<P>
   So the Aggies opened the season with two preseason All-Americans
_ closer Chris Russ and national home run champion Daylan Holt _
and a bunch of guys wearing name tags so they could be correctly
identified.
</P>
<P>
   But even Johnson, who in 15 years as the head coach has compiled
the sixth-highest winning percentage (.704) among active coaches
and won more games (668) than anyone in A&AMP;M history, was unprepared
for the steep angle of descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very young team, and we knew the season would be a
learning experience for a lot of players _ freshmen and transfers _
who are new to our system,'' he said. ``I think they have learned a
lot, but it's just hard to have to keep losing while you're
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these guys have shown promise for the future. But
we've also had a lot of injuries, and some of the things I had
hoped would develop as we got late into the season didn't
materialize. Primarily, we just don't hit well when we need to. I'm
not disappointed in the players, but I'm disappointed in the
season. It's been a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Holt hit his 15th home run _ he had 34 last year _ the
Aggies couldn't do much with D.J. Jones (10-3) and Beau Hale
(10-2), who won the first two games for Texas (37-12, 18-8) last
weekend. But Russ became a surprise starter in the third game,
pitching into the eighth inning before being relieved by freshman
Todd Deininger, normally a starter, who closed down a 4-2 victory
that likely killed any chance the Longhorns have of winning the
regular-season title.
</P>
<P>
   That bauble will probably go to Baylor (39-13, 20-7), which got
more outstanding pitching from Chad Hawkins (9-4, 1.70 earned-run
average), Kyle Evans (9-1) and Zane Carlson (13 saves) in a
three-game sweep of Kansas, which managed one run against Hawkins
and was shut out on three hits by Evans. The Bears' final
three-game series, after a week off for exams, is against
last-place Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   The other contender, Nebraska (36-12, 19-8) will be at Texas
this weekend for a three-game series that has been moved to
Saturday-Sunday-Monday because of the Cornhuskers' exam schedules.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
