<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER CUTS ABC TV STATIONS FROM CABLE LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Also moving in `f' category.) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millions of television viewers found themselves without access
to ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and many other popular ABC
television programs on Monday as a battle between the country's two
biggest media companies, Time Warner and Walt Disney, reached a
fever pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves how much Time Warner should pay Disney,
which owns ABC, for carrying its cable channels, which include The
Disney Channel, The Soap Channel and Disney Toon. But it also
touches on larger issues dealing with the distribution of news and
entertainment programming, including longstanding antipathy between
the cable and broadcast industry, growing competition between cable
and satellite companies and Disney's opposition to the proposed
merger between America Online and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Cable removed seven ABC stations from cable systems
serving 3.5 million homes _ in New York; Los Angeles; Philadelphia;
Houston; Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; Toledo, Ohio; and Fresno, Calif. _
at 12:01 a.m. Monday. The move came during one of television's most
competitive ratings periods, a sweeps month, when networks and
stations always trot out their most expensive shows. Disney had
offered a 24-day extension on its negotiations over the cable
payments.
 &UR;  &LR;  On Monday, ABC asked the Federal Communications Commission to
force Time Warner to restore the programming. A commission
spokesman, David Fiske, said the commission expected a response
from Time Warner by the close of business Tuesday and ``will
expedite a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC is basing its request on a vague clause about sweeps month
actions in the 1992 Cable Act. In a statement Monday, the
commission encouraged the companies to resolve the issue privately.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides acknowledged that they could be damaged by the
impasse. Disney stands to lose advertising revenue and the
opportunity to draw a maximum audience for some highly anticipated
programming, including the Kentucky Derby this weekend and the
season finales of many of its series. Time Warner risks alienating
its customers at a time when satellite distribution is growing and
giving fodder to those who are arguing in Washington that the
America Online-Time Warner merger would concentrate too much power
in one company.
</P>
<P>
   Even the extension issue is complicated by the merger, with Time
Warner demanding a bargaining deadline for eight months from now _
presumably after federal regulators had approved the AOL deal.
Disney had wanted the shorter 24-day extension, presumably to
retain the merger issue as leverage in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides worked furiously Monday to present their cases to the
public. Time Warner said it was under legal obligation to pull
ABC's signals because no agreement was in place and Disney had
failed to negotiate seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It charged that Disney is trying to boost earnings by extracting
hundreds of millions of dollars in what is known as
``retransmission consent'' negotiations. Broadcast stations have
the right to seek compensation from cable systems for the right to
retransmit their signals on cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives said they were close to a deal with
Disney in December that would have included turning The Disney
Channel from a premium to a basic channel, as well as adding two
other Disney cable channels, The Soap Channel and Disney Toon, to
Time Warner's cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that after the Time Warner merger with America
Online was announced in January, Disney backed off its agreement
with Time Warner, saying that the situation had changed. Disney
argues that it was concerned about maintaining free access to
opportunities created by the convergence of television with the
Internet, which Time Warner and America Online hope to explore.
Time Warner executives charged that Disney was merely using the
merger as leverage to seek more money.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Fred Dressler, the senior vice president of Time
Warner and the chief negotiator with ABC, said that Disney's new
demands added a total of $300 million to the 10-year agreement the
two companies already had in place. Robert Iger, the president of
Walt Disney, called the $300 million figure ``totally
preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences about the negotiations extend well beyond
motivation and money and extended to virtually every detail of the
discussions. Both sides charge the other with engaging in
regressive negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, viewers either needed to switch to an
old-fashioned antenna or sign up for satellite delivery in order to
receive ABC's programs in the cities affected.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of ABC's programs in about 3.5 million homes _ out of
about 100 million homes nationwide with television sets _ may not
drastically affect the overall ratings for the programs, but
advertisers will expect ABC to make up for whatever shortfalls are
experienced by granting them free future commercials, known as
make-goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy network television, and all of a sudden your
schedule is not delivering the kind of audiences you're expecting,
then it's a concern,'' said Bill Cella, the director of broadcast
programming for Universal McCann. Two senior media industry
executives said ABC could expect to lose between $2 million and $3
million a day in make-good commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The timing clearly increased ABC's anger, as did Time Warner's
effort to lay the blame for the removal of the signals at Disney's
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're liars and monopolists,'' said Preston Padden, the
executive vice president of governmental relations at Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Iger said, ``They told consumers a blatant lie in saying we
pulled the plug. The last time I checked they were responsible to
local authorization for their franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   But Time Warner executives were equally aggressive, both in
defending the company's decision to terminate ABC's signals and in
assailing Disney's negotiating tactics. Mike Luftman, the vice
president of communications for Time Warner Cable, said that
Disney's financial demands were so exorbitant there was no hope for
an agreement, and hence Time Warner would have ``violated the law''
by accepting another extension. Eventually these costs would have
been passed to the consumers, he said, adding, ``We have deep
regret for what happened because of Disney's intransigence and
greed.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, at least, ABC got backing from Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who attacked Time Warner as a predatory monopoly. ``This
is an example of what happens when you let a monopoly get too
big,'' Giuliani said. ``It has a particularly bad effect in New
York City, because we're a city which, given the high buildings,
the idea of going out and getting an antenna is stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner began a program of compensating customers $15 for
the cost of a switch that would allow viewing through an antenna.
</P>
<P>
   Dressler, the senior vice president of Time Warner and its chief
negotiator in the ABC deal, said Disney was only using the merger
issue as a smokescreen for its desire to extract the most possible
revenue out of the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
