<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2798 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-POLLUTION-CREDITS-     05-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLLUTION-CREDITS-(1300)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. PASSES BILL PROHIBITING POWER PLANTS FROM SELLING POLLUTION
CREDITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., N.C., Tenn., W.Va., Ohio, Mich., Ill., Ky., Ind., Wis.,
N.J., Md., Pa., Del.)   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The New York state Legislature Monday completed
passage of a bill that seeks to reduce the amount of air pollution
that has been drifting into New York from coal-burning power plants
in Midwestern and Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would stop New York companies from keeping the money
they make by selling pollution credits, earned by cleaning their
own smokestacks, to major polluters in the Midwest and the South.
The credits are now sold on the open market to companies with older
power plants that find it cheaper to buy such credits instead of
modernizing their plants and cutting their emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations permit a company that cuts pollution below
federal levels to sell credits it has earned to a company unable or
unwilling to meet those federal emission levels. The goal is to
reward companies that reduce their toxic emissions below the
federal standard, while forcing companies that exceed the standard
to buy the right to continue polluting.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the free-market approach has resulted in cleaner air
nationwide. But there has been a glaring glitch, according to
environmental experts. Major polluters in the South and the Middle
West have found it cheaper to buy pollution credits instead of
cutting toxic emissions that have blown downwind into New York and
contributed to the state's acid rain problem.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation adopted Monday is intended to help correct that
problem, essentially penalizing power companies in New York when
they sell pollution credits to coal-burning power plants in the
Midwest and in the South, whose pollution is a major cause of acid
rain in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation essentially calls for the state to seize all the
proceeds that a utility company would receive from such polluters
as part of a transaction for pollution credits. The bill allows
state regulators to impose a fine equal to the amount of such a
sale; the fine, in turn, would be used to promote the development
and use of nonpolluting energy sources like solar power.
</P>
<P>
   The action is the first by a state that directly challenges a
major provision in the Federal Clean Air Act of 1990: setting up a
marketplace in which companies can trade the right to pollute, in
the form of credits, as a commodity. Some New York utility
companies immediately threatened a court challenge to the new
legislation, saying the law could violate constitutional
protections for interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federal Environmental Protection Agency, which
administers the credit program, said it supported New York's
attempt to regulate pollution credit trading by companies within
its own borders.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Rubey, a spokeswoman for the agency, defended the credit
trading program. But, she added, ``We are also in favor of
providing maximum flexibility to states like New York in our common
effort to protect public health and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear the degree to which the legislation will reduce
pollution and acid rain in New York state, in large part because
polluters in the South and the Midwest could turn to other
companies in other states to buy their pollution credits. But
experts say the legislation will ultimately limit the amount of
pollution credits available to polluters in the Midwest and the
South and thereby force up the price of such credits.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Sheehan, a spokesman for the Adirondack Council, an
environmental group, said the measure could help protect regions of
the state that have been ravaged by acid rain, most notably tracts
of wilderness in the Adirondacks. He said government studies
estimated that in fewer than 40 years, half of that region's nearly
3,000 lakes and ponds would be too acidic to sustain the fish and
plants that now live in them if the acid rain problem continued
unabated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes no sense for New York to clean up its own smokestacks
and then hand the right to pollute to its neighbors,'' said
Sheehan, whose group played a major role in pushing the bill
through the Legislature. ``This legislation puts an end to New
York's squandering of the benefits of its own responsible actions
toward clean air.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure drew harsh rebukes from representatives of the
state's powerful utility industry, who said it potentially violated
the interstate commerce clause of the Constitution prohibiting
states from enacting laws that restrict trade outside their
borders. Proponents of the measure say companies still have the
ability to sell credits to whomever they want but run the risk of
incurring penalties when the credits go to out-of-state companies
that contribute to New York's acid rain problem.
</P>
<P>
   Carol E. Murphy, executive director of Independent Power
Producers of New York, said she expected utility companies to sue
the state over the measure. ``Either you have a national trading
program or you don't,'' she said. ``I haven't talked to anybody who
doesn't think this law is unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, New York utility companies have sold roughly 700,000
credits between 1995 and 1998 to polluters in the other states,
according to a recent report issued by the General Accounting
Office, the investigative arm of Congress. The credits now cost
about $140 each and allow polluters to emit one ton of sulfur
dioxide, a major contributor to acid rain and smog. New York's
pollution credits account for roughly 4 percent of all the sulfur
dioxide emitted in the United States, government and private
estimates indicate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was passed by the Republican-controlled state Senate by
a 59-0 vote early Monday afternoon. The Assembly, which has a
Democratic majority, passed the bill by a 129-15 vote earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure now goes to Gov. George Pataki, who has expressed
support for such legislation in the past but whose aides said
Monday that he wanted to review the measure carefully.
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carl L. Marcellino, a Republican who is the legislation's main
sponsor in the state Senate, said the state's action should send a
message to Washington that the current system had allowed utilities
in regions like the Midwest to burn high-sulfur coal at the expense
of states like New York. ``At the very least, I believe this
legislation will force Congress into action and ultimately require
the federal government to reduce acid rain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pollution credit trading system was approved by Congress at
the urging of economists and some environmentalists, who said it
would bring about pollution reduction with the least amount of
government intervention and the most efficiency. The act gave New
York utilities a windfall of pollution credits because a New York
state law had forced those companies to cut emissions in the 1980s
to levels below what the federal law requires.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation adopted Monday prohibits power companies from
selling their pollution credits to companies in 10 Southern and
Midwestern states. They are Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee,
West Virginia, Ohio, Michigan, Illinois, Kentucky, Indiana and
Wisconsin. It also prohibits sales to four neighboring states: New
Jersey, Maryland, Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The law also contains a provision prohibiting companies that buy
credits from New York utilities from turning around and selling
those credits to polluters in states that New York utilities are
not permitted to trade with directly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
