</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-MERGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON AND FRANKFURT STOCK EXCHANGES TO ANNOUNCE MERGER
</HEADLINE>
  By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In the most advanced step yet toward the
creation of a pan-European stock market, the London and Frankfurt
stock exchanges plan to announce a merger on Wednesday, according
to officials close to the negotiations by the two markets.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would unite Europe's two biggest securities exchanges,
creating a market for trading securities that would far outweigh
the proposed alliance between the Paris, Brussels and Amsterdam
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   But more surprising is the way that Frankfurt, which some have
considered as a backwater for trading compared with the city of
London, has jumped to the forefront of European securities
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement to be announced, the chief executive of the
combined company will be Werner G. Seifert, now chief executive of
Deutsche Boerse AG, which owns the Frankfurt stock exchange. The
supervisory board of Deutsche Boerse approved the plan over the
weekend, and the London Stock Exchange board is expected to do so
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, London will adopt the Germans' electronic trading
system, known as Xetra.
</P>
<P>
   That will be a remarkable reversal, because the London Stock
Exchange remains bigger in terms of trading volume than Frankfurt
and because London itself is the closest thing that Europe has to a
financial center, in many ways rivaling New York and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal reflects the extent to which Seifert, a former
management consultant, has expanded and redefined what had been a
sleepy stock exchange into a formidable institution.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that the Germans will exert such a dominant role
stems from their embrace of new technology as well as their
expansion into new markets. Two years ago, Seifert engineered a
merger between the futures and options exchange of Deutsche Boerse
and that of its Swiss counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   The combined exchange, called Eurex, is now the world's largest
derivatives market, larger even than the formidable Chicago Board
of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   But the Frankfurt exchange's biggest advantage is in technology.
Its electronic trading system has proved more reliable than that of
London and is being used for electronic trading on the Helsinki
derivatives exchange, the Vienna stock exchange and, later this
year, on the Irish stock exchange in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is being driven in large part by demands from big
financial institutions in Europe, which have complained for some
time that securities trading there is too inefficient and needs to
be freed from national boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were given further impetus with the announcement this
year of a new alliance among the Paris, Brussels and Amsterdam
exchanges. That alliance, to be called Euronext, could have posed a
serious competitive threat but is likely to be overshadowed by a
union of Frankfurt and London.
</P>
<P>
   German and British exchange officials have been in talks for
years about forming a long-term relationship. Indeed, they startled
other European markets two years ago by announcing an agreement to
align with each other rather than pursue more complex negotiations
involving the other European markets.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Frankfurt and London have talked in fits and starts,
but their negotiations ran into repeated disagreements over who
would control how much and whose technology had the best chance of
being accepted as a common platform for trading in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Both have announced plans for collaboration with Europe's
smaller exchanges. But those talks have been even more prickly and
appeared to be heading nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of new electronic trading networks, supported by some
of the biggest financial institutions on Wall Street and in Europe,
made it increasingly clear to market officials that their
franchises would be in danger if they failed to quickly provide
pan-European trading.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known what the combined entity will be called,
although the Deutsche Boerse had already planned to rename itself
Euroboard. If the merger is completed, the plan is to take the
combined company public.
</P>
<P>
   The new exchange will include the Deutsche Boerse derivatives
market but not Clearstream, a subsidiary that clears financial
transactions. The plan has been to let the London exchange handle
trading in blue-chip stocks while Frankfurt deals with trading in
derivatives and small technology stocks. But details on those
matters remained unclear Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the new headquarters was also not known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
