<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEN&AMP;JERRYS-MARKETPLAC     05-01 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN&AMP;JERRYS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: BEN &AMP; JERRY'S FLAVOR OF THE DAY: ROCKY ROAD? 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the founders of Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade Inc.
finally agreed to sell their company last month, the Unilever
executive credited with clinching the deal was Richard Goldstein,
who heads the company's North American business.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the founders and Goldstein gathered in New York to
discuss Ben &AMP; Jerry's future _ distribution, new products, the role
of the founders _ but it was a little awkward. And no wonder.
Goldstein, who cultivated the relationship with Ben Cohen and Jerry
Greenfield, will not be around much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, two weeks after the $326 million cash sale was
approved by Ben &AMP; Jerry's board, Goldstein said he was leaving
Unilever to become chief executive of International Flavors &AMP;
Fragrances. In other words, as he was persuading Ben &AMP; Jerry's to
join Unilever, Goldstein was himself a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had spent time with him over the last five or six months,
and I knew he might not be at Unilever forever,'' Greenfield said,
calling the departure a loss to Unilever that left him ``personally
really disappointed.'' He added, ``I didn't know he was considering
something else at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gould, a spokesman for Unilever, said Cohen and Greenfield
had been assured by Unilever's co-chairman, Niall Fitzgerald, that
Goldstein's departure would not affect the agreement. ``While Dick
was the one who happened to be involved in these discussions, the
agreements are on behalf of the company, not any one individual,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield, who called Goldstein ``a person of extremely high
integrity,'' confirmed that he had spoken to Fitzgerald. ``In that
regard, I do feel good about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was a sharp reminder of the surprises that come
with being part of a consumer-products giant. Neither Cohen nor
Greenfield expects it to be the last. In an interview Monday at
Unilever headquarters, Cohen said the transition would be complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Ben &AMP; Jerry's used to be is one of these smaller
`social-values-led' businesses,'' Cohen said, sitting at a
conference table in the Unilever executive suite with Greenfield
and Goldstein. ``What Ben &AMP; Jerry's is in the process of becoming
is an entity inside a larger business, trying to infuse those
values in that larger business. We expect that it will be a long
and winding road.''
</P>
<P>
   Both founders made plenty of money on the deal, which began
Sept. 8 with a letter from Goldstein. Cohen owns more than 900,000
shares in the company, which are valued at $39.3 million under
Unilever's offer of $43.60 a share. Greenfield, who had 220,000
shares, will receive $9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the founders will be paid $200,000 a year to remain at
the company, where they will continue as directors, according to
the document outlining the terms of the deal. Even though Goldstein
is going to another company, he is taking a seat on the Ben &AMP;
Jerry's board, becoming the sole Unilever representative, according
to Gould.
</P>
<P>
   The offering document also describes three shareholder lawsuits
filed last month against Ben &AMP; Jerry's and its board over an
earlier plan to take the company private at a lower price of $38 a
share. Unilever, Cohen and a venture capital group called
Meadowbrook Lane Capital were part of that plan, which the board
approved in late March. Ben &AMP; Jerry's said the plan was ``never
definitively approved'' and was dropped in the end, making the
allegations unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield said he was pleasantly surprised by his meeting last
month with Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to be nice to us but somewhat
patronizing,'' Greenfield said. ``He wasn't that way at all.''
While Unilever has practical reasons for wanting to, say, preserve
the oceans, the point ends up being similar to that championed by
Ben &AMP; Jerry's, he added. ``Ben and I come at it from a
peace-and-justice point of view, that it's the right thing to do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the merger deal contains a provision in which
Greenfield can sue Unilever, at Unilever's expense, for any breach
of the terms in the deal, Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a problem with that,'' Goldstein added. His last
day at Unilever will be May 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
