<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-MCCAIN-NYT &LR;      05-01 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THEMSELVES IN THE SAME HOUSE AGAIN, GORE AND MCCAIN MEET 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush can only hope his meeting next
week with Sen &UR; .  &LR; John McCain goes as well as McCain's meeting with
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   McCain met Sunday for 20 minutes with Gore at the Naval
Observatory in Washington, the vice president's official residence.
Both were appearing on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' which was being
filmed at the residence. When Gore learned Saturday that McCain
would be under his roof the next day, he called the Arizona senator
and invited him to come over early for a private chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're friends,'' Gore told reporters later, noting that the
two had served in the House and Senate together. ``It's not that
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood that McCain, who has suspended his own
presidential campaign, would be endorsing Bush, his fellow
Republican, for president. But ever since Gore locked up the
Democratic nomination, he has been invoking McCain's name and
making an overt play for his independent-minded supporters. On
Sunday night, Gore seemed eager to fill reporters in on the details
of their get-together, uncharacteristically allowing camera crews
to film him on his airplane discussing the matter as he flew from
Boston to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the two discussed campaign finance reform, McCain's
signature issue and one that Gore is advancing in his campaign.
``We talked about how to move the issue forward,'' he said, adding
that he expected future sessions with McCain on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said that the McCain-Feingold proposal to eliminate
so-called soft money from campaigns would be his No. 1 domestic
initiative, a move some critics suspect is an attempt to inoculate
himself against criticism that his own fund raising has been too
aggressive. The Sunday session thus struck some as an effort by
Gore to bask in McCain's credibility on the issue, or what Mark
Shields, &UR;  &LR; the political columnist, calls ``innocence by
association.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also wanted to signal that he could work with
Republicans, a theme that Bush has emphasized recently while
suggesting that Gore is excessively partisan. ``I will regularly
and routinely reach across party lines,'' Gore said Sunday night,
adding that his ``natural instincts'' are to work in a bipartisan
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore went even further in this direction by suggesting, in
answer to a question, that he might even name a Republican as his
vice president. ``I think that's unlikely,'' he said, but ``I would
not rule it out.''
</P>
<P>
   He ruminated further on the process of selecting a No. 2, saying
that his overwhelming goal was to pick someone who would be
qualified to become president. ``That just trumps everything
else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the cameras were still rolling, Gore also poked fun at his
own comments about the Elian Gonzalez case, which has caused him
much political heartache.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest laugh came when Gore referred to a ``bit part''
that he had played in a well-received video President Clinton had
made to show at the White House Correspondents Association Dinner
on Saturday night. A reporter on the plane remembered that Gore had
made a brief appearance in the video but said, ``I've forgotten
what it was,'' inadvertently summarizing Gore's long-time
difficulty in establishing himself outside of Clinton's shadow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
