   (NYT15) LISTVIYANKA, Russia -- May 1, 2000 -- RUSSIA-FISH-2 --
Siberians love the lowly omul, a gray, oily footlong fish. They
love it fried, dried, smoked, baked, grilled, salted, stuffed, with
internals and without internals, with and without scales. Residents
of the eastern shore of Lake Baikal even like it slightly decayed
-- ``with odor,'' they call it. Omul drying in a hut in the town on
the coast of Lake Baikal. (Jaqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LISTVIYANKA, Russia -- May 1, 2000 -- RUSSIA-FISH-1 --
Siberians love the lowly omul, a gray, oily footlong fish. They
love it fried, dried, smoked, baked, grilled, salted, stuffed, with
internals and without internals, with and without scales. Residents
of the eastern shore of Lake Baikal even like it slightly decayed
-- ``with odor,'' they call it. Vendors seeling omul eat some of
their goods while waiting for customers in the town on the coast of
Lake Baikal. (Jaqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KIZHUR, India -- May 1, 2000 -- INDIA-COMPUTERS -- At a
time of growing unease about the global gap between those who have
access to computers and those who have not - especially in
developing countries like India where the vast majority of people
cannot afford a telephone, much less a computer, local governments
and non-profit groups are testing new approaches to provide
villages with computer centers that are as accessible to all as a
public phone booth. Subrayan Panjaili with the family's only milk
cow, Jayalakshmi, whose life was saved by information obtained from
a computer. (Celia Dugger/The New York Times)
</P>
