   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 1, 2000 -- NY-LEVY-EDUC -- As if top
officials of the nation's largest school system did not have enough
to worry about, now Harold Levy, the interim chancellor of the
city's Board of Education, wants them to be more thoughtful too.
Music and poetry are among the more esoteric parts of a plan Levy
has instituted to, according to Levy, raise the internal level of
debate on education policy. Levy, right, confers with Jonathan Levy
prior to a meeting in the Chancellor's office at the Board of
Education last week. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 1, 2000 -- BLONDE-THEATER-REVIEW-2 --
Eight decades after a work of theater with the forthright title of
``Sex'' landed her in jail and 20-some years after her death, Mae
West is proving that she still has the power to shake things up.
She has also, not incidentally, provided the inspiration for
``Dirty Blonde'' which is, hands down, the best new American play
of the season. Playwright Claudia Shear, who also stars as Mae
West, in a scene from the play opening Monday night on Broadway at
the Helen Hayes Theater. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 1, 2000 -- BLONDE-THEATER-REVIEW --
Eight decades after a work of theater with the forthright title of
``Sex'' landed her in jail and 20-some years after her death, Mae
West is proving that she still has the power to shake things up.
She has also, not incidentally, provided the inspiration for
``Dirty Blonde'' which is, hands down, the best new American play
of the season. From left, Bob Stillman, Claudia Shear and Kevin
Chamberlin in a scene from ``Dirty Blonde,'' written and starring
Shear as West, opening Monday night on Broadway at the Helen Hayes
Theater. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- May 1, 2000 -- ROTH-BOOK-REVIEW -- Philip
Roth, author of ``Human Stain.'' Roth's latest book is not only a
philosophic bookend to ``Pastoral'' but another large and stirring
book as well. It is a book that shows how the public Zeitgeist can
shape, even destroy, an individual's life, a book that takes all of
Roth's favorite themes of identity and rebellion and generational
strife and refracts them not through the narrow prism of the self
but through a wide-angle lens that exposes the fissures and
discontinuities of 20th-century life. (Nancy Crampton, Houghton
Miflin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PRINCETON, N.J. -- May 1, 2000 -- SCI-FUCHS-ECONOMICS --
Dr. Victor Fuchs, an emeritus professor of economics at Stanford
University, also sees himself as a humanist, a person who is
interested in values and who inquires how economics can help people
to think about social problems and arrive at solutions. Fuchs
visited Princeton University last week, lecturing and meeting with
graduate students discussing how economic analysis could inform the
nation's wrenching debates about health care. (Norman Y. Lono/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- May 1, 2000 -- SCI-VITAL-SIGNS -- Researchers
in France and Switzerland have isolated the brain cells that may
bring on sleepiness and traced part of an intricate chemical
back-and-forth between substances that promotes alertness or
lethargy. Arnold Bocklin's ``Sleeping Nymph spied upon by Two
Fauns'' at the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam. (Van Gogh Museum/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- May 1, 2000 -- SCI-FROZEN-METEORITE -- This
piece of a meteor that fell in northwest Canada in January may
preserve a bit of the primordial solar system little changed from
what it was 4.5 billion years ago. A local resident collected the
fragment, wrapped it in plastic and froze it. It has been 31 years
since a carbonaceous chondrite like this one has been recovered
soon after its arrival, and never a frozen one. (NASA/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 1, 2000 -- ARMPIT-EFFECT-2 -- Dr. Jill M.
Mateo and Dr. Robert E. Johnston, both of Cornell University, with
a golden hamster used in their study. They found that the hamsters
apparently used their own smell to recognize relatives they had
never seen, or smelled. (Nicola Kountoupes, Cornell University/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 1, 2000 -- SCI-ARMPIT-EFFECT-1 -- Golden
hamsters can recognize their relatives by scenet. Some experts say
the finding might be applied to other animals, including humans.
(Nicola Kountoupes, Cornell University/The New York Times)
</P>
