<HEADER>
A2809 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NC-PRIMARY-COX     05-01 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-PRIMARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates for governor scramble for votes in N.C.
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH _ While the state's lieutenant governor, Dennis Wicker,
barnstormed Monday in a final swing for votes, front-runner Mike
Easley campaigned closer to home, clinging to a shrinking lead in
today's Democratic gubernatorial primary .
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Mason-Dixon poll showed Easley, 50, North Carolina's
attorney general, leading with 40 percent of 407 likely Democratic
voters surveyed. Wicker, 47, had 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed a tight race on the Republican side. Former
Charlotte Mayor Richard Vinroot, 59, had 37 percent support among
311 Republican voters surveyed, and state Rep. Leo Daughtry of
Smithfield, also 59, had 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling and hauling, that is what it is about right now,''
Easley told George McPhaul of Maxton, one of the African-American
supporters he is counting on to help give him the edge in the race
to succeed Gov. Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, a popular Democrat who cannot succeed himself after two
consecutive terms, has served 16 of the past 24 years as North
Carolina's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who wins the party nominations for governor, the
general election promises a fight over creating a statewide
lottery, an issue that helped propel Democrats to the governor's
mansions in South Carolina and Alabama in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The leading Democrats both support a lottery, but disagree on
how to use the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Easley would use the money to reduce class sizes in kindergarten
through third grade and for preschool programs for 4-year-olds
considered to be educationally at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Patterning his plan on Georgia's Hope scholarship program,
Wicker would use lottery proceeds to create a scholarship program
to provide a free college education to students who maintain a B
average or better.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican front-runners oppose a lottery. Daughtry said he
would veto legislation proposing a statewide lottery referendum.
Vinroot said he would allow a lottery referendum if one was passed
by the Legislature, but he would lead opposition to it.
</P>
<P>
   Easley spent Monday afternoon in his Raleigh campaign office
delivering get-out-the-vote messages to precinct leaders before
heading to Wilmington for a town hall meeting Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hopscotching by air, Vinroot flew from Asheville to Greensboro,
Raleigh and Wilmington before returning to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Easley had a bigger lead in the race for the
Democratic nomination, polling 54 percent to Wicker's 23 percent,
according to a Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research survey of 470 likely
Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to be a good scrap,'' said Thad Beyle, a
University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, political scientist.
Noting that 27 percent of respondents in last week's poll had not
yet decided, he said, ``The key to the election is who actually
turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   State Board of Elections director Gary Bartlett predicted a
Democratic primary turnout of about 25 percent. Traditionally in
North Carolina the Republican primary turnout has been lower.
</P>
<P>
   Beyle said if turnout is relatively low, African-Americans, who
have been courted heavily by both Easley and Wicker, could make the
difference in the Democratic race.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker, a two-term lieutenant governor, has the support of most
of the state's major black political organizations, including the
Durham Committee on the Affairs of Black People.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, one of Wicker's stops was Princeville, the Hurricane
Floyd-ravaged town founded by ex-slaves after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
