<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC BLACKED OUT IN CABLE DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   Millions of television viewers in major markets, including New
York and Los Angeles, found themselves without access to ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and many other popular TV programs as
Time Warner and Walt Disney fought over how much Disney should be
paid for its cable programming.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute also involved issues concerning the distribution of
news and entertainment programming, the growing competition between
cable and satellite companies and Disney's opposition to the
proposed merger of America Online and Time Warner. ABC asked the
Federal Communications Commission to restore programming.
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS STOP WORK ON COMMERCIALS
</P>
<P>
   The Screen Actors Guild and the American Federation of
Television and Radio Artists went on strike and called on their
membership of about 135,000 actors to stop working on all
television and radio commercials until an agreement could be
reached with advertisers. Actors rallied in Los Angeles, New York,
Chicago and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO REVAMPS BANKRUPTCY LAWS
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Congress has passed legislation to replace
bankruptcy and loan-guarantee laws dating to the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS CLIMB IN CALM SESSION
</P>
<P>
   Major market gauges remained in positive territory in a session
devoid of volatility. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 77.87
points, or 0.7 percent, to 10,811.78. The Nasdaq composite closed
at 3,958.08, up 97.42 points, or 2.5 percent, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index gained 15.82 points, or 1.1 percent, to
1,468.25.
</P>
<P>
   LEHMAN BROTHERS IS NAMED IN SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers, a source of financing for lenders catering to
customers with less than perfect credit, was named in a
class-action suit filed against First Alliance, a national mortgage
lender that filed for bankruptcy protection in March.
</P>
<P>
   REXALL AGREES TO $1.8 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch vitamin maker Royal Numico NV agreed to buy rival
Rexall Sundown Inc. for about $1.8 billion, bolstering its No. 1
position in the American vitamin and nutritional supplement market.
Numico is best known as Europe's top baby food maker and entered
the vitamin market last year. Shares of Rexall Sundown rose
$4.1875, to $23.4375.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTS SUGGEST ECONOMY IS STRONG
</P>
<P>
   Figures released by the National Association of Purchasing
Management on growth in manufacturing in April, along with a
separate government report of a surprising 1.4 percent rise in
construction spending in March, to a seasonally adjusted annual
pace of $765.2 billion, paint a picture of a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   REALISM IN FAST-FOOD ADVERTISING
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Freeman and Partners, known for offbeat commercials like
``Where's the Beef?'' for Wendy's, is serving up a television
campaign for Church's Fried Chicken that attempts to depict
realistic working families. The spots at first appear to be film
clips rather than commercials.
</P>
</TEXT>
