<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL IS CALM ON WALL STREET AS BIG GAUGES MOVE AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices moved broadly higher Monday in a session
that lacked the volatile swings that characterized so many trading
days during April.
</P>
<P>
   Major market gauges were up from the start. The gains included
technology, led by Microsoft; financial service stocks; major
retailers like Wal-Mart Stores; and biotechnology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice, consistent performance,'' said Michael Clark,
head of U.S. stock trading at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``It was
different from what we have seen in the recent past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 77.87 points, or 0.7
percent, to 10,811.78. Hewlett-Packard, Microsoft and Wal-Mart led
the advance in the blue-chip index.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 15.82 points, or
1.1 percent, to 1,468.25. Gains in Cisco Systems, Nortel, EMC and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter helped to fuel the gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index continued an advance that began in
earnest last week. It rose 97.42 points, or 2.5 percent, to
3,958.08. The index is now down just 2.7 percent for the year. But
it is 22 percent below its record high of 5,048.62, set March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Roth, chief technical market analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said the Nasdaq may now be poised to improve. ``The market
for Nasdaq stocks made a climactic low in mid-April, tested it in
late April and is now in an interim recovery that could continue
into the summer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think this is a temporary recovery in Nasdaq, and that
most investors who are overexposed in technology should look for
exit points.''
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 12.68 points, or 2.5 percent, to
518.93. The Russell is up 2.8 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Market breadth was good, but trading volumes were light. On the
New York Stock Exchange, nearly two stocks rose in price for each
one that lost value.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the Big Board was 966 million shares. On the Nasdaq
stock market 1.47 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was strong Monday. On its first trading day after the
Justice Department and 17 states asked a federal judge to split the
company in two, the software giant gained 3 11/16, to 73 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Monday's advance, Microsoft shares are down more than
37 percent so far this year. Some analysts said Monday they see
value in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Some portfolio managers said, however, that Microsoft's stock is
likely to remain under a cloud for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I see value in Microsoft?'' asked Henry Herrman, chief
investment officer at Waddell &AMP; Reed, which manages about $40
billion in assets. ``Sure I see value. But I also see a company
that, while not comparable to Philip Morris, will not be a
technology leader for quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Other technology stocks that did well included Cisco Systems and
EMC Corp. Cisco gained 2 7/64, to 71 7/16. And EMC rose 3}, to 142
9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology stocks had a big day. The Nasdaq biotech index
rose 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest gainers were Genentech, which jumped 9, to
129; and Human Genomics Sciences, which rose 12|, to 89 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service stocks gained, as investors continued to
grapple with how banks and brokerage firms will be affected by
further interest rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup gained }, to 60 5/16. J.P. Morgan rose 1], to 129}.
Chase Manhattan climbed 1|, to 73}. And Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
closed at 79}, up 3.
</P>
<P>
   Policy Management Systems, a maker of software for insurance and
financial service companies, gained 5], to 18|, after Electronic
Data Systems offered to buy the company for $18 to $20 a share in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   But Young &AMP; Rubicam fell 5|, to 50 1/16, after WPP Group said
over the weekend that it had pulled out of negotiations to buy the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the improved tone, Roth from Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
said that at some point he expects stocks to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old-economy stocks and new-economy stocks will go down
together to build a real bottom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you need to see cash build up in equity accounts. Right
now, only 4 percent of money in equity mutual fund accounts is in
cash, which is the lowest number ever. That implies to me that
portfolio managers are wildly optimistic, which by itself is a
reason to be cautious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
