<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;M BONFIRE PANEL DUE TO REPORT TUESDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M University will be the focus
of intense scrutiny Tuesday as a special commission studying the
deadly November Bonfire tragedy will return with a $1.6 million
report on why the log pile collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The commission meeting is expected to attract hundreds, perhaps
thousands, of spectators to the 12,500-seat Reed Arena to watch
five consultants present their findings.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants were charged not only with determining why the
1999 Bonfire fell, but also with assessing any cultural and
organizational conditions at the school that may have contributed
to the Nov. 18 disaster that killed 12 and injured 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope a lot of students are there, because it is important
that everyone get the right story, the facts, and not rely on the
media,'' said Beth Riedel, a former student who helped organize a
petition drive to maintain the Bonfire tradition.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 a.m. Nov. 18, the Bonfire pile quivered and then
collapsed with two loud snaps in roughly five seconds, according to
some survivors.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in five years the Bonfire had fallen. In
1994, the Bonfire stack collapsed much more slowly, allowing
students ample time to get clear. No one was injured in that
collapse, which was blamed on soft soil.
</P>
<P>
   University President Ray Bowen appointed Houston engineer Leo
Linbeck Jr. to chair the special commission investigating the
November collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation covered a variety of topics, including the
roles played in the tragedy by:
</P>
<P>
   --alcohol, which was found in the bloodstream of at least two of
the victims. Police found empty beer cans around the stack site.
</P>
<P>
   --the apparent disregard for university policy that Bonfire not
exceed 55 feet. At the time of the collapse, the stack was
estimated at 59 feet and appeared on its way to 70 feet.
</P>
<P>
   --the sloped ground where the Bonfire was built. Photographs and
an engineering report indicate that the first level of the
wedding-cake structure was leaning, while the other three followed
a true plumb line.
</P>
<P>
   --the quality of materials and workmanship that went into the
Bonfire. Eyewitnesses have said that this year's logs were more
crooked than those of previous years. Others said the logs were not
wired in place as carefully as in the past. This method was used to
stabilize the stack.
</P>
<P>
   --whether the center pole _ two telephone poles spliced together
to anchor the stack _ was unusually dry, as some witnesses have
said.
</P>
<P>
   -- crane that struck the Bonfire stack with enough force to
cause it to shudder days before the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report will not assess blame nor make
recommendations about whether the Bonfire tradition should continue
as it has for 90 years. That will be up to the university.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, Bowen is expected to meet with
representatives from the Faculty Senate's executive committee,
student leaders and others before deciding what to do about the
Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M is a university steeped in traditions, and Bonfire is
but one. The massive Bonfire was lit each year during a pep rally
preceding the football game against the rival University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at Texas A&AMP;M supports the tradition, however.
Biology professor Hugh Wilson sponsors a Web site criticizing the
Bonfire. Regardless of the commission's finding, Wilson said, the
school's reputation has already been tarnished. And it will only
get worse if the tradition continues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonfire makes it so hard for this school to reach (Bowen's)
goal of being a top-10 state university by 2020,'' Wilson said.
``While people on campus and around this community believe that
Bonfire is an important tradition, the first thing people around
the country think about this school is Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may like that tradition, but those closer to academics,
those responsible for determining a school's reputation, see it as
a tremendous waste of resources and a huge source of pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Texas A&AMP;M campus Monday the Spring semester of classes
was winding to a close. Students seemed more worried about final
exams than talking about the Bonfire, a stark contrast from last
winter, when the campus buzzed with debate about the tradition.
Many students were unaware Monday that the commission was about to
report its findings.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McWilliams, a junior studying engineering technology, said
most students spent so much time and emotion worrying about the
victims' families that they are ready to move past the Bonfire
tragedy. He expects the Bonfire tradition to continue, but with
modifications to the design.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty worn out with Bonfire,'' McWilliams said. ``Sure,
we want to see the results. But I believe in God, and he tells us
not to live in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   For other students, however, the Bonfire is a pressing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the student center Monday, Bonfire supporters gathered
signatures for a petition they will present Bowen during a student
forum later this month. So far, the group has more than 6,000
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   At the Texas A&AMP;M Bookstore, workers prepared a display for a
book critical of the school and the Bonfire. The bookstore kept the
book, ``The Texas A&AMP;M Bonfire: Tradition &AMP; Tragedy at Texas A&AMP;M,''
off to the side until the campus finished with Parents Day and
Muster, an annual memorial for current and former students who died
during the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be in bad taste to have it on display
before the parents left,'' said store trade book manager Brian
Wasson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
