<HEADER>
A2835 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-STARBUCKS-SCHULTZ-SPI     05-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARBUCKS-SCHULTZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARBUCKS' SCHULTZ HEADS TO ASIA TO FOR FIRST-HAND LOOK AT GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHY MULADY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's a week of firsts for Starbucks' Chief Howard
Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   During his first overseas trip since announcing his new role as
global strategist for Starbucks Coffee, and his first trip to
China, Howard Schultz opened the first Starbucks Coffee store in
heart of Hong Kong's financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz officially turns his chief executive title over to Orin
Smith on June 1 and takes on the new title of global strategist,
personally overseeing Starbucks growth worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is untapped potential to grow our company
Internationally,'' said Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed just before he began his current Asia trip, Schultz
said the four store openings in Asia this week reflect the momentum
of Starbucks' strategic growth internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely excited by our success in the international
marketplace which has come earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must seize the moment following the phenomenal reception
Starbucks has received in all the international markets we have
entered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is eager to see, and understand firsthand, Starbucks come to
life in different countries and different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Schultz was in Seoul, opening the company's largest
store, a five-story, glass-enclosed Starbucks with seating for 200
in the Myondong shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   The store was packed with Starbucks fans and customers waiting
to buy copies of Schultz's book, which has been translated into
Korean.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks first two stores open in Hong Kong Tuesday and
Wednesday. Thursday Schultz arrives in Shanghai to open yet another
new store.
</P>
<P>
   Back home last Friday, shareholders chastened Starbucks,
following the release of its quarterly financial report, apparently
unhappy with the announcement that the company is revving up its
already aggressive growth plan. Shares fell 18 percent Friday and
continued to hover around $30 Monday, down from $45 a few weeks
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz refused to be distracted by the stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always concentrated on our core business, regardless of
whether the stock was up, or in this case, it was down,'' he said
in an interview in Seoul. ``We take care of the customer and our
people, and the stock will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since opening its first store in Tokyo in the summer of 1996,
Starbucks Coffee International has opened stores in the Pacific
Rim, the Middle East and the United Kingdom. The goal of the
company, with retail locations in 15 international markets, is to
have 500 stores in the Pacific Rim and 500 stores in Europe by the
end of fiscal year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks has announced plans to open 750 stores worldwide
before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to leave Seattle Friday, Schultz was looking
forward to seeing for himself how the Starbucks experience
translates in China and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an intimacy around sharing a cup of coffee, taking
time out from your day,'' said Schultz. ``There is a common thread
between our countries, we are all aspiring more than ever for that
human contact.''
</P>
<P>
   A coffee tree with red coffee berries ready to be picked, grows
in one of the lobbies of the Starbucks headquarters. It's from the
original Starbucks store in Pike Place Market.
</P>
<P>
   While coffee is still key to the company, the Starbucks
experience is what sells. The company has carefully crafted an
oasis in the chaotic world, with hints of mystery and romance to
elicit an emotional response.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to work. The average Starbucks customer returns 18
times a month.
</P>
<P>
   The concept builds on the old European coffee house traditions
Schultz was inspired by. He wants customers to think of Starbucks
as the ``third place'' after home and work.
</P>
<P>
   That third place is very relevant in China,'' said Peter Maslen,
president of Starbucks International. ``When you go into a
Starbucks in China, you see people doing their homework, talking
and meeting friends. It's very much like in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks stores are identical to their American cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Maslen, who joined Starbucks in October, is a veteran of
overseas marketing, especially in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   He said Starbucks reliability, that the product and experience
are the same each time the customer visits, sets Starbucks apart
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said Starbucks' arrival is eagerly anticipated in Hong
Kong, where word of mouth, students returning from studying in the
United States and American movies such as ``You've Got Mail'' have
built excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Seattle roots have helped us, we are perceived as being
from a place where good things come from,'' said Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz and Maslen said women in Asia lead the rush to the local
Starbucks, then return later with their friends, husbands and
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong is ready for the Starbucks experience,'' said
Michael Wu, managing director of Maxim's Caterers. Maxim's has
partnered with Starbucks in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz joined Starbucks in 1982 as its marketing director,
providing coffee to restaurants and espresso bars in Seattle. After
traveling to Italy in 1983, he hit on the idea of bringing the
coffee bar culture to Seattle. Two years later, Schultz founded Il
Giornale, offering coffee drinks made from Starbucks beans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Schultz bought Starbucks' assets, and began growing the
company. But even Schultz sometimes seems amazed how far Starbucks
has come.
</P>
<P>
   He recently told about looking at a globe with his children one
evening, pointing out the places Starbucks would be opening this
week. He couldn't help feeling a little proud as he turned the
world for them to see.
</P>
<P>
   It became clearer to him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For God's sake, we are opening in China!'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Material from Bloomberg News was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
