u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-WIFE-NYT &LR;      05-01 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-WIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S WIFE TO POSTPONE HER ROLE IN `MONOLOGUES'
</HEADLINE>
  By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donna Hanover _ an actress, television personality
and the wife of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ announced Monday that she
was postponing her performance in ``The Vagina Monologues'' because
of ``personal family circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover's announcement came four days after the mayor announced
that he had prostate cancer and would spend the next two weeks
deciding on treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover had been scheduled to take a lead role starting May 30
in the Off-Broadway hit, which features monologues on topics like
orgasm and childbirth. She made her announcement in this
two-sentence statement released by her office: ``Due to personal
family circumstances, I have decided to postpone my performance in
`The Vagina Monologues.' I will work with the show's producers and
directors to set a date to join another team of esteemed actresses
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover had been scheduled to appear for two weeks in the show
with the actresses Kirstie Alley and Hazelle Goodman. David Stone,
the lead producer of the show, said Monday that he expected Hanover
to rejoin the show ``soon, in a couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover, who has led a separate public life from the mayor since
1996, had no further comment Monday. Giuliani's spokeswoman, Sunny
Mindel, said the mayor also had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Eve Ensler, the author of ``The Vagina Monologues'' and a friend
and political supporter of Hillary Rodham Clinton, the mayor's
opponent for U.S. Senate, was traveling in Afghanistan on Monday
and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides had said the mayor would not have been able to
attend his wife's opening night performance on May 30, which would
have occurred on the same night as the state Republican convention,
where Giuliani is expected to be designated as the party's Senate
nominee. It was unclear whether Giuliani would have attended any of
the other performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is independent, she leads an independent life, so do
I,'' the mayor said last month. ``I think those discussions will be
private discussions about whether I do or don't'' attend.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Hanover's said Monday that the mayor's wife probably
made her decision not because she considered performing in the show
inappropriate right now, but because of the practical concerns of
having to perform six nights a week with two children at home while
her husband might be in the hospital or undergoing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Giuliani said Monday at his daily City Hall news
briefing that he had met with his doctors in the morning but had
had no further tests for his cancer, which is in an early,
treatable form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even asked the doctor, `Any more tests?''' Giuliani said.
``It would be good to have another test. There are no more tests.
It's just a matter of analyzing all of the information that's
there, and figuring out the right option. Which is, you know,
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also told reporters not to expect regular bulletins on
his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give you daily medical updates,'' he said,
laughing. ``You want to know the discussions with my doctor today
and the whole thing?'' Giuliani added that after he got some second
opinions, ``which will be, you know, in a week or so, then we'll
discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said again that he was ``hopeful'' that he would be
able to run for Senate, but that his health was his first priority.
``My first decision, and the way I'm going to keep my mind focused
on this is, what is the best option in terms of getting the most
complete cure? I'm still less than a week into analyzing this, and
that's what I'm going to do. Running is something I would like to
do. Being alive and healthy is more important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
