<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT RULES IN TWO TEXAS CASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case brought by sheriff's deputies in Houston,
the Supreme Court ruled Monday that local governments can decide
how they compensate employees for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-3 decision, the court resolved in Harris County's favor
a long-standing pay dispute in which 127 deputies argued that
federal law allows them, and not the municipality, to decide how
their overtime work should be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   The county successfully countered that it can order workers to
take time off at their regular wage rather than pay them
``time-and-a-half'' in overtime compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In another Texas case Monday, a divided court overturned part of
the conviction of a child molester, saying state prosecutors relied
on improper testimony from the victim to secure the guilty verdict.
But the justices' 5-4 decision will not affect the life prison
sentence given Scott Leslie Carmell for having sexually assaulted
his young stepdaughter, identified in court papers as ``KM.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deputies' case, Harris County Attorney Michael Fleming
hailed the court's decision as a ``huge victory for local
taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it could cost the county up to $20 million in annual
overtime compensation if the Sheriff's Department was not able to
order deputies to take time off instead of pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local taxpayers have the burden of handling the budgets of
their governmental entities,'' said Fleming, who argued the case
before the justices. A ruling for employee control of overtime pay
would have ``destroyed the ability of local entities to plan their
budgets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies' attorneys said they were disappointed by the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for the working man,'' attorney Murray Malakoff
said. ``The bottom line is that they will bend the rules when the
rules favor management. It just gives you cause to wonder if there
is justice for the working men and women in the public sector these
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Richard Cobb said that unless Congress amends the law,
nothing more can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the last court of last resort,'' Cobb said.
``Congress should go back and amend the Fair Labor Standards Act so
that from now on, you have to pay everybody in cash. That would
eliminate the problem. But the cities will really squawk at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court, agreeing with the county, said the federal Fair
Labor Standards Act lets state and local governments determine
whether to reward its overtime employees with extra pay or paid
days off. The law demands only that employees receive ``timely
compensation'' for working overtime, Justice Clarence Thomas wrote
in the court's majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Thomas' opinion were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M.
Kennedy and David H. Souter.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting Justice John Paul Stevens said the federal law,
rather than giving employers leeway to set overtime compensation
rules, calls for employers and employees to agree on how extra
hours will be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens' dissent were Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and
Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   In the molestation case, Carmell, of North Texas, was convicted
on 15 counts of sexual abuse from February 1991 to March 1995. The
court's decision overturns the verdicts on only four of those
counts.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, while not addressing his more serious offenses,
said prosecutors violated Carmell's constitutional rights by using
a 1993 change in Texas trial procedure that allowed the girl to
testify about all the alleged attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, the court said the Constitution bars states
from making it easier for courts to convict defendants by rewriting
the rules of trial procedure to allow testimony that would have
been barred at the time the offense was committed.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of several of Carmell's offenses, sexual-assault
victims between ages 14 and 17 were barred from testifying against
their alleged attacker if they waited more than six months before
telling anyone of the alleged attack, as KM had done. The child's
testimony also had to be supported with corroborating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas, in its 1993 change, began allowing girls between 14
and 17 to testify, even if they had waited more than six months.
Juries also were allowed to convict defendants based solely on the
girl's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling marked a defeat for Texas Attorney General John
Cornyn, who had argued the case against Carmell before the
justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respectfully disagree with the court's decision, but
thankfully Mr. Carmell will remain in prison despite the court's
ruling,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, writing for the majority, said the ex post facto clause
of the Constitution forbids states from applying relaxed rules on
the admission of testimony at the trial of someone whose alleged
offense occurred before the rules were changed.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens' opinion were Scalia, Souter, Thomas and Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg, in a vehement dissent, said the Constitution does
permit states to change trial rules regarding when a child is
deemed competent to give testimony. Such an amendment does not
violate the ex post facto clause, which prevents defendants from
being charged with a crime that was not regarded as illegal at the
time it was committed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
