<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VINNY-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC MIGHT GET HURT BY SUMMER CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Henry Bibby is trying to build a competitive
basketball program at USC. He needs recruits to do that. Problem
is, few premier high school players go to sleep at night dreaming
of playing basketball for the Trojans. They'd rather go across town
to UCLA or to Duke or North Carolina, the Rolls-Royces of college
hoops.
</P>
<P>
   USC is more like a midsized sedan.
</P>
<P>
   So Bibby has a major sales job on his hands. He has to convince
these kids that USC is a viable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he needs ample time to cultivate relationships with
players, to visit with them and watch them play. In essence, Bibby
needs time to make up ground on the more-established programs he
battles each year for star recruits, battles that are sometimes won
or lost during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenge Bibby actually looks forward to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem being out there in the summer,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the NCAA is threatening to reduce Bibby's time dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the NCAA Division I board of directors voted to
pass a wide-ranging package of basketball reforms _ including
scaling back summer recruiting and limiting the number of men's
scholarships schools can annually award.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the summer evaluation period will be cut back from 50
days to 40 and then eliminated altogether the next season unless a
new plan can be formulated. The sweeping change is in response to
the participation of questionable coaches in summer camps run by
outside organizations such as the AAU and shoe companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unsavory influences that permeate summer basketball are
unacceptable to us and we have to shut that down,'' said Graham
Sanier, president of Penn State and chairman of the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Sanier has a point, of course. In some cases, college coaches
have to deal with summer coaches just for the chance to talk to
players. The coaches, often hangers-on or family friends or even
street agents, latch on to players with cash payments or gifts.
It's a system that invites trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby, and other coaches in similar situations, understand the
need to eliminate the seedy aspect of summer camps. But to do away
with the evaluation period altogether could seriously affect
smaller schools. They need the offseason time to scout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, I have to be out there to be in the ballgame with
recruits, if only to impress them and let them see me,'' Bibby
said. ``A lot of these bigger schools like UCLA or Duke send one
letter to a kid, and he wants to go there. We have to send 100
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA took action after brushing against the edgy side of
summer basketball this year. UCLA's JaRon Rush and his brother
Kareem, who plays at Missouri, were suspended for accepting gifts
from Kansas City summer league coach Myron Piggie. JaRon also took
money from an agent. St. John's star Eric Barkley was suspended
twice this year for similar infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie was charged April 13 in an indictment with paying JaRon
and Kareem, Oklahoma State's Andre Williams, former Duke player
Corey Maggette and ex-Wichita high school star Korleone Young more
than $35,000 while they were in high school and played for him
during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby agrees something needs to be done to exterminate corrupt
influences like Piggie. He just hopes the NCAA understands the
difficult task he has and that its future decisions will reflect
the challenge he faces.
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA's latest plan remains in effect, the
more-established programs will gain a monumental edge over their
smaller counterparts. In the past, Bibby was rewarded for his
hustle during the summer by landing key recruits. Had it not been
for Bibby's tenacity, some of those players might not have
considered USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key issues are the people involved in these summer
camps,'' Bibby said. ``So many people have their hands in the pot
at these camps that some of the bigger schools want to back off
them entirely. But doing that ends up hurting the smaller schools
that have to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah coach Rick Majerus agrees. Majerus built a national power
at Utah with his relentless recruiting, outworking other schools
for top players. Now he might not get that chance, at least during
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're Duke, you don't have to go out and recruit. They
select who they want,'' Majerus said. ``A guy like me has to
recruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the NCAA helped contribute to problems during the
summer. Many camps and tournaments during that time are put on by
shoe companies _ the same companies that many of the NCAA's member
schools are contractually tied to.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Michigan State, the defending national champion,
agreed to make Nike the exclusive outfitter for the Spartans'
basketball team. The deal will net the school more than $1 million
in cash and merchandise each year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the NCAA wants to clean up a mess it helped create. It's a
noble effort, only Bibby and Majerus and coaches from all the
lesser-known Division I schools wonder whether they'll get swept
out in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
