<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER CUTS ABC TV STATIONS FROM CABLE LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for additions and reorganization from graf 8 on.)   (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``f.'')  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millions of television viewers found themselves without access
to ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and many other popular ABC
television programs on Monday as a battle between the country's two
biggest media companies, Time Warner and Walt Disney, reached a
fever pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves how much Time Warner should pay Disney,
which owns ABC, for carrying its cable channels, which include The
Disney Channel, The Soap Channel and Disney Toon. But it also
touches on larger issues dealing with the distribution of news and
entertainment programming, including longstanding antipathy between
the cable and broadcast industry, growing competition between cable
and satellite companies and Disney's opposition to the proposed
merger between America Online and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Cable removed seven ABC stations from cable systems
serving 3.5 million homes _ in New York; Los Angeles; Philadelphia;
Houston; Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; Toledo, Ohio; and Fresno, Calif. _
at 12:01 a.m. Monday. The move came during one of television's most
competitive ratings periods, a sweeps month, when networks and
stations always trot out their most expensive shows. Disney had
offered a 24-day extension on its negotiations over the cable
payments.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, ABC asked the Federal Communications Commission to
force Time Warner to restore the programming. A commission
spokesman, David Fiske, said the commission expected a response
from Time Warner by the close of business Tuesday and ``will
expedite a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC is basing its request on a vague clause about sweeps month
actions in the 1992 Cable Act. In a statement Monday, the
commission encouraged the companies to resolve the issue privately.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides acknowledged that they could be damaged by the
impasse. Disney stands to lose advertising revenue and the
opportunity to draw a maximum audience for some highly anticipated
programming, including the Kentucky Derby this weekend and the
season finales of many of its series. Time Warner risks alienating
its customers at a time when satellite distribution is growing and
giving fodder to those who are arguing in Washington that the
America Online-Time Warner merger would concentrate too much power
in one company.
</P>
<P>
   Even the extension issue is complicated by the merger, with Time
Warner demanding a bargaining deadline for eight months from now _
presumably after federal regulators had approved the AOL deal.
Disney had wanted the shorter 24-day extension, presumably to
retain the merger issue as leverage in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides worked furiously Monday to present their cases to the
public. On the channels where it had been carrying ABC, Time Warner
posted the message, ``Disney has taken ABC away from you.'' A Time
Warner spokesman said the company was under legal obligation to
pull ABC's signals because no agreement was in place and Disney had
failed to negotiate seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But Preston Padden, the executive vice president of governmental
relations at Disney, said, ``They're liars and monopolists.''
Robert A. Iger, the president of Disney, said: ``They told
consumers a blatant lie in saying we pulled the plug. The last time
I checked they were responsible to local authorization for their
franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner charged that Disney was trying to boost earnings by
extracting hundreds of millions of dollars in what is known as
``retransmission consent'' negotiations. Broadcast stations have
the right to seek compensation from cable systems for the right to
retransmit their signals on cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives said they were close to a deal with
Disney in December that would have turned The Disney Channel from a
premium service to a basic channel, as well as adding two other
Disney cable channels, The Soap Channel and Disney Toon, to Time
Warner's cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two sides disagree on the payment terms of that
deal, both agree that after the merger with AOL was announced in
January, Disney backed off, saying the situation had changed.
Disney argued that it was concerned about maintaining free access
to opportunities created by the convergence of television with the
Internet, which Time Warner and AOL hope to explore. Time Warner
calls this a negotiating ploy.
</P>
<P>
   Padden, Disney's chief lobbyist, said the company was worried
specifically about being blocked from utilizing interactive
features like commercials with links to the Internet and digital TV
that could allow viewers to purchase goods.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Disney executives began to aggressively lobby
Congress against the proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Disney infuriated Time Warner by offering cable
subscribers in Houston a $99 rebate on a satellite dish when the
two sides were facing a deadline in that city. More than 15,000
people took Disney up on the offer, which Time Warner said was a
threat to its business.
</P>
<P>
   The differences about the negotiations extended to virtually
every detail of the discussions. Fred Dressler, the senior vice
president of Time Warner and the chief negotiator with ABC said
that Disney's new demands added a total of $300 million to the
10-year agreement the two companies already had in place. Iger, the
president of Disney, called the $300 million figure ``totally
preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of ABC's programs in about 3.5 million homes _ a small
percentage of the 100 million homes with television sets _ may not
drastically affect the overall ratings for the sweeps programs, but
advertisers will expect ABC to make up for whatever shortfalls are
experienced by granting them free future commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy network television and all of a sudden your
schedule is not delivering the kind of audiences you're expecting,
then it's a concern,'' said Bill Cella, the director of broadcast
programming for Universal McCann, an advertising agency. Two senior
media industry executives said ABC could expect to lose between $2
million and $3 million a day worth of commercials it would later
have to offer for free.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In New York at least, ABC got backing from Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who attacked Time Warner as a predatory monopoly. ``This
is an example of what happens when you let a monopoly get too
big,'' Giuliani said. ``It has a particularly bad effect in New
York City because we're a city in which, given the high buildings,
the idea of going out and getting an antenna is stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Time Warner cable subscribers either needed to
switch to an old-fashioned antenna or sign up for satellite
delivery in order to receive ABC's programs. Time Warner began a
program of compensating customers $15 for the cost of a switch that
would allow viewing through an antenna.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Disney spokesmen would not discuss the level of involvement of
Michael Eisner, the company's chairman, but Dressler of Time Warner
said all the Disney negotiators had said that ``Michael Eisner is
calling the shots on this and he's not going to take the deal we
had in December.'' He said the negotiating tactics were ``pure
Eisner,'' adding, ``This is Disney looking to increase revenues to
help its stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives said their own senior managers, including
the chairman, Gerald Levin, were extremely involved in the decision
to refuse Disney's extension offer. But Iger said that assigning
the dispute to a confrontation between the management of the two
companies was totally inaccurate. ``In no way is this about
testosterone, or a personal showdown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Compensation for programming has been an issue in numerous
confrontations between broadcasters and cable companies in the
past. Until the 1992 Cable Act, cable systems could carry broadcast
stations without offering compensation. At that time, broadcasters
won the right to negotiate with cable companies for some kind of
compensation. CBS led a move to force cable operators to pay
subscriber fees to network stations, just as cable operators do to
other programmers, like Lifetime or the Arts and Entertainment
Network. That move failed when the other networks, led, as it
happened, by ABC, opted _ instead of getting cash _ to increase
distribution for cable channels they owned. ABC won carriage for
ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast stations have rarely been pulled off cable systems.
News Corp. the parent of the Fox network, pulled its stations off
systems owned by Cox Cable late last year in a dispute over terms
of carriage of sports and movie channels owned by Fox. The matter
was settled in five days. An independent station in Portland,
Maine, pulled its signal from a Time Warner cable system in 1993,
seeking cash for retransmission consent. That dispute lasted one
day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Time Warner said it had not met with similar opposition in its
more recent retransmission deals with the other broadcast networks.
In late December it concluded a long-term deal with News Corp.,
which involved carriage of news sports and movie channels. Time
Warner had a deal in effect with CBS until 2003 and one with NBC
until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has reached agreement with Fox and CBS to carry new
features and stations that can be created as a result of digital
technology in the coming years. NBC is still negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from Fox, NBC and CBS declined to comment on the
Disney-Time Warner dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
