<SLUG> BC-FBN-LARRIMORE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRIMORE HAS HOPES FOR FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When you're a star at a NCAA Division II school
and you've played before smaller crowds in the Panhandle, Valley
Ranch can look like the King Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   But Cowboys rookie cornerback Kareem Larrimore, a former West
Texas A&AMP;M star, exudes confidence after his first taste of
professional football during the team's three-day minicamp that
concluded Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a small school, but we had good coaching and talent
there,'' Larrimore said. ``The only difference is when you're at a
larger school, you get 40,000, 50,000 or 80,000 people to watch you
play. At a small school, you get 13,000 at the max. The only
difference is the size of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, at this level, it's not a problem,'' Larrimore
added. ``You have to play as big as the big man. And I'm out to
play with the big boys.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds of reaching NFL stardom do not favor players from
Division II schools, said Larry Lacewell, the Cowboys' director of
pro and college scouting. He said there is ``a huge dropoff''
between even Division I-AA and Division II competition.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't prevented the Cowboys from finding stars among the
lower ranks of college football.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have four players _ Guard Larry Allen (Sonoma
State), linebacker Dexter Coakley (Appalachian State), defensive
tackle Leon Lett (Emporia State, Kan.,) and tackle Erik Williams
(Central State, Ohio) _ who did not play Division I-A football who
went to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell said the Cowboys have three rookies from Division II
schools _ Larrimore, drafted in the fourth round, receiver Drew
Cone (Southern Arkansas) and defensive end Bryant Shaw (Mississippi
College) on their roster.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, 5-foot-11, 190, said he was surprised, but not
intimidated, by the speed of veteran pro receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They teach you so well here that you adapt very quickly,'' he
said, adding that the minicamp was ``pretty much what I expected.
You know, TV doesn't lie. After you watch the \Rveteran players\S
on TV and see them run here, you know it's not a joke. Everything
that I saw \Ron TV\S was the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, who was timed in 4.34 seconds in the 40-yard dash at
the NFL Combine in Indianapolis, said his gameplan is to find his
niche and impress head coach Dave Campo, who said he liked
Larrimore's aggressiveness and his willingness to participate in
drills when an extra person was needed. Campo also said he was
impressed by Larrimore's courage to take on veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just starting off as a nickel back and trying to move my
way up the ladder,'' Larrimore said. ``Everything is so fast and
the coaching is so excellent, that I can't help but get better. If
I focus and do what I have to do, I'll be primed for Sundays.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
