<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLABKB-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOISO, RUSH OFF TO NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Continuing a recent tradition with UCLA men's
basketball, sophomores Jerome Moiso and JaRon Rush will announce
today they are making themselves available for the the NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   As first reported in the Daily News on April 13, Moiso and Rush
are giving up their final two years in Westwood. Last year, point
guard Baron Davis made a similar decision and he was drafted by the
Charlotte Hornets with the third pick.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rush nor Moiso are expected to be picked that high. But
their simultaneous departure leaves UCLA without two of the
Pacific-10's premier players.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, a 6-foot-10 forward/center, averaged 13.0 points and 7.6
rebounds per game for UCLA, which went 21-12. Moiso is athletic,
but NBA scouts question his toughness. He's projected as a possible
lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, a 6-6 forward, was instrumental in UCLA winning eight
consecutive games late in the season, including an upset at
top-ranked Stanford, where he made the game's winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   Rush owes $6,525 for NCAA violations that led to his being
suspended for 24 games, plus legal fees. His mother, Glenda, told
the Daily News in April she thinks her son should stay in school,
but Rush, who averaged 12.1 points and 5.7 rebounds in nine games,
impressed many in the six post-suspension games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the NBA as been a goal of mine,'' said Moiso in a
statement released by UCLA, ``and I feel this is the time for me to
take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush said: ``This is the decision that is best for my family and
me.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Steve Lavin, who was in Phoenix for the Pac-10
coaches' meetings, also issued a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two young men have evaluated their individual situations
and have made decisions they feel are best for them,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   With Rush and Moiso, the Bruins would have returned all five
starters and likely been a top-10 preseason pick. Now, they have
two significant holes. Reserve Matt Barnes replaces Moiso, but
there's no one on the roster to replace Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Earl Watson, center Dan Gadzuric and wingman Jason
Kopono all return, but Kapono said recently he hasn't ruled out a
jump to the NBA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
