<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS     05-01 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS FOR A 2-1 ADVANTAGE OVER LEAFS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Following Coach Larry Robinson's
instructions almost to perfection, the Devils gained the upper hand
Monday night in their Eastern Conference semifinal series with a
5-1 victory over the Toronto Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the goaltending of Martin Brodeur, the Devils did
everything so well upon returning home after splitting the first
two games in Toronto that they had the crowd of 18,524 at
Continental Arena chanting ``Sixty-seven, sixty-seven,''in mock
reference to 1967, the last time the Leafs won the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in the first two games, the Devils played tight
defense for the most part and created traffic in front of
goaltender Curtis Joseph for their shooters. This time, though, the
shooters clicked.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive wealth was spread around as five different Devils'
players scored goals on a joyous evening, reminiscent of the 1995
playoffs, when the Devils captured the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs did not get their goal until after the Devils
had scored all theirs goals. Toronto's goal, by Kevyn Adams, came
with 4 minutes 17 seconds to play. Brodeur stopped the other 22
Toronto shots; the Devils had 36 shots on Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons the Maple Leafs are down by 2-1 in a
series that resumes here Thursday night is the lack of production
by their premier line of Mats Sundin centering for Jonas Hoglund
and Steve Thomas. This threesome produced 20 points in the
elimination of Ottawa in six games in the first round; against New
Jersey it has a huge zero.
</P>
<P>
   While Toronto's premier line failed, the Devils' top line of
Jason Arnott centering for Patrik Elias and Petr Sykora came alive
with a a goal from each member. The other goals came from Scott
Gomez and Alexander Mogilny.
</P>
<P>
   Elias, who had 35 goals in the regular season, also had two
assists. But it was his short-handed goal on a back-handed shot
that was the talk of the night, and left the Leafs talking to
themselves as they fell behind by 3-0 shortly before the second
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless first period that was wide open, the teams
tightened up on defense in the early stages of the second period.
The game's pace picked up again after Arnott opened the scoring
with his first goal of the playoffs, 9 minutes 42 seconds into the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the slot during the third man advantage in the game
for the Devils, Arnott scored by deflecting Bobby Holik's shot from
the left circle.
</P>
<P>
   All the speculation over whether the Devils should have benched
Gomez, the league's top-scoring rookie in the regular season, never
materialized. Gomez got the least amount of ice time among New
Jersey forwards in the first two periods, but he made an impact
near the end of the second period, when he scored his second
playoff goal.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez's goal was the second in the game for the Devils and it
was all his work. He started the scoring sequence by winning a
face-off from Kevyn Adams, and gained control of the puck as Adams
fell down in the right circle. Gomez cut into the middle and beat
Joseph with a shot under the glove with 4:57 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils continued to show more jump and desire than Toronto
for the rest of the period and were rewarded with a stunning
short-handed goal by Elias with 2:27 left in the second period.
Elias intercepted a clearing pass and skated down the right wing,
eluding a Toronto defender before he faked Joseph to his knees,
then went around the net from right to left and beat Joseph with a
backhander. It was the second playoff goal for Elias.
</P>
<P>
   The goaltending of Joseph and Brodeur highlighted a loosely
played first period that featured 25 shots on goal, 14 by the
Devils. But none found the target. For the Maple Leafs, it was the
ninth time in their nine playoff games this spring that they failed
to score in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph's biggest saves in the session came 12 minutes into the
period, , when he thwarted Holik, Randy McKay and Steve Kelly even
though he lost his stick. Luck might have played a role, too, as
one of the shots hit him while he was sitting in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   With Claude Lemieux leading the way, the Devils created traffic
in front of Joseph, but he somehow managed to pick out the puck,
infuriating Lemieux, who took a penalty for interfering with
Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's best moments in the opening period came in the 10th
minute and 17th minutes. First, he denied Igor Korolev after Devils
defenseman Colin White mishandled the puck at the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Korolev showed plenty of patience as he stood poised to shoot
from the left of Brodeur, but Brodeur was even more patient,
denying Korolev's shot and the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Seven minutes later, the crowd, again short of a sellout, gave
Brodeur a standing ovation when he stopped Dmitri Khristich's shot
and then blocked a rebound shot by sprawling in the crease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ALAIA-FASHION-ART-2TA     05-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAIA-FASHION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENIUS HAS A HABIT OF SHOWING UP EVERY SO OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In mid-May, Azzedine Alaia, the Tunisian-born designer
whose rare public displays of genius place him somewhere between
Charles James and the Shadow, will present his largest collection
in years. Many of the 117 store buyers who have been summoned are
expected to come, even though Alaia, who doesn't adhere to seasons
or the calendar, is presenting his fall clothes months behind the
rest of the fashion world.
</P>
<P>
   On top of this, a retrospective of his work is being planned for
the fall in New York, and Alaia, who ranks as one of the last real
couturiers _ he does everything, from the pattern making and
cutting to the pinning and ironing, with his own hands _ said he
will present a small couture collection during the shows here in
July, which would be a first.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Alaia has something substantial to show comes at a
time when many people in the business assume he has nothing at all.
It's not unusual to hear fashion editors say: ``Azzedine? Is he
still making clothes?'' when a visit to 7 rue de Moussy in the
Marais, where Alaia has his studio and employs 25 people, would
tell them that he is.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is hard not to feel that Alaia has managed his own
oblivion. He has done this in part by refusing, since 1992, to hold
runway shows, in the belief that they are outmoded, and in part by
delivering his clothes to stores late, or not at all. The only
American store to have carried Alaia's clothes consistently since
he began doing ready-to-wear in the early 1980s is Barneys New
York, and its executives have long been reconciled to planning
their seasonal budgets around him _ a concession granted to no
other designer. ``There is no cancellation date for him,'' J.P.
Correa, a buyer for the store.
</P>
<P>
   But while Alaia's ultra-sexy dresses may fly out the door once
they do arrive, other retailers aren't so indulgent. Jacqueline
Schnabel, who opened an Alaia boutique in the New York City
neighborhood of SoHo in 1987 when she was married to the painter
Julian Schnabel, said she had been forced to close it after five
years because of delivery problems _ a decision that drew a
characteristic reaction from Alaia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He refused to even walk on Mercer,'' said Schnabel, referring
the the SoHo street, adding with a light laugh: ``Now it's OK. He
came by a couple of years ago with Julian, and we made up.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although Alaia is diminutive in size and bears a resemblance to
Gertrude Stein, as the writer Ingrid Sischy once noted, with his
pixie bangs and round, many-dimpled face, he can be intimidating.
``He'll just sort of glare at you,'' said the photographer Michael
Roberts, ``and you'll think, `What have I done?' But he's very
funny when you get to know him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Simon Doonan of Barneys sensed a few years ago that Alaia's
prestige was slipping, he created some windows filled with glowing
fan tributes. Alaia's only response to Doonan's list of luminaries
was, ``Where is the queen mother?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of reasons at the moment to pay attention to
what Azzedine Alaia is doing. For one thing, the current revival of
'80s fashion will mean a rush of Alaia references. No designer
defined the decade with more giddy authority. Alaia's clothes _ the
studded leather gloves, the clingy skirts and stretch dresses
inspired by Egyptian mummies _ didn't just emphasize the feminine
body. They drew a circle around it and marked it with a dot. ``He
orchestrated the collision between sex and fashion,'' Doonan said.
``It looked French. It looked severe.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In those years, Alaia's atelier was like an all-hours salon,
with 3 a.m. fittings and a surfeit of supermodels. ``Everyone used
to go around and sit for hours,'' Roberts recalled. ``It became
family. Azzedine could talk on the phone, two phones, and still be
pinning clothes on models. It was fascinating. You just don't see
that kind of thing anymore. Maybe you didn't then.''
</P>
<P>
   Doonan remembers going to shows when Alaia would still be
pressing clothes at the last moment. ``Yes, the shows were totally
chaotic,'' said the model Veronica Webb. ``But let me tell you
something: Even if your shirt was still hot from the iron, you knew
you were above reproach. You might as well have had a crown and a
scepter.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Alaia isn't interested in reviving the '80s. He has put into
his archives in the basement of his house virtually every garment
he has made. It is a gold mine of style. But pull from the crowded
racks, say, a leather blouson jacket and ask him if he might repeat
it, and he will shake his head and mutter, ``No, no.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It's also true that Alaia has managed to do something rare in
the fashion world. ``He knows how to retire from the whole thing,''
said the shoe designer Manolo Blahnik. ``He was right not do any
more runway shows. Why should he do those horrible exercises, which
is like supermarket nonsense?''
</P>
<P>
   Alaia has always made clothes for private clients, but without
fanfare. Indeed, anyone who takes the trouble to drop by rue de
Moussy, where Alaia lives on the top floor with Christoph von
Weyhe, a painter who is his business manager, and a pack of dogs
and cats, might be surprised by who turns up these days. One
evening last February, Mouna Ayoub, the couture patron, came by to
discuss a long buff suede skirt that Alaia was making for her. On
another night, Bettina Graziani, a well-known model from the 1950s,
was being fitted for a suit of speckled English tweed in the
ground-floor boutique.
</P>
<P>
   And in March, at the Vanity Fair Oscar party, Carine Roitfeld
arrived straight from styling Gucci's fall ads wearing a new Alaia
gown with a leopard-stenciled calf top laced almost savagely up her
bare back. As Roitfeld said, explaining her choice that
fashion-heavy night, ``I went to Azzedine because I knew I would be
the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable thing to be so devoted to one's craft as to
be considered, almost by default, the only one. But that is exactly
what Alaia has become. He has never had backers nor licensed his
name, and though he has come close, von Weyhe said, to signing
deals for a perfume or to design another company's line (he was
approached by Dior in the early '90s), he has refused, even though
it would have meant more money. ``Quite simply, I do things how I
like to do them,'' Alaia said. ``I prefer to stay poor than to give
my name over to someone who's going to do what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Brant, an art collector who is married to the model
Stephanie Seymour, and who has been talking with the Guggenheim
Museum about doing an Alaia exhibition this fall at the Guggenheim
in SoHo, said he has tried to give Alaia financial advice, but to
no avail. Alaia certainly doesn't sell as much as he did in the
'80s, and there was a while in the mid-'90s when he didn't seem to
produce much at all.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it affected his chic or his cult much. Five years ago,
Linda Evangelista, Naomi Campbell and Christy Turlington flew in
just to model Alaia's clothes for the half-dozen retailers who were
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women will never let me be forgotten,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alaia said the business makes enough money to support his staff.
His one indulgence seems to be buying vintage couture clothes _
Charles James, Adrian, Vionnet. One imagines that this is his way
of communing with kindred spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Lesage, the embroidery maker, who has known Alaia for
years, said: ``It is easier to look at Azzedine's place in the
fashion world than to explain it. He is a little bit like a temple
of fashion. His sensibility is so much in opposition to the way to
act, to live today, that he reminds me of Balenciaga. He loves to
talk and laugh, but when he is alone, he's alone.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As much as Alaia enjoys paradox, and is frequently as vague as a
child, his clothes have always expressed an exceptional clarity.
They are about cut, line, silhouette. And it makes you realize just
how much contemporary fashion is based on obscuring the lack of
invention or thought with gimmicks and cheap revivalism. Alaia, who
usually stays up until 5 a.m. sewing and watching old movies (and
gets up again at 9 a.m.), will often spend months perfecting a cut
or pattern. For his latest collection, he has been working on
leather kilts with tiny flowers embroidered on the pleats. The
process started more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Correa has watched Alaia's ideas evolve, too, and he said he may
even see, later in May, a few things for next spring. But it's all
right if he doesn't. ``I see hundreds of collections a year, but
the trips I make to Azzedine's are the highlight of my year,''
Correa said. ``In my entire career, I will never see it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
