<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-01 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LEAFS CARRY THE BEACON FOR CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Toronto Maple Leafs have their own
burden of failure, their personal cross to bear, without taking on
an entire country's as well. Thirty-three years without a Stanley
Cup or even a trip to the finals is well along the road to other
droughts of lore, but there can be no getting around the
inescapable and nationalistic truth.
</P>
<P>
   The drying out of Canada as a once-bottomless well of National
Hockey League champions illuminates the Leafs as the last team from
north of the border not to go south before the second round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to confuse Edmonton and Ottawa, the only other
qualifying Canadian teams this season, with those erstwhile outfits
from Winnipeg and Quebec that have actually emigrated deep into
Nielsen Land, or any others trying to resist the bottom-line urge.
But those teams are also part of the wagon-train reality of NHL
2000, the slow and sad expatriation of the Canadian game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there is a more nationalistic approach around us because
the economics have affected the ability of the Canadian teams to
compete,'' said Pat Quinn, the Maple Leafs coach, before the Devils
wasted his team, 5-1, Monday night in Game 3 of the Eastern
Conference semifinals that the Devils lead, 2-1. ``You just hope
your players don't feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful the Leafs are feeling anything more than the
frustration of the Devils shutting them out for five straight
periods, or until it didn't matter last night. While there was no
trademark contrast of styles on a night the Devils opened up and
embarrassed Toronto at its own game, there remains the obvious
polarity of what and whom these franchises represent.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Quinn contended, the Leafs are as important to
English-speaking Canada as the Yankees are to baseball-worshipping
America, then this particular series symbolically boils down to
Canadian Yankees versus YankeeNets, the pride of a nation against
the identity-challenged, sellout-deprived boys from the 'burbs. It
is another battle in the failing holy war to prevent the sport from
being ripped from its roots, for the sake of better arena and
television deals.
</P>
<P>
   If the Leafs don't rally, this will be the seventh consecutive
year that the Stanley Cup has not spent the off-season on Canadian
soil, a record. The six years from 1936 to 1941 matches the current
streak, one obliterated by Canada's domination between 1956 and
1990, when it captured 26 of 35 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Summers up north have been getting colder and drier, with
nothing to drink from. After Montreal won in 1993, Quinn's
Vancouver Canucks became the last Canadian team of the decade to
reach the finals, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest does wane,'' Quinn said, describing the malaise that
overtakes Canada as it watches the playoffs sink deeper into
America's Sun Belt. It's as if the Expos were playing the Blue Jays
every October, and if no radical restructuring of the game's
finances is done, Quinn agreed the possibility exists that Toronto
and Montreal, the original Canadian two, could eventually be the
only two left.
</P>
<P>
   In Vancouver, the 1994 run to Game 7 in Madison Square Garden
already feels as dated (for different reasons) as it does in New
York. ``They've had staggering losses over the last two years,''
Quinn said. ``What can you do? The players get a disproportionate
share of the money. It's not their fault. We give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   With more Americans and Europeans in the NHL, there is less
sentiment for smaller Canadian markets. Even Garry Valk, the Leafs
left winger who grew up in Edmonton and deplores the negativism he
hears every summer at home in Vancouver, said he doubts many
Canadian players would resent more teams relocating to the States.
</P>
<P>
   The players have become conditioned by the owners and the league
marketing gurus who pose as front-office visionaries and measure
the soul of a sport by the dollar it turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare what Calgary can offer to what an Anaheim
can,'' Valk said. ``It's that way in baseball, and it's that way in
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, Valk and Tie Domi said they and their
teammates pulled for Montreal and Vancouver as those teams made
unsuccessful late-season playoff runs. ``You want to see as many
Canadian teams as possible because they need the postseason
revenue,'' Valk said. ``It's good for hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, what players root for bears little consequence to
what they'll sign for. American cities with little hockey
orientation have greater revenue potential, foretelling a day when
Canada's string of cup-less years could be as long as the Leafs'. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
