<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-REPORT-COX     05-01 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-REPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tradition in turmoil
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investigators today (Tuesday) will disclose their theory on why
the Texas A&AMP;M University bonfire collapsed in November, killing 12
and injuring 27. But the university-appointed commission will not
recommend whether the 90-year-old custom should continue. That
decision falls to Texas A&AMP;M, a university synonymous with
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, it may seem strange that a dozen deaths would not
extinguish a bonfire _ no matter how big, celebrated and cherished.
To Frank Cox III, author of 'I Bleed Maroon,' a book on A&AMP;M's
traditions, the thought of eliminating the bonfire is what seems
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that,'' said Cox, who graduated in 1965. ``To
stop it would be a slap in the face of those who gave their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cox promotes an idea of his son's, also an Aggie: A
safe bonfire surrounded by 12 smaller bonfires commemorating the
twelve deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the investigation, and as A&AMP;M officials weigh
their options, Aggies will be left trying to explain what the
bonfire represents.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, Aggies call it Bonfire. ``It's like saying, 'I'm
going to church.' You don't say I'm going to the church,'' Cox
explains. ``It's an event that doesn't need a 'the' in front of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire is immense in physical terms, commitment and
influence over the Aggie faithful. What began as a trash fire in
1909 had become a full-scale logging and construction project,
culminating in bonfires of record-book size.
</P>
<P>
   It includes 6,000 to 8,000 logs and is supposed to stand 55 feet
tall. The record bonfire was 109 feet, 10 inches. The incomplete
bonfire that collapsed last year was 4 feet above the 55-foot
height limit.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire involves 5,000 students cutting, loading and
stacking logs; 700 gallons of diesel to ignite it and an estimated
125,000 work-hours spent building and torching it.
</P>
<P>
   Even beyond the shared experience of building such a structure,
the bonfire's communal reach is awesome. Students and faculty watch
the mountain of logs rise on campus each fall. Aggies around the
world watch its progress on the university's Web page. Tens of
thousands witness the burning in person. It's televised locally for
those who do not brave the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   To measure the bonfire's meaning is more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Constructed over two months and burned before the football game
with A&AMP;M's rival, the University of Texas, the bonfire is intended
to demonstrate the Aggies' ``burning desire to beat the hell out of
t.u.'' In the common Aggie refrain, t.u. is meant as a derogatory
reference to UT.
</P>
<P>
   At times it has been marred by drinking, hazing and horseplay.
But Aggies say critics _ including some fellow Aggies _ are wrong
to dismiss the bonfire as a waste of time and natural resources for
a drunken pep rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think we throw a lot of sticks together as an excuse to
get drunk,'' said Ryan Nelson, a senior who has worked on the
bonfire for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Nelson said, ``It embodies the fraternal spirt of the
student body at A&AMP;M, the willingness to devote themselves to Aggie
tradition and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that 12 died building last year's bonfire has made some
even more dedicated to that spirit and optimistic about the
bonfire's future.
</P>
<P>
   Jerretta Holmes, an 18-year-old freshman, said she wants to help
build the bonfire next year, should it continue.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths, she said, ``make me want to participate more.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, a biomedical student, planned to watch the commission's
public release of the report on television in her dorm room today.
</P>
<P>
   Her longtime friend Charmika May, also a freshman, didn't agree.
An industrial engineering student, she said she wants to know first
how the commission reached its conclusion and what steps will be
made to make the bonfire safe before deciding whether it should
continue and whether she would take part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play by the rules,'' she said. ``It takes only one
person to die for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire is just one of A&AMP;M's litany of traditions. Aggies
around the world recognize all the Aggies who have died the
previous year during a ceremony called Muster; they have a campus
ceremony for Aggies who died the past month, Silver Taps; and
Aggies stand during football games as the Twelfth Man ready to
enter the game if needed. Those are just a few of the prominent
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the common joke is, ``If it happens more than once
at Texas A&AMP;M, it's a tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   No campus event other than the bonfire, however, is big enough
to unite so many, said Forrest Lane, a member of the A&AMP;M's military
Corps and student body president. He said it not only brings
together the thousands who build it, but its influence permeates
the campus and the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels they have a piece of this tradition and this
university,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire maintains its hold on many graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Buster, a construction sciences major who graduated in
1998, commutes the 90 miles from College Station to his full-time
job of pouring foundations in Houston. Each autumn he helps A&AMP;M
students building the stack: ``Bonfire is one of the main reasons I
stay in town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buster said he was at the stack of logs just an hour before it
collapsed about 2:30 a.m. Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Buster is not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Breen, 25 and a 1997 graduate visiting the campus to
help with the bonfire, was one of the dozen who died.
</P>
<P>
   Even longtime graduates cherish the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan lawyer Bill Youngkin, who graduated in 1969, was the head
yell leader and in charge of building the bonfire. He said he
remembers a great sense of accomplishment _ not for himself, but
for his fellow Aggies _ as they built a bonfire towering toward 100
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us seldom do something that people can visually see
and say, 'Oh, my gosh,''' Youngkin said. ``You can do that at Texas
A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Youngkin has two daughters at A&AMP;M. He said both have worked on
the bonfire and he understands that it must be made safer _ a
feeling expressed by other Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's determined that we were just lucky in the past, and we
expose kids to death every time they do it, we can live without
it,'' he said. ``Nobody wants to risk life and injury for this _
that's a sacrifice for family and country,'' Youngkin said. ``But
I'd like to believe it can be made safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who also was a head yell leader in charge of the bonfire in
the mid-1960s, agrees the multilayered bonfire can be made safe:
``I don't care if it's five stacks, four stacks or three, as long
as they let the students have the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said he would support increasing adult supervision and
putting more of the building instructions in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty amazing that there haven't been more
accidents with people that young passing on most of that
information by word-of-mouth and on-the-job training,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox warns that the students must have the responsibility for
running the bonfire or they will lose the benefit of ``learning to
be leaders instead of bosses.'' He said the bonfire spirit would be
lost if the university removed students from the leadership roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be Bonfire if an engineering company came in and
built the biggest, most beautiful bonfire ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the university goes too far and curtails the bonfire beyond
recognition, Cox said, ``Knowing the Aggies, knowing the Corps,
they would find a way to have it off campus.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Laylan Copelin at lcopelin(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
