<HEADER>
A2862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-01 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BRAVES ARE STILL IN A LEAGUE OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not even John Schuerholz, baseball's master architect, is
exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The team he designed and has redesigned annually was riding a
13-game winning streak Monday, and where was Schuerholz? Not in Los
Angeles, where the Braves were going for No. 14 Monday night. Not
in Richmond, Va., or Myrtle Beach, S.C., scrutinizing the
organization's minor league talent for the next Rafael Furcal. Not
even at his desk in the Braves' offices at 755 Hank Aaron Drive.
</P>
<P>
   No, John Schuerholz was in an Atlanta courthouse on jury duty.
Well, better Schuerholz than Andres Galarraga or Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz, however, could be away from the office and away from
the team content with the knowledge that the Braves are yet again
the wonder of Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Yankees are in first place in pursuit of their third
consecutive World Series championship and the St. Louis Cardinals
are bashing everyone in sight and the Chicago White Sox have
captured the attention of people looking for good young teams and
Chuck Finley has the Cleveland Indians thinking that yes, this
could be the year they beat the darn Yankees, and Pedro Martinez
and Randy Johnson are staging an every-fifth-day domination of
their teams' opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But over there at the side, quietly going about their business,
not letting anyone forget that they are the one constant Major
League Baseball has had for a decade, are the Braves. Eight
successive seasons as division champions, the Braves have the best
won-lost record in sight en route to No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   As much frustration as the Braves have suffered by winning only
one World Series in those eight years, they inflict even more
frustration on teams trying to keep up with or overtake them. In
the immediate instance, the team that most fits that description is
the Mets, a wild-card team seriously seeking entry to the
postseason party as a division winner. Yet, before Monday night's
games, the Mets had won 11 of their last 14 games and had lost two
and a half games in the National League East standing to the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half weeks ago, neither team was in first place, but
the Braves were a half game closer to it than the Mets. When they
began their games on the West Coast Monday night, the Braves were
in first place and the Mets were in second, three games back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not frustrating yet,'' Steve Phillips, the Mets' general
manager, said by telephone after arriving in San Francisco Monday.
``It's less frustrating this early in the season than if it was
July or August and we put a run like that together. But it's to be
expected. We didn't expect the Braves to fold up and go away. They
won 104 games last year without Galarraga and without Lopez for
most of the season. You know they're going to win their share of
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' share of victories is just greater than other teams'
shares. In 1993, for example, the Giants won 103 games, but the
Braves won 104. The difference developed on the last day of the
season. The teams began that day with 103 victories each and a
share of first place but ended it traveling in different
directions, the Braves to the playoffs, the Giants home. These
days, at least, a team in the Giants' position could be the
wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the Braves have a very good team,''
Phillips said. ``They're not missing a beat this year. They're
hitting on all cylinders now. I feel good that with the streak
they've put together, we're only three games behind. We're not
hitting on all cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive of the Braves' eight cylinders is Galarraga,
whose comeback has been as phenomenal as any has ever been. The
venerable Venezuelan missed all of last season undergoing treatment
for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and now, seven weeks shy of his 39th
birthday, he is among the National League leaders in home runs
(10), runs batted in (24) and slugging percentage (.683).
</P>
<P>
   When Schuerholz was designing the 2000 Braves last winter, he
figured that if the first baseman could come back, it would be as
if the team had acquired an additional player. It was one fewer
trade he had to make or free agent he had to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Lopez is back, too, recovering successfully from knee
surgery for a torn ligament and rendering false the whispers around
the league that had suggested he would never catch again.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the initial uncertainty about Galarraga and Lopez, the
Braves faced fallout from the John Rocker suspension for boorish
verbal behavior and the problem of replacing John Smoltz, one of
their top pitching stalwarts, whose injured elbow knocked him out
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocker issue proved to be no distraction. The closer, in
fact, returned after the first victory of the winning streak and
gained five saves in a nine-victory span. Smoltz's absence has yet
to be felt, too. Terry Mulholland, his replacement, was the winning
pitcher in the first game of the winning streak as well as the 5th
and the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux has been himself (4-0, 2.49 earned run average) and
Glavine has been spectacular (5-0, 1.80) as the Braves' pitching
staff has compiled a 3.08 ERA, putting it in a league of its own.
The next lowest ERA in the majors is Boston's 3.76; in the NL, it
is Arizona's 3.86.
</P>
<P>
   In completing the design for this season's team, Schuerholz and
Manager Bobby Cox decided to combine youth with experience at
shortstop. With the 36-year-old Walt Weiss in place, they added
Furcal, a 19-year-old Dominican, who had not played above the minor
leagues' Class A.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the move has worked. With Cox dividing their
playing time evenly, Weiss has a .447 on-base percentage, Furcal
.392. It's just another cylinder that Schuerholz did not have to
worry about as he sat in the jury room Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
