<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARANGUING ABOVE THE RIM BEGINS BETWEEN KNICKS AND HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the surreal instant that Tim Hardaway's blind
fling at the basket dropped through the net on April 9 in Miami,
the Heat players spun, leaped and threw up their arms as if they
were children hearing the last school bell of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a buzzer, not a bell. And it was the regular season,
not a title. It merely seemed like something much bigger because of
the Heat's response to their dramatic overtime victory against
their nemesis, the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pieces of the puzzle are all falling into place,'' Alonzo
Mourning said that evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``About time something went right for us against them,''
Hardaway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a coincidence that there were 4.7 seconds
on the clock; that's about the same amount of time when Allan
Houston bounced his in last year _ ironic,'' said Coach Pat Riley,
drawing a comparison to Miami's interrupted playoff run a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the background of the Heat's jubilation, some of the Knicks
smirked inwardly. One Knick said privately, ``You think they'd
really won something.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one game of 82. Only a Heat team finishing off a season
series with a 3-1 edge against the Knicks. But as the Knicks proved
with the completion of a three-game sweep of Toronto over the
weekend, the regular season does not set a precedent for the
playoffs. The Raptors had a 3-1 edge, too, in the regular season,
but it was the Knicks who advanced.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, in the sun-baked city that has become their second
home, the Knicks will open their four-of-seven-game, second-round
playoff series against _ who else? _ the Heat, at American Airlines
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said that Toronto beat us up in the regular season,''
Patrick Ewing said after the Knicks eliminated the Raptors in Game
3 on Sunday. ``They'll be saying that same thing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, few people bought into Coach Jeff Van Gundy's artful
attempt to cast his playoff-tested Knicks as the desperate
underdogs against a Raptor team led by a neophyte star like Vince
Carter. While the Heat is battle tested, the team seems a bit
spooked by its New York rivals, who have eliminated them on their
home floor two years in a row. Along with their frustration, there
has been palpable contempt for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate them with all the hate that you can hate with,''
Hardaway once said. ``Can you hate more than that? If you can, I
hate them more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound bites like these merely amuse the Knicks. While they
respect the Heat, they lick their lips and rub their hands together
at the thought of eliminating Miami once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to this challenge,'' Larry Johnson said.
``It's an up note for us, nothing but happy feelings around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The regular season does not even register in the Knicks' minds.
It does not matter if they shot only 42.1 percent against the Heat
in their four games, or if Mourning mauled them for 33 points on
April 9. It does not matter if Latrell Sprewell shot only 37.7
percent in the shadow of Jamal Mashburn this season, or if Chris
Childs hit only 22.7 percent of his shots against Hardaway. It does
not matter if the Knicks lost three games by a total of 16 points,
or won one of them at Madison Square Garden by an impressive score
of 94-80.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them at their place when Tim hit that miracle shot,''
Marcus Camby said. ``We're confident we can beat them there, on
their floor. We didn't play well against them in the regular
season, but this is the playoffs. People said we couldn't get it
done in Toronto because they handled us in the regular season, but
it didn't end up that way at all. We went there and took care of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   With time to dissect the Raptors, Van Gundy came up with the
right double-team plan _ which was implemented by a focused
Sprewell _ and the Knicks took the ball out of Carter's hands. With
no sure-fire teammates around Carter to deliver, the scheme worked.
Now, Van Gundy has five days ahead of him to prepare his team. Has
he fallen in love with the once forbidden double team? Probably
not.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat is an entirely different team than the Raptors. As
Childs put it, ``We look at them and we're looking into the
mirror.'' If anything, Van Gundy will have to purge the Knicks of
any false confidence coming off their series with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's back to work,'' Sprewell said. ``We have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat players are steeling themselves as well. It may have
seemed like a turning point against their rival at the time, but
April 9 is forever ago. And the regular season is long gone, too.
Even the Heat realizes that now. Since Hardaway's wild shot sent
the team into an uncharacteristic frenzy, the players have come
down to earth. ``These are two evenly matched teams,'' Heat forward
P.J. Brown said Monday after practice in Miami. ``It's a
flip-of-the-coin type of thing. It comes down to who plays the
hardest, like the last game played against them. It came down to
who was more desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a playoff situation, but it definitely felt good
to get those guys. I see the highlights of the ending, and say,
`Wow, what a wild shot.' It helped us, but the regular season
doesn't matter. We all thought Toronto-New York was going to be a
better series, but look what happened.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
