u s BC-RAC-PLETCHER-NYT &LR;      05-01 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PLETCHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STUNNING DEBUT IN DERBY: TRAINER SADDLES FOUR HORSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ J.J. Pletcher remembers the young boy who got
so angry when one of his father's horses lost a race that he would
lie down in a stall and kick and cry. He remembers the young man so
eager to become a trainer that as soon as graduation ceremonies
were over at the University of Arizona, father and son drove
overnight toward New York and Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   There, J.J. turned Todd Pletcher over to another horseman's son
to put polish on the lessons begun on the dusty back sides of
grits-and-hard-toast tracks in places like Bossier City, La., and
Hot Springs, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   On Pletcher's first day, Jeff Lukas, dad D.Wayne's top
assistant, handed him the lead of an expensive horse, one named
Houston who had led the 1989 Kentucky Derby for a mile before
fading to an eighth-place finish behind Sunday Silence.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let him get loose, Jeff Lukas told Pletcher. He held on to
Houston with both hands then, and now, at 32, Pletcher has
demonstrated he has retained every horse lesson ever imparted to
him, from his days mucking stalls with his father to graduating
from the Lukas finishing school in 1995 and starting his own
stable.
</P>
<P>
   In a year where perhaps eight trainers will make their Kentucky
Derby debut, Pletcher's bow is still extraordinary. He will saddle
four starters, which in the 125 years of the race is a number
matched by only James Rowe Sr. in 1923 and exceeded only once, by
Lukas in 1996. Better is that all of his entries have proved on the
oval that they belong.
</P>
<P>
   In Graeme Hall and Impeachment, he has the Arkansas Derby (Grade
II) winner and third-place finisher. His colt Trippi captured the
Flamingo (Grade III). And Pletcher's More Than Ready lost the
Bluegrass (Grade I) by a head, has won 6 of his 10 races and has
been in the money in all but one graded stakes race.
</P>
<P>
   ``In April, I was hoping I might have More Than Ready in place
to go, but then we got the big races from the other three, too, and
it was clear they all earned their way into the race,'' Pletcher
said. ``Sure we're fortunate, but the people in our program have
worked hard to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   The influence of the Lukas program is evident in Pletcher's
crisp presentation. His barns, whether here or at the home base for
his 80 horses in New York, could pass for sidewalk cafes: manicured
landscapes, silk saddlecloths and monogrammed blankets. The morning
muckout of stalls resembles a swift, silent square dance; the
grooms march into the cubicles as the hot walkers circle the horses
outside.
</P>
<P>
   But Pletcher also displays a wry, salty streak inherited from
his father, a Texan with a catalog of tales from his days
crisscrossing quarter-horse and second-tier thoroughbred tracks
across the South and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The father hoped a college education might keep his son away
from the unpredictable milieu of the back side. ``I told him he was
going to college and he was going to know what he wanted to
study,'' said J.J. Pletcher, who won 370 races as a trainer,
including the 1982 Oaklawn Handicap with Uncool. ``I helped him get
summer jobs with Charlie Whittingham and Lukas. He also learned
from my mistakes. I could never juice an owner into paying so much
money for a horse. I wanted him to have the option to do something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, when his assistant trainer and primary exercise
rider, Cindy Hutter, returned from an impressive workout aboard
Trippi, who went six furlongs in 1:12.96, Pletcher sounded like his
father in feigning being upset. ``I told Cindy I wanted him to go
in 1:13,'' he said. ``Four one-hundredths off. I'll scold her
later.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also perhaps more flexible than Lukas, as his handling of
More Than Ready this year has demonstrated. As a 2-year-old, the
smallish black colt ticked off five brilliant victories in a row at
sprint distances, including the WHAS Stakes here on Derby day. But
after spiking a fever that interrupted his late-summer training,
More Than Ready finished third by a half-length in the Futurity at
Belmont and followed it with a desultory fifth place in the
Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The colt was shipped to Lexington and what is the equivalent of
the equine Mayo Clinic for extensive tests. Veterinarians found
nothing wrong. So while many wrote off the colt as a precocious and
perhaps broken-down sprinter, Pletcher and his owner, Jim
Scatuorchio, did not.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pletcher prepared More Than Ready for the Derby with
three races of increasing distances. The colt was a dead-heat
winner in the seven-furlong Hutcheson, was passed in the final
yards in the one-and-one-sixteenth-mile Louisiana Derby (Grade II)
and, after showing he could rate behind horses, dueled through the
stretch before losing to High Yield in the one-and-one-eighth-mile
Blue Grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a detail guy, an incredibly hard worker,'' Scatuorchio
said. ``But what has really been impressive is his ability to come
up with a plan and his patience to stick to it. There were times I
think both of us thought about walking him over to the Fountain of
Youth or Florida Derby because he was doing so well. He wouldn't,
and that's why we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid off. Four of the horses who beat or tied him _ Bevo,
Greenwood Lake, Mighty and Summer Note _ are injured and not here
for the Derby. More Than Ready, on the other hand, is a dead-fit
threat to wrestle the Derby away from the likely favorites,
Fusaichi Pegasus, War Chant, The Deputy and High Yield. The colt
worked a brisk five furlongs in 1:00 4/5 Monday, which was even
more impressive because Hutter all but dragged her feet on the
ground to keep the obviously More Than Ready in hand. ``We're in
business,'' was the assessment of Pletcher, a onetime animal
science major.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens the first Saturday in May, Pletcher has
grown out of the behavior that sent him to his father's horse
stalls after a loss. Asked how much it might hurt his former boss
if one of his four horses runs down Lukas' High Yield at the wire,
he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``About as much it hurt me when he got me in the Blue Grass,''
he said. ``And I'll take it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
