r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     05-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS EXPECT DIFFERENT SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ This is how mortal Shaquille O'Neal _ the NBA's
pre-eminent scoring machine, muscleman and all-around Superman _
looked Sunday afternoon: He asked out of the game during the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For a breather. For a cup of water. For a chance to re-gather
his game, which was inexplicably out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal _ whose every vehicle has a spiffy Superman ``S'' emblem
stamped on it _ appearing, gulp, human? What happened to the guy
with the cape?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was Clark (Kent) yesterday,'' O'Neal quipped Monday
afternoon, a day after the Lakers' 99-91 defeat to the Sacramento
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But even with O'Neal playing more like Clark Kent, mild-mannered
reporter (!ital!there's a funny concept), the Lakers had their
chances to win Game 3. And with a 2-1 lead in the best-of-five
series, and another shot at eliminating the Kings tonight, the
Lakers are confident their superhero will return to form to finish
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about Shaq,'' Ron Harper said. ``Shaq knows how
to play the game. And he knows that he missed some easy shots, and
he knows that he didn't play well. But we also, as guys on the
team, have to get him some good help, too, at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, O'Neal's 8-for-22 day wasn't his worst of this
MVP season. But it was ill-timed.
</P>
<P>
   Some early fouls probably inhibited him, some pesky Kings
defense disrupted him, forced him out of prime post position. But
in the end, O'Neal said it was ``Just one of those days, brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it the best defense Sacramento has played against O'Neal or
just him having a bad day? ``Just me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all just have to come out and do our part,'' O'Neal said.
``I'm going to do my part. I'm sure the other guys will do their
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Lakers are hoping for more from Glen Rice (13
points Sunday) and from the bench corps (11 points), everyone
understands it comes down to O'Neal _ their statistical and
emotional leader _ to knock the air of renewed confidence out of
the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Neal who had to catch his breath in Game 3. In a rare
moment, he asked out of the game for a rest with 9:01 left in the
fourth, the Lakers clinging to a 74-73 lead. The Lakers trailed by
a point when he returned two minutes later and they never took a
lead again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hung in there for a little bit, but then we lost it,''
coach Phil Jackson said. ``We lost it on a sequence of a few
turnovers and a couple of rebounding efforts by their team that got
the ball back for them, and (Peja) Stojakovic hit a 3-pointer that
put them over the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their players were really animated by that energy that the
crowd picked up, and it looked like it depleted us. We were the
team that was reacting instead of acting.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal also made just 5 of 14 free throws and, as usual, felt he
was fouled a lot more often than was called. Jackson said the
Kings' strategy is to drive at O'Neal, hope fouls are called and
get him off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's problematic for him to be fouled a lot, maybe not
complete the free throws, be fouled a lot and not have them
called,'' Jackson said. ``A couple things happened to him out there
where all (the Kings) did was take the ball at Shaq and try to make
the referees call the foul on him, even though there were a couple
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those things, I think, exacerbated his mental toughness,
and that's the area which I think is difficult to overcome for
Shaquille. . . . I think it wears the guy out (mentally).''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, whose 35 points kept the Lakers afloat, expects his
tag-team partner to return with a vengeance tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have a better game. A lot better,'' Bryant said.
``We all know Shaq, we all know what he did over this entire
season.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Kings. And they expect a different O'Neal, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to come out smoking,'' said Kings guard Jon
Barry, a former Laker. ``I know he's upset. . . . I don't think he
got the ball much in the fourth quarter. We did a good job. I think
that's a combination of us and them. They started to rush some
shots in the fourth and I don't think he touched the ball. I don't
think he was real happy about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
