<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA FINALLY HONORS KING  
 BABBITT NOT RUNNING FOR GOVERNOR  
 RUBIN NOT INTERESTED IN VICE PRESIDENCY  
 NADER DISCUSSES ENDORSEMENT WITH UAW LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the signature of Gov. Jim Hodges, South Carolina Monday
became the last state to honor the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. with
an official holiday. The bill was signed despite protests from the
NAACP, which had opposed the legislation because it also created
Confederate Memorial Day on May 10. The organization said two such
contrasting ideologies should not be linked. A spokesman for Hodges
said that Hodges would have preferred a bill honoring only King but
had to accept the Confederate holiday as the price for passage. The
NAACP has also objected to a state Senate bill, now before the
House, to move the Confederate battle flag from the Capitol dome to
a memorial in front of the building. Meanwhile, officials in North
Carolina said that despite the furor in South Carolina, a
Confederate flag would be over the Capitol in Raleigh on May 10, as
is required annually under a legislative decree.
</P>
<P>
   BABBIT TO RETURN HOME
</P>
<P>
   There has been considerable speculation in Arizona that once
Bruce Babbit finished his tour as secretary of the interior, he
would return to the state to run for governor, a job he held from
1978 to 1986. But Babbitt said over the weekend that he had other
plans. He would return to Arizona, he told The Arizona Republic,
but not to run for governor. ``I'm out of politics, but I'm back to
Arizona,'' he said. ``I'm a little homesick. I want to re-engage as
a citizen.'' He did not say what he planned to do. But he made it
clear that he was tired of Washington's ``witch-hunting
mentality,'' referring to the 19- month investigation into his
handling of permits for Indian reservation casinos. He was cleared
of any wrongdoing. ``Maybe I was the poster child for the repeal of
the independent counsel statute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN PLAYS DOWN SPOT ON TICKET
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin, one of many prominent
Democrats mentioned as a potential running mate for Vice President
Al Gore, seemed to reject the idea Monday, calling it ``a curious
notion.'' Discussing economic policy and what he saw as key issues
in the campaign, Rubin said that while he has been around politics
for many years, including a stint as a Democratic fund-raiser, he
viewed running for and serving in office as a special field,
``something unto itself.'' Rubin suggested that it was unwise to
choose a nominee who has not been tested by other campaigns. ``You
don't want somebody in a presidential campaign, which is the
ultimate of political experience in this country, who hasn't been
tested by running before.'' Rubin spoke on Political Points, the
Webcast of The New York Times and ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   THE GREENS
</P>
<P>
   NADER COURTS AUTOWORKERS
</P>
<P>
   The consumer advocate and Green Party presidential candidate
Ralph Nader discussed an endorsement Monday with leaders of the
United Automobile Workers in Detroit. Nader said that he did not
directly ask for an endorsement and that the union would not
endorse a candidate until after a congressional vote, scheduled for
late May, on establishing permanent normal trade relations with
China. Nader, the autoworkers and other major unions oppose the
bill. Union officials were unavailable for comment. The union,
which has criticized President Clinton's trade policies, broke with
the AFL-CIO in October, when the labor federation endorsed Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
