<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-MARATHON-MORRIS-N     05-01 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-MORRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORRIS MADE HIS MOVE LONG BEFORE THE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After finishing 10th at the 1996 Olympic marathon trials, an
effort that brought him little recognition and not enough money to
file a tax return, David Morris made a radical change in both his
life and his career.
</P>
<P>
   American distance running was floundering. Morris questioned
whether athletes in the United States were dedicated enough,
willing to run punishing miles in training, to regain their
competitiveness in an event dominated by Africans, Japanese,
Europeans and Mexicans. So he moved to Japan in May of 1997, began
running with a corporate-sponsored team and trained up to 176 miles
a week, 25 to 50 miles more than conventional workouts.
</P>
<P>
   He was largely unknown, so it stunned the American running
community last October when Morris finished fourth at the Chicago
Marathon in 2 hours 9 minutes 32 seconds. That time is considered
the official American record because it was run on a certified loop
course; however, most people consider Bob Kempainen's 2:08:47, run
at the 1994 Boston Marathon, a point-to-point course, to be the
real national record.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Morris has emerged as a bright exception to a generally
bleak American distance landscape. He and Joe LeMay enter Sunday's
Olympic trials in Pittsburgh as the only American marathoners to
have achieved the ``A'' qualifying standard of 2:14 for the 2000
Summer Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of felt Americans were missing something as far as
training goes,'' Morris, who will be 30 on May 17, said yesterday
on a conference call, explaining why he moved to Japan. ``Everyone
says Americans are soft.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much uncertainty about Sunday's race, given the
potentially hot weather, Pittsburgh's hilly course and the
unsettled status of Khalid Khannouchi, the marathon world
record-holder from Morocco who is trying to gain American
citizenship. Harry Gee, Khannouchi's Houston-based attorney, said
in a recent interview that he was optimistic that Khannouchi would
have his citizenship by Thursday. However, marathon officials said
privately that Khannouchi may not run because of a sore hamstring
and ankle aggravated during a third-place finish at the London
Marathon on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's a citizen, he should be entitled to run,'' Morris said
of Khannouchi, who set the world record of 2:05:42 at Chicago last
fall. ``I would just run to make the team pretty much. I'm not
going to chase after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the tattered state of American distance running, Morris
said he thought it could become a trend, with international
athletes gaining American citizenship and supplanting American-born
runners in major events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture and lifestyle aren't conducive to distance
running,'' said Morris, who has a degree in computer science from
the University of Montana. ``People don't want to work hard at
running and make a long-term commitment. They want to take a tech
job and make money. People from less fortunate countries come here,
work hard and can make a lot of money and can make the national
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Going to Japan to train for an Olympic marathon is not without
precedent. A Japan-based Kenyan named Eric Wainaina finished third
at the Atlanta Olympics. Morris settled in Hamamatsu, about 200
miles southwest of Tokyo, where he was sponsored in a group of 18
runners by Honda. He was paid a salary that required him to make an
appearance for half a day at the Honda factory, where he mostly
studied Japanese and answered e-mail messages. Essentially, the
sinecure allowed him to focus on his training.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans often concentrate on speed training, the
Japanese are more geared to endurance training _ higher mileage and
longer tempo runs. An average week consisted of 100-120 miles, but
one week a month, the group trained three times a day for a total
of 140 to 160 to 176 miles, with tempo runs of 12.5 miles to 30
miles, Morris said. It took six months before he could make it
through the workouts at the required speed, and a year before the
training began to result in improved racing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally I'm a lot tougher in having three years of 100 miles
a week in my legs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Morris returned to the United States, where he
lives frugally with a friend in Missoula, Mont., and has shuttled
to altitude in New Mexico every few weeks, not having a house of
his own. He grew up in Eagle River, Alaska, a suburb of Anchorage,
where he avoided video games and walked a mile to school. He
coaches himself, and on Sunday, he will learn whether his unusual
methods have made him an Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen myself as having a desk job,'' Morris said.
``I've always been good at running. When I was 10th in the '96
trials, I knew if I got in real good training, it would be my turn
to make the team in 2000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
