<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: ORANGEMEN CANCEL
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order has canceled a May 28 march in Dublin that
would have been the Protestant group's first there since 1937. Ian
Cox, an Orange official, said he took the action because the order,
widely viewed as anti-Catholic, had received ``abusive letters and
phone calls'' and city officials had ``abandoned'' the organizers.
The order holds hundreds of parades in Northern Ireland in the
annual ``marching season,'' which began last week.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: POLICE BODIES FOUND
</P>
<P>
   The military said it had found the bodies of nine Russian
policemen near the Chechen town of Vedeno. The policemen came from
the Perm region of Russia and were part of a column ambushed on
March 29. The discovery raises the death toll from that ambush to
at least 36. Chechen rebels claim to have taken the nine policemen
prisoner and executed them after Moscow refused to turn over a
Russian officer accused of killing a Chechen woman.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: HEALTH SPENDING
</P>
<P>
   Of more than $56 billion spent each year on health research,
less than 10 percent goes to conditions, including tuberculosis and
malaria, that account for 90 percent of the world's health
problems, a Geneva-based health group said. Health research is
disproportionately focused on diseases of concern to high-income
countries, the report said. The study said pneumonia and diarrheal
diseases are the biggest killers, but only one-fifth of 1 percent
of research dollars is spent on them.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: GOVERNOR REMOVED
</P>
<P>
   Ending an impeachment trial, the supreme court of Morelos State
ruled that Gov. Jorge Carrillo Olea ``never showed any interest in
upholding the principle of legality'' during his tenure. The court
removed Carrillo from office and barred him from holding any public
post for 12 years. Carrillo took a leave of absence in 1998 amid a
widening kidnapping and narcotics scandal, but kept his title as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: MAY 28 RUNOFF
</P>
<P>
   The runoff vote between President Alberto Fujimori and Alejandro
Toledo will be held May 28, the National Election Board said. The
date was announced after the board received final returns from the
April 9 first round election, in which neither candidate received
the required majority. Polls show the vote will be close.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: EXTRADITION REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   The government has formally rejected a request by Judge Baltasar
Garzon of Spain to arrest ex-military leaders for the deaths of
Spaniards during the 1976-83 dictatorship, according to judicial
documents. The request was rejected because it was not accompanied
by a demand for extradition, the documents showed. The position
taken by President Fernando de la Rua is close to that of former
President Carlos Saul Menem.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLERS REMOVED
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, soldiers forcibly removed settlers
from a hilltop in the West Bank. This short-lived, makeshift
encampment, reflecting a growing protest movement by the settlers,
was in the Nablus area.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: BLUNT `DISCLOSURE'
</P>
<P>
   Oded Eran, the senior Israeli peace negotiator, said bluntly in
Eilat what everyone here knows: that a Palestinian state will be
the outcome of the final-status peace talks. But the prime
minister's office was bothered by the baldness of his public
statement and issued a clarification: What Eran meant to say, the
statement said, was that if there is a Palestinian state, it will
be as a result of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: U.N. OFFICER WOUNDED
</P>
<P>
   A Nigerian officer in the United Nations peacekeeping force was
seriously wounded after a skirmish with rebels near Port Loko, a
center for refugees and former combatants wishing to disarm. The
rebels are former soldiers who, like thousands of members of the
Revolutionary United Front, have refused to respect a peace pact
that calls for total disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: TAKESHITA BOWS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Citing ill health, former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, one
of Japan's most powerful postwar figures, announced his retirement
from politics. Takeshita, first elected to Parliament in 1958, was
prime minister for less than 18 months, starting in 1998, resigning
because of a stock distribution scandal. But he remained undisputed
kingmaker during much of the 1980s and early '90s.
</P>
</TEXT>
