<HEADER>
A2980 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLA     05-01 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON SAYS LOSS TO KINGS NOT BAD THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A 67-win season has produced some unreasonable
expectations for the Los Angeles Lakers, the first of which seemed
to be they could go unscathed in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That much is no longer possible, thanks to the Sacramento Kings'
99-91 victory over the Lakers in Game 3 of their first-round
series. But coach Phil Jackson, who sees lessons in every failure,
said the loss was not all bad, coming early in the Lakers'
championship drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing that we lost the game,'' Jackson
said Monday, ``because we didn't play well enough to win it. And if
we're going to be a team that goes on in the playoffs, we have to
play better than that. It was not a good game or showing by our
team at all, and so we have to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he clarified, ``I wasn't happy last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant sounded a similar note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody thought we were unbeatable. We weren't
going to go undefeated,'' he said. ``But I think it was a good test
to play in a hostile environment, here in Sacramento against a good
ballclub, early in the playoffs. I think it was good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also bristled at the idea that the Lakers had lost some
sense of being invincible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The invincibility is not on our part, it's on your (the
media's) part. You guys are the ones that have crowned us as
champions before we even got off and running in the playoffs,'' he
said. ``We have to be tested and the mettle and the wherewithal
that comes within this team to ride out tough things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have a 2-1 advantage in the series, so Jackson
disagreed with any notion that the pressure is on them tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not eliminated if we lose the next game, right?''
Jackson said. ``They're still going home (if they lose). So that's
a big difference. They still have elimination in the back of their
head.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Oh, baby: Rick Fox and wife Vanessa Williams at last welcomed
the arrival of their first child Monday, when Sasha Gabriella Fox
was born in New York. She weighed 7 pounds, 3 ounces, and both
mother and daughter were said to be doing well.
</P>
<P>
   The team said Fox hopes to be back in time for tonight's game,
and Jackson hopes he'll return with a clearer head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually all bought him a ticket to go there because he's
so distracted by the whole situation that he hasn't had his head in
the ballgame,'' Jackson said wryly. ``So we encouraged him to go,
and if he can't get back, stay, we'll be OK without him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Overlooked: The Kings seemed a bit perturbed Monday by the
notion that the Lakers gave them the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``From their opinion, they say they gave us the game,'' Jon
Barry said. ``If that's what they want to feel, that's fine. The
way I saw it was we beat them in the fourth quarter and we took the
game from them. They didn't give us anything. We played superior
offense and defense in the fourth quarter and we won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the thought the Lakers will come out angry tonight,
that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think they know we're going to come out angry, too,''
Vlade Divac said. ``We're down one game. We're facing elimination,
so we have to come out very angry and try to force a fifth game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
