<HEADER>
A2984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-LEAF-QUINN-NYT &LR;      05-01 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEAF-QUINN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS KEEPS LEAFS, BUT NOT QUINN, QUIET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Twice in three games, Pat Quinn, the
Toronto Maple Leafs' coach and general manager, has attempted to
shift the focus off his team and on to what he considers
questionable tactics by the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy might have helped before Game 1, which Toronto won
by 2-1. But it definitely did not work Monday night. The subject of
Quinn's comments this time, Scott Stevens, the Devils' captain, was
obviously unruffled. For the third consecutive game, Stevens helped
hold Mats Sundin's top line without a point, and the Devils came
within 4 minutes 17 seconds of shutting out the Maple Leafs for the
second straight game.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils settled for a commanding 5-1 victory to take a 2-1
lead in the four-of-seven-game National Hockey League Eastern
Conference semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   At the Maple Leafs' morning skate Monday, Quinn accused Stevens
of trying not once, but twice, to injure Toronto players during the
series by hitting them knee on knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what that kid on the other side was thinking _
there's two knees he's tried to take out,'' Quinn said, referring
to Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen that before out of him. There's something
wrong there.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whom he felt Stevens was out to get, Quinn _ who had
called the Devils a punch-and-run team before the series opener in
Toronto last Thursday _ responded that Darcy Tucker was the first
one. Quinn did not say who the second Leafs player was.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stevens did not have anything to say to reporters
before tonight's game. He did have something to say to the Maple
Leafs, however.
</P>
<P>
   As the final seconds of a scoreless first period were ticking
down, Stevens gave Sundin, the Toronto captain, a few whacks with
his stick behind the play. Once the horn sounded signaling the end
of the period, Stevens had words at the red line with Sundin, along
with Steve Thomas _ Stevens' former teammate with the Devils _ and
the Toronto tough guy Tie Domi.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 18-year NHL career, Stevens, 36, has become
expert at containing the opposing team's top line. But perhaps
never more so than this season. At least, that is what Ken Daneyko,
who just turned 36 himself, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as I've seen him,'' said Daneyko, who has been
Stevens' teammate since Stevens joined the Devils for the 1991-92
season. ``Especially at the end of the year and now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens played in his 11th All-Star Game this season and led the
Devils with a plus-minus rating of plus-30. But he has saved his
best for last.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far this postseason, the 6-foot-1-inch, 215-pound
defenseman has done a brilliant job. He and Brian Rafalski helped
hold Pavel Bure to a solitary goal in the Devils' four-game sweep
of the Florida Panthers in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   All Bure did in the regular season was score the most goals in
the league, 58, which was 14 more than the runner-up, San Jose's
Owen Nolan. But Stevens was all over Bure during the first-round
series, pounding him at every opportunity to almost single-handedly
neutralize him.
</P>
<P>
   This series, Stevens' assignment is to shadow Toronto's top
line, which is centered by Sundin, with Thomas at right wing and
Jonas Hoglund at left wing. Tonight, Stevens and Rafalski, along
with the forward line of Steve Kelly, Bobby Holik and Randy McKay,
were on the ice every time Sundin's line played at even strength,
until the Devils scored their fifth goal.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Sundin called Stevens a borderline dirty player,
albeit with a smile on his face. Tucker, who scored the winning
goal in Game 1, did not go that far. But Tucker did say that he
thought Stevens was intentionally trying to knee him Saturday night
midway through the second period of Game 2, which New Jersey won,
1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, on the other hand, did his talking with his stick. He
whacked at Sundin and Hoglund in front of net during the second
period tonight. And after the Devils scored 5 goals on 8 shots in a
16:19 span that began at 9:42 of the second period, New Jersey had
romped in its first game on home ice this series.
</P>
<P>
   And Sundin's line _ thanks in large part to Stevens _ was still
looking for its first point. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
