<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2987 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MARGIN-DISASTER-SFCHR     05-01 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARGIN-DISASTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARGINED TO DEATH _ INVESTORS LEARN PAINFUL LESSON ABOUT BUYING 
 STOCKS WITH BORROWED FUNDS 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; For long-term investors who buy stocks with cash, the violent
price plunges that shook the market early last month have been
reduced to a vaguely painful memory _ like yesterday's tooth
extraction.
<P>
   But for a beleaguered minority _ those who bought stocks with
money borrowed on margin _ April 2000 will forever be regarded as
something akin to the Great Depression and World War II combined.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of days, hours, even minutes, many thousands of
margin speculators had their nest eggs either wiped out or damaged
beyond hope of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The carnage culminated on April 14, when the Dow Jones
industrial average plunged a record 617 points and the Nasdaq
composite index plummeted 355 points _ also a record.
</P>
<P>
   As prices fell, brokers, fearing that their loans were in
jeopardy, bombarded borrowers with margin calls _ demands to pour
more collateral into their accounts to back up their debts. Some
brokers, in what can fairly be described as a lender's panic,
didn't bother to formally request the money _ they just took it, by
selling out customer positions.
</P>
<P>
   While brokers were legally entitled to do this, their
pre-emptive actions caused a tremendous amount of ill will among
their margin customers.
</P>
<P>
   Several margin investors interviewed by The Chronicle said they
would have put additional funds into their accounts if they had
been given the opportunity. And, they ruefully point out, that
would have been a good idea because the market bounced back.
</P>
<P>
   Market-watchers say the margin selling had an indirect effect on
nonmargin customers, accentuating the decline of many stocks _
particularly a host of fast-moving, high-technology stocks favored
by margin speculators.
</P>
<P>
   Although things went terribly wrong in April, it is easy to
understand why many investors got hooked on margin speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the margin rules laid down by the Federal Reserve,
investors can borrow up to 50 percent of the purchase price of a
stock from their brokers. That has the effect of doubling any
investment gains.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you buy 100 shares of Company XYZ at $50 per
share, you only have to come up with $2,500 of the $5,000 purchase
price, while your broker will lend you the remaining $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   If XYZ's price then rises 10 percent to $55, the $500 increase
in the value of the 100 shares represents a 20 percent gain on your
$2,500 outlay _ minus the interest and commissions charged by your
broker.
</P>
<P>
   Margin speculation has proved especially appealing to buyers of
high-tech stocks. The tech-laden Nasdaq composite _ as investors
may nostalgically recall _ rose 86 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that margin debt shot up dramatically last year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Association of Securities Dealers, it
totaled $284 billion at the end of February _ more than double the
total as recently as October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the amount of margin debt appears to have
declined somewhat, says Charles Biderman, chief executive of Market
Trim Tabs, a Santa Rosa firm that monitors fund flows. He bases
that conclusion on discussions with executives of ``a number of
brokerage firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's April horrors ``squeezed out some of the marginal
margin buyers,'' Biderman quips.
</P>
<P>
   Those people discovered too late that the magic of margin not
only can double your gains, but also your losses.
</P>
<P>
   If, to continue our example, the value of XYZ stock drops 50
percent to $25 per share, your equity will be wiped out. The 100
shares in your account, reduced in value to $2,500, will belong
entirely to your broker, which loaned you exactly that amount.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, however, brokers don't sit and wait while stocks
are declining that steeply.
</P>
<P>
   If the value of your equity declines below a certain level _
known as the ``maintenance margin'' _ either you will receive a
margin call or the broker will simply sell part or all of your
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum maintenance margin established by the Federal
Reserve is 25 percent, but most brokers require more than that.
</P>
<P>
   At Charles Schwab, for example, where margin loans have soared
to more than $20 billion from less than $10 billion at the end of
1998, the maintenance margin for most stocks is 35 percent; and for
some particularly volatile stocks, Schwab has scaled it up to 80
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   When maintenance is at 35 percent, you will be asked to add
assets to your account if the equity in the account, minus the
margin debt, falls to less than 35 percent of the equity.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the value of what used to be $5,000 worth of XYZ stock
drops to $3,846, the broker will want you to pump more assets into
the account.
</P>
<P>
   Huma Qureshi, 36, a Sunnyvale network consultant, still laments
a $25,000 loss she suffered in her online margin account with
Dreyfus Brokerage Services.
</P>
<P>
   She had created a complicated position involving the options of
Broadvision Inc., amounting to a bet that the company's stock price
would soar. But on April 14, Broadvision fell more than 25 percent
and Dreyfus sold the position out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no effort made by the brokerage firm to get in touch
with me,'' Qureshi complains, although she acknowledges that it
wasn't required to do so. She says she would have forked over the
money needed to bolster the position if she had been given the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   She also says Dreyfus didn't make it clear enough on its Web
site that her margin position was deteriorating to the point where
she might have to deposit more funds.
</P>
<P>
   Replies Dreyfus spokeswoman Beth Basilio: ``Although this is a
situation that we do not take lightly, margin calls are standard
practice throughout the industry.'' She says the Dreyfus Web site
includes enough ``investor educational materials'' to make it plain
where its margin customers stand.
</P>
<P>
   A California state employee named Mike, who asked that his last
name be withheld, says his margin account was liquidated by his
broker ``with no notice whatsoever'' during the April 14 debacle.
In addition, the broker has billed him for $1,200 that wasn't
covered by the account's assets.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Mike's portfolio of two high-tech stocks _ F5
Networks and AtHome _ was worth about $17,000, half of it borrowed.
But both stocks fell so hard that his equity vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had notified me, I would have put in more money to
hold onto my stocks,'' Mike says. ``I knew that things would
eventually get back to normal and was willing to ride that wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at age 39, he is thinking of withdrawing from the stock
market permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really shocking, and pretty ugly,'' he remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Shocking, ugly _ not to mention rude _ but it's entirely legal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the standard contract between brokers and their margin
customers, a broker can act peremptorily if the firm thinks its
assets are in danger.
</P>
<P>
   When stock prices are merely declining, not plummeting, most
brokers take the trouble to issue margin calls as a courtesy _ even
though it is not required. And they usually are willing to give you
three business days to beef up your account.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but if the value of your stocks shoots back up
during those three days, many brokers will withdraw their demands
for more money.
</P>
<P>
   But when the market is plunging at a record pace, etiquette goes
out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Di Chiro, a spokesman for E-Trade Group, a leading
online broker based in Palo Alto, says his firm tries to issue each
margin call in multiple ways _ by telephone, Mailgram, e-mail and
by posting a warning on its Web site that customers will see
immediately when they log on to their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to tell you,'' Di Chiro adds, ``that a day like
April 14 was not a normal day.'' In many, if not most, cases, he
says, the only notification that day was the Web site warning.
</P>
<P>
   So, you were just out of luck if you happened to be a margin
customer with an imperiled account who was busy with something else
that day _ like working for a living _ and didn't bother to check
the E-Trade Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is their responsibility to make sure, if they are
transacting on margin, that they know where they stand,'' Di Chiro
says.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunn, a spokesman for Datek Online, a leading online
brokerage and one of the industry's technology pioneers, says the
firm's computers automatically send e-mail requests for more money
to margin customers when the value of their equity falls below
maintenance levels.
</P>
<P>
   He says the system ensures that no customer in margin trouble
will go unnotified, no matter how busy the Datek staff may be.
</P>
<P>
   But New York travel agent Bob Anderson (not his real name;
margin losers tend to be shy) says he didn't receive an e-mail
before Datek liquidated his account. An e-mail finally arrived days
later, he says, too late for him to add money to the account.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn says that if Anderson's statement is accurate, he cannot
explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning days of bloody April, there were murmurs to the
effect that the margin rules should be tightened.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, which has the power to raise the 50 percent requirement
that's been in effect for the past quarter-century, hasn't
indicated any intentions to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Elisse Walter, NASD's chief operating officer in charge of
regulation, says her organization has ``a concern about whether
current margin levels are adequate.''
</P>
<P>
   NASD itself could impose stricter margin rules on its members,
who make up more than 99 percent of the securities industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't taken action to date,'' Walter says. ``We might or
might not in the future. We will monitor the situation very
closely.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, she says, ``there clearly needs to be much more
investor education done about this.'' Too many investors didn't
fully appreciate ``what it means to have a margin account.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
