<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TAKES ITS CASE TO THE PUBLIC 
 &HT;     BY KELLY ZITO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Microsoft lawyers work behind the scenes to prevent a breakup
of the software titan, the company's publicity machine is kicking
into high gear in the battle for John Q. Public.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a fuzzy TV spot featuring Microsoft chief executive
Steve Ballmer ran during ``60 Minutes.'' And yesterday, Microsoft
placed full-page ads in a spate of newspapers claiming that the
government's proposal to carve the company into two pieces would be
``a major setback for consumers, the high-technology industry and
the American economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dismantling of Microsoft would also send a signal that
companies in America that are `too' successful will be punished
harshly _ a signal that will be welcomed by foreign competitors
seeking to overtake America's global leadership in technology,''
said the ad's letter, co-signed by Ballmer and Microsoft Chairman
Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Department of Justice antitrust chief Joel
Klein used the pulpit of Sunday's ``Face the Nation'' program on
CBS to reiterate that the federal government and the 17 states who
endorsed the breakup proposal are confident the case will move
forward no matter what political party sits in the White House
after this fall's election.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the de facto Republican presidential candidate,
has seemed more sympathetic toward Microsoft's position. And if the
software giant appeals the federal's judge's ruling in the case, as
it has promised, Bush could assume a major role in how the case
plays out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be irresponsible and futile for a new administration
to weaken'' the case, Iowa Attorney General Tom Miller said.
``That's totally intolerable to the states.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Department of Justice and attorneys general from
the 17 states recommended splitting Microsoft into two separate
companies: one for Windows operating system software; the other for
Microsoft's applications, including the popular Office product and
the Internet businesses. Both the breakup and restrictions on the
company's business practices are designed to sever Microsoft's
chokehold on th PC market and spur competition in the software
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a court filing supporting the proposal, the government said
the company is using its operating systems monopoly to enter the
highly competitive Personal Digital Appliances market.
</P>
<P>
   ``(O)n July 11, 1999, less than thirty days after the conclusion
of trial in this action, Bill Gates wrote an e-mail directing that
Microsoft redesign its software in order to harm competitors. This
time, the products in question were the Personal Digital Appliances
that Microsoft heralded at trial as one of the products that might
someday undo its monopoly,'' the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail from Gates was not included in the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has until May 10 to respond to the remedy proposal. On
May 24, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is scheduled to
hold a hearing to consider the issue, but Microsoft said it needs
more time to prepare its arguments against a proposal suggesting
such an ``extreme'' remedy as a divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   As the case winds its way through the final chapter of the
two-year saga, both sides are taking their campaigns to the people.
But Microsoft obviously has more to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a chess game, and Microsoft has got some damage
control to do,'' said Rich Gray, a Silicon Valley antitrust
attorney. ``From now until Jackson releases his final judgment it's
in Microsoft's best interest to keep their version of the future
out there, and I expect them to keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   `If I'm Microsoft, I'm not just relying on the hope that Bush
beats Gore, I'm trying to create a grassroots groundswell'' of
support against a breakup, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it appears Microsoft is off to a good start _ though
that's no indication of how the judge may rule.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent CBSMarketwatch /AOL survey, 47 percent of
members polled (the survey didn't give a total figure) agreed with
the idea that ``breaking up Microsoft would hamper the progress of
technology by hurting the largest and most successful technology
company in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A third of those polled believe a split would benefit progress
by ``ensuring that all technology companies have access to the
marketplace and that all can compete fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Those figures may reflect Wall Street's highly divergent
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock rallied $3.69 yesterday, closing at $73.44. But
it's unclear whether that means investors believe the company
stands a good chance on appeal or whether two Microsofts ultimately
hold more value for shareholders than one.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts pegged the combined stock prices of two
Microsoft's at a relatively high $135, others looked less favorably
on a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't embrace this theory that the company's better off
split up,'' said William Epifanio, an analyst at JP Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it became 100 percent certain that Microsoft would be
broken up, I would sell first and ask questions later.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
