<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF LIMITS ON ROTH IRAS 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR; Early in 1999, I opened a Roth individual retirement account in &LR; 
 &LR; the belief that my income would be below the cut-off point for &LR; 
 &LR; eligibility. Later in the year, several limited partnerships &LR; 
 &LR; that I had gone into during the early 1980s were sold, and I &LR; 
 &LR; learned that my adjusted gross income for 1999 was pushed above &LR; 
 &LR; the Roth limits. My accountant advised me to redesignate my &LR;   &LR; 1999
contribution to 2000, but by then I had already made my &LR;   &LR; Roth
contribution for this year. What are my options? &LR;
<P>
   A: You could have wriggled out without a penalty by converting
the Roth to a traditional, nondeductible IRA, says Internal Revenue
Service spokesman Jesse Weller. There are no upper income limits
imposed on that type of IRA. (With a Roth, the upper limit is
$160,000, with a phaseout beginning at $150,000; for a single
person, the upper limit is $110,000 and the phaseout begins at
$95,000.)
</P>
<P>
   You had to make the conversion before the due date of your 1999
tax return. Ordinarily that would have been April 17, but if you
didn't file by that date and instead requested an extension, you
still have until August 15.
</P>
<P>
   If you already have filed, you will have to pay a 6 percent
penalty tax on the amount of your 1999 contribution. Assuming that
you contributed $2,000, you would owe a penalty of $120. Also,
Weller warns, you had better withdraw your 1999 contribution from
the Roth promptly, or you will be hit with another 6 percent
penalty for this year as well.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; New Shares for Old Stock
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been asked to help an elderly blind woman find out the
value of an old stock certificate in her name. The company is
Kaiser Aluminum &AMP; Chemical Corp., and the certificate is dated Feb.
8, 1982. Can you offer any advice?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kaiser Aluminum &AMP; Chemical, formerly based in Oakland, hasn't
been a stand-alone company since 1987. At that time it was folded
into a newly formed holding company called KaiserTech Ltd.,
controlled by British investor Alan Clore. Kaiser Aluminum
shareholders exchanged their shares for KaiserTech stock, but for
some unknown reason your friend failed to make the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   KaiserTech was bought for cash by Charles Hurwitz's Maxxam Inc.
in 1988. Three years later, Maxxam made an initial public offering
of stock in a company called Kaiser Aluminum Corp., of which the
old Kaiser Aluminum &AMP; Chemical _ still bearing that name _ is the
operating subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   You ought to write or call the Maxxam investor relations
department and find out how to cash in the Kaiser certificate. The
address: 5847 San Felipe; Houston, TX 77057. The phone number:
(713) 975-7600.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Assessment Not Deductible
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our homeowners association levied a $5,800 charge per
homeowner for the cost of fixing a hillside slide. The slide
occurred on common property and did not affect us directly.
However, the association threatened to put a lien on our house if
we did not pay.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed out that all our property values could be adversely
affected, and we would be liable for lawsuits from a neighboring
community if we did not fix the slide. Our homeowners insurance did
not cover the cost because the slide was not on our own property.
Is this fee tax deductible?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: IRS spokesman Weller says that it is not. But it might
work to your tax benefit later on, if you ever sell your property.
</P>
<P>
   Weller says you are entitled to add the $5,800 to the cost basis
of your home in figuring the capital gain _ assuming there is one _
when you sell.
</P>
<P>
   That may or may not save you tax money.
</P>
<P>
   In selling your home, you are entitled to a $500,000
capital-gains exclusion if married, or a $250,000 exclusion if you
are single. If your profit on the home sale is less than that, you
won't be taxed, so the $5,800 outlay won't help you save on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But, as we have been reading lately, the prices of Bay Area
homes continue to soar out of sight. More and more homeowners are
finding themselves sitting on enormous paper profits that exceed
the exclusion limits. It could happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, save the receipt and any other documents relating
to your $5,800 assessment. The day may come when you will be asked
to show them to a tax auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions about how to manage your money to
 &LR; moneybag &LR; sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
