<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PEACE OVERTURES IN COLOMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 2:
</P>
<P>
   With his decision to establish a safe haven for Colombia's
second-largest guerrilla group, President Andres Pastrana is
showing admirable persistence in trying to negotiate an end to his
nation's 35-year-old civil war. The plan would draw the group, the
National Liberation Army, into Pastrana's peace talks for the first
time. Colombians have learned not to expect too much from periodic
negotiations, and a peace agreement is still a long shot. But the
inclusion of the National Liberation Army provides the best chance
in recent history to negotiate an end to the activities of a
guerrilla army whose kidnappings and bombing of oil production
facilities have terrorized Colombians.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana took office in 1998 with an overwhelming mandate to
negotiate peace. One of his first acts was to pull army troops out
of a zone that became a safe haven for Colombia's largest guerrilla
group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC.
Ensconced in a sparsely populated area the size of Switzerland, the
FARC proceeded to increase coca production, stockpile arms and
drive out local authorities. The group's bad behavior and repeated
snubs at peace talks have made Pastrana look weak and damaged the
public consensus for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an auspicious backdrop for a second safe haven _
especially because the National Liberation Army recently infuriated
Colombians by kidnapping 160 worshipers at a Catholic Mass as well
as an airliner full of people. In addition, the area proposed for
the new safe haven is heavily populated and borders on an important
oil-producing zone.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastrana has made a better deal this time, mainly because
the National Liberation Army is smaller than the FARC and more
enthusiastic about peace negotiations. The new enclave will be
smaller in area and easier for the army to retake if the guerrillas
violate their promises. The group has apparently agreed to release
its hostages. Crucially, guerrilla leaders will also allow
Colombian and international observers into the area.
</P>
<P>
   There are still many details to be worked out, and no guarantee
of good behavior, but the plan is nevertheless a major step. The
recent announcement by the FARC that it will ``tax'' millionaires
by kidnapping them _ which has long been its practice _ is a
setback, but there have been advances as well. The FARC observed a
cease-fire over Christmas, and is proposing another one. It has
decided to create a political party. Perhaps Colombia's rebels are
finally ready to negotiate in good faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
