<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MICROSOFTS COULD BE WORTH MORE, OR LESS, THAN ONE 
 &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
How much are two Microsofts worth?
<P>
   As little as $50 per share or as much as $135, according to
three Wall Street estimates published since Friday, when the
government proposed breaking the software giant into two parts.
</P>
<P>
   How could analysts, in many cases using the same forecasting
models, come up with a range of estimates wide enough to drive a
Ford Excursion through?
</P>
<P>
   Technically, it turns on price/earnings ratios, growth rates and
discount factors _ tools of the analysts trade.
</P>
<P>
   But fundamentally, it boils down to whether analysts think
shareholders will be better off with two monopolies or one.
</P>
<P>
   At one extreme is David Readerman, an analyst with Thomas Weisel
Partners, who believes that two Microsofts would be worth about $55
per share _ $20 for the operating systems business and $25 for the
applications business. (Microsoft closed yesterday at $73.44, near
the bottom of its 52-week range of $66.63 to $119.13.)
</P>
<P>
   Readerman didn't return my calls, but his report issued
yesterday called the breakup a ``corporate castration'' that will
``destroy shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   The operating system company, he says, would become ``the new
economy equivalent of a public utility.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the ``intellectual property'' associated with the
Internet browser would go to the applications company. The OS
company could incorporate one version of Microsoft's Internet
Explorer into Windows. After that, it would have to license new Web
browsers from competing (non-Microsoft) companies or develop its
own.
</P>
<P>
   The OS company would ``resemble a university research think tank
with little entrepreneurial incentive. The goal will be winning
tenure professorships and getting lucrative consulting and board
seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Readerman says his numbers reflect a ``worst-case scenario'' but
doesn't offer a best case.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme is Michael Stanek of Lehman Bros., who
thinks a two-piece Microsoft could be worth a total of $125 to $135
per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operating system company won't be as exciting,'' he
admits, ``but applications looks like a terrific business, mainly
because it will be able to merge with other companies'' such as
Ariba or other B2B Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   He figures the OS company would be worth $31 to $34 per share,
with the rest of the value in the applications business and $6 to
$9 per share in cash and equity investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say the company's going to have problems because of
all these government regulations, but it's still a monopoly and the
market will pay for a monopoly,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At both extremes _ and in the middle _ is Melissa Eisenstat of
CIBC World Markets, who believes a post-breakup Microsoft could be
worth a total of $52 to $134 per share, based on four different
valuation techniques:
</P>
<P>
   _Market cap to revenues: $52. This valuation was arrived at by
multiplying Microsoft's estimated revenues for each segment by an
average multiple for leading competitors in each segment. Eisenstat
says this is a better way to value startups with no earnings than
big moneymakers like Microsoft, and she doesn't put much faith in
this estimate.
</P>
<P>
   _Discounted cash flow: $59. This involves estimating the present
value of Microsoft's cash flow over the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   _P/E to growth: $58. Eisenstat multiplied her estimated earnings
for each segment by a multiple based on the growth rate for each
segment. The result is ``almost exactly the result we achieved
through DCF  &LR; discounted-cash-flow analysis, and more closely
reflects the traditional method of valuing mature software
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   _Relative valuation: $134. Eisenstat valued the two pieces based
on P/E ratios of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to tell you it's going there (to $134). And if
psychology on the stock turns, it could go there,'' Eisenstat says.
But she thinks the two middle valuations _ $58 and $59 _ ``do the
best job of valuing the intrinsic business.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstat, who was one of the first Wall Street analysts to
downgrade Microsoft this year, says the company could be worth less
than it is now because of ``the loss of the network effect. One
product helps you sell another. You're losing that whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   KWATINETZ' NEW VENTURE: Michael Kwatinetz was one of the first
analysts to come up with a breakup value for Microsoft. Late last
year, when the stock was much higher, he estimated the company
would be worth $553 billion in a breakup, or about 20 percent more
than its market value at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Kwatinetz, who quit his job at Credit Suisse First Boston two
weeks ago to open an investment company in the Bay Area, said his
valuation was based on a breakup into three companies _ for
operating systems, applications and Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they separated the company into three parts and let each
one be competitive, the (combined post-breakup value) would be 50
percent more than it is now,'' Kwatinetz said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But the remedy the government proposed Friday would ``impose
sanctions that would make both companies noncompetitive and would
bury the Internet value in the applications company,'' he said.
Under that scenario, ``I'm not sure it's worth any more than it is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwatinetz has recruited (or should I say raided) an impressive
lineup for his new venture, Azure Capital Partners. They include
three colleagues from CSFB: Paul Weinstein, an analyst covering
networking stocks; Cameron Lester, who was an investment banker in
the e-software division; and Paul Ferris, an investment banker in
the communications division.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth partner is Frank ``Quint'' Slattery, who was managing
the PBHG New Opportunities fund until April 11. The partners plan
to have offices in San Francisco and Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Final note: CSFB took Microsoft off its recommended list
yesterday, but only because no one is covering the stock at the
moment. However, Elliott Rogers, CSFB managing director, called
Microsoft ``the Philip Morris of technology stocks,'' meaning it
could be bogged down for years in legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
