u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-     05-01 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TO SEEK ENDORSEMENT FROM THE CONSERVATIVE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after a former congressman from Westchester
County, Joseph J. DioGuardi, announced that he would seek the
Conservative Party endorsement to run for the U.S. Senate, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani declared Monday that he, too, wanted the party's
endorsement. Giuliani's aides sought for the first time to set up a
meeting between the mayor and state Conservative Party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Long, the state party's chairman, said that he was
called early Monday by an aide to Giuliani requesting a meeting. An
aide to Giuliani confirmed the call, and said a meeting could
happen over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a credible conservative candidate is a matter of
clear concern to Giuliani's aides, since DioGuardi, running on the
right, would presumably draw votes away from Giuliani in his Senate
contest with Hillary Rodham Clinton. And DioGuardi, the former
two-term congressman, said in an interview that he wants to run as
the candidate of the Conservative, Right-to-Life and Independence
Parties.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Long and Giuliani has been strained,
and evidence remained Monday of abundant hostility between the two.
Aides to both suggested that Giuliani's prospects of winning the
Conservative endorsement remained fairly remote. Long noted he had
repeatedly said that he was open to a meeting with Giuliani over
the last year, and that Giuliani had shunned his overtures _until
DioGuardi's plans became known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they were planning to make the call anyhow,'' Long said
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   Guy V. Molinari, the Staten Island borough president and a close
ally of Giuliani, attacked Long for entertaining the prospect of
running DioGuardi against the mayor. ``Mike Long has been on a
mission to destroy Rudy Giuliani,'' Molinari said. ``And now
putting Joe DioGuardi out there clearly is designed as an
opportunity to try to siphon off enough votes to make Rudy Giuliani
a loser. It doesn't elect Rudy Giuliani. It elects Hillary. If Rudy
loses, people are going to blame Mike Long and the Conservative
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was filled with maneuvering by the smaller parties who
are trying to wield some influence in this Senate race. Clinton
announced she would appear before the policy committee of the
Liberal Party on Saturday. Her aides, though, sought to play down
expectations, noting Giuliani's close friendship with Raymond B.
Harding, the party leader.
</P>
<P>
   And Lenora Fulani, a leader of the left-wing New Alliance Party
who controls a faction of the Independence Party, called a news
conference to assail Clinton for attacking ``extremism'' in the
Independence Party when she and Giuliani appeared before its
members on Saturday. The first lady was referring to the party's
affiliation with Fulani and Patrick J. Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   `` Clinton's slanderous personal attacks on me at the
Independence Party forum on Saturday indicate that she and her
professional advisers thought she could score some political points
by name-calling,'' Fulani said. ``Obviously, they feel completely
secure that they have the support of New York's black leadership
and that they can single me out for abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, defended the remarks. ``Pat
Buchanan and his chief ally in New York, Lenora Fulani, have a long
history of making anti-Semitic and divisive statements,'' he said.
``That's why Hillary made it very clear on Saturday that she won't
compromise her principles by running on a ticket with Pat
Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, Giuliani said he had expressed his interest in
winning the Conservative Party endorsement when Long called him on
Thursday to offer best wishes, after the mayor announced he had
prostate cancer. Giuliani said he had talked briefly with Long
about his political support, adding that it would be better to work
out any details in private.
</P>
<P>
   Long disputed Giuliani's account, saying the mayor never asked
for the endorsement. ``My door is open'' to discussion, Long said,
but reiterated that he would not support endorsing Giuliani unless
he dropped his opposition to bans on some forms of late-term
abortion, and abandoned his effort to run as a Liberal Party
candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
