u a BC-NY-KLAN-RALLY-NYT &LR;      05-01 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KLAN-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KU KLUX KLAN SAYS IT WILL SEEK PERMISSION FOR A MASKED RALLY IN
NYC
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Ku Klux Klan, which created a furor when a
handful of its members demonstrated in lower Manhattan last year,
plans to reapply for a permit to demonstrate again this fall, the
group's lawyer has said.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's rally, Klan members were forced to doff their
masks as a result of a 155-year-old New York state law that forbids
demonstrators to cover their faces. City officials invoked the law
after the Klan applied for a permit.
</P>
<P>
   The group challenged the order that the masks be removed, which
was overturned by a federal District Court judge, but then
reinstated by a federal appeals court. The case is now back in
district court.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the New York Civil Liberties Union, which is
representing the Church of the American Knights of the Ku Klux
Klan, said the group intended to again ask the court to allow the
demonstrators to wear masks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used this statute as a pretext for denying the Klan the
right to effectively demonstrate,'' said the lawyer, Norman Siegel,
executive director of the civil liberties group. ``Once they could
not wear their masks it substantially decreased the number of
people who would demonstrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said the group planned to reapply for the permit, and
this time would ask a judge to permanently bar the city from
enforcing the ordinance. ``The Klan intends to come back and
exercise their right to wear the hood and the mask,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they were merely enforcing an existing law,
which prevents organized groups from demonstrating while wearing
masks. The law dates back to the mid-19th century, when tenant
farmers demonstrated against their landlords. Wearing disguises,
the farmers would stage protests, and sometimes riots, and escape
to the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons behind the statute are as valid today as they were
when the law was passed, and that is to create accountability for
one's actions when one is in a crowd,'' said Daniel S. Connolly, a
lawyer for the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
