<DOCNO> NYT20000501.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-DILBECK-COLUMN-LA     05-01 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DILBECK-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HAVEN'T WON A THING YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Now, don't go getting all nervous. Can the panic
attack. Forget the fast retreat, the jumping ship, reaching for the
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost a first-round playoff game. OK, more accurately,
they lost a playoff game they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   A game that a championship team does win. Champions close out a
series when it's there for the taking. They don't blow a
five-point, fourth-quarter lead. They smell blood. Go for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did not. They were on their way to a methodical,
uneventful sweep to their first-round playoff series Sunday against
the Kings, when they let the little upstarts find new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing. We had a chance to land a knockout
punch,'' Lakers general manager Mitch Kupchak said. ``You learn
when you have a chance to end it, you've got to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A playoff series is something that's not choreographed. It's a
live event. Anything can happen. You can get flu, injuries, there
are so many variables. Rick Fox is now in New York looking after
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to end a series as soon as possible. You don't want
to give a team hope or life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chalk this up to a learning experience. When the opportunity was
there, the Lakers did not finish off the Kings the way champions
do. But here is a real news flash: The Lakers aren't champions.
</P>
<P>
   They have won nothing yet. Sixty-seven victories in the regular
season is just so much prolonged prelude to the real season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers remain a work in progress. This is a team that has to
grow before us in the playoffs. They're not soup yet, although the
simmering aroma has been intoxicating to Laker faithful ready to
fit them for rings since January.
</P>
<P>
   The press, opposing coaches, other players, have all taken turns
to lavish praise upon the Lakers and all but anoint them as NBA
champions before the first playoff tip. A league eager for its next
super team fell upon its knees. If they were made out to be any
greater, after the courts finished with Microsoft, they'd go about
busting up the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Only, the Lakers are not invincible. They are not greatest thing
since Sir Michael landed. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The invincibility is not on our part, it's on your (media)
part,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``You guys are the ones who
have crowned us champions before we even got off and running in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be tested, the metttle and the wherewithal that
comes within this team to ride out tough things and situations on
the court that make it difficult to play _ missed free throws,
those kinds of things _ are still to be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have made progress on two of their long-time
problems, yet both were again evident in Sunday's 99-91 loss to the
Kings: Shaquille O'Neal remains unreliable at the free-throw line
and Kobe Bryant too often is prone to go solo.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever advances made in both areas this season, they have to
prove themselves in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers have earned everyone's respect this season, they
are not the answer to Social Security, Elian's woes or explaining
professional wrestling. They have not earned an automatic ticket to
the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody in our league sees them as invincible,''
Kings coach Rick Adelman said. ``They have all the components to
get to the finals, and that's really what your goal is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in some ways, if they beat us in this playoff round, I'm
sure Phil will look back on that game (Sunday) night and say, `Hey,
this is what can happen to us if we don't take care of what we have
to do.' I think he's very good at making them understand where they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Western Conference is so competitive, if you don't come to
play your best on the road, you will lose regardless of the
opponent. The Kings are the eighth-place team, and only twice in
NBA history has a No. 8 upset a No. 1 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did not play their best Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one of those days, brother,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Great teams don't have many in the playoffs. But each of the
Lakers' five championship teams in the '80s lost at least two
playoff games. They lost nine times on the way to winning their
last title in '88.
</P>
<P>
   We'll see tonight just how much mettle this contingent has. The
crowd, relatively quiet until the fourth quarter Sunday, will be in
full force from the start tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a challenge, the kind great teams overcome. And the
playoffs is where greatness evolves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
