r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     05-01 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS TRY TO SHUT DOWN, SHUT UP SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stars winger Blake Sloan doesn't know a lot about computers.
</P>
<P>
   But he does know the dot.com geeks who abound Sharks games sound
more like John Belushi in ``Animal House'' than Bill Gates at a
Microsoft shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's bad,'' Sloan said. ``Not as much the noise, but
their fans are ruthless. They have no qualms about putting anything
on signs or billboards.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes likely won't change for Game 3 tonight at San Jose
Arena. An effigy of Stars goalie Ed Belfour falls from the stadium
roof. Signs, bearing less-than-original, billion-dollar punch
lines, hang everywhere. All while Sharks fans stand and scream in
anticipation of that first goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars know the best way to shut them up is to shut them
down.
</P>
<P>
   They have just the defense capable of doing it, too. The Sharks
didn't score a goal in either game in Dallas. They were shut out
only four times in 82 regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in their mind now they haven't scored in two
games,'' Stars defenseman Sylvain Cote said. ``And that's why I
think the first period is going to be big. If we are able to keep
their shots low and get just one goal, that's all we need for them
to really say `Oh God, this is happening again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' defense has a way of getting into an opponent's head.
</P>
<P>
   Stars captain Derian Hatcher invaded the Edmonton Oilers'
craniums in the first round. The Oilers couldn't talk about the
series without somehow mentioning him. Hatcher this, Hatcher that,
Hatcher, Hatcher, Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sharks, it's all about Belfour, like Jan Brady pouting
about Marcia. They put 37 shots on him in two games. They've yet to
get one by him. He hasn't allowed a goal in 138 minutes and 53
seconds. It's always Eddie, Eddie, Eddie.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it Eddie, Matty, Hatch?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is Eddie, Sergei, Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget Eddie, Cote and ``Charlie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of like our own little family,'' Darryl Sydor said
of Dallas' defensive corps. ``I think we really feel good together.
All six of us back there know what we have to do to get it done.
Obviously, the less time you have in your zone the better. Our
motto is to get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what they've been doing.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks come charging up to the blue line full of vim and
vigor only to be turned away by the wall of Hatcher and Richard
Matvichuk or Sydor and Sergei Zubov or Cote and Dave Manson.
</P>
<P>
   It grows disheartening after a couple of minutes. The Sharks
have been battling it for 120 minutes so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating for any team,'' Matvichuk said. ``It would be
frustrating for us, too, if we weren't able to get into the
opposition's end.''
</P>
<P>
   If San Jose needs a sympathetic shoulder to cry on, call
Detroit. The Red Wings couldn't get the puck through the neutral
zone, and scored only once against Colorado goalie Patrick Roy in
the first two games of that series, before coming back with a 3-1
victory last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were as tough or tougher than Colorado's defense in
the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a great job of clearing out'' the crease, San Jose
forward Tony Granato said. ``We have to keep fighting, but they
have Hatcher, Matvichuk, Manson, a lot of big guys, around there.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars didn't feel they played that great defensively in
Game 2. Too many odd-man rushes, too many times when Belfour was
expected to bail them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the answer to it all, but we can't continue to live on
that,'' Stars assistant coach Rick Wilson said. ``We can play
better defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about exactly what the Sharks didn't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the numbers fool you. It's Game 3, but it might as
well be Game 7 for the Sharks. If they don't win tonight, their
chances of winning out to steal the series are almost as slim as
Gates' chances of filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   So they really need to win Game 3. The crowd, they hope, can do
what they haven't been able to: Rattle Belfour and the Stars'
defense.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars, it's equally simple. Shut the Sharks down. Shut
the crowd up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to do it is make them spend time in their own
end, more time than they want. Don't let them get started,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It can turn quickly. I know it has been
a quiet building when they are unsuccessful.''
</P>
<P>
   If they shut up the dot.com geeks, it's likely to be
www.starswin.com. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
